<SLUG> BC-RAC-GOLDSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDROYALE HAS TRAINER IN DRIVER'S SEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Rags-to-riches gelding Budroyale's game
second in Sunday's Hollywood Gold Cup felt almost like a triumph to
adoring owner Jeffrey Sengara.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't be any prouder if he'd won by 10 (lengths),'' the
Vancouver lumber businessman said.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-year-old California-bred picked up $200,000, pushing his
earnings over $892,000 since Sengara claimed him for $50,000 in
February 1998 and over $1.1 million for his 40-race career.
</P>
<P>
   Sengara had promised trainer Ted West Jr. a car if Budroyale
broke the $1 million mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have to ask him which (car) he wants,'' Sengara said.
``Which one I give him is another situation entirely.''
</P>
<P>
   Record run: The performance of the day was turned in not by Real
Quiet but by 4-year-old sprinter Mazel Trick, who shattered the
Hollywood Park record for 7 furlongs in winning the Triple Bend
Handicap by five lengths.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying Chris McCarron and 115 pounds, Mazel Trick rallied from
sixth on the outside and was clocked in 1:19 4/5, cutting
three-fifths of a second off the record shared by Memo, Hal's Pal,
Another Star and A.P. Assay.
</P>
<P>
   A faster 7 furlongs has been run at Hollywood Park _ Rich
Cream's American-record 1:19 2/5 in 1980 _ but that was before the
oval was reconfigured and the track statistics-keeping started
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised the police weren't there to give him a
speeding ticket,'' said Alex Solis, who rode favored Regal Thunder
to third place.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Frankel-trained Mazel Trick, a French import, hadn't raced
since having bone chips surgically removed from both front ankles
in December.
</P>
<P>
   The day's other stakes, the A Gleam Handicap for fillies and
mares, went to Enjoy the Moment and David Flores.
</P>
<P>
   Bad breaks: Emile Ramsammy, fourth in the Hollywood Park jockey
standings, fractured his right collarbone and possibly his left
knee in a fall at Woodbine racecourse near Toronto on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The accident occurred in a race following the classic Queen's
Plate Stakes, in which Ramsammy and Frankel-trained Euchre ran
third to Woodcarver and Mickey Walls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
