<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BUDGET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO UNVEIL PLAN TO SHORE UP SOCIAL SECURITY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON with ADAM CLYMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seeking to capitalize on new projections showing
that the federal budget surplus will grow far bigger than
anticipated, President Clinton plans to unveil sweeping new
proposals on Monday to allocate the windfall among Social Security,
Medicare and other spending and tax cut proposals, Democrats said
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan is sure to renew and intensify his long-running
battle with Republicans in Congress over the nation's priorities as
it enters a new era in which the two parties must divide up pots of
money far larger than anything they could have imagined even a year
or two ago.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said new projections by the White House's Office of
Management and Budget showed that the total budget surplus would be
$179 billion higher over the next 5 years, and $517 billion higher
over 10 years, than its last estimates, in January.
</P>
<P>
   The White House wants to use much of the money on revised
approaches to shoring up the two big entitlement programs, Social
Security and Medicare, both of which will face serious financial
problems in coming decades.
</P>
<P>
   Under his new plan, Clinton will say that Social Security can be
put on sound footing until 2053, nearly two decades beyond the
point it will run into trouble if nothing is done. And he will call
for Medicare to get enough new financing to keep it solvent until
2027, an improvement of about a decade beyond current predictions.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said that with so much extra money now on the table _
the new projections show about $1 trillion available over the next
decade even without including excess Social Security revenues that
have swelled surplus figures in recent years _ Clinton will open
the door to a sizable tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Clinton had insisted that he would agree to a tax cut
only after Social Security's finances had been made stable for at
least 75 years, the actuarial benchmark for the retirement system's
solvency. His new approach implies that he would be willing to
consider a tax cut even if Social Security's solvency is not
guaranteed for that long.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Democrats said Clinton intended to demand that
Republicans accede to his approach to Social Security and Medicare
before considering tax cuts or allowing any substantial increase in
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are already calling for a tax cut of $775 billion
over the next decade, and the new surplus figures are certain to
make them more determined to return more money to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   But there is considerable pent-up demand for additional spending
within both parties, for purposes as varied as the military,
transportation, education and health.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, however, will not call for a removal of the tight
spending limits imposed on Congress by the bipartisan 1997 balanced
budget agreement, Democrats said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also wants his main tax-cut proposal, to provide
incentives for retirement savings to low- and middle-income
families, to get priority over Republican calls for tax-rate
reductions, reduced capital gains taxes, cuts in the estate tax and
other tax cuts at the top of the Republican wish list.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials declined to provide details of the budget
plan, which Clinton is scheduled to unveil early on Monday before
leaving on a fund-raising trip. Clinton is scheduled to unveil a
separate proposal on Tuesday for overhauling Medicare, the health
insurance system for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   But people who had been briefed on the White House plan said
Clinton would propose that starting in 2011, general tax revenues
be diverted to Social Security to help shore up the system as the
baby boom generation begins retiring in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   So robust is the expected flow of revenue into the Treasury
under the new White House proposals that by 2015, the government
will have paid off the entire $3 trillion in national debt held by
the public, they said.
</P>
<P>
   In putting out a proposal on Monday, Clinton is trying to get a
step ahead of the Republican leadership, which will have a new set
of surplus estimates available from the Congressional Budget Office
in the middle of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's new plan includes a revised version of a proposal that
the two parties have been jockeying over in Congress for several
months: a ``lock box'' to insure that the excess Social Security
revenues are not spent, but used only to reduce the national debt
or to insure the retirement system's long-term viability.
</P>
<P>
   In his original budget proposal in January, Clinton proposed
reserving 62 percent of the budget surplus over 15 years for Social
Security, but in a way that would allow him to spend a portion of
the Social Security surplus in the next few years. Both parties
have rejected that approach, and although they differ on details,
have basically endorsed setting aside every dollar of each year's
Social Security surplus.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said their new plan would respond to the
congressional criticism, and would also include a provision that
would link reducing the national debt to improving Social
Security's long-term financial condition.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The administration's original effort to do that in its January
budget was built around a complex proposal under which the benefits
of reducing the national debt would have been funneled to Social
Security in the form of new government bonds, an approach that
Republicans rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said the new plan would try to reach
the same end by different means.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very hopeful that the new presidential proposal, that
new Social Security lock box, will be a way of bringing together
both Democrats and Republicans,'' Gene Sperling, the director of
the White House's National Economic Council, told CNN's ``Late
Edition'' on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In part because of Clinton's ``Social Security first'' strategy,
the degree to which the two parties can agree on tax and spending
priorities seems largely to depend on whether they can make enough
progress on shoring up the retirement system to give them political
cover for using the surplus for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   With Republican efforts to pass spending bills in danger because
of the tight spending caps _ and with Clinton likely to veto the
$775 billion, 10-year tax cut they have in mind _ party leaders
have increasingly been banking on a budget windfall to help avoid
gridlock. House Speaker Dennis Hastert said last week that he
expected to promptly use any non-Social Security surpluses that
becomes available.
</P>
<P>
   But there are several different sets of ideas on what to do with
any windfall. Congressional Republicans will say it underlines the
good sense of tax cuts. Clinton indicated on Friday that he would
use the money as a way to help deal with both Medicare and Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   But House Democrats openly, and many Republicans quietly, see
new good news on the budget as the only way out of a spending box
they built in 1997. Then, they set tight caps on the amount of
money Congress could spend on the military and on domestic programs
other than Social Security, Medicare, welfare and other so-called
entitlement programs.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike agreeing on tax cuts or Medicare and Social Security
legislation, passing annual spending bills is something Congress
really has to do; it is Hastert's first priority. Right now the
process is in a shambles, with only the smallest bills coming to
the House floor and the Senate considering none of them at all.
</P>
<P>
   But the underlying problem is that the limits agreed to in 1997,
as some critics said at the time, are too low to maintain federal
programs at their current levels, making no additions except to
adjust for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Just to maintain domestic discretionary spending and allow for
inflation would require such spending to go to $299 billion in the
year beginning October 1, from $285 billion in the current year.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping defense spending level, except for inflation, would take
an increase to $268 billion, from $260 billion. And hardly anyone
wants to keep defense spending level, so under the overall caps,
the pinch on domestic spending is even tighter.
</P>
<P>
   Enforceable limits on federal spending, first enacted in 1990
and extended in 1993 and 1997, steadily applied the brakes to
growing deficits and were generally effective so long as balancing
the budget was a widely accepted goal.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the question is how to use surpluses, discipline in
pursuit of a more abstract kind of fiscal responsibility is less
attractive and harder to maintain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
