<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1490 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-REDS-HNS &LR;      06-28 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-REDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The road to the National League Central title may still go through
Houston, but if the past four days are any indication, it might not
be a bad idea to keep your eyes peeled for those exit signs marked
Cincinnati.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After being in the driver's seat for 57 consecutive days, the
Astros surrendered control to the Reds, who completed a four-game
sweep with a 5-2 victory Sunday at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this series was more like a carjacking. The Reds
pistol-whipped the Astros' pitchers and shot holes through their
hitters in a manner that was almost demoralizing. The Astros hit
.151 in the series and were outscored 26-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like they (the Reds) were playing against the last-place
team in baseball,'' said Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell, whose
only hits in the series were a pair of home runs. ``Obviously,
we're disappointed; we have to play better than this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds pulled even with the Astros in the standings but are
actually ahead by a percentage point. The new NL Central leaders
have won nine of their last 11 games, including seven in a row. The
Astros tied their season-worst losing streak with their fourth
straight defeat, and they have dropped nine of their last 13 games,
losing six games in the standings in the span of a week.
</P>
<P>
   The sweep marks the Astros' first in a four-game series at home
since the Reds turned the trick in June 1995 en route to the NL
Championship Series. The Astros no doubt hope history isn't in the
process of repeating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something is wrong, and we need to figure it out,'' said
Astros pitcher Jose Lima (11-4), who has lost two of his last three
starts and hasn't won since June 12. ``We're better than that, and
we need to do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to make any excuses or take anything away from
the Reds. Everything is going their way right now. They're doing
everything that you have to do to win games _ all of the little
things. Nothing is going our way right now, but I'll tell you one
thing: It's not over yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The best sight the Astros saw all weekend was the Reds' team bus
heading for the airport. The Astros are off today, and they'll try
to change their luck beginning Tuesday when the Cardinals check in
for a three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good time for an off day,'' Astros interim manager
Matt Galante said. ``We need to get away from the mental part of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite what appears to be a desperate situation, the Astros
insist they have not begun to panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know what the word means,'' Galante said.
</P>
<P>
   As a group, the Astros are having trouble with the meaning of a
certain three-letter word: H-I-T. They were held to five hits or
fewer in three of the four games against the Reds, and they are
hitting .204 in their last 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the worst we've played all year,'' said Astros third
baseman Bill Spiers, who was 0-for-13 in the series despite a .326
career batting average against the Reds. ``Hopefully, this is as
down as we'll get. They came in here on a high and really took it
to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Reds right fielder Michael Tucker, who is hitting .429 with
eight RBIs in his last five games, greeted Lima with a solo home
run in the first inning. Lima retired six of the next eight batters
he faced, including five on strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell's 24th homer, a solo shot into the loge level in left
field, tied the game in the fourth inning. But Reds starter Pete
Harnisch got all the support he needed in the sixth when Barry
Larkin and Eddie Taubensee stroked a couple of ground-ball singles
through the infield to account for all three runs in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lima gave us a chance to win the game,'' Galante said. ``We
just didn't get a very good offensive performance. Their pitching
just dominated us in this series.''
</P>
<P>
   Harnisch (7-6) left after five innings, and Friendswood native
Scott Williamson blew the Astros away with a wicked assortment of
pitches in three perfect relief innings that included four
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got as good a bullpen as anyone,'' Galante said.
``Once you get into their bullpen when they've got a lead, it's
tough to get anything going.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett's ninth-inning home run off Danny Graves confirmed
the Astros' pulse, but by then the real damage already had been
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can get any hotter than they are now,''
Astros second baseman Craig Biggio said of the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe the Astros can't get any colder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
