<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1492 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     06-28 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WIMBLEDON, England _ According to how some interpret the prophecies
of Nostradamus, the world is going to end Sunday, having been laid
to waste by the Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse. But it remains
unclear whether war, death, famine and plague will finish wreaking
their havoc at the behest of the King of Terror before, during or
after the men's final at Wimbledon. Nostradamus didn't give us a
time, just a rough date, presumed to be the first Sunday of July
1999.
</P>
<P>
   The foolhardy All England Club officials, however, seem thus far
disinclined to move the match up, playing the men as part of a
doubleheader with the women's final on Saturday, just to be on the
safe side. After all, Nostradamus appeared to have warned us about
the Great Fire of London, the French and Russian revolutions,
Hitler's rise to power, the Kennedy assassination and possibly the
Guf War, depending on how you decipher his admittedly ambiguous
prognostications.
</P>
<P>
   Wimbledon tends to believe it's above everything, though, rain
included. A pity, because the prospects for a Sampras-Agassi or
Sampras-Becker final are looming larger by the hour.
</P>
<P>
   For all the recent blather about ``girl power,'' about how the
women have gained the upper hand in tennis _ an apocalyptic notion
in its own right, according to those entrenched in their belief
they should compete for less prize money here _ the current
Wimbledon fortnight is now a bit of a throwback.
</P>
<P>
   There are nice stories on the ladies' side, but a preponderance
of the most compelling ones center on the blokes.
</P>
<P>
   Can Pete Sampras win a modern-day-record sixth title and thus
equal Roy Emerson's Grand Slam championship count of 12?
</P>
<P>
   Can Andre Agassi, born again as a contender, pull off the first
Roland Garros-Wimbledon double since Bjorn Borg's in 1980?
</P>
<P>
   Can Jim Courier, the forgotten American, shrug off the effects
of a bad cold, a case of severe dehydration and two five-set
first-week battles to reprise his run to the final in 1993?
</P>
<P>
   Can Todd Martin, the unsung American, join his aforementioned
mates in the Grand Slam club?
</P>
<P>
   Can Boris Becker, the erstwhile boy wonder who has come out of
semi-retirement for a last Wimbledon moment, pull off as amazing a
feat at 31 as the one he managed at 17?
</P>
<P>
   Can either Tim Henman or Greg Rusedski, England's pair of
long-ballyhooed, long-thwarted hopes, finally bring the title home
after a wait of more than six decades?
</P>
<P>
   Can Goran Ivanisevic, thrice the runner-up, end his personal
Centre Court agony?
</P>
<P>
   Can Patrick Rafter or Mark Philippoussis, two of Wimbledon's
most conspicuous underachievers, give back to the Australians the
championship that once seemed theirs by birthright?
</P>
<P>
   Can Gustavo Kuerten, the former French Open champ from Brazil
who still hasn't dropped a set, become the first resident South
American male (Alex Olmedo lived in California, not his native
Peru) to conquer the hallowed lawns?
</P>
<P>
   And one last question: Where's Nostradamus when you really need
an answer, when you'd like to lay a quid or two down on one of the
lads?
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Sampras gets past the Serb-turned-Canadian Daniel
Nestor in the fourth round _ and it's a safe assumption he will, no
matter how spotty his pre-Wimbledon play _ he'll face either
Rusedski or Philippoussis in the quarters, and likely either Henman
or Courier in the semis. No matter. He is the prohibitive favorite
until someone proves him otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Becker, the sentimental favorite for almost everyone except the
Henman-loving Brits, probably will have to go through Ivanisevic
and Agassi after Rafter to reach the final for the eighth time.
While his bid remains an improbable one, given that his third and
most recent championship came 10 years ago, only Sampras feels more
comfortable on Centre Court than Becker.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter, the GQ cover boy who answers to ``Stinky'' around his
mates, has won two U.S. Opens in a row but heretofore has only
stunk things up at Wimbledon, never advancing beyond the fourth
round despite being as well-suited for these lawns as the Aussie
titans of lore.
</P>
<P>
   Most ill-suited, of course, would be Kuerten, a resolute
baseliner. But ``Guga'' can draw inspiration from Agassi, his next
obstacle if he survives Lorenzo Manta, a Swiss-Italian. Andre is
the decade's lone groundstroker to prevail at Wimbledon, having
begun Ivanisevic's enduring agony in the final of seven summers
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Goran, there's a reason to finally like his chances.
With his dark, haunting eyes, beard and flowing hair, he actually
bears a slight resemblance to the drawings we have of Nostradamus.
</P>
<P>
   Prophetic?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
