<HEADER>
A1500 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-SANCTION-     06-28 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-SANCTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LA LOSES MINOR LEAGUERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an unprecedented decision, Major League Baseball has stripped
the Los Angeles Dodgers of two promising minor leaguers who accused
the team of holding secret tryouts in Cuba and arranging the
players' defections in violation of major league rules.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Carlos Diaz, a first baseman, and outfielder Josue Perez
were informed Friday by their managers that they had been granted
free agency, the players said. Diaz and Perez had asked to be
released from their contracts, arguing that the Dodgers had denied
them the opportunity to obtain fair contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions, which have not been announced by baseball's
Commissioner's Office, also are believed to include a heavy fine
against the Dodgers for violating rules against scouting in Cuba.
It is unclear whether the club also violated a US trade embargo
that prohibits American companies from conducting business on the
Communist-ruled island.
</P>
<P>
   The Commissioner's Office was not available for comment Sunday.
In a release, the Dodgers said they would abide by the
Commissioner's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz, who was hitting .303 with nine homers and 52 RBIs in 66
games at Double A San Antonio, and Perez, who was hitting .279 with
14 stolen bases at Single A Vero Beach, are now eligible to sign
with other teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just told the truth, and we were asking them to do what was
just, what was right,'' Perez said in a telephone interview. ``But
we have mixed feelings. We have a lot of friends with the
Dodgers.''
</P>
<P>
   The case, which was first reported by the Globe last month,
marks the first time a team has been caught scouting in Cuba. It
also represents perhaps the most extraordinary scheme by a major
league club to tap into a goldmine of Cuban baseball talent that
remains largely hidden despite dozens of defections over the past
eight years.
</P>
<P>
   In separate incidents in 1996 and 1997, Pablo Peguero, a scout
who also heads the Dodgers' baseball academy in the Dominican
Republic, entered Cuba by posing as a tourist and made contact with
Diaz, Perez, and several other players he apparently was interested
in signing.
</P>
<P>
   According to Diaz, Peguero videotaped a secret tryout for him on
the outskirts of Havana in 1996. Perez said Peguero returned and
held a tryout for him in 1997. In both cases, the players said
Peguero then helped them obtain visas by having women _ in one case
the scout's cousin _ pose as their girlfriends. The women told
Cuban immigration authorities that they had invited the players to
visit the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Once Diaz and Perez were in the Dominican Republic, the women
disappeared, and the players were placed at the Dodger baseball
academy. With no prior negotiations, and without allowing the
players to be represented by an agent, Peguero signed the players _
Diaz for $65,000, Perez for $40,000 _ and told them they should
tell people they came to the Dominican Republic on their own if
they ever were asked about it.
</P>
<P>
   Gus Dominguez, the players' Los Angeles-based agent, said the
case was an indication of the heavy demand for Cuban players and
``lack of respect'' on the part of the Dodgers. ``They thought they
were bigger than baseball and they're not,'' Dominguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Peguero and Ralph Avila, a Dodgers senior vice president who was
involved in the signings, initially denied the charges. But the
Dodgers later released a statement saying they would cooperate with
an investigation by Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, the team and its supporters argued that the players
should have been grateful for the Dodgers' assistance in getting
them out of Cuba. They noted that the players waited three years to
file the grievance, during which the demand for Cuban players has
continued to skyrocket.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz and Perez said they were interviewed by baseball
investigators for three hours about the incident. Although they
were notified Friday that they had been granted free agency, the
Dodgers apparently began to prepare for the decision as early as
last Wednesday, when they abruptly pulled Perez out of the Vero
Beach lineup. Diaz was pulled from the lineup the following day,
Dominguez said, and was told he could attend the game only as a
spectator.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the club told the players that they would be sent back
to the Dominican Republic. Perez said he was told that Dominguez
would be waiting there for him. When he called his agent, who was
holding tryouts for 11 other Cuban players in San Jose, Costa Rica,
he learned that he had been misled.
</P>
<P>
   Dominguez put the players on a flight to Los Angeles, where they
are expected to attend a press conference early this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 0054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
