<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1501 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      06-28 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT THEATER DOESN'T NEED A GREAT THEATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As the building's unofficial mom, Carol Keaton, the
Kingdome media manager, has a favorite baseball story about her
concrete child.
</P>
<P>
   More than an hour after the Mariners defeated the Yankees in the
1995 American League Division Series, including the final one in
soul-sapping fashion, George Steinbrenner trudged solemnly out of
the Kingdome's visitor dugout onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   The bombastic Yankees owner, long contemptuous of Seattle
baseball and a leader in the fight against the Mariners'
Japanese-led ownership, encountered an acquaintance, Kingdome boss
Vern Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner and his entourage paused as Wagner politely allowed
as to how the Yankees had had some good luck in the past, but ...
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``This building,'' he said gravely, ``killed us.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Ken Griffey Jr. Not Alex Rodriguez. Not Randy Johnson. Not
Edgar Martinez. Not even Jay Buhner, whom Steinbrenner handed to
the Mariners in his most knuckleheaded trade as Yankee strongman.
</P>
<P>
   The Kingdome doomed 'em. For the series' final three games, the
Yankees stood in the middle of an audio riot, nearly helpless and
all but defeated.
</P>
<P>
   While the players would be hard pressed to quantify just how
difficult was the task, when was the last time the recently
dynastic Yankees lost three straight postseason games?
</P>
<P>
   Renowned as a magnet for derision, yes, the Kingdome was also
the decibel's best friend; sufficient to make Steinbrenner, one of
the more reviled figures in American sport, eat local dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Fenway has the Monster. Wrigley has the ivy. Yankee Stadium has
the monuments. The Kingdome had the reverb.
</P>
<P>
   Esthetically speaking, the other trademarks are preferable. But
for wins, take the noise and give the runs.
</P>
<P>
   Worked for the Minnesota Twins, world champions in 1987 and
1991. Their beauty-free yard, the Metrodome, was a large factor in
producing the last baseball title for a small-market team.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Mariner ownerships have never been as successful
in taking advantage of their park. Complaining, it seems, is much
easier than building a team that exploits the home field.
</P>
<P>
   For four years, the noise, fans and enthusiasm have been there.
As one playoff win in the last three seasons suggests, the talent
has not.
</P>
<P>
   But at least for a day, the final day, the imagination was
ignited again. The 40th and last sellout in the Kingdome turned
into an unlikely storybook fiesta of camera-flash baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching: Four innings of shutout relief!
</P>
<P>
   Fielding: Griffey reaches over the fence to save a three-run
home run!
</P>
<P>
   Hitting: Griffey hits a three-run home run!
</P>
<P>
   Running: Catcher Dan Wilson steals a base! A streaker briefly
steals the show!
</P>
<P>
   Griping: Edgar Martinez gets thrown out for arguing strikes!
</P>
<P>
   Winning: Mariners, 5-2!
</P>
<P>
   Please excuse the exclamation points, the last refuge of a
desperate writer. But when that many rare, even unique, Mariner
developments collide in front of a full house in farewell pucker,
well, writing ``gee whiz'' a dozen times gets a little busy.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in a well-done post-game ceremony that featured Mariner
old-timers as well as the current heroes and Ken Griffey the Dad,
well, a standing O for the day was irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   For a franchise that has been stepping on rakes with remarkable
consistency lately, Sunday's celebration was welcome relief.
</P>
<P>
   The decibels came home, the fun was back, and the gee was whiz.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey was at the epicenter, accounting, with his catch and his
homer, for a six-run turnaround. Even when he struck out with the
bases loaded in the eighth inning, the tingle was better than 98
percent of the past NBA season.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the coolest thing for him about the whole day was the
fact that his dad was flown in from his coaching job with the
Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   It was a baseball reunion of that day in 1990 when they took to
the Kingdome outfield, the first father and son tandem in major
league history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something no one else has done,'' he said Sunday. ``It
means a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey continues to do many things no one else is doing,
including increasing his mastery of theater. For the last of the
more than 32 million fans to witness Kingdome baseball, Griffey
launched the building's final homer, and made sure by denying the
opponent a checkmate.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great day for Junior,'' said manager Lou Piniella, ``and a
great day for fans at the Kingdome.''
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion of baseball's history at the Kingdome also made
the point that great theater doesn't need a great theater. What it
needs are good actors, rich with passion and commitment and wrapped
in history.
</P>
<P>
   For a day, the Mariners had it all, loudly.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
