<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S WANT MORE OFF-SPEED PITCHES FROM BULLPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ More than anything else, Stan Williams believes, the
problem with the Mariners bullpen has been a reluctance to throw
breaking pitches. Jose Paniagua and Jose Mesa have fastballs in the
mid-90s, but they need more than that to get by.
</P>
<P>
   ``This league hits fastballs,'' said Williams, the Mariners'
pitching coach. ``If they come in and get behind with the fastball,
then they have one thing to go to _ the fastball. Hitters can turn
it up a notch and sit on it.''
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's game, when Paniagua allowed a three-run,
game-tying double to the Rangers' Roberto Kelly, Williams spoke to
Paniagua about throwing more breaking pitches, mimicking various
grips as he talked.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua said he has been giving up too many hits off his
slider, but pledged to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to throw more inside, more breaking balls,'' Paniagua
said. ``That's what (manager) Lou (Piniella) asked me. More
split-fingers, everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, he was using his split-finger more effectively,''
Williams said. ``This year, he'll throw one warming up and bounces
it, so he quits on it. We're trying to get it back so he uses it in
ballgames, along with his slider. They're both excellent pitches
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa also had gotten away from off-speed pitches, but used more
in Saturday's save, getting a check-swing groundout on a slider the
Rangers weren't expecting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to mix it up, off-speed and fastball,'' Mesa
said after saving Sunday's game. ``If you use just fastballs, no
matter how hard you throw it, they still can hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   STARS AND STARTERS: Left-hander Jamie Moyer is on schedule to
start the opening game at Safeco Field July 15, but that could
change if Moyer is selected for the All-Star Game _ ``which he
deserves to be,'' said Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   Both Moyer and Freddy Garcia will be rested if chosen for the
game in Boston on July 13. Moyer makes his last start July 7 in
Anaheim, Garcia July 9 in Los Angeles. If Moyer is selected and
pitches in Boston, Garcia would be the likely Safeco starter.
</P>
<P>
   If Piniella has any say, both Moyer and Garcia will make the
All-Star team. Each year the American League asks managers to pick
an All-Star pitching staff, with the results weighing heavily in
the league's selection process. Among Piniella's choices: Garcia,
Moyer and standout rookies Jeff Weaver of the Detroit Tigers and
Jim Parque of the Chicago White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   THUMB FOR EDGAR: One unlikely ``last'' at the Kingdome was the
last ejection _ mild-mannered designated hitter Edgar Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was thrown out by home plate umpire Brian O'Nora, who
earlier had tossed Texas manager Johnny Oates and shortstop Royce
Clayton. Martinez was upset after striking out in the seventh
inning on a pitch he said M's pitchers had not been getting for
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK if it's for everybody,'' Martinez said. ``I would
have no objection. But when you see the other guy getting them and
not your own guy _ I didn't mean to insult him, but I just really
wanted to let him know.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, whose only previous ejection came at Boston on Aug.
23, 1996, said he told O'Nora, ``Just call it the same both ways.''
</P>
<P>
   MINOR MOVES: The Mariners sent 19-year-old left-hander Andrew
VanHekken to the Detroit Tigers Sunday as one of the two players to
be named later in the trade that brought outfielder Brian Hunter to
Seattle. VanHekken, a native of Holland, Mich., was 6-3 with a 4.43
earned run average at rookie league Peoria last year. He was the
M's third-round choice in the 1998 draft.
</P>
<P>
   While VanHekken was going, Cha Sueng Baek was reporting to
Peoria, nearly four months late. Baek, a 19-year-old right-hander
with a Freddy Garcia build, was considered the top high school
pitching prospect in South Korea when he signed with the M's last
September for $1.3 million. His military obligation was the main
issue holding him back in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Class AAA right-hander Kevin Hodges, acquired from Houston for
Matt Mieske last week, threw six scoreless innings Saturday in his
Tacoma debut.
</P>
<P>
   BUHNER UPDATE: Right fielder Jay Buhner (strained left
hamstring) will resume running tomorrow, and told Piniella he's
hoping to be playing again by the start of the Mariners' series in
Anaheim on July 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
