<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1506 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KINGDOME-SPI &LR;      06-28 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KINGDOME-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KINGDOME GOES OUT ON WINNING NOTE, AWASH IN MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELLIS E. CONKLIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For more than three emotion-chilled hours Sunday
afternoon, no one cared to call it the Dump on the Duwamish.
</P>
<P>
   No, the Kingdome on its final date with baseball _ this ungainly
pill of a pillbox, celebrated as a practical, no-frills and at
times heroic home to a generation of fans _ was bathed in memories.
</P>
<P>
   Eyes misted and goose bumps flared during a touching postgame
memoir as thrilling highlights of past victories danced on the
DiamondVision screen. At every turn, the magic playoff ride of 1995
was invoked. A father hugged his son as they watched a replay of
the decisive 11th inning of Game 5 of the division playoff series
between the Mariners and New York Yankees that culminated with Ken
Griffey Jr. beaming beneath a pile of giddy teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Current Mariner stars and past legends like Ruppert Jones, Julio
Cruz, Bill Caudill, Alvin Davis, Dave Valle, Dave Henderson, Harold
Reynolds, and, of course, Gaylord Perry, who notched his 300th
victory at the Dome, made a slow promenade in from center field
amid a burst of fireworks and green lasers. It was a Mariner
version of the Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies and gentlemen, this place has been called an ugly
duckling by a lot of people. She's always been beautiful to me,''
bellowed Dave Niehaus, the radio and TV voice of the Mariners since
their first season 22 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The last ceremonial pitch was, fittingly enough, tossed for a
strike by 7-year-old Corey Segui, son of Mariner first baseman
David Segui and grandson of Diego Segui, who started the Mariners'
first game on April 6, 1977. After the pitch, a sea of blue and
silver confetti poured down on the green carpet.
</P>
<P>
   From Diego to David Segui, from Danny Kaye to John Ellis, it was
the ecstasies of 22 seasons _ not the agonies _ that were recalled
by a raucous sellout crowd of 56,530.
</P>
<P>
   And, on this last game of 1,755 contests the Mariners played at
the Dome, the home team beat the Texas Rangers, 5-2. The final
tally: 852 wins and 903 losses, witnessed by 32,668,785 fans.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, a playoff atmosphere enveloped Pioneer Square.
Thousands of fans, many toting souvenir oversized tickets suitable
for framing, lined up in front of the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   At Gate D stood Don Harrington. First in line. He had arrived at
8:20 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched them build this. I needed to be here,'' Harrington
said.
</P>
<P>
   At Gate B, Janet Longley waited with her two young sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally got to take them to a game,'' she said. ``Made it
just in time, didn't I? I really wanted them to see the Kingdome.
People have made a lot of fun of it, but they're going to miss it
when it's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   At 10:40 a.m., most of the Mariners were still in street
clothes, just beginning to dress for the game. The locker room was
quiet. Only the murmur of the Yankee-Oriole game on a television
could be heard. Edgar Martinez was getting a haircut. Ken Griffey
Jr. was playing ball with his son Trey, and chatting with his
father, Ken Griffey Sr., who is the batting coach with the
Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Mariners General Manager) Woody (Woodward) told me to come on
out. Said I owed him a favor,'' Griffey Sr. said with a grin.
</P>
<P>
   David Segui said the thought of moving into Safeco Field on July
15 hasn't dawned on him yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really a sentimental person. Maybe 'cause players are
used to moving around,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Segui said his father planned to attend the game, but there was
a mix-up with his plane ticket.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:25, Ramiro Garcia was manicuring home plate with a broom.
Garcia has been a groundskeeper at the Dome the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sad,'' he said. ``Tomorrow, and no more. Very sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariner spokesman Tim Hevly celebrated his 11th birthday at the
Kingdome, which will be demolished next year to make room for the
new Seahawks stadium. He said he's going to miss it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A whole generation has moved through here, the first one ever
to see major league baseball. Now we're moving on,'' Hevly said.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Richards of Seattle said he had tickets to the game on the
infamous evening of July 19, 1994, when three 12-pound wood-fiber
roof tiles tumbled into the box seats of Section 113 between home
plate and first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still keep those tickets,'' Richards said. ``For me, it sort
of represents the worst moment the Kingdome ever had. But things
got better here. The Dome is going out in style today.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:35, the gates opened and thousands pushed their way past
the turnstiles. The Moose, the Mariner mascot, signed commemorative
``I Was There'' T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before noon, dueling signs lined the perimeter
mezzanines _ a testament to mixed feelings. ``Thanks for the
Memories'' read some of them. Said another: ``Out with the Old. In
with the View.''
</P>
<P>
   On the concourse outside the 300 level, Elane Roberts puffed on
a cigarette and gazed out at the shimmering glass and steel that is
Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to be so cold over there. We're not used to
outdoor baseball,'' said Roberts, who attended the Mariner opener
on April 6, 1977 _ a 7-0 loss to the then-California Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I raised my kids here. I wanted to take my grandkids, too, so
this is a difficult day for me.''
</P>
<P>
   At 12:40 p.m., Irene Strait, an usher for 21 years, was working
her customary aisle 109 on the 100 level behind home plate where
the Mariner wives sit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm crying already,'' she said. ``I don't know what it'll be
like after the game. This is it for me. My knees have pretty well
given out.''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, while Annie Tonda was serving up her last
meal in the media cafeteria, Jay Buhner was ruminating in the
locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll miss it here. This has been my security blanket. After
almost 11 years, I know every nook and cranny of right field,''
said the ailing Buhner, who signed more than a dozen bats for
Kingdome workers.
</P>
<P>
   At 1:29, the national anthem for the last baseball game at the
Kingdome was sung by county-western singer Lila McCann, who's from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd rose as one as the Mariners took the field at 1:37.
The first pitch came two minutes later when Freddy Garcia served up
a ball to Rangers center fielder Tom Goodwin.
</P>
<P>
   At 1:55, the Mariners down 2-0, Rick Kaminski, ``The Peanut
Man,'' took a break in the peanut-tossing action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen families grow up here,'' he mused. ``Kids that I've
known have brought their own kids to see me. It's been a wonderful
time. A great trip.''
</P>
<P>
   At 2:04, Griffey strode to the plate. Everywhere, miniature
lights flashed from snapping cameras. Two minutes later, he crushed
a line-drive homer to right field, a three-run blast. It was his
198th round-tripper at the Dome, and it would be the last ever
belted by a Mariner at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   At 3, Griffey raised the roof again with a leaping,
over-the-fence catch to rob Juan Gonzales of a three-run homer. The
crowd's roar was deafening.
</P>
<P>
   At 3:25, Lester Smith, who was part of the original ownership
group that included entertainer Danny Kaye, was rooting in the
owners box along with Ellis, Sen. Slade Gorton, and former King
County executive John Spellman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' said Smith, pointing downward to the spirited crowd,
``look at the enjoyment this (Dome) has given all these people.
Baseball would not be here without it.''
</P>
<P>
   At 3:41, the hydroplane races appeared on the screen for the
last time.
</P>
<P>
   At 4:04, a streaker, whom police declined to identify, was in a
holding cell at the Kingdome before being booked for second-degree
trespassing. Seattle Police Officer Larry Harvey called him
``Tarzan.'' In the bottom of the seventh inning, the young man, in
jock strap and sneakers, sprinted into left field, where he
performed a cartwheel before being spiritedaway.
</P>
<P>
   At 4:28, Griffey struck out swinging with the bases loaded on a
1-2 count from Rangers rookie Mike Venafro. He was the last Mariner
to bat at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   At 4:40, Rusty Greer lifted a long fly ball to left field that
Brian Hunter easily hauled in, and that was it. Baseball was over
at the Dome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
