<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INKSTER SLAMS DOOR 
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ Juli Inkster made an emotional walk into the
history books of the game Sunday on a sultry afternoon out here in
the Brandywine Valley, becoming just the second woman and sixth
player overall to win golf's Grand Slam when she slammed the door
shut on her pursuers with an eagle-birdie-birdie finish to win the
LPGA Championship at DuPont CC. She joined Pat Bradley as the
second to win the modern women's slam.
</P>
<P>
   It was a shining moment, as Inkster pumped her fists after she
holed a birdie putt on the 18th green and was engulfed by the noise
of a roaring crowd fully aware of her accomplishment. Just three
weeks ago at Old Waverly GC in steamy West Point, Miss., Inkster
had won the US Women's Open. She'd earlier won the Dinah Shore (in
1984 and 1989) and the du Maurier (1984), the last two of the four
tournaments that make up the modern slam. (Mickey Wright and Louise
Suggs won a slam when two of the tourneys were different).
</P>
<P>
   Inkster, who turned 39 just three days ago, completed her run
with a 6-under-par 65 Sunday for a 16-under 268 to beat persistent
challenger Liselotte Neumann (68) by four shots after her
four-birdie barrage wilted in the face of Inkster's heroic finish.
Nancy Scranton faltered late and settled for a 70, winding up in a
tie for third at 273 with early finisher Mardi Lunn (66) as a
jammed leaderboard broke up in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Embracing younger daughter Cori, with older daughter Haley at
her side, Inkster had been mother, chef, and bottle washer this
week. She also had a magic wand on the greens as she saved pars on
the 13th and 14th, ran in an eagle putt with a perfect right-left
curl from 15 feet on the 16th, hit an 8-iron into the par 3 17th
and made a 3-foot putt, and made the 25-foot putt for birdie on 18.
</P>
<P>
   This completed a remarkable run. She said Saturday she felt
there was more pressure to win the US Women's Open because she had
a four-shot lead entering the final round. ``Here it's really
anybody's tournament,'' she said. Six players either led outright
or shared the lead Sunday. ``It's the person who's going to make
the least amount of mistakes,'' Inkster said. She has a 68.6 stroke
average in the first three majors this year, with the du Maurier to
come.
</P>
<P>
   If Inkster needed something to jump start her round with so many
players in the hunt, it came with birdies on the eighth (5 iron, 20
feet) and par 5 ninth (sand wedge, 15 feet) to get to 12 under. The
killer touch started at the par-3 13th, where she saved par, and
the par-4 14th, when she saved it out of a trap. The two putts were
of 8 feet. ``Those were key,'' she said. Then came the finishing
stretch; she had just seven putts over the final six holes and only
15 over the last 12 holes. That is how you win majors, just ask
Payne Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   After the walk up the hill on the 18th after she struck a 7-iron
second shot to 25 feet, she made the putt and promptly realized she
had become a part of the game's lore. She also took a giant step
toward getting into the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   The last player with a realistic chance to catch Inkster was
Neumann, whose first victory was the US Women's Open 11 years ago
when she was just 22. After she made her fourth birdie on the
incoming nine, hitting out of a bunker to 4 feet on the 16th, she
could hear the roars of the crowd behind her. ``I felt if I could
birdie 17 or 18 I might have a chance,'' she said. ``I hit a good
shot on 17, but I got a bad kick. I gave myself a good opportunity
on 18 maybe. I was walking up and saw Juli had eagled 16 so that's
where I was at that point. I was putting for second.''
</P>
<P>
   So this was Inkster's day to bask in the hazy sunshine. She's
balanced her life between family, her home in Palo Alto, Calif.,
and the LPGA Tour. ``I saved par on seven,'' she said after she
surged past Karrie Webb to the top of the LPGA money list, ``and
that really got me going. I played well today. There were a lot of
people in it. I hit my career shot on 16, and then to make that
putt was an electric feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to calm down a little bit. I knew had a two-shot lead.
When I finally got to 18, it was putting into a bucket. I just knew
it was going in. I always thought I wanted to win the four majors.
I won two really quick, and I wondered if I was ever going to win
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be able to sit back and really reflect on it later,
because it is quite an accomplishment. I felt a lot of pressure at
the Open because I felt it was my tournament. This tournament was
anybody's tournament.''
</P>
</TEXT>
