<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1510 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-WHITESOX-B     06-28 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX KNUCKLE UNDER 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-WHITE SOX-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Tim Wakefield could walk into any VFW club or American
Legion hall in a six-state radius and be given the same advice.
</P>
<P>
   Never volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   But there are enough Purple Hearts floating around to show that
the vets often ignored their own counsel. And while Wakefield took
a hit in Sunday's 7-6 loss to the White Sox, blowing a save for the
first time since he agreed to serve as closer in Tom Gordon's
absence, he wasn't looking for the nearest foxhole for refuge.
</P>
<P>
   On a day the Sox led, 5-0, after two innings, Wakefield was
unable to hold a two-run lead in a ninth inning that began with
third baseman Lou Merloni's second throwing error of the game and
reached its nadir when reserve infielder Craig Wilson hit a two-run
homer that put Chicago ahead. The knuckleballer, who had been
perfect on the seven previous occasions he'd been called upon to
protect a Sox advantage, was asked if it might be best to be thrust
in the same circumstances ASAP.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, I've never been in this situation,'' Wakefield
said. ``I'm doing it on a volunteer basis.''
</P>
<P>
   With Gordon out indefinitely with a bad elbow, Wakefield is in
for a longer tour of duty in the bullpen than he anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever it takes,'' he said. ``I've always been the type of
guy who tries to help the ball club win. Obviously, I didn't get it
done today. But I'd like to get back out there tomorrow and redeem
myself a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox appeared well on their way to their third straight
win over their pale cousins when Troy O'Leary doubled home two runs
in the first and Nomar Garciaparra hit a three-run double in the
second, extending his hitting streak to 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they were left to sort through the surprise of losing
for only the third time in 45 games in which they'd led after eight
innings. The loss, which ended their four-game winning streak and
was only their second in the last nine games, dropped them two
games behind the Yankees in the AL East for the first time since
May 13.
</P>
<P>
   At first, manager Jimy Williams tried explaining that these
things happen. ``They happen because they've got heartbeats, that's
what makes them people,'' he said. ``You can't be perfect all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   But when he sensed that his interrogators smelled blood,
Williams took another tack. ``The cup's half empty around here,''
he said. ``Mine's half full.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager's patience went on life support when someone with a
microphone asked him if there were times he went home wishing he
could do some things differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Little League team do you coach?'' Williams said evenly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played in Braintree,'' his questioner replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Braintree surgeon,'' Williams said, pulling out the
Jimywocky.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, his questioner tried to get in the last word,
assuring Williams he wasn't pursuing a negative course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' Williams said. ``Not in New England.''
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox teed off on rookie Brian Rose in the fourth, when
Frank Thomas homered past the TV cameras in center, Greg Norton
cranked one into the right-field grandstand, Brook Fordyce hit the
next pitch for a double, and Wilson, a light-hitting backup whose
previous 10 hits this season were singles, hit his first home run
into the left-field screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got a five-run lead, you want to get your team
back in the dugout as soon as you can and stay away from the big
inning,'' Rose said. ``Unfortunately, that didn't happen today.
Basically, one pitch hurt me, and that was my slider. It was pretty
flat that inning. The hanging slider got me today. There weren't
many, but they hit 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who hadn't given up three home runs in an inning since
Jose Canseco's Oakland A's hit four in the third inning Aug. 21,
1997, suddenly went from tanning salon to sweatbox in Sunday's
88-degree temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Lowe, who spelled Rose after the fifth, kept the heat from
rising with three hitless innings of relief. But the Sox left the
bases loaded in the fifth, when Creighton Gubanich was called out
on strikes, and in the sixth, Merloni and Garciaparra both bounced
out with Darren Lewis on third with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when Chicago third baseman Norton made his third error of
the game, throwing away Jason Varitek's grounder, and easily could
have been charged with a fourth when Merloni singled off his glove
to score Varitek, the Sox had a two-run lead and Wakefield on deck
for the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   But Merloni, who earlier was wide with a sidearm throw for a
no-harm, no-foul error in the third, threw high to first baseman
Mike Stanley on Carlos Lee's bouncer to start the ninth. ``That
second one, I rushed it,'' Merloni said. ``It was an aggressive
play, but I threw a little high.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I caught it and tagged (Lee) in the head, but he was already
on the bag,'' Stanley said. ``A little sooner, and it would have
been no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Norton then lined a ball off Stanley's glove for a double.
``Tipped off the top of my glove,'' Stanley said. ``I was never
very good at jumping.''
</P>
<P>
   Fordyce's sacrifice fly made it 6-5, and Wilson then buried a
1-and-0 pitch into the screen. Stanley drew a leadoff walk in the
bottom of the ninth, but was erased in a game-ending double play
turned by shortstop Mike Caruso, who made a diving stop of Reggie
Jefferson's grounder up the middle, then flipped to Wilson, who
ignored oncoming pinch runner Trot Nixon to finish off the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like they stole one from us,'' said Merloni, who has
spent the week bouncing from second to short to third. ``The
biggest thing for me here is my defense, but I didn't do the things
I need to do. Every play counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in Braintree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
