u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS &LR;      06-28 1384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH SET TO MAKE WIMBLEDON RACKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ They waited late into the moonless English night. Their
vigil was illuminated only by the wan light from the corridor to
the players' locker room at the All England Club. It was witnessed
only by the skeletal security force eager to close up shop some two
hours after the day's final match concluded at about 8:30.
</P>
<P>
   There were approximately 30 of them, mostly teenagers, and they
were armed with cameras, programs, scraps of paper, and symbols of
their allegiance, such as the Union Jack that served as a wrap for
one girl. They stood alongside and atop the railing that prevented
them from gaining access to the silver van waiting outside the
doorway, protected by a lone sentry.
</P>
<P>
   At last, the reason they had sacrificed most of their social
opportunities on a Friday night appeared. Greg Rusedski emerged
from the darkness into the adulation as the throng besieged and
beseeched him, congratulated and exhorted him. While camera flashes
dotted the night like shooting stars, Rusedski obliged his
constituency by signing whatever was thrust at him for two minutes.
Then he climbed into the van and was off. Unsated, the entourage
followed the vehicle off the grounds like dogs mesmerized by
spinning tires.
</P>
<P>
   Such is this nation's craving for a male Wimbledon champion that
it is willing to embrace a player who is British by virtue of
loophole, not birth. Rusedski was born in Montreal, son of a
Canadian father, and he capitalized on his mother's English
citizenship to migrate to this more accommodating tennis climate.
He has no more of a British accent than does Wayne Gretzky, but
that is utterly irrelevant to the true believers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows his roots,'' said one of the hardy souls who wouldn't
leave the grounds until catching a glimpse of him.
</P>
<P>
   And the Brits know what they're rooting for. They are the Red
Sox fans of tennis, having waited 63 years since the reign of Fred
Perry (1934-36) for another British Wimbledon king. If Jack the
Ripper could win on the final Sunday at Centre Court, they'd
probably exalt him.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, they now have two more appealing _ and likelier _
candidates. Ninth seed Rusedski and No. 6 Tim Henman, a born and
bred Brit, have advanced into Monday's round of 16, launching the
second week of The Championships, when, as Rusedski observed after
his third-round victory over Magnus Norman, it truly is anybody's
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The natives are counting on two people in particular, though
neither is guaranteed survival even until midnight Monday. Monday
afternoon lefthander Rusedski will exchange bullets with the only
man on the ATP Tour whose serves can keep up with his,
seventh-seeded Mark Philippoussis. Even more daunting _
psychologically, at least _ Henman will oppose rough-and-ready Jim
Courier. The resilient veteran's last visit to this side of the
Atlantic, in behalf of the American Davis Cup team in April at
Birmingham, was punctuated by indelible five-set triumphs over
Henman and Rusedski, the latter in the fifth and deciding match,
which came down to an 8-6 climax.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted no less a tormentor than former Wimbledon champion
John McEnroe, who is here to play mixed doubles with Steffi Graf
and to talk trash on television, to observe derisively, ``The Brits
are sweating now because of Courier. They choked their fannies off
at Birmingham.''
</P>
<P>
   Bizarre anatomical imagery aside, the British get the point. The
fact is: That loss two months ago still haunts them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to win this match desperately,'' said Henman.
</P>
<P>
   But if both somehow get through to Friday _ and Rusedski, in all
likelihood, would have to confront five-time titlist Pete Sampras
first _ it would create an all-English semifinal. The Empire just
might not survive the delirium, for that would guarantee either a
native or adopted son in the championship match.
</P>
<P>
   Until the arrival of Henman and Rusedski _ both born,
portentously enough, on the same date, Sept. 6, though Rusedski,
25, is a year older _ the British haven't had even a middling male
contender since Roger Taylor gained the semis twice in the early
'70s.
</P>
<P>
   It's not for lack of trying. Asked what has ailed British tennis
in the interim, Henman said, ``How long have you got? It's
hopefully beginning to change, and you've seen some of the results.
The likes of (Arvind) Parmar and (Jamie) Delgado and (Miles)
MacLagan'' _ youngsters who were eliminated in the first week but
performed credibly _ ``those are the guys, I think, that need to
keep making that sort of progress. And you look at our (junior)
results at 15 and 16, I think they are much better now. You'd still
have to question perhaps the problem we've had in the past in
making that transition from the junior game to the senior game.
Hopefully, some of those guys can really come through and start
pushing myself and Greg at the top of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Rusedski wouldn't mind the company, either. ``Hopefully, players
like Miles and Arvind can build from those experiences and not just
play extremely well at Wimbledon, but take it on all year round,''
he said. ``Hopefully, with the right coaching and the right people
behind them and the right belief, they can move up in the world
rankings and make a positive start from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Henman and Rusedski are it. Or, more precisely,
they're It. They represent England's lone semblance of success on
the world stage. Henman was a semifinalist here last year, a
quarterfinalist the two years before that, and Rusedski was a
quarterfinalist in 1997, the year he nearly made his Grand Slam
breakthrough, losing in the US Open final to Patrick Rafter.
</P>
<P>
   Those achievements are relatively modest in comparison to those
of, say, the Americans and Australians and Swedes. But the British
will take what they can get. And while tennis is no better than
third in the sports pecking order here _ behind soccer and cricket
and perhaps even rugby union _ Wimbledon is this nation's World
Series, Super Bowl, NBA Finals, and Stanley Cup finals rolled into
one.
</P>
<P>
   So Henman and Rusedski are bona fide idols, endorsement
millionaires whose every move, breath, and thought is scrutinized
and dissected by the voracious London tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, this is a fortnight in a fishbowl for them.
Henman rediscovered this to his chagrin last Monday when he was
asked about the women pros' campaign seeking earnings parity with
the men in Grand Slam events. He dismissed the crusade as ``getting
a bit greedy'' _ and set off a firestorm. By Thursday, a chastened
Henman said, ``Those comments I made, in hindsight, they probably
created a lot more attention than I wanted. So that's it. I learned
my lesson, and no more talking about equal prize money.''
</P>
<P>
   Rusedski, who grew up in an environment where a tennis player
wouldn't inspire even a yawn unless he wore skates on the court, is
perhaps more tolerant and appreciative of the attention _ all
right, the mania; what else could you call a legion of followers
wearing, red, white, or blue clown wigs, with ``Tim'' or ``Greg''
inscribed on their faces and the Union Jack functioning as an
article of clothing, at each Henman and Rusedski match? And the
demands they bring with them may not be as evident, but they're
palpable nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just the British public wants a Wimbledon
champion so bad because the last champion was Fred Perry in 1936,''
said Rusedski. ``And I think Tim and I have a great opportunity. I
think this year (the expectations are) more than ever. I think for
myself and for Tim, they really want us to do well. You see a lot
of people face-painted, you know, with either Tim's name or banners
with Tim, or faces painted with my name on it, and things like
that. So it's very nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Henman knows that nice isn't enough. The Wimbledon obsession has
been ingrained in him almost since birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biggest, best tournament,'' he said. ``It's where I've always
wanted to play. I realized pretty young that this is what I wanted
to do, and now I'm doing it, I realize I don't want to be just
playing here. I want to win here.''
</P>
<P>
   He shares that sentiment with a nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
