</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMILTON SET TO LET IT RIP IN NBA 
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-HAMILTON-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   His memories of them are so sharp that you wonder if he is
looking at their photographs. You can ask him about the stars who
played for him at the University of Connecticut. You can ask him
about his role players. Jim Calhoun is the coach who remembers them
all.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Allen: ``He was the most athletic player we've had. He was
beautiful to watch. Watching Ray was like watching ballet on the
basketball court.''
</P>
<P>
   Donny Marshall: ``We have a mile run for our players and Donny
ran the fastest. I think he finished in 4:52. That's not what the
top track people run, but you like to see a basketball player who
can get up and down the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard ``Rip'' Hamilton: ``I once teased him and said, `Rip,
you're from a different place, man.' He thought I was talking about
cities and said, `Yeah, I'm from Coatesville (Pa.).' I said, `No,
Rip. You're from a different era.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun said that because it seems as if the 6-foot-6-inch
Hamilton took a wrong turn out of the 1970s and wound up in the
chaotic '90s. All the depressing things you hear about modern
athletes don't apply to him. His ways are old. His game is old,
too. And as we have just witnessed in the NBA Finals, old ways and
old shots (Tim Duncan's bank shot) are back in style.
</P>
<P>
   In two days, some NBA team will call Hamilton's name on draft
day. He has been told he can go as high as fourth, to the Clippers.
He also could go as low as eighth, to the Cavaliers (a pick
previously owned by the Celtics), but not much lower.
</P>
<P>
   The team that acquires him will be happy. Hamilton has a
midrange game, which means he usually takes and makes 17-footers.
He makes his free throws (83 percent last season). He has won a
national championship. He is a good friend of Kobe Bryant's; their
friendship began when they were teammates on the same AAU team.
Bryant is a young star whose game is rooted in flash, leaps, and
spins. Hamilton is not like that. He forces nothing, working
silently and effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to say to him, `Was your mother keeping score tonight?
Because I never saw those 30 points you supposedly had,' '' Calhoun
said.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates teased him, too. They teased him for what they
perceived as his innocence. Once, Calhoun and Kevin Freeman were
driving with Hamilton, on their way to East Hartford to speak about
gang intervention. They talked about gangs being prevalent
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not in Coatesville,'' Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rip,'' Calhoun replied. ``You've got to be kidding. You live
30 minutes outside of Philly.''
</P>
<P>
   While other guys talked about girls, Hamilton didn't have much
to say: He has dated the same young woman for three years. Even his
nickname has a modern/aged split to it. The name used to belong to
his father, who became Big Rip when Hamilton was born. One story is
that when Big Rip was a child, he always ripped his clothes. Thus
the name. As Little Rip began to excel in basketball, he took over
the name. Now it has a double meaning. People in Hamilton's family
know it was passed down. But there are times when young people talk
about an extraordinary performance and say, ``He ripped it . . . ''
or did something good. Hamilton ripped it in three seasons at
UConn, winning Big East Player of the Year twice. He shared the
honor with Miami's Tim James last season.
</P>
<P>
   After his second season of Ripping it at UConn, Hamilton asked
Calhoun if he should leave school.
</P>
<P>
   He averaged 21.5 points per game his second season, but people
wondered about his size. He is listed at 185 pounds. ``I told him
not to worry about his size,'' Calhoun said. ``Reggie Lewis _ God
rest his soul _ was skinny, too. But I never worried about Reggie's
size. He went on to be an All-Star.''
</P>
<P>
   What the coach worried about was psychology. If Hamilton had
left after two seasons, he would have been drafted but probably not
in the lottery. He was a good player, but so young.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was feeling good about himself, but I said, `I don't think
you're ready,' '' Calhoun recalled. ``I told him that he needed to
be a great player longer. All the guys who play the 2 and 3 spots
in the league are great players; you can go through the list. They
are the people who score the points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rip needed to have a psychological base; he needed another
year of knowing that he was a great player. Plus, you get a
positive stigma when you're a lottery selection.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton waited and won a championship. He won't have to wait
much longer to officially join his friend Bryant in the NBA. By
late Wednesday, he could be a Clipper, Timberwolf, Cavalier, or
Wizard. The NBA didn't institute the lottery system until 1985. But
the people who know Hamilton will understand if someone refers to
him as a lottery pick from the '70s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
