<SLUG> BC-BBA-WHITE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILSON FILLS THE BILL(S) 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-WILSON-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The three $100 dollar bills were neatly tucked behind
the nameplate above Craig Wilson's locker in the visitors'
clubhouse at Fenway Park. Without counting his loot, Wilson quickly
stuffed it in the front pocket of the blue jeans hanging in his
stall.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just nothing,'' Wilson smiled, when asked about the
money. ``It's just something somebody owed me.''
</P>
<P>
   What it was was a much-welcomed incentive bonus from Frank
Thomas, who was happy to pay Wilson his bounty after the utility
infielder and .200 hitter provided the Chicago White Sox with an
unlikely source of power by belting a pair of two-run homers in
Sunday's 7-6 victory over the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say, Wilson was Chicago's big money player.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson went 2 for 3 and drove in four runs with his two homers,
his first and second of the season. But he didn't just do it with
his bat. After starting the game at shortstop and moving to second
base in the seventh when Mike Caruso entered at short, Wilson
turned Caruso's spectacular diving grab of a Reggie Jefferson
grounder up the middle into a game-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we had fun today,'' Thomas said when asked if he
was the philanthropist who left the cash in Wilson's locker. ``I
told the guy, `You do something special today, you get paid for it,
but we gotta win.' And Craig Wilson put us on his back and he did
(do something special). He hit two home runs, and he didn't have
one all season.''
</P>
<P>
   Until he teed off Sunday against Sox starter Brian Rose in the
fourth and knuckleballer Tim Wakefield in the ninth, touching each
for a critical two-run blast.
</P>
<P>
   After going 0 for 2 as a defensive replacement in Boston's 17-1
massacre Saturday, Wilson capped a four-run outburst on three
homers off Rose in the fourth with a 370-foot shot to the screen in
left that scored Brook Fordyce and rallied the White Sox from a 5-0
deficit to within a run.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, Wilson took Wakefield deep for a two-run shot that
proved the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's swings, like (Saturday) when I went 0 for 2, where I
felt like I was having a pretty good approach and putting some
pretty good swings on the ball,'' Wilson said. ``It's kind of the
way it's been the last couple of weeks. I felt comfortable up
there, but I just hadn't put the right part of the bat on the ball.
I'd been hitting them on the barrel, but I'd hit the top of the
ball. Today, I just went up there and tried to shorten up my swing
a little bit and made good solid contact.''
</P>
<P>
   He was right on the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy (with his fourth-inning homer),'' said Wilson, who
entered with a .200 average with no RBIs or homers and improved to
.222 with four RBIs and the two homers by game's end. ``I was just
trying to get a two-out hit. I haven't gotten one, a two-out RBI,
let alone an RBI, the whole year. I guess I just hit them in
streaks. I can't explain it, but I'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   So how did Thomas figure Wilson as his ``pick to click'' when he
offered $300 to the player who lifted the White Sox out of their
doldrums?
</P>
<P>
   ``He came out huge,'' Thomas said. ``Sometimes when a guy lays
it on the line, he can't do it. But Craig was a money player for us
today. And it had to come out of my pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   After losing six of their previous 10 games, and two in a row,
Thomas's clubhouse challenge ``was just an incentive to play hard
today, that's all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So how was Wilson going to spend his winnings?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably take everyone out to eat,'' Wilson grinned.
``Probably McDonald's.''
</P>
<P>
   Three hundred dollars can buy a lot of Happy Meals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
