<HEADLINE>
PAR SUITS BYRD FINE 
</HEADLINE>
 AMATEUR-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUMFORD, R.I. _ Jonathan Byrd was ahead by four strokes entering
Sunday's final round of the 38th annual Northeast Amateur
Invitational at 6,661-yard Wannamoisett Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't make the Clemson University student from Columbia,
S.C., feel secure, however. Byrd, who placed ninth in the Atlantic
Coast Conference Championships and 16th in the NCAA Division 1
Championships, believed the front nine would be crucial.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd did well, completing those holes in even par, and with a
birdie and a bogey on the back nine shot a par 69. His 274 total
was seven strokes better than 18-year-old Australian Arron Baddeley
(67_281).
</P>
<P>
   Bryce Molder of Georgia Tech and Conway, Ark., finished third
with a 73_282, with bogeys on the last four holes. Mike Capone and
David Eger tied for fourth at 283. Capone, from Cranston, R.I., and
Wake Forest, shot a 71 while Eger, a 37-year-old from Ponte Verda
Beach, Fla., fired a 73, which included five bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel that I had a solid golf stroke, one that didn't
break down,'' said Byrd, who was named a first-team all-NCAA
Division 1 All-American this spring. ``I hit shots all day long
that I was impressed with. My swing and my tempo both stayed good
under pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd handled himself well on the front side. ``I wanted to play
those first holes aggressively, but put myself in the right spots
where pars are good scores,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd made par on the second hole with a 6-footer that had about
a four-inch break. ``I got a lot of confidence from that,'' he
said. Byrd, who birdied the 13th and bogeyed the 16th, made a
5-footer on the fifth hole to save par, missed a 4-footer on the
seventh for birdie, and was able to get up-and-down from the right
bunker on the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could get some bogeys and let everybody back in the
tournament or I could get pars and maybe some birdies and kind of
keep my distance, and that's what I did all day long,'' he said.
``I only had three bad hits. It's been a long time since I've
played like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd knew the title was his on the 16th, when he shot a bogey 5.
``I could have made a double there after missing the green, having
to punch out of the trees, and if I got doubles, I think I would
have let people stay in the match,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Baddeley, who was playing in his first US Amateur and has been
compared with countryman Greg Norman, played well, with five
birdies and two bogeys. He hopes to play another year as an amateur
and possibly turn pro. He doesn't like the comparisons to Norman,
though.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't focus on what people say,'' Baddeley said. ``You've
got to practice on things you've got to improve on, you have to
pick up shots here and there. I worry about the future, not the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   Molder, the 1998 NCAA Division 1 Collegiate Player of the Year,
knew he needed a sterling round to catch Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in wanting to win, but what I really wanted was to have
a chance going into the last day and I did that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a little frustrating right now. I didn't give up but
I just lost my concentration when I realized that winning was out
of the picture. Maybe I was worn out or I had bad concentration. I
just wished I finished better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
