<HEADER>
A1525 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLDRAFT-BRUINS-B     06-28 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS HOPE TO FIND INSTANT KARMA 
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-BRUINS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Two years ago, when the Bruins were picking No. 1 and
No. 8 in the NHL draft, held that year at the Igloo in Pittsburgh,
there was rampant optimism among management and fans that the club
would be coming out of the annual crapshoot with two impact players
who would help turn the franchise around after it had missed the
playoffs for the first time in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   They selected Joe Thornton and Sergei Samsonov and both are
living up to expectations, with Samsonov the early thriller and
Calder Trophy winner and Thornton coming into his own in his second
year.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday at the FleetCenter, with the Bruins' first two
selections coming at Nos. 21 and 56, it appeared there wasn't much
chance of grabbing instant contributors.
</P>
<P>
   However, that changed when Boston went after a pair of
20-year-old Memorial Cup-winning teammates in defenseman Nick
Boynton and left wing Matt Zultek. Boynton, who was the most
valuable player of the tournament as the Ottawa 67s knocked off the
Calgary Hitmen in the finals, and Zultek had been through this
drill before.
</P>
<P>
   Boynton was taken with the No. 9 overall pick by Washington in
1997, one selection after Samsonov, but thought the Capitals were
low-balling him. Part of the problem was that the Capitals, who
failed to make the postseason just before the draft, were in a
state of transition. The front office changed and Boynton said in
some ways he felt he was a victim of the incoming philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might have had something to do with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Blackhawks expressed interest in Boynton and tried to get
something done before he went back into the draft, but the
youngster said that offer was even lower, so he took his chances.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he'll have the privilege (unenviable task?) of negotiating
with the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   In Boynton's favor is the fact he is two years closer to playing
than an 18-year-old would be. He's had four years of junior hockey,
he's filled out to 6 feet 1 inch, 210 pounds, which certainly will
help his transition to the NHL. Even better for Boston, if he
doesn't prove ready for the NHL, he could play in Providence.
Boynton had 11 goals and 59 points in 51 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a terrific defenseman,'' said assistant general
manager Mike O'Connell. ``For us, he was probably the best
defenseman who was available in the draft. He was the Memorial Cup
MVP, a first-round pick a couple of years ago, and he's two years
closer to playing than most of these other kids. With the depth we
have on the blue line, we feel he'll get a chance to play this year
for us. If not, he'll play in Providence, which is a huge, huge
plus for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Zultek is mammoth, listed at 6-4 and 222 pounds. He was taken
with the 15th pick overall in '97 by the Los Angeles Kings but they
couldn't come to terms by the June 1 deadline, despite some serious
negotiating by GM Dave Taylor, so Zultek went back in.
</P>
<P>
   With Thornton, Samsonov, Boynton, and Zultek, the Bruins now
have four of the top 15 players taken in the first round of that
'97 draft and three of the top nine.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Bruins very much would like to see Zultek throw his
weight around a lot more, the fact is he's a left wing who can
score. The Bruins don't exactly have a boatload of those. Zultek
tallied 33 goals and 66 points in 56 games. Sure that's junior
hockey, but if management believes he could use some seasoning, he
always can go down to Providence for a couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Saturday's draft wasn't as big as 1997 in terms of
players with name recognition, but if the Bruins can come to terms
with these two prospects, it would go a long way toward beefing up
their roster.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns said he was intrigued by the first two picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can get in there now and play, that's a lot better,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
