<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1526 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TAPIA-AYALA-BOS &LR;      06-28 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TAPIA-AYALA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AYALA WIN OVER TAPIA IS A HIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Freddie Roach knew his man was in trouble before the
first bell tolled Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   As the veteran trainer turned to squirt some water on the
mouthpiece of the World Boxing Association bantamweight champion
minutes before the first round of a title defense against Paulie
Ayala, Roach lost sight of his fighter for a moment. In that
instant Johnny Tapia's unraveling began.
</P>
<P>
   When Roach looked back there was an emotional Tapia in the
center of the ring pushing Ayala in the chest. As he had hoped, the
challenger had managed to raise Tapia's ire.
</P>
<P>
   Roach was already aware his tightly wrapped boxer's emotions
were on edge as his first defense of the 118-pound title
approached, but he was sure he would remain professional about his
work because that is how he had won two world titles and not lost
in 48 fights. But after he saw his fighter angrily charge Ayala for
no reason, he knew where Tapia was. He was in danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad sign,'' Roach said of the brief incident that
opened what would turn out to be Tapia's first defeat in nearly 11
years, a close but unanimous 12-round decision after which Ayala
collapsed in the ring in tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm usually more observant than that. I usually don't let my
fighter get away from me, but I didn't want to put a dry mouthpiece
in Johnny's mouth. I turned away for a second and he was gone.
After I got to him, I told him, `Johnny, keep your head.' Johnny
was really angry with this guy. He got caught up in the hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he did enough not to lose his title. He didn't fight
a smart fight, but it was maybe one of the best fights I ever
saw.''
</P>
<P>
   No eyewitness would dispute that even if they might debate the
decision that broke Tapia's winning streak and dropped his record
to 46-1-2. There may be a better fight sometime this year but it's
not likely.
</P>
<P>
   For 12 rounds, two wiry and wise fighters stood toe-to-toe
trying to take each other's measure. From the first bell to the
last the crowd at the Mandalay Bay Events Center was roaring as
first Ayala would fire away with rapid combinations in close and
then Tapia would respond with crushing body shots to the liver and
his own fierce retaliations.
</P>
<P>
   Round after round it ground on this way. Neither man was willing
to fall and seldom would even retreat. So close were many of the
rounds that the judges agreed only four times yet they all agreed
at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Jutras had Ayala winning, 115-114, but with a 1-point change
in the 11th round, which he called a draw, the fight would have
been even in his eyes. Duane Ford and Fernando Viso had it 116-113
and scored the last round even. Had they given it to Tapia, as many
ringside observers did, only 2 points would have separated the two.
It was no different on the Globe's card, which had Ayala winning,
115-113, by giving him the last two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   For Tapia it was a harsh night but the kind he always has
refused to back down from. Although he started slowly and ended the
same way, in the middle he came on strong and seemed to seize the
fight after the 10th round, as he often had in the past, with a
relentless body attack and superior experience. But those were
other nights, not this one, in fights against other men, not this
one.
</P>
<P>
   This time Ayala had a little too much youth and a little too
much hand speed, more often finishing off their exchanges than the
champion could manage, which made the difference. Yet even though
Tapia refused to do what he does best _ box masterfully _ he still
nearly pulled out the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Had Ayala not successfully goaded the champion into abandoning
the style that brought him first the junior bantamweight and then
bantamweight championships as well as a big-money victory over
hard-punching Danny Romero two years ago, perhaps things might have
been different. But Tapia could not control his warring emotions
and Ayala took advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tapia goes on his emotions,'' Ayala (21-1) said. ``I wanted to
goad them. When he pushed me it was all part of it. We were playing
some mind games. I intended to wish him luck but he was in a
different mode.''
</P>
<P>
   Tapia was in war mode and that's what the fight became from the
first. Ayala started quickly, winning the first three rounds with
his quick hands and some searing combinations, but when you fight
Tapia you need to bring a full lunch pail, so just when some were
thinking the 32-year-old champion had perhaps had it, he came back,
scoring with some powerful shots in the middle rounds and some
devastating body punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He caught me with some good body shots but I could take
them,'' Ayala said. ``I wanted to make it this kind of fight.
Johnny's a great boxer and a legendary junior bantamweight but that
doesn't work in the bantamweights. He caught me with some shots but
I've been blessed with good whiskers.''
</P>
<P>
   Good thing because Ayala needed them, and some cast iron ribs to
go with them to hold off Tapia, and that he did by winning more of
the toe-to-toe exchanges, of which there were so many it reminded
you what a great fight really is.
</P>
<P>
   It is trench warfare, hand-to-hand combat of the fiercest and
bravest kind. Here were two fighters unwilling to back down and
able to take all the other was ready to give for the opportunity to
return fire. When it was over, even the hard-nosed Tapia grudgingly
conceded this might have been Ayala's night, as his scratched and
marked face testified. Yet just as with his champion's belt, he was
not willing to make such a concession without a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my last fight with Top Rank,'' Tapia said of promotor
Bob Arum, suggesting Arum favored the younger Ayala even though he
holds rights to both fighters. ``You know what happened. Everybody
knows what happened. I thought I won but I give total respect to
Paulie. I was banging him to the body. I hurt him with every shot.
Nobody got hurt and the best man won. Put up the money and we'll do
it again.''
</P>
<P>
   As well they should, because it is for nights like this that
fight fans live. It was an affair of the heart, a brutal work of
art played out on a 20-foot canvas in which one man beat another
but nobody really lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
