<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZENGA MAKING BELIEVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Walter Zenga so far has reached his first
goal as player-coach of the Revolution. His team has yet to be
blown out of a game and much of the players' self-confidence has
returned.
</P>
<P>
   And, thanks also to the abysmal failures of the MetroStars and
Miami, the Revolution appear to have realistic hopes of being in
playoff contention, even after a 2-0 loss at Dallas Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good team now,'' Zenga said. ``You remember at the
start of the season when you said we were playing Italian-style,
defensive. Well, in this game what happened? We played against
Dallas, the (second-place) team in the West, and they only have two
chances to score until the final seconds. We have a lot of chances
to score, and it is Dallas that is on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say we were unlucky, but we deserved better. Now, we
have to continue to work and put ourselves in position to win every
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Revolution are acting, and often playing, like a
team that believes in itself. They have surrendered as many as
three goals only twice and the specter of 6-1 and 5-1 defeats of
last year seems to have faded.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution feel secure defensively, so the other parts of
their game have a chance to flourish. Joe-Max Moore, Giovanni
Savarese, and Johnny Torres hit the crossbar or goal posts in the
first half as Dallas retreated into defense.
</P>
<P>
   But the Burn displayed a composed counterattacking ability, and
Leonel Alvarez and Jason Kreis combined to set up Jorge ``El
Zarco'' Rodriguez for a 37th minute goal. The Revolution seem able
to impose their will on the opposition, and dictate the pace of the
game, but they have not developed as poised a counterattack as the
Burn.
</P>
<P>
   The role reversal was significant. As the underdog visiting
team, the Revolution should have been the ones to absorb pressure
and counter. Instead, Dallas took on that role and the Revolution
appeared to be in a position of strength.
</P>
<P>
   They will have to maintain that attitude when they host the
MetroStars Sunday and Los Angeles July 11 in the final games before
the midseason all-star break.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997 and '98 seasons, the Revolution became extremely
vulnerable because of lack of depth and lack of vibrant,
complementary personalities. But they compensated for the loss of
starters Richard Goulooze (Achilles' strain), John Harkes
(hamstring strain), and Ivan McKinley (suspension) against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Gori, acquired from Miami in a trade for Edwin Gorter,
performed well at left back. And Jamar Beasley, Paulo Dos Santos,
and Paul Keegan provided reinforcement off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both teams looked tired and that's one reason why we couldn't
capitalize on mistakes,'' Torres said. ``It's tough when you get
behind. If we had scored a goal, we could have sat back and
defended, paced ourselves a little bit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
