 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, June 28.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BOMB-DAMAGE (Djakovica) _ In the two weeks since NATO
forces arrived in Kosovo, alliance officials have scaled back their
initial estimates of the damage inflicted by the 78-day air
campaign on the Yugoslav army, which they concede remains a force
capable of maintaining Slodoban Milosevic's grip on power. While
NATO and Pentagon officials stand by their claims to have
significantly damaged the Yugoslav army and special police, they
acknowledge that the units that withdrew from Kosovo a week ago
were clearly not as damaged as they had believed. By Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA (Belgrade) _ The collapse of Greater Serbia can be
told through the story of one Serbian family, expelled from
Croatia, resettled near Belgrade, then bounced to Kosovo, and now
living in squalid housing outside Belgrade again. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VILLAGE (Slovinje, Yugoslavia) _ The old Balkan cycle of
fear and revenge meets NATO's attempt to impose order. By David
Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DRUNKS (Moscow) _ Accidental deaths in Russia due to
drunkeness are on the rise in the hot summer months, with two dozen
men drowning in Moscow rivers. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-POLITICS (Jakarta) _ Hundreds of non-governmental
agencies have suddenly begun flexing their muscles now that
Indonesia's dictator is gone. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   CROATIA-TUDJMAN (Zagreb) _ For a leader whose small Balkan state
is unable to pay pensions, save banks from collapse, or stem
mounting discontent, Croatia's President Franjo Tudjman seems
strangely preoccupied with history. By Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   BARBARY-LIONS (Hoedspruit, South Africa) _ Veterinarians who
examined some abandoned circus animals now say that a lion in the
group is one of the few Barbary lions left in the world. The last
one in the wild was shot in 1921 in Morocco, and for a few months,
there were claims that the circus lion was the only Barbary left.
But the excitement over finding him led small European zoos and
circuses to pipe up, ``Hey _ we've got a lion that looks like
that.'' One of them even agreed to ship its lioness to South
Africa, and now the possibility exists that the subspecies can be
bred back into viability. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-GAY-SEX (New York) _ A study of homosexual men in New York
City has found that they have significantly reduced their levels of
risky sexual behavior; the number of men infected with the AIDS
virus has dropped sharply.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MENTAL-HEALTH (New York) _ A recent tragedy on the city
subway system illustrates the city's failure to find and treat
mentally-ill people.
</P>
<P>
   WHALE-NOISE (Friday Harbor, Wash.) _ A concert of sorts brought
the best sounds humans have to offer to the whales _ Monteverdi's
vespers, Afro-Brazilian music, and more. The whales were out in
force, making lots of their own noise. The result was a
fascinating, unusual scene of whales being whales, and humans,
trying to reach out and connect with another species, being human.
By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA-NUWABIANS (Eatonton, Ga.) _ Eatonton is home to a cult
called the Nuwabians. They migrated to Georgia from Brooklyn and
built a compound whose main feature is pyramids. They walk around
in a kind of Egyptian attire. The basis of the cult seems to the
leader's belief that a spaceship will come and take them all away
someday. Once a year, on the occasion of the leader's birthday, the
cult opens the compound to the public. The cult is also in the
middle of a minor legal dispute with the county over property
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BUDGET _ Seeking to capitalize on new projections
showing that the federal budget surplus will grow far bigger than
anticipated, President Clinton plans to unveil sweeping new
proposals on Monday to allocate the windfall among Social Security,
Medicare and other spending and tax cut proposals, Democrats said
on Sunday. By Richard W. Stevenson with Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-ASBESTOS _ Congress prepares for a legislative solution
to asbestos litigation. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   BREAUX-PROFILE _ Sen. John Breaux, whose Medicare commission
failed to come up with a plan that all its members could agree on,
now has to deal with the Clinton proposals. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-SNAFU _ Problems with the immigration service's controls
over stolen documents have let undesirables, including terrorists,
drug runners, and smugglers of illegal aliens, slip across U.S.
borders.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MILKEN-LIBEL-BOOK (Undated) _ Who's putting the big bucks behind
a libel suit filed against `Den of Thieves' author James Stewart?
Lowell Milken, the brother of Michael. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   REMNICK-NEWYORKER-MEDIA (New York) _ The gulf between the glitzy
style and frenetic pace of Tina Brown, the former editor of The New
Yorker, and the more earnest, relaxed mien of David Remnick, the
magazine's new editor, has become the hallmark of Remnick's first
year at the magazine. By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo and graphic have been sent to NYT photo/graphic
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NET-DOMAIN-NAMES (Washington) _ The protracted effort to
introduce competition into the lucrative business of registering
Internet addresses has been delayed for at least three weeks
because of escalating tensions between the Clinton administration,
its handpicked successor for running the global network and the
government contractor that has had a monopoly on the business. By
Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-GARTNER (Washington) _ How much will the battle to tame Year
2000 computer problems cost? When will Year 2000 computer
malfunctions hit? Which countries or industries are furthest along
_ or furthest behind _ in dealing with Y2K? One name comes up
repeatedly when such questions are posed: Gartner Group. By Barnaby
J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   QWEST-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ When the board of Frontier Corp.
meets Monday, as expected, to discuss the unsolicited bid made by
Qwest Communications International Inc., the debate will be far
from elementary. That's because nothing is ever as simple as it
looks. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-REALPEOPLE (Undated) _ Electronic commerce companies have
spent millions trying to make their sites more ``personal,'' with
technology that allows them to customize their product offerings to
a particular shopper's needs. Now those sites are trying a novel
approach to personalization: real people. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
