<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK SHOWING NO SIGNS OF IMPROVEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The seven games of sitting and thinking, forced
by suspension, did nothing to improve Chan Ho Park's on-field
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Since returning to the rotation, the Los Angeles Dodgers
right-hander is 0-3 with an 8.47 ERA. The latest abomination came
in Sunday's 8-7 loss to the Giants at 3Com Park.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Dodgers manager Davey Johnson voiced his extreme
displeasure about Park's season-long performance, especially after
electing to leave Park in the game after the Dodgers scored twice
in the fourth to cut a five-run deficit to 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect a lot more from Chan Ho,'' Johnson said. ``You're the
No. 2 starter, three runs down, go out there and hold them.
Otherwise, I would have pinch hit for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Park didn't make it out of the fourth inning, earning Johnson's
hook after allowing a one-out triple and a two-out RBI single. He
allowed six runs in 32/3 innings, walked four and struck out four.
</P>
<P>
   It's the third time Park has allowed at least six earned runs in
a start, and second in the last three. In what was supposed to be a
breakout season, Park is 4-6 with a 5.54 ERA. He's allowed 19
homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like he was throwing the ball instead of pitching,''
Johnson said. ``I left him in hoping he'd be mad and go out there
and pitch. And he didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a season of distraction and disaster for Park, who
declined to talk to the media.
</P>
<P>
   He has already tied a major-league record by allowing four grand
slams, was distracted by aborted contract talks and then released
his frustration by punching and kicking Angels pitcher Tim Belcher
in a fight earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to pitch the ball, and not throw the ball,'' catcher
Todd Hundley said. ``I can see it. When it's easy to see, you know
it's there. When you have a long swing, it's easy to see but you
don't feel it. Same thing with pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sometimes he'll just try to overanalyse situations and
try to make the perfect pitch and then it's 2-0, 3-1, and a hitter
doesn't have to protect the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   White scratched late: Johnson just finished talking about how
much he liked his lineup because he alternated right-handed hitters
with left-handed hitters when he learned center fielder Devon White
couldn't play because of a stiff neck.
</P>
<P>
   The initial intention was to give Gary Sheffield the day off and
play Todd Hollandsworth in left. Instead, Hollandsworth started in
center and Sheffield played left.
</P>
<P>
   Mills mulls outing: Dodgers reliever Alan Mills gave up three
runs in the eighth inning in Saturday's win, including an Ellis
Burks homer to give the Giants a short-lived lead, which didn't sit
well with him. But Mills was bothered more by costing starter
Carlos Perez the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel bad about getting hit and giving up runs. That's
going to happen,'' said Mills, who had allowed one run in his
pervious eight outings. ``I feel bad for Carlos. He threw the ball
well and he deserved to win. That's what I feel bad about.''
</P>
<P>
   FYI: Johnson said he will keep right-hander Kevin Brown working
every five days, which means Brown will start Wednesday in San
Diego. Ismael Valdes opens the series Tuesday for the Dodgers and
Darren Dreifort will close it Thursday. Johnson said he was
concerned about Brown, who felt a twinge in his non-pitching
shoulder during his Friday start. Johnson said Brown has been
seeing a chiropractor and getting massages to ease the pain. Brown
said he'll be fine.... Giants outfielder Barry Bonds tied a
major-league record when he was intentionally walked in the fourth
inning. It was the 293rd time of his career, tying Hank Aaron....
The Dodgers have scored twice (three runs) in the first inning in
23 games in June while opponents have scored 10 times (16 runs) in
the opening inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
