<HEADER>
A1558 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANK-CODES-SPI &LR;      06-28 1461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-CODES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CODED' BANK ACCOUNT NUMBERS STIR FIGHT OVER MARKETING SUCH
INFORMATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE HADLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Olympia-based Heritage Bank gave the names, bank
account numbers and addresses of its customers to another company
that then used the information to try to sell the customers
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Benefit Consultants Inc., encrypted each bank
account number in a way it thought would not be identifiable
without a special code.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one problem: Albert Newman.
</P>
<P>
   Newman, a Heritage Bank customer, received one of the insurance
solicitations. The letter said that if he wanted the insurance, the
company could automatically deduct the cost from his bank account.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `How in the Sam Hill could they do that?'''
</P>
<P>
   He soon found out. Examining the insurance solicitation, he
noticed a code in an upper corner. The combination of letters and
numbers seemed odd yet familiar. Drawing on his World War II
cryptography training, Newman, 79, quickly decoded the information
to discover that it was his bank account number.
</P>
<P>
   He was outraged. Newman, who had more than $100,000 in the bank,
began writing letters to the bank, telling it not to give his
account number and other information to other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his objections, the mailings continued.
</P>
<P>
   After more than three years of continued solicitations, Newman
finally sued Heritage Bank. The mailings stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Newman has agreed to testify at a July 29 hearing called by the
Washinton state Senate's Commerce, Trade, Housing and Financial
Institutions Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Committee chairwoman Sen. Margarita Prentice, D-Seattle, said
she decided to call the hearing because she's concerned about the
increasing reports of banks disclosing customers' account
information to marketers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really violating that kind of trust relationship we're
supposed to have with our financial institutions,'' she said.
``Banks are built on trust. They've violated this trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Also planning to testify July 29 is John Bley, director of
financial institutions for the state. After Minnesota's attorney
general announced a lawsuit against US Bank for allegedly selling
customer information to a telemarketing firm earlier this month,
Bley's office got more than 100 calls from Washington citizens with
similar concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``To receive that many was certainly out of the ordinary,'' Bley
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the debate in Congress over new banking privacy
legislation has boiled down to the question of whether the bank
owns customer information or whether the customer owns the
information. Legislation that assumes the bank owns it puts the
burden on the consumer to tell the bank not to give away or sell
the information. Those who believe the customer owns it say the
bank must get the customer's explicit permission before disclosing
the information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think most people would say, `No, that's my
information,''' Bley said. Yet that position is treated as
``extreme'' in Congress right now, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it such an extreme position that federal law ought to
protect the reasonable privacy expectations of its citizens?'' Bley
said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Jay Inslee, D-Wash., has introduced banking-privacy
legislation that would put the burden on the consumer to object.
Inslee said he would prefer the legislation put the burden on the
banks to get permission, but he had to compromise to win support
for his bill from moderate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Inslee also plans to testify at the July 29 hearing in Olympia.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General Paula Selis, who is investigating
BrandDirect Marketing, is also expected to testify at the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Bley said banks use the questionable tactics because they're in
``a highly competitive industry in a securities market that demands
maximum return.'' Bank executives might be loathe to resort to
disclosing account information, ``but the securities market tells
financial institutions if you're not going to maximize return,
you're going to be subject to hostile takeover, and management will
be put in place to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Heritage Bank declined to comment on Newman's suit because it is
in litigation. But letters from bank attorneys to Newman's Olympia
attorney, Shawn Newman (no relation), contend that the bank is
providing the account information to Benefit Consultants merely to
``assist the bank in communicating with its customers.''
</P>
<P>
   That is proper and not a violation of Albert Newman's rights,
wrote Heritage attorney William Holt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems basic that Heritage has the right to communicate with
its customers. It can do this through its own employees or through
independent contractors.''
</P>
<P>
   But Shawn Newman said this was not communication between
Heritage and Albert Newman.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hired independent contractors to solicit their bank
customers to purchase insurance. This is not an internal deal,''
Shawn Newman said. ``This came from Trumbull, Connecticut. These
are independent contractors that are soliciting for the Insurance
Company of North America.''
</P>
<P>
   The solicitation invited Albert Newman to fill out an
``application to Insurance Company of North America for accidental
death and dismemberment insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   The solicitation included a letter signed by Heritage Chairman
Donald Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   Heritage recently offered Albert Newman money to settle the
suit, but Albert Newman said he turned it down because it would
have required him not to discuss the suit or his complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Newman said far from wanting to ``shut my mouth'' about his
experience, he wants to shout it from the mountain top.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the public to know what the banks are doing to them and
the fact that they're so arrogant that if you question them, they
say get lost.''
</P>
<P>
   In the field artillery during World War II, Newman said his unit
was given instruction in cryptography so they could decipher and
encode messages. A common technique then was to use letters to
stand for numbers and vice versa, he said. Benefit Consultant's
code was simple to break, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Newman, who ran a boat repair yard in Vallejo, Calif., before he
retired, also wants to be compensated for the $5,000 or $6,000 in
lost interest he incurred in transferring his funds out of the bank
and for his legal expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to hire an attorney to shut it off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once someone has your bank account number, they can find out
many other things about you, including the amount of money in your
account, both Albert and Shawn Newman said.
</P>
<P>
   Summary judgment motions in the case are to be heard in Thurston
County Superior Court Aug. 13.
</P>
<P>
   According to the suit, the bank's stated policy said the bank
would disclose Newman's account information to third parties only
where necessary to complete transfers, to verify the existence and
condition of his account for a third party such as credit bureau or
merchant, or to comply with court orders. Also, information could
be disclosed if he gave permission or if his account was closed for
abuse or because he owed the bank money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says there you're in safe haven. They don't tell you that
for a couple of bucks they'll sell everything about you,'' Albert
Newman said.
</P>
<P>
   The bank maintains it does not sell any account information but
refused to be questioned on the assertion. Shawn Newman said the
bank may technically not be paid specifically for the information,
but undoubtedly receives some form of commission for insurance
sales that result from the solicitations.
</P>
<P>
   Another bank attorney wrote Shawn Newman that generally the bank
does not provide its customer list or account numbers to third
parties, but on occasion the bank has ``an opportunity to offer
services to its customers through third-party providers.'' In
another letter, Rhodes, the Heritage chairman, wrote that more than
2,000 customers signed up for the insurance, causing the bank to
believe that its customers valued the service.
</P>
<P>
   The first $1,000 of coverage is provided free; customers pay for
any additional coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Newman's lawsuit alleges that the bank's disclosure of his
account information was a breach of contract, negligent, an
invasion of privacy and violated the state's Consumer Protection
Act.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Walsh, a professor of tort law at the University of
Washington, said he thinks many juries might well decide against
the bank on most of these points.
</P>
<P>
   Most customers would want to be ``clearly alerted'' to the
possibility that the bank would disclose their account information
to a third party, Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My instinctive sense is that a lot of people really would find
this offensive,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
