u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC--BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SP     06-28 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC--BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS FANS HEAD OUTDOORS ALL WARM INSIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A funny thing happened on the way to the Kingdome
Sunday, before Ken Griffey Jr. cranked a big-moment homer, before a
pink-skinned streaker gamboled across the outfield and before sweet
Edgar Martinez got tossed for arguing balls and strikes:
</P>
<P>
   It got sunny.
</P>
<P>
   The clouds broke apart and the sky turned mostly blue.
</P>
<P>
   A historic Seattle morning that started off as thick and gray
and baleful as, well, the Kingdome ceiling blossomed into a
wonderful early summer Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   A perfect day for a game outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Let's call it an omen.
</P>
<P>
   No offense to the Kingdome _ which after 22{ seasons marked its
baseball finale Sunday with a packed house, special guests and a
stream of videotaped memories _ but Seattle has done the right
thing.
</P>
<P>
   The future looks bright. The future has atmosphere. It has a
different set of sounds, smells and energy _ the kind that make it
possible for baseball to really seep into your soul, from April to
October, 81 times a season.
</P>
<P>
   Although baseball has no future in the Kingdome, it owes its
future here completely to the Kingdome. The Dome is the reason
baseball is here. It is where 32 million spectators got a look at
the game and its players _ the good ones, the bad ones, the
greatest ones, like Griffey, and our favorites, like Edgar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little sad,'' Martinez said. ``When I came to the
stadium, there were a lot of people walking around. It felt like a
playoff game, and it made you realize it was the last game. We're
sad, but at the same time, we're looking forward to the new
stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the obscene half-billion dollar cost and the disastrous
politics, and even in spite of the end run that Mariner owners are
now making to garner $60 million in excess tax revenue to help pay
for the $100 million in cost overruns, Seattle has what it needs to
make baseball what it should be.
</P>
<P>
   As Mariners pitcher Freddy Garcia threw the first pitch to the
Rangers just a little after 1:35 p.m., I walked around the outside
of the Kingdome to where the new, controversial, pricey and
enticing outdoor designer ballpark sits, waiting.
</P>
<P>
   And even as the Kingdome celebrated its, shall we say
interesting, baseball legacy, I could not help but think the switch
from baseball indoors to baseball outside was coming not a minute
too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Outside in the sun, seagulls were flying around, squawking. The
heavenly scent of grilled hot dogs infused the air.
</P>
<P>
   The crackle of the Mariners radio broadcast was amplified
through speakers outside the Kingdome, and it mingled with sounds
of traffic and the stir of the monstrous crowd that was still
snaking its way into the old concrete Dome.
</P>
<P>
   And the overwhelming feeling was: What an oddity. Going inside
just as the day outside turned ideal.
</P>
<P>
   But at least this would be the very last time. This quirky
Northwest ritual is over now.
</P>
<P>
   That is why so many people showed up for the Mariners' final
Kingdome game _ the first sellout of the season.
</P>
<P>
   That's why they did the wave with zeal. That's why they sang
``Louie, Louie'' so joyously during the seventh-inning stretch.
That's why they cheered for the almost-naked streaker, who was
handcuffed and escorted off the field as everyone laughed,
including the Mariner players and some of the cops.
</P>
<P>
   The finale was a party as much as it was a goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so much overwhelming nostalgia or teary sentiment that
prompted the 56,530 to take a seat in the Dome, even as 300-game
winner Gaylord Perry was applauded and Alvin Davis was lauded for
his place as Mr. Mariner and Harold Reynolds was saluted for all
those plays.
</P>
<P>
   The turnout was the pull to be part of history, since the
Kingdome has just become baseball history in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The farewell hype was designed to stir up sentimentality in us,
but as it turns out, the most stirring thing about the day was
Griffey, not the Dome.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, Griffey hit the home run that anyone who
knows Griffey knew he would hit.
</P>
<P>
   With his father Ken Sr. in the house and son Trey there, too,
Griffey is as much if not more baseball history here than the
Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's uncanny flair for making the big moments even better
all but guaranteed his theatrics. That included the sensational
wall-climbing, homer-saving catch in straightaway center that
Griffey made, saving three runs.
</P>
<P>
   No offense to the Kingdome, but Ken Griffey will still be Ken
Griffey in Safeco Field, even if Mariner hitters are concerned
about the outdoor park's larger dimensions and the heavier air _ so
much different than the outdated band box called the Kingdome,
whose time and place on the Seattle skyline has come and gone.
</P>
<P>
   No one was found sobbing inside the Kingdome. Joey Cora was
nowhere to be found, except in the video montage.
</P>
<P>
   Cora might be the last man who ever out and out cried in the
Kingdome. His breakdown in the dugout after the Mariners lost the
1995 American League Championship Series to Cleveland is a
crystalline Kingdome memory that will never go away.
</P>
<P>
   But we will.
</P>
<P>
   We're ready to walk down the street to the new era of outdoor
baseball in the new ballpark, the sun on our backs.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
