<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1561 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      06-28 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S LEAVE KINGDOME IN STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The ball was in another glove for an instant, just
long enough for Brian Hunter to catch it and flip it to the place
it belonged.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Greer's fly, the one that retired baseball at the only
home the Mariners have known, landed in the webbing of Ken Griffey
Jr.'s mitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his show,'' said Hunter, the Mariners' left fielder. ``He
won't admit it, but I feel that way. So I just wanted to give him
the last ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners were shut out when they christened the Kingdome in
1977, one of those years that was all but over by opening day. They
won Sunday, as a sold-out crowd of 56,530 saw them gain a game on
the division-leading Texas Rangers with a 5-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   These games matter more. These Mariners have a chance. More than
anyone else, Griffey is responsible for that.
</P>
<P>
   The center fielder hit the final homer in the Kingdome, a
three-run shot in the first inning. He took away a three-run homer
in the fourth, climbing the wall in left-center field and reaching
over to keep Juan Gonzalez in.
</P>
<P>
   Two final jolts to a place Griffey wired when he moved here as a
teenager. On July 15, it's on to Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here 11 years,'' Griffey said. ``It's like if you
move out of your home, you're going to miss that. I know all the
ins and outs of this ballpark. I'll have to figure it out next
door. They're sending me a blueprint of the new place so I can
sneak in and out.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey doesn't sneak out of places. Not when he's on his way to
his 10th Gold Glove. Not when his next homer will start him on the
second half of his pursuit of Hank Aaron's record 755. Not with his
singular ability to make the moment his.
</P>
<P>
   Leaping to a new building with a single bound was only so
typical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since I've known him, whether it's the All-Star Game, a
big game, a national TV game, he's always done it _ always,'' said
Harold Reynolds, the Mariners' second baseman for Griffey's first
four years. ``That's just Junior. We used to joke about it _
`Uh-oh, he's got his cape on again.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Junior's done it his whole career,'' said designated hitter
Edgar Martinez, Griffey's teammate from the start. ``He rises to
the occasion, and it wasn't any different today.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey insisted he doesn't handle big games differently. He
went hitless in the one-game playoff with the Angels in 1995, he
reminded reporters. His approach is simple: ``If it goes out, it
goes out. If it doesn't, it doesn't. Make the catch. That's it.
Don't show emotion and go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's home run? As Griffey nonchalantly told Dave Niehaus on
the podium during postgame ceremonies, he was just trying to get
the runners over.
</P>
<P>
   To say he changes when the red light glows would be to imply a
lesser effort when it doesn't. It's the same effort every day,
Griffey said, and it may be that his ability to maintain that
approach, no matter the circumstance, gives him an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just settles down and becomes very calm,'' said his father,
Ken Sr., one of a dozen or more ex-Mariners on hand Sunday. ``I
tried to teach him that scenario, about blocking out everything but
him and the pitcher. But there's some things you can't teach.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's homer erased the two-run shot Greer hit off Freddy
Garcia in the top of the first. Garcia (9-4) then loaded the bases
on a walk, a double and an intentional walk, but ended the inning
by getting a ground out.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie right-hander followed with four scoreless innings,
and Frankie Rodriguez and Jose Mesa added four more. Griffey's
homer in the bottom of the inning, his 198th at the Kingdome and
201st including the postseason, was all the M's needed.
</P>
<P>
   That, and his catch in the fourth. Gonzalez, whose two MVP
awards bookend the one Griffey won in 1997, came up with two outs
and two on. He had been fooled by Garcia's change-up in striking
out his first two at-bats, but unloaded on a change-up this time.
Griffey raced back, planted his right spikes in the padded wall,
and grabbed it, holding the ball high as he began his trot in.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know when he plays,'' Garcia said, ``anything can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey returned to the bench and took a seat next to rookie
Charles Gipson. Gipson, who said he often calls his father to rave
about playing with Griffey, tried to share his excitement over the
catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Griffey said. ``But we've still got some game left.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He does it so much, it's second nature,'' Gipson said. ``Most
players would be like a little kid and get all excited. He's like,
`Let's just keep on playing.' Amazing. Amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey is all done playing in the Kingdome. But the memories,
of him and especially the team he helped raise to contenders, will
always amaze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came over when it was still a little bit empty over here,
and we were losing some years twice as much as we were winning,''
said right fielder Jay Buhner, an 11-year Mariner. ``But now, to
build what we've built here, a winning tradition and a winning
mind-set, and to be able to transfer that next door, that's pretty
awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   And there will be more building to do at Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Start a new tradition over there, hang up some banners,''
Griffey said. ``Some big ones, not the ones that say `division
title' _ the ones that say `World Series.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
