<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Movie industry embraces urinals
 &HT;    (For release June 30, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the president and seemingly everyone else is down on the
motion picture industry for its embrace of violence and sex, I find
myself on a different page. What troubles me most about films these
days is, simply, bad taste.
</P>
<P>
   About the only Oscar that the latest Austin Powers movie ever
could attain would be if they were giving one out for bad taste.
</P>
<P>
   The insipid film (no, I have not seen it _ and will not _ but
have seen enough of it on TV to know how crude it is) asks
questions of moviegoers: Are you obtuse enough to call this
entertainment? Did you walk into the theater by accident, thought
you were going to see something intelligent in the auditorium next
door? Are things so bad at home that you need to see something
totally stupid to take your mind off the ballooning second
mortgage? Did you not understand the most recent ``Star Wars''
film, and so thought to find something easier to comprehend?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there is nothing wrong with being entertained by
stupidity. Laurel and Hardy, Abbott and Costello, the Three Stooges
and Jerry Lewis had long Hollywood careers being slapstick moronic,
but this Austin Powers character, he's not as clever as his
predecessors because, unlike them, he needs to inject bathroom
humor into the film.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly, every click of the TV remote finds Mike Myers, who
co-produced, co-wrote and starred in ``The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' on
another talk program, throwing out his phrases and definitions, as
a susceptible audience of mostly teenagers embarks on a second
language.
</P>
<P>
   So taken have people become with this crude entertainment that a
Web site was established by New Line Cinema, distributors of the
film, whereby you may purchase Austin Powers-related items such as
a penis enlarger, various party packs, T-shirts and martini and
shot glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the film's distributors _ not content with all the
sordid phraseology already circulated _ went a step further and
tried to outgross another film I have not seen (ask me about ``Tea
With Mussolini,'' though) by copying its advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The promotion of ``Big Daddy'' has, as the graphic in its large
newspaper ads, a man and a boy urinating against a brick wall. This
is supposed to capture our goofy attention. Most bizzarely, it has
become film-fashionable to include men urinating. (This act is not
reserved for stupid comedies; in dramas, cross-talking criminals
devise new schemes also while addressing the urinal. Real guys stop
their cars along deserted highways and walk 10 yards away to
relieve themselves against a bush.)
</P>
<P>
   This act is competing well with the male-cherished slipping bra
strap, although I cannot believe that female viewers get any thrill
out of seeing men urinating.
</P>
<P>
   In last Sunday's major newspapers, instead of the toothy,
grinning face of Austin Powers in ads for that film, we find a
grown man and a height-impaired person in the exact pose as the
``Big Daddy'' display ad, urinating against a brick wall. No one,
it seems, has a copyright on bad taste.
</P>
<P>
   If all the film has to sell is a scene like that, what does that
say about the rest of the movie?
</P>
<P>
   I never could understand the accolades heaped on ``Something
About Mary'' last year. It was, to me, a most offensive film using
the most disgusting sight gags I'd ever seen in a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, I'm not speaking as a moralist. There is a difference
between morality and bad taste. Films the moralists condemn cover a
wide range: sex, abuse toward religion, innuendoes _ gross
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Bad taste films send a different message: bad taste.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
