<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Imprisoned Jews are pawns of Iranian politics
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can believe, if you wish, that Israel would put Iran's
remnant Jewish community at high risk by recruiting spies wholesale
from its ranks. And that, for some odd reason, it would favor
provincial religious teachers and students for the task.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can suspect, with far better reason, that the 13 Iranian
Jews imprisoned as alleged spies are pawns in the dead-earnest
power struggle between elected moderate President Mohammed Khatami
and radical Islamist clergy hellbent on preserving the extremist
theocracy of the late, founding ayatollah, Ruhollah Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
   Officially a ``tolerated minority'' in 90-percent Shiite Muslim
Iran, the 27,000 Jews who remain, essentially trapped, out of a
onetime population of 100,000 are in fact, like Baha'is,
evangelical Christians and others in that begrudged status, in
fragile circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Popularly elected two years ago, Khatami advanced his
breakthrough early this year by virtually sweeping the Islamic
republic's first local elections. Khatami allies took 70 percent of
the vote nationally and won 12 of 15 seats on the Tehran city
council. Hardliners were aced out everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The results were striking enough to move the U.S. State
Department, never the fastest sprinter in the blocks, to
acknowledge, though with elaborate cautions, Khatami's attempts to
resume contacts with the West.
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely that prospect that alarms Iran's revolutionary
clerics, and what better counter than that old reliable ploy in
intra-Islamic one-upmanship, the Zionist conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the recent clamor against the 13, after months of official
silence. Ayatollah Mohammed Yazdi, head of Iranian courts, told
worshipers at prayers recently that the Jews must be tried under
Islamic law and could be sentenced to death ``several times.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not an idle threat. Iran executes casually, even
whimsically.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty obviously, the game here has less to do with espionage
than with Iranian politics. Just by making the charge, the
hardliners put Khatami and his followers in position to be called
pro-Zionist if they come to the prisoners' defense.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, the same potential slander neutralizes other
Islamic countries. Saudi Arabia, for instance, very much wants
Iran's extremists boxed, but as the defender of the faith it will
hold back from supporting Khatami if he is cast as a Zionist
sympathizer, however absurd the claim.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has protested the arrests (the 13 were at first also
charged with spying for the ``big devil'' _ that's us, of course)
and so has the European Union, led by Germany. France dressed down
the Iranian ambassador, to no apparent avail. Human rights
organizations have been barred from visiting the prisoners, an
additionally worrisome sign.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of this affair will say a good bit about which way
Iran is trending, but other nations cannot afford to look on with
only academic interest. International success in preventing the
trials also would bolster Iranian moderation. Only the region's
terrorists and their political groupies can want otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
