<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1727 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN29-C     06-28 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Global gap in preparedness
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The world is a better place than it was just this past
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least better prepared to fight the Year 2000 computer
flaw, commonly called the Y2K bug. Last week, more than 170 nations
sent delegates to a conference at the United Nations headquarters
in New York to assess worldwide plans for coping with the software
problem that will cause many computers, especially older ones, to
malfunction when the date changes to 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The experts were optimistic about the enormous progress made in
recent months, saying the world's business and political leaders
are now focused on fixing the software needed to keep banks, power
companies, water providers and other utilities functioning smoothly
as the year changes from '99 to '00. ``Action is under way
everywhere, by and large according to schedule,'' declared
Pakistan's U.N. Ambassador Ahmad Kamal, who chairs the U.N. working
group dealing with Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Still, reports coming out of the conference suggest that
progress remains wildly uneven, with developed countries in far
better shape than less wealthy countries, especially those in Latin
America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Because so much emphasis has been put on preparing banks and
nuclear power plants, those sectors should do reasonably well
worldwide. But smaller countries continue to have serious problems
with key industries such as shipping, health care and oil
exporting. Island nations that rely heavily on tourism worry that a
fear of flying in early January will keep many travelers home.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, politics are impeding progress on this
technological problem.
</P>
<P>
   For example, North African and Middle Eastern nations refused to
allow Israeli officials to join in a regional Y2K meeting at the
U.N. conference. ``The Y2K problem should break down boundaries and
barriers, and not create them,'' Israeli Ambassador Dore Gold told
the conference. ``Israel is prepared to share its expertise with
its neighbors ...''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his role as the U.N. leader on Y2K problems, Kamal
defended the snub of Israel. ``We can't force people to invite
people they don't want in their homes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cultural differences also play a role in how countries are
approaching the critical period from Dec. 31 to Jan. 2. In the
United States, some bankers are saying they will be working on
Saturday, Jan. 1, rather than enjoying a routine weekend holiday.
They want to keep the doors open and lights on to show how
confident they are about their bank's transition to the new year.
</P>
<P>
   But at least 20 other countries around the world have declared
Dec. 31 a bank holiday, closing their financial institutions Friday
so that employees will have more time to complete back-up plans for
possible Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   And while Jane Garvey, head of the Federal Aviation
Administration, has announced she'll be taking a midnight flight to
demonstrate confidence in air safety, Vietnam Airlines already has
thrown in the towel and canceled domestic and international flights
that would be in progress at midnight Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in Venezuela, Y2K is turning out to be a boon to
shrinks. Hugo Castellanos, head of the government's Y2K task force,
told U.N. conference attendees that Venezuela is trying to psych
out the software bug. ``We're talking to psychologists and
psychiatrists about how to reach people in the right way'' to avoid
panic, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps no two countries did a better job at the U.N
conference of displaying their national character and role in the
global community than Yugoslavia and North Korea. Their chairs were
empty.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
