<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1728 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANE-COLUMN29-COX     06-28 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMENTARY: New $20s incite political backlash
</P>
<P>
   By Mark Lane
</P>
<P>
   c. Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Every so often a political issue appears
from nowhere. It is handed to a politician like Excalibur rising
from the lake. Find it and you're on TV with talking heads nodding
in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Could the conservative backlash against the new $20 bill be such
an issue? The $50 and $100 redesigns affected only big spenders.
But the $20 hits close to the ATM.
</P>
<P>
   You can't blame Steve Forbes for giving it a road test. Watching
his spiel on the flat tax fall flatter than the blue line you see
here which represents the maximum rate of taxation on earned
income, Forbes was desperately casting about for something new.
</P>
<P>
   Like Lamar Alexander and Dan Quayle, Forbes has a presidential
campaign teetering on the edge of becoming a throwaway line on
David Letterman's Top 10 List. (``Top 10 Organizations that could
do a better job managing the Mets: ... No. 5 _ The Yugoslav Air
Force; No. 4 _ The Forbes Campaign; No. 3 ...'' )
</P>
<P>
   It's a fate candidates lie awake at night contemplating.
</P>
<P>
   There were too many right-wing candidates for president for any
candidate to get noticed by threatening to punish somebody new.
(``If elected, I will move immediately to arrest all the
Teletubbies!'')
</P>
<P>
   The boring middle, the moralistic right and the kinder and
gentler left all have been taken up by what people believe George
W. Bush might say when that glorious day arrives for him to say
something specific.
</P>
<P>
   And everyone running for the Republican nomination already wants
more missiles, lower taxes and to make kids stand up straight, pray
before class and stop being so snotty.
</P>
<P>
   How is someone supposed to stand out?
</P>
<P>
   The only way to break out from pack is to find a brand new issue
and jump on it feet first.
</P>
<P>
   Commentators say such issues ``fly under the radar.'' The
pollsters can't spot them. They can only be chased like fireflies.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, then, went chasing and found the answer was right there
in his wallet _ as so many answers are for multimillionaires.
</P>
<P>
   The $20 bill. You can almost hear how the inspiration crept up
on him:
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at that sorry thing, will you? That grossly oversized
Jackson _ a Democrat! _ staring up at you with those nasty crazed
eyes that follow you every time the ATM spits out cash. It's wrong.
Not like the old $20s. The old bills had dignity, proportion and a
nice view of a Clintonless White House. But these new things.
Numbers without serifs. Looks European or something. Looks like
that stupid moose-money they spend up in Canada. Hey-y-y ...''
</P>
<P>
   An idea was born.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes hit the trail in Iowa damning bills that ``look like
Monopoly money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something that's going to change if a certain person is
elected president. We'll have money that looks real again,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A new issue was discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Money that looks real again. Certainly a slogan to conjure with.
No pocketbook issue could be easier to grasp, to visualize. It asks
us to hearken back to a time when men were men, women were women
and $20 bills looked like $20 bills.
</P>
<P>
   This could be easily broadened to a cry for cars that look like
real cars, offices that look like real offices and restaurants that
serve food that looks like real food.
</P>
<P>
   For our kids to start looking like real kids and wear shoes that
look like real shoes. For beer that tastes real again. And chicken
that tastes real in every real-looking pot.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are asked to absorb crazy amounts of change. And for
that reason, we get cranky over small things. Like blue M&AMP;Ms. Like
learning new area codes. Like not being given the option of paper
bags at the supermarket. Like $20 bills that have numbers in a
Hershey-bar typeface.
</P>
<P>
   Money that looks like money. It sounds dumb, but to change-weary
Americans it might be just dumb enough to strike a chord.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe someone will push for a constitutional amendment. It's a
bad week, indeed, when the House of Representatives doesn't get
around to passing another new amendment to the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   But, then again, that could create even more change, which
wouldn't be in the spirit of this issue. Maybe this is something
best left alone.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
