<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1729 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN29-COX     06-28 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's a different world in Miami
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI, Fla. _ ``Let me tell you about the very rich. They are
different from you and me.'' F. Scott Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amen.'' E. Elizabeth Schuett.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Miami, my old home town, a sun-drenched world of
conspicuous consumption, where if the local marina can't come up
with a dock large enough to accommodate your new 70-foot yacht, you
simply buy a $7 million waterfront home and float your own boat.
True story.
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon I saw a little league team in a swanky-looking van
pull into Baskin-Robbins for an after-game treat. I commented on
the pretty truck to my friend Jeanne. ``Pretty expensive
transportation,'' she said. ``It's a Mercedes SUV.'' When she told
me what it cost, I almost lost my yogurt and watched uneasily as
the team scrambled back in with their 31 flavors of potential
disaster in hand, and wondered if I was the only one worrying about
the upholstery.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when I'd had time to think about it, I figured it's kind
of like the old boat thing _ if you have to ask how much, you
obviously can't afford it, and if you're going to worry about
Junior slopping his chocolate-mint ripple on the custom upholstery,
you shoulda' bought a used pickup.
</P>
<P>
   One stoplight and a grocery store pretty much describes
Gibsonburg, the farm village in northwest Ohio that I have called
home for the past 16 years. Most of our houses have garages, some
are even attached, but nobody has a dock. The nearest body of water
is an abandoned lime quarry on the outskirts of town, and our idea
of a luxury car is one that will crank even when it's 20-below.
Kids still ride bikes to the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald was right. The rich really (SET ITAL)are(END ITAL)
different from the rest of us and one muggy Miami afternoon, I
figured it out.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne maneuvered us into a parking place just outside a ``must
see'' used clothing shop in Coconut Grove. I wasn't so sure I
wanted to look at a bunch of dresses somebody else had already
worn. ``Bleeck!'' was my astute comment. ``It'll probably stink in
there.'' Jeanne assured me it was well worth the visit and that the
``stinking rich'' really didn't smell bad. She said most of the
clothes had only been worn once anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne had to ring a bell to get us in. I asked why. She said
she wasn't sure but thought it was probably to keep out the
undesirables. From the way the clerk was eyeballing me, I figured
maybe that was us. She watched closely as we fingered our way
through a rack of designer labels and bugle beads. Suspecting she
could size up our Dun &AMP; Bradstreet from idle chatter, I muttered
something about dining with Buffy and Bippy since it was cook's
night out. Jeanne snickered.
</P>
<P>
   And that's when I asked the world's all-time most stupid
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is everything a size 4?'' The world-weary clerk stared in
disbelief and asked me if I was from out of town. When I failed to
come up with the right answer, she humored me.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Madam wishes,'' she oozed, ``we have zeroes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a look, lady,'' I said, spreading my arms for closer
inspection, ``does this body look like a zero to you?'' Rigorous
training prevented her from answering but I kept going. ``Where do
these clothes come from, anyway? The Betty Ford Clinic?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Palm Beach,'' Miss Congeniality sniffed as if she needn't
explain any further. She needn't. I asked what rich women eat.
``Practically nothing,'' Jeanne whispered. I suggested that was
because they were spending the grocery money on designer dresses. I
told Jeanne I felt the need for hot fudge. We bugged out.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of disparities, and we were, have you read about
Columba Bush (the Florida governor's wife) who went on a little
shopping jaunt to Paris and tried to sneak $19,000 worth of clothes
and jewelry through U.S. Customs? Says she didn't want her husband
to know how much money she'd spent.
</P>
<P>
   Enough, already. Beam me home, Scotty, and back to reality.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
