<HEADER>
A1730 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A29-COX     06-28 1587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am trying to locate an official Texas Rangers badge for
friends in California who would like to wear it on a trail ride
celebrating their sesquicentennial. _ Don Sulak A: Don, Don, Don _
think about it for a minute. The first official Texas Ranger badge
was issued in 1935 and there have been three designs since then. In
1935 there were only 42 Rangers (107 currently). Not that many
badges out there. So the official badges tend to stay with the
Rangers or their families. I would be suspicious of the
authenticity of any purported badge at an auction. The current
style (circle star) first appeared in a design used by a Ranger
Detachment under Ira Aten, whose squad quelled the 1889
Jaybird-Woodpecker War in Fort Bend County. The Texas Ranger Museum
archivist suggests you pick up a replica badge from the museum gift
store in Waco. Call (254) 750-8631.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We are having trouble with carpenter ants in our trees and
house. We cut back the trees and had a pest control company spray
the house. We need someone who can take care of the trees and the
house. _ Brenda T.
</P>
<P>
   A: Carpenter ants build nests in hollow trees and logs as well
as wood in homes. Unlike termites, the ants use the wood as a home,
not food. Entry points? Branches or utility lines touching a home,
window cracks, crevices, air conditioning ducts and attic
ventilation openings. The experts at the Texas Agricultural
Extension Service recommend that home owners identify colony
locations before treatment, replace decaying wood, repair plumbing
leaks, provide proper clearance between house and wood, remove
stumps and wood debris near the house and treat colonies within 100
feet of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was President Clinton's lottery number in the draft? Is
there a way to find out who had to go to Vietnam because he did
not? _ Henry M.
</P>
<P>
   A: No way to find out if someone went in an individual's place,
says Selective Service spokesman Lew Brodsky. President Clinton's
stint in the ROTC forestalled his induction in the armed services.
In the 1969 Selective Service Lottery, President' Clinton's
birthday, Aug. 19, was lucky _ No. 311. He and the other
registrants born between Jan. 1, 1944, and Dec. 31, 1950, were the
first to depart from the traditional method of induction call
(oldest men not yet 26). No. 1 in the 1969 lottery? Sept. 14.
Brodsky adds that when a draft is in operation, the most vulnerable
year for a young man to be drafted is the year he is 20 (out of
high school, usually not yet married and in good physical health).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Could you tell me the name of Hopalong Cassidy's horse? _
V.M.
</P>
<P>
   A: Topper was the white steed of the black-and-white-clad
Hopalong (actor William Boyd). His sidekick? Red Conners played by
Edgar Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Q: For many years I have looked up at those monstrous water
towers and wondered about the millions of gallons of water just
sitting there and, well, looking not unlike my dog's water dish _
mossy and just plain yucky. Have you? _ David R. Compton
</P>
<P>
   A: Can't say that I have. Great mental picture, but incorrect.
The water in these towers meets drinking water standards. If you
climb up there, you can sip safely. Texas Natural Resource
Conservation Commission's Tom Kelley says the interiors of these
tower tanks are steel with an approved protective coating. The
water is checked regularly. Occasionally a tower tank water supply
will be the subject of complaints. Unprotected exterior painting of
the tower may toss paint chips and powder in the water. Yuck.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Gov. George W. Bush was re-elected to office and announced
his candidacy for president. Now that he is campaigning while in
office, what happens to his salary and what is the amount? _
Barbara Hatter
</P>
<P>
   A: The governor continues to earn his annual salary _
$115,344.96 _ while campaigning. When the governor is out of the
state for a complete calendar day (midnight to midnight), the
acting governor also receives a salary for that day, says spokesman
Scott McClellan. For example, if Bush is out of the state that full
calendar day, then Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, as acting governor,
receives $316.01 for that day, on top of his munificent annual
salary of $7,200.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some kids have told me that if you save 100 Tootsie Pop
wrappers with the Indian shooting an arrow with a star and send
them in you get a year of free Tootsie Pops. Please confirm or
deny. I am up to my ears in wrappers. _ Becky R.
</P>
<P>
   A: Sorry, Becky, there is no free Tootsie Pop. Toss the
wrappers. You are correct _ the wrapper with the star and Indian is
uncommon _ only about one in four are so marked. Chief Shooting
Star is the legendary inspiration for the chewy, Tootsie-centered
lollipops.
</P>
<P>
   First introduced in 1931, the Tootsie Pop, named for the
5-year-old daughter of maker Leo Hirshfield, has been the focus of
much research. Purdue University Engineering students modeled a
licking machine after a human tongue. With it the students
determined it takes an average of 364 licks to get to the chewy
center of a Tootsie Pop. (No crunching allowed.)
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you give me the name of the theme song for the television
program ``Providence''? Also, can I buy it? _ Tom Hutchins
</P>
<P>
   A: How soon we forget. ``In My Life'' (a Beatles hit) is sung by
Chantal Kreviazuk. I have not found the song on her albums, but the
tremendous popularity of this show leads me to suspect the
``Providence'' soundtrack can't be long in coming. (Remember the
``Northern Exposure'' phenomenon?)
</P>
<P>
   Q: What should I do? I was informed of someone trying to use my
Social Security number to get credit. Do I need a new Social
Security number? Can I even get a new number?
</P>
<P>
   _ C.H.
</P>
<P>
   A: Trouble in River City. Glad you were notified. Some people
only find out after credit is extended to the thief. Contact the
three major credit reporting bureaus immediately and have your
credit history flagged. You will be contacted before credit is
extended in your name: Equifax at (800) 525-6285; Trans Union at
(800) 680-7289; and Experian at (800) 301-7195. If you are still
disadvantaged by the misuse of your number after these agencies
have been contacted, a new Social Security number may be assigned
to you. Then you must report the changed number everywhere you do
business. Of course there is no guarantee, says Social Security's
Sandra Talbot, that the new number will not fall into the wrong
hands. Please be careful.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a 30-year-old male with thinning hair. I am not the kind
of guy who looks good in a hat, so my scalp just keeps getting
sunburnt. A friend told me about a sunscreen for the scalp, but I
am not able to locate it _ Head Smart by Coppertone. I have looked
on their Web site and did not find it either. Have you heard of a
sunscreen that I can spray onto my scalp after my hair has been
shampooed and fixed, and should it be sprayed before or after I
apply hairspray? _ Brent N.
</P>
<P>
   A: Head Smart was test marketed last year in select areas so it
is not available currently. However, the next generation of this
spray-on sun block is. Pick up Coppertone Sport Sun Block Spray in
SPF 15 or SPF 30. This is sweatproof and should be applied after
grooming. Remove it later from your scalp with soap and water. It
is fast-drying and, good news, widely available.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I got an idea off the Web to give my reception guests tree
saplings as favors. Supposedly this person called a conservation
department and they sent her the saplings in tubes. Do you have any
idea whom to contact for this? _ L. Warren
</P>
<P>
   A: Sure do. The GreenWorld Project sells several items that fill
the bill. Trees from this organization are sent in a clear plastic
sleeve or tube with your personal message attached or inside.
Perfect for wedding guests or for other events. Some customers
order the trees to memorialize lost loved ones. You may select a
ribbon color and cap color for the tubed trees, which come in 8-,
10-, and 14-inch sizes. Maybe the wedding day petals, birdseed or
bird feeder tree would interest you. To help make a decision, order
the wedding day sample package (one of everything) before deciding.
The 8-inch tree in a tube begins at $2.25 each plus shipping.
Sorry, no break for quantity unless you have a really big wedding _
a thousand people. Contact GreenWorld at (800) 825-5122 or
www.greenworldproject.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I finally got around to watching the movie ``Saving Private
Ryan'' on video. It was an awesome movie, but it left me wondering
about the final scene, which shows an elderly ``Private Ryan''
looking over the grave of Captain Miller at the cemetery at
Normandy, France. I thought those service members buried at
Normandy had died during that battle, not at other battle sites (as
indicated by the movie). _ Mark M.
</P>
<P>
   A: American soldiers who died in the general area, not just
those who died in the invasion, were eligible for burial in this
cemetery, according to the American Battle Monuments Commission.
The fictitious Captain Miller died in the area so his interment at
the cemetery is plausible. This cemetery, by the way, was the first
American military cemetery established in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
