<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With proper search utensil, you can locate any recipe
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Almost every good cook owns a shelf or two of
cookbooks. It's easy to recognize the best cookbooks on the shelf.
Those are the ones with grease spots and flour on the cover.
</P>
<P>
   Even the best library of cookbooks fails us from time to time.
There will be a recipe you can't find, or it'll be time to find a
new way to prepare an old dish. That's when it's time to browse the
world's largest library of recipes _ the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of great sites filled with recipes and _ with
most _ you can use the computer's ability to search for information
and keywords to go directly to the recipe you need.
</P>
<P>
   Our appetizer on today's culinary adventure is a site called
SOAR. That stands for the Searchable Online Archive of Recipes.
You'll find the site at soar.berkeley.edu/recipes/. This place
lives up to its name. While you can search for recipes by category
_ main dish, dessert and so on _ the real strength here is in the
search engine.
</P>
<P>
   If you're like a lot of people, you may not remember the formal
name of the dish you want to prepare, but you do remember the
ingredients. For instance, let's say all you know is that the
recipe used the Italian wine Marsala.
</P>
<P>
   Using Marsala as a keyword, the search turned up more than 100
recipes (you'll have to do your own search to find out exactly how
many of the 57,000 recipes in this database use Marsala) before I
stopped counting. There was Linguine Gamberini, Chicken Florentine,
Pork with Figs, Salmon Scampi ... the list goes on.
</P>
<P>
   The search even has a feature that helps poor spellers: You can
set it so that even if you spell Marsala as ``marsalla'' it'll find
the term. You can also use multiple search words, which is
especially handy with a database this size. You probably wouldn't
want to search, for instance, simply for ``beef.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the ability to search is so important, let's take a look
at another recipe site with search features. This one is called the
Online Cookbook and is located at i99.com/cook/. You can search
this site by keyword, just like in our first example. However,
instead of the 100-plus recipes, a search for ``marsala'' here
turned up just six recipes. The difference seems to be that at this
site, you'll only get recipes with the keyword in the title. You
can also search an alphabetical index. So if you know the name of
the dish starts with a ``B,'' you can browse those recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Our next site, the Culinary Cafe at www.culinarycafe.com/,
doesn't offer a keyword search. Instead, it uses a more
conventional approach. You select the category for the recipe _
cookies, cakes, main dishes, appetizers and so forth. For instance,
if you select the broad term of seafood, you'll go to a page where
you can then select recipes based on the type of seafood. It's a
more cumbersome process if you're searching for a specific recipe
but may be a handy method when you know that you want to prepare a
seafood dish but don't have a specific recipe in mind.
</P>
<P>
   The last stop on our search for the perfect recipe is at a place
called 1st Traveler's Choice Internet Cookbook at
www.virtualcities.com/ons/recipe.htm. The notion here is that the
recipes were gathered from famous restaurants, inns and hotels. The
search method here is the same as the one used at Culinary Cafe.
But there is a nifty feature that most cooks will appreciate. There
is a program on the page that helps you convert various measures.
So you'll be able to quickly find, for instance, that a half cup is
the same as 4 ounces, or 8 tablespoons, or 24 teaspoons, or 118 ml.
If you use a variety of cookbooks, including some from countries
that use liters and milliliters, then this will help you decipher
the measuring system.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
