r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETWATCH29-COX     06-28 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hey, candidates: Show a little life
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The presidential pregame show is already under way,
even though there's more than a year to go before the actual
election. In addition to political advisers and pollsters, the
candidates of the next millennium are also hiring gurus to design
Web sites that will engage voters, garner donations and keep the
media up to date on their latest campaign doings.
</P>
<P>
   As the trade magazine The Industry Standard put it, ``Move over
James Carville and Mary Matalin. There's a new breed of political
consultant out there, one that knows how to write (Web design code)
HTML.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, nobody's doing a particularly good job of online
campaigning. Despite some of the high-paid firepower employed by
some of the leading candidates, it appears the heavy artillery is
on hold. What we have now are primarily introductory Web sites,
offering information, travel agendas, speeches, slogans and secure
servers so Web surfers can make donations before hopping off to
eBay to bid on that Rocky and Bullwinkle vintage lunchbox.
</P>
<P>
   However, there's one bit of advice every political candidate and
his or her Web team must learn. Write it on a blackboard 500 times
if you must, just learn it.
</P>
<P>
   The Web is a visual, interactive medium. Yes, that's right,
in-ter-ac-tive. Remember, you are talking to people who are used to
posting book reviews on Amazon.com, complaining to Lands' End that
their weekly overstocks site has too many orange polo shirts and
clogging Yahoo! Finance message boards with hot Internet stock
tips.
</P>
<P>
   This is your chance to let people talk to you. Complain to you.
For heaven's sake, this is a 24-hour, seven-day-a-week town
meeting. Go for it. Post your best pictures. Provide excerpts from
your best speeches. Tell us when you'll be in our town. Ask us what
we care about. Maybe have us take a poll or two. Do something,
anything to make voters get involved with you and your Web site.
</P>
<P>
   In-ter-ac-tive. If you don't know what it means, ask one of your
college student volunteers. Then do it.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the presidential sites are wading into the Web waters
with so-so results. For example, Al Gore, self-described Net geek,
has a Web site that lives up to his reputation as a somewhat
less-than-colorful candidate. But as anyone who has seen the vice
president poking fun at himself with David Letterman knows, the
candidate does have a lighter side. Only pieces of it show on his
Web site, and as Ross Perot would say, ``That's just sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Gore is online every day, the people who put his Web
site together might want to head back to the design studio for a
few pointers. The site posts Gore's speeches as just one long page
of plain text. No pictures, nothing, simply an endless stream of
pale blue text. Few political speeches are memorable barnburners
the ordinary citizen will want to read again and again. However, if
the candidate has a serious message to convey, pouring it onto the
Internet is not the way to do it. It's boring and doesn't give
voters much insight.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's Town Hall section is the most interesting part of the
site, and he'd do well to put this kind of interactive feature on
all his pages, especially the ones with the deadly speeches.
Ordinary people ask questions, and Gore gives simple answers in a
chatty but dignified tone.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate could also learn a thing or two from the page
devoted to his wife, Tipper. The page is filled with pictures of a
smiling Tipper traveling the world, hugging children and jogging
with the Russian Olympic team. Should Gore win the election, Tipper
won't have the political influence of Hillary Rodham Clinton, but
here she's shown at her political and personal best.
</P>
<P>
   Another tip for aspiring presidential candidates: Register those
Web addresses early and often. Register every variation on your
name or campaign you can think of. Pay for it yourself. They're
only $70 each from Network Solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, you'll find yourself in the unfortunate situation of
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, whose late entry into the online
campaign left plenty of room for a parody site, www.gwbush.com. The
site's not quite as funny as some of the parody sites that popped
up in 1996, but it is still official-looking enough to prompt the
governor, the apparent Republican front-runner, to file a legal
complaint against the site, which lampoons his personal life and
policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There ought to be limits to freedom,'' Bush told The Dallas
Morning News. Not good. Definitely not good with those
free-speech-loving, anti-regulation Internet types. Taken out of
context, it could be upsetting to a whole lot of people who've
grown fond of the First Amendment over the last 210 years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush now has his own official Web site, www.georgewbush
</P>
<P>
   .com, which looks as if it were designed by the folks who did
the parody site. Also not good. However, it was the first bit of
online political excitement to date and a potential political
setback for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates all have miles to go before the Web becomes an
essential campaign tool. There's plenty of time to learn to use it
to its best advantage. It really does matter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
