<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-WARHEROES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia's (Revolutionary War) superheroes
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Casimir Pulaski wasn't from Georgia, but he was one of
our greatest heroes of the American Revolution. That's why a county
in Georgia and dozens of others across the country are named in his
honor.
</P>
<P>
   After fighting the British in Charleston during the Revolution,
Pulaski _ appointed a general by his friend George Washington _
took his cavalry to Savannah to win back land held by the British.
</P>
<P>
   In October of 1779, Pulaski's troops were ordered to support the
Colonial infantry in breaking the redcoats' line of defense in what
is now downtown Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in a crossfire, the American patriots and their French
allies were routed, but Pulaski led a charge to try to win the day.
</P>
<P>
   He was wounded in the fighting and was taken to a nearby
plantation, where he died.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pulaski was a Polish general who had led several failed
revolts in his own country, he's best remembered _ even in Poland _
as an American hero. There were lots of others from Georgia as
well.
</P>
<P>
   During the Revolution, Georgia was one of 13 American Colonies
that belonged to Great Britain. Most of the state was woodlands,
populated by small farmers.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Georgians weren't as angry with the British as people
in other Colonies. But after the Battle of Lexington in
Massachusetts on April 19, 1775, that began to change.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble was, the British had lots of soldiers in Georgia, mainly
to protect Colonists from Indians.
</P>
<P>
   So, when war came, many Georgians rooted for, and fought with,
the British. They were called Tories, and there was a lot of
fighting between Tories and patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Button Gwinnett, George Walton and Lyman Hall were Georgians who
could have been hanged as traitors for signing the Declaration of
Independence on July 4, 1776.
</P>
<P>
   All three have counties named for them in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   So does Archibald Bulloch, who at one time was president of
Georgia. He was a planter, clergyman and politician in the Colonial
version of the Georgia Legislature. He later was a delegate to the
Continental Congress.
</P>
<P>
   He was an outspoken leader for patriots _ at a time when
speaking against the British could cost you your life.
</P>
<P>
   Another county is named for Nancy Hart.
</P>
<P>
   Her deeds are so amazing that many think she's only a legend.
</P>
<P>
   She's known for killing a Tory and capturing four others all by
herself. Once, she dressed like a man to spy on the British in
Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   And although most black people in Georgia were slaves, some
fought for America's independence. One of the most famous is Austin
Dabney, who was given his freedom for his heroism in a battle near
Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's state government paid him a pension for wounds
suffered in battle until he died in 1830.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolutionary War ended on Oct. 19, 1781. It took another
eight months to kick the British out of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the patriots lost the Battle of Savannah _ but found
a hero in Pulaski.
</P>
<P>
   DID YOU KNOW?
</P>
<P>
   There were many stories about what happened to Gen. Casimir
Pulaski's body after he died. Recently, some bones were found in a
55-foot monument that was falling apart in Savannah. Scientists
believe the bones are Pulaski's. They are testing DNA from the
bones to see if they match a Pulaski relative. The results are
expected soon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
