<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dive sticks can hurt kids
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Check your garages for pool dive sticks and don't play
with them anymore. The U.S. government says the sticks can hurt you
badly. These hard plastic sticks stand up in the bottom of pools
for kids to retrieve. However, a few kids cannonballing into the
water have been hospitalized after landing on the sticks and
getting stabbed.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second largest recall ever by the U.S. Consumer
Product Safety Commission, which tries to protect people from
dangerous products. More than 19 million of the sticks have sold
since 1979. The Commission also wants to ban the sticks so they
can't be sold again.
</P>
<P>
   You should return them to the stores from which they were bought
for refunds or substitute toys.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees flood homeland
</P>
<P>
   Peacekeepers in Yugoslavia are struggling to protect Serbs from
revenge attacks by returning Kosovar Albanians. More than 300,000
of the Muslim refugees flooded back into Kosovo last week. The
returning refugees torched Serb houses and looted Serb-owned shops.
Panicky Serbs left nearby towns, accusing ethnic Albanians of
chasing them out.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Serbs were attacking the Kosovar Albanians,
killing many and forcing others from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   About 860,000 Kosovar Albanians were reported to have fled or
been expelled from Kosovo since NATO launched a bombing campaign
March 24. The bombing was meant to force Yugoslavia to accept a
peace plan for the province.
</P>
<P>
   Man not tasty to sharks
</P>
<P>
   You'll be relieved to know that most great white sharks don't
want to eat you. In fact, they don't even think you taste very
good. A research team observed 128 white shark attacks on seals,
sea lions and birds. They noted the sharks attacked seals with such
gusto that some were bitten in two. Yet with other items _ a
pelican, a decomposing seal, a sheep's carcass, a buoy and a
surfboard _ the sharks would cautiously mouth them and spit them
out. The scientists say the same is true with humans.
</P>
<P>
   One possible explanation is that white sharks are warm-blooded,
and may need a high-energy diet. To a shark, a blubbery seal is
like a Snickers bar, but humans aren't fatty enough.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there have been a few exceptions. Worldwide, there
have been 245 documented great white shark attacks on people and 64
deaths since 1876, according to the Florida Museum of Natural
History.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
