<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-ALBUM29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Family photo album has gone high-tech
 &HT;    By Omar Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ I have a cousin named Brianna whom, because of
work commitments, I wasn't able to see in person for a long time
after she was born.
</P>
<P>
   When she was about 2 years old, I opened my e-mail to discover a
huge, full-color photo of the baby sent by my parents. Immediately,
I got a breathless call from my mother. She wanted to make sure I
received the scanned photo, and of course, to comment on how cute
Brianna was. ``Que hermosa!'' my mom said.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing my mother get excited about an infant isn't new, but
seeing her thrilled about a new piece of technology (in this case,
a scanner I'd lent her) is.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of other home users are getting excited, too, because PC
components like scanners, digital cameras, color printers and
editing software have dropped so far in price that even casual PC
users can turn their computers into photo editing studios.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just about price, although sub-$100 scanners and
ever-cheaper color printers have helped. The real reason why people
are turning to digital photos is that many users who only use their
computers for word processing or checkbook balancing have found a
killer application that is practical and truly useful.
</P>
<P>
   Digital photos are the culmination of several wants that
consumers have had and technological and pricing steps that are
fulfilling them. They are:
</P>
<P>
   _Storage _ Print photos decay, get lost, get torn up by angry
ex-spouses, get misfiled in family albums. The increasing size of
hard drives and the increasing number of storage options on PCs
(Zip drives, recordable CDs) make storing large numbers of large
photo files possible. Software makers like E-Book Systems have
created software like ``Digital Flip Album,'' which lets users
create slide shows and computerized photo albums.
</P>
<P>
   _Web development _ As more companies and individuals put up Web
pages, digital cameras and scanners have made it easy to turn
text-only Web pages into colorful, image-laden sites.
</P>
<P>
   _Easy mailing _ E-mail has made the near-instantaneous exchange
of data a reality. Being able to send photos to grandma with a few
clicks of a mouse button (provided she has an Internet account) is
a real-world, practical use for all the technology that the Intels
and Microsofts have been pushing all these years.
</P>
<P>
   _Easy transport _ Digital photos are pretty portable as it is,
with several dozen fitting on a single Zip disk, but future plans
are to make them even more so. Sony, for instance, has introduced
the Memory Stick, a plastic piece of memory that measures about the
size of a stick of gum. A memory stick will hold music, photos and
files and can transfer information between computers, digital
devices and even digital picture frames that can display an image
on a flat screen.
</P>
<P>
   _Photo editing _ Last week, Britain's new Earl of Wessex, Prince
Edward, had a royal photographer replace a glum-looking Prince
William from a photo of Edward's wedding with a happier image of
the young man using digital editing. While this may be a little
extreme, digital editing software can perform more simple tasks
like removing red-eye from photos, cropping a photo, erasing
smudges and spots on an image and even changing the background on a
picture. While it also makes it easier to doctor photos to suggest
alien abductions, photo editing can help correct problems in what
would otherwise be perfect pictures.
</P>
<P>
   _Quality and production _ The newer digital image products,
including mega-pixel digital cameras and high-resolution scanners,
produce much better-quality images than older models, which
sometimes produced grainy, pixelized pictures. A chief complaint
among early adopters was poor imaging, but as the technology has
improved, digital photos can now rival the sharpness and depth of
print photos. If that can be achieved without a stop at the
one-hour photo shop, consumers will find it more convenient.
</P>
<P>
   No one is suggesting that the digital revolution spells the end
of print photos, but print image giants like Kodak and Adobe have
been quick to produce software and Web sites that cater to home
users who want new ways to store and use photos.
</P>
<P>
   Archiving digital memories will continue to get cheaper and
easier, saving us more time and money to take photogenic vacations
that will end up in our PC scrapbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
