<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oohs and aahs tell the story of this minivan
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If I told you that minivans are the vehicles that
drive me to renew my driver's license, I'd be lying. They are the
dry toast of the automotive industry _ necessary, useful, but not
adrenaline-pumping.
</P>
<P>
   You can imagine my curiosity when I saw this look of pure
ecstasy come over a woman at the post office as she approached the
Honda Odyssey I was test driving. I understood her reaction when
she climbed into her own 10-plus-year-old minivan.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, it was a similar experience in the parking lot of
a local discount store, but this time, the driver was lusting from
a new minivan. Then, at a racetrack, the driver of a late-model
stock car who had just turned in a blistering qualifying lap was
more interested in talking about the Odyssey than his qualifying
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear it's got lots of room,'' he said. ``My neighbor
actually uses his to transport his son's competition go-kart and
all its spares on the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   I liked the Odyssey's 3.5-liter V-6 low-emissions VTEC engine,
the most powerful in the minivan segment. But I also liked the way
the Odyssey drove. Many minivans, when loaded down, tend to waddle
down the highway. To its credit, the Odyssey's handling
characteristics remained consistent whether fully loaded or with
just me driving. This could be because of the Odyssey's rear
double-wishbone suspension and gas-pressurized shocks.
</P>
<P>
   Odyssey's low entry threshold accommodates easy entry and exit.
Loaded, at highway speeds, the Odyssey gave better than 23 miles
per gallon. I also liked all the usable space.
</P>
<P>
   You really don't realize just how big a vehicle it is until you
go to wash it.
</P>
<P>
   The fold-down third seat is without question the best in the
industry. The Odyssey can have a perfectly flat floor from the rear
door all the way to the back of the front seats.
</P>
<P>
   I was fond of the little table between the two front bucket
seats. My initial reaction was that it would be flimsy and
impractical, but nothing could have been further from the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The minivan set knows its stuff. From women lusting in the
parking lots to racers looking for a new set of wheels, a 159.2
percent increase in Odyssey sales in May confirms the vehicle's
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
