<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DeLorme's Topo USA knows its terrain well
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ DeLorme, the most prolific and diverse publisher of
digital maps, has produced a topographical map of the United
States, available in one whopping big DVD disk or by regions on
single CD-ROMs.
</P>
<P>
   While I am no cartographic expert, Topo USA seems a remarkable
achievement; the entire United States _ all 50 states _ in
topographical detail on a single disk, with a full complement of
bells and whistles.
</P>
<P>
   The most amazing thing about the maps is the available detail.
You can zoom in to a scale of 100 feet to 1 inch, with contour
changes shown at intervals of 20 feet everywhere but in Alaska,
where the maximum is 100 feet. I was able to determine the
elevation of my own house.
</P>
<P>
   You can search for a geographic point, a town or a street
address, and all are produced remarkably quickly.
</P>
<P>
   There is a set of tools for drawing on a map, and a mode in
which you can set up a hiking trip, complete with waypoints. All
this can be saved as a separate map and printed out in case you
aren't lugging your laptop with you.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you are lugging the laptop, the map will
work with DeLorme's Global Positioning satellite receivers to show
you exactly where you are at any given time.
</P>
<P>
   The normal view is top down with standard indicators of
elevation change. As you move the cursor across the screen, a
window on the left side contains boxes that constantly change to
show the latitude and longitude, and the elevation, of the cursor
location. Upon your order, the view will shift to a 3-D elevation
that can be controlled in terms of angle and rotation. It is not a
great rendering, but it gives a good idea of the terrain.
</P>
<P>
   You can change the regular cursor to a ``query cursor,'' so that
clicking anywhere on the map provides information on the specific
location. This is most useful, as the maps are not cluttered with a
lot of place names. Ponds of 4-5 acres loom like the Great Lakes at
maximum zoom levels. Many creeks that doubtless have names are
relegated to the status of ``intermittent stream,'' but you can't
expect everything, I suppose.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, Topo USA is full of pleasant surprises. I asked it to
find Ingalls in Oklahoma, expecting no response. But the program
cogitated for a couple of seconds and then presented me with a map
of north central Oklahoma and a label pointing to Ingalls.
</P>
<P>
   This was a surprise because Ingalls no longer exists. More than
100 years ago it was an outlaw town, and became the scene of one of
the most epic gunbattles in Western history when a couple of
wagonloads of U.S. deputy marshals tried to capture the Doolin
gang. Now, however, none of the buildings remains and it is largely
blackjack thicket, a piece of history gone forever.
</P>
<P>
   Not in Topo, however, and to my delight, when I asked the
``query cursor'' to report on the location, it came back describing
Ingalls not as a town, but as a locale.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not a hiker, but I love maps and Topo USA is a treat. The
DVD is priced at a very reasonable list of $100.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
