<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Flat-rate' repairs usually aid customers
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Last winter, the power window in my mother's '81 Olds
decided to quit in the down position. With our mild climate in
Atlanta, this situation would have been nothing more than an
inconvenience. But in Reno, Nev., freezing temperatures, blowing
snow and my 98-year-old granny turning blue in the front seat
constituted an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   My mother managed to get the car to her mechanic's shop just as
he was closing down for the weekend. Realizing her predicament, he
reopened the shop door and motioned her inside. Within half an hour
he had restored the window to the up position, a temporary fix that
would require the replacement of the window motor when the part
came in. Until then, the car could be driven, and the heater would
keep its passengers warm.
</P>
<P>
   Mom relayed the story to me the following week, complaining,
``He charged me for an hour's time to do that job and it didn't
take him 20 minutes!''
</P>
<P>
   I was appalled at her attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're lucky you got it fixed at all,'' I retorted. ``Most
shops would have kept the car and sent you and Nonnie home in a cab
without weekend transportation.''
</P>
<P>
   My irritation spent, I calmly went on to explain the flat-rate
system. In short, most mechanics get paid by the job, not the
amount of time it takes them to do that job.
</P>
<P>
   Her mechanic probably had done that kind of repair many times.
She was charged for his knowledge of the problem and his expertise
in fixing it. An inexperienced mechanic might have taken two hours.
The charge still would have been for one hour. While not all
automotive repairs, particularly diagnostics, neatly fit into the
``flat-rate'' category, those that do usually work to the
customer's advantage.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the system encourages volume production. With
many businesses that operate this way, quality can suffer.
</P>
<P>
   I could have sympathized with Mom's tale had the window fallen
down or broken on the way home, but it held throughout the week, as
promised. She was, of course, charged again when the window motor
was replaced, and the mechanic beat the flat rate on that job, too.
The window still works fine.
</P>
<P>
   I hear the ``flat-rate blues'' all the time from both customers
and mechanics. Customers feel like they're being overcharged for
labor. Mechanics say that the flat-rate time being paid for many
complicated repairs is not enough to do the job properly.
Consequently, they may make money on the easy repairs and lose
money on the hard ones.
</P>
<P>
   The system certainly encourages shortcuts. Some are harmless,
but some produce shoddy results.
</P>
<P>
   While I am not a fan of the flat-rate system, it seems to work
for non-automotive businesses.
</P>
<P>
   A recent bout with pneumonia sent me to my HMO provider's
medical office. After an examination and a chest X-ray, I was sent
home with a bag full of medicine. A week passed and my symptoms
worsened, so I went back to the office. Another office visit,
another co-payment.
</P>
<P>
   When you think about it, salaries are a method of flat-rate pay.
If the job is completed in 30, 40 or 80 hours, the pay is the same.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter, who has 27 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, writes exclusively for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
