<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Private technology leaders recognized
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's a list for everything these days, and private
technology companies are no exception. The June issue of Upside
magazine lists what it considers the 100 top private technology
companies. The winners were picked, the magazine says, from some
1,000 contenders. Among those selected was Brocade Communications
Systems of San Jose, Calif. It makes fiber-channel switching
equipment used in digital networks. Another winner was Copper
Mountain Networks of Palo Alto, Calif. Copper Mountain makes a
technology that speeds up the digital telephone technology the Baby
Bells are trying to deploy.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   You can learn just about everything via computer these days, and
that includes music. Harmonic Vision, based in Evanston, Ill., has
released two computer CDs that teach kids the fundamentals of music
theory and how to read music. The CDs are called Music Ace and
Music Ace 2. The first program is for beginners, the second for
more advanced students. Each program retails for about $50. For
more information about the Music Ace CDs, check out the company's
Web site at www.harmonicvision.com. You can also download free
demos of the programs, which will work on both Macs and PCs, from
the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Edmark, a educational software company based in Seattle, has
released two new titles in its Thinkin' Things series. ``All Around
Frippletown'' uses the motif of a silly town to teach
problem-solving and logic. Edmark's second title uses a mystery
motif to teach the same skills in ``Sky Island Mysteries.'' Kids
help Inspector Cluestoe solve 14 mysteries. In doing so, they are
called on to gather information and draw conclusions. Each game is
available for either PCs or Macs and retails for about $30.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   There are tons of new developments in the Apple and Mac
community. A great way to keep up with all the changes is a Web
site called MacSurfer. It's a compendium of headlines and items
from the major Mac sites across the Web. Click on a headline, and
you'll jump right to the story. MacSurfer also maintains links to
sites that list software upgrades. You'll find MacSurfer at www
</P>
<P>
   .macsurfer.com.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the fastest way to look up information, but it does
work. Encyclopedia.com is a Web-based encyclopedia. You type in a
request in the search window, and the site presents a definition
and other information. You'll find this site at www
</P>
<P>
   .encyclopedia.com/.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
