r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-CENTURY-'50S-T     06-28 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-CENTURY-'50S-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MICK HAD THE NAME, AND THE GAME
</HEADLINE>
 
1950s ATHLETE OF DECADE MICKEY MANTLE (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mickey Mantle was born and bred to be a baseball player.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Elvin (Mutt) Mantle, a zinc and lead miner in
eastern Oklahoma named Mickey in honor of Tigers' Hall of Fame
catcher, Mickey Cochrane. Mutt, who also played semipro baseball,
tutored his son from an early age and taught him to switch-hit.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Mantle went on to become the most feared switch-hitter in
baseball history as a member of the New York Yankees. QUOTE HERE He
began his major-league career in 1951, ultimately bridging two eras
of Yankees dynasties at the twilight of Joe DiMaggio's career.
Mantle helped lead the Yankees to six World Series titles in the
'50s (1950, 1951, 1952, 1953, 1956 and 1958).
</P>
<P>
   His best year statistically came in 1956 when he won the Triple
Crown, batting .353 with 52 home runs and 130 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   He led the American League in home runs three years in the
decade (1955, '56 and '58) and RBI four times (1954, '56, '57 and
'58). A three-time MVP, Mantle finished with 536 home runs but left
his fans wondering how much more he could have done if not for a
career shortened due in part to injuries and the toll of his
carousing off the field. Mantle battled through chronic knee pain
that originated in the '51 World Series when he tripped over a
sprinkler head going after a fly ball.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Mantle maintained a larger-than-life persona as
the greatest player on one of the greatest dynasties in sports
history.
Runners-up:
</P>
<P>
   Bill Russell: He who won two NCAA championships with San
Francisco in 1955 and 1956 and helped revolutionize the NBA game as
center for the Boston Celtics. Russell helped the United States to
a gold medal in the 1956 Olympics and led the Celtics to the NBA
title in 1957, starting a run in which they took 11 of 13
championships.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Mays: Despite missing almost two seasons while in the
Army, Mays hit 250 home runs, drove in 709 runs and batted .317 in
the decade. His sprinting, back-to-the-infield, over-the-shoulder
catch of Vic Wertz's 440-foot drive to center field in the eighth
inning of Game 1 of the 1954 World Series helped ignite the New
York Giants to a four-game sweep of the Cleveland Indians, who had
won 111 regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Hogan: The Fort Worth resident staged a remarkable comeback
from a near-fatal automobile accident that occurred in 1949. Hogan
won the U.S. Open in 1950, '51 and '53. In his greatest year, 1953,
he captured three major championships _ the U.S. Open, Masters and
British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Gordie Howe: The durable Howe teamed with Ted Lindsay and Sid
Abel on the famed ``Production Line'' that led the Red Wings to
Stanley Cup titles in 1950, 1952, 1954 and 1955.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1769 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENTURY-SPORTS-'50S-T     06-28 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-SPORTS-'50S-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE ATHLETICS' UNDERSIDE REVEALED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the spring of 1950, college basketball had finally arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Playing to a packed Madison Square Garden, City College of New
York defeated Bradley University, 69-61, in the National Invitation
Tournament championship game. Eight days later, they pulled an
unprecedented double by defeating Bradley again, 71-68, in the NCAA
Tournament championship.
</P>
<P>
   CCNY's ``Cinderella Team,'' led by super sophomores Eddie Roman,
Al Roth and Floyd Layne, appeared on the verge of becoming college
basketball's first big-time dynasty. But behind the scenes,
gamblers had gotten to CCNY's stars and convinced them to shave
points.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal wasn't unearthed until the 1950-51 season. On July
6, 1951, those three players were among 13 who pleaded guilty to
accepting bribes and shaving points.
</P>
<P>
   By the conclusion of New York district attorney Frank Hogan's
investigation, 33 players from seven schools, including CCNY,
Kentucky, Long Island University, Toledo and Bradley, had been
implicated in fixing 49 games in 23 cities. Overall, 90 games had
been discussed and a total of $72,950 had changed hands in bribes,
bringing the ascendant game to the brink of self-destruction.
</P>
<P>
   In a 63-page ruling, Judge Saul Streit blamed, among other
things, athletic scholarships, win-first philosophies, and
overzealous and overgenerous boosters for the manipulation of
often-impoverished students who fell prey to gamblers, mobsters and
bookies. He insisted that ``everyone is doing it'' and that players
should get a piece of the financial windfall that basketball
brought the colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds familiar, eh?
</P>
<P>
   Though many of the players in the '51 scandals were banned from
collegiate and professional basketball, the temptations outweighed
the punishment. As they do to this day. In 1997, two former Arizona
State players pleaded guilty to attempting to shave points in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA last week concluded a two-year study on gambling. It
supports a recommendation to restrict legal gambling to those over
age 21 and to ban legal betting on college and amateur events.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way we keep our sanity around here is that we admit we're
not going to solve the problem,'' said Bill Saum, who heads the
NCAA's investigations into gambling. ``It's not going to go away.
But we're trying to have a dramatic effect on those who wish to
wager and a dramatic effect on any individual who may even think
about point shaving.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1770 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-REPEAT-TEX     06-28 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-REPEAT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS START TALKING ABOUT POSSIBILITY OF ANOTHER TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The NBA has come full circle in the '90s: from
Detroit's Bad Boys to San Antonio's Choir Boys.
</P>
<P>
   After capping their dominating run through the playoffs with a
4-1 Finals romp against the New York Knicks, the Sunday School
Spurs yesterday headed back to the Alamo City praising their
wholesome foundation, dismissing talk of their title being tainted
and already chatting up a repeat in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got as good a chance as anybody else,'' said Finals MVP
Tim Duncan, who poured in 31 points in Friday night's clinching
Game 5. ``I think the major pieces will be back, and there's no
reason to think we won't get better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Goody Two Sneakers Spurs, whose major controversy this
season was deciding which warm-ups to wear for pregame layups, hit
the trifecta by winning their first championship in the franchise's
26-year history. Not only do they get a summerlong fiesta on the
Riverwalk, they also provided momentum for the funding of a new
basketball-only arena and, in turn, gave Duncan motivation to
remain in San Antonio when his contract expires after next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was huge, bigger than just the moment,'' Spurs owner
Peter Holt said. ``Hopefully we'll look back someday and point to
this \RGame 5\S as where the dynasty really started rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   As evidenced by television ratings only slightly higher than a
late-night psychic hotline infomercial and a mundane game plan
founded on the rugged defense of 7-foot Twin Towers Duncan and
David Robinson, the Spurs don't keep fans on the edge of their
seats. But the NBA might as well sit back and get comfortable
watching, because they will likely be around for a while. The
nucleus of Duncan, Robinson, Sean Elliott, Mario Elie and Avery
Johnson return next season. Among the team's key contributors, only
Jaren Jackson and Malik Rose are scheduled to become free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a great chance to win another one,'' Elie
said. ``If we just stay healthy I don't see why not.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the lockout that canceled 32 regular-season games,
the absence of Michael Jordan and a Finals matchup against a
depleted, eighth-seeded Knicks team, some critics are calling for
an asterisk on San Antonio's title. New York played without center
Patrick Ewing, and key players Larry Johnson and Chris Childs were
hobbled by knee injuries. New Los Angeles Lakers coach Phil Jackson
last week called the entire postseason ``tainted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what Phil says, I'm going to cherish this ring
and wear it proud,'' Elie said. ``Lockout or not, every team we
played in the playoffs wanted to win just as much as we did.''
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio, previously known as the birthplace of barbed wire,
chili and Carol Burnett, now boasts an NBA champion that politely
asked its place into history with a simplistic coach (Gregg
Popovich), a point guard (Johnson) who once was cut on Christmas
Eve, a superstar (Duncan) who grew up with dreams of being an
Olympic swimmer, and a defense that held the Knicks to a Finals
record-low 79.8 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   In the clincher, the Spurs held New York's Allan Houston
scoreless in the fourth quarter and shut the Knicks out the final
3:12 to rally for a dramatic 78-77 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grinded it out, like we did most of the season,'' said
Robinson, whose team became the first former American Basketball
Association team to win the NBA's title. ``When all else failed,
our defense was there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, born from the death of the old Dallas Chaparrals in
1973, started the season 6-8 but won 46 of their final 53 games.
Their 15-2 playoff run _ which included a record 12-game winning
streak _ tied for the second-best in league history, validating the
career of Robinson and giving redemption to the undrafted Johnson.
Once cut by the Denver Nuggets on Christmas Eve, released by the
Spurs while still in his tuxedo from attending Robinson's wedding,
and labeled a loser who would never lead a team to a title by
Portland Trail Blazers guard Damon Stoudamire, the little guard
with the big heart swished the series-clinching jumper with 47
seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole team is a great example to a lot of kids, even a lot
of adults, of what kind of good things can happen to those who
persevere,'' Johnson said. ``After all I've been through, I can't
believe I'm here under these circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Spurs celebrated their transformation of eras from
Iceman George Gervin-to-Nice Guys by popping the tops off several
O'Doul's, the Knicks were left to only wonder how the series might
have been different had they had a healthy lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Them not having Patrick killed them, that's no secret,'' Elie
admitted. ``With him, they probably would have pushed us to a Game
7.''
</P>
<P>
   New York's Summer of San (Antonio) ended because Larry Johnson
couldn't hit a 3-pointer and they couldn't keep Texas' version of
the World Trade Center towers off the boards at crucial times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great run, and I think everyone in our locker room
really believed we could win,'' said Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy,
who, along with Latrell Sprewell and Ewing, is committed to return
to New York next season. ``San Antonio just didn't give us much
margin for error.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
