<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S SOCCER MOVES FROM SHADOWS TO SPOTLIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   California-born Brandi Chastain has been telling reporters about
the first time that Team USA returned from the Women's World Cup of
soccer.
</P>
<P>
   When the Americans got off the plane from China that day in
1991, a lone newspaper guy was there at the New York airport to
greet them.
</P>
<P>
   ``How'd ya do?'' the man asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won,'' Chastain answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good deal,'' the guy nodded, jotting something down in a
notebook.
</P>
<P>
   And that, Chastain said, was pretty much the extent of Mia Hamm
and Company's triumphant soccer return.
</P>
<P>
   No ``Sports Illustrated'' commemorative issue. No Sportswon
T-shirt tent sales. Not even a wisecrack from David Letterman.
</P>
<P>
   It is a long way, therefore, from Beijing to Foxboro, Mass.,
where a team of U.S. women will play soccer in front of an expected
crowd of 50,000 today. Last weekend's World Cup opener at Giants
Stadium in New Jersey drew 78,972.
</P>
<P>
   They can't all be there to watch Mia Hamm.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, an intriguing alignment of planets is taking place. We are
the home team. We are a land of soccer moms. And in this sport, for
the most part, we can still kick the world's butts.
</P>
<P>
   You go, girls.
</P>
<P>
   Timing is everything, of course. In this country, the
renaissance of the female athlete began with the flowering of
Florence Griffith Joyner, Jackie Joyner-Kersee and Evelyn Ashford _
Olympic track champions all.
</P>
<P>
   Title IX, in turn, secured the seed money that allowed women's
soccer programs to flourish at places like North Carolina and
softball teams at Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   The women who first burst through the locker-room door 10 years
ago are now the soccer moms. Some are even the head coaches or
married to one.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, soccer players were blessed by being
unencumbered by old-school notions. As recently as 10 years ago in
Brazil, where soccer sambas through their veins, the notion of
women playing the national game was ridiculed.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer was too rough, they said. Too physical. Without an
established professional league, it was seen in Brazil as too much
of a waste of a woman's time.
</P>
<P>
   But American women haven't had to fight that. Unlike the men,
young U.S. females aren't steered toward football and baseball at a
young age. Thus, Hamm and Michelle Akers are soccer players.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the men, they haven't had to go through life being asked,
``Hey, what's with the knee socks?''
</P>
<P>
   They're good. They should be. And unlike in basketball, where
the women's game continues to suffer from comparison to the men's,
American audiences view women's soccer with minimal preconceptions.
</P>
<P>
   When they see Team USA score seven consecutive goals against the
Nigerians _ seven _ something tells them that this isn't their
fathers' soccer.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Nike'' commercials showing Hamm throwing Michael Jordan to
the mat are priceless. You don't need to be a soccer dad to see the
intended symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   One of the dispatches from the United States' 3-0 opening
victory over Denmark sniffed that, yes, the crowd was 78,972 but
that there were ``rumors of ticket giveaways.''
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me? The U.S. team that finished 32nd of 32 teams at last
year's men's World Cup couldn't have given away even a sniff of
that many tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The men's national team has changed coaches and is in midstream
of an earnest rebuilding job, one that maybe will even be able to
beat Iran three years from now. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   But Hamm and Company are good now, and in this country that can
have an irresistible appeal. In overall World Cup play dating back
to 1991, the U.S. women are 12-1-1 going into today's match against
North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   They almost certainly will advance to the quarterfinal round,
despite the fact that they play with the fate of women's soccer in
America on their shoulders. The Brazil women may be worse _ they
carry an entire continent's female soccer future.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians wear the familiar canary jerseys and even have
the solo names of their male counterparts. Watch out for Sissi and
Pretinha and the goalkeeper whose name is Maravilha, Portuguese for
``marvelous.''
</P>
<P>
   A championship run for the U.S. women could mean the birth of a
North American professional league. Just as women have supported
the WNBA _ a reported 72 percent of their tickets are bought by
females _ the same audience might one day support soccer teams with
Hamm, Chastain, Julie Foudy and Briana Scurry.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, only one country, Australia, has bid to host the
2003 Women's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   You go, girls. Timing, remember, is everything.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
