<HEADER>
A1772 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-DRAFT-PREVIEW     06-28 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-DRAFT-PREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
 
ODOM'S TALENT, IMMATURITY HAVE bULLS WAFFLING ON NO. 1 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wally Szczberiak is climbing. Corey Maggette is
sliding. Lamar Odom is somewhere doing 360s.
</P>
<P>
   And, most important, Jerry Krause isn't talking.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the 1999 NBA draft, where mediocre talent and
immature personalities have the lottery-winning Bulls still
uncertain if their pick is priceless, or prize-less.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a consensus No. 1 guy, that's for sure,'' said
Bulls coach Tim Floyd, who will defer to general manager Krause
Wednesday night at Washington's MCI Center. ``There are still a lot
of ways we can go. There's some feeling toward taking a couple of
different players, and trading down also seems to make some
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls, trying to rebuild their franchise in the wake of
Krause's dismantling of the Michael Jordan-Scottie Pippen-Phil
Jackson dynasty last summer, believe Odom is the best physical
prospect in the draft. But, like every team except the Vancouver
Grizzlies, they haven't interviewed him or gotten the chance to
work him out privately.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Odom, a 6-foot-10 guard/forward from Rhode
Island, left school after one season, hired an agent, fired him,
tried to withdraw from the draft and re-enter school, and now has
gone into hiding in the last week when told he couldn't regain his
college eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   With unlimited range on his left-handed jumper and ball-handing
skills of a point guard, Odom has teams licking their chops. But he
also has them scratching their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd love to see him because we think he's a great talent,''
Krause said. ``But it's difficult when you haven't had a chance to
spend time with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rhode Island coach Jerry DeGregorio, ``If Lamar says he'll
meet you Thursday at 8, he'll be there. The only question is what
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Most experts figured Odom was Chicago's top choice before his
recent flip-flop flip-out. Now, the Bulls are apparently wavering
between the safe choice of Duke power forward Elton Brand and
trading the top pick to the Toronto Raptors for forward Tracy
McGrady and the fifth pick, which they would use to select Miami,
Ohio, small forward Szczberiak. The Raptors, in desperate need of a
point guard to play alongside rookie of the year Vince Carter,
covet Maryland's Steve Francis.
</P>
<P>
   In a peculiar draft in which six teams own multiple first-round
picks and nine teams _ including the Mavericks _ are without one,
there are likely to be several draft-day trades. For example, the
Utah Jazz (with picks No. 19, 24 and 28) is attempting to use its
three selections to move into the top 10, and the Atlanta Hawks
(Nos. 17, 20, 21 and 27) are looking to exchange their picks for a
proven veteran scorer like Golden State's John Starks.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls (1 and 16), Cleveland Cavaliers (8 and 11) and
Minnesota Timberwolves (6 and 14) have the most leverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are basically five options in this draft,'' said Raptors
general manager Glen Grunwald. ``After Brand, Francis, Szczberiak,
Odom and \RUCLA point guard Baron\S Davis, it's wide open.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand measured a surprisingly tall 6-foot-8 in his socks and
impressed scouts with his soft hands, and teammate Maggette has
shot horribly during private workouts. The draft's strong suit is
point guards, with Francis, Davis, Utah's Andre Miller, Duke's
William Avery and Arizona's Jason Terry. It could be, however, the
worst draft ever for centers, with 7-foot-3 Yugoslavian Alek
Radojevic the best of a group of Eric Montross clones that includes
Northwestern's Evan Eschmeyer and Washington's Todd MacCulloch.
</P>
<P>
   TCU's Lee Nailon is widely considered the fourth-best power
forward behind Brand, Mississippi high-schooler Jonathan Bender and
New Mexico's Kenny Thomas, and is projected as a late first-round
pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as big men, you have Brand,'' said Scott Layden, Jazz
vice president of basketball operations, ``and after that it gets
sketchy.''
Up for grabs ``Star-Telegram'' NBA writer Richie Whitt takes a look
at how the top 10 picks in Wednesday's NBA Draft might shake down:
No. Team Player Pos. Height School Comment 1. Chicago Bulls Elton
Brand F 6-8 Duke If they don't trade down, Brian Grant-prototype is
best of a horrible big-man crop 2. Vancouver Grizzlies Lamar Odom
G/F 6-10 Rhode Island Out of Randy Moss syndrome, can't pass on the
draft's best talent despite immaturity 3. Charlotte Hornets Steve
Francis G 6-3 Maryland Allen Iverson-type skills would fit well in
backcourt with Eddie Jones 4. LA Clippers Baron Davis G 6-3 UCLA
Rare breed in that he is a talented player who actually wants to
play for the Clippers 5. Toronto Raptors William Avery G 6-2 Duke
In desperate need of a point guard, Plan A is trading up to nab
Francis. 6. Minnesota Timberwolves Jonathan Bender F 6-11 Picayune
HS, Mississippi Their last 6-11 high-school pick _ Kevin Garnett_
turned out pretty well. 7. Washington Wizards Wally Szczerbiak F
6-8 Miami, Ohio In need of a small forward, and Wally wowed scouts
with shooting and ball-handling. 8. Cleveland Cavaliers Richard
Hamilton G 6-6 Connecticut Without a coach but desperate for
Szczerbiak, they're looking to trade up. 9. Phoenix Suns Ron Artest
F 6-6 St. John's Pick acquired from Mavericks could also be used on
Utah point guard Andre Miller. 10. Golden State Warriors Jason
Terry G 6-2 Arizona Slender scorer provides an immediate upgrade
over Bimbo Coles and Muggsy Bogues.
</P>
</TEXT>
