<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, July 4) 
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending June 19, at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. BAG OF BONES, by Stephen King. (Pocket, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A series of terrifying events besets a best-
</P>
<P>
   selling novelist four years after his wife's death.
</P>
<P>
   2. SUMMER SISTERS, by Judy Blume. (Dell, $7.50.) Two
</P>
<P>
   young women from very different backgrounds come of
</P>
<P>
   age on Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   3. TOM CLANCY'S OP-CENTER: State of Siege, created by
</P>
<P>
   Tom Clancy and Steve Pieczenik. (Berkley, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Rogue soldiers from a peacekeeping force threaten
</P>
<P>
   the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   4. REBELLION, by Nora Roberts. (Harlequin, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Romance in the 18th century between a dashing Englishman
</P>
<P>
   and a fiery Scotswoman.
</P>
<P>
   5. THE GENERAL'S DAUGHTER, by Nelson DeMille. (Warner,
</P>
<P>
   $7.50.) The investigation of the murder of an officer,
</P>
<P>
   a general's daughter, unearths scandals in the military.
</P>
<P>
   6. THE PILOT'S WIFE, by Anita Shreve. (Back Bay/Little, Brown,
</P>
<P>
   $13.95.) After learning that a plane flown by her husband
</P>
<P>
   has exploded, a woman tries to unravel the secret life
</P>
<P>
   he led.
</P>
<P>
   7. THE BLESSING, by Jude Deveraux. (Pocket, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A corporate executive and his physician brother fall
</P>
<P>
   in love with the same young widow.
</P>
<P>
   8. THE RETURN JOURNEY, by Maeve Binchy. (Dell, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Stories involving affection in its many forms -- between
</P>
<P>
   lovers, friends, relatives.
</P>
<P>
   9. SERPENT, by Clive Cussler with Paul Kemprecos.
</P>
<P>
   (Pocket, $16.) The Andrea Doria's remains yield
</P>
<P>
   treasures that point to a deadly conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   10. BREACH OF PROMISE, by Perri O'Shaughnessy.
</P>
<P>
   (Island/Dell, $7.50.) A young lawyer finds herself
</P>
<P>
   representing a woman whose business partner -- and
</P>
<P>
   former mate -- has deserted her.
</P>
<P>
   11.(x) THE FACE OF DECEPTION, by Iris Johansen. (Bantam,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) A woman who helps identify the dead from their
</P>
<P>
   skulls is enmeshed in danger.
</P>
<P>
   12. MEMOIRS OF A GEISHA, by Arthur Golden. (Vintage, $14.)
</P>
<P>
   The life of a young woman growing up in Kyoto who has
</P>
<P>
   to reinvent herself after World War II begins.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE FIRST EAGLE, by Toni Hillerman. (Harper Paperbacks,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) Navajo policemen pursue a mysterious killer: Is it
</P>
<P>
   a plague or a person?
</P>
<P>
   14. DAY OF CONFESSION, by Allan Folsom. (Warner Vision,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) A Hollywood lawyer, in Rome to claim his brother's
</P>
<P>
   body, is targeted by terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE MIDNIGHT CLUB, by James Patterson. (Warner
</P>
<P>
   Vision, $6.99.) A New York journalist finds herself
</P>
<P>
   threatened by a psychopathic killer.
