<HEADLINE>
MILLENNIUM MAKEOVERS FOR THE APPEARANCE-CHALLENGED 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(lb) 
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the Desk of Giancarlo LaMans, Director, Millennium
Makeovers Ltd.:
</P>
<P>
   Face it, friends. If you are appearance-challenged, you are
hitting speed bumps on today's exciting but fiercely competitive
job superhighway, where Youth and Beauty are zooming past in
Ferraris.
</P>
<P>
   You may have seen an article in The New York Times last week
with the headline ``The Chef as Beefcake.'' The message was as
arresting as some of the buff studs pictured, one naked except for
a well-placed blender: A great chef can no longer be just a pudgy,
marginally psychotic tyrant who cooks like an angel. No! Today's
top chef is a sex kitchen utensil who writes cookbooks with titles
like ``Boy Meets Grill.''
</P>
<P>
   Though most of us prefer the cooking staff to be clothed at all
times, that's beside the point. In careers all across America, the
homely, flabby, balding and aged are Out. The young and beautiful
are In. How about that article on the ``aerobic pop-star'' Padre
Marcelo, who's packing the churches in Brazil?
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe you were born before the Carter administration and
have the silhouette of a sack of potatoes. We here at Millennium
Makeovers are dedicated to the proposition that Sex Appeal boosts
any career! Let me describe a few examples from our great selection
of professional services, available at the more than 250 Millennium
Makeovers Career-Buffing Centers:
</P>
<P>
   BUSMAN'S HOLIDAY: Both Gotham Bus Co. and Alice Kramden would
have been a lot happier if one of Ralph's bright ideas had been to
join Millennium Makeovers' exercise program for those carrying a
wide load. Our staff lead bus drivers in aerobic ``Get on Board,
the Engine's Revved'' sessions. Exact change only. No smoking,
spitting, radio playing!
</P>
<P>
   BYTES `R' US: Intense workout for pasty computer programmers
looking for an upgrade. Graduates receive T-shirts that say ``Giga
Dude'' or ``Giga Gal.''
</P>
<P>
   PUMPED-UP PLUMBERS: Exercise workout for plumbers with an extra
twist: Once they can get their new ``fittings'' in Spandex bike
shorts, they attend self-esteem sessions. Graduates receive a
T-shirt with the slogan ``Plumbers Are Lovers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, this is all quite interesting, Giancarlo,'' I hear you
say. ``But what if I'm a lazy professional who doesn't want to go
to the gym with bus drivers and computer nerds?'' Not to worry, my
friend! Millennium Makeovers has a marketing staff that is working
overtime just for you.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-JACKET BOFFO: So your new novel reads like F. Scott
Fitzgerald but you look like Barry Fitzgerald. Tired of ending up
on the remaindered table while the crowds elbow past for books with
jacket photos of hunks who, inexplicably, have time to write?
</P>
<P>
   No sweat! We simply sell you a new face for your book jacket,
drawing from our vast archive of Unclaimed Fashion Model and
Theatrical Publicity Photos. Proven results! I'll bet you didn't
suspect that the Post-Feminist Siren-Scribe Naomi Wolf is actually
an 87-year-old former researcher for the WPA Writers Project. Or
that Sebastian Junger, hunkster-author of ``The Perfect Storm,'' is
really a 98-pound weakling who hasn't had a real photo taken since
that unfortunate barracuda accident off Barbados in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Millennium Makeovers also offers youth-enhancing apparel like:
</P>
<P>
   HABEAS CORPUS: Our ``hip'' line of sexy designer underwear for
that ambitious lawyer who wants to ``court'' new clients. Items can
be personalized with sayings like: ``Sustained!'' or ``Motion?
Here's Your Motion, Pal.''
</P>
<P>
   Wait, there's more! We've produced smash classical music CD
packages like ``Vivaldi Violin Vixens,'' ``Baywatch Beethoven'' and
``The Ring-a-Ding-Ding Cycle'' sung by Frank Sinatra and the Rat
Pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fat lady sings?'' Not if Millennium Makeovers can help it!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1829 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-COKE-APOLOGY-REVIEW     06-28 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-COKE-APOLOGY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COCA-COLA HOPES THINGS GO BETTER WITH `SORRY' 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(dw) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike love, being in business sometimes means having to say
you're sorry. Last week, the chairman and chief executive of
Coca-Cola Co. issued one of the more elaborate public apologies by
an American business leader. In newspaper ads in Belgium on Tuesday
that followed an outright ban on the company's products after
reports of people becoming sick, Douglas Ivester said ``I'm sorry''
or ``we regret'' or ``I apologize'' five times.
</P>
<P>
   The ban, which began on June 14 and spread to France, Luxembourg
and the Netherlands a day later in varying degrees, turned into the
largest recall of Coke products in history and created a
public-relations mess for the company. Ivester's apology in the
newspaper was the second issued in less than a week.
</P>
<P>
   But what are the ramifications of saying ``Sorry'' in
circumstances like Belgium's, where the government says 249 people
reported symptoms like nausea, dizziness and vomiting after
drinking Coke? One expert says it neither opens the way to lawsuits
nor prevents them _ but ought to be done nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of saying you're sorry, if it's genuine, is to say
you're sorry,'' said Steven Fink, president of Lexicon
Communications, a public relations firm that was called in by
Foodmaker Inc. after three children died from eating contaminated
hamburgers from its Jack in the Box restaurants. ``It should come
from the heart, and it should come swiftly.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies that have been slow to apologize _ Exxon, for
example, following the Alaskan oil spill in 1989 _ have found it
hard to recover from perceptions that they just don't care.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester's apology stopped short of admitting liability;
Coca-Cola also released a toxicology report that suggested
something else must have caused the symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   That made Coke's apology a more limited serving of humble pie
than other corporate leaders have had to dish out. In Japan,
executives not only apologize publicly but also personally, to each
person harmed in incidents. American Express apologized profusely
in 1989 for a smear campaign against Edmund J. Safra, a former
executive who founded a competing bank. That apology, by James D.
Robinson III, then the company chairman, was reinforced with $4
million in contributions to charities specified by Safra. (Robinson
is now a director of Coca-Cola.)
</P>
<P>
   Johnson &AMP; Johnson is considered the gold standard of crisis
management. Its chairman, James E. Burke, dealt with tampering in
its Tylenol pain-reliever capsules in 1986 by removing products
from the market permanently to prevent similar incidents in the
future _ something that has come to be seen as the ultimate
apology.
</P>
<P>
   The ban on Coke products was lifted last week for the most part,
and the company plans to spend heavily across Europe to rebuild
public confidence. On Wednesday, after Belgian authorities let the
company reopen its bottling plants and put products back on store
shelves, Ivester felt compelled to say the S-word one more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let down the people of Belgium,'' he said, ``and we're
sorry for that.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 11:47 </DATE_TIME>
