</P>
<P>
   This has been a blow to Bosnia as a whole, whose economy now
relies almost entirely on international reconstruction money _ $5.1
billion over the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, a fragile political balance created by the Dayton
accords and enforced by NATO soldiers has held. This month, when a
Bosnian Croat, Ante Jelavic, assumed Bosnia's rotating presidency,
he pledged to accelerate Bosnian integration into the West. But
roughly 800,000 Bosnians remain displaced and only a few thousand
have returned to prewar homes in areas now controlled by other
ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia, the southernmost of these lands, is the poorest; it
obtained independence in 1992 without a fight (it has deep ethnic
divisions but an insignificant Serb minority), and is often
portrayed as a contrast to its explosive neighbor, Kosovo. But
Macedonia also seems to be proving that a tolerant and enlightened
political leadership is no guarantee of economic progress.
</P>
<P>
   Last year elections produced a coalition government that united
the leaders of Macedonia's most polarized ethnic groups _ the
Macedonian Slavs (the majority) and the Albanians (about a quarter
of the population). The government inherited a stable but
dirt-poor, economy, with unemployment about 35 percent. Now the
Kosovo war has had a devastating effect. More than 250,000 Kosovar
Albanians poured in, taxing the economy and jeopardizing the ethnic
balance; lost trade and deals cost an estimated $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton arrived last week, the Kosovar Albanians he visited
were still waiting in Macedonia to go home, even as NATO used the
country as a route north for its peacekeepers. To the Macedonians
he pledged Western help to keep the country on the ``path of
prosperity, and even stronger democracy and freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Macedonians, and others in the region, will be watching to see
how soon it arrives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1834 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-THIS-WEEK-REVIEW-2T     06-28 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THIS-WEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHLIGHTS OF THE PAST WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   House Bill Makes It Harder to Seize Property
</P>
<P>
   A surprising coalition of liberals and conservatives on the
House Judiciary Committee persuaded the House to pass a bill that
would sharply limit the power of the police and prosecutors to
confiscate property in narcotics and other criminal cases. The
measure marked the first time in nearly 30 years that Congress had
taken away from law enforcement some of the vast powers it approved
at the height of the war on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The 375-48 House vote is more than enough to overcome opposition
from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEPHEN LABATON
</P>
<P>
   Loan to China Approved
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like a no-brainer for the World Bank: Give China a
loan to move 58,000 poor farmers _ volunteers only, please _ to
more fertile land in western China. But there was a hitch: The land
was partly settled by Tibetans. Congress and the administration
protested that the project would help China dilute the presence of
ethnic Tibetans in the area.
</P>
<P>
   What followed was a remarkable fight between Washington and the
bank, which ultimately decided to overrule its biggest shareholder
and go ahead with the loan _ but only after another review to make
sure the resettlement violates none of its own rules.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID E. SANGER
</P>
<P>
   Senate Kills Steel Bill
</P>
<P>
   No one has Washington wired like the steel lobby. At least,
that's what everyone thought. For a year Big Steel has been
complaining about big imports. It got the Clinton administration to
crack down on Japanese, Korean, Russian and Brazilian steel
``dumped'' in the United States at super-cheap prices.
</P>
<P>
   But it wanted more: a law setting quotas on the amount of
imported foreign steel. The House went along, but now the Senate,
in a surprise vote, said this was no time to turn to protectionism.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID E. SANGER
</P>
<P>
   AMA to Form Union
</P>
<P>
   Long before HMOs came along, Americans envied doctors for their
incomes and independence. But in this age of managed care, doctors
have started to sound like blue-collar workers, complaining about
shrinking incomes and being pushed around. As a result, the
American Medical Association has approved a startling resolution to
form a union to help the many doctors who believe banding together
is the only way to stand up to managed-care companies.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the AMA, which represents 34 percent of the
nation's doctors, insist that the union's goal will be to improve
patient care, but many health-care experts say its main goal will
be identical with that of any other union: to fatten its members'
paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVEN GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   Senate Backs U.N. Payment
</P>
<P>
   The United States took a big step toward paying nearly $1
billion in back dues to the United Nations. The Senate voted 98-1
to pay the arrears in exchange for a reduction in the overall U.S.
contribution to the United Nations from 25 percent to 20 percent of
its budget.
</P>
<P>
   There is still far to go before the dues are actually paid,
however. The bill now goes to the House, where Republicans are
threatening to add anti-abortion provisions, as they have in the
past. That could lead to a presidential veto.
</P>
<P>
   _ PHILIP SHENON
</P>
<P>
   Salinger Letters Are Sold
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Maynard, the tell-all journalist who once had a romance
with the obsessively private author J.D. Salinger, put 14 of his
letters up for sale at Sotheby's. She had already been criticized
for publishing a memoir about the author.
</P>
<P>
   Then Peter Norton, a software entrepreneur, bought the letters
for $156,500 and said he would return them to Salinger. In a
forgiving gesture, Norton said Ms. Maynard had every right to sell
the letters to support her children.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like closure. But now the author's daughter, Margaret,
says she intends to write her own memoir about her father.
</P>
<P>
   _ DINITIA SMITH
</P>
<P>
   Another Hat in the Ring
</P>
<P>
   With most of the Republican establishment treating George W.
Bush's presidential nomination as a fait accompli, and 10 other
candidates already in the field, Orrin Hatch of Utah announced that
the time had come for him to run.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted he was a long shot, ready if Bush stumbles. But then
he offered some qualifications with an edge, from experience
working with Democrats to humble origins to distance from the
establishment. Bush can make no such claims.
</P>
<P>
   _ ADAM CLYMER
</P>
<P>
   Musical Conductors
</P>
<P>
   Call it musical chairs for conductors: Seiji Ozawa, who has led
the Boston Symphony Orchestra since 1973, announced unexpectedly
that he would quit after the 2002 season to take over the podium of
the Vienna State Opera. A day later, the Berlin Philharmonic
selected Sir Simon Rattle, who recently stepped down from the City
of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra in Britain, to wield its baton
after Claudio Abbado retires in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   That fills two top jobs, but orchestras in New York,
Philadelphia, Atlanta and Indianapolis, among other cities, are
still shopping for new music directors.
</P>
<P>
   _ RALPH BLUMENTHAL
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
