<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5119 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-GERM-WARFARE-REVIEW     06-28 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-GERM-WARFARE-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOING PUBLIC PENANCE FOR MAKING GERMS INTO BULLETS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (The Week in Review) 
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   His English halting, his hand never far from a cigarette, Ken
Alibek sat in his office near Washington on a gray day about a year
ago and said he would readily give up his life if that were what it
would take.
</P>
<P>
   He told of a death threat. A serious one. But his demeanor in
recounting the incident was calm, even peaceful. In hours of
interviewing and talk, and in subsequent conversations over the
course of a year, he seemed to be a warrior with an eye not so much
on victory as on redemption, a man trying to make amends for a dark
past.
</P>
<P>
   Alibek was a military physician in the Soviet Union. Like every
doctor, he took an oath to preserve life and guard against medical
abuse. But after doing so, he devoted himself for 17 years not to
healing but to the science of germ warfare _ devising new ways of
harnessing deadly microbes to maim and kill people. Among his
killers were smallpox, anthrax, tularemia and plague.
</P>
<P>
   It was more than a theory. Mishaps of infection killed peers and
once struck him with a raging fever. In time, Alibek was promoted
to the top of the Soviet Union's sprawling effort to advance germ
warfare, which employed more than 60,000 experts even as Moscow
publicly denounced biological weapons as immoral and repugnant.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Alibek was born a Kazakh and sprang from the
region's ancient nobility _ the Asiatic hordes that gave Moscow the
jitters _ his lineage was impeccable from a socialist perspective.
His grandfather was a hero of the communist revolution in
Kazakhstan and was the republic's first people's commissar of
internal affairs, responsible for the police and security there in
the 1920s and 1930s. His father was decorated for bravery in World
War II and served as a police official in Alma-Ata, the old name of
the Kazakh capital now known as Almaty.
</P>
<P>
   But a decade ago, that whole world began changing. Soon after
the Soviet Union fell apart in late 1991, Alibek quit his
germ-warfare post and cut his ties with the Russian military,
hoping to free himself from labors he had begun to despise. Still
in Moscow, he worked for a Kazakh bank.
</P>
<P>
   But in June 1992, he recounts in his new book, ``Biohazard''
(Random House), he returned home to a newly independent Kazakhstan,
where high officials asked him to head a military program they said
they were establishing in germ warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Appalled, he declined the offer, his hands trembling in anger
and frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, he defected to the United States, ready to blow the
whistle on Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   After a year or so of secret debriefings, intelligence officials
offered him a new identity. Shorn of his past, he could become a
new person, with a new life and a new job.
</P>
<P>
   He declined. Instead, Kanatjan Kalibekov changed his name to
make it sound more American, becoming Ken Alibek. Eventually, he
decided to speak out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government officials asked me not to,'' Alibek said in his
office. ``For five years, they tried to keep me silent.''
</P>
<P>
   American experts feared for his life, suspecting that former
Soviet bosses and associates might seek revenge, he recalled. But
Alibek decided to run the risk. ``You know,'' he said, ``if a
solution of this problem would cost just my life, that's a pretty
fair cost.'' After a visitor expressed surprise at his statement,
he said it again, deadpan.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion,'' he continued, drawing near, his wide face
hinting at his Central Asian roots, ``we're very close to serious
changes. The problem is biological terrorism. If we don't start
discussing this situation openly _ if we don't start developing
serious protection in many areas, using political approaches,
medical approaches, scientific approaches _ we'll face serious
problems in the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year Alibek went public with that message, appearing in
television and newspaper interviews. His book details the germ
weapons that he says Moscow made, including warheads for long-range
missiles. He not only suggests that germs were sold abroad as the
Soviet state collapsed and Russian scientists sought new ways to
support themselves, but he also names the names of many high
officials, rogue scientists and former colleagues, potentially a
dangerous thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   He said one of his motives is remorse. ``Of course I feel
guilty,'' Alibek said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived with this situation for years, and with the knowledge
of the situation,'' he continued. But after defecting to the United
States and meditating on the work of Russia's germ warriors, he
said, ``Even for me it was scary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an enormous, huge, sophisticated program,'' he said.
``A lot of people were involved, a lot of resources. And all people
who were in charge were very important, had a lot of privileges
like personal cars, special telephone lines, special medical
treatments _ you know, a lot of such things. And of course, that's
why not a lot of people want this program to be destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   He suspects that Russia still harbors a clandestine program for
germ warfare and said he hopes his revelations will help force
Moscow to end its deceptions and redeem itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia is angry,'' he said. ``It has denied what I am saying.
But I will continue my disclosures. My final, ultimate objective is
to have Russia as a partner _ but after, just after, we know
everything that is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Nightmares used to haunt him, he said. Wrapped in a
claustrophobic anti-germ suit, he would be trapped in a production
maze, caught amid fermenters brewing swarms of deadly microbes. But
such dreams, he said, are rare now that he has left that world and
spoken out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's some kind of relief,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As a boy growing up in Kazakhstan, Alibek was fascinated by the
image of medics saving lives amid battlefield smoke. ``It struck me
that military physicians were soldiers after their own fashion,
waging a private war,'' he writes in his book.
</P>
<P>
   In medical school, he planned on being a psychiatrist, on
