   ``If you ever return to Moscow, you won't be leaving,'' Alibek
said a Russian visitor warned him, passing on a death threat.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Alibek, 48, is employed at Hadron, Inc., a company in
Annandale, Va., that does consulting work for the federal
government. As in his public advocacy, he hopes to advance germ
defenses. His research centers on a way to boost the body's immune
system to heighten overall protection against deadly germs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my dream,'' he said of creating a shield against the
kinds of bullets he once made as a warrior.
</P>
