<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MASS-ISLAND-REVIVE-ART-735&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STINKING HEAP IN BOSTON HARBOR IS ON WAY TO REVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPECTACLE ISLAND, Mass. _ An island just cannot get any more
down and out than Spectacle Island did.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the exact opposite of St. Tropez, or the anti-St.
Lucia. Imagine a hideous, stinking, toxin-leaking dump right in the
middle of Boston Harbor, which itself used to be compared to a
toilet, what with sewage and all. A 100-acre hellhole just three
miles out from Boston that no one was allowed to land on, and who
in the world would want to anyway?
</P>
<P>
   For some in this sorry life, though, there is redemption. For
people, for islands, even for whole harbors, given a great deal of
work and the right historical juncture.
</P>
<P>
   When a group of officials and advocates boated over to check on
Spectacle Island's progress on Friday _ and invited the first
reporter to land there since the island's transformation, they said
_ they surveyed a newly terraformed world still in the making, but
already easy to imagine as a park inviting enough to attract
tourists as planned, in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Spiraling dirt roads led up a grassy, man-molded hill that
offered a 360-degree view of the harbor, once considered the
dirtiest in the United States and now, after a court-ordered
cleanup costing billions of dollars, redeemed enough that many
parts are swimmable and dolphins deign to visit.
</P>
<P>
   To one side lay Boston's lopsided skyline _ the two great
skyscrapers and the financial district cluster of smaller ones _
and to the other, the scattering of other harbor islands long so
little used that many Bostonians do not even know they exist.
</P>
<P>
   The public pier was partly finished, the man-made beach was
already washed with seaweed and spotted with jellyfish, and here
and there, roses and daisies bloomed, kept alive in these dry weeks
by water barged over from the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   It gets better. Last week the U.S. Department of Transportation
announced a $1 million grant to make Spectacle Island a futuristic
land of zero-emission power. It will be powered by solar-energy
collectors, and offer visitors rides in electric cars and on an
electric boat and electric bicycles, becoming a kind of demo for a
post-fossil-fuel world, and a model for other national parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be 200 years of trash piled here,'' said Sheila
Lynch, chairwoman of the Spectacle Island Park Advisory Committee
and director of the consortium overseeing the zero-emission grant,
as she trod a new road past saplings and rose bushes. ``To see it,
in 12 years, go from a very bad landfill to a zero-emission park is
like seeing a phoenix rising from the ashes.''
</P>
<P>
   Now here is the serendipitous twist that turned Spectacle
Island's tale from woe to winning: None of this could have happened
without the $12 billion highway project known hereabouts as The Big
Dig.
</P>
<P>
   That big digging involves sinking the city's Central Artery
underground, along with adding a third tunnel to Logan Airport. All
that tunneling produced a lot of dirt, much of it contaminated.
Without a place to put all that dirt, the project could not have
gone forward. Meanwhile, the dumps on Spectacle Island needed to be
capped so they would stop leaking into the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   To make a long story short _ a story of more than a decade of
legal battles, politics, obtaining of permits, public pressure and
assorted city-state-federal struggles _ Spectacle Island ended up
getting about a third of the Big Dig dirt, more than 3 million
cubic yards of it. In return, the Big Dig builders were obligated
to provide ``mitigation'' services, from containing the old waste
to building a visitors' center, trails, beach and mussel habitat
area.
</P>
<P>
   All that piled and compacted dirt made the island grow about 60
feet upward to become the tallest point in the harbor. When it is
finished, planners say, Spectacle Island, which is co-owned by the
city and the state, will become a gateway point for the new
national park consisting of the harbor's 30 islands and peninsulas,
which include colorfully named spots like Hangman Island, Bumpkin
Island, Button Island and World's End.
</P>
<P>
   Plans are afoot to develop, gingerly, several of the islands,
and to vastly increase public access to them, turning them into
what one official described as a sort of poor man's Nantucket,
where city folk could take quick public ferries out to enjoy
seaside views, wind-surfing, nature education and the like.
Currently, only about 100,000 people a year ferry out to the
islands.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   So change awaits several of the islands, but surely none will
embody as dramatic a turnaround, as telling a history, as
Spectacle, which was so named because its original form, two mounds
connected by a sand bar, resembled a pair of spectacles.
</P>
<P>
   Long a summer gathering point for the Massachusetts Indian tribe
for which the state is named, it was used as pastureland in
colonial times; as a quarantine hospital site in the 18th century;
then as a resort spot that, by the mid-19th century, had gained
such ill repute for its gambling and dancing that the authorities
closed it down.
</P>
<P>
   A Boston businessman then installed a horse-rendering plant on
the island, and for years it absorbed thousands of Boston's equine
corpses. For much of the 20th century it was simply a dump, and
produced so much methane that in 1960, underground fires broke out
and smoldered there for years.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, the Defense Department, which had owned the
strategically located islands at the mouth of the harbor, sold
them, and most became part of a state park. But there was no money
to fix Spectacle until the Big Dig came along.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though still owned by the city and state, it is effectively
the ward of the kind of complex, interlocking, impeccably inclusive
public-private partnership typical of many 1990s projects.
</P>
<P>
   On the boat to the island were federal transportation and park
officials; state environmental and park officials; New England
Aquarium, Boston Edison and University of Massachusetts project
managers; environmentalists; members of advisory committees for
Spectacle Island and for the whole island park, and others.
</P>
<P>
   It was crowded on deck. But cheery.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Spectacle Island, said Brian MacDonald of the New
England Aquarium, ``is like the greatest story you can tell about
recovery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
