<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENTAL-GIZMOS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-TECH DENTAL GIZMOS REDUCE PAIN
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photo of a dentist at work 
 By MARTHA NOLAN MCKENZIE 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget Laurence Olivier wielding a dental drill as an instrument
of torture in '' Marathon Man.'' Say goodbye to Steve Martin's
portrayal of the leather-clad, sadistic practitioner in ''Little
Shop of Horrors.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's dentist could be cast as a cross between the gentle
Marcus Welby and the high-tech Dr. McCoy. An array of new tools,
including lasers, intraoral cameras and digital X-rays, is taking
the fear and pain out of a visit to the dentist's chair for many
patients.
</P>
<P>
   '' I think this is a wonderful time to be a dentist, and each
day it becomes more wonderful to be a patient,'' said Dr. Stewart
Rosenberg, a dentist in Laurel, Md., who frequently lectures on the
new technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Wonderful, that is, if your dentist happens to have the new
gizmos and gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   While nearly half of all dentists have an intraoral camera,
fewer than one in five are equipped with an air abrasion system _
often used instead of a laser to remove cavities _ and only about 4
percent have a dental laser or a digital X-ray.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, cost is the primary impediment for dentists. A
dental laser can set an office back anywhere from $10,000 to
$45,000, and a machine that can make crowns and other ceramic
restorations on the spot sells for about $75,000.
</P>
<P>
   While supporters claim the devices pay for themselves by
allowing dentists to get patients in and out of the dental chair
with record speed, some of the extra cost is inevitably passed on
to patients.
</P>
<P>
   And not all dentists agree that the extra expense brings
improved care.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta dentist Dr. Ronald Feinman admits some of the new
advances are more ''hype-tech'' than high-tech, particularly dental
lasers. Lasers have been used on soft tissue, such as gums, for
over a decade, but they were approved for use on hard tissue by the
Food and Drug Administration just last year.
</P>
<P>
   '' Lasers have really been hyped,'' said Feinman.'' Everyone has
made a huge deal out of their ability to cut teeth, but we already
have enough equipment to cut teeth _ equipment that is just as good
but a lot less expensive than lasers.''
</P>
<P>
   And the new devices and techniques have not been around long
enough to convince everyone that they are completely safe.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whenever there is a change in any field and different methods
are used, we come to discover there are some adverse reactions,''
said Dr. Kenneth Burrell, senior director of the council on
scientific affairs for the American Dental Association. '' And
those can only be discovered through post-marketing surveillance _
after the methods have been in use for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Cautionary tales notwithstanding, dentists are starting to
embrace the new technologies because of the improvements they offer
in two main areas _ diagnostic and cosmetic.
</P>
<P>
   Patients may be troubled to know that the traditional method of
detecting cavities _ taking X-rays and poking around with a sharp
probe _ is only about 25 to 30 percent accurate, according to
Rosenberg. That's a lot of missed cavities that can grow into
painful problems. Intraoral cameras and digital X-rays allow
dentists to catch cavities much earlier and more reliably.
</P>
<P>
   The intraoral camera, which is mounted on the tip of a slender
wand, sends pictures of the teeth and gums to a computer screen
that can be viewed by the patient as well as the dentist. The
digital images of a cracked tooth or a pocket of decay can be
magnified for closer examination and maximum impact.
</P>
<P>
   Digital X-rays expose the patient to only about 10 percent of
the radiation of traditional X-rays, and no film needs to be
developed. The image is displayed instantly on the computer screen,
and it can be blown up and colorized to highlight problem areas.
Digital X-rays are also used to evaluate the bone levels in the
gums.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg uses another weapon in his arsenal to find and destroy
cavities. It's a dye that is painted on a patient's teeth. The dye
stains the decayed areas, forcing cavities, even in the very
earliest stages, out of hiding.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the new tools can help dentists find cavities, they can
help patients deal with the aftermath. Instead of suffering under a
drill rotating at a head-jarring 400 rpm,patients may not even need
anesthesia as a dentist removes decayed tooth with air abrasion.
Like sand blasters that are used to clean buildings, air abrasion
systems shoot tiny particles onto the surface of the tooth,
removing decayed material while leaving most of the tooth structure
intact.
</P>
<P>
   '' Air abrasion prepares the tooth without any heat, vibration
or pressure,'' Rosenberg said. ''That means there are no needles or
drills for a lot of the procedures that we do.''
</P>
<P>
   And that means patients might visit their dentist more often.
''About 50 percent of the population only goes to the dentist when
they have an emergency, and the overwhelming reason is fear,''
Rosenberg said. ''One of the most exciting things about these new
procedures is that they are bringing back patients who were afraid
of going to the dentist.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanity is also bringing people back to the dentist. Everyone, it
seems, wants whiter teeth, and dentists increasingly are able to
make that wish come true. Until very recently, the best way for
someone to get a brighter smile was to have a '' tray'' made that
was molded to their teeth. Then every night for two weeks, the
patient would squeeze a dab of hydrogen peroxide bleaching gel into
the tray, press it in place against the teeth and sleep in it.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the patient can get the same results _ or better _ in one
or two hours in the dentist's chair, thanks to lasers. The dentist
paints a bleaching solution on the teeth and then activates it with
a laser or other high-intensity light source. ''With the tray
system, you can achieve a four-shade improvement,'' said Dr. Don
Wilson, a dentist in Florence, Ala. ''The laser generally achieves
a seven-shade improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   The laser also lightens the patient's wallet by several shades.
The at-home tray bleaching system typically costs around $500. The
price tag for laser bleaching, by contrast, can range between
$1,000 and $3,000. However, using an alternative light source can
bring down the cost considerably, since they cost less than lasers
and a hygienist can operate them. Only a doctor is allowed to use a
laser. Rosenberg, for example, charges $695 to bleach the entire
mouth with an alternative light source, while he used to charge
$3,000 for laser bleaching.
</P>
<P>
   As dentists continue to shift their focus from treatment to
prevention, cavities and gum disease may go the way of polio. And
patients may not be able to remember a time when they were afraid
to go to the dentist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Martha Nolan McKenzie writes for the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
