<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1857 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-SEAT-LIFEBEAT-NYT     06-28 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SEAT-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLYING ON VACATION? TAKE THE CAR SEAT
</HEADLINE>
  By REBECCA BAUMGOLD 
 c.1999 Child magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ten years go this month, Ruth Ness left her Colorado home to
visit her parents in New York. Ruth was flying with a friend,
Debbie McKelvey, and her kids, Devon, 5, and Ryan, 7.
</P>
<P>
   In Denver, they boarded United Airlines flight 232, which would
take them to Chicago. They never made it: Their DC-10 aircraft
crashed into a cornfield in Sioux City, Iowa, and 112 of the 296
passengers were killed.
</P>
<P>
   'We were flying along, when all of a sudden there was an
explosion at the back of the plane. We just started to drop,''
remembers Ness, now a 37-year-old mother.
</P>
<P>
   ''Eventually,'' she continues, ''Captain Haynes came on and
explained to us what was happening _ we were going to make an
emergency landing in Sioux City.
</P>
<P>
   ''The flight attendants told us to take off our glasses and
tighten our seat belts,'' Ness recalls. ''They said that any parent
holding an infant in her lap should wrap the baby in a blanket,
place him on the floor, and grip him between her legs,'' the
standard crash procedure for unrestrained children.
</P>
<P>
   For some of the infants, this was not enough protection. One
baby was killed on impact when he was torn from his mother's hold.
Another baby was thrown 15 rows and landed in an overhead bin.
Incredibly, a passenger heard his cries and was able to rescue him
from the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   The tremendous force of the crash caused the huge jetliner to
break into pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ''The part of the plane I was in flipped upside down and slid. I
could see fire and smoke and hear muffled voices,'' says Ness.
''When we stopped, Devon and I were hanging upside down in our
seats. I unhooked myself and Devon, and we fell to the floor _
actually the ceiling _ of the plane. I picked her up and tried to
find a way out. Luckily someone shouted out, 'This way,'and I
turned around and followed.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ness carried Devon out of the plane, she found herself in a
cornfield, surrounded by stalks 6 feet tall. When they emerged,
they saw a group of stunned survivors huddled together. Amazingly,
Devon's mom and brother were among them, also unhurt
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, devastating plane crashes like the one Ruth Ness
survived are exceedingly rare. In fact, the chance of being hurt or
killed in a car is thousands of times greater than the chance of
being hurt or killed in a plane.
</P>
<P>
   But while fatal crashes are rare, injuries from turbulence and
rough landings are more common _ and, luckily, you can do something
about them. Today, Ness and her husband, Roy, fly several times a
year with their kids.
</P>
<P>
   But as a mother and a crash survivor, Ness wants all parents to
become informed about air safety when flying with children.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the information you need to know:  &UR; Car seats: the bottom
line &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If there is one thing safety experts agree on, it's this: The
only safe way for kids 40 pounds and under to fly is in an approved
car seat. Look for a label saying the seat is certified for use in
cars and aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) and the National Safe
Kids Campaign both strongly urge parents to use car seats.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board, the agency that
investigates airline crashes, and the Association of Flight
Attendants (AFA) go further. They have lobbied Congress for years
to pass a law requiring car seats for kids under age 2 although
currently, a child under 2 can fly for free in an adult's lap.
</P>
<P>
   ''By law, everything on board an aircraft, from laptops to
luggage, must be properly secured or stowed during takeoff and
landing, except for kids under 2,'' says Patricia Friend,
international president of the AFA and a flight attendant for 30
years. As Sioux City and similar tragedies have shown, ''it is just
physically impossible for a parent to hold onto an unrestrained
child in severe turbulence or an accident,'' she adds.
</P>
<P>
   As in a car, infants under 20 pounds should use a rearfacing
seat; kids 20 to 40 pounds should use a forward-facing seat.
Children over 40 pounds can safely use the airplane seat belt.
Check that your car seat measures 16 inches or less across; any
wider and it may not fit.
</P>
<P>
   When booking a flight, you must purchase a ticket for kids under
2 to guarantee that you'll be able to use a car seat.Most airlines
offer significantly discounted fares to make this an affordable
option. If you can't afford a ticket for your child, ask the
airline which flights will be most likely to have empty seats.
Off-peak flights are typically early morning, late night and
midweek afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   And ask if the airline offers preboarding _ a real convenience
when it comes to stowing carry-ons and strapping in car seats _
since it's no longer standard practice on all flights.
 &UR; How to reduce the risks whenever you fly &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, the biggest danger you face when traveling on an
airplane is turbulence _ rough patches of air that often occur
without warning and can significantly jostle the plane. In nonfatal
accidents, turbulence is the leading cause of passenger injuries
each year.
</P>
<P>
   The solution is simple: Make sure that everyone stays buckled in
an appropriate restraint. For kids 40 pounds and under, this means
a car seat.
</P>
<P>
   ''When turbulence hits, a child held in a parent's lap can be
thrown high enough to hit the ceiling. The only sure way to prevent
this is with a car seat,'' Friend notes.
</P>
<P>
   For children who weigh more than 40 pounds, protection means
making sure they keep their seat belt on whenever seated. ''I tell
parents to look at seat belts in a plane as they do seat belts in a
car,'' says Friend . ''You wouldn't unbuckle yourself or your child
in a car going 50 1 miles an hour, so why would you do so in a
plane going 500 miles an hour?''
</P>
<P>
   Another potential for danger? Planes overstuffed with carry-on
bags.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA estimates that 4,000 passengers a year are injured by
carry-on bags. And the problem is growing, prompting safety
officials to call for a reduction in the number of carry-ons
allowed on flights.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are often hit by bags when packed overhead bins are
opened in flight, and bins have even been known to pop open,'' says
Friend.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it's important to pay attention to the safety
demonstration given by the flight attendants before takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   ''Each aircraft is a little different in terms of where the
emergency exits and flotation devices are,'' explains Friend. Ness
agrees: ''I always pay attention, and look around to memorize the
closest exits. And when my kids are old enough, I'll talk through
the safety presentation and point out the exits to them. It helps
me feel in control, like I've done my part to protect us.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Rebecca Baumgaold is the associate editor of Child magazine.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
