<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 12:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1862 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERIAL-KILLER-SURVIVO     06-28 1492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-SURVIVOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTACK SURVIVOR NOW HAS NAME TO GO WITH FACE SHE CAN'T FORGET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA TEACHEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Ky. _ The attacker may not remember her face.
</P>
<P>
   She cannot forget his.
</P>
<P>
   And now the 22-year-old woman believes she has a name to go with
it: Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, the cross-country drifter suspected of
riding the rails en route to at least eight homicides in three
states. She marvels that she did not die as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's bothered more now that he has been identified,'' said a
person close to the woman, who is the only survivor of the rampage
that put Resendez-Ramirez on the FBI's Ten Most Wanted list. ``She
doesn't like to be alone. If her parents are gone she stays with
her married sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``But she's doing great,'' the source added. ``She's a very
strong young lady. She is one of those people who will probably
volunteer at crisis centers for the rest of her life because of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 29, 1997, the woman, whose name is being withheld to
protect her privacy, survived a vicious attack in which her
boyfriend was killed. The couple were at a popular hangout for
students a mile or so from the University of Kentucky campus.
Unfortunately for them, its attraction lies in the dual set of
Norfolk Southern Railway tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Sorrell, a Lexington police detective, recalled last week
that the woman and 21-year-old Christopher Maier were still getting
to know each other. They had gone to a friend's house on Suburban
Court, a maple tree-lined street of nicely kept, World War II-era
homes that dead-ends at the tracks. About 1:30 a.m. they and two
other friends decided to walk down there.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a steel tower that goes over the tracks,'' Sorrell
said. ``They would go down there and hang around at the bottom of
the tower. I think some kids have gotten up on the tower to watch
the trains go underneath.''
</P>
<P>
   When no trains rolled by after about 20 minutes, the two
friends, both male, returned to the house. Maier and the woman
remained.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ... had only been dating a few months,'' Sorrell said.
``So they stayed there talking.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple talked for half an hour before deciding to leave. As
they headed back, a man burst from the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   He grabbed Maier, forced him to the ground and dragged him to a
dense tangle of brush on the eastern side of the tracks, ordering
the woman to follow. He restrained them with a cord and demanded
money.
</P>
<P>
   Maier and the woman tried to comply, said Sorrell. They offered
the keys to Maier's car. They said they could get money for him.
They would give him their ATM cards. They would give him the access
numbers. They would do whatever he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christopher just kept saying `Don't do anything to her. Don't
hurt the girl,''' Sorrell said.
</P>
<P>
   But the attacker became more agitated with each plea. At one
point he gagged both of them.
</P>
<P>
   The woman was able to free herself and even attempted to unbind
Maier, but the man stopped her with brutal force and bound her
again.
</P>
<P>
   After determining neither had money, the man picked up an object
(another investigative source says it was a rock) and bludgeoned
Maier in the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``He then turned on the female victim,'' Sorrell said. ``She
physically attempted to fight him off by kicking and thrashing at
him. But he became more violent. She had no choice but to comply.''
</P>
<P>
   During her struggle, the woman could hear gurgling noises coming
from Maier and asked the attacker to position him so he would not
drown in his own blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suspect got off her for a moment, then came back and said,
`Don't worry, he's gone,''' Sorrell said.
</P>
<P>
   What took place next should have killed the woman.
</P>
<P>
   She was raped and beaten, possibly with a board or a rock. She
suffered a broken jaw, a crushed eye socket and numerous gashes and
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   She fought as much as she could until the man told her how easy
it would be to kill her, Sorrell said. ``It was at that point she
quit resisting.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward the man walked away, leaving the unconscious woman for
dead.
</P>
<P>
   The exact length of the attack is not clear. According to police
documents the first report came in about 4:15 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before then, the woman had become alert enough to
stagger to a nearby house.
</P>
<P>
   ``The door was opened to that residence,'' Sorrell said. ``She
just walked in and the person living there helped get the gag off
of her and called the police.''
</P>
<P>
   Chad Goetz was a fellow UK student.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a bad dream,'' Goetz told a local television news
reporter. ``I woke up and there was a bloody person at my door.''
</P>
<P>
   Goetz said he didn't know who the woman was until sometime later
when he received an e-mail thanking him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I did was open my door, sit her on the couch,
call 911 and talk to her,'' Goetz said. ``I hope someone would have
the same common courtesy for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Maier's body was found later near the tracks north of the steel
tower.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, Christopher Maier did exactly what has been
taught by police agencies for years as to how to react,'' Sorrell
said. ``He looked out for the welfare of his female companion. He
complied with the suspect's demands, offered money, his car. He did
everything that you're supposed to do. But he just ran into a
killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sacrificed his life trying to protect the female victim.
...''
</P>
<P>
   There was no solid suspect in the case until about three weeks
ago, when DNA samples collected in Lexington were matched to those
at two crime scenes in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 17, Dr. Claudia Benton, 39, was found stabbed to death
in her home in West University Place, an enclave of Houston. On
April 30, the Rev. Norman ``Skip'' Sirnic, 46, and his wife, Karen,
47, were beaten to death with a sledgehammer in Weimar.
Fingerprints and other evidence have linked Resendez-Ramirez to
those and three other Texas homicides.
</P>
<P>
   He is suspected in the June 4 slaying of 73-year-old Josephine
Konvicka at her home in Fayette County near Weimar; the June 5
death of Noemi Dominguez, 26, near Houston's Texas Medical Center;
and the June 15 deaths of 79-year-old George Morber and his
daughter Carolyn Frederick, 51, in Gorham, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her fear has always been that somebody else may be subject to
what she was,'' Sorrell said of the Kentucky survivor. ``And to
learn his identity by linking it to the deaths of three other
people in Texas, and now that number has risen, has really been an
emotional trauma for her.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman has declined to talk publicly until Resendez-Ramirez
is captured, but the person close to the family said she is coping
well and plans to resume her college education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's pondered why she's the only one who's lived, why
she was blessed,'' said Sorrell.
</P>
<P>
   With the increasing frequency of attacks, authorities added
Resendez-Ramirez to the FBI's Ten Most Wanted list. They have
organized a nationwide manhunt.
</P>
<P>
   He was charged last week with murder, assault, robbery and rape
in the Kentucky case and faces murder charges in the two Illinois
deaths. A federal warrant also has been issued for his arrest for
unlawful flight to avoid prosecution. The charge stems from the
burglary charge in Harris County, stemming from the Benton killing,
and allows the continued involvement of federal agents in the case.
</P>
<P>
   All of the victims have lived or have been near train tracks,
allowing Resendez-Ramirez to escape quickly and travel across the
country by illegally stowing away on trains.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a high-profile crime for us since it occurred,''
Sorrell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have about 20 to 25 homicides a year here. We don't have
many serial killers come through.''
</P>
<P>
   The crime, and recent sightings of the suspect about 70 miles
away in Louisville, have made people more cautious in this
university town in the heart of Kentucky's horse country.
</P>
<P>
   ``People had sort of gotten past it, and back into their normal
routine,'' said Phillip Thompson, manager of a small auto repair
shop next to the tracks, about a block from the crime scene. ``Now
they're a little more aware again, especially with what's in the
news right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Johnson, 43, has lived on Suburban Court for 26 years.
She said she, her husband and their young daughter, niece and
nephew take a few more precautions than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody just wants that dummy to be caught,'' she said.
``I've got a big dog in the back of my house and a gun in the
front. If he ever tries to come in my house, he's gonna be laid
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said she and her neighbors still see vagrants along the
tracks only ``every blue moon.'' The UK kids still hang out there,
if not as frequently as before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we just take it one day at a time,'' she said. ``I've
told the kids to keep the door locked and to be a little more
cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
