<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-NUDIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST BOOK OUT OF THE BOX
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) 
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There's this box. About as big as _ and the same
shape as _ a refrigerator turned on its side. It's painted white.
There's a folding door at one end of it. When the door folds back,
a cloud of warm humid air emerges, followed by Po Bronson.
</P>
<P>
   He's thin. Male-model good-looking. At 35, Bronson is one of the
hottest writers of the moment. His current book, ``The Nudist on
the Night Shift,'' was just excerpted in this month's Wired
magazine, which featured Bronson's face on the cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nudist'' follows the trials and tribulations of the young men
and women coming to San Francisco and Silicon Valley, looking to
carve out their share of the overheated digital economy.
</P>
<P>
   Bronson's bio, found at www.pobronson.com, includes a stint as a
24-year-old mid-six-figure bond salesman. Which led to a book,
``Bombardiers,'' about hyperactive bond traders. Which led to
another book, ``The First $20 Million Is Always the Hardest'' about
hyperactive technology start-ups. Which led to a movie deal. Which
also led to a kudo from Tom Wolfe, who has proclaimed Bronson as _
wait for it _ the next Tom Wolfe.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's that box. Bronson writes in the box, shut off
from the world by headphones, the CD player set on repeat. The box
sits deep inside The Grotto, a Folsom Street writers' cooperative.
It's where we met him.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What prompted ``Nudist''?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think it's very cool that a lot of young people are excited
these days about Silicon Valley. It's cool that they're drawn here
from all over the country. Youth are custom-made for the change.
Every three months they get a whole new set of classes in school.
Every summer they get a new job. Then they graduate and it's ``slow
down'' and ``oh God, I'm going to have this job for the rest of my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   They're moving out here like crazy. You always read these
retrospective stories. How did they make their money? Did they
deserve it? I wanted to do a longitudinal study.
</P>
<P>
   Follow them from the day that they got here. I met about 20 and
I followed them for the last three years. In the end they were all
doing pretty well. And it was not that long ago that they were all
still eating pancakes. I wanted to see if it was all a myth, or is
it really a popular phenomenon. To see what would really happen to
you if you moved out here.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you a techie?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm not interested in technology. I write people stories. I
don't find the technology itself as interesting as how technology
triggers a culture, how it changes people's lives.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You were on Wall Street during the junk bond days. Are we
repeating this here on the West Coast?
</P>
<P>
   A: I was an investment banker in '87-'88. We were going up
against Michael Milken. We were trading against the crash. Back
then, there was still sort of the remnants of the old-school
around. These guys from New Jersey who had worked their way up from
the mailroom. There was that kind of hubris created by that, with
all the new people coming into this world. That helped lead to the
crash. Now, that crash was short lived. But that culture never came
back.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So no Gordon Geckos?
</P>
<P>
   A: I am worried about too many people coming in just for the
score. I'm worried that writers will jump ship and go work for
these companies, because they're jealous or they're tired of making
writers pay. I hope my book reflects this. That it's a fight for
the soul of this business. I wanted to explore the question: Is it
flaunted wealth at Woodside, or is it people who are here for the
adventure and the spirit, and the money is a by-product.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You live and write in San Francisco, and have spent a lot of
time in Silicon Valley. Do you see any differences between the city
and the Valley?
</P>
<P>
   A: Radically different. People here (in the city) are media
savvy, but much more aware of what they're giving up. It's
different in the Valley. There's a much higher level of cynicism in
San Francisco. But there are tons of greedy, greedy people in the
Valley. There's sort of this sheer jealously driving people.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's reaching critical mass.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Sheer jealously?
</P>
<P>
   A: For a lot of people out here, it was just dumb luck that they
were at the right company to make a couple of millions bucks. But
for others, to watch your generation sort of move up _ that's
tough. I spoke to people this weekend who were headed for Harvard
Business School, who now won't go. They want to get in on the big
score. But my book doesn't turn up its nose at that culture. It has
a lot of fun with it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will people stop talking to you after this book comes out.
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm sure there's going to be the ``I don't like how you
portrayed me.'' But that's part of the business. I'm not too
worried about that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are Internet stocks due for a crash?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think about that every day. Obviously, these Internet
valuations lack real value, but the issue is, can the momentum
continue. I don't see any slowing down in the venture capital
investments in these types of companies.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's with writing in the box?
</P>
<P>
   A: It just walls me off from everybody. I go in there, and it's
just me and the writing. I like that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
