<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-VIDEOS-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERLOOKED `STILL CRAZY' AND `RUSHMORE' SHARE DEFIANT SPIRIT &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   One value of video is it gives films a second chance. Two movies
reaching video Tuesday deserve it.
</P>
<P>
   Houston-made ``Rushmore'' (R, Touchstone, CC, priced for rental)
and British ``Still Crazy'' (R, Columbia TriStar, CC, priced for
rental) are birds of a feather. Both boast quirky humor,
sensational performances and British rock in their soundtracks _
not to mention a defiant rock spirit in tone.
</P>
<P>
   Both also earned critical praise and Golden Globe nominations
(``Still Crazy'' was nominated for best musical or comedy), then
faltered in theaters via art-house runs that failed to tap their
commercial potential.
</P>
<P>
   With its plot about '70s British rockers reuniting in the '90s,
``Still Crazy'' was pegged by some critics as a cross between ``The
Full Monty'' and ``This Is Spinal Tap.''
</P>
<P>
   Ignore them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still Crazy'' is a potent, feel-good entity in itself. It
isn't about male strippers, nor is it a mock documentary about
witless head-bangers. It's one of the best rock movies since ``A
Hard Day's Night.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Still Crazy'' depicts the fictional Strange Fruit, a big-time,
hard-rocking group that played to packed stadiums during its '70s
heyday. Then excesses of drugs, sex and egos _ as well as a literal
lightning bolt _ sent the members scampering to lives of plodding
obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Fate hurls them together again 20 years later for a
nothing-to-lose attempt to surf the nostalgia wave and rekindle the
sparks that once gave them magic.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Rea plays keyboardist Tony, who still longs for former
groupie Karen (Juliet Aubrey), who now manages the band like a
patient den mother. Bolstered by a loyal Scottish roadie (Billy
Connolly of ``Mrs. Brown''), the group takes a bus tour of European
clubs to reassert its chops.
</P>
<P>
   Karen pines for guitarist Brian, who's disappeared and presumed
dead from drugs, in the mold of his late brother, Keith, the first
lead singer.
</P>
<P>
   To replace Brian, the group recruits a hotshot guitarist (Hans
Matheson) who adds youthful credibility alongside the wizened Ray
(Bill Nighy), Keith's '70s replacement. Only Ray has stretched out
his earnings and now lives on a country estate _ though it's fading
and for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Moody bassist Les (Jimmy Nail) resents Ray, belittling him for
being a poser and not a genius. Affable drummer Beano (Timothy
Spall) remains recklessly crazy after all these years.
</P>
<P>
   The tour starts in disaster, but it doesn't end there.
</P>
<P>
   Given a chance, this band can be good _ even great _ as shown in
the stirring power ballad ``The Flame Still Burns'' and the grandly
exuberant ``All Over the World,'' a galvanizing performance that's
3 1/2 minutes of rock 'n' roll glory.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the music is this good, but the songs aren't a
put-on, either. Spinal Tap? Give us a break.
</P>
<P>
   The tunes were written by such real-life rockers as Electric
Light Orchestra's Jeff Lynne, Foreigner's Mick Jones, Squeeze's
Chris Difford and Argent's Russ Ballard. The actors ably do their
own singing; Nail hails from a recording background.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still Crazy'' also has a solid film pedigree. It was written
by Dick Clement and Ian La Frenais, who penned the screenplay for
the ribald Irish soul-music movie ``The Commitments.'' Directing
was Brian Gibson, who did the powerful Tina Turner biopic, ``What's
Love Got to Do With It?''
</P>
<P>
   Their joint work is informed about the music business without
being an in-joke. If anything, ``Still Crazy'' is a universal,
human tale about turning midlife crises into second chances _ about
the flame still burning at any age.
</P>
<P>
   It's also rousingly funny, thanks to Spall's uncouth bluster and
the fragile brilliance of Nighy, a British stage actor who's a real
revelation.
</P>
<P>
   His Ray is a lovably hapless, helpless soul _ a brain-fried,
recovering alcoholic who'd be lost without his support group, from
his bossy Swedish wife (Helena Bergstrom) to his AA meetings to
Karen's calm control of the tour. But Ray poignantly soldiers on,
and onstage he can be superb.
</P>
<P>
   You pull for him _ and the rest of this band _ because you care
for these characters. We laugh with them, not at them, thanks to
filmmakers who respect the liberating spirit of their mission.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, their songs can sound retro and overwrought. But take a
closer listen and they could grow on you.
</P>
<P>
   Strange Fruit may not represent your favorite band, but it does
represent rock itself, and that means a lot. Heck, it means
everything.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Rushmore,'' this artful labor of love from Houston-born
director Wes Anderson was inspired by his years at St. John's
School, where most of the movie was shot.
</P>
<P>
   Max (Jason Schwartzman) is an eager student who throws himself
into wildly diverse clubs and stages bizarre plays. Unfortunately,
he's too busy to pass his classes.
</P>
<P>
   Max finds a new outlet for his fierce focus when he falls for
Mrs. Cross (Olivia Williams), a sweet young teacher who's been
recently widowed. But she's also courted by Mr. Blume (Bill
Murray), a wealthy, depressed alumnus who's befriended Max.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love her,'' Mr. Blume informs the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved her first,'' Max responds with irrefutable kid-speak
logic.
</P>
<P>
   Written by Anderson and Owen Wilson, ``Rushmore'' has many
inspirations but can be wildly original, from its strange plot to
the intriguing contradictions in its hero _ or antihero, as in
Dustin Hoffman's equally obsessive romantic in ``The Graduate.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwartzman was worth the lengthy casting search. Somehow he's
both arrogant and naive, slick and klutzy, lovable and
exasperating.
</P>
<P>
   But Murray was an actor first, and his strong body of work
entitled him to an Oscar nomination for this funny-sad performance,
recognition he was denied.
</P>
<P>
   Williams also is memorable as the grieving but hopeful Mrs.
Cross, and the young supporting cast _ including many Houstonians _
is impressive. The strong song score also is a star in itself.
</P>
<P>
   You may not embrace ``Rushmore'' upon first viewing. It's
decidedly different _ an adjustment. But give it a chance.
Originality deserves that much.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
