<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH LISTENED _ AND LEARNED _ FROM BULLOCK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, in eulogizing Bob Bullock,
praised the late Texas leader for reaching out to a ``green
governor across parties and generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullock, indeed, reached out. But Bush, as a rookie in statewide
politics in 1994, was savvy enough to reach out to Bullock first,
and Bush's initiative was key to what became a strong working
relationship and close friendship between the veteran, wily
Democrat and the younger, up-and-coming Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Without Bush's overtures and Bullock's response back
then, the governor's face may not have recently graced the covers
of a couple of national news magazines.
</P>
<P>
   In all fairness, it would be too much of a stretch to say that
Bullock's help during the governor's first term led to Bush's
commanding presence in the presidential race now. Several other
factors _ including a well-known name, an inherited money-raising
network and a dearth of strong GOP opposition _ also are at play.
</P>
<P>
   But Bullock, as lieutenant governor and the Senate's presiding
officer, was instrumental in giving Bush the early legislative
victories and the success story that Bush is now touting throughout
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Another Democrat, House Speaker Pete Laney, was equally helpful
in securing easy approval of the civil justice, education, welfare
and juvenile justice changes that Bush made the cornerstone of his
first legislative session and parlayed into overwhelming public
popularity for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock, often controversial during four decades of public
service and never shy about messing with governors from his own
Democratic Party, was a potential stumbling block for a new
governor, particularly a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   While state comptroller, Bullock had held a news conference in
early 1983, just as fellow Democrat Mark White was moving into the
governor's office, to announce that he was going to run for
governor in the next election. Bullock never did run for the higher
office, but his announcement was no less an affront to White.
</P>
<P>
   And shortly after taking office as lieutenant governor in 1991,
Bullock put Gov. Ann Richards, another Democrat, on the spot by
openly advocating a state income tax _ one of Texas' biggest
political taboos _ as a solution to a revenue shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious differences between Bullock and Bush were great.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Bullock had fought his way to prominence from a modest
childhood in Hillsboro. Republican Bush was a son of privilege, a
preppie who had attended Yale.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock was almost a generation older than the new governor, and
his knowledge of state government was vastly greater _ an
encyclopedia vs. a few footnotes.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush had unseated Richards, Bullock's longtime Democratic
comrade in Texas' political wars.
</P>
<P>
   If ever Bullock was going to give another governor a hard time,
Bush was ripe for it. Or so it would have seemed.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush made a point of taking the first step. He didn't wait
for Bullock to come calling. Before Bush ever took office, he went
to Bullock and got acquainted with him, and if there had been any
potential conflict, it was soon defused.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his critical first legislative session in 1995, Bush
kept communicating privately with Bullock and Laney on his
legislative priorities. And Bush listened _ and learned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't the imperial governor,'' longtime Bullock aide Tony
Proffitt recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Both Democratic leaders found Bush a refreshing change from the
Richards administration, when communications between the
legislative and executive branches of government hadn't flowed as
smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   The good-ol'-boy network may have been a factor in Bush's
ability to relate to Bullock and Laney. And it certainly didn't
hurt that, during that first session, a majority of the
Legislature, Democrats and Republicans alike, shared the governor's
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, with the two major parties nearing parity in the
Legislature, the three leaders recognized that bipartisanship was
essential to legislative success.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock angered many Democrats by endorsing Bush for re-election
last year over Democrat Garry Mauro, a former Bullock aide. Bullock
also said early on that he thought Bush would make a good
president.
</P>
<P>
   As far as I know, Bullock never aspired to be president, and
it's just as well. Despite his abilities and accomplishments, he
was too rough around the edges and carried too many battle scars to
ever have had a shot at the office.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, according to the polls, does have a good chance at the
White House. But he will need a Bullocklike toughness to get there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
