<HEADLINE>
HIDDEN CHARGES DESTROY TRAVEL BUDGETS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The travel agent confirmed a rate of $48 per day for a
four-day car rental in Hartford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   So why am I staring at a bill for $287.72?
</P>
<P>
   The hotel reservations clerk quoted a $100-per-night tariff for
three nights at an upstate New York hotel.
</P>
<P>
   And yet I'm signing a credit-card receipt for $356.16.
</P>
<P>
   I hear kids in the neighborhood talking about ``new math,'' but
this is ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Most other frequent travelers can empathize. Taxes, fees,
surcharges, concessions, gratuities _ no matter what you label
them, these ``hidden costs'' are playing the devil with our
vacation and business travel budgets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FEES ADD UP &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Consider these addendums to my car-rental bill:
</P>
<P>
   A ``concession fee recovery charge'' of 10 percent. A ``tax
rate'' of 9.18 percent that includes a 3 percent Connecticut
``car-rental surcharge.'' A separate Connecticut ``surcharge'' of
$1 per day.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, I made the mistake of requesting an ``upgraded vehicle.''
No, I didn't ask for a Lincoln Town Car or Corvette; I merely
wanted a Toyota Camry, which I drive at home and knew would prove
more familiar, thus safer, during a 500-mile odyssey on uncharted
roads.
</P>
<P>
   Extra charge: $11 per day; $44 total. For a Camry?
</P>
<P>
   At least I was wise enough to return the car filled with gas.
The ``fuel and service'' charge at the car return center: $3.57 per
gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I'm not trying to pick on Hartford. I've had similar
experiences in other cities. And anyone who followed the debate
over funding for Houston's new downtown baseball stadium knows that
car-rental surcharges have increased dramatically here, too.
</P>
<P>
   Also, according to the Runzheimer Guide to Daily Travel Prices,
Houston's 17 percent lodging tax is the nation's highest. But only
marginally: You'll pay 16 percent in Seattle and 15 percent in
Chicago, Cleveland, Milwaukee, San Antonio, Austin, Fort Worth and
Amarillo. Yes, Amarillo.
</P>
<P>
   What a great partnership U.S. cities have devised. We'll tax
yours; you tax ours. As long as folks don't venture beyond their
living room couches, they'll never be the wiser. Everyone can build
as many stadiums and arenas and conventions centers as they fancy.
</P>
<P>
   Only the traveler is penalized.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MORE SURPRISES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, only a portion of these extra charges has any connection
to sports facilities. My inflated hotel bill, for instance, was the
result of an 8.72 percent taxation and a $10 per day ``gratuity.''
I have no idea who benefited from this money since an additional 17
percent was added to in-house restaurant and bar bills, and
instructions were clear that bellmen and doormen were to be tipped
individually. These types of gratuities are becoming more
commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what burns me most, though: I could accept surcharges and
fees and mandatory gratuities if only car-rental firms, hotels and
other travel service providers were conscientious about revealing
their existence in advance of a trip.
</P>
<P>
   I abhor surprises that dent consumers' pocketbooks. And the
impact on many unsuspecting travelers is becoming severe enough to
affect whether taking a trip is even feasible. I appreciate that
car-rental firms and hotels don't benefit from most of these taxes
and fees; on the contrary, the added charges can hurt their
business. But that doesn't absolve them from a responsibility to
tell us the whole story about what we'll pay.
</P>
<P>
   According to Laurie Berger, editor of the monthly Consumer
Reports Travel Letter, ``The National Association of Attorneys
General estimates that surcharges, taxes and fees can increase your
car rental by as much as 75 percent and wipe out any savings earned
from hours spent searching for rock-bottom air fares.'' (Dare I
admit that I chose Hartford over more convenient gateways for my
trip because of a $237 round-trip air fare?)
</P>
<P>
   Berger continues: ``Consumers get surprised by these charges
because rental agents don't always volunteer information about
add-ons over the phone. Most vacationers first confront such
budget-busting fees at the rental counter, where they're least
prepared to make an informed decision.'' (And where they are
already befuddled by pressure to pay for optional insurance; that's
a subject for another day, but suffice it to say that recent
changes deem it more important than ever for business and leisure
travelers to know in advance if rentals are covered by their
corporate or personal automobile policies.)
</P>
<P>
   Failure to disclose all charges is inexcusable; in some
instances it borders on fraud. (And I have a better word for a
$3.57 per gallon refueling charge: gouging.) Remember the criticism
cruise lines took (justifiably) a couple of years back for not
informing passengers clearly about port charges? At least that
information appeared in brochures, albeit often in the tiniest of
print.
</P>
<P>
   The NAAG, according to Berger, has proposed establishing a
car-rental task force to examine advertising prices and how well
fees are disclosed during the reservation process. The public would
be well-served if the organization expanded that project.
</P>
<P>
   Some credit is due companies whose advertisements hint at add-on
costs. Near the bottom of a Hertz promotion in the June 20 Houston
Chronicle Travel section was this disclaimer:
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending on the rental location, the following charges may
apply: A Vehicle Licensing Fee ranging from 20 cents to 60 cents
per day or from 2 percent to 11.5 percent per rental; an Airport
Facility Use Fee of up to $3 per day or $5 per rental; and an
Airport/Hotel Concession Fee Recovery of up to 12 percent per
rental. Government surcharges, taxes, tax reimbursement and
optional items ... are extra.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a commendable start. But are the words ``ranging from 20
cents ... to 11.5 percent'' vague enough? Telephone reservations
agents, online services and travel agents should be required to
provide travelers a list of all specific costs before a booking is
confirmed. And the same criteria should apply to hotels, tour firms
and others in the travel industry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1900 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-WARRIORS-HNS &LR;      06-28 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WARRIORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREP STAR WORKOURT IMPRESSES WARRIORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JORGE L. ORTIZ  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Garry St. Jean likes to tell the story of the
Eastern Conference general manager who insisted that his colleagues
deal with him only over the phone ``so he wouldn't have to lie to
your face.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the time of year when few GMs want to meet their peers
in person. As Wednesday's NBA draft approaches, the phone lines are
crackling with phony evaluations, false reports and misinformation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't give your hand away,'' said St. Jean, the Warriors'
GM. ``It's OK for people to think that you're moving up or moving
down.''
</P>
<P>
   So, are the Warriors doing either? You'd have better luck
getting St. Jean to give you his ATM card and PIN code than to
answer truthfully.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't kept rumors from circulating, and there are plenty
involving the Warriors. The juiciest one has the club looking to
open up salary cap room to make a run at Mitch Richmond, the
Wizards' free agent shooting guard who has made it clear he would
love to return to the San Francisco area.
</P>
<P>
   Even after making a qualifying offer to their own free agent
center Erick Dampier, the Warriors can open up about $2 million in
cap space. That wouldn't be enough to tempt Richmond, who at 34
(Wednesday) is looking to make up for years of being underpaid.
</P>
<P>
   But what if the Warriors dumped another big contract, say, John
Starks', which has one year left at $4 million? According to a
source in Atlanta, the Hawks are interested in Starks as a backup
and insurance for Steve Smith, whose injuries in the past have
crippled the team.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is over the cap, but holds a $4.5 million salary
exception from the Christian Laettner trade to Detroit as well as
four draft picks _ Nos. 17, 20, 21 and 27 _ that it could use as
inducement.
</P>
<P>
   St. Jean acknowledged that both the Hawks and Jazz are looking
to move some picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because there isn't a (Tim) Duncan or a Shaq (O'Neal) in this
draft, and with some teams holding several picks, it opens the door
to more conjecture as to what might happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors generated some conjecture of their own last week
when they worked out UCLA point guard Baron Davis, who is expected
to be a top-four pick. That prompted speculation that Golden State
would look to move up in the draft from its No. 10 spot. Charlotte
has emerged as a possible trading partner.
</P>
<P>
   Stuck with two expensive power forwards in Derrick Coleman and
Anthony Mason, the Hornets want to unload one, preferably Coleman
and the last four years of his $40 million contract. They're
dangling the No. 3 pick and may be willing to part with it in
exchange for the Warriors' selection and Donyell Marshall, whom
Golden State desperately wants to move.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets could still get a young point guard to groom _
perhaps Duke's William Avery _ and get rid of an attitude problem
in either Coleman or Mason (two years, $11 million total). The
Warriors aren't likely to bite, even with the temptation of getting
out from under Marshall's contract, which has three guaranteed
years at $18 million remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall's name has also be mentioned in a possible trade for
New Jersey's Kendall Gill, a swingman whose contract ($5 million)
expires after next season. The salary numbers would work under the
cap without a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about trade talks with other teams, St. Jean replied
cryptically: ``I'd say they have been fruitful, but they're not
especially ripe yet.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a growing feeling that beyond Steve Francis _ possibly
the draft's top selection _ and Davis, the Warriors were not that
enthused about the other three point guards deemed worthy of
lottery selections _ Andre Miller, Jason Terry and Avery.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the team is concerned about their ability to come
in and make a difference right away, especially at a position of
such responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's quantity, but there's lots of youth,'' assistant GM
Gary Fitzsimmons said of the point guards in the draft. ``Even with
the senior point guards, other than Andre Miller, you have guys who
have played lots at the scoring position and are relatively young
as far as being a point guard is concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Warriors would like to pry free agent Terrell Brandon _
whom Fitzsimmons knows well from their days in Cleveland _ in a
sign-and-trade with Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The Timberwolves reportedly also have talked to Portland about a
swap of Brandon for disenchanted Damon Stoudamire.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're dreaming if you think you're going to wind up with
Brandon,'' said a league source, ``unless you can give up something
extraordinary, and the Warriors don't have anybody extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they would if they could land Jonathan Bender, the
6-foot-10 high schooler from Mississippi whose draft stock seems to
be rising. The Warriors were impressed with his athleticism and
shooting ability when they had him in for a workout and project him
to be taken between the fifth and 16th picks.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzsimmons has long preached the value of drafting the best
player available, regardless of the team's needs, so this could be
a test of that theory. Ideally, the Warriors would like to move
into a better drafting spot and put themselves in position to
choose the best player available and also fit a need at point
guard.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would tell a fan who queried him about whether the
team will stay at No. 10, St. Jean went into GM mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say, `I can't hear you,''' he replied. ```I've got wax in
ears.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
