<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1901 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SMITH-PROFILE-2T     06-28 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SMITH-PROFILE-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILD, WILD WILL: RIDING SHOTGUN WITH THE FASTEST MOUTH IN THE
`WEST' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trims) 
 
By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ Will Smith is striding around the room,
demonstrating what he liked about playing Jim West in ``Wild Wild
West.''
</P>
<P>
   The tight pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole Western thing and the clothes and the tight pants,''
he says. ``Those pants were so tight because Robert Conrad (who
played Jim West on television) always had them tight. That's how he
could walk so straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith goes on strutting around the hotel room, laughing and
exuberantly showing the effect of tight pants. He's having a great
time.
</P>
<P>
   Talking with Smith, star of two of the Top 10 movie moneymakers
of all time (``Independence Day'' and ``Men in Black''), is like
chatting with a happy electric generator. The minute he walks into
the room, the energy needle starts banging against overload.
</P>
<P>
   His conversational volume is at least three times higher than
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a cup of coffee this morning,'' he explains. ``I rarely
take any aspirin or anything like that. If I would be a little
saggy on the set, (director) Barry (Sonnenfeld) would give me a
cappuccino. The slightest sip of caffeine or sugar takes me way
over the top. We were calling it crack-accino.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith exudes life force from every pore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not just turning that (personality) on for you; that is
who he is,'' says Sonnenfeld, who also directed Smith in ``Men in
Black.'' ``Occasionally when I'm depressed, I'll call Will or see
him. He's almost like my religious adviser. He'll walk me through
my life and remind me why I should be so happy.''
</P>
<P>
   All of Smith's ``Wild Wild West'' cohorts _ Kevin Kline, Salma
Hayek, Kenneth Branagh _ tell the same story: Smith is always
happy, always energetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's fantastic,'' Hayek says. ``He's always, always in a good
mood. Weird. Always singing. Extremely generous, like, really
generous. Funny. Great heart. Talented. Focused. Very professional.
Down-to-earth.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's Smith's pal Sonnenfeld who plays head cheerleader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this sounds like I'm blowing smoke, but when Will's
around, you're just in a good mood,'' says Sonnenfeld, who is an
outrageous character himself. ``You won't know why you've suddenly
gotten in a better mood, and you realize Will has silently come
onto the stage. He has that karmic thing about him. He has an
aura.''
</P>
<P>
   After ``Men in Black,'' Sonnenfeld swore he wouldn't do any more
big special-effects movies. Then he got the script for ``Wild Wild
West,'' a big summer roller-coaster version of the 1965-'70 TV
series about a secret agent in the post-Civil War West.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Warner Bros. I would do it if I could do it with
Will,'' Sonnenfeld says. ``By using Will, I could put a spin on it
and make it different and hip and cool, in the same way Robert
Conrad was in 1967.''
</P>
<P>
   So Sonnenfeld sent Smith the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry said, `I'm sending you a script that you have to do, so
you don't need to read it 'cause you're doing it anyway,''' Smith
says.
</P>
<P>
   But he did read it and had a few questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Barry, have you ever seen the television show? Um,
did you notice any subtle differences between myself and Robert
Conrad?' Barry said, `Oh, yeah, he's a little shorter than you, but
don't worry about it.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, Smith wears an updated variation of the absurd
pseudo-Western outfit Conrad wore in the series: short black
jacket; fancy vest; rakish, wide-brimmed hat; and, of course, those
dark, tight pants.
</P>
<P>
   Today, at the Four Seasons Hotel, he's sporting a casual white
suit with zipper pockets and zipper front. It looks suspiciously
like an infamous leisure suit, but he flashes open the jacket to
reveal the label.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ain't nothin' but Gianni (Versace), baby,'' he says with a big
grin.
</P>
<P>
   His black belt has a silver Armani buckle. He's wearing a white,
ribbed tank-top undershirt, so it's easy to see his substantial
silver chain necklace. The shoes are heavy and black.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's hair is cut short, and it looks like he hasn't shaved,
on purpose, in four days. There are no rings or bracelets.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 30, is married to actress Jada Pinkett Smith. He has two
sons, Jaden, 1, and Trey (Willard III), 6, from Smith's first
marriage. Last year the family bought a 100-acre ranch in the
Malibu-Santa Monica mountains for a reported $7.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was a fan of ``Wild Wild West'' from watching reruns, but,
on the whole, he wasn't big on Westerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, there weren't a lot of black folks in the American
Western,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   How about Woody Strode (``The Professionals'')?
</P>
<P>
   ``There you go,'' he says. ``That's one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
``The picture of what a cowboy is in America has always been John
Wayne, so to me, it feels great to now give the opportunity to
young black kids, who will now see Will Smith as a cowboy. That
will be their memory of Westerns.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A black Secret Service cowboy may be nontraditional, but ``Wild
Wild West'' is anything but traditional. Like the original TV
series, it's as much science-fiction as Western, as much comedy as
action. We're talking about a Western in which the villain has
tanks and 200-foot-tall mechanical spiders at his disposal.
</P>
<P>
   Kline plays West's sidekick-partner, Artemus Gordon (played on
TV by the late Ross Martin). Branagh is Dr. Arliss Loveless, a
character based on evil scientist Dr. Miguelito Loveless, played on
TV by Michael Dunn. This Loveless is not a dwarf, as the late Dunn
was; he has lost both legs and travels around in a motorized
wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the cast, for no reason except to give West and Gordon a
woman to pursue, is Hayek.
</P>
<P>
   One big difference from the original is the budget. Rumors have
had the film going way over its $105 million budget, though
Sonnenfeld and Smith both deny it spiraled anywhere near the $200
million that some publications have reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were people who were already hating the movie,'' Smith
says. ``In the rap world, we call them player haters. Maybe the
whole July 4 thing, for some reason (they thought we) needed to be
smacked down a little bit. It's time for Will Smith to get knocked
down.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``July 4 thing'' refers to Smith's record of success on that
holiday. Both ``Independence Day'' (1996) and ``Men in Black''
(1997) were Fourth of July mega-hits. Now ``Wild Wild West'' is
trying to repeat the success for the third time in four years by
opening Wednesday for an extended July 4 weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Smith wasn't the first to refer to ``Big Willie Weekend,'' but
he admits he loves the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy the spectacle and saying it's Big Willie Weekend, the
music video and all of that. Big Willie Weekend is part of being
American now.''
</P>
<P>
   It's only fair to add that Smith says things like that with a
big grin and a self-deprecating air. He has a healthy ego, but he
also seems to have a sense of who he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will is never going to change, he just isn't,'' Sonnenfeld
says. ``At the age of 16, he had a hit record and was a
millionaire. He moved out of his home, into a mansion and had six
cars. At the age of 17, his second record didn't do any business.
He got into tax trouble, moved back home, sold the mansion, the
cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``So Will's seen major success and major failure early in his
life. And also his relationship to his parents grounded him and
made him into a godlike figure in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asked about that period in his life, Smith pauses for just a
split second, a long time for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got arrogant. I felt like whatever I put out was going to
work,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's been a big part of why I've been successful: my
work ethic and my focus and my obsessive behavior and perfectionist
attitude. It happened in music. I had a chance to be successful and
have money and then lose it, and then work hard and get it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was in the military, so I was raised with a
hard-core military background. Anytime you get away from working
hard and focusing, you have to expect that something's not going to
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so much better to be broke and make money than to have
money and lose it. There was a time I had a mansion and six cars
and three motorcycles, but didn't have money to put gas in the
cars. I would say I was broke. People would say `No, you're
rich-people broke.' I'd say, `No, no, no, I was regular-folks
broke.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me so appreciative of the opportunities that I don't
want to do anything to mess up the position.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There have been accusations that his reluctance to risk his
position has made Smith too careful. Some critics have called his
rap music too homogenized. His acting choices have been for
unchallenging roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always dealt with it in the music,'' he says. ``I've
always had (detractors). I've always been soft or popcorn or not
real rap. My skin is hard in the music. But in film, this is the
first time I've dealt with potshots.''
</P>
<P>
   He's been criticized about his films and acting before, but
``that's after they've seen the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   He says some people began attacking ``Wild Wild West'' before
they had seen it, spreading rumors that the extensive reshooting
completed after test screenings was a sign the movie was not good.
</P>
<P>
   Sonnenfeld and Smith counter by saying that many films are
reworked after test screenings,which allow filmmakers to see what
works with an audience and what doesn't. Perfectly true, although
there is seldom as much reshooting as there was on ``Wild Wild
West.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone that makes movies would love to watch the movie and
then go back and say, `Oh, God, I wish I had said it this way,'''
Smith says. ``And go back and redo it and make it funnier or more
emotional or different.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Reshooting) was getting that sexy, funny, cool balance. We
took a little of the gunplay out. This was just a bad summer for
gunplay,'' he says, referring to all the violence in the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Willie Weekend was funny last year. To some people, it's
less funny this year. I feel a sense that some people (think), `Let
this guy get a little knock-down here. He's a little high on his
`Wild Wild West' horse.'
</P>
<P>
   ``(It) kind of hurt my feelings a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The comedy, which was an important but small part of the TV
series, is also a lot bigger in the new ``Wild Wild West.'' And
edgier. Sonnenfeld played off Smith's blackness for a lot of risky
humor, such as an outrageous scene in which West tries to joke
racists out of lynching him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went out on a limb a little bit with the political
correctness,'' Smith says. ``It might be a little over the edge for
some people, but to the people that get it, it's really funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Before filming began, Smith read a quote by Conrad reminding
people he did most of his own stunts in the original action-packed
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``So now, I'm trying to do all my own stunts,'' Smith says.
</P>
<P>
   In one scene, West is on a small rail car that goes underneath a
train, and then slides backward under another train following.
Smith found that pretty scary.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a real train, and we were on train tracks. The train
was probably doing 45 or 50mph, and I have to be whipping through
at 60 mph and getting snatched back. I'm under there trying to
figure out why the hell did I let Robert Conrad make me do this,''
he laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Smith also had to learn to ride a horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never been on a horse in my life. So for six weeks I'm
crunching, trying to learn to ride. We were working in Santa Fe
(N.M.), so I was riding a horse back and forth to work. I was
getting a good 10 miles in a day.''
</P>
<P>
   So far Smith has no horses on his ranch, just lots of dogs, but
he's planning to change that since he has learned to ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing like being on a horse. That's such an amazing
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smith is an agreeable interview, but he's also in control. If
the conversation gets a little serious, he has a way of gracefully
steering it in the direction he wants. Asked what he learned as an
actor on this film _ perhaps a silly question considering the
film's silly nature _ he turns it into a joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just learned that I have a really, really great (rear
end),'' he says without missing a beat. ``It's just really fun,
it's generous, it's caring. It's one of those, when you see it,
because I was naked in the first scene, it's just saying to you,
`Hey, pal, how are you doing?' You know?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whether ``Wild Wild West'' is a flop or the third Big Willie
Weekend, Smith plans no more big summer movies for awhile. He wants
to concentrate on smaller or more serious roles to create a
platform for his career, even if he is already one of the
highest-paid actors out there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Late this year he plans to start a Muhammad Ali biopic, again
working with Sonnenfeld. He plans six months of training before the
film, which will probably cover Ali's life from the Olympics to his
long boxing career. He is also meeting with Nicolas Cage to discuss
a comedy script about two heterosexual firemen who decide to
secretly marry in Hawaii, where same-sex marriages are allowed, to
ensure benefits for their children should they be killed on the
job.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a film called ``The Mark,'' another
blockbuster-type movie Smith is considering doing with the
``Independence Day'' producers, but not for a few years.
</P>
<P>
   And waiting out there, maybe, is a ``Men in Black'' sequel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry and I haven't signed for it. We kind of agreed not to do
any sequels,'' he says. ``But you know, the studios can be
persuasive.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, anything is possible. Smith has even been quoted as
saying he thought he could get elected president, if he set his
mind to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I was saying that kind of half-joking,'' he says.
``But I really feel like I could. ... You know?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
