NYT-06-28-99 1235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1910 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-CHILDREN-RDP-HNS     06-28 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CHILDREN-RDP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRY POTTER IS BACK IN SECOND ADVENTURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JANE P. MARSHALL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alice and Lewis Carroll. Willy Wonka and Roald Dahl. Peter Pan
and J.M. Barrie. And now Harry Potter and J.K. Rowling.
</P>
<P>
   When Rowling scratched out Harry Potter's first adventures on a
chunk of paper in a cafe, did she dream her mind-child would join
Alice, Willy and Peter Pan as a household name?
</P>
<P>
   Did she imagine herself never fretting again about the grocery
bill? Did she think of making Entertainment Weekly's It List for
1999? Did she realize that peace and quiet would fly out the window
faster than Harry on his Nimbus 2000 broom?
</P>
<P>
   Rowling's first adventure of the 11-year-old Potter zoomed to
the New York Times best-seller list faster than the Snitch in a
game of Quidditch at Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry.
</P>
<P>
   Harry's stories propel at the same speed. No long descriptions
or subtle philosophy here. Harry moves faster than a video game
character, gets in more fixes than Mario ever dreamed of and faces
menaces who would make Darth Mahl seem like a puppy.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``The Hobbit'' meets ``Goosebumps.'' Children's books will
never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry Potter'' and the ``Sorcerer's Stone'' has been on the
national best-seller list for more than six months, a statistic
unheard of in children's literature. It is still there.
</P>
<P>
   Now, rushed three months ahead of schedule into American
bookstores, ``Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets''
(Scholastic, $17.95) elicits as many squeaks of delight and late
nights of reading as Book No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Adventure No. 3, ``Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban,''
should be in bookstores in September. Rowling plans seven Potter
books. Film rights to the first two have been optioned by Warner
Brothers. Is that a good thing?
</P>
<P>
   The series retains its delight and speed, with more creative
characters than George Lucas' cantina scene in ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   Like so many of the longest-lasting children's stories, ``Harry
Potter'' isn't mired in morals. In decades to come no scholar will
likely analyze Rowling's motives and undercurrents.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Sorcerer's Stone,'' ``Chamber of Secrets'' is just plain
fun. It's packed with what kids can relate to: sports competition,
too much homework, mean classmates, strict teachers and rules that
beg breaking.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, one of the rules is that underage student wizards cannot
use their magic outside the classroom. Sure, their teachers lord
over classes such as Herbology, Defense Against the Dark Arts and
Transfiguration.
</P>
<P>
   Harry, now 12 and in his second year at Hogwarts, is a hero,
known throughout the wizard world because of how he got the tiny
scar on his forehead. He's whole-blood, meaning both his parents
were wizards. Most of us are Mudbloods, and our parents are
Muggles, people without magic powers.
</P>
<P>
   He continues to play Quidditch (a team sport executed on magic
brooms) and deal with the traumas and joys of school. Traumas focus
on a ghost in a girls bathroom, the magic chamber, monstrous
creatures, a book with no writing and a devious plot.
</P>
<P>
   Harry and his friends unravel the mystery in P.D. Jameslike
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Rowling builds a parallel universe. Wizards have to deal with
the Muggles world, but Muggles only suspect the magic world.
</P>
<P>
   Complex? You bet. Otherwise kids would turn on the TV. Original?
Yes. Here, as an example, is a bit of Rowling vocabulary:
</P>
<P>
   Skele-Grow _ a potion to grow bones back when a spell has taken
them away.
</P>
<P>
   Aparecium _ the magic word that makes invisible ink visible.
</P>
<P>
   Spellotape _ used to mend a magic wand.
</P>
<P>
   Parseltongue _ the ability to speak to snakes.
</P>
<P>
   Peskipiksi pesternomi _ this spell does not work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry'' ranks near the top of a read-aloud family project. But
don't expect a wind-down sleepy-time moment.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the magical read-aloud category is Mercer Mayer's new
``Shibumi and the Kitemaker'' (Marshall Cavendish, $18.95). Mayer's
classics reach back years and include such wonders as ``Professor
Wormbog in Search for the Zipperump-A-Zoo'' and ``A Book, A Dog and
a Frog.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shibumi'' is a different path for Mayer.
</P>
<P>
   First, he creates the entrancing art for this picture book in
Adobe Photoshop, ElectricImage, FormZ, Bryce, Painter, Adobe
Illustrator and Tree Professional computer programs.
</P>
<P>
   Second, he sets the fablelike story in Japan. Mayer writes that
he has been enthralled by Japanese culture since he was a child.
``As familiar as I have been with the Japanese culture, I never
felt as though I could penetrate it, being a foreigner.''
</P>
<P>
   He continues: ``I first heard the word `shibumi' on that trip to
Japan. I loved the way it sounded, but no one could translate it
for me except to say it meant something fashionable or in good
taste. Later on I gave it a meaning of my own, and out of that grew
the story. As far as I know it has no basis in Japanese folk
literature. `Shibumi' takes place in a culture that might have
been, or in a place that exists even now _ certainly in my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   His profound and heartfelt words echo through the pages as he
spins the tale of a princess who is protected from ugliness until
one day she climbs a tree and looks over the palace wall. The shock
sets her on a fateful path that, with the help of the royal kite
maker, tests her convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Change is possible, but not without pain.
</P>
<P>
   Summer magic is best epitomized by a movie _ ``Episode I: The
Phantom Menace.'' Not everybody is sick of the ubiquitous ``Star
Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   Some like wearing ``Star Wars'' clothes, sleeping on ``Star
Wars'' sheets, drinking from Star Wars Pepsi cups and reading
``Star Wars books.''
</P>
<P>
   The phenom wouldn't be complete without ``Star Wars _ Episode I:
The Visual Dictionary'' (DK, $19.95) or ``Incredible
Cross-Sections'' (DK, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologist David West Reynolds, a ``Star Wars'' nut himself,
approached his task the way he would a study of ancient Rome or
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   With artists Hans Jenssen and Richard Chasemore, he describes
the guts of spacecraft such as the Naboo N-1 Starfighter and the
Sith Infiltrator, and places them in the galaxy with their
functions and histories. You've probably wondered where the array
of 16 droid signal-receiver stations were located on the Droid
Starfighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Visual Dictionary'' is even better. Take a close look at
Sebulba's blue-skinned groomers. Stop and study characters that are
on screen only seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Astound your friends with your knowledge of ``Star Wars''
trivia: the scar of remembrance that divides Queen Amidala's lip,
the parts of Maul's lightsaber, the members of the Jedi High
Council.
</P>
<P>
   In the long list of small-type acknowledgments, Reynolds writes:
``FBI Special Agent R. Matthew Bliss offered the benefit of his
expertise in refining the secret profile of Darth Maul, marking
what was probably the first time a U.S. federal agent has
professionally explored the background of a Sith Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a wonderful, magical summer. Enjoy it with books.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
