<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1913 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-AIRLINES-ART-HNS     06-28 1438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-AIRLINES-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON A WING &AMP; A PRAYER: AIRLINES ENLIST CHEFS TO IMPROVE MEALS AT
35,000 FEET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT database) 
 
(Eds.: Moved in ``d'' and ``l'' categories) 
(Eds.: Accent marks needed over u in Cordua, e in Americas and e in
souffles.) 
 
By DAI HUYNH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ The hectic pace was nothing new for the former
waitress.
</P>
<P>
   It would take time, though, for Resa Kelly to get used to the
rocking and rolling of this dining room _ a Boeing 757.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the upside-down world of what I do,'' says the Houston
chef, grabbing the lobster tail with du Barry sauce from the flight
attendant and scuttling down the aisle to deliver the appetizer to
the passenger in seat 4F.
</P>
<P>
   Returning for another plate, Kelly is thrown off-balance by the
turbulence that would cause flight attendants and passengers to
feel like tossed salads at the end of the day. In the galley,
several unwrapped food trays shot out of the storage cart like
aluminum rocket ships. Glasses of water turned over, causing a
minor flood at the entrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like working in a kitchen during an earthquake,'' says
Kelly, the owner of Resa's Prime Steak and Piano Bar in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The 41-year-old restaurateur was recently added to the roster of
notable chefs enlisted by Continental Airlines to redesign and
revamp its food.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly joins celebrity chefs Michael Cordua of Americas and
Churrascos in Houston, Don Pintabona of Tribeca Grill in New York
City and Roy Yamaguchi of Roy's restaurants worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   And like them, she will serve as the in-flight chef on several
of the airline's transcontinental and international flights
throughout the year, trying to get a better understanding of the
food service on board an aircraft 35,000 feet above ground.
</P>
<P>
   She will then apply the information to develop menus for the
airline's business, first-class and, eventually, coach cabins.
</P>
<P>
   If all this sounds like a restaurant with wings, that is exactly
the point, and Houston-based Continental is the first to admit that
the Chef on Board program is a great publicity tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a learning opportunity for the chefs; but it's also great
PR for us to show customers that there's a lot of thought put into
our food,'' says Siegfried Lang, managing director of food and
beverage planning.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly signed up for the 6:45 p.m. flight from Newark, N.J., to
San Francisco. Standing inside the 5-by-6-foot galley, the mother
of three struggles to unwrap the layers of plastic wrap around the
plates of food.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to suggest that they start using plastic covers.
It'll be easier for the flight attendants to remove,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Continental's transcontinental business and first-class
passengers dine on menus designed by the celebrity chefs. The
five-course meal on this flight was created by Pintabona, executive
chef of Tribeca Grill. It features selections such as a mixed grill
of veal, lamb and beef; macadamia-crusted salmon; breast of duck;
and spinach ravioli with Alfredo sauce.
</P>
<P>
   As flight attendant Steve Miller transfers the entrees to the
plates, Kelly helps with the presentation, adding a few fine-dining
touches by artfully crossing the asparagus and drizzling sauces
around the vegetables _ an attention to detail that may seem
revolutionary. But Continental isn't the only airline trying to
transpose cabin dining into fine dining; its competitors have also
jumped on board.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, United Airlines convinced internationally
celebrated chef Jacques Pepin to bring his cooking on board
selected domestic flights. But already on the Chicago-based
airline's payroll are such familiar faces as Martin Yan of PBS-TV's
``Yan Can Cook'' series and Mary Sue Milliken and Susan Feniger of
the Food Network's ``Too Hot Tamales'' series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it's not going to be a restaurant per se. We just want
to emulate some of its features and to bring a fine-dining
experience along with the long-haul air experience,'' says Bob
Braden, United Airlines's manager for on-board service planning for
North America.
</P>
<P>
   To get an edge on competitors, it seems, airline executives are
banking on better food _ this after years of slashing in-flight
meals and snacks to reduce costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's greater competition among the carriers in the total
perception of the product by customers. Food is a big part of
that,'' explains Lynda Zane, senior director of dining services for
Continental.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly joins a long list of culinary luminaries upgrading and
updating airline food, including Paul Prudhomme for American
Airlines, Michel Roux for British Airways and Raymond Blanc for
Virgin Atlantic. But not every flier will sample creations by the
celebrity chefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the celebrity chefs are involved in first-class or
international meals. Celebrity chefs don't seem to touch much on
the rest of the passengers,'' says Randy Petersen, editor and
publisher of InsideFlyer magazine and an expert on frequent-flier
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrity chefs have been around for 20 years. None of them
has made any long-lasting impression on what airline food is today.
It will never, ever change.''
</P>
<P>
   Most industry watchers agree that airline food is often driven
by economics. Right now, the airlines are flying high financially _
hence the attempt to upgrade the food.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can all imagine that if the industry isn't doing well,
we'll all be back to peanuts,'' Petersen says.
</P>
<P>
   While the first-class passengers on this Continental flight
munch on duck, veal and lamb, those in the coach cabin are chewing
on chicken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was starving. I haven't eaten since 10:30 this morning,''
says Mark Tolanel of New Jersey, looking down at his empty tray in
coach. ``It was really just mediocre. But the food, at least, comes
to you warmer than it used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Michael Hales, 26, is finishing off his bean-and-rice
burrito.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish they had better desserts. Just because we're
vegetarians doesn't mean we don't like fatty, creamy-filled foods.
This is no fun,'' he complains, waving a small cinnamon twist.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I got this stuff on the ground, I would never go back to
the restaurant,'' girlfriend Joanna Brief adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we're being too critical, especially since the food is
complimentary,'' Hales says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Complimentary?'' Brief replies. ``You're paying for it!''
</P>
<P>
   On average, airlines spend $2-$4 per person on domestic flights,
according to industry insiders. International flights range from
$30 to $50 per person per flight, because airlines serve more
elaborate meals and free alcohol on longer hauls.
</P>
<P>
   Continental will spend about $250 million this year on in-flight
food service. The air carrier serves up about 80,000 meals daily.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly can grill a mean steak at her restaurant in Houston. But
up in the air, she does little cooking since the meals are already
prepared and partly cooked in one of the airline's six Chelsea
Catering kitchens around the country. Her job on board is to simply
switch on the convection oven, which will reheat the food at 350
degrees for 15 to 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't from the kitchen to the table. It has to go through
two other steps to get to your plate,'' Kelly says. ``It's a real
challenge coming up with dishes that will withstand all those
steps. But it's just a matter of picking out things that will
translate well.''
</P>
<P>
   What Kelly hopes will work are her bread soup bowls, which
Continental will introduce in a couple of months. What she's
certain won't work are dishes such as poached eggs, risottos and
souffles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything you need to eat immediately isn't going to be good,''
Kelly says. ``They're not cooking back there; they're plating what
has already been prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the first-class cabin, Houston businessman Mark
Weisberger chomps appreciatively on his lobster tail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The food has gotten better. There's more variety now,'' he
says. ``I haven't seen anyone dump anything on anybody's lap in a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of miles _ and one meal _ away from Newark, the plane
is 45 minutes from San Francisco. The food has been served. The
dishes have been cleared.
</P>
<P>
   Looking around the galley, Kelly shakes her head in amazement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been tough. You're working in a space that wouldn't
meet a Texas woman's requirement of a closet,'' she says. ``The
turbulence was really interesting, too. For a while, we were riding
that bucking bronco in the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   But she survived, and the airlines hope the program will
survive, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
