<SLUG> BC-VATICAN-COLLEGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC CHURCH'S PROCLAMATION LEADS MOSTLY TO PAPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Six months after U.S. bishops called for closer
ties between Catholic colleges and the Vatican, the proclamation's
most visible legacy is paper _ lots of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My pile on `Ex corde' is 7 inches thick,'' said Mark Sullivan,
president of the College of Saint Rose.
</P>
<P>
   The paper trail is testament to the substantial confusion
surrounding a papal document called ``Ex corde Ecclesiae,'' or
``From the Heart of the Church.''
</P>
<P>
   From the day U.S. bishops responded to the document last
November, it threatened to rock the precarious balance at Catholic
colleges between maintaining high academic standards and a uniquely
Catholic identity.
</P>
<P>
   Professors blanched at medieval-sounding proposals that seemed
aimed at their academic freedom: Schools would appoint ``faithful''
Catholics as professors and trustees. New presidents would make an
``oath of fidelity'' to the church. And the local bishop would
judge whether a theologian's teaching accurately portrayed church
doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about 20th century American faculty taking a
loyalty oath,'' said Raymond Boisvert, a professor of philosophy at
Siena College. ``There'd be a revolt.''
</P>
<P>
   Administrators worry that the interpretation would make
non-Catholic students and faculty feel like second-class citizens,
and that federal aid requiring a clear separation of church and
state would dry up.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, millions of dollars in so-called ``Bundy aid'' to
Catholic colleges hinges on the understanding that they are not
``under the control and direction of any religious denomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Others fear discrimination lawsuits and losing the
seal-of-approval of non-religious accrediting bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Since most Catholic colleges receive little or no money from the
church, the worst penalty they could face if they don't comply is
to lose their right to call themselves ``Catholic.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Albany region, the three main Catholic Colleges _ Maria
and St. Rose in Albany, and Siena in Colonie _ have reacted
cautiously to the proposals.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, St. Rose will hold a retreat on ``Ex corde''
featuring Sullivan and members of the college's board of trustees.
The Rev. Kevin Mackin, president of Siena, has embraced a
substantially watered-down proposal offered last month by the
Association of Catholic Colleges and Universities.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the references to loyalty oaths and mandates for
majority-Catholic faculties. Instead, the alternative asks colleges
to make ``all reasonable efforts'' to find professors who are
``committed to maintaining the specific Catholic identity of the
institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Many faculty interviewed recently said they were unaware or
unphased by the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't affect me personally, and I don't think in a
million years it will happen,'' said Peter Zaas, a Jewish professor
at Siena who teaches New Testament theology.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying much of the discussion, however, is a subtler debate
about the direction of the nation's Catholic schools at the turn of
the millennium: Just how Catholic are they?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any bishop has the time or the energy to run a
college,'' said Bishop Howard Hubbard of Albany. ``But I think it
is the will of bishops and college administrators that
secularization doesn't erode our Catholic colleges.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Harvard, Duke and Yale all started as Protestant
institutions but are now seen as non-religious.
</P>
<P>
   The tug-of-war between Catholic schools and the Vatican is as
old as the university itself. It dates to the 13th century, when
Thomas Aquinas ran afoul of church authorities for mixing biblical
theology with the teachings of Aristotle at the University of
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   In this century, the debate came into sharper focus following
the Second Vatican Council, which promoted a freer church spirit.
Colleges that had been exclusively controlled by the clergy saw an
increasing reliance on laymen.
</P>
<P>
   One result is that Catholic colleges became less of a training
ground for future religious leaders. A recent survey by the
Official Catholic Directory found that there were 40 percent fewer
priests in the nation than there were just 30 years ago, at a time
when the Catholic population has risen by 15 million. Some believe
those statistics are a key reason the Vatican is looking to bring
the nation's Catholic universities closer to the fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when 2 out of 3 graduates at St. Rose went on
to holy orders, and Siena almost had a quota on numbers who went
into the priesthood,'' said Bruce Johnston, chair of the department
of religion and philosophy at St. Rose. ``Now, we have a situation
in the region where parishes are served by lay people because there
aren't enough priests around.''
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II has sought to re-assert the church's influence
and step back from Vatican II. He has hunkered down on
controversial social issues like homosexuality and abortion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
