</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIDI-CIGARETTES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIDIS GAIN FAVOR WITH NATION'S TEENAGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD FITZPATRICK  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Sitting on a bicycle outside Albany High School,
the 16-year-old student unfolded his wallet and plucked out one of
the thin, flavored cigarettes that are gaining popularity among
teenagers in the Albany area.
</P>
<P>
   The hand-rolled, unfiltered butts _ called bidis, or beedies _
release two or three times the nicotine and tar of regular
cigarettes. Yet many people, including this teenager, think they
are cleaner than the average smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Most people over 30 wouldn't know a bidi from a Beanie Baby. But
the scent of the tiny cigarettes is wafting over hip teen hangouts
from Boston's Harvard Square to San Francisco's Haight-Ashbury, and
Albany teens are becoming part of the trend, according to merchants
and anti-smoking activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very popular,'' said Erin Wisnewski, substance abuse
prevention specialist at the LaSalle School for Boys in Albany.
``All of the kids are smoking them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bidis have all the trappings of a true teen fad. They look like
joints, so they have a rebellious quality. They are made in India,
so some consider them exotic. And they come in flavors _ vanilla
and chocolate, cherry and strawberry, cardamom and clove.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, they can be lethal. Yet some people are smoking them
with the idea that they are less harmful than regular cigarettes.
``There's not as much addictive stuff,'' the boy on the bike, who
asked to remain anonymous, said as he lit a bidi and handed another
to his buddy.
</P>
<P>
   Such misconceptions are alarming to anti-smoking activists, who
see bidis as a candy-coated ploy to get young people to begin
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flavor makes them exciting and makes them the current
trend,'' said Jill Fenton, program director for the American Lung
Association of Northeastern New York, based in Colonie.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, kids ate candy cigarettes. Now, Fenton said,
``They're enticing children with candy-flavored real cigarettes
that have the same real drug and the same real cancer-causing
agents.''
</P>
<P>
   Fenton said the problem with underage smoking is already bad,
with the average smoker taking that first drag at age 13, and 90
percent starting before they turn 18. Bidis can only make matters
worse, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Teenagers interviewed for this story said taste is one of the
main reasons they smoke bidis.
</P>
<P>
   One 17-year-old from Albany said he smoked his first bidi at age
13, before he had ever touched a regular cigarette. ``They don't
taste that bad,'' the boy said of bidis as he sat at the Cafe Dolce
coffeeshop, cracking open a package of regular cigarettes. ``Cherry
is good.'' ``Vanilla is best,'' said his friend, a 17-year-old
girl, also from Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Bidis have been sold in the United States for decades. At first,
they were popular only with natives of India or other parts of
Asia, but in the past couple of years they have become fashionable
with a larger population in the United States, France and England,
said Dr. Samira Asma, an epidemiologist with the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention, based in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Bidis are becoming more common and popular in convenience stores
and tobacco shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sell very well for a boutique or deluxe cigarette,'' said
Dick Adair, regional director of Smokers' Paradise, which has nine
stores in the Albany region. ``There is definitely a following.''
</P>
<P>
   In India, that following is an older crowd. But in the United
States, the devotees are decidedly young. ``No one over 30 knows
what they are,'' Adair said.
</P>
<P>
   New York State law prohibits the sale of tobacco products,
including bidis, to people younger than 18. But kids say it's easy
to get bidis, and they are buying them.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the taste, observers say there are a number of reasons
why the smokes are catching on despite their danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's regarded as something very hip, ethnic, exotic,'' Asma
said. Indian culture is weaving its way into American music and
fashion, and bidis are becoming as trendy as the toe ring, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people like that they have a homemade quality to
them,'' said Dan Heins, owner of the Shining Star incense shop. The
store does not sell bidis but often has customers asking for the
cigarettes, which are hand-rolled and tied with a string. ``It kind
of has a Third Worldish, cottage-industry feel to it.''
</P>
<P>
   It also has the look and smell of smoking marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like you are doing a criminal act when you are just
smoking a bidi,'' Heins said. ``You can't get in trouble for it,
and you don't walk around stoned all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Anti-smoking activists say bidis play into a new marketing
gimmick, tried by the Winston brand, that emphasizes the lack of
additives in some cigarettes. Also, bidis are smaller than regular
cigarettes and contain less tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, bidis are more hazardous than your basic butt,
releasing two or three times more tar, nicotine, carbon monoxide
and other cancer-causing agents, Asma said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're terribly dangerous,'' said Russell Sciandra, director
of the Center for a Tobacco Free new York, based in Albany. ``They
are unfiltered, full of carcinogens. They're a very dirty smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, bidis are beginning to make it onto the radar screen of
lawmakers. Earlier this month, Arizona became the first state to
enact legislation banning the sale and distribution of the tiny
cigarettes. The impetus was concern about how popular bidis were
becoming among young people, Asma said.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to bidis, Asma said, the message for teens is
simple: ``It's not as cool as it appears to be. They are really
deadly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
