w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BILL-PULLMAN-IN-LAKE-     06-28 1472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILL-PULLMAN-IN-LAKE-PLACID-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL PULLMAN AND THE CROC OF DOOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Bill Pullman with Brendan Gleeson in a
scene from ``Lake Placid.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Lions and tigers and bears, oh my.
 &HT;    Bill Pullman was in the wilds of Vancouver, British Columbia,
roughing it with the cast of an upcoming movie in which he plays a
macho game warden, but there's a big difference between acting and
being.
 &HT;    ``Listen, Bill,'' the forest-ranger liaison told him, ``when it
gets dark, for God's sake do not venture out of your campgrounds.
There have been bear attacks in the area.''
 &HT;    So picture the reaction of Bridget Fonda, his co-star in ``Lake
Placid,'' when Pullman announced around midnight that he was going
for a walk to pick blackberries.
 &HT;    ``I was screaming, `Bill, don't go! The bears!''' Fonda recalls.
``You see, I panic for other people. But Bill gets this glint in
his eye and says, `I'll be back with dessert.'''
 &HT;    Pullman says he didn't actually think much of it.
 &HT;    ``I didn't take the ranger seriously at all. Modern society has
gotten us all a little neurotic,'' the actor says. ``I figured if I
made a little noise going into the woods, then the bear would leave
me alone or ask for an autograph.''
 &HT;    But once he was alone in the forest ...
 &HT;    ``I guess nerves did take over,'' he says. ``By the end of my
walk, I was banging so many sticks and cups together that I sounded
like a percussion section.''
 &HT;    As he relaxes over a Saturday-morning breakfast at Los Angeles'
Four Seasons Hotel, Pullman doesn't look much like an outdoorsman.
Model-handsome in black slacks and a gray shirt, with overgrown
bangs falling into his face, the 45-year-old actor doesn't look
like he'd have much of an idea of what to do if confronted by a
30-foot-long, man-eating crocodile in the pristine Maine
wilderness.
 &HT;    But that's the setup for ``Lake Placid,'' which opens July 16
nationwide. Pullman's character heads a group of misfits including
a nature-phobic paleontologist (Fonda), an out-of-his-league
sheriff (Brendan Gleeson) and an eccentric mythology professor
(Oliver Platt) who must somehow capture or kill the deadly
creature.
 &HT;    His advisors urged him not to sign on to what is essentially an
inland ``Jaws,'' Pullman says. But he liked the script, written by
David E. Kelley, creator of ``The Practice'' and ``Ally McBeal.''
And besides, he had another, less typical reason for making the
movie.
 &HT;    ``Secretly, I wanted to do it for my brother,'' Pullman says.
``When we were growing up, our hero was a forest ranger from
upstate New York named Art Flick, who wrote for Field and Stream.
He had a patch on his sleeve and the coolest truck just loaded with
gear. We wanted to be Flick.
 &HT;    ``I knew if I did this movie and played a ranger, my brother
would be so jealous,'' he adds with a wicked laugh. ``He's only a
doctor. I could be a ranger!''
 &HT;    Other than squaring off against some pretty ugly aliens in
``Independence Day'' (1996), Pullman didn't have much experience
with monster movies. His typical roles as good-guy leading men in
such films as ``Sleepless in Seattle'' (1993), ``Malice'' (1993)
and ``While You Were Sleeping'' (1996) weren't the kind that lead
an actor to spend weeks in a freezing-cold lake with a huge,
artificial crocodile.
 &HT;    ``The weird thing in the water is that you would notice waves
that were not being made by our effects crew,'' Pullman says. ``All
of a sudden, a huge beaver would swim by you.
 &HT;    ``Beavers do not respect actors.''
 &HT;    At other times, he recalls, his own imagination was his worst
enemy.
 &HT;    ``You're psyched up to do a horror movie, and all of a sudden in
the lake, something with tentacles grabs at your feet,'' he says.
``You jump, and then blush when you realize it's only a big weed.''
 &HT;    It's a strange way to make a living, especially for a boy from
Hornell, N.Y., who's the son of a doctor father and a nurse mother,
and whose four siblings who are all in the medical profession.
 &HT;    Given this background, he says, his parents were ``horrified''
when their youngest son, a National Merit Scholarship winner,
decided to forgo medical school in favor of a two-year vocational
school for building construction.
 &HT;    ``At school I think I gave the plumbing students an inferiority
complex,'' Pullman says.
 &HT;    He wanted to go into urban planning _ until a teacher at the
vocational school insisted he join their drama club.
 &HT;    ``Yes, they had a drama program,'' Pullman says. ``One day I
showed up for auditions with some refrigeration students.''
 &HT;    Something clicked, and Pullman abandoned technical school for
drama, earning a master's degree in directing from the University
of Massachusetts at Amherst. He subsequently produced plays and
taught at Montana State University, where he ran the theater
department for two years.
 &HT;    In the 1980s, after a stint studying directing in England,
Pullman moved to New York to pursue an acting career. He was
advised to try the stage, because he wasn't film-star material.
 &HT;    ``I heard, `Your face is not distinctive,''' he says.
 &HT;    Determined to prove otherwise, he moved to Los Angeles, working
at the Los Angeles Theatre Center and angling for movie roles. His
film debut came in ``Ruthless People'' (1986).
 &HT;    Since then, and especially since his breakout role in
``Sleepless in Seattle,'' Pullman has alternated mainstream roles
in films such as ``While You Were Sleeping'' and ``Independence
Day'' with quirkier fare such as ``The Last Seduction'' (1994) and
David Lynch's ``Lost Highway'' (1997).
 &HT;    ``I make strange choices,'' he says, ``because the curse in this
business is when the powers go, `We have this type of role. Get me
a Bill Pullman type.'
 &HT;    ``I think of my type as still evolving,'' Pullman says. ``In
fact, my favorite question from a journalist is `What is your
favorite role?' My answer always will be, `It's a role I haven't
played yet.'''
 &HT;    Not all his roles have been seen, however. Take his role in
director Terrence Malick's long-awaited comeback film, ``The Thin
Red Line'' (1998).
 &HT;    ``It was disappointing,'' Pullman says. ``At one point during
production, Terry thought I should narrate the film. So he sent me
28 single-spaced pages of very complicated dialogue. I worked on it
with him for weeks.''
 &HT;    Then one day Malick called to inform Pullman that he was no
longer the narrator. In fact, he was no longer in the movie at all
_ his role had been cut in its entirety.
 &HT;    ``I guess the people who are actually in the movie should say
the narration,'' Pullman says, shrugging. ``To me every role is a
lark _ I don't let it hurt me.''
 &HT;    Besides, he's too busy to brood. He's currently scouting
Canadian locations for his screen directorial debut, a TNT
adaptation of Owen Wister's classic novel ``The Virginian,'' in
which he will also star.
 &HT;    ``The best part of directing is that I finally feel like an
urban planner,'' Pullman says. ``I'm actually building a Western
town. The other day I found myself saying, `Let's build the school
here.'
 &HT;    ``It's nice how things come full circle.''
 &HT;    As for his career, his viewpoint seems to have been shaped by
his recent wilderness excursion.
 &HT;    ``I think of Hollywood like it's a forest,'' Pullman says.
``Most days I'm swimming through a lake. There are some cold places
in that lake. There are warm places. You just have to keep floating
around, not knowing what will happen next.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
