<SLUG> BC-PHIL-COLLINS-SINGS-TARZAN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHIL COLLINS HELPS `TARZAN' SWING 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of singer/songwriter Phil Collins.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    This could be big. Really big.
 &HT;    And Phil Collins knows big when he sees it. The British
singer/musician/songwriter/producer _ and occasional actor _ has
released eight multimillion-selling solo albums, plus another
half-dozen during his years with the band Genesis.
 &HT;    But even he's awed by the scale of his latest project, five
songs for the Walt Disney Co.'s new animated feature, ``Tarzan.''
 &HT;    ``It has the potential to be vast _ and I don't necessarily mean
in financial terms, just in terms of the kind of audience it can
reach once these things get on a roll,'' the 48-year-old Collins
says.
 &HT;    ``The music in these films, it's part of movie heritage,'' he
explains. ``You think of the songs almost before you think of the
stories, the old songs like `When You Wish Upon a Star,' `Whistle
While You Work.' The music has always been so integral to those
films. I'm proud to be part of it, actually.''
 &HT;    A big part, really. Collins recorded 10 different versions of
the various songs for the `Tarzan'' soundtrack album, including
separate versions of ``Trashin' the Camp'' with actress Rosie
O'Donnell and with the pop group `N Sync. The album swung into the
Billboard Top 10 during the week following the film's release.
 &HT;    But Collins didn't simply write the songs, as such predecessors
as Howard Ashman/Alan Menken and Tim Rice/Elton John have. He also
sings them in the movie, rather than their being sung by
``Tarzan's'' characters, as in a true musical. Even John sang only
one song in ``The Lion King'' (1994), and that was over the closing
credits.
 &HT;    ``The only other comparable thing was Elton,'' Collins says,
``and his brief was different _ that he write, with Tim Rice, some
songs that would work for the movie. The music was taken and shaken
about a bit and sung by the characters in the film, and he sort of
did the end-credit thing. That's the traditional way it's been.''
 &HT;    Disney wanted a different approach for ``Tarzan,'' which
initially worried Collins.
 &HT;    ``They wanted to break a few molds with this,'' he says. ``I was
a bit apprehensive at first, of people hearing my voice instead of
the characters. For me, that was a worrying issue, but for them, it
wasn't.
 &HT;    ``It obviously makes the film different from anything they've
done before,'' he adds, ``but from my point of view it makes me an
integral part of the movie, which is better than just writing the
songs.''
 &HT;    ``Tarzan'' is only the latest step in the evolution of Collins,
a former child actor who joined Genesis as its drummer in 1970 and
moved out front as its lead singer following Peter Gabriel's
departure in 1975. In 1994 he himself left the group, to
concentrate on his solo career _ though he did participate with the
band in a new recording of their hit ``The Carpet Crawlers'' for a
greatest-hits album, due out this fall.
 &HT;    Since Collins' departure, Genesis has struggled. Founders Tony
Banks and Mike Rutherford replaced Collins with Ray Wilson for
their first album without him, ``Calling All Stations'' (1997).
Fans, particularly American fans, generally criticized the album,
which Collins doesn't mind saying he finds unfair.
 &HT;    ``I mean, all those Genesis fans who have been wringing on over
the last 15 years that I f--ked the band up by taking it and giving
it commercial success, those are the people who should be loving
this band now,'' Collins says. ``I'm not there, and they've got
Tony and Mike, who are basically the spirit of Genesis, writing the
songs ... and they've turned their backs on the band.''
 &HT;    If ``Tarzan'' seems a bit off the beaten track for a longtime
rock star, his other current musical project is even more unusual:
a big band, which he introduced in Switzerland at the 1997 Montreux
Jazz Festival and took on tour in 1998, playing brass-fueled
versions of Genesis favorites, his own solo hits and occasional
covers. In July the band will release a live album, ``A Hot Night
in Paris.''
 &HT;    Collins says the big-band idea was spurred by his desire to
reconnect with drumming after years of fronting Genesis and his
solo band. An invitation to put together a group for the Montreux
festival, following his own move from Britain to Switzerland,
sealed his resolve.
 &HT;    ``It was like climbing Everest at first,'' he says with a laugh.
``I knew it was not going to be easy, but I didn't realize just how
difficult it was going to be to do it properly. You're sort of
playing along or snapping your fingers along to a Buddy Rich record
or a Count Basie record, and it's quite easy. But then actually
being in the driver's seat is very, very difficult.''
 &HT;    It wasn't easy for his fans, either. Despite ample advertising,
many who turned out for the band's tour performances expected to
hear the familiar versions of Collins' material. There were, he
acknowledges, ``some scenes'' _ at a show in suburban Detroit, he
even eliminated the encore portion of the show, during which he
planned to sing a couple of songs, because he felt that some in the
crowd had been rude to guest singer Oleta Adams.
 &HT;    But Collins hopes that, after the release of ``A Hot Night in
Paris,'' which was recorded last summer, his fans will grasp the
big-band concept and be more prepared for what they'll get when he
takes it on the road again next year.
 &HT;    ``I think there will be much more awareness of what it is next
time I go out, which will be great,'' he says. ``It's something I
want to continue. It's not a novelty for me _ it's something I
think is a big part of my years to come.''
 &HT;    Not that he's giving up on pop, however. Between promotional
jags for ``Tarzan'' he's beginning work on his next album, drawing
on material left over from previous recordings as well as more
recent ideas.
 &HT;    It may not sound like ``classic Collins,'' however. The
singer/songwriter notes that ``Tarzan'' and the big band have left
indelible marks on his creative sensibility.
 &HT;    ``I always like to try to do different things and keep moving,''
says the twice-divorced Collins, who is engaged to marry his
girlfriend, Orlanne Cevey. ``This and the big-band thing are two of
the most exciting things that have happened to me, really, for a
long time.
 &HT;    ``It's great it keeps sort of changing, even at this late
date.''
 c.1999 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Tarzan,'' consult the official
Website at www.tarzan.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
