<SLUG> BC-MENA-SUVARI-IN-AMERICAN-PIE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL-`AMERICAN' GIRL: MENA SUVARI STARS IN `AMERICAN PIE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Mena Suvari with Chris Klein in a scene
from ``American Pie.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Walking along a Los Angeles street one day in May, someone she
didn't know recognized Mena Suvari.
 &HT;    ``It was,'' Suvari says, ``a little ... weird.''
 &HT;    The 20-year-old actress had never before been recognized by a
stranger, despite roles in the films ``Nowhere'' (1997) ``Kiss the
Girls'' (1997) and ``The Rage: Carrie 2'' (1999). It took, of all
things, the dunderheaded Rob Lowe miniseries ``Atomic Train'' to
win her one of the classic signs of impending stardom.
 &HT;    ``If I sat down and thought about being recognized, it would
have weirded me out,'' Suvari says. ``Everybody always says, `Oh, I
never thought it would happen to me,' and I didn't think it would
happen for me.
 &HT;    ``So many people are here in L.A. trying hard to make it in this
business, and for me it's just been so much easier than it could
have been. Things are really happening.''
 &HT;    Suvari's not kidding. The petite, blue-eyed blonde stars in two
highly anticipated films, namely the raunchy teen comedy ``American
Pie,'' opening July 9, and ``American Beauty,'' a dark and sexy
drama due out this fall.
 &HT;    The titles may be similar, but it shouldn't be too hard to tell
the two films apart: ``American Beauty'' is a high-profile drama
co-starring Kevin Spacey and Annette Bening, while ``American Pie''
... well, it's about four horny high-school boys who make a pact to
lose their virginity before graduation, and you don't want to know
what the title refers to.
 &HT;    Suvari plays Heather, the angelic choirgirl who catches the
attention of Oz (Chris Klein), a hunky lacrosse player who prefers
to be called ``Casanova.''
 &HT;    Plumbing the same shameless depths as ``There's Something About
Mary,'' ``American Pie'' features crude jokes, nudity and more than
the usual amount of baked-goods sleaze. Think ``Porky's'' meets
``Fast Times at Ridgemont High.''
 &HT;    ``I think America is ready for it,'' Suvari says by telephone
from the Los Angeles home she shares with her boyfriend. ``A close
friend of mine told me the other day that she liked the film
because most films haven't gone there, in terms of the sexual
experiences shown and the funniness of it all. It's out there, but
I think people are ready for it.''
 &HT;    Heather, of course, doesn't go out there.
 &HT;    ``She's kind of innocent, and I tend to play that role a lot,''
Suvari says, laughing. ``I lived in South Carolina before I moved
out to L.A., and I was involved in the choir, so it was easy to
jump back into that mindset.
 &HT;    ``The relationship between Heather and Oz is so sweet,'' she
adds. ``All the funny stuff happens in other parts of the movie,
which makes our scenes stand out and grounds the film a little more
in reality.''
 &HT;    Suvari's co-stars Shannon Elizabeth, Tara Reid, Alyson Hannigan
and Natasha Lyonne play much flashier characters and, yes, Suvari
did feel twinges of jealousy.
 &HT;    ``Of course I did, but I loved my character just the same,'' she
says. ``I didn't audition for the other roles.
 &HT;    ``I guess my agents or maybe the film's casting people just
didn't see me as any of the other roles,'' she says. ``There's a
part of me that could have played Vicky (Reid) or Jessica (Lyonne),
but Heather was the role that I could most easily identify with.''
 &HT;    Suvari didn't identify so easily with Angela, the title
character in ``American Beauty.''
 &HT;    ``Talk about playing different sides of yourself,'' she says.
``Kevin Spacey and Annette Bening are a married couple. They're
both having affairs on the side, and he's chasing after me.
 &HT;    ``I'm their daughter's best friend,'' the young actress adds.
``My character is very sly and manipulative, yet somehow
innocent.''
 &HT;    Oh, and she kisses Spacey.
 &HT;    ``It was just like kissing any other person,'' Suvari says,
laughing. ``He's an intelligent, experienced actor, and he knows
how to make things comfortable on the set.
 &HT;    ``He was nice and polite to me, and very funny,'' she adds. ``He
can also be intimidating. I've heard people say that about him _ he
takes what he does seriously, and expects everyone else to do that,
too.''
 &HT;    Even more intimidating for Suvari, however, was stepping into
``American Beauty's'' first table reading _ an informal rehearsal _
with director Sam Mendes.
 &HT;    ``That was scary,'' she says. ``I walked into the room and saw
Kevin, Annette, Sam Mendes and everyone else sitting there, and I
had to say, `Hello, I'm going to be working with you ... '
 &HT;    ``It made me feel I wanted to try even harder. I wanted to keep
up with these experienced actors. And every direction Sam gave me I
listened to.''
 &HT;    Like so many actresses, the Rhode Island-born Suvari began her
professional career as a model. She first posed before a camera as
a sixth-grader living in South Carolina, then visited Los Angeles
when she was cast in a Rice-a-Roni commercial.
 &HT;    ``After that my agency said, `You should move out here,' which
we did,'' Suvari says, the ``we'' referring to her parents and
three brothers. ``I did acting as kind of an afterschool hobby.''
 &HT;    When she graduated from high school in 1997, she adds, ``I
started thinking of acting as my job, and I took it very
seriously.''
 &HT;    Now she's beginning to truly enjoy the craft and all that comes
with it.
 &HT;    ``Everything fascinates me,'' Suvari says. ``I like the
challenge that's involved in playing someone else. I like meaty
roles, roles that have some texture.
 &HT;    ``It's all so new to me, meeting people, taking direction,
having people really like a film that I'm in,'' she says. ``I think
I'm very blessed to have been given what I've got so far.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``American Pie,'' consult the
official Website at www.americanpiemovie.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
