w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CATHERINE-HICKS-IN-7T     06-28 1452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHERINE-HICKS-IN-7TH-HEAVEN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HEAVEN' CAN'T WAIT: CATHERINE HICKS AND THE SURPRISE SUCCESS OF
`7TH HEAVEN' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Catherine Hicks in a scene from ``7th
Heaven.'') 
 By CHRISTOPHER LOUDON  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The booths are lined with show-biz power lunchers, sycophantic
waiters silently scurry about and the buzz of cell phones vies with
the soothing jazz wafting from hidden speakers.
</P>
<P>
   In short, it's an average Wednesday afternoon at Chasen's, the
fabled see-and-be-seen Beverly Hills eatery.
</P>
<P>
   But for 7-year-old Catie Yagher, the day is anything but
ordinary. She's here with her mom, Catherine Hicks, star of the WB
network's surprise hit, ``7th Heaven,'' which recently wrapped its
third season.
</P>
<P>
   To mark the occasion, the little brunette has been allowed a
rare treat. Waving her tiny fingers, she shows off a carefully
applied set of miniature, press-on nails.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please believe me,'' Hicks says, ``this is not normal for us.
I'm really not big on little girls being made up to look like
adults _ that whole JonBenet Ramsey sort of thing _ but I gave in
this once because this is a very special day for us.''
</P>
<P>
   And as the youngster shifts her focus to her crayons and drawing
pad, Hicks relaxes for an interview. As bright and personable as
she is beautiful, she's also surprisingly sanguine for someone
who's survived a bumpy 20-year ride in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed easy at first. Less than two weeks after graduating
from Cornell University in Ithaca, N.Y., Hicks landed a recurring
role in the ABC soap ``Ryan's Hope.'' Soon afterward she was on
Broadway, acting with Jack Lemmon in ``Tribute.''
</P>
<P>
   An outstanding performance as Marilyn Monroe in ABC's ``Marilyn:
The Untold Story'' (1980) earned her rave reviews, huge ratings and
an Emmy nomination. Good parts in good movies followed: the
enchanting actress who charms Ron Silver in ``Garbo Talks'' (1984),
Kathleen Turner's excitable best friend in ``Peggy Sue Got
Married'' (1986) and the dedicated defender of whales in ``Star
Trek IV: The Voyage Home'' (1986).
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, though, her career began to falter. Lackluster film
roles, mediocre television movies and failed series began to pile
up.
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, things had gotten critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad had died, and I'd bought this house near mine for my
mom,'' she recalls. ``One day I got a call from my business
manager, who said, `Cath, you've gone through your pension money
and everything else to pay for that house. You don't have a choice,
you're going to have to give it up.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And I remember thinking, `This can't be!' I had this feeling,
deep down inside, that something or someone would come along to
save the day.''
</P>
<P>
   That savior turned out to be Aaron Spelling. The mastermind
behind such lowbrow fare as ``Dynasty,'' ``Beverly Hills 90210''
and ``Melrose Place'' had been asked by the fledgling WB network to
produce a family drama, created by former ``Mad About You'' writer
Brenda Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   In casting the saga of a compassionate minister and his family,
he immediately thought of Hicks, who had starred in a short-lived
1994 series he'd produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aaron remembered me from when we worked together on `Winnetka
Road,''' Hicks recalls. ``He called and said, `Please do this for
me.' And even though I really needed the work, I told him that I
didn't want to play a mom. So he said, `Just read the script.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I read it,'' she says, ``and as I was going through it I
kept saying to myself, `Oh yeah, I want to say that line, and that
one, and that one too!' The quality was so evident, and so was the
humor. That's when I realized I couldn't possibly turn it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Though pleased with the part _ and the paycheck _ Hicks still
had reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid to commit to it,'' she confesses, ``because a
weekly series really owns you. It was very hard the first season.
Even though it was a much-welcomed gift, I was a little resentful
of the show. I kept thinking, `Who are all these kids? I have my
own child I want to be with, and here I am pretending to be mother
to these strangers.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I must admit that I wasn't that friendly,'' she adds, ``though
I wasn't really conscious of it. Isn't it amazing how we can all be
experts on how others should behave and yet have these giant blind
spots about our own behavior?
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyway, I'm happy to report that that's all changed,'' she
concludes. ``Now we really love each other. They all love Catie and
she loves them. She's an only child, so it's like she's found all
these wonderful stepbrothers and sisters to spend time with.''
</P>
<P>
   In its third season, ``7th Heaven'' emerged as the
fastest-rising show on network television, after spending its first
couple of years in the ratings doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God for the WB,'' Hicks says. ``If we'd been on one of
the bigger networks, we would have been yanked after three weeks.
But the folks at the WB really believed in us. We knew we weren't
going to get bounced if we didn't get big numbers right out of the
box. It's taken us over two years, but we've finally made it.''
</P>
<P>
   The secret of their success, she says, is the same thing which
initially caught her eye: good writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brenda prides herself on doing no rewriting,'' Hicks says.
``When she's done with a script, it's done. There's no interference
from Aaron or from the WB. A lot of times on network shows you end
up with this diluted junk, because there have been 15 rewrites
simply to appease executives who want to hear themselves talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``A script is a delicate puzzle,'' she adds. ``If you change or
delete one thing, you change the whole energy. Brenda knows
precisely what she wants, what stories will work, and they trust
her to deliver. As a result, every week there's something that
touches you.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Hicks' own character, Annie Camden, she admits that it
took her some time to get used to the idea of playing a housebound
mom with seven kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``All through the first season I kept thinking, `God, I'm going
to be the Donna Reed of the '90s,'' she recalls. ``I was pretty
insecure about it. I kept saying to Brenda, `Couldn't she go to
night school or something?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And then I thought about the moms at my daughter's school,
lawyers and executives at the very top of their professions who
made the choice to stay at home with their kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started thinking about them, I stopped feeling like
Annie was some sort of freak,'' she says. ``Sure, she spends a lot
of her time in the kitchen, but she's strong and she's smart, too.
And I get so much gratitude from fans. They look me right in the
eye and say, `Thank you. Thank you for what your show has done for
my family.'''
</P>
<P>
   And, speaking of families, it's time to wrap things up. Catie
has been promised a trip to her dad's office _ Hicks' husband is
special-effects designer Kevin Yagher _ and she's eager to get
going.
</P>
<P>
   But before they can depart, disaster strikes. One of Catie's
precious new nails pops off and sinks into her mom's cappuccino.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry,'' Hicks says. ``I'm sure the nice people here at
Chasen's can get it back for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick as a wink, the cup is whisked into the kitchen. Moments
later, a waiter returns to solemnly present the polished pink
treasure to his young customer. Catie squeals with delight.
</P>
<P>
   It's another happy ending. Of course.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Christopher Loudon is the editor of TV Guide Canada, based in
North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
