<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOTE-PROFILE-2000(3TAKES) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRITER HORTON FOOTE SAVORS LIFE IN HIS BOYHOOD HOME OF WHARTON,
TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHARTON, Texas _ This hamlet of 10,000 residents in the muddy
lowlands 60 miles southwest of Houston is laid out in long, thin
blocks around the Colorado River. In the center of one of these
blocks, not far from Wharton's old-fashioned town square, is a
bright, canary-yellow frame house. Living in that house is
83-year-old Horton Foote, perhaps America's most honored dramatist
and certainly, along with TV newsman Dan Rather, Wharton's most
distinguished native son.
</P>
<P>
   Foote, whose glittering resume includes two Academy Awards for
best screenplay and a Pulitzer Prize for drama, is required by
obligations in the theater business to spend some of his time in
New York. But for the past dozen years, he has returned to the
house on Wharton's North Houston Street where he grew up, the house
his grandfather built as a gift for Horton's parents in 1916.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for me to live here,'' said Foote, now 83, as he sat
in his cool, comfortable parlor. ``I also keep a place in New York
City. My son lives there, so it's not wasted when I'm here.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New York, people act a little different towards me, very
respectful. Here, they treat me just like someone they grew up
with. Not that too many people I really grew up with are still
present, but there's still the sense of just being home I don't
have anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Foote's sense of home has been prevalent in almost all his
writing. His plays in particular are inevitably set in fictional
Texas towns that mirror Wharton. The characters he creates reflect
the huge, tightly knit, colorful family who surrounded him during
his early years.
</P>
<P>
   As much as the town of Wharton is crucial to Foote's creativity,
his childhood home itself may be more so. It was at the breakfast
table or on the porch during warm summer evenings that Foote's
grandparents, parents, uncles and aunts regaled him with tales of
family history that became, decades later, the basis for plays and
telecasts and films.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Brookes-Foote House, as it's listed in the National
Directory of Historic Places, has been brought to greater
prominence by Foote's recently published ``Farewell: A Memoir of a
Texas Childhood'' (Scribner, $24). In this book, he allows readers
to join in Foote family gatherings, sharing the same stories,
heartbreak and dreams that fuel real lives as well as fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might say I've been thinking about writing this book all
my life,'' Foote said. ``I wanted to re-create this Texas childhood
of mine, but without it being an autobiography. I wanted to write
about these other wonderful people and perhaps bring back to
readers' memories some of the places, the rooms, where they once
lived.''
</P>
<P>
   Foote acknowledged that ``Farewell,'' which has received
rapturous critical reviews and probably will be short-listed for
Pulitzer Prize and National Book Award consideration, would not
have been written while some of the relatives described in it were
living.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother, for instance, would not have approved,'' he
said. ``Still, I hope I've written about the people I love with
compassion and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   He loves his house just as much. In ``Farewell,'' Foote
painstakingly details how it was built, the way light reflected
through windows on the lovingly polished floorboards. He wrote
about the trees in the back yard, and the nearby fields where he
and his friends romped before being called home to supper.
</P>
<P>
   Wharton has changed a lot since. Its sumpy surroundings have
fewer farms and more fast-food franchises. Some neighborhoods,
though not Foote's block, have the unmistakable air of genteel
decay.
</P>
<P>
   Even Foote's house isn't quite the same. It used to be painted
white. The canary-yellow color was selected by his late wife,
Lillian, a dozen years ago when the Footes decided to live there at
least part time.
</P>
<P>
   The house is inviting. Foote has decorated with sturdy, plain
New England furniture, and the walls are adorned with the stark
Puritan art associated with that region.
</P>
<P>
   Hallway walls are studded with framed movie posters (''The Trip
to Bountiful,'' ``Tender Mercies'') and an Andy Warhol minimalist
poster for ``1918'' that, Foote says, ``I liked but the producers
didn't, so it was not used.'' There are framed letters from
presidents. But taking pride of place are photographs of Foote's
children.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere, bookshelves sag with old volumes dogeared from
constant use.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sometimes read a lot, and also like to spend time just
thinking,'' Foote said. ``It took me some time to realize that
thinking was part of my work. The reading is a pleasure. Recently,
I realized I had not read Jane Austen in some time, so I'm becoming
reacquainted with her now.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Foote enjoys being in his house, he rejoices in his
huge back yard, happily pointing out a huge pecan tree, some
colorful crape myrtles, a fig tree that stubbornly refuses to bear
fruit.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   Although it would be easy enough anyway to find Foote in Wharton
_ his telephone number is listed in the city phone book _ the
canary-yellow house is a magnet for fans, who drop by at all hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come and say they just drove to Wharton on the chance
they might meet me,'' Foote said, shaking his silvery head.
``Recently, there were people from Wisconsin. That's a long way to
come on the chance I might be home. Fortunately, I was able to
visit with them. I try to be friendly when I can, though sometimes
I'm working and have to say I can't be disturbed. I'm always honest
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Constant disturbance was the main reason Foote couldn't live in
his hometown while most of his relatives were alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had no concept of writing,'' he said. ``They felt they
could interrupt me anytime, so I worked better in New York. But
that's not a problem now.''
</P>
<P>
   An unlisted phone number would also reduce the number of current
calls or visits from strangers, but Foote won't consider getting
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be very pretentious,'' he said chuckling. ``I
couldn't have that.''
</P>
<P>
   Foote's octogenarian days in his longtime home are built around
simple routine. He has a secretary who comes in at 9 in the
morning, and sometimes earlier; in the evenings, a woman cooks his
dinner. His days are still spent writing furiously, sometimes
obsessively.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when I'm writing that I stay up and work
through the night,'' Foote said, smiling shyly and sounding
confessional. ``I really do work all the time. I'm just back from
New Haven, where for two months a play of mine has been in
rehearsal. I'm working on a new play which was commissioned by a
New York theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Foote has been busy in the theater for more than 50 years.
``Farewell's'' last scene is in 1932, when Foote, then 17, leaves
Wharton to study acting in California. He later moves to New York,
where his gift for improvising dialogue in workshops leads to a
suggestion that he try his hand at script-writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote a one-act play with a part for myself, a critic came
and quite liked it, and said so,'' Foote says. ``I thought, `This
is how I'll establish myself as an actor, by writing material for
myself.' I came back here and wrote `Texas Town,' which was
produced in 1942. All of a sudden the desire to act just left me. I
wanted to write.''
</P>
<P>
   Theater critics embraced Foote's work. He made much of his
living, though, writing for the new medium of television. Perhaps
Foote's most successful effort was 1953's ``The Trip to
Bountiful,'' which he would eventually adapt for the theater, and,
three decades later, for film.
</P>
<P>
   Foote gained national prominence in 1962 when he won an Academy
Award for his screen adaptation of Harper Lee's novel ``To Kill a
Mockingbird.'' (Foote and the reclusive Lee remain close friends.)
He wrote other screenplays, including ``Baby, the Rain Must Fall,''
but during the 1970s he moved to a New Hampshire farm with his wife
and four children, and wrote very little until the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Foote re-emerged, winning his second screenplay Oscar
for ``Tender Mercies.'' He's been at full tilt ever since,
especially during his late-life Wharton homecoming, though he
paused again briefly seven years ago when his wife died. Horton
Foote and Lillian Vallish, a theater producer, were married for 48
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, you don't choose the ultimate direction of your
life,'' Foote said. ``It chooses you. I miss my wife terribly. I
always thought I would go first. We were happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you go on. This is what human beings do. I write about
people learning to do such things.''
</P>
<P>
   Foote's four grown children, two daughters and two sons, comfort
their father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm blessed with my children,'' he said. ``So many people
better than I am, better intellectually, better PEOPLE, have
difficulties with their children. I don't. So I have them, and
since my wife has been gone, the writing has been a very sustaining
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Foote sleeps in the same small bedroom he occupied as a boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That somehow seems right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   Except for the loss of his wife, the recent years have been good
to Horton Foote. He continues to write plays, and has finally
completed the nine-play ``The Orphan Cycle,'' which is based on his
father's life. In 1995, his play ``The Young Man From Atlanta'' won
the Pulitzer Prize for drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I won the Pulitzer Prize, I don't think people in Wharton
cared very much,'' Foote said grinning.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought the first Academy Award was pretty good. The
second time I got one of those they thought it was old news. And
they never seemed to care at all about the Emmys.''
</P>
<P>
   Wharton seems to care about Foote, but its residents don't make
a fuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wharton's good for me because the people here take me down to
size,'' he said. ``I think they like me generally, and would have
if I had never written a word.''
</P>
<P>
   Foote says he has no plans to slow down. There's a new play
commissioned by the New York theater; there may be a sequel to
``Farewell,'' which ends with the teen-aged Foote leaving Texas on
a bus for California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those first 17 years of my life that I wrote about were more
about the town and my family than me,'' he said. ``If I could write
a book, say, about the next 15 years of my life and somehow make it
more about the theater, I might do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his parlor, Foote tried to define his writing
philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really am fascinated by the human condition,'' he said,
pausing to sip more tap water, his soft voice sounding like
wind-blown leaves rustling on the giant pecan tree in his yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think of the things people are called on to go through
in their lives _ the losses of loved ones, frustrations with jobs,
trying hard to find ways to be happy _ I am moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I know all the faults of people, but on the whole human
beings are quite amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Foote summed up his own life succinctly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I have been blessed,'' he said. ``No life is perfect.
If I had my way, my wife would still be here. But I have my work.
And this house. It's good here.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
