<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING FOR INCOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKERE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 71 1/2 and have been retired for 10 years. My wife is
the same age. I have $150,000 in two separate IRA accounts, which
have been invested in bank CDs for the past 10 years, averaging 5
to 6 percent yields and currently in the neighborhood of 5 1/2
percent. Aside from Social Security of about $1,200 a month, we
have no other income. Can you suggest an investment where we might
earn more income, or income and growth?
</P>
<P>
   W.T., Lake Arrowhead, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The two goals you suggest are pretty much mutually exclusive.
For example, you'd have a pretty good shot at a solid dividend and
growth of your principal over the long haul if you invested in a
mutual fund that divides its portfolio between stocks and bonds and
other fixed-income investments. But to get that prospect of capital
growth, you would sacrifice yield.
</P>
<P>
   A good example of a fund in this category is Fidelity Puritan
fund, which has produced average annual total returns of 13.58
percent over the past decade. But since more than half of the
portfolio is invested in stocks, it would bring you a yield of only
3.1 percent, or $3,600 a year less than you're getting from the
bank.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, such a fund would represent a significant level of
risk, especially when compared with government-insured CDs. It's
true that you could invest in such a fund and gamble that it is
likely to average total returns in excess of 8 percent over the
long haul, and that you could therefore withdraw that 8 percent
annually, effectively drawing down both the fund's yield and some
of the anticipated gains in principal.
</P>
<P>
   Such a strategy would net you $3,750 a year in additional income
when compared to the CDs, but it's also fraught with danger.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose your fund encountered a sour market right at the outset,
with the fund losing 5 percent in each of the first two years; the
effect is that entering the third year your principal would be down
to $112,509, and you would henceforth require annual returns of
11.2 percent just to support the sequence of withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   This all may seem like a pretty gloomy approach to take, but
historically the stock market has delivered jolts of this sort to
overambitious investors many times.
</P>
<P>
   So a better approach would be to consider a straight
fixed-income portfolio, where your goal is to get a solid income
stream and to retain your principal, but without any prospect of
serious growth.
</P>
<P>
   For retirees I usually suggest a three-part portfolio,
representing the conservative, center, and higher-risk end of the
bond markets.
</P>
<P>
   If you used the Vanguard family of funds, for example, you might
start with 25 percent of your money in the Vanguard Short-Term
Corporate Bond fund, currently yielding 6.33 percent, then
establish a central position with 50 percent in Vanguard GNMA,
currently yielding 6.66 percent, and finishing with Vanguard
High-Yield Bond fund, which now yields 8.91 percent. Such a
portfolio would bring you a yield of $10,665 at current rates.
</P>
<P>
   Just as with the balanced fund, for that extra $2,415 a year in
income you will be facing a higher risk level than with the bank,
but if you look at these funds carefully you'll see that over the
very long term with such there is much shuffling up and down and
very little change.
</P>
<P>
   There also is a middle ground that you might explore. This would
be to put about $120,000 of your savings into a fixed-income
portfolio such as I proposed _ enough to give you the same income
stream that you now enjoy with the CDS. The other $30,000 could
then be invested in a fund such as Fidelity Puritan, which ought to
deliver solid principal growth over the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are both 29 and are homeowners. We are making
extra mortgage payments every year to get our house paid off early.
We would like to retire comfortably at the age of 50. My wife
participates in her company's 401(k) plan, with her contributions
and the employer matches amounting to $700 a month. It is 60
percent invested in Fidelity Contrafund and the rest in one of the
Fidelity Equity-Income funds. I am self-employed and add $100 a
month to a SEP-IRA invested in Vanguard Growth and Income. I also
save $400 a month in taxable accounts invested in Vanguard Growth
and Income and Vanguard Index Growth. The taxable accounts are
designed to provide us with liquid funds to use until we reach age
59 1/2 and can tap into the tax-deferred savings without penalty.
We have been saving for about two years now, and have $60,000 in
these accounts. I also have 450 shares of Disney and 150 shares of
PepsiCo. Are we on the right track for retirement at age 50?
</P>
<P>
   M.R., Aliso Viejo, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You've set yourselves a pretty tough goal. While all of your
investments (including the two common stock positions) would grow
to $1,543,416 over 21 years, presuming continued contributions at
current levels and 10 percent average annual returns from the
portfolio, the number's not quite so impressive when we factor it
for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Presuming average annual inflation at 3.5 percent for the next
21 years, that impressive sum would have the buying power of only
about $750,000 in today's money. If you invested all of the
retirement pool on the fixed-income side, it would provide you with
an income stream equivalent to about $48,000 in today's dollars _
less than your wife alone is now earning.
</P>
<P>
   And it gets worse. When you retire early, you not only have to
anticipate your income-stream needs but also establish a sizable
pool of money that can be left in the stock markets for growth, to
offset inflation during the later years of your retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier you retire, the more you will need to have in that
inflation-buffer account. Retiring at age 50, you might want as
much saved to protect you against inflation as you will need for
current income. So if you are following that thinking, what you'd
end up with is the equivalent of about $24,000 in current dollars,
which is hardly what most people would consider a comfortable
retirement income.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, some mitigating factors. If your wife
continues to save as a percentage of her earnings, every time she
gets a raise the contributions, and thus the expected accumulation,
will grow larger.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, if you increase savings as your business prospers,
there will be further growth there as well. Nonetheless, you'll
have to decide for yourself what a comfortable level of income in
retirement will be, and then, using the inflation percentages I
have supplied, calculate how much more you will need to save to
reach your target.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I understand that there is a Massachusetts mutual fund that
is both federal and state tax-free. Can you give me the name and
address of the fund?
</P>
<P>
   N.D., Winchester, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. According to Lipper Analytical Services Inc., there are 79
mutual funds that invest in securities that are free of both
Massachusetts and federal taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Of these, 11 are tax-free money market funds, 10 invest in
intermediate term municipal bonds, and the remaining 58 hold
general tax-free portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   The largest fund in each category, respectively, is Fidelity
Massachusetts Municipal Money Market, Boston 1784 Massachusetts
Tax-Exempt Income (an intermediate term fund), and Fidelity Spartan
Massachusetts Municipal fund.
</P>
<P>
   Call 800-544-8888 to reach Fidelity, or 800-BKB-1784 to reach
the 1784 group, which is managed by BankBoston. Or you could tap
the resources of a good public library and root through the other
76 funds in the category.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
