<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1985 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS &LR;      06-28 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURE-ALL GIVES RUSSIAN MAFIA A LEASE ON LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The gangland boss had a problem. He had more money than
he ever dreamed he would earn, an extravagant lifestyle and the
power and influence he needed to keep it that way.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly, life had lost its meaning. Being a mafia chieftain
just wasn't fun anymore. So he went to see a shrink. . . .
</P>
<P>
   You think you've seen this movie? Well, analyze this: The scene
was Moscow, not New York; the mobster was the leader of one of
Russia's most feared crime gangs, not Robert De Niro; the
specialist he went to for help was Aron Belkin, psychoanalyst to
Russia's rich and infamous.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the wisecracking psychiatrist played by Billy Crystal in
``Analyze This,'' Belkin was not taken aback by his encounter with
a fearsome crime lord suffering from fits of self-doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Belkin has been analyzing that since the dawn of post-Communist
Russia's free-for-all market economy in 1992. Many of his clients
got rich quickly through illicit means. Plenty of them have been
violent, dangerous characters. But not in Belkin's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the doctor, my patients have to be afraid of me,'' said
Belkin, a timid-looking man with a tiny, raspy voice. ``I'm the
doctor, they have to respect me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not only do they respect him; they have spread the word.
Although he does not advertise, Russian biznesmeny have flocked to
Belkin's slightly dilapidated central Moscow office. Over the
years, Belkin has developed a theory _ and a cure _ for what ails
so many of his patients. He calls it ``money sickness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They had no idea what money was until the late 1980s,'' Belkin
said recently. ``Then suddenly, they became rich. Not just rich,
but they were getting money not only quickly, but easily. Suddenly
they were surrounded by diamonds and gold, and many of them could
not handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Their euphoria is soon replaced by fear of an early, violent
death, not unfounded given the high rate of contract killings among
Russian businessmen. ``The typical patient starts trying to get
money all kinds of illegal ways and then spend it in just as crazy
ways,'' Belkin said. ``His brain demands forbidden and extravagant
risks, whatever allows him to remove the alarm, to forget about his
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   And the cure?
</P>
<P>
   ``The best treatment is to stop making money,'' Belkin said.
``We talk about what bothers them, and why. My advice is usually to
get out of business and go straight.''
</P>
<P>
   The mafia chieftain, for example, quit his ``job'' and went to
graduate school. Now he runs a legitimate business and lives
without fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works,'' Belkin said. ``That's why they come to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But why don't they bust open his head when he tells them to stop
earning money? Belkin replies, ``I tell them to stop earning. They
get to keep what they already have.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If none of these problems existed in Soviet society, neither did
the cure. Until the late 1980s, psychoanalysis was officially
banned as a science too individualistic for Soviet collectivist
ideology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Soviet Man did not need to be fixed,'' said Moscow
psychiatrist Dmitry Kraisner. ``He needed to be imitated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Psychiatric care,'' in Soviet practice, was often confused
with mental illness _ a misconception that survives to this day.
Soviet psychiatry also acquired a sinister function _ locking up
dissidents in mental hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   But the regime was unable to stop the study and practice of
psychoanalysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, I was an underground psychiatrist,'' Belkin said.
Belkin also wrote numerous works on psychology, which he has since
published.
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed. Moscow has seen a small boom in psychiatric
care, which is gradually becoming more accepted _ and more desired
_ among wealthier, worldlier Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Belkin turns away more patients than he accepts, letting his
competitors pick up the extra business. Unlike some of his
patients, Belkin has not let the chance to make money change his
lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like writing books,'' he said. ``I'm happy with what I
have.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Filipov is the Globe's Moscow bureau chief.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
