<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GYPSIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO'S GYPSIES: USED BY SERBS, HATED BY ALBANIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRIZREN, Yugoslavia _ Every morning, the Gypsy grave digger made
his rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Driving a garbage truck through this town's ravaged streets,
Jevded Mazreco would go about the gruesome task of collecting
bodies of people slaughtered by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   Mazreco says he buried more than 300 murdered ethnic Albanians
during Serbia's methodical three-month campaign of ethnic
cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would bury 15 here and 12 there,'' he said. ``They made us
do this. It was either dig the graves, or die.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gypsies of Kosovo, or Rom, as they call themselves, said
they were forced laborers for the Yugoslav Army, police, and
paramilitary units that rampaged through Kosovo. Now the Gypsies
are labeled collaborators by the Kosovo Liberation Army and have
become the focus of brutal revenge by KLA troops and returning
ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   With Serbian forces withdrawn and many Serb civilians fleeing,
the Gypsies are the ones left behind to blame. Hundreds of Gypsies
who tried to escape to Serbia were sent back to Kosovo by Serb
border officials. It seems once again Europe's Gypsies are caught
in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   It is the history of the Rom. In this conflict, and in wars and
campaigns of terror over the centuries, Gypsies have been forced to
choose sides to live. In this war as in many others, the Gypsies
have chosen the wrong one. But their role may also hold a key to
their survival.
</P>
<P>
   They know where the bodies are buried.
</P>
<P>
   Mazreco pulled hard on a hand-rolled cigarette as he pointed to
several large mounds of earth on the fringes of a Muslim cemetery
and said, ``I buried an entire family there, at least 12 people.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators for the International Criminal Tribunal for the
former Yugoslavia, located in the Hague, which is seeking to
collect evidence to support the indictment of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and others, have interviewed Mazreco at length.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know what it was like to pick up the bodies of children
and whole families?'' he asked. ``Do you think anyone would do this
if they were not forced to?''
</P>
<P>
   The father of six children said he mostly hides in his home now,
fearing that he will be labeled a collaborator and killed. He
insisted he was never paid for his grisly labor.
</P>
<P>
   He was simply told where to collect the bodies by the head of
the Prizren Public Works Department, Jova Vanovic, and the local
head of the feared Ministry of Interior Police, Petrovic Jakovic,
he says.
</P>
<P>
   This, investigators said, is an example of how Gypsies could
provide crucial insight to not just the location of mass graves,
but an understanding of the Serbian chain of command in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Before the war, Mazreco, 45, had worked for several years as a
laborer in the Public Works Department. He mostly collected garbage
and occasionally dug graves.
</P>
<P>
   Then Mazreco was paid $20 a month for his work. But during the
war, he said, he was not given a paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Works offical ``Vanovic told me my payment was that I
would not be killed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During the weeks of slaughter and the nights of heavy NATO air
raids, Mazreco said, he would hear the Serbian officials gathering
at the Public Works Department garage joking about the use of a
garbage truck to dispose of the ethnic Albanian victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried when I saw those poor people who had been killed,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But ethnic Albanians do not buy the tears.
</P>
<P>
   Nejar Betuca, 50, an ethnic Albanian refugee who had just
returned from living three months in a refugee camp to find his
home burned and looted, burst his way into the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are just as responsible as the Serbs. They are
collaborators,'' he said, pointing a finger at Mazreco and three
other Gypsies standing in the Public Works Department lot filled
with broken tractors, smashed cars, and old trucks. Betuca was
there looking for his stolen car.
</P>
<P>
   ``They guided the paramilitaries to our homes to kill us and
then they stole everything we owned,'' said Betuca, being held back
from the Gypsies by a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Many ethnic Albanians haven't held back in attacking Gypsies.
</P>
<P>
   Five Gypsies were found killed in a field last week in the
village of Obilic by NATO forces who theorized that they had been
branded collaborators.
</P>
<P>
   On June 18, German NATO troops found 25 KLA fighters who had
taken 15 elderly Gypsies to the Interior Ministry building in
Prizren for allegedly looting the homes of ethnic Albanians. One
Gypsy was found dead with his hands chained to a chair. The others,
most of whom were chained to radiators, said they were beaten and
told they would be executed before the peacekeeping troops raided
the building and disarmed the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the reigns of conquering empires, from the Ottomans
to the Hapsburgs to the Nazis, the Gypsies have been persecuted and
forced to keep moving in a diaspora that stretches from Russia to
Spain to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A 1991 Yugoslav census puts the number of Rom in Kosovo at
35,000 out of a total of 1.4 million. As in other European
countries, they live on the margins of society, cobbling an
existence out of day labor and street peddling. They are a closed
society with a deep mistrust of the ``gadge,'' or ``outsiders,'' as
they refer to all non-Gypsies.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Gypsies move quickly out of war zones. During the
Bosnian war, most Bosnian Gypsies moved into Serbia; their caravans
lined the Danube River. But the NATO airstrikes knocked out bridges
and trapped many inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In a ramshackle Gypsy village near Obelic, Fehmi Haliti, 46,
fearfully peered through a crack in a door newly reinforced with
corrugated tin before finally coming outside with a friend who held
a shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   He is a local leader of the Rom community and explained that the
Gypsies of Kosovo have two divided cultures, one speaks Albanian
and one Serbian. The chiefs of these two different Gypsy clans were
represented at the peace talks in Rambouillet before the
negotiations collapsed and led to war.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the story of the Rom. We have always had to survive in
the middle of conflict. We will survive again, and we will move on
when we can. But now people are just trying to stay alive,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrating how the Gypsies exist within conflict, the grave
digger Mazreco was busy last Thursday burying the body of an
80-year-old Serb man who died of an apparent heart attack when KLA
soldiers kicked in the door of his home.
</P>
<P>
   A UN official who arranged the funeral said the Gypsies were the
only ones they could find to dig a grave for a Serb.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
