<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-PINCH-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITALS TAKING A HIT FROM MEDICARE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX AND AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON -- For a midsummer Friday night at Boston Medical
Center's emergency room, the city's busiest, it's unusually quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Still, chief resident Peter Weimersheimer ministers to 30
patients during his nine-hour shift _ crash victims, cases of hand
trauma, pneumonia sufferers, patients in psychiatric crisis, and
end-stage alcoholics, such as a 45-year-old vodka addict who says
he's been vomiting ``cups'' of blood but resists being admitted for
a complete workup until Weimersheimer explains that he is
``probably going to die'' if he doesn't stay.
</P>
<P>
   For his labors, Weimersheimer earns $15 an hour, about half what
he used to get as a carpenter and $5.37 short of a third-year
Boston Medical Center nurse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little dismayed at all the talk about cutting residents
when we're such a cheap source of labor for hospitals,''
Weimersheimer says. ``There's no way they could hire enough
attending physicians to replace us.''
</P>
<P>
   Cutting residents? It's hard to imagine at a time when Boston's
teaching hospitals are often full to the gunnels and nearly all of
them routinely have trouble finding a bed for one more patient.
</P>
<P>
   But these are no ordinary times. The outlook at the nation's
premier hospitals _ those, like Boston Medical Center and a dozen
others in the Boston area that train doctors and deal with
difficult cases _ is the darkest in memory, with no clear way back
to the light.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no plan to lay off interns and residents, who
have hospital commitments to complete three- and four-year training
programs, leaders of academic medicine expect to pare training
slots in the future. But other hospital jobs are in jeopardy as
teaching hospitals struggle to maintain what they call their unique
mission to train the next generations of physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Brigham and Women's Hospital and Massachusetts General are
eliminating a total of 240 jobs to stem a joint operating loss of
$14.1 million for the first half of this year. That's a little more
than a third of the $39 million operating loss suffered by their
parent, Partners HealthCare, New England's largest hospital system.
(With investment income and other revenue, the system saw a net
profit of $2.4 million, compared to $30.4 million a year ago.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working our butts off and still losing money,'' said Dr.
Laurence Ronan, a staff doctor at Massachusetts General. ``We can't
continue to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Across town at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, things are
even shakier. The institution has lost $38 million on operations so
far this year, and BI Deaconess is a much smaller operation than
Partners. ``We're scrambling behind the scenes to protect our
medical training programs,'' said Dr. Steven Weinberger, the
hospital's director of medical education.
</P>
<P>
   In Worcester, UMass Memorial Health Care has closed programs and
cut staff to trim $60 million in annual costs, and are still losing
money so far this year. To break even next year, officials say they
need to slash $70 million more.
</P>
<P>
   Can there be any doubt that hospitals are in trouble, especially
the teaching hospitals that are the undisputed crown jewels of US
health care?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there are plenty of doubts, especially in Washington,
where the leaders of Boston health care are pinning their hopes for
a congressional reprieve from their fiscal difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics don't doubt that hospitals are losing money. But they
do question why, how bad it will get, and whether it's the federal
government's responsibility to do anything about it. And it's not
just fiscally conservative Republicans raising the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bar is high, and we're not going to just go and give money
away because people say they're experiencing hardship,'' said
Daniel Mendelson, the senior health policy official in the White
House budget office. Despite the hospitals' complaints, ``we don't
see the systemic evidence that one might like to see before doing
something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, President Clinton seems ready to support an idea that
would make the hospitals' hunt for money even harder. He is
expected to propose giving Medicare beneficiaries broad new
coverage for prescription drugs, a potentially costly idea that,
whatever its social merits, might siphon funds that could otherwise
go to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Congress agrees to boost health care spending overall,
Clinton's proposal ``would be very damaging'' to hospitals, said
Senator John F. Kerry of Massachusetts. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dilemma has roots in act of Congress &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals didn't arrive at their current dilemma overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Industry leaders blame their troubles on an act of Congress, the
Balanced Budget Act of 1997, which imposed the deepest cuts on
Medicare in the federal program's 35-year history. But there is
broad consensus among industry analysts that the hospitals' current
state resulted from forces set in motion early in this decade. The
problem is a complicated amalgam of:
</P>
<P>
   --Inadvertent Medicare overpayments, especially for inpatient
care;
</P>
<P>
   --The 1994 collapse of the Clinton health reform plan, which
many view as a lost opportunity to rationalize funding of teaching
hospitals' social missions;
</P>
<P>
   --A post-1994 unleashing of market forces in health care that
permitted managed care plans to extract deep discounts from
hospitals desperate to keep patients flowing their way.
</P>
<P>
   It took awhile for the drift to become clear to hospitals, some
observers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between 1994 and 1997, things were looking pretty damn good
for teaching hospitals, and their Medicare profit margins were
especially good,'' said Dr. David Altman of the Lewin Group, a
health care consulting firm. ``There were some Cassandras saying
the sky was going to fall, but not everybody was listening during a
boom period.''
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, the Medicare overpayments seem especially striking
_ and unlikely to continue indefinitely at a time when bankruptcy
was forecast by 2008 for Medicare's Part A trust fund, which pays
for hospital care.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of this decade, US teaching hospitals were
making $7 in ``profit'' for every $100 it cost them to provide
inpatient care to a Medicare patient, according to a recent
analysis by Stuart Guterman of the Urban Institute, a
Washington-based think tank. By contrast, community hospitals were
losing almost an equal amount on each Medicare patient in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   By 1997, Medicare profit margins for inpatient care at teaching
hospitals had ballooned to 28.4 percent, and nonteaching hospitals
were making a 12.4 percent profit.
</P>
<P>
   The largesse stemmed from formulas built into federal law that
automatically update Medicare hospital payments to keep pace with
inflation. But hospital costs flattened in the 1990s, instead of
climbing steadily as the formulas assumed they would. ``Medicare
was a missile just cruising along with no controls,'' observed Dr.
Thomas O'Donnell, chief executive of New England Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals point out that they lost money on Medicare outpatient
care. Outpatient margins dropped to a negative 12 percent in 1996,
and fell further to nearly twice that in 1998, according to the
American Hospital Association. But hospitals' total margins
remained in the black throughout the first seven years of the
decade, according to Guterman's analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare overpayment on the inpatient side handed hospitals a
timely opportunity in the 1990s, although hospital executives don't
like to admit it. It allowed them to bid low for all-important
contracts with managed care plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to hold onto market share they've cut very low-priced
deals with managed-care companies,'' said Stuart Altman, a Brandeis
University professor who served on a congressional Medicare reform
commission. This implicit Medicare subsidy of private insurers is
``an unfair and unsustainable situation.''
</P>
<P>
   To the extent that hospitals have been caring for privately
insured patients at less than their actual costs, that has left
them especially vulnerable to erosion in Medicare payments. ``They
knew that Medicare was paying above costs, and you can say, `well,
they should have been prepared for this,' '' said Katharine London,
chief of policy development at the Massachusetts Division of Health
Care Finance and Policy. ``But they're in a very competitive
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Stuart Altman: ``I've been saying (to managed-care
executives) for some time that the only way they have been able to
squeeze down hospital payments is that hospitals have been filling
their pockets from Medicare. Will they be as successful if Medicare
cuts back?'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Balanced budget a blow to teaching hospitals &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Medicare has cut back _ with a vengeance, some would say.
</P>
<P>
   As the name implies, Congress intended the Balanced Budget Act
of 1997 to balance the federal budget. With considerable help from
a booming economy, it did _ four years ahead of schedule, and with
spending cuts mostly derived from Medicare. Moreover, the law has
helped to postpone the day when Medicare's hospital trust fund will
run out of money to 2015, buying time for more systematic reform.
Or perhaps buying time to do nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching hospitals are disproportionately affected by the BBA
because their older, sicker caseload makes them far more dependent
on Medicare than other hospitals. Medicare accounts for at least
half of a typical teaching hospital's inpatient revenues. In
addition, teaching hospitals are apt to have more Medicaid and
uninsured patients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1990 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOSPITAL-PINCH-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     06-28 1473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-PINCH-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... uninsured patients.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The upshot is that revenue from treating privately insured
patients provides much less of a financial cushion for teaching
hospitals when Medicare cuts its payments.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the BBA decreed a 29 percent reduction between 1998
and 2002 in Medicare payments for ``indirect medication
education.'' These funds are intended to cover Medicare's share of
the special costs of being a teaching hospital _ not interns' and
residents' salaries, which come out of a separate fund, but the
amorphous expenses associated with having sicker patients, more
technology, and trainees involved in patient care.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Medicare payments, these so-called IME funds had also
risen sharply in the 1990s, from $2.5 billion in 1990 to $4.6
billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   When it was passed, the BBA was expected to cut Medicare
spending by $115 billion over what it would otherwise have been.
But in the first year and a half of the new regime, the slowdown in
Medicare spending ``was greater than expected,'' Gail Wilensky,
chairwoman of the Medicare Payment Advisory Commission told the
Senate Finance Committee this month.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the way the law is phased in, the deepest cuts have
not yet occurred. By hospital industry estimates, the BBA will cut
as much as $220 billion from Medicare spending between 1998 and
2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress overshot the mark by almost double,'' said Thomas A.
Scully, chief executive of the Federation of American Health
Systems, whose members include for-profit hospitals. ``Congress did
not vote for $220 billion. Congress didn't intend that.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Congress could never have foreseen some of the reasons
why Medicare is spending so much less than expected. A good deal of
it, analysts said, is due to more scrupulous billing by hospitals _
an apparent reaction to the Clinton administration's campaign
against fraudulent billing and ``upcoding,'' in which providers
jack up reimbursement by billing for a more severe illness than
patients actually have. In this light, Medicare hospital payments
are now more in line with the true cost of serving patients.
</P>
<P>
   Taken by themselves, the 1997 Medicare changes will cut total
profit margins of hospitals by two percentage points by 2002, from
6.7 percent _ the highest point in 17 years _ to a relatively
healthy 4.7 percent, according to Guterman, who spent a decade as
deputy director of the federal agency that advises Congress on
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   However, if managed-care insurers continue to wring payment
concessions out of hospitals at recent rates, total hospital profit
margins could fall to 1.5 percent by 2002. Guterman called that ``a
very low margin that would pressure a considerable number of
hospitals.'' But, he pointed out, ``It looks like Medicare by
itself isn't a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   This analysis is gaining currency in Washington, adding to the
hospitals' burden as they lobby for a rollback _ or at least a
``pause'' _ in the BBA's Medicare cuts.
</P>
<P>
   When a delegation of Boston hospital executives visited the
capital recently, they got a reality check from Donna Shalala, the
US secretary of health and human services. ``Shalala's attitude
was: `The reason you guys are having trouble is that you negotiated
bad deals with HMOs, gave them too many discounts, and Medicare is
making up the difference,' '' said New England Medical Center's
O'Donnell, who was in the group.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Representative Peter Stark of California, the senior
Democrat on the Medicare subcommittee in the House, suggests that
hospitals look to private insurers, not Medicare, for more money.
Stark recently asked government auditors to investigate the source
of hospitals' financial woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, are Medicare fee-for-service payments
becoming just another way that we funnel money to the nation's HMOs
to ensure their profits?'' Stark wrote to the General Accounting
Office.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such doubts, some on Capitol Hill think hospitals have a
shot at wringing limited relief out of Congress this year. To that
end, the American Hospital Association is waging what its policy
chief, Carmela Coyle, calls the largest lobbying campaign in
memory. Senators from states with large clusters of teaching
hospitals are on board, including Kerry and Edward M. Kennedy,
Republican Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania, and Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, Democrat of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a good chance we'll get a bill this year that will put
some money back into Indirect Medical Education,'' said one senate
staffer. ``The academic medical centers have got themselves
organized in a way I've not seen in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if they succeed in this stopgap effort, the Mass.
Generals and Beth Israels and Mt. Sinais know they need to win a
much bigger debate if their teaching mission is to be secured in a
market-driven world. They need reliable support, on a broader base
than Medicare, for the costs of training the physicians of the
future. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Apprenticeship comes with a high price tag &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We all need good doctors and, therefore, everybody ought to
pay to train them,'' said Dr. David Blumenthal, director of MGH's
Institute of Health Policy. ``But we also need good lawyers, good
engineers, and good plumbers, and we don't have a public program to
train them.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference, Blumenthal argues, is consumer protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We allow lawyers to practice law immediately out of law
school, but we don't allow doctors to do that,'' he noted. ``We
require doctors to have minimum amounts of real-world experience.
Somebody has to pay for that apprenticeship.''
</P>
<P>
   Medical students pay tuition _ lots of it. (Weimersheimer, the
Boston Medical Center resident, is carrying $160,000 in medical
school debt.) After graduation, the newly minted physicians
subsidize the cost of their obligatory apprenticeship by taking
hospital training posts that pay $15 an hour _ or less _ for
60-hour workweeks _ or more.
</P>
<P>
   Still, anyone who doubts the cost of residency training should
follow Team D on its morning rounds on MGH's Bigelow Building
medical wards.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Yiming Zhao, a second-year resident, launches the morning
routine at 8:15, accompanied by a half-dozen white-coated medical
students, interns, and residents. Meticulously reviewing each
patient's situation, they troop in and out of 17 rooms,
interviewing, poking, prodding, and consulting with each other on
the medical puzzles they encounter.
</P>
<P>
   At 10:25, Team D gathers over crullers and coffee in a
windowless conference room with two ``attendings,'' senior staff
physicians who go over each case, consider the possibilities, offer
advice. Then they all head off for more bedside consultations.
</P>
<P>
   It results in some of the best care anywhere, as well as
rigorous training, but no time-and-motion expert would call it the
most efficient way to take care of patients.
</P>
<P>
   Even less cost-effective _ but increasingly important in the
training of tomorrow's doctors _ is the clinical training that Dr.
Jeffrey Schnipper is just completing. After each patient interview,
Schnipper consults with his supervisor, Dr. John D. Goodson, and
the two of them then interview the patient together. From the way
his patients react to Schnipper's news that he is moving on to a
different training phase this month, it's clear they value the time
and attention they've had from the 28-year-old resident.
</P>
<P>
   But the examining room Schnipper occupies for the afternoon
could be more profitably used by a senior doctor who could see more
patients and bill for each encounter. Neither Medicare nor any
other agency _ and certainly not private insurers _ explicitly pay
for outpatient training. And practicing doctors are feeling so
pressured to see more patients in less time that it's hard to
recruit them for proctoring duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to move to a new system in which graduate medical
education is explicitly recognized and funded by all payers,''
Goodson says. ``It really is for the greater good.''
</P>
<P>
   There's widespread agreement that a better way is needed, but no
consensus on what it might be. All concur that the teaching
hospitals' ultimate goal _ a so-called all-payer system in which
private and government payers contribute a small tax to support
physician training _ will be an uphill political battle. That fight
won't even begin until after the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, teaching hospitals will have to find their own ways
to sustain the academic enterprise while they compete for patients
and haggle with private insurers for higher payment rates. Somehow
they will, because anything else is unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teaching is how we maintain our preeminence in the world,''
said MGH's Laurence Ronan. ``If we dismantle this system, it will
take 30 or 40 years to put it back together again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
