<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1991 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-TENNIS-BOS &LR;      06-28 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-TENNIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ANSWER TO THE TENNIS CALL CONTROVERSY? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've ever seen a John McEnroe or Venus Williams temper
tantrum on the tennis court, you know that the accuracy of umpires'
line calls is often a controversial topic in professional tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Have a little sympathy for the umpires: Judging whether a 2
5/8-inch felt ball moving up to 110 m.p.h. made a thousandth of a
second's worth of contact with a two-inch stripe on the ground has
to be one of life's more difficult challenges.
</P>
<P>
   For years, inventors have been working on systems that would
automate the process, and some are in use in major tournaments.
Earlier this month, a small, five-year-old Sudbury, Mass. company
that has done sonar work for the US Navy won a patent for its own
system that it thinks could be much less expensive and more
reliable than others on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph R. Fisher, president of Signal Processing Systems, and
colleagues William C. Booth of Stow, Mass. and Francis E. McInnis
of Marlborough, Mass. won patent 5,908,361 for an ``automated
tennis line calling system.''
</P>
<P>
   One key innovation in Fisher's system is that it combines
wafer-thin coaxial wire sensors in the tape that marks the playing
area with a system of microphones mounted around the court. A
computer evaluates the unique sound characteristic of a ball
hitting the ground to determine where the ball bounced. That helps
filter out false sensor readings from the impacts of players' feet
or racquets.
</P>
<P>
   The system also includes sensors that reveal whether a ball hit
the top of the net _ a ``let'' that requires the server to serve
again _ and it can be used to chart where serves and shots landed
as an aid to trainers and sportscasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linesmen do a remarkably good job, but basically, they're
trying to do something that can't humanly be done,'' Fisher said of
the challenge to consistently judge whether a shot was in or out.
With the huge prizes offered in major tournaments, ``There's a lot
of money at stake potentially'' in getting calls right.
</P>
<P>
   One existing system, called Cyclops, uses light beams projected
along the back of the service box to judge whether serves were in
or out. Major tournaments including the US Open, Wimbledon and the
Australian and Italian national tournaments use it as a complement
to human officials.
</P>
<P>
   However, to avoid being set off by a player's foot, Cyclops must
be immediately turned off after each serve. And the cost of leasing
it typically runs to $20,000 per court for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Fisher is optimistic that once he gets enough
investors to help fund mass-manufacturing of his system, it could
be purchased outright for the same $20,000, declining to as little
as $3,000 a court once it could be produced in volume. And it could
reduce the expense of hiring and training as many as 11 officials
watching lines around the court in pro matches.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher's company has installed prototypes for testing at the
Longwood Cricket Club in Chestnut Hill, Mass. and at Cape Cod
Academy in Osterville, Mass., and had US Tennis Association judges
up to the Cape two years ago to run tests. The only visible
difference is a small electronics box the size of a hardback book
mounted on the net post, plus tiny microphones in the fence.
</P>
<P>
   The USTA director of officials, Rich Kaufman, said he found
Fisher's system interesting, but cautioned: ``There have been
probably 6 to 8 major attempts to make a system like this, and most
of these systems have failed miserably.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so much in its infancy, and they've come across so many
problems, that we're still pretty far away from getting to a
situation where we would then have the discussion of,
philosophically, do we think we should replace human beings with
machines?'' Kaufman said.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher acknowledges that ``not everybody thinks it would be good
for the game of tennis to have a computer call the lines.'' But he
thinks skeptics can be won over or persuaded to use it to
complement human eyes. Ultimately, he thinks, a big market might be
at tennis clubs where casual players might prefer trusting a
machine rather than their opponent's honor when it comes to
deciding whether their shot was in or out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
