<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1993 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-GUNS-BOS &LR;      06-28 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCUMENTARY TAKES ON A LOADED TOPIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
INVESTIGATIVE REPORTS: GUNS IN AMERICA 
Anchored by: Bill Kurtis 
On: A &AMP; E 
Time: Monday through Friday, 9 p.m. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By late April, Bill Kurtis and four producers on A &AMP; E's
``Investigative Reports'' were wrapping up a year of work on an
ambitious, weeklong documentary series on the gun culture in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Then fresh proof of that culture's pervasiveness erupted at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo. When the shooting
stopped, 15 lay dead, the national gun debate had been rekindled,
and Kurtis and company had some editing to do.
</P>
<P>
   But while the shadow of Columbine lies across ``Guns in
America,'' and while the terrible toll of gun violence is a major
theme, the series does not begin on an anti-gun note, and
throughout strains for evenhandedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to really give the gun owners their day in court,''
Kurtis said in a phone interview from Chicago, where
``Investigative Reports'' is produced. ``They feel under siege by
the government and the media. We wanted to really understand why
they love their guns so much, and why it's such a part of
America.''
</P>
<P>
   There is now a ``great divide'' on the gun issue, according to
Kurtis, with the National Rifle Association on one side and
middle-class soccer moms on the other. The split is in part
geographical, he said, with pro-gun passions highest in the West
and in rural areas, and antipathy toward guns strongest in cities
and suburbs. In rural communities, said Kurtis, ``people feel the
gun is their constitutional right, while in urban areas, people say
`This is so unreasonable and insane; how could these people be
feeling this in the face of Columbine?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Kurtis said it became clear from interviews with NRA members
that the hardline anti-gun-control position espoused by NRA
leadership does not fully reflect the views of the membership.
``They don't feel as strongly as the leadership does about holding
the line; the guys down the line would be willing to help solve the
problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with ``Guns in America,'' the 9 p.m. time slot on A &AMP; E
will be occupied from now on by documentaries under the
``Investigative Reports'' banner. A &AMP; E executives clearly hope the
documentaries will firm up the channel's identity. Within an
increasingly crowded cable universe, the 15-year-old A &AMP; E faces
the challenge of establishing a niche broader than simply the home
of ``Biography.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kurtis, the anchor and executive producer of ``Investigative
Reports,'' the task of filling five prime-time hours per week is a
mixed blessing. ``It's every journalist's dream to choose your own
stories and spend as long as you want on them,'' he said. ``On the
other hand, it uses up every spare second I have.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A prescient choice &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the ``Investigative Reports'' team began considering topics
for its kickoff series a year ago, Kurtis said, ``we thought of
drugs and education and things like that, but chose guns, figuring
that somewhere along the line something would come up and make it
newsworthy. And then, of course, Columbine hit.''
</P>
<P>
   With memories of the carnage so vivid, the Columbine context may
color some viewers' response to the gun enthusiasists depicted in
Part 1.
</P>
<P>
   Ranging from Texas to Nevada to Michigan, ``Guns in America''
explores the tradition of gun use for hunting and sport (and
refrains from mocking even those gun aficionados who appear
on-screen in pseudo-cowboy Wild West garb). ``Guns in America''
lends a sympathetic ear to those who argue that guns are sometimes
necessary for self-defense, especially for women.
</P>
<P>
   The fervor of some gun owners is exemplified by a woman who
continues to own the very gun factory where her 21-year-old son was
killed in an accident. She blames his death not on guns but on his
failure to follow safety precautions.
</P>
<P>
   But there are cooler heads making cogent pro-gun arguments in
``Guns in America,'' such as University of Chicago professor John
Lott. He notes that guns are used defensively 2 million times a
year in the United States, and describes how his attitude toward
guns changed when his research found that states with ``right to
carry'' firearms laws have lower rates of violent crime than other
states.
</P>
<P>
   Those security arguments are balanced by the Wednesday
installment, which takes viewers inside Chicago's Cook County
Hospital emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the statistics _ 22,000 gun deaths in the United States
last year, one person shot every two minutes _ acquire a human
face. Teenagers, their bodies torn by bullets, writhe in agony on
blood-soaked sheets _ and they're the lucky ones who lived.
</P>
<P>
   Three women, close friends, wrenchingly describe the pain of
losing sons to handgun violence within two years of one another.
What is so chilling is how casually their sons' killers pulled the
triggers, how easy guns make it to kill.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guns are ending up in the hands of children,'' says a
nurse, who also lost a child to gun violence. ``As long as it's
happening in the black community, as long as it's happening in the
Hispanic community, it's not (seen as) that important.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Kurtis said there are nearly 240 million guns
in America, with more pouring onto the streets every day, thanks to
gun manufacturers intent on finding ways to maintain a revenue
stream that accounts for more than $1 billion a year. For instance,
Kurtis interviewed a gun maker who explained how he got around bans
on assault rifles simply by not appending a ``flash suppressor'' to
the front of the barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Kurtis said he came away from the ``Guns in America'' project
believing that gun-control efforts will always face an uphill
battle because so many Americans are simply not willing to give up
their weapons, in part due to distrust of the government. But he
tempered that prediction by noting that, as with the tobacco
industry, gun makers face unprecedented new legal challenges now
that big-city mayors are lining up to file class-action lawsuits
against them.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that in the post-Columbine climate, all the
usual bets regarding gun control may be off. ``The Littleton group,
the housewife group, they are going to take over,'' said Kurtis.
``And that is what the NRA should be afraid of.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
