<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Tuesday,
June 29. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD: Several inches of rain pound the Kansas City area Sunday
and Monday. Streams pour out of their banks, intersections flood,
areas around Southwest Boulevard, 16th and Washington in Kansas
City, Kan., are evacuated, power outages reported and rescues
abound. Missouri Water Patrol called out to search for a 7-year-old
child at Woods Chapel Road and Mill Drive at the entrance to Lake
Tapawingo. Stuff reportedly is floating out of homes in Kansas
City, Kan. And more rain is on the way this week. Before Monday,
Kansas City already was 10 inches above average rainfall for the
year and three inches above for the month. Also rainfall ratings
for the area. Matt Campbell, Donna McGuire, Matt Schofield, Lynn
Horsley, Summer Harlow, Winston Ross, Bobbie White, Mike Rice,
Shawna Hamel, Anne Lamoy, Steve Nicely and others. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   HEP: Lots of families are scrambling this summer to get their
kids inoculated with the Hep B vaccine. Seventh graders in Missouri
need at least one of three required shots or they won't be let into
school this fall. with box on where clinics are. Mara Rose
Williams. 15.
</P>
<P>
   SHOW: Show business keeps calling Emery ``Spanky'' Henderson. No
matter that he worked 36 years in Kansas City as a meteorologist
and computer expert, all as a federal employee. Henderson, 63, is
bound for the bright lights of the Celebrity Theater in Branson as
a part-time singer for The World Famous Platters, a copy act
reviving the original Platters' '50s and '60s Top-40 hits. Bill
Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS. Royals go for three out of four against the first-place
Cleveland Indians. 7:05 p.m. Dick Kaegel. 16-18. Photos
</P>
<P>
   GWYNN. What cruel irony that Tony Gwynn, the consummate hitter
of baseballs, would have to wait so long to get his 3000th. For
months, the San Diego Padres have been hyping the event _ the team
even built a trailer outside their stadium featuring Gwynn _ but an
untimely injury has fans getting anxious. Steve Rock. 35-40.
</P>
