<HEADER>
A1995 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-MYSTERY-BOS &LR;      06-28 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MYSTERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMING-OUT PARTY FOR MYSTERY AND CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBIN W. WINKS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I write this on the first day of summer, a moment of almost
ritualistic ushering-in, of waking up to the new, of putting the
academic year behind me (for I am, after all, one who works to the
rhythms of ``the school year''). At such a moment I have always
liked to devote myself to first novels, debuts of writers who have
newly offered themselves up for critical appraisal and to the gods
of the marketplace. Will their books sell? Will the dream of being
a novelist, of living by wits and words, begin well? Perhaps
reviewers can never escape the urge to play Pygmalion. To help
launch a career, to smash all hopes _ what arrogant notions of
power the reviewer may entertain. For myself, I prefer only good
news, so here are eight first novels about which the news is
largely good.
</P>
<P>
   Three of these debuts hew closely to recipes that have been
proven so consistently successful that merely getting the cake to
rise again may be considered a triumph. Formula one:
Turn-and-turn-again _ cast suspicion (with suspicion's companion,
fear) repeatedly, alternatively, logically, on a tiny cast of
characters. Jonathan Stone works with this formula brilliantly in
``The Cold Truth'' (St. Martin's, $23.95). Julian Palmer is chosen
by the legendary Winston ``Bear'' Edwards, chief of police in an
upstate New York snow-belt town, to work with him in a training
program. As he shambles toward retirement, the chief has on his
desk one unsolved case, the brutal murder and dismemberment of a
young waitress; otherwise his record is perfect. Until Palmer
arrives, the chief doesn't know that his new associate is a woman.
The two work together in alternating trust and distrust, and the
chief also enlists the services of a well-known local psychic.
Stone takes this mix, follows the recipe, and gives us a compelling
tale true to all the expectations of the genre.
</P>
<P>
   Formula two: Suggest there is a monstrous conspiracy that, if
its roots are revealed, will launch upon the world a disaster so
horrible one may be given only hints of it. Catch an attractive
innocent up in the conspiracy, make him an unwitting pawn in a game
he does not even know he is playing. Give him the support of an old
girlfriend. Stalk him with an eerie professional killer, or perhaps
two, who pursue our innocent and his friend down the rural roads of
America (in this case, to Mississippi via North Carolina) while a
hacker friend discovers information that even the most powerful man
in the world appears to be unable to suppress. Make sure the
chilling professional killers are, when it comes to it, remarkably
incompetent. Few cooks can make this mixture read to truly frantic
purpose, but Russell Andrews, in ``Gideon'' (Ballantine, $24.95),
serves it up with aplomb. (Nothing is ever as it seems in this
literature: Andrews is a ``first-time writer,'' but he is also
Peter Gethers and David Handler, who between them have written a
score of novels.)
</P>
<P>
   Formula three: Wed ``Raiders of the Lost Ark'' to this week's
headlines. In ``Cleopatra's Needle'' (Forge, $23.95), Steven
Siebert tells us the tale of the world-famous archeologist at the
Metropolitan Museum of New York who sends an assistant to find a
broken Egyptian ankh in the musuem's storage collection, unleashing
untold mayhem. The assistant disappears and turns up murdered at
the foot of Cleopatra's Needle in Central Park. Meanwhile, as the
dust jacket summarizes, ``Jacinda El-Bahri, a Mossad agent, is
running for her life in Cairo after stealing the other half of the
ankh from a powerful terrorist. Known as Salameh, he plans to use
the relic's incredible energy to unleash a power of biblical
proportions.'' For people who like this sort of stuff, this is
definitely the sort of stuff they will like: Siebert dishes up his
startling nonsense with great charm.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one wants to escape from formulaic fiction every now
and then, and Meira Cook's ``The Blood Girls'' (Overlook, $22.95)
provides wonderful relief from the allegedly unexpected twists and
turns of the manipulative plot. The opening sentence certainly drew
me in: ``Seven days before Easter Monday, in a small town north of
Winnipeg, Manitoba, an eleven-year-old girl sitting in her
classroom began to bleed from the palm of her left hand.'' The
story that follows, probing a small town's response to the
miraculous, is (we are told) reconstructed from interviews,
newspaper articles, journal entries, letters, and memory. Its
central characters _ a priest, a doctor, a journalist, and Molly
Rhutabaga, who has lived in the same house all her life _ are
wonderfully real. I truly hope we will hear much more from Cook, a
South African transplanted to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   I feel the same excitement about Leslie Forbes, whose ``Bombay
Ice'' I missed in hardcover a year ago and now debuts in paper
(Bantam, $13.95). This is the story of a British journalist who is
called to Bombay by her sister, whose film-director husband is
suspected of murdering his ex-wife. The book is self-consciously
rich in detail, complex where Cook is simple, given to meditation
on alchemy, death, and sexuality _ and despite all this, amply
rewards the reader wanting an exotic locale and a plot to sink the
teeth into. More, please!
</P>
<P>
   Members of our legal fraternity seem increasingly dissatisfied
with the messy nature of their day jobs and are turning to lawyerly
novels where everything can be made to come out right. ``A
Cinderella Affidavit'' (Forge, $25.95) by Michael Frederickson,
general counsel to the Massachusetts Board of Bar Overseers (which
looks into cases of wrongdoing by lawyers), draws upon his
expertise for a cunning story of crime, corruption, perjury, and
murder in Boston. ``Big Easy Backroad'' (St. Martin's, $22.95) is
by Martin Hegwood, a former assistant district attorney now working
for the Mississippi secretary of state's office. He gives us Jack
Delmas, a freelance investigator who helps a barmaid look for her
missing boyfriend and quickly discovers that New Orleans is steamy
even when air-conditioned. Both these books are well-above-average
hammock reading.
</P>
<P>
   We stay in the sultry Southland with Darryl Wimberley's ``A Rock
and a Hard Place'' (St. Martin's, $22.95), which introduces Barrett
Raines, a black detective in a small town in Florida's Panhandle.
He faces the usual gumbo of racism, family ties, small-town gossip,
and bottle-on-the-counter taverns _ but Wimberley puts all this
together very well, ushering in summer with just the right mix of
mystery, chilled beer, and doubt that we will ever get cool again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1996 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-MIRACLE-BOS &LR;      06-28 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MIRACLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JOYS AND PERILS OF A LOVE AFFAIR WITH SOCCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE MIRACLE OF CASTEL DI SANGRO 
By Joe McGinniss 
Little, Brown, 407 pp., $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early on in ``The Miracle of Castel di Sangro,'' Joe McGinniss
is explaining his raison d'etre to the local capo, who also happens
to own the soccer team McGinniss will be following.
</P>
<P>
   McGinniss explains that he has forfeited a $1 million fee to
write a book about ``Mr. O. J. Simpson'' in order to spend a season
in the hills of Abruzzo, researching the story of an obscure
village's giant-killing team. The capo apparently decides that
anyone deranged enough to refuse such a lucrative offer should be
left to pursue his caprice.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, McGinniss has been similarly indulged by his agent,
publisher, family, and friends in recent years. Maybe they realized
that some outlandish acts have been committed in the world of
soccer, and that for McGinniss to relinquish $1 million to follow
the sport makes him one of the more reasonable ``tifosi di calcio''
_ literally, typhus-infected soccer fans.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, soccer is as much a part of life as the church,
family, and food. McGinniss discovers this in an intimate way and
relates even the innermost details, at his own peril. McGinniss
perceived this as a romantic story, the embodiment of some of the
true meritocratic values of sport. The team from a village of 5,000
rises through the lower divisions, defeating clubs from much larger
and more influential cities, and is one step away from competing in
Serie A, the richest soccer league in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Within days of arriving in Castel di Sangro, McGinniss has been
granted access to the most important figures in the region. Once he
learns the language, he develops confidences with nearly everyone
else. He finds that soccer very quickly leads to the Italian heart.
And McGinniss thrives on the opportunity, offering the coach his
opinions on player personnel and tactics. McGinniss's judgments are
remarkably sound, for someone who has been following the game for
only a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   McGinniss immerses himself in the culture. He stands on his seat
at the stadium, urging the coach to make substitutions. He joins
the villagers in cheering on the team. He becomes a part of the
story. ``Finally, at the age of 53, I had been united with my
people,'' he notes after an early-season victory.
</P>
<P>
   As with most sports stories, this one begins with fairy-tale
innocence. Players confide in McGinniss and he even acts in an
agent's role, trying to interest the New England Revolution in
signing a goalkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   McGinniss was attracted to European soccer by his exposure to
the World Cup, which was held in the United States for the first
time in 1994. The Italian midfielder Roberto Baggio caught
McGinniss's attention, not just because of his Buddhist faith,
ponytail, and charismatic image but also because of his uncanny
ability to decide games in dramatic fashion. McGinniss was so
impressed he changed his e-mail address to incorporate Baggio's
name.
</P>
<P>
   But Baggio is near the top of the soccer pyramid, in all its
glamour, glory, and billions of lira. Only a super ``tifoso'' would
be attracted to the story of Castel di Sangro.
</P>
<P>
   But the story of Castel di Sangro is not all fun and games.
Soccer is also a modern manifestation of ancient city-state
rivalries, even among the small clubs. In Machiavelli's time,
battles were conducted by mercenaries who often merely arranged a
show of force, then negotiated a suitable outcome. Such pragmatism
often prevented messy wars of attrition.
</P>
<P>
   Castel di Sangro achieves its improbable goal of surviving for
another year among the richer clubs, despite problems with
corruption, drug smuggling, a tragic auto accident, absurd
publicity stunts, perceived racism.
</P>
<P>
   McGinniss is about to celebrate a happy ending when reality
intrudes and the season ends on a Machiavellian note. McGinniss
becomes persona non grata in Castel di Sangro. Even during times of
supposed enlightenment, the church and the city-states often exiled
or persecuted artists, scientists, and writers whose work upset the
power structure. And this becomes McGinniss's final Italian lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Miracle of Castel di Sangro'' is excellent in its
portrayal of lower-division professional soccer and in providing an
image of a mountainous, remote part of Italy. These two aims of the
book are not as distinct as they might seem to an American reader:
The Uruguayan author Eduardo Galeano notes that with the blending
of cultures, the globalizing of economy and politics, the only true
identifying characteristic of nationality is the style of a
people's soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer has provided inspiration for Albert Camus, Roddy Doyle,
Vladimir Nabokov, Harold Pinter, Salman Rushdie, Luis Sepulveda,
Mario Soldati, and many other prominent literati. McGinniss is
among the first of his sociocultural background to write
extensively on the subject. Often, as he admits, he might have been
well advised to opt for silence rather than inserting himself so
boldly into the story he has to tell. But then again, his
ingenuousness and his obtuse nature create the humorous clash of
cultures that makes this story his own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1997 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-28 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING THE RETURN OF FOUL AIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Everybody who likes to take a breath without
choking should be relieved that Carol Browner knows how to fight as
well as make sound policy.
</P>
<P>
   This week the head of the Environmental Protection Agency will
fight a federal appeals court panel's ruling that would gut tougher
clean air standards based on the latest generally accepted
scientific evidence of the dangers ozone (smog) and fine,
particulate matter (soot) pose to healthy lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite two years ago, the EPA received several petitions from
Eastern states seeking relief from ozone pollution originating
elsewhere. This month, the agency acted to make sure that this
relief is granted without the kind of legal train wreck that has
for the moment stopped a more comprehensive approach to harmful
levels of smog and soot.
</P>
<P>
   Browner was able to do this by using an older standard for
permissible levels of smog, providing a legally unassailable basis
for action. That meant that she could approve petitions from New
York, Connecticut, Pennsylvania, and Massachusetts, while
continuing to review the status of Maryland, New Jersey, and
Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Fine and dandy. But that still leaves the pending litigation. At
stake is the integrity of the Clean Air Act itself and nearly 30
years of judicially untouched decision-making under five presidents
and 15 Congresses that has updated and strengthened the law three
times.
</P>
<P>
   Also at stake is a logical concept of governance that has stood
the tests of time and litigation for nearly three generations,
since the beginning of the New Deal _ that Congress can delegate
specific rule-making authority to federal agencies under broad
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the second generation of robber barons was seeking to
evade basic responsibilities to American workers and consumers has
serious attention been paid to the lame argument that regulatory
authority is illegitimate unless exercised solely by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But give or take a nuance or two, that is exactly what a divided
appeals court panel here ruled this spring, blithely overturning
more than 60 years of precedent and practice as well as the EPA's
comprehensive reponsive to smog and soot. Presumably the
government's appeal will now go to the full court in the
expectation that a dangerous attempt at radical activism will be
stopped cold.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate impact of the panel's action is on a central
portion of the Clean Air Act _ that the EPA just set air pollution
rules that protect public health, with a decent margin of safety,
based on the best scientific information available. Already, since
1970, the Act has reduced air pollution overall by nearly a third
even as population and economic growth have increased. And it has
virtually wiped out emissions of lead and cut soot by 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the job under the law was far from complete. Early in the
Clinton administration, a massive review of the science by an EPA
panel found smog and soot still at unhealthy levels for 125 million
people, one million of whom face respiratory trouble as a result,
and 15,000 of whom will die prematurely every year.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Browner battled successfully two years ago to toughen
the standards under the law. Her case was so powerful that there
was no serious move to soften, much less set aside, the standards.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, people who produce smog and soot for a living and their
most extreme allies in Congress went for the judicial back door.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the appeals court panel refused to accept the
major claims that there was anything flawed in the EPA's process or
that the science was inadequate or that the tie to adverse health
consequences wasn't shown. It said exactly the opposite. Instead,
it reached back to the dark ages to decide that Congress has
delegated powers only it can exercise _ a recipe in a complex
society for chaos.
</P>
<P>
   As Browner has noted, the stakes go beyond air pollution, to
standards affecting everything from water to food to lethal toxic
waste.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, she was right to press for an all-out assault on the
panel's ruling, and right to do what she could in the interim. And
at least 125 million pairs of fingers are crossed that this attempt
at upsetting one of the pillars of 20th century government is
crushed decisively.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
