<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2005 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CLOCK-BOS &LR;      06-28 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CLOCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BODY CLOCK MORE ACCURATE THAN A TIMEX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 40 years, circadian rhythm researchers have thought that
humans' biological clocks naturally drift toward a 25-hour day and
have to be set back an hour each day by exposure to morning light
and other time cues.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Boston scientists have overturned this dogma with a set
of experiments showing that the timekeeper buried in the depths of
human brains ticks on a cycle of 24.2 hours. And _ another surprise
_ it keeps excellent time into old age.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a remarkable discovery: an important human function
that does not deteriorate with age,'' commented University of
Pittsburgh neuroscientist Richard Y. Moore. ``Clearly, nature would
not go to the trouble of constructing such an elegant, functional,
and durable timepiece if it was not critical to us throughout our
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The iconoclastic finding, reported in this week's issue of the
journal Science, is causing researchers to rethink many circadian
phenomena. For instance, the reason why elders have a tendency to
awaken too early is not because their circadian timekeepers are
losing track of time, as they long thought. The real reason is
still a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the reason why it's so hard to get up on Monday
mornings is not, as previously supposed, that sleeping in on
weekends promotes to the body clock's natural tendency to slide
toward a longer day.
</P>
<P>
   And specialists will have to reconsider the treatment of a
common sleep disorder called sleep-onset insomnia, because current
therapy is based on the notion of a natural 25-hour cycle. ``This
means a lot of conclusions about sleep disorders are wrong,'' said
Dr. William Dement of Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery also resolves a biological paradox: why are humans
unique among living things in having a circadian cycle so different
from the 24-hour day? Now scientists know that we aren't. With very
little variation from one human to another, it now appears that
Homo sapiens has evolved to have an average cycle of 24 hours and
11 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is right in line with the Gila monster, mosquito,
kangaroo rat, fruit fly, and all our other brethren in the animal
kingdom,'' said Dr. Charles A. Czeisler of Brigham and Women's
Hospital, who led the new experiments.
</P>
<P>
   How could scientists have been so wrong for so long?
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on Thomas Edison, whose invention of the electric light
bulb 120 years ago changed night into day and altered human biology
in ways researchers are only beginning to appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   In scores of experiments over the past four decades, researchers
have studied innate biological rhythms by isolating human subjects
in windowless laboratories without clocks, radios, or other
external time cues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to elaborate lengths to shield people from outside
cues, including even subtle electromagnetic forces, but then we
would give them an electric light and said they could switch it on
and off at will,'' Cseisler said. ``We used to think that people
were relatively insensitive to light and that social interaction
was the potent signal.''
</P>
<P>
   But experiments over the last decade have shown that light ``is
the most powerful signal in this system,'' Czeisler said. In 1996,
the Boston team reported that even ordinary room light can reset
humans' internal pacemakers.
</P>
<P>
   Even totally blind people, the researchers have found, are
exquisitely sensitive to the pacemaker-resetting effects of light
that falls on the retina at the back of the eye, where receptors
transmit the signal to a tiny bundle of cells called the
suprachiasmatic nucleus, lying atop the optic nerves.
</P>
<P>
   Czeisler and his colleagues unmasked humans' real circadian
cycles by keeping 24 subjects (divided into a younger group and an
older group) in isolation for up to 38 days. The researchers
required the subjects to sleep and wake on a 28-hour day _ too far
outside the normal range to allow their body clocks to adapt.
Lights were kept to very dim levels to avoid the clock-resetting
effects that had confounded earlier experiments.
</P>
<P>
   The realization that ordinary room light has such powerful
effects in resetting biological clocks has profound implications.
It begins to explain why most denizens of industrialized societies
live with the burden of chronic sleep deprivation _ what Dement has
called ``our national sleep debt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This light we're all getting between sunset and bedtime has
shifted billions of people in the industrialized world several
hours later,'' Czeisler said. ``It's as if everybody in Boston were
shifted to West Coast time, even though we're still living on the
East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   On weekends, many people alter their sleep patterns in an
attempt to repay this sleep deficit. ``You could say that what
happens on the weekends is we stop fighting,'' Czeisler said. ``But
we're the ones, with our own self-exposure to artificial light, who
are inadvertently shifting our clocks to a later hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Research suggests the sleep debt blunts humans' cognitive
performance on a chronic basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know also that when sleep-wake cycle is working at adverse
times with our circadian rhythm we're not going to get good sleep
and our cognitive functioning is not optimal,'' said Andrew Monjan,
of the National Institute on Aging.
</P>
<P>
   What to do about it? It's not likely that 21st-century humans
will go to bed with the sun or spend their evenings in candlelight.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, I think we have to raise the consciousness of people
about the effects of evening light,'' said Richard Kronauer of
Harvard University. ``People need to appreciate the importance of
maintaining a regular sleep-wake schedule or they're going to get
screwed up.''
</P>
<P>
   The researchers also suggest sleeping with room-darkening shades
to avoid light exposure too early in the morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
