<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2006 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-PEDIATRICS-ART-BO     06-28 1428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PEDIATRICS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERIOUS KID STUFF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Dr. Eugenia Marcus does a routine physical exam, the
pediatrician not only checks the young patient's eyes, ears, and
heart, but asks about guns in the house and quizzes the child about
what to do if he or she found one.
</P>
<P>
   It's a striking example of how the pediatrician's job has
changed in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In times past, pediatricians had to deal with so much
infectious disease that there was no time to bring up the fact
that, by the way, Johnny is failing in school and violent toward
his brother,'' says Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she says, with many childhood diseases waning, today's
pediatricians are increasingly confronting problems far outside
their traditional scope, from learning disabilities to child abuse
to the impact of divorce on a family.
</P>
<P>
   And certainly one of the biggest questions following the
Littleton, Colo., school massacre has been: how do you identify
potentially violent young people in time to intervene?
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to look at the Littleton tragedy to see the
questions people are asking _ what is the role of parents? How do
we know which children are going to have that kind of explosive
behavior? What contributes to it?'' says Dr. Barry Zuckerman,
chairman of pediatrics at Boston University School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pediatricians are being asked to shoulder the burden of all
the ills of society,'' says Dr. Steven Parker, head of
developmental and behavioral pediatrics at Boston Medical Center.
``We're being asked to deal with every problem there is, but we
have less time to spend with patients, not more'' because of
managed care constraints, he said.
</P>
<P>
   This drastic shift has been highlighted with the establishment
of a new specialty called Developmental and Behavioral Pediatrics.
In March, the American Board of Medical Specialties added the new
discipline to its 24 existing ones, and will oversee the testing
and certification of the new specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this could make a big difference in pediatrics,'' says
Dr. Ellen Perrin, a pediatrician at the University of Massachusetts
Medical Center and president of the American Society for
Developmental and Behavioral Pediatrics, the organization that led
the push for the specialty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to do more education of physicians in training,''
she says, and ``we wanted to have greater impact on medical
students and residents and doctors in family practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors who become board-certified in the new specialty will
undergo more intensive and standardized training than general
pediatricians normally receive. Many will become teachers
themselves in medical schools.
</P>
<P>
   And their reimbursement by insurers should be better, too. At
present, says Perrin, general pediatricians might spend an hour
with a family talking about behavioral problems ``but (were) only
reimbursed for 15 minutes of `well-child' care,'' she adds. With
their new designation as specialists, the new behavioral
pediatricians presumably will be able to collect larger
reimbursements for their expertise and time.
</P>
<P>
   In the past several decades, research has revealed far more than
was previously known about what is ``normal'' development, how it
varies among individuals, and how it is affected both by the
child's inherent nature and his or her home and community
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Perrin said the new specialist pediatricians will be equipped to
diagnose and treat a long list of disorders in development and
behavior, but also problems that aren't in any textbook. These
might include toileting difficulties, discipline problems, extreme
shyness, and being concerned about being adopted or having gay or
lesbian parents, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Developmental disorders include mental retardation, language and
speech delays, autism, and other conditions reflecting a problem in
a child's normal progression through the stages of physical,
mental, emotional, and social growth.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many behavioral disorders are attention deficit and
hyperactivity disorder, anxiety, depression, separation problems,
eating disorders, and oppositional and defiant behavior. Some
problems don't neatly fit into one category or the other, Perrin
noted.
</P>
<P>
   Together, developmental and behavioral disorders affect an
estimated 10 to 20 percent of US children. And, unlike many
traditional diseases, they've not been conquered with a shot or a
pill.
</P>
<P>
   Perrin said the new specialty will benefit families in two ways.
First, because there will be more pediatricians who become
board-certified in behavior and developmental problems, parents
will be able to choose a doctor based on their child's particular
needs. Second, even general pediatricians ``graduating five to 10
years from now should be more sophisticated in these areas _ more
supportive, more knowledgeable about what is a problem, and what
needs early intervention,'' says Perrin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope what this will mean is there will be more (experts)
able to look at'' children's problems, says Dr. Leonard Rappaport,
a behavioral pediatrician at Children's Hospital in Boston. ``There
are now long waiting lists'' for specialists in behavior and
development because there aren't enough people to do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The establishment of the new specialty actually reflects a
change occurring over the past several decades, as vaccines and
antibiotics have overcome many common childhood diseases, like
polio, TB, whooping cough, and measles.
</P>
<P>
   Today, says Marcus, families are in need of help to cope with
problems created by higher expectations of children, a faster-paced
society, and, for many couples, less time to attend to their
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``With two parents working, everything is so programmed and
scheduled that if something derails it, it can bring down the whole
household system,'' says Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   Depression, school problems, drug, and sexual issues _ all are
preoccupying parents who are casting about for help.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, parents had the same concerns in the past, ``but
they didn't see it as what the pediatrician did, and the
pediatricians didn't either,'' says Zuckerman of Boston Medical
Center. Now, he adds, the pediatricians ``see it as part of their
responsibility to address the whole child and the whole family, not
just physical health.''
</P>
<P>
   A milestone in recognizing this change was an article published
in 1973, by Dr. Robert Haggerty, a University of Rochester
pediatrician, who termed behavioral and developmental issues ``the
new morbidities.''
</P>
<P>
   The term reflected what Haggerty and his colleagues had found in
door-to-door surveys in which Rochester families were asked about
their children's greatest health problems. ``It always came out as
behavior, allergies, and teeth,'' he says. ``They didn't mention
the traditional diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   But behavioral problems ``can be disabling'' just as much as
physical diseases, added Haggerty. When such problems are severe,
pediatricians may refer the family to a child psychologist or
psychiatrist. But today there are only 3,500 to 4,000 child
psychiatrists in the United States, while there are 55,000
pediatricians: clearly the pediatricians are the front line in
detecting troubled children and treating them or referring them to
specialists.
</P>
<P>
   The new specialist pediatricians _ including some who have been
concentrating in development and behavior without the certification
_ will have to take a test to become board-certified. Training for
the specialty will be done in a three-year fellowship following
residency training in pediatrics.
</P>
<P>
   Families will be referred to the new specialists by their
general pediatricians in most cases.
</P>
<P>
   Haggerty says that parents may feel more comfortable being
referred to a behaviorally oriented pediatrician: ``It doesn't have
the stigma of being referred to a psychiatrist,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Haggerty adds that he was initially opposed to the new
specialty, because ``I think behavioral pediatrics is a part of all
pediatrics _ I was concerned it would be looked at as something
separate.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he became persuaded of the need for certification so
that insurance companies would reimburse the services
appropriately. He also approves of standardizing the training of
the behavior specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've changed my mind,'' he says. ``I think it's a good
thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
