<HEADER>
A2007 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-28 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON HEALTH INSURANCE, KENNEDY TRIES TO FIT THE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been seven years since the Clinton administration's
universal health care campaign met an ill fate at the hands of a
Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Since that time, Democrats have adopted a new strategy and a new
leader _ Senator Edward M. Kennedy _ to bring affordable health
care to all Americans. In the past two years, particularly in
recent months, Kennedy has proven to be an able general.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of trying to push through a huge, complex national
health care plan (such as the Clinton package) that is an easy
target for the GOP, Kennedy and other key Democrats are working to
expand health care one step at a time. Ironically, they are even
getting some support from Republicans along the way.
</P>
<P>
   For example, two years ago Congress, led by Kennedy, expanded
health care to include millions of poor and low-income children
across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks ago, the Senate, by a 99-to-0 vote, passed a
bill sponsored by Kennedy that expands health benefits to millions
of workers with disabilities. Called the Work Incentive Improvement
Act of 1999, the bill assures that disabled workers will not lose
their Medicaid and Medicare benefits if they return to work. It's a
strong incentive to get back on the job.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is currently in House committees. Despite some GOP
resistance in the House, supporters say passage by next month is
possible _ perhaps to coincide with the anniversary of the
Americans with Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   With Senate passage of this bill, Kennedy has become the
acknowledged leader for the Democrats on health care issues.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's success in health care is due partly to his skill,
ability, and willingness to work with even some of the staunchest
Republican opponents of his legislation, such as majority leader
Trent Lott of Mississippi and majority whip Don Nickles of
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   A Kennedy backer called the Massachusetts senator ``an
experienced and wily veteran'' who is working to achieve as much
health coverage as he can with a GOP-controlled Congress that
resists expanded care.
</P>
<P>
   Another Kennedy backer said the senator ``never shied away from
his willingness and desire to pass universal health care. More than
41 million Americans are still without health insurance. But in a
Republican-controlled Congress he recognizes the need to do what is
achievable and doable now, and then wait for more opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's leadership role was evident to those at a closed-door
meeting of Senate Democrats last week to discuss their next step
regarding their latest health care goal: passage of their Patients'
Bill of Rights.
</P>
<P>
   During that meeting, some Democrats debated whether to consider
Republicans' version of a managed-care health bill, which contains
little or no improvement, or continue to hold out for a floor
debate on the Kennedy-Dingell Patients' Bill of Rights legislation.
Kennedy made an impassioned case to fight for the Democratic
initiative, and he easily prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP managed-care bill has so little merit that it is not
even supported by such groups as the Chamber of Commerce. Kennedy's
bill, on the other hand, is backed by a host of groups, including
doctors and nurses associations.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans opposing Kennedy hope to persuade the public that
the bill will make health care more expensive, that it will cost
more for family coverage, will increase costs to the federal
government, and will cost the private sector billions more than it
already pays.
</P>
<P>
   But GOP members of Congress know that they cannot back these
arguments up. And they know their arguments will not hold water
with an American public eager for a bill to protect them against
abuses by HMOs and insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the GOP dares not allow the Patients' Bill to come to
the Senate floor for a full dicussion on its merits _ despite
repeated requests by Kennedy and other Democrats to do so. If it
were allowed, Democratic arguments would prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, for example, offered in a recent speech that ``the
purpose of the Patients' Bill of Rights is to protect American
families against abuses that too often rob citizens of their
savings and their peace of mind _ and even their health and even
their lives. Doctors and patients should be making medical
decisions, not insurance company accountants. Too often today,
managed care is mismanaged care.'' For millions of Americans, he
added, ``these reforms are truly a matter of life or death.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy added that he is confident that if the Republican
majority allows the debate to proceed, ``I believe that the Senate
will pass strong reforms that will be signed into law by the
president.'' This debate, he added, ``is a test of the Senate's
willingness to put a higher priority on the needs of families than
on the profits of special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican opponents of the Patients' Bill of Rights might
consider that their own political health may be at stake if they
continue to deny protections against health care abuses to millions
of American voters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
