<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2010 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEALTH-WORRIES-ART-BO     06-28 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEALTH-WORRIES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PSYCHOLOGY OF MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By IAN SHAPIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a November night in 1985, Stef Fuegi recalls, he saw that a
friend was too tired to continue driving and vainly urged him to
pull over. A nearly fatal accident followed, putting Fuegi in the
hospital for months. Four years later, the accident led to an
out-of-court settlement that made Fuegi a near-millionaire at age
22. But it wasn't to last.
</P>
<P>
   The former New Haven, Conn. resident ended up squandering the
$800,000 he received from the settlement. He bought a Toyota
Superturbo sports car, spent more time at expensive restaurants
than in his own kitchen, and stayed in the best hotels while
following Grateful Dead concerts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to do with it,'' Fuegi, now 32, says of the
wealth. ``I felt guilty just because there are so many people who
don't have enough. Here I was with the money I didn't earn. There
was no one to talk to. I felt isolated and I felt like if I talked
to people, they wouldn't understand me.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuegi's sentiments, though unlikely to evoke sympathy, speak to
the problems some people face when they become wealthy abruptly.
Whether through an insurance settlement, a court verdict, an
inheritance, or the lottery, winning bundles of money and jumping
social classes can pose financial and psychological conundrums.
</P>
<P>
   ``You grew up middle class, you didn't go to Harvard, you went
to UMass, so the questions become: `Do you share? How do you share?
Where do you fit?' '' says Pam Rogers, who works with the Haymarket
People's Fund, a foundation that assists individuals who want to
use their money for social change.
</P>
<P>
   Financial consultants such as Rogers agree that those who get
very rich very fast must cope with a startling fact of life: Big
bucks can create big problems that require considerable thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the suddenly wealthy person, they do tend to go through a
more deliberate process of thinking than a person who has grown up
with money all their life,'' says Amy Domani, a Boston-based family
trustee and coauthor of the book ``The Challenges of Wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, anxiety over money lingers as perhaps our culture's most
private collective taboo. The ambivalence surrounding money can
quickly sap an adult's maturity level.
</P>
<P>
   ``People remain childish around the issue of money,'' says New
Yorker magazine columnist Daphne Merkin, who recently wrote about
her conflicted attitude toward wealth in the publication's
``Money'' issue. ``They either hide it under their beds or buy up a
candy store. Reasonableness must be hard to come by with suddenly
wealthy people.''
</P>
<P>
   Money can be so confounding to so many people that sex, by
comparison, is a more inviting conversation piece. Or, to put it
another way, ``Everyone can have sex, but not everyone can have
money,'' says Dr. Steven Berglas, a psychiatrist whose wealthy
clients sometimes complain that their fortunes prompt a
``competitive rage'' among their friends and colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, Christopher Mogil and Anne Slepian founded a
nonprofit group, now called More than Money, that tries to help the
wealthy make sense of their good fortune. Among other aids, the
married couple's Arlingon-based organization publishes a newsletter
on managing wealth that now has 1,300 subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are excited that they can tap into a whole community,''
says Mogil, who has had personal experience in coping with sudden
wealth. In the '80s, when he received two inheritances worth over a
half-million dollars, he sought advice from others with similar
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``There weren't that many people to talk to, yet it was such a
central thing in my life,'' Mogil adds. ``I didn't feel like
talking about it with people struggling for money _ that would be
inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   With More Than Money, readers find a safe corner in which to
vent. The quarterly publication has a different theme each issue.
Recent topics included ``Money and Children,'' ``How Much to
Give?,'' and ``Cross-Class Relationships.'' The publication largely
consists of subscribers' letters contemplating the financial and
moral dilemmas they otherwise couldn't air.
</P>
<P>
   A former Harvard student wrote a letter that was titled,
``Loving My Dad, Not My Inheritance,'' telling how he had arrived
at some particularly hard truths. ``I hadn't been aware that I was
wanting my father's money and waiting for him to die,'' he
recounted.
</P>
<P>
   Though many inheritors certainly live most of their lives
knowing they are going to be wealthy one day, the reality of it can
still have an impact. ``Here I was,'' says Domani, the family
trustee, ``about to tell a woman for the first time she has over a
million dollars. She later told me she was quaking, crying out of
`freakdom.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Pond is a financial planner and PBS television
commentator who offers advice to those bequeathed large sums. He
says that inheritors should take the news of their good luck and
use it to take time ``to clarify their values.'' He also suggests
to his moneyed clients that benefactors and recipients have long
discussions prior to an eventual bequest, a practice that enables
adults to impart real-world financial education and values to their
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because, if they squander it, they're going to feel awful. You
buy a boat, a second home, and you'' throw the money away, Pond
says. ``You're 56 and you have nothing to show for it. What's this
going to do to your psyche?''
</P>
<P>
   The most important thing the suddenly rich can do, though, Pond
and other consultants say, is to stick with your job, even though
it's tempting to quit. ``Your friends are going to have a lot more
respect for you if you continue to work. They'll admire your values
and feel that even though you're not in their financial ballpark,
you're still one of them,'' says Pond.
</P>
<P>
   Domani echoes that it is important to lead a normal life: ``Take
out a mortgage, go through the bothers of walking the dog, and have
people count on you,'' she suggests.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's the path taken by Bo Peabody of Williamstown, Mass. A few
years ago, Peabody was building up his computer company, Tripod,
and living with four college buddies from Williams while paying
$300 a month in rent. Then, the Internet search engine Lycos bought
Tripod.
</P>
<P>
   For $58 million. He was 26.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Peabody about affluence and here's what he says: ``It tends
to create more hassles than it creates pleasures.'' To counter some
of that, the millionaire bachelor lives in a two-bedroom house,
drives a used Audi, and is paying for his ``little brother'' to
attend a Vermont boarding school as part of the Big Brothers/Big
Sisters program.
</P>
<P>
   Peabody says he has found the true value and best meaning of
money: ``To me, wealth is freedom. It isn't about buying things,
but time and doing whatever you want to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
