<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW DOES THE BRAIN INTERPRET MUSICAL SOUNDS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How does our brain turn the sounds we hear into what we
perceive as music?
</P>
<P>
   M.R., Concord, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. ``That's one of the very fundamental questions in all of
cognitive neuroscience,'' says Robert Zatorre, Associate Professor
of Psychology at the Montreal Neurological Institute and one of the
world's leading experts on the perception of music. ``...The short
answer is, we don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   But Zatorre and other cognitive neuroscientists have been able
to figure out where music perception apparently takes place within
our brains.
</P>
<P>
   Zatorre says a growing body of evidence indicates that the a
section of the temporal lobe of the brain, on your right temple
just above and in front of your ear, is a key site of music
processing.
</P>
<P>
   One clue came from the case of Russian composer Dmitri
Shebalian, who suffered a stroke. He was paralyzed on his right
side, indicating the left side of his motor cortex was damaged. He
was also rendered mute. But he later would write some of his most
impressive music, still able to communicate in the language of
music.
</P>
<P>
   That told neuroscientists that there was probably a separate
area of the brain specific to the processing of music. The question
was, where?
</P>
<P>
   Since Shebalian couldn't speak, it indicated probable damage in
a section of the brain called Broca's area, in the left temporal
lobe, known to be critical to the ability to speak. That was a clue
that the music center might be on the right. So Zatorre interviewed
people known to have brain damage to their right temporal lobe, and
found that indeed, they had trouble processing sound into music.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out not just where but how this musical processing
takes place, may offer important clues about all forms of human
perception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music is a use of sound that's uniquely human,'' Zatorre says.
``Other animals make sounds that sound like music. Like birds
singing. They're just conveying territoriality, or trying to mate.
We're the only species we know of that makes sounds just because we
find them pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Understanding how those uniquely human pathways work would not
shed light on how the human cortex turns any outside stimulus _
sounds, smells, light _ into what we perceive it to be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write to
How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
