<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-LAWFIRM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS AWAIT $8.3B IN TOBACCO CASE FEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The zebra stripes that undulate on the avant-garde
walls at Brown Rudnick Freed &AMP; Gesmer greet visitors to a law firm
that trumpets strategic innovation, social conscience, and an
animal intensity for victory.
</P>
<P>
   They also decorate a firm that has a deal with the state to
recover the lion's share of the $2.075 billion in potential legal
fees from the state's share of the national tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   And like the lion, which often feasts on the zebra, such fees
are deemed predatory by some.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Governor Paul Cellucci has called the fee
``obscene,'' Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly has pledged to fight
such an award, and ordinary citizens are left shaking their heads
at the prospect of such mind-boggling riches.
</P>
<P>
   The firm, along with a handful of others, has a similar deal
with the city of Boston for 25 percent of any settlement or award
in the city's suit against gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Within the high-rise offices at One Financial Center, where
Brown Rudnick lawyers await arbitration on their fees in the
tobacco case, the talk is of years of painstaking labor, enormous
corporate risk, and the willingness to do the right thing for
millions of lung cancer victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``This piece of litigation was the most labor-intensive
litigation effort in the history of the commonwealth,'' said Thomas
M. Sobol, lead attorney in the case against what he called ``the
most powerful civil litigant in the history of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown Rudnick took on a Big Tobacco behemoth that had never
settled a lawsuit, never mind lost one.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other major (Boston) firm was willing to take this on,''
Brown Rudnick partner Daniel D. Sullivan said. ``Frankly, the idea
that there would be a large cash settlement never occurred to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts will receive $8.3 billion from the national
tobacco settlement to help cover the cost of treating
smoking-related illnesses. Under their original deal with the
state, five firms would share 25 percent of the settlement, or
$2.075 billion in legal fees, with most of that expected to go to
Brown Rudnick, the lead firm in the case.
</P>
<P>
   But the national tobacco settlement last November set up an
arbitration process for paying legal fees, separate from any
previous deals law firms may have cut with states.
</P>
<P>
   Under that process, which could be concluded for Massachusetts
this week, Brown Rudnick and the four other firms are likely to get
substantially less. The other firms, according to legal sources,
have asked for a one-time payment of $400 million; the tobacco
industry is said to have countered with $100 million over 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Any fees awarded Massachusetts through arbitration would be paid
by the tobacco industry and would not be deducted from the state's
share of the national tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   But if Brown Rudnick is unhappy with the award, legal sources
said, it could ask the state to honor its deal for $2.075 billion
in legal fees. And that amount would be deducted from the state's
$8.3 billion tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   To many, the prospect of paying lawyers more than $2 billion out
of the state's settlement symbolizes runaway corporate greed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frightening when states team up with trial lawyers to
effectuate these types of situations and these types of fees,''
said J.V. Schwan, counsel for civil justice reform at the
Washington-based Citizens for a Sound Economy. ``It gives them more
money than they know what to do with'' and encourages ``giving
boatloads of money to politicians who are friendly to their
causes.''
</P>
<P>
   States should pay on an hourly or flat-fee basis, Schwan said.
Otherwise, he added, ``It's dangerous to the voters, it's dangerous
to the legislatures, and it's simply bad policy to hire lawyers on
contingency fees.''
</P>
<P>
   Sobol and other Brown Rudnick lawyers contributed a total of
$7,225 to then-Attorney General Scott Harshbarger between 1995 and
1998, when the attorney general lost to Cellucci in the governor's
race. It was Harshbarger who decided in 1995 to take on the tobacco
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Brown Rudnick the other firms are: Schneider Reilly
Zabin &AMP; Costello, and Thornton Early &AMP; Naumes, both of Boston; Ness
Motley Loadholt Richardson &AMP; Poole of Charleston, S.C.; and Lieff
Cabrasser Heimann &AMP; Bernstein of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   When Harshbarger decided to sue the tobacco industry, Brown
Rudnick stepped up. For a 150-lawyer firm that did not have a
full-time health-care lawyer before 1991, the move was audacious.
Moreover, Sullivan said, ``It was the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Massachusetts was the fifth state to consider
litigation against the tobacco industry, seeking to recover some of
the billions of dollars spent treating the victims of
smoking-related diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco suit ``was litigation that I would not have gone
near because of the risk,'' said Boston medical malpractice lawyer
Michael Mone, who testified by videotape for the arbitration panel.
``That was a case on which you could literally bet the future
existence of your firm. There were potentially thousands of hours
of work, and very high costs for expert analysis and statistical
analysis in a case that no one had ever won.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown Rudnick cloaks its motivation in idealism, part of the
bold yet caring image that the 51-year-old firm wants to project.
Specializing in corporate and financial law, its promotional
literature declares: ``Nothing by rote. No pat formulas.''
</P>
<P>
   Sobol would not say whether Brown Rudnick will try to gain
additional money from the state if the arbitration award is deemed
unsatisfactory. However, he said, ``We think it is best to pursue
fees to the maximum extent possible from the tobacco industry.''
</P>
<P>
   A fight with the state does not appeal to the firm. ``We have
the best collaborative working relationship with the attorney
general's office ever in the history of the commonwealth,'' Sobol
said.
</P>
<P>
   That could sour if Brown Rudnick _ flush with, say, $200 million
from the arbitration award _ seeks to augment its payday with part
of Massachusetts' share of the national settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Brown Rudnick ``will be under tremendous pressure to accept
what's offered (in arbitration) if it's at all reasonable, because
they practice law in Massachusetts,'' said Richard Daynard, a law
professor and chairman of the Northeastern University School of
Law's Tobacco Products Liability Project. ``As a practical matter,
they would be likely to accept anything they saw as a fair
amount.''
</P>
<P>
   Such acceptance also would protect Brown Rudnick's reputation as
one of the more socially conscious law firms in the city. Its
lawyers are encouraged to do substantial pro bono work, and the
time they spend in charitable labor is counted toward the
2,000-plus hours they are expected to bill each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is part of the culture of this firm and how people are
valued at this firm to give back of themselves to the community,''
said Ellen Lutch Trager, director of health care strategies for
Brown Rudnick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
