<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2014 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-VIDEOS-BOS &LR;      06-28 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-VIDEOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RED LINE' IS STUNNING; `GRAY'S' SUBTLE AND FUNNY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES: ``The Thin Red Line'' _ Terrence Malick's
long-awaited film, based on the James Jones novel, is a stunning
achievment of idiosyncrasy and artistry over conventional drama.
Malick rarely puts the camera where you expect it. During a battle
scene he floats the camera through the jungle as if he were bored
with the upfront action. Curiously, it also gives us a clearer idea
of combat than Steven Spielberg's ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gray's Anatomy'' _ The title, a take-off on the definitive
anatomy textbook, is an X-Ray of monologist Spalding Gray. Hip,
well-written, stunningly subtle, funny, and challenging. And, no
special effects except Gray's brilliantly constructed use of the
language.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BLOCKBUSTER BUSTER: The Wal-Mart of the video business continues
its Godzillian march toward video outlet domination. Just how much
power is concentrated in Mega-Blue? According to Video Business
magazine, Dreamworks shipped 1.2 million VHS copies of ``Saving
Private Ryan.'' Blockbuster received 600,000-650,000 of those
tapes. Traditional wholesalers purchased 300,000 copies and the
rest were shipped to Rentrak, a major distributor, and other
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMING VHS ATTRACTIONS: July 6: ``Affliction,'' ``The King and
I'' (cartoon), ``Hilary and Jackie,'' ``Desert Winds,'' ``Kidnapped
in Paradise,'' ``Siberian Lady MacBeth,'' ``The Red and the
