<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2016 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-HOSPITAL-SHORTFALL     06-28 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-HOSPITAL-SHORTFALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIAL CITES SHORTFALL IN MENTAL CARE FOR YOUTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DORIS SUE WONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Suicidal and violent youngsters are languishing in
hospital emergency rooms for hours and in pediatric beds for days _
and are sometimes simply sent home with panic-stricken parents _
because Massachusetts psychiatric hospitals have no room for them.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprisingly frank letter this month to two fellow
commissioners, state mental health commissioner Marylou Sudders
warned that the demand for acute psychiatric hospital beds for
children and adolescents has reached ``near crisis proportions.''
</P>
<P>
   In the June 10 letter to acting Department of Social Services
commissioner Jeffrey Locke and Bruce Bullen, commissioner of the
Division of Medical Assistance, which is responsible for acute-care
health coverage for the poor, Sudder said that on that day in
Boston alone there were eight children who needed psychiatric
hospitalization but were being held in medical and surgical wards.
</P>
<P>
   Sudders said her agency had received more than a half-dozen
calls from private hospitals asking permission to place children in
adult psychiatric units _ a violation of state law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the state normally sees a drop-off in
hospitalizations in the summer months, that does not appear to be
happening, rather, the tragedy in Littleton, Colorado, is only
increasing the demand for care at all levels,'' wrote Sudders.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of mental-health advocacy groups, who have long
argued for more hospital beds for troubled youths, cheered
Sudders's letter and said they agreed with her dire assessment of
the state's ability to treat seriously troubled children.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are basically being watched and kept safe, but they are
not getting the treatment they need,'' said Lisa Lambert of Parents
Professional Advocacy League, a children's mental health advocacy
group. ``We wouldn't ask a child with leukemia to wait or send the
child two states away for treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Willett of Pepperell had to wait last fall when her
14-year-old son, Michael, already diagnosed with
obsessive-compulsive disorder, became more seriously ill.
</P>
<P>
   After she found him sobbing and collapsed in his room, saying
voices were telling him he was bad and to kill himself, her son
agreed to go to a psychiatric hospital and even packed a bag in
preparation.
</P>
<P>
   But within an hour, Willett said, his psychiatrist called to
break the news that no beds were available.
</P>
<P>
   Although Michael was heavily medicated, Willett and her husband
stayed up half the night, watching to make sure he didn't hurt
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was terrifying,'' said Willett, who later learned her son
was schizophrenic. ``It's not the same thing as a toothache. You
can't take medication for the pain and just wait. He could have
been dead that night.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of children in need of acute psychiatric care tends
to undergo seasonal and even daily fluctuations. Friday, for
example, about two dozen out of the 376 acute psychiatric beds for
youngsters were available, according to Division Medical of
Assistance spokesman Richard McGrail.
</P>
<P>
   On many days, the system is overbooked. The logjam has been made
worse with the recent closing of the New England Regional Center in
Stoneham and Charter Brookside in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, demand for mental health services for children
and adolescents has only grown since the student shootings at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., which has made parents,
teachers, and mental health professionals more vigilant about
trying to make sure troubled youngsters get help, say advocates and
mental health professionals.
</P>
<P>
   David Mattioto, head of the Massachusetts Association of
Behavioral Health Systems, which represents psychiatric hospitals,
estimated 20 to 30 youngsters in need of acute care are turned away
each day because an equal number of youngsters are ``stuck'' in
short-term psychiatric hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The ``stuck kids,'' many of whom are in the custody of the state
Department of Social Services, are ready to move into other
programs such as long-term psychiatric hospitals, residential
treatment centers, and foster homes.
</P>
<P>
   But those programs often have long waiting lists. And some
residential treatment programs _ still jittery following the
restraint-related death of 16-year-old Mark Soares in a Marlborough
group home last year _ are refusing to take in youngsters they feel
ill-equipped to handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``With managed care, psychiatric hospitals don't do what they
are supposed to do,'' said Locke, whose agency has about 200
residential treatment beds under contract. ``They say, `Forty-eight
hours ago this child came in eating razor blades. We have adjusted
the child's medication and the child says they aren't hungry. Here,
the child is yours.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Locke said many stuck youngsters also tend to have multiple and
complex mental health problems no single program can deal with.
</P>
<P>
   The growth in the number of youngsters with serious mental
health problems is not a recent phenomenon, but has been taking
place over a number of years.
</P>
<P>
   David R. DeMaso, associate chief of psychiatry at Children's
Hospital in Boston, said that in 1992 an average of 35 youngsters,
ranging in age from 2 1/2 to 19, showed up in the emergency room
each month in need of mental health treatment.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, the monthly average has been 90.
</P>
<P>
   State officials have been meeting in recent months to try to
address the logjam in the child and adolescent mental health
system.
</P>
<P>
   DSS plans to provide more funding to residential treatment
programs so they can hire more mental health staff workers, Locke
said.
</P>
<P>
   McGrail said 25 acute-care and transitional-care beds have been
added to the psychiatric hospital system since April and there are
plans to add as many as 80 more this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Psychiatric hospitals also have been negotiating with state
officials over state payment rates for stuck youngsters. The state
payment rate drops from $700 to $150 a day for children who no
longer need to be in psychiatric hospitals, a policy hospitals say
is placing them in financial jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Not all are convinced the problem will be easily solved.
</P>
<P>
   State officials such as Sudders and Locke say state agencies
must work together to get a clear picture of how many youngsters
are in need of mental health services _ and how many are being
turned away.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wonder how a mental health system dealing with kids could
be so messed up,'' said Locke. ``I am not confident we have found
all the answers yet. But everyone is working in the right direction
and I think we are all committed to seeing this stop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
