<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``Big Daddy'' Adam Sandler softens the usual gross-out
stuff by putting a kid between himself and it. It's a clever enough
piece of manipulation, though not so clever that you're ever
unaware you're watching strings being blatantly pulled. Sandler is
a good-hearted slacker who finds himself pushed into adulthood by
playing father to his absent roommate's kid. Still, you'll likely
laugh often enough to put up with it. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   !!1 1/2 ``Eternity and a Day'' Greek filmmaker Theo
Angelopoulos's intimate epic about an aging poet (Bruno Ganz)
getting ready to die turns into a poetic meditation on life and the
things that give it flavor. There are times when the film slows
down, but its aspirations are so high and its rewards are so deep
that they more than repay the response it asks. (Unrated) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   !!!! ``An Ideal Husband'' Sheer delight, as filmmaker Oliver
Parker finds ways to update Oscar Wilde with sparkle and nuance,
exchanging farce for comedy and comedy for romance. It's
brilliantly played by a lively and silken ensemble that includes
Cate Blanchett, Jeremy Northam, Julianne Moore, Minnie Driver, and
Rupert Everett, drolly underplaying (in ways he never could in a
stage production) the central role of a dandy unable to conceal his
generous heart beneath Wilde's wit. (PG-13)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
