<SLUG> BC-CONOMIKES-RETIRES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONOMIKES ANNOUNCES RETIREMENT AS PRESIDENT OF HEARST-ARGYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John G. Conomikes, president and co-chief executive
officer of Hearst-Argyle Television, Inc., announced Monday that he
will retire at the end of the month, concluding nearly 45 years in
the broadcasting industry.
</P>
<P>
   Conomikes will be succeeded as president and co-chief executive
by David J. Barrett, currently executive vice president and chief
operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett in turn will be succeeded as chief operating officer by
Anthony J. Vinciquerra, who will retain his title of executive vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Conomikes, who began his broadcasting career in 1955 and joined
Hearst's WTAE-TV in Pittsburgh in 1959, remains a director and
chairman of the executive committee of Hearst-Argyle Television as
well as a corporate vice president and a director of The Hearst
Corporation, Hearst-Argyle's majority shareholder. He is also a
trustee of the trust established under the will of William Randolph
Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Marbut, is chairman of co-chief executive officer of
Hearst-Argyle.
</P>
<P>
   At WTAE-TV, Conomikes served in various sales positions before
becoming vice president and general manager in 1970. He was named
general manager of television for The Hearst Corporation in 1981,
and was elected a vice president of the corporation and general
manager of Hearst Broadcasting, then a three-station TV group, in
1983. In August 1997 the Hearst broadcast group merged with Argyle
Television, Inc. and is today, as Hearst-Argyle, a 26-station
group.
</P>
<P>
   Conomikes serves on the boards of the International Radio &AMP;
Television Society Foundation and the Association for Maximum
Service Television Inc. He is chairman of the Television Operators
Caucus and is an Honorary Trustee of The Foundation of American
Women in Radio and Television.
</P>
<P>
   He is a past chairman of the ABC Television Affiliates
Association and served two terms on the boards of the National
Association of Broadcasters and the Television Bureau of
Advertising. Conomikes is also a member of the Board of Trustees of
the University of Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, in addition to his new role as president and co-chief
executive officer, continues as a director of Hearst-Argyle
Television and of The Hearst Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the formation of Hearst-Argyle Television, Barrett was
a vice president of The Hearst Corporation and deputy general
manager of the broadcasting group.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, he was vice president and general manager of
Hearst's WBAL Division. He joined Hearst in 1984 as general manager
of the Baltimore radio properties.
</P>
<P>
   Before Hearst, Barrett held vice president and general manager
positions with Doubleday Broadcasting in St. Louis (KWK-AM/FM), and
Washington, D.C., (WAVA-FM). He began his broadcast career in
Chicago as a sales executive before relocating to Canada where he
held senior management positions at radio stations in Montreal and
Toronto. At age 24, Barrett was named general manager of Montreal's
CHOM-FM.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett is the recent past chairman of the ABC Television
Affiliates Association, comprised of ABC's 223 affiliated stations.
He is also a board member of the Ad Council and of the National
Association of Broadcasters. A native of Chicago, he attended
Loyola University there.
</P>
<P>
   Vinciquerra has served as executive vice president since
Hearst-Argyle's formation. He joined the Hearst broadcasting group
in May 1997 as group executive. Previously, he was executive vice
president of the CBS Television Station Group, overseeing a number
of the CBS owned-and-operated stations.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, he was vice president and general manager of KYW-TV
in Philadelphia. Prior to KYW, he was vice president and station
manager of WBZ-TV, Boston. He began his media career in advertising
sales at the Albany (N.Y.) Times Union newspaper, owned by The
Hearst Corporation. He later moved into broadcasting with Hearst as
a sales manager at WTAE-TV in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Vinciquerra serves as a director of the Television Bureau of
Advertising and the National Association of Television Program
Executives. He is also a director of the Boston-based Genesis Fund,
the fundraising organization of the National Birth Defects
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Albany, he graduated from the State University of
New York there.
</P>
</TEXT>
