<HEADER>
A2023 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-CENTURY-BOS &LR;      06-28 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CENTURY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VIRTUAL NOVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
TURN OF THE CENTURY 
By Kurt Andersen. Random House. 659 pp. $24.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With its mag wheels and major torque, Kurt Andersen's ``Turn of
the Century'' is the killer SUV of the summer: It's big and
unwieldy and way over-powered, but it's also flashy and
symbolically cool _ a semiotic key-card into the land of In. Some
of the atmospheric pressure surrounding the novel is based on
authorial vita. One of the cofounders and editors of Spy magazine
(which managed to be legendarily funny within its first five
minutes on the newsstands), Andersen has high-gloss media
credentials that include New York magazine (former editor), Time
(former architecture and design critic), and The New Yorker
(current columnist). All of which make him eminently qualified to
take on Manhattan as subject, target, and major character of this
gargantuan first novel. And there's no argument that ``Turn of the
Century'' is brimming with wit, intelligence, and double-cappuccino
cleverness. What it doesn't possess is much evidence that Andersen
knows how _ or why _ to write a novel. Or, it must be added, when
to end one.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the creepily familiar cyberworld of the day after
tomorrow, ``Turn of the Century'' opens in February 2000, in a New
York where cell phones ring at funerals and where Prada and the
price of Microsoft matter more than God. It's today taken up a
notch, in other words: a virtually realistic New York from Hell _
exactingly depicted here in computer and stock-market patois,
saturated with pop culture and media references and fueled by its
own near-nihilistic irony. Imagine Jay McInerney's love-hate affair
with New York crossed with Tom Wolfe's unstoppable satire, and
you'll get an idea of this novel's hybrid impulses. But that
description stops short of capturing Andersen's byzantine grasp of
the arcane, artificial world a lot of postmodern powerbrokers
inhabit: that place where everything, including sex and money,
happens on screen. Oh, and cyber-death. Leave it to a couple of
hackers to try to accomplish that.
</P>
<P>
   The Ken and Barbie at the center of this high-pixel coldness are
George Mactier and his wife, Lizzie Zimbalist. Besides their three
precocious children (the youngest is death-obsessed), they have
important careers to parent. He's a producer for MBC, the brazen
new TV network run by Harold Mose; she's a software maverick and
Harvard MBA trying to run her own company and stay out of Bill
Gates's way. Or in it, for the price. Much of ``Turn of the
Century'' involves the steaming behemoth that is Microsoft, from
its NASDAQ worth at day's close to the virtual existence, or lack
thereof, of the wealthy misfit who runs it. Married for a decade,
George and Lizzie are a prime-time-of-life couple who started out
pretty normal _ Minnesota boy and LA girl _ each of them now more
successful than they ever dreamed and riding the wave. Which has
its cost: When George's mother is killed in a car accident in the
opening pages of the novel, his overriding concern is the
new-series presentation for Mose he has scheduled that evening.
</P>
<P>
   That bit of virtual grief, delivered deadpan, is supposed to set
the tone of the novel _ meant to signal that real emotion has been
traded for Nielsen-number thrills, and that even the ambient noise
here will be over-the-top. What ensues is in keeping with that
message, with Lizzie and George lurching among LA, Seattle, Tokyo,
and New York, each consumed with the absurd cruelties of fame and
success. George's pet project, hailed and feared by critics before
it's even in production, is a factoid-fiction show called ``Real
Time,'' where actors read the news, and invented ``dramedy'' is
spliced into world-events copy. Torn among the demands of
motherhood in New York and a dying father in LA, Lizzie is having
dinner with guys like Buster Grinspoon, who has been doing brain
implants on cats and thinks artificial intelligence is about to be
smarter than Einstein. Then Harold Mose tries to hire her as his
in-house media genius, and the discrete spheres of Mactier et
Zimbalist have become, whether they like it or not, a conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   Their newly blended corporate family takes the story into the
realm of black screwball comedy, with George assuming that Lizzie
is sleeping with Mose and Lizzie assuming George is losing his
mind. Neither fear turns out to be true, but their interminable
quests to find that out make Myst look like a game of computer
solitaire by comparison. The straight line between fact and
revelation _ George and Lizzie talking, in other words _ has been
replaced by the garbled web of the modern age: e-mail and
cyber-stalking and memos left in town cars, or rumor and electronic
pagers and misplaced power books. The ultimate example of this
media manipulation is George's visit to a psychiatrist, a man who
is his and Lizzie's mutual friend. Wanting to convince George of
his wife's fidelity, the shrink reveals that he's been snooping in
his own girlfriend's e-mail, where the only ``hard'' truth about
Lizzie's innocence exists.
</P>
<P>
   There are also countless subplots, the best of them involving a
trio of hackers who break into Reuters, a financial wizard with a
golden heart who can make Wall Street swoon with a click of his
finger, and a limo driver with a strange accent who used to work
for Microsoft. There are weird characters galore: Harold's TV
wizard, Featherstone, who speaks only in cliche and hyperbole;
George's brother-in-law, Cubby, who has spent his life building a
miniature model city that no one will ever see _ a job that seems
more meaningful than any in the novel. And there are about 19 witty
lines and insider jokes per page, which is amusing and impressive
at first, then tiresome, then enervating. About halfway through the
nearly 700 pages of this kind of high-IQ cleverness, you start to
feel as though you're trapped in e-mail jail _ where you get
distribution-list nonsense that goes on forever, but you have to
keep reading to see if anything important is encrypted therein.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen's intelligence is unquestionable. He is funny, shrewd,
and erudite, and he has a facility for the set piece, whether it's
Lizzie's power golf with the guys or George's meeting with a
Hollywood wonder boy. What Andersen doesn't have, or at least
doesn't exhibit here, is the novelist's heart _ the sensibility
that knows the difference between dialogue and depth, and that can
convince us that any of this matters. We learn piecemeal, for
instance, that George has lost part of his arm to a mortar shell in
Nicaragua, when he was a journalist for Newsweek, but this
information is used so poorly _ either as farce or as nonchalant
pathos _ that it winds up seeming irrelevant. The most humanly
revealing parts of the novel are few and far between; when they're
introduced at all, it's often at their own expense, and
consequently more contrived than revealing. Deus ex machina nova.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to love this novel, even if it is too long by half. It
starts off with delightful gusto and street-smart skepticism, and
then it keeps on repeating the same high-wire tricks. In the
paradox that defines so much of art, satire, to work, must have a
perceptible emotional and moral center _ otherwise it strays toward
the empty towers of cynicism and nihilism. Andersen's emotional
center appears far too seldom and too late in ``Turn of the
Century,'' which falls victim to its own satirical devices. And as
the writers of George's fact 'n' fiction show might tell you, if
you don't believe it, you've at least got to care.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is chief book critic of The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
