<HEADLINE>
ON-LINE BANKING SHOULD BE DONE WITH CAUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN AND BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You'd think Bob Kerwin would be clutching his old-fashioned
checkbook after his horrendous first experience paying a bill
through BankBoston's on-line banking system.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he still finds some benefits to using the bank's
HomeLink program. But he has learned the hard way _ through a
four-month ordeal that included mis-sent funds, dozens of
``customer-relations'' phone calls, conflicting explanations and a
temporarily canceled credit card _ that on-line banking has some
risks that are worth avoiding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very selective about what bills I pay using HomeLink,''
said Kerwin, a 37-year-old software salesman.
</P>
<P>
   It was late February when Kerwin made his debut click with the
BankBoston's popular on-line banking system. He picked a relatively
simple transaction: He requested that a $300 check be drawn from
his BankBoston checking account and sent to his BankBoston Visa
account to pay a monthly bill.
</P>
<P>
   He figured it was an easy transaction, which would require only
one easily-cut check mailed directly to BankBoston Visa. Also, the
money essentially was being transferred within the same institution
and the amount was a nice flat sum.
</P>
<P>
   But about two weeks later, on March 13, BankBoston Visa informed
him that they never received his check. Because of nonpayment, the
credit card was temporarily shut off and marked delinquent.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Kerwin called the HomeLink program. It showed they
sent a $300 check to BankBoston Visa and the check cleared on March
3.
</P>
<P>
   What gives?
</P>
<P>
   After four months of an exhaustive, one-man crusade to correct
the problem, Kerwin discovered that his $300 check mistakenly went
to Fleet Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In April, he managed to get a clerk to give him a copy of the
cashed check. The ``payee endorsement'' section of the back of the
cashed check showed a stamp from Fleet Bank in Medford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Kerwin presented it to BankBoston officials, but it wasn't good
enough to get him off the hook. They declined to credit him $300 in
his checking or credit card accounts.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston Visa and HomeLink officials insisted they couldn't
fix the problem until they got the $300 back from Fleet, and, at
various times, suggested more investigation needed to be done.
</P>
<P>
   As if it were some grand gesture of generosity, BankBoston Visa
officials told him in April they would no longer label his account
past-due and they would raise his credit limit from $7,000 to
$7,300.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been out my $300 since the beginning of March,'' said
Kerwin, after e-mailing us for help. ``We're now at the end of
June. Why should I be out the money? It's not my mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   When we made some calls last week, BankBoston officials
confirmed the check mistakenly got into the hands of Fleet Bank in
a bizarre glitch that BankBoston officials say has nothing to do
with the proposed merger of the institutions.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston spokesman Bruce Spitzer said he has yet to figure out
the exact problem, but believes it was caused either by a coding
mistake or clerical problems at either the HomeLink or Visa
check-processing centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did go to Fleet, but we don't know how it got there,''
Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the face of the check says BankBoston Visa,
Fleet cashed the check and got the money.
</P>
<P>
   Kerwin said he's a reasonable guy and knows life is full of
innocent mistakes. But he is baffled at how long it has taken
BankBoston to correct the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said the bank is issuing an apology to Kerwin about the
long ordeal and has credited his account $300.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regret the amount of time it has taken to come up with the
answers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said the bank has now set up Kerwin's HomeLink account
so that, in the future, Kerwin can transfer funds directly from his
checking account to his Visa account, eliminating any need to cut a
check. If you don't use this transfer system, the only way now to
pay such BankBoston Visa bills on-line is through individually cut
checks.
</P>
<P>
   He insists such problems are extremely rare with the HomeLink
program, which has 350,000 customers and 22 percent of the bank's
retail customers.
</P>
<P>
   For Kerwin, he's pleased to finally get his $300 and now feels
as if this sobering experience has taught him about the possible
drawbacks of the on-line banking world. He said he now uses on-line
banking only for registered vendors, such as some phone companies
or department stores that can receive HomeLink payments directly,
without the need for checks.
</P>
<P>
   He said he also thinks twice before using on-line banking for
big important bills, such as mortgage payments that have strict due
dates. He can't bear the thought of another lost check.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to hold onto his money longer. When HomeLink cuts
a check, your money is deducted almost immediately. It's sent into
limbo land, collecting no interest, until the payee cashes it. With
traditional checks, you hold onto the money until the check clears.
</P>
<P>
   Kerwin said he hopes this one consumer fiasco is his last.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I got my $300 back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Defective stroller fiasco
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A mother of infant twins sent us a letter complaining that
Boston Baby in Newton, Mass. refused to exchange a defective
double-stroller she bought this year.
</P>
<P>
   As Kathryn Delhome puts it, she bought the Graco
double-stroller, called Duo Rider, last January at this baby
mega-store, along with $5,000 in baby furniture and car seats. She
didn't start using the stroller until the warm weather in April,
and within two months, the strap for one of the seats broke.
</P>
<P>
   When she pursued the problem with the store, the managers told
her to call Graco. When Delhome called Graco, the company said they
could ship her a new seat with a new strap, but she would probably
not get it until August. Furious, she went back to the store and
was again told it couldn't do a thing.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to state law, the store has direct responsibility
for bad goods. Merchants are allowed to set any refund policy they
want for nondefective goods, but they must refund, replace or
repair _ it's the customer's choice _ any defective merchandise
sold at their store, said assistant attorney general Diane
Szafarowicz.
</P>
<P>
   We called owner Harvey Slobodkian on Thursday, inquiring about
this case. He initially defended the store's actions, saying he
hadn't ruled out ``consumer abuse'' in explaining the broken strap.
He also said he found it difficult to talk to the couple because
they were so angry at him.
</P>
<P>
   Later, however, he said he would provide them with a new harness
at no charge for the stroller, or if necessary, he'd comply with
their request for a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   But Delhome said she's just going to wait for the Graco-shipped
seat because she doesn't want to re-enter Boston Baby. ``I don't
want to deal with the store again,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Odds &AMP; ends
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Revenge for telemarketer calls. What do you do when a
telemarketing firm calls you repeatedly after you tell them to
stop? The answer is that you have legal recourse, but it's not
easy, state officials say. First, you must document as much as you
can, including dates and times of the calls and the name of the
company and callers. Tell them you want to be on their do-not-call
list. If you can prove the repeated calls caused you to incur at
least $50,000 in damages (such as getting tricked into a fraudulent
deal), you can sue in federal court under the telemarketing sales
law. If it was an automated-voice call, you can sue in small claims
court. But still the hassle falls in your lap. The best bet is
probably to call your state's attorney general's office with your
data. They have the power to bring action if they get repeated
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   --Phone fee increase. Four weeks ago we told you about a way for
low-volume phone users to avoid some of the fees popping up on
their long-distance bills. We suggested doing away with your
long-distance carrier and using a dial-around company (the 10-10
numbers), a prepaid calling card or an Internet calling system to
make your calls. At the time, the only fee involved with this
approach was a 53-cent-a-month charge to cover the cost of
long-distance access. Now we have learned that as of July 1, that
fee will rise to $1.04 for primary lines, $2.53 for nonprimary
lines. The increase cuts the amount of savings, but it still may
make sense. After all, fees assessed by long-distance companies are
also expected to rise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(If you have a consumer tip, e-mail mohl(at)globe.com or
wen(at)globe.com, or write Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
