<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2028 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-CARAVAGGIO-BOS &LR;      06-28 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CARAVAGGIO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAUGHTY BOY WITH A BRUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
CARAVAGGIO 
A Life 
By Helen Langdon. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. 436 pp. Illustrated.
$30. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three full-length biographies, several important interpretive
studies, a couple of crime novels. That's the list of books on the
Italian painter Caravaggio published in just the last year, just in
English. And it doesn't count catalogs for exhibitions that
included stellar shows at the Boston College Museum of Art and the
Wadsworth Atheneum in Hartford, which owns the only Caravaggio in
New England, ``The Ecstasy of St. Francis.'' (It's on tour until
mid-July, when the Atheneum puts it back on view.) The attendance
at the BC show _ almost 66,000 _ set a record for the museum. Then
there's Derek Jarman's 1986 feature film, ``Caravaggio,'' which got
a jump on the craze.
</P>
<P>
   What is it about Michelangelo Merisi, born in 1571 in the small
Lombard town of Caravaggio, that fascinates so? British author and
art historian Helen Langdon attempts to figure it out in
``Caravaggio: A Life,'' the latest of the biographies. On the
surface, the reasons for the painter's allure are obvious. He was
the original bad-boy artist. He divided his time between street
gangs and sybaritic cardinals. He was an habitue of Italian jails.
He was also, people have assumed all along, a homosexual; hence the
bee-stung lips and come-hither eyes of those pale male musicians he
painted. He was a murderer who spent the last months of his life on
the lam. Even on the run he had enough friends in high places to be
made a Knight of Malta, an honor stripped from him after an
involvement in a Malta brawl. Pardoned by the pope, he was
returning to Rome when he died, somewhat mysteriously, in the
summer of 1610.
</P>
<P>
   Book-worthy? You bet. But Langdon resists sensationalism in
favor of facts. Alas, the facts are few. You sense her frustration
at cold trails and missing evidence. Consider a sentence that
starts with an exasperated ``It is extremely unclear what he was
doing through this period, and no paintings remain . . .'' She's
obviously a zealous researcher; he, the most elusive of artists. In
a sense, author and subject are as much at odds as the protagonists
in Caravaggio's ``Judith and Holofernes,'' with its self-righteous
Judith sawing methodically through Holofernes' neck, undaunted by
the blood spurting forth. You can almost imagine it's Langdon,
getting even with Caravaggio at the lack of solid info he left
behind.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she soldiers on, providing a long account of a short
life. Her strong suits here are two. One is her descriptions of the
paintings, many of which are reproduced in color _ in very small
scale, unfortunately. The other is the elaborate context she
creates. She explains how patronage and building projects operated
in papal Rome, and explains the temper of the times. Sure,
Caravaggio was violent, but he lived in an age of gangs and
murders. His behavior was typical. He also lived in an age of
feverish gambling among low-life types and huge interest in music
among the intelligentsia. His paintings of card sharps and
lutenists didn't come out of nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   About those lutenists. Langdon doesn't buy the argument that the
provocative boys in Caravaggio's paintings are evidence of his
homosexuality. She traces that notion to a 17th-century English
traveler's spurious jottings, and to English tourists who were, she
writes, ``so convinced that sodomy was a favorite Italian
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   From the moment he picked up a paintbrush, Caravaggio has gone
in and out of favor _ very quickly in his own era, at a slower pace
in subsequent centuries. He was a nonentity in the 1800s; his star
rose with a series of shows and studies in the 1950s. He's now
recognized as the most modern of 17th-century artists, perhaps the
only one who can make religion relevant to contemporary viewers.
That's what he did in his own day, when the Counter-Reformation was
fighting back against Protestant personal piety with images
designed to stun strays into submission.
</P>
<P>
   The Roman Catholic Church of Caravaggio's day _ whose princes
were among his greatest patrons _ advocated an accessible, clear,
emotionally stimulating style of painting. Langdon makes it sound
Norman Rockwell-ish, and offers a suitably bland example in
Scipione Pulzone's ``Holy Family.''
</P>
<P>
   Caravaggio, never bland, took this mandate and created the
painting equivalent of Shakespeare in modern dress. As models for
the saints, he used whores and riff-raff, clad in grubby street
clothes. His earthy naturalism fit Catholicism's aim of making
viewers identify with stories of the saints _ to the point of
self-flagellation. Caravaggio's canvases might not make
late-20th-century viewers beat their bare backs, but these images
can still make them weep.
</P>
<P>
   But Caravaggio took naturalism to an extreme. Some of his
paintings were rejected by the very people who had commissioned
them _ and were horrified with the results. The Discalced
Carmelites turned down Caravaggio's ``Dormition of the Virgin''
because the Virgin was dirty, swollen, barefoot, and obviously
modeled on a prostitute who was the artist's own lover. She was, in
short, not their idea of the Queen of Heaven. But other patrons
appreciated Caravaggio's shock tactics: Their co-opting of his
radicalism was a little like what might have happened if the
National Endowment for the Arts had harnessed Robert Mapplethorpe
instead of reviling him.
</P>
<P>
   For all its downplaying of sensationalism, Langdon's book is
strong on stranger-than-fiction truths like the preparations for
the Jubilee Year of 1600, including stepped-up schedules of torture
and public executions in anticipation of the apocalpytic date.
Langdon makes you glad to live in 1999 instead of 1599: The threat
of Y2K is nothing compared with this frenzy in the name of
holiness.
</P>
<P>
   Crammed with detail, Langdon's biography lacks shape;
everything's given equal weight. Desmond Seward's ``Caravaggio: A
Passionate Life'' (Morrow, 1998) is half the length, twice as
focused, and a more entertaining read, while not going off the deep
end of salaciousness _ easy to do, in writing about Caravaggio. And
for something that's all mood and no information, there's Jarman's
movie, shot in the close-up, claustrophobic style of one of
Caravaggio's paintings, even borrowing the painter's rich, dark
palette and tenebrous shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Mysteries about Caravaggio persist. What about those paintings
that disappeared during World War II? At present, there are only 50
or so works that experts accept as by his hand. One, the star of
the recent BC show, was thought to be by Gerard Honthorst until the
Dublin Jesuits who own it sent it out for a cleaning that revealed
its true identity. This kind of revelation is what keeps scholars _
and the public _ enthralled with the painter whose brush could
describe wanton pleasures and then produce pictures that are still
sublimely persuasive arguments for the Christian faith. In the
Jesuits' nocturnal ``The Taking of Christ,'' the figure of the
artist himself is at the right, holding up a lantern. It is not
only a key moment in Christianity that he illuminates, Langdon
points out. ``His holding of the light was an evangelical call to
younger artists,'' she writes, ``a revelation of the true path to
follow, a symbol of the rebirth of painting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
