<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2029 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-WEST-BOS &LR;      06-28 1429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVVY SALMA HAYEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Refusing to take no for an answer is never a
bad career move. Ask Salma Hayek. It helped Hayek that she could
say no in a couple of languages to people who said no to her, first
in her native Mexico, then, repeatedly, in Los Angeles. But ever
since she achieved high visibility in Robert Rodriguez's
``Desperado,'' she's been saying yes a lot. Her profile will be
higher than ever this week when she opens opposite Will Smith and
Kevin Kline in ``The Wild Wild West,'' a high-stakes summer entry
that straddles the comedy and action genres.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Hayek elaborates between cups of coffee at the Palm Beach
Film Festival, where she's part of the awards scene, it's an action
adventure Western comedy. ``Oh yeah, and a musical. We all get a
number in this,'' she says. ``I get to sing, Kevin gets to sing,
and Will gets to dance. I play a woman way out of her league, in
1867, pretending to be someone else, looking for somebody who's
really trouble. So she attaches herself to this duo, and they both
get crushes on her. She's sort of like a Marilyn Monroe character.
She thinks she knows what she's doing, but she hasn't got a clue.''
</P>
<P>
   The toughest part of the shoot wasn't the heat, Hayek says, or
traveling all over the West. She loved trying out a German accent
the script called on her to use in Utah. She loved the shopping in
Santa Fe. ``Toughest was the corset,'' she says. ``It was one of
those 19th-century corsets with all these buttons and strings
attached to them. I did all my own stunts. That was fun. I wished
they had more. It made me feel like one of the boys. I was such a
girl in the film, but I tell you, the best stuff was rolling around
the floor of a train at high velocity with Kevin Kline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest torment, though, was when I had to do the music
video with Will Smith.'' Smith sells a lot of records, which in
turn sell his films. ``I didn't have to, but I wanted to. We did
the video for a song that he wrote for the movie. For it, they put
tarantulas on me, real ones, like crawling all over my neck and
stuff. But the song's worth it.'' Plus, it provides Hayek with a
wonderful metaphor for the movie business. Not, she notes, that
there was anything else she ever wanted to do since she was growing
up in the Mexican town of Coatzacoalcos. ``Going through puberty, I
pretended that I had given up. I went to college and majored in
political science. But then I got fed up with the lying and
pretending.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly soaps
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So Hayek broke the news to her parents, who took it well, she
says, and got her first acting job doing children's theater in
Mexico City. Then came a TV soap opera that thrust her into a
prominence that weirded her out. ``Overnight I became very
successful because that was the No. 1 show. But nobody in my house
ever watched TV. Actually, my mom is antisoap. I had no idea what I
was doing and I said I was going back to theater because it was a
more healthy environment and I was still forming as an actress. I
picked an Alan Ayckbourn play so that I wouldn't be the star. But
people would come to see me and they would bring big cardboards
saying `I love you, Teresa,' which was the name of my character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody goes to see theater in Mexico. It is dying. But this
play sold out. Producers were seating people in the aisles. I
thought I was going on a journey of learning about myself, but this
was making the journey very confusing, so I decided to leave. I
packed my two bags, left the play in the middle of my contract, and
came to Los Angeles. I went to the Stella Adler conservatory and
was very fortunate because I got to take the last class Stella
Adler taught before she died. But I could not speak English well.
Often I couldn't understand what my homework was for the next day.
I would spend hours in the library in front of a huge dictionary,
and it would take me five times as long as anyone else because I'm
dyslexic.
</P>
<P>
   ``But little by little, I started getting better. Then I did
scenes from Shakespeare _ `Taming of the Shrew,' `Hamlet,' `Romeo
and Juliet,' `As You Like It.' In one way, it was very hard because
the dictionary didn't have words like `goest.' But I also found
Shakespeare the closest thing to the Latin world. The way he
approached language has a lot of Spanish qualities, the rhythm, the
way he sings it. Normally, when I try to speak English, I try to
diminish my accent and talk flat. But with Shakespeare it was
talking the way I normally talk. I could even move my hands and it
felt like part of the dance. Once I could understand the meaning of
the words, I found a home in Shakespeare.''
</P>
<P>
   To her surprise, Hayek found more of a home in Shakespeare than
she did in Los Angeles or, initially, in the movie business.
``Everybody tried to make me see how wrong and crazy I was,'' she
says. ``Everybody thought I was so out of my league. In Hollywood
were the first ones to try and discourage me. `Go back,' they said,
`you have no future here.' Finally, I got some roles in television.
But coming from a Spanish-speaking background put me out of the
running for every role except prostitutes and maids, to the point
where people would see my name and picture and would want to meet
me, and then they would realize I was Mexican and would send me
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I would tell them my grandfather is Lebanese, they would
say, `Pretend you're Lebanese.' Not that it's OK to be Lebanese.
But it's a little better than to be a Mexican. In the end, I don't
have to overcome prejudice. They have to overcome the prejudice. I
have a different type of conviction. And I don't take no for an
answer. And because of that, I think it has opened the eyes of some
people to perceive things as I see them. It's the accomplishment of
the industry for beginning to see it, and of me, for not giving up.
A lot of people become what they have been told they are. But I
don't, and I never will. I'm as stubborn as a mule. I'm the last
one to set myself up as a role model of any kind, because I did
things in a crazy way. I don't want anyone to imitate me. But it
can be done. It can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sold on ``Dogma''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because Hayek appreciates stubbornness, and mavericks, she
signed on for a role in Kevin Smith's ``Dogma,'' which although yet
to be released has aroused considerable controversy with its
contemporary retelling of the Christ story. ``It's very pro-God,''
Hayek says. ``We all knew it was a cause going in. My role is the
most incredible character. Are you ready for this? I play a muse
who is fed up with everybody talking about Mozart and Shakespeare
and all these grand people of the world and she gets no credit or
recognition. So she asks God to be allowed to come to earth to try
for her own fame and fortune as a writer. But when she gets here,
because she has no muse, she gets writer's block. And she ends up
having another mission on earth that she was not counting on.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayek also harnesses her visibility-raising energies on behalf
of Mexico. She's proud of the first film she made there, ``Midoq
Alley,'' based on a work by Nobel Prize-winning Naguib Mahfouz.
She's even prouder to have produced a new film of Nobel laureate
Gabriel Garcia Marquez's ``Nobody Writes to the Colonel,'' by
leading Mexican filmmaker Arturo Ripstein (she plays a small role
in it, too). Hayek also is developing a long-gestating film about
Frida Kahlo (1907-54), the legendary Mexican painter and feminist
icon.
</P>
<P>
   Hayek has headed her own production company, Ventanarosa, for
several years. She just signed a deal with Columbia to produce TV
programming in English and Spanish. Her first project is a series
about the lives of the saints. ``It's an experiment,'' Hayek says.
``They're reenactments, but the people don't talk, which I think
works very well, because special people like that you don't want to
hear their voices. You want to know their stories, and you'll see
them. Voice-overs will tell you the story. Therefore you can do it
in any language and show it in different countries. Friends are
helping me, like Antonio Banderas and (directors) Afonso Cuaron and
Guillermo Del Toro. Outrageous, wonderful stories! Not from a
religious point of view, but from an anthropological and dramatic
point of view. I'm not in them in any way whatsoever,'' Hayek says.
But the diminutive Hayek, energized and focused, is in the biz for
the long haul.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
