<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2045 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-28 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RATTO-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS BUD'S FOR YOU, BUT WHAT ABOUT BASEBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bud Selig usually has to hold the cab door open
for his fellow commissioners. Well, OK, maybe Gary Bettman is
driving the cab, but Selig has been looking up at David Stern and
Paul Tagliabue for a long time, and for a lot of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Tags had all the money and the TV ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Stern had Larry Bird and Magic Johnson and Michael Jordan and
all the TV ratings Tagliabue couldn't use. Even Bettman had Wayne
Gretzky and Mario Lemieux and the Stanley Cup playoffs, and lots of
markets into which to expand.
</P>
<P>
   Bud? He had a few strikes and lockouts, his own team faded
further and further from the national scene, he had dwindling
ratings and runaway payrolls and owners as pliant and cooperative
as the bronze statue of Stan Musial outside Busch Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Being Bud, in short, wasn't a whole lot of fun.
</P>
<P>
   But now look. Tags' ratings are down, and so is his sport's
scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, his spare time is spent keeping both sets of DeBartolos
away from the family knife drawer.
</P>
<P>
   Bettman's own sport no longer has Gretzky or Lemieux, it nearly
lost a team to a bankruptcy court, its scoring is down to mid-'60s
levels with no apparent solution despite a string of new rules
announced the day after a hugely controversial Cup final in which
he looked particularly silly.
</P>
<P>
   And Stern's sport is just finishing up a strike-mangled year, no
more Jordan and yet another
lowest-scoring-since-the-Eisenhower-administration playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Being Bud seems like an OK deal after all now.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, he's still got the odd troubled franchise, including
one that is only two years old, and his beloved Brewers are
currently the only sixth-place team in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   But scoring? Bud's got all the scoring he could want. In fact,
he's got slow-pitch softball scoring, and is one more expansion
away from out-and-out T-ball. The Colorado Rockies went through an
eight- game stretch this past week in which they scored
double-digit runs in six, and lost twice. And nobody thought
anything of it.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the games are longer than they've ever been (the Indians
are averaging three-hour, 12-minute games, and the Giants are
second at 3:08), and teams now are routinely filling half their
roster spots with pitchers because good ones are so hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody says the games are boring any more.
</P>
<P>
   For this, the owners, and Bud by extension, should be commended.
They spent a good $7 billion or so of other people's money building
stadiums smaller and cozier than their antecedents. In the last
decade, new parks have been or will be built in Atlanta, Baltimore,
Boston, Cincinnati, Cleveland, Dallas- Fort Worth, Denver, Detroit,
Houston, Milwaukee, Phoenix, Pittsburgh, San Diego, Seattle and of
course, our little burg, which spent a huge hunk of a bank's money.
None of these edifices are being called pitchers' parks.
</P>
<P>
   They also spent year upon year supervising the development of
the titanium/kryptonite alloy added to the baseballs to make them
scream, and watching as the umpires shrank the strike zone smaller
than a Big Mama Thornton commemorative postage stamp.
</P>
<P>
   They viewed with interest but no intervention as pitchers were
transformed into the finest Dresden china, spared the rigors of
four-man rotations and seven-inning starts. They whistled with
admiration the development of Coors Field as the launchingest pad
baseball has seen since the Phillies played in Baker Bowl in the
'30s (280 down the line in right, 300 to the alley in
right-center).
</P>
<P>
   In other words, they did over a great expanse of time what the
other three leagues have yet to do _ change the size and shape of
the playing surface, change the ball used and actively legislate
against the defense. More than that, they changed the culture of
those who played the game, although in fairness that was largely by
accident and owes much to the introduction of the metal bat in all
other forms of ball.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, and no matter how the credit is divided,
Bud Selig no longer has to be ashamed of his sport's product. There
is scoring like never before, Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa are folk
heroes, and Derek Jeter is being positioned by marketers and scouts
alike as the Griffey-Jordan combo plate.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, he is no longer going to have to get the door for David
Stern. Tags, of course, is another story, but we trust Bud will get
there, even if he has to live to be 135.
</P>
<P>
   Which, we suspect, he probably will, even if only to see the
look on Don Fehr's face when he does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
