<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, June 29.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STEM-CELLS (Bethesda, Md.) _ The presidential bioethics
advisory commission struggles over the issue of whether federally
financed researchers should be allowed to obtain primordial human
cells from embryos. The cells offer potentially giant advantages in
treating a range of diseases, but opponents of abortion, among
others, say it is immoral to obtain them from embryos. By Nicholas
Wade.
</P>
<P>
   This story was also listed on the AM-NYT-BUDGET.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AMISH-GENES (Undated) _ The Amish and Mennonites may forgo
most modern conveniences, but there is one bit of progress that
they are especially eager to embrace: gene therapy. Three children
from these communities are expected to become the first humans ever
to test a new method of gene therapy. If it works, it will spare
them the devastating effects of a rare but deadly inherited disease
known as Crigler-Najjar syndrome. It occurs when a substance called
bilirubin, a waste product from the destruction of worn out red
blood cells, builds up in the body and destroys the liver and grows
toxic to the nervous system. By Denise Grady. (2800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GLOBAL-WARMING (Undated) _ As evidence that the earth's
atmosphere is warming continues to accumulate, scientists are
making slow progress toward an answer to the big, frustrating
climatic question of the day: How much of the warming can be
attributed to human activity and how much to natural causes? By
William K. Stevens. (2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEUTRINO (Undated) _ A team of Japanese, American and Korean
scientists announced Monday that they had for the first time fired
a neutrino particle through a 155-mile slice of the earth's crust
and recorded its arrival at the surface. By Malcolm W. Browne. (550
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LEFTHANDED-DNA (Undated) _ Scientists at MIT have discovered
that Z-DNA, or the left-handed DNA strand, is more than an oddity.
In research described in a recent issue of the journal Science,
they found that nature does make and use a left-handed DNA, and its
role in the regulation of the chemistry of life might be quite
important. By Philip J. Hilts. (680 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ABALONE (Undated) _ Scientists at the University of
California at Santa Barbara have uncovered the secret to abalone's
remarkable strength, and the findings may help in the development
of a new class of strong, lightweight materials. By Henry Fountain.
(600 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SMALL (Undated) _ An essay: Miniaturization has become a
vital attribute of technology; but, at a certain point, it can go
no further. One example in particular is the computer chip. By
Malcolm W. Browne. (1135 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Shorts on science: Items on the chirp of
ancient crickets based on fossil data, the increasingly dangerous
junk in space and killer bees in Florida. (570 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DAIRY-DIET (Undated) _ With the deliberations in full swing
for revisions of the federal Dietary Guidelines for All Americans,
to be reissued next year, what started as a mild controversy is
fast progressing into a contentious argument: Should the government
recommend dairy products as part of a balanced diet, given that
once most nonwhites leave childhood, they cannot easily digest the
products. By David France. (1140 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: Poison
ivy dermatitis is not so easy to avoid, but prevention is possible.
When that fails, quick recognition of an outbreak and appropriate
action can greatly reduce its severity and the resulting
discomfort. Unfortunately, myths and misconceptions about it abound
and all too often result in extensive outbreaks that require
medical attention. By Jane E. Brody. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HIV-YOUNG (Undated) _ A study of young people showed they
believed HIV could not affect them, but they were still willing to
be tested for it. By Alisa Tang. (570 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEALTH-DECEPTION (Undated) _ A look at patients who lie to
doctors for reasons as diverse as getting out of work, getting
attention, evading prosecution or receiving drugs. Some even
deceive themselves. By Sandeep Jauhar, M.D. (970 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TRAMPOLINE-FITNESS (Undated) _ Next year, trampolining will
become an Olympic sport, combining the high drama of diving with
the fluidity of figure skating. By Nancy Stedman. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TRAMPOLINE-KIDS (Undated) _ Though afficionados of
trampolining hope that the Olympics will inspire children to
participate, some doctors don't share their enthusiasm. (380 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Shorts on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Pro &AMP; Con: Should potential employees have to pass a physical
fitness test before being hired for a job, and are physical
performance standards discriminatory when used as criteria for job
hiring?
</P>
<P>
   _ Soaking meat in some kinds of marinade can reduce the risk of
cancers. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HYPERTENSION-BLACKS (Undated) _ Two studies dealing with
black men and hypertension: One says black men traditionally
receive poor treatment for strokes; another says that campaigns
aimed at black men help them reduce their blood pressures. By John
O'Neil.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered: When a school of
fish or a flock of birds all seem to turn at the same moment, how
do they manage to do that? (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
