<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2051 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-REDBONE-COX     06-28 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-REDBONE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RedBone Press gives life to works of black gays and lesbians
 &HT;    By Shilanda Woolridge
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If you are a gay black woman with a story to
tell, how can you get it printed in a tight publishing industry?
You do what Lisa C. Moore did. You start your own press.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Moore went looking for lesbian coming out
stories to buy for a friend and found ``a sprinkling of stories
here and there, but no books specifically for black women.''
</P>
<P>
   At first she planned only to self-publish the anthology she had
created called ``does your mama know?'' But Moore, then in her
early 30s, quickly realized that she liked publishing, and felt her
degree in business from Louisiana State University, followed by one
in journalism, had given her the skills to run a press. The result
was RedBone Press, now based in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Moore did everything on the press herself, from soliciting the
submissions to packing and shipping the book after it was printed.
She accomplished all of this while working as a part-time copy
editor at the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, doing freelance
writing, and raising her 2-year-old nephew.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of '97, Moore took ``does your mama know?'' on an
extensive reading and signing tour, visiting 18 cities where the
authors lived. All of the readings took place at independent and
feminist bookstores. The following June, the book won two Lambda
Literary Awards _ the Academy Awards of gay and lesbian writing.
With its initial print run of 3,000 sold out, the anthology has
gone back to press twice more.
</P>
<P>
   Acceptance to the University of Texas graduate program to study
Anthropology in the African Diasapora (specifically, cultural links
between her native New Orleans, and Haiti and Cuba) brought Moore
to Austin. She teamed up with Austin's Sharon Bridgforth of the
Root Wy'mn Theatre company, and released Bridgforth's first book
``the bull-jean stories'' in October '98. Bull-jean is the name of
a mythical Southern black lesbian living in the '20s, the
``single'' aunt that everyone knows and loves but never discusses.
</P>
<P>
   On April 29, ``the bull-jean stories'' was awarded a 1998 Lambda
Literary Award for best small press, netting RedBone Press its
third Lambda Award. A week earlier, a CD version of ``the bull-jean
stories'' was released by RedBone Press.
</P>
<P>
   RedBone has two more books planned for the coming year. Moore
will edit the ``Black PFLAG'' book, which will contain interviews
of parents, friends, and relatives of black gays and lesbians. ``I
think it's probably a cultural thing when black people say, `Oh,
that's a white thing to be gay.' The ``Black PFLAG'' book is a book
for the straight people, to get their take on what it's like to
have a black gay person in your life.''
</P>
<P>
   The other will be a book on black gays and lesbians dealing with
religion and spirituality. ``The editors are planning on going onto
gospel radio shows on Sunday and going to churches,'' Moore said.
``I said, `You guys are bold!'''
</P>
<P>
   Moore should include herself in her description of boldness. Her
position at the helm of RedBone press Press will impact the lives
of many people, gay and straight, as her books reach this
previously hidden market.
</P>
<P>
   Woolridge writes for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
