<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2076 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-VCHIP-BOS &LR;      06-28 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-VCHIP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARRIVAL OF V-CHIP LETS PARENTS TUNE OUT UNWANTED TV 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (e and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The V-chip is here.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three weeks, televisions equipped with the device
have started appearing on store shelves. But some consumer groups
and parents foresee problems with the device that is being touted
as a tool for filtering unwanted programming from children's
television viewing.
</P>
<P>
   The V-chip will be in at least half of all new television sets
13 inches or larger on the market by Thursday, as required by the
1996 telecommunications act. By January, the device will be a
regular feature.
</P>
<P>
   At least 25 million new television sets are expected to be sold
within the next 18 months, according to Representative Edward J.
Markey, the Malden Democrat who drafted the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within a few months, tens of thousands of V-chip TVs will be
in homes all across America. Within a year, millions and millions
of Americans will own one,'' said Markey's spokesman, David
Moulton.
</P>
<P>
   Even if new televisions come equipped with a V-chip, millions of
families still own TVs without the device, said Andrew Schwartzman,
president of Media Access Project, a telecommunications law firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having the V-chip in one TV doesn't prevent kids from watching
a TV in the next room that doesn't have one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Televisions that are not equipped with the device can be
upgraded with the purchase of a V-chip box.
</P>
<P>
   V-chips block out selected programs by reading the ratings based
on viewer age and content that flash on the screen during the first
15 seconds of a program. The technology for the V-chip to read the
electronic ratings works the same way that close-captioned
information is transmitted.
</P>
<P>
   All V-chips require an access code, usually a four-digit number,
to activate or deactivate the device. Based on the television
ratings, parents can choose to block certain programs through the
V-chip by entering the code.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as you wouldn't tell anyone your ATM or calling-card PIN
number, you don't tell your kids the V-chip code,'' said Kathryn
Montgomery, president of Center for Media Education, a children's
advocacy group that has compiled a booklet to help parents
understand the V-chip. The pamphlet is available at
www.vchipeducation.org.
</P>
<P>
   However, several parents looking for television sets at one
store this week said they were not particularly interested.
</P>
<P>
   Abdelhadi El Tahir of New York, shopping with his two children,
ages 10 and 14, said although he agreed with the purpose of the
V-chip, he sees problems with the device.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blocking channels out will make children even more curious,''
El Tahir said. ``These days, children are more technically able,
and they'll find ways to get around it.''
</P>
<P>
   Erin James of Washington, who has a 4-year-old, said even if her
television was equipped with a V-chip, she would be reluctant to
use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you block out certain shows, there's always going to
be something that you missed,'' James said. ``You have to be like
God to catch everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Charren, a visiting scholar at the Harvard School of
Education and founder of Action for Children's Television, said she
believes parents will be more likely to use the V-chip after the
school shootings in Littleton, Colo., and the recent debate in
Congress about youth violence and gun control.
</P>
<P>
   But Charren said the V-chip and the television ratings system
have their drawbacks. Because the V-chip, when activated,
automatically filters out programs based solely on the ratings,
certain beneficial shows could get censored, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Programs about the Civil Rights Movement or about war will get
flagged for violence,'' Charren said. ``But those programs are the
kind of things that parents might actually want their children to
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Charren said the best way for parents to use the V-chip is to
talk to their children about the kinds of programs they want them
to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``V-chip or no V-chip, only parents can take care of their
children,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   V-chip advocates say the device can be an additional tool to
help parents monitor their children's television viewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The V-chip is not supposed to be a baby sitter,'' said Ann
Saybolt of the Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association,
which represents the TV makers. ``It's not a replacement for
parenting.''
</P>
<P>
   It will take only a few years for these new televisions to
become a staple in American homes. According to the latest Census
Bureau statistics, 98 percent of all households have an average of
2.3 television sets each _ a total of about 223 million TVs. The
Center for Media Education estimates that about 25 percent of all
households purchase a new television every year.
</P>
<P>
   V-chip advocates attribute the initial hesitance of parents to
use V-chips on a lack of awareness. Federal Communications
Commissioner Gloria Tristani said many parents don't realize that
the technology is available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we educate parents about the V-chip, they can't use it
to make educated choices for their children,'' Tristani said.
</P>
<P>
   In a random survey of 13 major electronics stores in the
Washington area, only one reported having customers ask about the
V-chip, and that was from a few shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Markey sent letters to top national
newspapers urging them to include both the age- and content-based
ratings in their TV listings.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of USA Today and the Boston Herald, most of
the nation's top-selling newspapers, including The Boston Globe,
carry only the age-based ratings, according to Markey. A Globe
spokesman said the editors are looking into the matter with the
syndicate that provides the daily listings to the paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to make the ratings as familiar to the parents as
the Nike `swoosh' is to the kids,'' Markey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
