<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2084 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOSPITAL-PINCH-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     06-28 1477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-PINCH-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 (a and f coding)  
 BOSTON: ... uninsured patients.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The upshot is that revenue from treating privately insured
patients provides much less of a financial cushion for teaching
hospitals when Medicare cuts its payments.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the BBA decreed a 29 percent reduction between 1998
and 2002 in Medicare payments for ``indirect medication
education.'' These funds are intended to cover Medicare's share of
the special costs of being a teaching hospital _ not interns' and
residents' salaries, which come out of a separate fund, but the
amorphous expenses associated with having sicker patients, more
technology, and trainees involved in patient care.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Medicare payments, these so-called IME funds had also
risen sharply in the 1990s, from $2.5 billion in 1990 to $4.6
billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   When it was passed, the BBA was expected to cut Medicare
spending by $115 billion over what it would otherwise have been.
But in the first year and a half of the new regime, the slowdown in
Medicare spending ``was greater than expected,'' Gail Wilensky,
chairwoman of the Medicare Payment Advisory Commission told the
Senate Finance Committee this month.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the way the law is phased in, the deepest cuts have
not yet occurred. By hospital industry estimates, the BBA will cut
as much as $220 billion from Medicare spending between 1998 and
2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress overshot the mark by almost double,'' said Thomas A.
Scully, chief executive of the Federation of American Health
Systems, whose members include for-profit hospitals. ``Congress did
not vote for $220 billion. Congress didn't intend that.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Congress could never have foreseen some of the reasons
why Medicare is spending so much less than expected. A good deal of
it, analysts said, is due to more scrupulous billing by hospitals _
an apparent reaction to the Clinton administration's campaign
against fraudulent billing and ``upcoding,'' in which providers
jack up reimbursement by billing for a more severe illness than
patients actually have. In this light, Medicare hospital payments
are now more in line with the true cost of serving patients.
</P>
<P>
   Taken by themselves, the 1997 Medicare changes will cut total
profit margins of hospitals by two percentage points by 2002, from
6.7 percent _ the highest point in 17 years _ to a relatively
healthy 4.7 percent, according to Guterman, who spent a decade as
deputy director of the federal agency that advises Congress on
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   However, if managed-care insurers continue to wring payment
concessions out of hospitals at recent rates, total hospital profit
margins could fall to 1.5 percent by 2002. Guterman called that ``a
very low margin that would pressure a considerable number of
hospitals.'' But, he pointed out, ``It looks like Medicare by
itself isn't a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   This analysis is gaining currency in Washington, adding to the
hospitals' burden as they lobby for a rollback _ or at least a
``pause'' _ in the BBA's Medicare cuts.
</P>
<P>
   When a delegation of Boston hospital executives visited the
capital recently, they got a reality check from Donna Shalala, the
US secretary of health and human services. ``Shalala's attitude
was: `The reason you guys are having trouble is that you negotiated
bad deals with HMOs, gave them too many discounts, and Medicare is
making up the difference,' '' said New England Medical Center's
O'Donnell, who was in the group.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Representative Peter Stark of California, the senior
Democrat on the Medicare subcommittee in the House, suggests that
hospitals look to private insurers, not Medicare, for more money.
Stark recently asked government auditors to investigate the source
of hospitals' financial woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, are Medicare fee-for-service payments
becoming just another way that we funnel money to the nation's HMOs
to ensure their profits?'' Stark wrote to the General Accounting
Office.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such doubts, some on Capitol Hill think hospitals have a
shot at wringing limited relief out of Congress this year. To that
end, the American Hospital Association is waging what its policy
chief, Carmela Coyle, calls the largest lobbying campaign in
memory. Senators from states with large clusters of teaching
hospitals are on board, including Kerry and Edward M. Kennedy,
Republican Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania, and Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, Democrat of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a good chance we'll get a bill this year that will put
some money back into Indirect Medical Education,'' said one senate
staffer. ``The academic medical centers have got themselves
organized in a way I've not seen in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if they succeed in this stopgap effort, the Mass.
Generals and Beth Israels and Mt. Sinais know they need to win a
much bigger debate if their teaching mission is to be secured in a
market-driven world. They need reliable support, on a broader base
than Medicare, for the costs of training the physicians of the
future. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Apprenticeship comes with a high price tag &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We all need good doctors and, therefore, everybody ought to
pay to train them,'' said Dr. David Blumenthal, director of MGH's
Institute of Health Policy. ``But we also need good lawyers, good
engineers, and good plumbers, and we don't have a public program to
train them.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference, Blumenthal argues, is consumer protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We allow lawyers to practice law immediately out of law
school, but we don't allow doctors to do that,'' he noted. ``We
require doctors to have minimum amounts of real-world experience.
Somebody has to pay for that apprenticeship.''
</P>
<P>
   Medical students pay tuition _ lots of it. (Weimersheimer, the
Boston Medical Center resident, is carrying $160,000 in medical
school debt.) After graduation, the newly minted physicians
subsidize the cost of their obligatory apprenticeship by taking
hospital training posts that pay $15 an hour _ or less _ for
60-hour workweeks _ or more.
</P>
<P>
   Still, anyone who doubts the cost of residency training should
follow Team D on its morning rounds on MGH's Bigelow Building
medical wards.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Yiming Zhao, a second-year resident, launches the morning
routine at 8:15, accompanied by a half-dozen white-coated medical
students, interns, and residents. Meticulously reviewing each
patient's situation, they troop in and out of 17 rooms,
interviewing, poking, prodding, and consulting with each other on
the medical puzzles they encounter.
</P>
<P>
   At 10:25, Team D gathers over crullers and coffee in a
windowless conference room with two ``attendings,'' senior staff
physicians who go over each case, consider the possibilities, offer
advice. Then they all head off for more bedside consultations.
</P>
<P>
   It results in some of the best care anywhere, as well as
rigorous training, but no time-and-motion expert would call it the
most efficient way to take care of patients.
</P>
<P>
   Even less cost-effective _ but increasingly important in the
training of tomorrow's doctors _ is the clinical training that Dr.
Jeffrey Schnipper is just completing. After each patient interview,
Schnipper consults with his supervisor, Dr. John D. Goodson, and
the two of them then interview the patient together. From the way
his patients react to Schnipper's news that he is moving on to a
different training phase this month, it's clear they value the time
and attention they've had from the 28-year-old resident.
</P>
<P>
   But the examining room Schnipper occupies for the afternoon
could be more profitably used by a senior doctor who could see more
patients and bill for each encounter. Neither Medicare nor any
other agency _ and certainly not private insurers _ explicitly pay
for outpatient training. And practicing doctors are feeling so
pressured to see more patients in less time that it's hard to
recruit them for proctoring duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to move to a new system in which graduate medical
education is explicitly recognized and funded by all payers,''
Goodson says. ``It really is for the greater good.''
</P>
<P>
   There's widespread agreement that a better way is needed, but no
consensus on what it might be. All concur that the teaching
hospitals' ultimate goal _ a so-called all-payer system in which
private and government payers contribute a small tax to support
physician training _ will be an uphill political battle. That fight
won't even begin until after the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, teaching hospitals will have to find their own ways
to sustain the academic enterprise while they compete for patients
and haggle with private insurers for higher payment rates. Somehow
they will, because anything else is unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teaching is how we maintain our preeminence in the world,''
said MGH's Laurence Ronan. ``If we dismantle this system, it will
take 30 or 40 years to put it back together again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
