<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-PINCH-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITALS TAKING A HIT FROM MEDICARE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX AND AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON -- For a midsummer Friday night at Boston Medical
Center's emergency room, the city's busiest, it's unusually quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Still, chief resident Peter Weimersheimer ministers to 30
patients during his nine-hour shift _ crash victims, cases of hand
trauma, pneumonia sufferers, patients in psychiatric crisis, and
end-stage alcoholics, such as a 45-year-old vodka addict who says
he's been vomiting ``cups'' of blood but resists being admitted for
a complete workup until Weimersheimer explains that he is
``probably going to die'' if he doesn't stay.
</P>
<P>
   For his labors, Weimersheimer earns $15 an hour, about half what
he used to get as a carpenter and $5.37 short of a third-year
Boston Medical Center nurse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little dismayed at all the talk about cutting residents
when we're such a cheap source of labor for hospitals,''
Weimersheimer says. ``There's no way they could hire enough
attending physicians to replace us.''
</P>
<P>
   Cutting residents? It's hard to imagine at a time when Boston's
teaching hospitals are often full to the gunnels and nearly all of
them routinely have trouble finding a bed for one more patient.
</P>
<P>
   But these are no ordinary times. The outlook at the nation's
premier hospitals _ those, like Boston Medical Center and a dozen
others in the Boston area that train doctors and deal with
difficult cases _ is the darkest in memory, with no clear way back
to the light.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no plan to lay off interns and residents, who
have hospital commitments to complete three- and four-year training
programs, leaders of academic medicine expect to pare training
slots in the future. But other hospital jobs are in jeopardy as
teaching hospitals struggle to maintain what they call their unique
mission to train the next generations of physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Brigham and Women's Hospital and Massachusetts General are
eliminating a total of 240 jobs to stem a joint operating loss of
$14.1 million for the first half of this year. That's a little more
than a third of the $39 million operating loss suffered by their
parent, Partners HealthCare, New England's largest hospital system.
(With investment income and other revenue, the system saw a net
profit of $2.4 million, compared to $30.4 million a year ago.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working our butts off and still losing money,'' said Dr.
Laurence Ronan, a staff doctor at Massachusetts General. ``We can't
continue to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Across town at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, things are
even shakier. The institution has lost $38 million on operations so
far this year, and BI Deaconess is a much smaller operation than
Partners. ``We're scrambling behind the scenes to protect our
medical training programs,'' said Dr. Steven Weinberger, the
hospital's director of medical education.
</P>
<P>
   In Worcester, UMass Memorial Health Care has closed programs and
cut staff to trim $60 million in annual costs, and are still losing
money so far this year. To break even next year, officials say they
need to slash $70 million more.
</P>
<P>
   Can there be any doubt that hospitals are in trouble, especially
the teaching hospitals that are the undisputed crown jewels of US
health care?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there are plenty of doubts, especially in Washington,
where the leaders of Boston health care are pinning their hopes for
a congressional reprieve from their fiscal difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics don't doubt that hospitals are losing money. But they
do question why, how bad it will get, and whether it's the federal
government's responsibility to do anything about it. And it's not
just fiscally conservative Republicans raising the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bar is high, and we're not going to just go and give money
away because people say they're experiencing hardship,'' said
Daniel Mendelson, the senior health policy official in the White
House budget office. Despite the hospitals' complaints, ``we don't
see the systemic evidence that one might like to see before doing
something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, President Clinton seems ready to support an idea that
would make the hospitals' hunt for money even harder. He is
expected to propose giving Medicare beneficiaries broad new
coverage for prescription drugs, a potentially costly idea that,
whatever its social merits, might siphon funds that could otherwise
go to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Congress agrees to boost health care spending overall,
Clinton's proposal ``would be very damaging'' to hospitals, said
Senator John F. Kerry of Massachusetts. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dilemma has roots in act of Congress &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals didn't arrive at their current dilemma overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Industry leaders blame their troubles on an act of Congress, the
Balanced Budget Act of 1997, which imposed the deepest cuts on
Medicare in the federal program's 35-year history. But there is
broad consensus among industry analysts that the hospitals' current
state resulted from forces set in motion early in this decade. The
problem is a complicated amalgam of:
</P>
<P>
   --Inadvertent Medicare overpayments, especially for inpatient
care;
</P>
<P>
   --The 1994 collapse of the Clinton health reform plan, which
many view as a lost opportunity to rationalize funding of teaching
hospitals' social missions;
</P>
<P>
   --A post-1994 unleashing of market forces in health care that
permitted managed care plans to extract deep discounts from
hospitals desperate to keep patients flowing their way.
</P>
<P>
   It took awhile for the drift to become clear to hospitals, some
observers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between 1994 and 1997, things were looking pretty damn good
for teaching hospitals, and their Medicare profit margins were
especially good,'' said Dr. David Altman of the Lewin Group, a
health care consulting firm. ``There were some Cassandras saying
the sky was going to fall, but not everybody was listening during a
boom period.''
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, the Medicare overpayments seem especially striking
_ and unlikely to continue indefinitely at a time when bankruptcy
was forecast by 2008 for Medicare's Part A trust fund, which pays
for hospital care.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of this decade, US teaching hospitals were
making $7 in ``profit'' for every $100 it cost them to provide
inpatient care to a Medicare patient, according to a recent
analysis by Stuart Guterman of the Urban Institute, a
Washington-based think tank. By contrast, community hospitals were
losing almost an equal amount on each Medicare patient in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   By 1997, Medicare profit margins for inpatient care at teaching
hospitals had ballooned to 28.4 percent, and nonteaching hospitals
were making a 12.4 percent profit.
</P>
<P>
   The largesse stemmed from formulas built into federal law that
automatically update Medicare hospital payments to keep pace with
inflation. But hospital costs flattened in the 1990s, instead of
climbing steadily as the formulas assumed they would. ``Medicare
was a missile just cruising along with no controls,'' observed Dr.
Thomas O'Donnell, chief executive of New England Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals point out that they lost money on Medicare outpatient
care. Outpatient margins dropped to a negative 12 percent in 1996,
and fell further to nearly twice that in 1998, according to the
American Hospital Association. But hospitals' total margins
remained in the black throughout the first seven years of the
decade, according to Guterman's analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare overpayment on the inpatient side handed hospitals a
timely opportunity in the 1990s, although hospital executives don't
like to admit it. It allowed them to bid low for all-important
contracts with managed care plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to hold onto market share they've cut very low-priced
deals with managed-care companies,'' said Stuart Altman, a Brandeis
University professor who served on a congressional Medicare reform
commission. This implicit Medicare subsidy of private insurers is
``an unfair and unsustainable situation.''
</P>
<P>
   To the extent that hospitals have been caring for privately
insured patients at less than their actual costs, that has left
them especially vulnerable to erosion in Medicare payments. ``They
knew that Medicare was paying above costs, and you can say, `well,
they should have been prepared for this,' '' said Katharine London,
chief of policy development at the Massachusetts Division of Health
Care Finance and Policy. ``But they're in a very competitive
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Stuart Altman: ``I've been saying (to managed-care
executives) for some time that the only way they have been able to
squeeze down hospital payments is that hospitals have been filling
their pockets from Medicare. Will they be as successful if Medicare
cuts back?'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Balanced budget a blow to teaching hospitals &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Medicare has cut back _ with a vengeance, some would say.
</P>
<P>
   As the name implies, Congress intended the Balanced Budget Act
of 1997 to balance the federal budget. With considerable help from
a booming economy, it did _ four years ahead of schedule, and with
spending cuts mostly derived from Medicare. Moreover, the law has
helped to postpone the day when Medicare's hospital trust fund will
run out of money to 2015, buying time for more systematic reform.
Or perhaps buying time to do nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching hospitals are disproportionately affected by the BBA
because their older, sicker caseload makes them far more dependent
on Medicare than other hospitals. Medicare accounts for at least
half of a typical teaching hospital's inpatient revenues. In
addition, teaching hospitals are apt to have more Medicaid and
uninsured patients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
