<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS PRESSURED BY THE CLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN FORNOFF  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Too much time on their hands SGA officials need
to take up knitting or needlepoint and stop getting so antsy over
pace of play on the final day of the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   There were Payne Stewart and Phil Mickelson ``on the clock,''
which is to say being timed because they'd fallen off the
USGA-prescribed pace, for the final holes at Pinehurst No. 2. By
the 16th hole, they were tied for the lead and tension was high.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if one of the players stood too long at his ball and
incurred a one-stroke penalty that cost him the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I disagree with being on the clock when you're in the last few
groups of a major championship,'' said Tiger Woods, who was being
timed in the next-to-last group. ``If somebody gets a bad time and
another bad time, that's a one-shot penalty. With the greens as
severe as they are ... it takes time to figure out the slopes. If I
understand the pace of play rule, there are exceptions to it.
</P>
<P>
   And by looking at these greens, I think that's a pretty good
exception.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true that pace of play is a major problem in the early
rounds of the U.S. Open. Anyone playing in an afternoon threesome
on Thursday or Friday has to be prepared for a six-hour round.
</P>
<P>
   That was the pace on Friday, but then USGA officials began to
try to rush the later groups along so that they'd finish before
dark. There were many players trying to make the cut in a hurry,
even though those who had gone before them were able to take their
time.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't seem to be an issue at all if you're playing in the
last twosome on Sunday. After all, if you slow down, who cares
other than TV?
</P>
<P>
   Ah, now we're getting somewhere. Like those laggards on Friday,
the last group on Sunday has to finish before dark _ dark airtime,
in this case. And while you would like to think that the USGA
wouldn't really wallop a U.S. Open leader with a slow-play penalty
for the sake of NBC, the mere threat of one is bad enough.
</P>
<P>
   Woods gives the example of a shot he had last Saturday that
changed when the wind shifted. He went back to his bag to change
clubs, made his par and then was told he had a bad time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be tough to say, you know what, if I do it again I'm
going to get a one-shot penalty,'' Woods said, feeling he had done
the proper thing. ``And to lose the U.S. Open by one would be
pretty tough to swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   ... The Senior PGA Tour is for men over 50, but the new LPGA
senior tour will be for women over 40. Just another example of how
women are perceived to be over the hill much earlier than are men,
and if you don't believe that, go to the movies.
</P>
<P>
   ... Jack Nicklaus has declined his invitation to the British
Open this year because he feels his game hasn't recovered yet from
his hip replacement surgery. But he's gearing up for St. Andrews
next year as his last.
</P>
<P>
   ... Payne Stewart was jazzed about qualifying for September's
Ryder Cup matches and says he's the rah-rah type who'll take
teammates by the throat and get them going. ``Better not put his
hands around my throat,'' said David Duval, who is not so excited
about his first Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ... It's a big month for golf babies. Not only did Amanda Brynn
Mickelson arrive on Monday afternoon, around the time that
Stewart-Mickelson playoff would have begun, Pat Hurst had her first
child, a boy, on June 18.
</P>
<P>
   ... Juli Inkster celebrated her 39th birthday on Thursday with a
68 at the LPGA Championship. She's not quite over the hill, it
appears.
</P>
</TEXT>
