A2121 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-TEX     06-28 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH TEST LIES AHEAD FOR GOP FRONT-RUNNER
</HEADLINE>
 
(DUPLICATION ALERT: Story also moving in ``a'' general news
category) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ On the face of it, California would seem like
friendly territory for Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Like Texas, it is a large state that shares a border with Mexico
and boasts a bustling high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   If the comparisons stopped there, Bush would have little to
worry about as he embarks this week on his first presidential
campaign swing to the vote-rich Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   But the political differences between Texas and California could
hardly be more stark.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has a Republican in every elected statewide office. In
California, where the Clinton-Gore team won in 1992 and 1996,
Democrats hold all the major statewide elected offices (the GOP
holds two lesser offices) and both houses of the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush won impressive numbers of Hispanic voters and
women in his 1998 re-election campaign, some experts say his
conservative positions on such issues as abortion, guns and the
environment could put him on the defensive with the California
electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think California will be a real test for his message,'' said
Raphael Shonenshein, a political scientist at California State
University in Fullerton. ``People will easily decode style over
substance.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush nevertheless has had an impressive start in California _
even before showing up.
</P>
<P>
   As in other states, Bush is far outpacing his Republican rivals
in California in money and in opinion polls. A recent Los Angeles
Times poll had Bush leading Elizabeth Dole 50-13, with other GOP
hopefuls stuck in single digits.
</P>
<P>
   A hypothetical matchup between Bush and Vice President Al Gore,
however, is much tighter. The Times poll showed Bush ahead 49-44,
but that is a statistical dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   And Gore recently completed his 57th visit to California, which
has been kind to his campaign coffers, generating more than $1
million in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is no slouch in California fund-raising circles, either.
The state has given him his second-highest number of dollars _
behind Texas _ and Bush has already had to move a Silicon Valley
fund-raiser scheduled for next week to a new location because the
first site could not hold everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Beckwith, a Bush spokesman, predicted that the governor
will pull in a whopping $3 million during the three-day swing,
which will squeeze in at least seven fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The valley has historically been pretty apolitical,'' said
Floyd Kvamme, a Bush backer and member of the Technology Network, a
group of high-tech companies that have banded together to advance
their political agenda. ``An awful lot of companies are realizing
we're not going to escape notice any longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Kvamme is one of many high-tech executives who have met with
Bush in Austin. Months ago, Bush strategist Karl Rove helped
organize several meetings with computer executives, many of whom
have joined the California fund-raising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tremendous number of our people have operations in Texas,
either in Dallas-Fort Worth or in the Austin area,'' Kvamme said.
``They've seen what's happened in Texas and they like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's supporters say the high-tech angle provides the governor
with an opportunity to favorably contrast himself with Gore, who
has developed strong ties to the industry.
</P>
<P>
   One issue is the wave of lawsuits that could stem from the Y2K
bug, a widespread programming glitch that is expected to cause many
computers to fail because they will recognize the year 2000 as
1900.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are eager to use that issue to drive a wedge between
Gore and a top source of Democratic campaign money, trial lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush signed a bill in Texas limiting business liability for the
Y2K bug; the Clinton administration has voiced objections to
legislation in Congress limiting liability.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Silicon Valley, the Bush camp is hoping that his
``compassionate conservatism'' and Texas-tested appeal to Hispanics
will help attract voters who have been turned off to Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who criticized a California initiative aimed at cutting
off education to the children of undocumented immigrants, won about
40 percent of the Hispanic vote in Texas last year, polling data
show.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Leonard, a California assemblyman representing the area
between Los Angeles and Palm Springs, called Bush a ``natural'' who
is more like Ronald Reagan (a former California governor) than his
father.
</P>
<P>
   ``His compassionate conservatism is the same kind of optimism
and confidence in the future of America,'' Leonard said. ``He has
said some of the most conservative things that have ever been said
on the national stage, but he has said it with a smile on his
face.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, however, say that by the time Californians find out
more about Bush, support for him will drop precipitously.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the National Abortion Rights Action League is
announcing an Internet-based advertising campaign ``exposing Bush's
`two-step' on abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said that he supports the concept of a constitutional
amendment outlawing abortion but that most Americans are not ready
for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll pay a price in California on the abortion issue,'' said
Bob Mulholland, spokesman for the California Democratic Party. ``He
doesn't fit California. He's from Texas, and he doesn't support a
woman's right to choose. California is the most pro-choice state in
the union.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1537EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2122 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILDWILD-WEST-LADN     06-28 1394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILDWILD-WEST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKLASH LOWERS EXPECTATIONS FOR `WILD WILD WEST'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(This moved late Friday on ``e'' entertainment wire)  
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They were supposed to see ``The Matrix.'' That's
what they had been told, at least. So when a Warner Bros. marketing
executive told a recruited audience of 15- to 35-year-old men in
Redwood City, Calif., that they would be seeing ``the new Will
Smith comedy'' instead, the crowd went ballistic. Many were still
booing when the lights went down.
</P>
<P>
   The deception had been intentional. Warner Bros. executives
didn't want director Barry Sonnenfeld to show his new would-be
Fourth of July blockbuster, ``Wild Wild West,'' to a test audience.
Sonnenfeld balked, saying he needed an audience in order to gauge
the movie's effectiveness. Warner Bros., in turn, tried to keep the
screening a secret by advertising it as a ``Matrix'' preview. That
or they just wanted to see how the movie would rate with young
males.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went one step further in terms of dumbness,'' says
Sonnenfeld, director of such previous hits as the ``Men in Black,''
``Get Shorty'' and the ``Addams Family'' movies.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy backfired when word of the disastrously low test
scores leaked on the Internet. Soon afterward, there were reports
that Sonnenfeld recalled the film's stars, Will Smith and Kevin
Kline, for 10 days of additional shooting to punch up the movie's
comedy. And there were whispers that the picture's budget,
originally south of the $100 million line, had spun out of control.
Never mind that most visual-effects films test poorly and that
movies routinely go back for reshoots. Ignore, too, the fact that
none of the anonymous sources quoted in stories about the ``Wild
Wild West'' budget would have any real knowledge of how far the
film was over budget. (Most reports pin the final figure around
$125 million.)
</P>
<P>
   The stigma had stuck. ``Wild Wild West,'' the big-screen remake
of the popular '60s TV series, has been branded as this year's
``Godzilla.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Time will tell,'' says Paul Dergarabedian, president of the
box-office tracking firm Exhibitor Relations Co. ``Certainly, it
has a lot of insurance with Will Smith and his Fourth of July track
record. After that opening weekend, however, it will be up to the
word-of-mouth. And right now that's rather mixed.''
</P>
<P>
   Such guarded optimism is a step down from the sky-high
expectations that led Warner Bros. to take out advertisements last
July 4 proclaiming: ``Enjoy this year's Fourth of July. Next year,
it's going to be `Wild!''' The ads were actually Sonnenfeld's idea,
and he now admits they may have been ill-conceived.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it did was put a target on the film's back,'' Sonnenfeld
says. ``It was like we were inviting people to do mean things to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, I wanted Warner Bros. to commit that `Wild Wild
West' was going to be their big summer movie,'' the director
continues. ``At the time, they were also planning on making
`Superman' with Nic Cage and Tim Burton. And I wanted them to give
`Wild Wild West' top priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who plays James West (he of the tight pants) to Kline's
Artemus Gordon (master of disguise), upped the ante by repeatedly
calling the July 4 weekend ``Big Willie Weekend.'' Not that Smith
doesn't have history on his side. He starred in ``Independence
Day'' (1996) and ``Men in Black'' (1997), both of which opened on
the Fourth of July weekend and went on to win the summer box-office
crown.
</P>
<P>
   Never one to back down from a challenge, Smith compares the
film's naysayers to people in the rap world _ ``playa hatas,''
Smith says _ who deride rappers for their mainstream success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing with `Big Willie Weekend' was me coming out
and having fun with the spectacle,'' Smith says. ``But you have
some people who don't like you to have fun or be successful, so
they try to knock you down.
</P>
<P>
   ``For instance,'' Smith says, ``one newspaper printed a lie that
they knew was a lie, about how the `Wild Wild West' budget was $200
million. They know it's not true, but they still print it. It kind
of hurt my feelings a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith will probably recover. After all, the ``Wild Wild West''
soundtrack, featuring Smith rapping the movie's title song, is
already a monster hit. And despite the bad buzz surrounding the
film, most expect it to do OK.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Armageddon' wasn't exactly a critical favorite last summer,
but people still went to see it,'' Exhibitor Relations'
Dergarabedian says.
</P>
<P>
   The movie itself follows the ``Men in Black'' buddy concept,
pairing Smith and Klein in an Old West that mixes James Bond
gadgets with Jules Verne science fiction. Kenneth Branagh plays the
villain, Dr. Loveless, a scientist threatening to overthrow the
U.S. government with a steam-driven 80-foot mechanical tarantula.
Salma Hayek is on hand as the scantily clad (token) love interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a romp, a summer entertainment,'' says Kline, an actor
rarely seen in such films. ``You leave your mind out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   After the inauspicious test screening, Sonnenfeld decided that
the movie needed more physical comedy and fewer explosions. He shot
two new scenes with Smith and Klein and added a pre-title sequence
where a flying rotary blade chases a terrified scientist through
tall grass.
</P>
<P>
   Going back to reshoot what Sonnenfeld euphemistically calls
``additional photography'' is pretty much standard procedure for
big-budget movies. ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' was
altered significantly after test screenings, and Adam Sandler's
``Big Daddy'' was retooled with a completely new ending.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Men in Black,'' Sonnenfeld tossed out the original finale
some 16 weeks into production because he felt the movie lacked
``oomph.'' His new ending: Angry bug swallows Tommy Lee Jones;
Smith blows up bug to save Jones. To achieve this, Sonnenfeld
ordered 45 3-D computer graphics shots, scrapping a $1 million
mechanical bug model designed by Rick Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Says Sonnenfeld: ``You could have written: ```Men in Black''
throws out ending at last minute in a desperate attempt to save the
movie.' Or you could shut up and not do anything and wait and
discover the movie. At the time, we were so under-the-radar that no
one noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, Sonnenfeld didn't take out an advertisement promoting
``Men in Black'' a year before it was released. Big Willie Weekend
hadn't become an American institution. And Internet movie sites
weren't posting terrible advance reviews, which isn't the case with
``Wild Wild West.''
</P>
<P>
   (Sample item from Harry Knowles' popular aint-it-cool-news.com:
``The film wasn't bad. It was godawful.'' Knowles himself, usually
an optimist when it comes to movies, weighed in about ``Wild Wild
West,'' writing, ``I don't think this is a project that's gonna be
saved.'')
</P>
<P>
   To which Sonnenfeld says: ``The Internet is going to screw up
moviemaking, and I really resent that. It's dangerous because it's
all anonymous. These reports are making studios afraid of having
advance screenings because if the buzz is bad, it kills you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What other form of art gets judged before the final product?''
Sonnenfeld continues. ``I don't read reviewers talking about I.M.
Pei's design for the CAA (Creative Artists Agency) building. I
don't hear someone say, `I read the first draft of `Bonfire of the
Vanities,' and it's 1,900 pages long. But everyone gets to be an
expert on movies.''
</P>
<P>
   That's unlikely to change given the general public's
ever-increasing appetites for the Internet and movie gossip.
Sonnenfeld realizes this and already has a tongue-in-cheek plan in
place for his next film, a biopic of boxer Muhammad Ali that will
once again team the director with Will Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we have a start date _ and I've talked to (Columbia
Pictures distribution president) Jeff Blake about this _ I want to
hold a press conference to announce to everyone that the budget of
the movie is $500 million, that the shooting schedule is 18 months
and that we are building into the production 16 weeks of additional
photography.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonnenfeld pauses, considering if he has left out anything.
``That about covers it. What could they make a stink about then?''
</P>
<P>
   It's a question he really doesn't want answered. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
