<HEADLINE>
BOY HELPS TRIP UP A COUPLE OF TURKEY POACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The youngest detective in California is a
9-year-old boy who got the goods on two turkey poachers, a case
that not only led to arrests and convictions _ but a reward.
</P>
<P>
   The case started when the 9-year-old witnessed two strangers,
both men with shotguns, enter his grandparent's property. Curious,
he followed them, and then in horror, watched them shoot a wild
turkey.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly returned home, told his mother, and together they
were able to get the poacher's vehicle type and license number.
</P>
<P>
   They then called the DFG's poacher hotline, 1-888-DFG-CALTIP,
and the boy described the incident that he had witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jack Edwards of the Department of Fish and Game,
the DFG dispatcher then made contact with the nearest officer
available, a sheriff. He was able to get to the scene and nab the
poachers, still trespassing.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that in 17 years the poacher hotline has been
operating, the 9-year-old is the youngest tipster to be honored by
the program. He received a $100 cash reward, two $100 savings
bonds, a CalTIP hat and a thank-you letter from the CalTIP Board.
</P>
<P>
   The CalTIP Board, which operates independent of the DFG, accepts
donations and provides rewards for anonymous reports of wildlife
crimes and pollution incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid knew the difference between hunters and poachers,''
Edwards said. ``That's what impressed me. That's the thing that
stood out. He knew the difference between legal hunting from
illegal hunting, that what they were doing wasn't right. It's nice
to see someone 9 years old knows the difference between right and
wrong, especially when some adults have don't seem to recognize the
same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ethical hunter obeys the law and respects landowner
property rights,'' Edwards said. ``Poachers are thieves of our
wildlife resources and they show no respect for laws or people.''
</P>
<P>
   In all cases with CalTip, callers remain anonymous so their
identities cannot be traced by anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Fear and loathing:
</P>
<P>
   At Lake Davis near Portola, the tension and concern over pike
spiraled this past week when a 3-inch pike, the size of a fish born
this spring, was caught by the DFG biologists while electro-shock
fishing. It means a spawning population of pike may exist in the
lake, bringing fear that pike may have spread over the dam and
downstream to threaten salmon, striped bass and endangered species
in the Delta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hoping against all odds that the three adult pike
found in May would be the end of the story,'' said DFG director Bob
Hight. ``We are investigating the possibility that pike could have
spawned in Lake Davis earlier this spring, as well as looking at
other sources from where these pike may have come.''
</P>
<P>
   The DFG is still awaiting news from the DNA lab at UCLA that
will document whether the pike were illegally planted this year, or
survived the lake's poisoning in fall of 1997. Meanwhile, the
Plumas County Fish and Game Commission added $5,000 on top of the
DFG's $25,000 for information leading to the arrest and conviction
of any person or persons who planted illegal pike in Lake Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Lions vs. bighorns:
</P>
<P>
   The lion isn't exactly laying down with the lamb, but the
Mountain Lion Foundation, best known for winning protected status
for lions in California, has been invited by the DFG to participate
with a special committee to protect the Sierra bighorn.
</P>
<P>
   This is a landmark, with the foundation agreeing that some
predator lions may have to be taken in order to protect the
endangered bighorn, now down to about 100 head, with the recent
decline blamed mostly on kills by lions. The key, notes Executive
Director Lynn Sadler, is that stock grazing (cattle and domestic
sheep) is all too common, even in wildnerness, and should stop
within 20 miles of land designated as habitat for Sierra bighorn.
</P>
<P>
   Wolves, the latest:
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service likely will decide not to
push for the reintroduction of wolves into the Klamath-Siskiyou
region of Northern California, as has been done in parts of Idaho,
Wyoming and Montana, according to an informed source.
</P>
<P>
   To do so would apparently push the button to activate the
Endangered Species Act, which would thus become the single force
that would drive all environmental decisions in the region, which
is exactly what scientists do not want. That would disrupt current
ecosystem-wide management of the area designed to benefit dozens of
species of wildlife, fish, trees, plants and watersheds, not a
single species with a large range.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
