<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWEST WORD GAME: ``NAME THAT NEIGHBORHOOD!'' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 4)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When in California, you'll want to go to  &UR; SoMa &LR; . Down in
Florida, don't miss  &UR; SoBe &LR; . And in Connecticut, the place to go is
 &UR; SoNo &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All these so-so names are a result of  &UR; stump compounding &LR; . A
 &UR; stump &LR;  is a piece of a word, the front or the back. Otto
Jespersen, the great Danish linguist, noticed in 1922 that children
tended to shorten names by using the ends: Albert became  &UR; Bert &LR; ,
Arabella just  &UR; Bella &LR;  and Elizabeth  &UR; Beth &LR; ,  &UR; Betty &LR;  or  &UR; Bess &LR; .
Adults, he found, liked to make the  &UR; stumps &LR;  out of the beginnings
of words: a gymnasium became a  &UR; gym &LR; , a kilogram a  &UR; kilo &LR; , a
photograph a  &UR; photo &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Exceptions abound, and the adults have adopted telephone's
 &UR; phone &LR;  and caravan's  &UR; van &LR; . But as language hurries up, the
pressure is on to chop big words down to their  &UR; stumps &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Geographers are leading the way.  &UR; Bosnywash &LR;  long ago triumphed
over ``Northeast Corridor,'' compounding the  &UR; stumps &LR;  of Boston and
Washington with the initials of New York. In the nation's opposite
corner is  &UR; SeaTac &LR; , a community that has grown around the airport
serving Seattle and Tacoma. (Next:  &UR; DallWorth &LR; ?)
</P>
<P>
   The boom on  &UR; stump compounding &LR;  is in neighborhood nomenclature.
The  &UR; So &LR;  is for ``south''; hence,  &UR; SoMa &LR;  is south of Market Street
in San Francisco, which old-timers looking at the cable-car tracks
called ``south of the Slot'';  &UR; SoBe &LR;  is South Beach in Miami, and
 &UR; SoNo &LR;  is South Norwalk, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The grandpappy of these coinages (a play on London's Soho
neighborhood) is  &UR; SoHo &LR; , chopped down and put together in the early
'70s to describe the neighborhood south of Houston Street in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   In the current issue of Beitrage zur Namenforschung
(``Contributions to the Study of Personal and Place Names''),
published in Heidelberg (perhaps your copy is late in the mail),
David L. Gold, a New Yorker, explains that  &UR; stump-compounded &LR; 
neighborhood names in Gotham are ``an expression of trendiness and
gentrification.'' When the South Bronx wanted to assert itself as
an arts colony, it adopted  &UR; SoBro &LR; . In the '80s came  &UR; LoBro &LR; , for
Lower Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   A refinement of  &UR; SoHo &LR;  is  &UR; SoSoHo &LR; , which tells the visitor that
the area is both south of  &UR; SoHo &LR;  and kind of middling. Such punning
is popular: Gold points to  &UR; NoLiTa &LR; , ``a Nabokovian coinage for
North of Little Italy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TriBeCa &LR; , the name of the area bounded by Canal Street,
Broadway, Chambers Street and West Street, is derived from the
first syllables of the words  &UR; tri &LR; angle  &UR; be &LR; low  &UR; Ca &LR; nal. (It's more
a trapezoid than a triangle, but there's no longer a canal on
Canal; a little poetic license is allowed in  &UR; stump compounding &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   The annoyed reader will note that I am using the abomination of
capital letters in the middle of words. Don't worry about this
affectation, recorded here only to show the etymology of the
compounds. Both in common usage and in telephone directories, the
 &UR; stumpifications &LR;  are melded to  &UR; Soho &LR; ,  &UR; Tribeca &LR;  and the like.
</P>
<P>
   English is not the only language that chops and jams its words.
According to Rolf Bergmann, editor of Namenforsch (see? I just
shrank the name of his publication),  &UR; Kripo &LR;  is the  &UR; stump &LR;  of
Kriminalpolizei and  &UR; Juso &LR;  is short for Jungsozialist. The Germans
call this formation a Kurzwort, ``short word.'' The Russian
 &UR; Komsomol &LR;   &UR; stumped &LR;  Kommunisticheskii soyuz molodezhi, which means
``Communist Union of Youth.''
</P>
<P>
   Do not confuse  &UR; acronyms &LR; , which are pronounceable words made up
of a phrase's initials, with  &UR; stump compounds &LR; , which are shortened
words glued together.  &UR; NATO &LR;  is an  &UR; acronym &LR; , from the initials of
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization;  &UR; KFOR &LR; , from Kosovo Force,
is an  &UR; initialized stump &LR; , pronounced KAY-for. A pure  &UR; stump
compound &LR;  is  &UR; Intelsat &LR; , from  &UR; In &LR; ternational  &UR; Tel &LR; ecommunications
 &UR; Sat &LR; ellite. Consortia and corporations like these herky-jerky
names in the language of globalese.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry to break the news to residents of a Brooklyn neighborhood
where Walt Whitman sang the song of himself _ and that now styles
itself as the new Bohemia _ that their  &UR; Dumbo &LR;  does not qualify as
a  &UR; stump compound &LR; . The name formed from the initials of Down Under
the Manhattan Bridge Overpass is an  &UR; acronym &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   GRAMPS/GRANDPA/GRAMPA
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear  &UR; Grampa &LR; '' is the title of a chapter in Rabbi Steven Z.
Leder's uplifting book, ``The Extraordinary Nature of Ordinary
Things.'' The ordinary thing that gets to me is the extraordinary
disconnect between the spelling and the pronunciation of what we
call our parents' fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Most adults think they are saying  &UR; grandpa &LR;  when the sounds they
make are  &UR; granpa &LR;  without the  &UR; d &LR; . Most children, who use the word
more often, say  &UR; grampa &LR; , changing the  &UR; n &LR;  to  &UR; m &LR; , which comes more
easily before the  &UR; p &LR; . (The dental  &UR; n &LR;  conflicts with the labial
 &UR; p &LR; , as Peter Suber, a philosopher and semanticist at Earlham
College, in Indiana, has shown, and it alters to  &UR; m &LR; .  &UR; Amp &LR;  is
easy;  &UR; anp &LR;  takes much too much effort.)
</P>
<P>
   The first use I can find is attributed to Nelly Custis in 1799.
George Washington's granddaughter was reported by a visitor to
Mount Vernon to cheer up ``the General, whom she always calls
 &UR; Grampa &LR; .'' The happiest use is in a 1957 poem by Ogden Nash: ``How
confusing the beams from memory's lamp are/One day a bachelor, the
next a  &UR; grampa &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   I say it's time to spell the informal word the way it sounds:
 &UR; grampa &LR; . Got that,  &UR; gramps &LR; ? (All previous written usages are
grandfathered.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
