<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2171 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAMPOLINE-FITNESS-AR     06-28 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAMPOLINE-FITNESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR `BOUNCERS,' A CHANCE FOR THE GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Ore., Iowa)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By NANCY STEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a preschooler, Jennifer Parilla often climbed onto her
parents' bed and jumped as high as she could. ``I loved the feeling
of flying,'' recalled Ms. Parilla, of Lake Forest, Calif. Then,
when she was 5, she began lessons in the sport of trampolining.
</P>
<P>
   Now 18 and the national women's trampoline champion, Ms. Parilla
has a chance to demonstrate her sport before an enormous audience.
Last month, the International Olympic Committee announced that
trampolining would be a competitive event at the 2000 games in
Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Trampolining combines the high drama of diving with the fluidity
of figure skating. Jumping on a springy rectangular canvas,
bouncers, as the athletes call themselves, catapult up to 30 feet
into the air and perform precision feats.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some routines, out of 10 skills, at least 3 are triple
somersaults and the rest are doubles,'' said Ann Sims, the program
director for U.S.A. Gymnastics Trampoline and Tumbling Office.
</P>
<P>
   Lani Lokendahle of the University of Oregon in Eugene said the
sport of trampolining was created by two American originals, a
vaudeville acrobat and college gymnastics teacher named Larry
Griswold (and nicknamed ``Leapin' Larry'') and his University of
Iowa protege, George Nissen, a sometime carnival performer who
often chose to walk on his hands rather than his feet.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1930s, Nissen, inspired by the netting used under
circus acrobats, pieced together a trampoline by attaching a piece
of canvas to an iron frame with springs.
</P>
<P>
   By 1942, enough moves had been worked out to fill a trampolining
textbook produced by Griswold, who died in 1996. Later, Nissen, who
lives in San Diego, gained control of the manufacturing firm they
started. His favorite publicity shot showed him and a kangaroo as
they jumped in tandem on a trampoline.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, trampolining became an immensely popular
children's activity, both in physical education classes and at
special play centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a well-supervised situation. There were lots of
injuries, some very serious,'' said Ms. Lokendahle, who teaches
college-level trampoline classes. The injuries caused trampolining
to fall out of favor in the '60s and '70s, Ms. Lokendahle said.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans continued to train on trampolines, however, and as a
result this made-in-America sport is dominated by countries like
Russia, Belarus and France. Ms. Parilla, the lead American women's
competitor, is ranked 15th worldwide, while the top men's
trampolinist, Ryan Weston, 19, of Chubbuck, Idaho, is rated 8th.
</P>
<P>
   Americans may not even get a chance to compete at next year's
Olympics. Under the qualifying rules, 12 male and 12 female
competitors, only one each from a country, will be chosen from the
top performers at the world championship trampolining event to be
held in Sun City, South Africa, in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are totally opposed to choosing Olympians a year ahead,''
said Ms. Sims, whose organization has registered its disapproval of
the policy.
</P>
<P>
   Missing the Games would be a blow to Weston, who sold Popsicles
door to door to finance his first competition abroad at the age of
10 and who cleans his gym to pay for lessons. He recently received
$1,500 for expenses from the U.S.A. Gymnastics national committee.
``It really helped,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Weston, however, worries that the character of trampolining may
change with Olympic exposure. ``As trampolining gets bigger and
bigger,'' he said, ``I hope it doesn't acquire the ugly side of
competition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
