<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-TRAMPOLINE-KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS GROUP PONDERS SAFETY ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, Utah)   (af)  
 By NANCY STEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though aficionados of trampolining hope that the Olympics will
inspire children to participate in the sport, some doctors do not
share their enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   The American Academy of Pediatrics, citing an estimated 83,400
trampoline-related injuries in 1996, recently reiterated its 1981
position that the equipment should not be used in homes, in routine
physical education classes or on playgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Several studies show that injuries occur when children land
incorrectly on the trampoline, hit the frame or springs, fall or
collide with another person. Nationally, about one child dies a
year from trampolining injuries.
</P>
<P>
   A study of emergency-room patients at Children's Hospital in
Columbus, Ohio, found that most injuries were sprains and strains,
followed by fractures. Some 96 percent of the accidents happen with
home equipment, according to the study's lead author, Dr. Gary A.
Smith, an emergency medicine specialist at Ohio State University
College of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Parental supervision makes little difference; 73 percent of the
injuries involving young children happen when a parent is present.
``Time and time again in the emergency room, I hear parents say, `I
was right there and I couldn't do anything,''' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Sands, an exercise physiologist at the University of
Utah, argued that sales of home trampolines have increased at a
much higher rate than injuries _ 260 percent in sales between 1990
and 1997 compared with 154 percent in injuries. He said the
accident rate on trampolines was below that of other popular
equipment, including bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any physical activity carries risks,'' he said. ``I get the
feeling that we're supposed to be walking around in a big padded
suit.''
</P>
<P>
   But Smith insisted, ``This is an epidemic by any definition.
Diverting attention to another public health problem doesn't
diminish the importance of the one at hand.'' He said children
could benefit from trampolining as long as it was taught with
proper supervision at a gymnastics school. ``It helps develop
balance and coordination skills,'' Smith said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
