<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE QUESTION AND ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By C.CLAIBORNE RAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flocks and Schools
</P>
<P>
   Q. When a school of fish or a flock of birds all seem to turn at
the same moment, how do they manage to do that?
</P>
<P>
   A. Scientists studying the complex behavior of schools of fish
or flocks of birds, which they term schooling or flocking, once
assumed that it had to do with signals from a leader who was
somehow able to coordinate the movements of the group, and to do so
instantaneously.
</P>
<P>
   But with the help of computers, many researchers have come to
suspect that this extremely close synchronization is more like the
``wave'' of people standing up and sitting down that is frequently
seen moving across a sports stadium. In such patterns, each member
of a crowd acts individually based on a fairly simple set of rules
for behavior, with the outcome being mass synchronization.
</P>
<P>
   Experiments with flocks and schools often examine how the groups
react to a stimulus that resembles a predator. Though the overall
motion of the group is easy to see, it takes computers to keep
track of individual movement decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers do not know all the rules that govern the
decisions, but they do know that birds and fish must try to keep
some minimal distance away from their neighbors and that stragglers
on the outskirts of a flock are at risk. The first individuals may
move slowly, with the rest picking up speed as the ``wave'' travels
through the flock.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions by postal mail to
Questions, Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43d Street,
New York, N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to:Question(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Questions of general interest will be answered in this column,
but requests for medical advice cannot be honored and unpublished
letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
