<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2190 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT     06-28 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ancient Chirp of Crickets
</P>
<P>
   Fossils can give a good idea of what the natural world might
have looked like millions of years ago, but because organs of
communication are so rarely preserved, not much is known about how
it might have sounded.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a study of 55-million-year-old fossils found in Denmark has
revealed one sound from the ancient world: the chirp of crickets.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from the University of Goettingen in Germany,
examining fossilized forewings of a large (five-inch wingspan)
cricket, show that it had the same sound-producing structures as
modern varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Male crickets are the insect world's strolling violinists,
bowing their wings together and creating chirps as teeth-like
surfaces on the left wing scratch across a raised vein on the
right. The right wing also has a complex of spines, and a membrane
(larger than a similar membrane on the left) that helps the sound
radiate.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, writing in the journal Nature, saw these same
structures on the fossilized crickets and reported that the insects
probably produced a song with a frequency peak of about 7,000
hertz, or cycles per second, similar to the chirps of living
species.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists also saw signs of how crickets have evolved. In
the fossilized crickets, both wings had spine complexes, and the
difference in membrane size between the two wings was less
pronounced. The researchers suggest that crickets evolved from a
bilaterally symmetrical ancestor, becoming asymmetric over time as
courtship behavior evolved (the chirps being essentially love
songs). The asymmetry started to show itself in the fossilized
species and has progressed much further in modern crickets.
</P>
<P>
   Collision Course in Space
</P>
<P>
   As high-tech communications gadgets proliferate on Earth, the
satellites enabling them to work proliferate above. Increasingly,
communication systems call for whole constellations of satellites,
orbiting at about the same altitude, to provide global coverage.
One constellation, the Iridium system, with 66 spacecraft, is now
in place, and more are planned.
</P>
<P>
   All those satellites, however, have to share near-Earth space
with lots of junk _ 10,000 pieces of debris four to eight inches
across or larger; 100,000 pieces bigger than about half an inch.
Because all that debris is traveling at thousands of miles an hour,
the possibility of a collision severe enough to destroy a satellite
is a real one.
</P>
<P>
   Just how real has been revealed by Italian scientists, who
analyzed the risk for a constellation of satellites like Iridiums.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in Nature, they concluded that there was a 10 percent
chance per decade that a satellite in a typical constellation would
have a catastrophic collision. That is bad enough. But worse is
what could happen next.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the nature of the orbits in a satellite
constellation, the debris from one collision (which itself could
create thousands more pieces of junk) would increase the chances of
another collision with a satellite in the constellation, to 10
percent over five years. The eventual result could be a chain of
collisions that may irreversibly pollute a portion of near-Earth
space much faster than previously thought, perhaps over a century,
rather than 300 to 500 years.
</P>
<P>
   Bees Arrive by Sea
</P>
<P>
   The first colonies of Africanized honey bees _ the so-called
killer bees, though ``killer'' is something of a misnomer _ have
been found east of the Mississippi River, and they have come not by
land, but by sea.
</P>
<P>
   Florida agriculture officials discovered the colonies at the
port of Jacksonville. DNA testing showed that the bees were of the
Africanized variety and that the queens had mated with drones from
other colonies. Previously, colonies had been found on ships at the
port, but these were the first to hop to land. It is unclear
whether they may spread.
</P>
<P>
   The aggressive bees first came to the United States in 1990,
into Texas from Mexico. But their eastward spread has halted around
Houston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1644EDT &QL; 
