<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF SHOPPING IS OUR ECONOMY, WE SHOULD GET BETTER SALESPEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Shopping, the All-American pasttime, lies at the
heart of consumerism. Furthermore, the United States economy, off
on a record tear, is powered by consumer spending more than any
other factor, putting in the shade such financial stalwarts as
manufacturing and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Consumerism seems a chancy reed to lean on for the continuation
of such fabulous national well-being for so long a time. After all,
it is subject to vagaries, such as the psychic mood of the people
who are doing the buying. It's not like relying on a powerful
industrial base, for example, with its comparative stolidity.
</P>
<P>
   All the more reason, then, to buttress the arts of retail, the
selling of goods, in which spirit these observations are offered.
</P>
<P>
   If, as planned, this column were written several weeks ago, it
would have quickly concluded that consumerism is facing
insurmountable difficulties, which would mean that our economy was
in imminent danger of loosing steam.
</P>
<P>
   This gloomy assessment stemmed from personal experiences,
dealing with sales people in the wide spectrum of stores and
businesses to which foot soldiers of consumerism expose themselves
every day, including Sundays, as they venture on their mission to
keep this country's prosperity on its upward track.
</P>
<P>
   It was precisely in the course of doing my civic duty by
relentless shopping, that I began to notice that in transaction
upon transaction, whether in independently owned stores or in
outlets of national chains, whether the establishments were
franchises or boutiques, shopping was depressingly similar.
</P>
<P>
   The affair was terribly one-sided. The buyer enters, unheralded,
selects the merchandise without help or guidance, brings it to the
cashier, turns over cash money, check or credit card, and is
greeted at best by indifference. More likely, there is sullenness,
occasionally hostility, as if the process of paying for goods
interfered with more pressing concerns for the so-called
salesperson.
</P>
<P>
   Not a word of friendliness, certainly no thanks, are uttered as
American money is turned over to the person whose own financial
security depends upon the frequency of these dealings.
</P>
<P>
   It was unsettling and worse. Let's not shirk its true
significance, this was unpatriotic.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that there were rare encounters with obliging
salespeople, who knew their stock, provided help when it was
needed, and did it all with courtesy and pleasantness, only served
to highlight how miserable in comparison were the more numerous
encounters of the other kind.
</P>
<P>
   It was a depressing state of affairs, in which our national
decline and fall on the brink of the new millenium was writ clearly
and large. If shopping were to continue to be so frightfully
unpleasant, it would surely lead to a diminution with all the
resultant risks of stalling growth. Just as I was sitting down at
the computer to expose the threat to the common welfare my shopping
experiences began to change.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of meeting clods behind the counter or sales station,
bit by bit the ratio of exemplary employees increased. This, of
course, impaired the premise of the column, so I had to wait and
see, lest I commit a journalist indiscretion I would come to
regret.
</P>
<P>
   So rather than focusing on the declining state of shopping, with
its profound implications, I sounded off on secondary issues such
as war in the Balkans, presidential politics and life in the cyber
age.
</P>
<P>
   Reserving judgment turned out to be the right thing to do. My
earlier experiences shopping were like my lottery games: I had run
into a sustained and unrelieved streak of very bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the poor experiences have been eclipsed by the many more
pleasant ones. These have lightened the mood, and I now longer
despair about the nation's future.
</P>
<P>
   However, there remains substantial concern, if not a crisis.
Averaging out the two halves of my shopping episodes, it is clear
that while there are many fine, accomplished salespersons to be
found, their opposites are in place in roughly equal number.
</P>
<P>
   So there is much yet to be done by owners and supervisors to
inculcate the proper attitudes in many of the help, who apparently
were raised by wolves in the wilderness, and were never schooled,
and thus don't know the relevance of the expressions ``May I help
you?'', ``Thank You'' and ``You are welcome'' in human intercourse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large at the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
