<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FILM-FALCO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDIE FALCO FINDS OVERNIGHT SUCCESS AFTER DECADE OF WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Edie Falco's career finally took off when she
quit a job she had, and didn't get a job she wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few short years ago, Falco was living in New York City
(as she still does, in the West Village), doing some B movies and
guest roles on shows like ``Homicide: Life on the Street'' and
``Law &AMP; Order.''
</P>
<P>
   She was also waitressing. As she said, ``I had to have some kind
of job or another to pay the rent.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, two things happened. After making the film ``Cost of
Living'' (released in 1997), she quit working tables. Falco was
going to stretch the money from the film as far as it would go, and
just act, ``jumping off without a net.''
</P>
<P>
   Around this time she also appeared in a television pilot based
on the movie ``Fargo.'' It didn't go anywhere. Falco still needed a
job.
</P>
<P>
   Then she got one. And another one. And another.
</P>
<P>
   After years of being told she didn't have the right hair, or
face, or voice, or whatever, Falco is now riding a wave most actors
can only dream about. She is a star on Broadway in ``Side Man''
(she plays Terry), the Tony Award winner for best play. She also
plays Diane Wittlesey, a female correction officer on the gritty
prison drama ``Oz'' (the third season premieres Wednesday, July 14,
at 10 p.m. on HBO).
</P>
<P>
   Then Falco took on another project, also for HBO, playing the
wife of a New Jersey mobster. It was so different the cast didn't
know if the show would last. It stuck, and ``The Sopranos'' became
the most talked about show of the season after its debut in
January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oz'' and ``The Sopranos'' are the two best examples of the
programming HBO has done in recent years, transforming the cable
network from just a home of movies we see over (and over, and over
...) to an outlet for some of the best first-run shows on
television.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of all this is Falco, whose schedule often means
she is shooting a television episode during the day and performing
live in the play at night. ``The Sopranos,'' with new episodes
starting up in January, soon begins production on the next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pretty tired,'' Falco conceded in a recent telephone
interview from New York City, when she took some time out from a
magazine photo shoot. ``You go for so many years without any work
... I am just so grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   Falco, 35, is especially grateful since she and other cast
members were not that sure the story of a mob guy, his family, his
Family and a shrink would resonate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that the scripts were great,'' she said. ``But I know
better than to get too attached to these things. I didn't think we
would be picked up. None of us thought anyone was going to get
it.''
</P>
<P>
   So why did America get it? ``I do not know,'' she said. ``I have
no perspective if it is something I'm in. I hope we can keep it
going.''
</P>
<P>
   (This is as good a spot as any to remind readers I was in the
same huge graduating class as Falco at Northport High School.
Thankfully, she didn't remember me.)
</P>
<P>
   So, does Falco ever confuse Terry with Carmela Soprano, or
Carmela with Diane, or any of them with Edie? Nah.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go to `Oz' ... I don't wonder if I'm Terry,'' she said.
``It is very clear. I couldn't ask for three more different and
fulfilling parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask Falco what she will be doing a decade from now and she
answers she has no clue. What she does know is she has no plans to
slow down now; she is just on too hot a streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to think my whole life could be filled with
projects I cared as much about,'' she said. ``I have the energy now
I may not have in five years or 10 years. I might as well take
advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about it. She is, she is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
