u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      06-28 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; PRO &AMP; CON: Physical Fitness As a Job Yardstick &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. Are physical performance standards discriminatory when used
as criteria in hiring? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ALISHA BERGER &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Valid physical fitness tests for employment in demanding jobs do
not discriminate because they measure an applicant's ability to do
the work. Test validation involves defining the job's critical
physical tasks, and the physiological demands of the job. The
testing goal is to identify a applicants with fitness congruent
with demands. If a job involves lifting a 75-pound box, a valid
test defines the strength a worker needs to lift the box. If a weak
worker cannot lift 75 pounds, a stronger worker should be given the
task.
</P>
<P>
   Research shows that work-related injuries, especially back
injuries, increase when workers are not matched to the physical job
demands. Also, hiring fit workers is a sound business. It leads to
lower worker compensation and health care costs and increased
productivity.
</P>
<P>
   -DR. ANDREW S. JACKSON, professor of health and human
performance, University of Houston
</P>
<P>
   Pre-employment physical fitness tests are discriminatory. More
than 100 physiological differences have been found between men and
women, making it virtually impossible to construct a test that is
fair to box sexes or that yields results that can meaningfully be
applied to the work site.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively larger size and substantially higher levels of
lean body mass of the average man enable him to be stronger, faster
and more powerful than women. But women have better balance, manual
dexterity, flexibility and coordination. Obviously, depending on
what test items are selected, a specific assessment battery can be
skewed toward one sex or the other. But it is hard to imagine a
test that would not be weighted to favor muscular fitness-related
measurements.
</P>
<P>
   -DR. JAMES A. PETERSON, Sports medicine specialist, Monterey,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Marinades and Cancer &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Cooks know that marinating a steak before grilling improves
flavor and tenderizes. Now, scientists suggest the technique
decreases the production of carcinogenic compounds in meats and
fish cooked at high temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't know what magic bullet in the marinade reduces
it,'' said Mark G. Knize, a Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory
scientist, who tested recipes and products to find the effects of
marinade on meat. He and his colleagues stumbled onto it as a small
part of a a study financed by the National Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   They found that marinating chicken even less than an hour before
grilling substantially decreased the production of heterocyclic
amines, cancer-causing agents that develop as fat from grilled meat
drips on hot coals and then wafts upward. The amines have been
linked in laboratory tests on rodents and monkeys to breast and
colon cancers.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Hawaii Cancer Research Center, Dr. Pratibha
V. Nerurkar and her colleagues have taken the research further.
Reporting in a coming issue of Nutrition and Cancer, their team
tested Hawaiian teriyaki and an Indian turmeric-garlic marinades on
beef and found that both slowed production of carcinogenic agents.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nerurkar, a biochemist, said she suspected the liquid
content of the marinade added moisture and prevented the meat from
burning too much.
</P>
<P>
   The American Institute for Cancer Research in Washington
described the reports as encouraging. ``What a great thing to do if
we can significantly reduce the amount of carcinogens formed on
meat and fish on the grill and also make foods taste better,'' said
Melanie Polk, the director of nutrition education at the institute.
</P>
<P>
   -NANCY BETH JACKSON
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
