<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2262 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-DAIRY-DIET-ART-NY     06-28 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DAIRY-DIET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUPS DEBATE PLACE OF MILK IN DIETARY GUIDELINES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Pa., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By DAVID FRANCE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the deliberations in full swing for revisions of the
federal Dietary Guidelines for All Americans, to be reissued next
year, what started as a controversy is fast progressing into a
contentious argument: should the government be recommending dairy
products as part of a balanced diet, given that once most nonwhite
people leave childhood, they cannot easily digest those products?
</P>
<P>
   Led by groups like the Congressional Black Caucus, a growing
chorus of health and civil rights organizations are saying no, and
calling for reworked guidelines that reflect the nation's digestive
diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the caucus wrote to President Clinton arguing that
the current guidelines ``demonstrate a consistent racial bias.'' It
said the revised guidelines should list dairy products as
``optional and in no way superior'' to other dietary sources of
calcium, which is vital to bone strength.
</P>
<P>
   But the nation's dairy industry is resisting, as is the
Department of Agriculture, whose dual mandate is to advise
consumers about good eating while promoting American farm products.
As instructed by Congress, the Agriculture Department updates the
guidelines every five years, and uses them as the basis for the
Eating Right Pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are called Guidelines for Americans, so they should
reflect all Americans,'' said Donna M. Christian-Christensen, a
Democrat who is the Virgin Islands delegate to Congress. She heads
the Congressional Black Caucus' Health Brain Trust and is a family
physician.
</P>
<P>
   All children are born with the intestinal enzyme lactase, which
is necessary for digesting milk. Beginning at age 5, however, many
people whose genetic background is not Northern European begin to
produce less lactase and lose their ability to digest milk by age
10. Without it, dairy products travel through the stomach
undigested and then ferment in the small bowel, a process that can
cause discomforting symptoms like gas, cramps and diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
   Across the board, 25 percent of Americans have trouble digesting
milk, estimates Dr. Walter C. Willett, chairman of the department
of nutrition at the Harvard School of Public Health. Among
Asian-Americans, 95 percent are naturally lactose intolerant, said
Dr. Richard Grand, a professor of pediatrics at Tufts University
Medical School who has published studies on genetic variables for
lactose intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Some 65 percent of African-Americans and American Indians are
lactose intolerant as are half of all Hispanic Americans, he said.
Among Caucasians the figure is 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Because dairy products are a rich source of calcium, the
government has recommended that everyone consume them. Eight ounces
of milk contains 300 milligrams of calcium; the recommended daily
allowance for most adults 20 to 50 is 1,000 milligrams a day.
``Calcium deficiency is a much more important problem than lactose
intolerance,'' Grand said.
</P>
<P>
   Dairy products are not the only good source of calcium. Others
include dark, leafy green vegetables, like kale and collard greens.
But nutrition experts say that Americans are unlikely to embrace
them. That is one reason why the guidelines have not emphasized
them, said Shirley Watkins, the Agriculture Department's under
secretary for Food, Nutrition and Consumer Services.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, she said, even people who are lactose intolerant (as
she is) can often consume small amounts of milk. ``It's not
life-threatening,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Guidelines issued in 1995 call for two to three servings of
milk, yogurt or cheese daily. Among other things, the guidelines
are used for determining menus by a number of federal food
assistance programs, which reach a disproportionately high
percentage of minority group members. Public school lunch programs
are required to provide milk to all students, based on the
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Watkins said a lactose-intolerant student must provide a
doctor's note if he or she wants a lactose-free alternative. Ms.
Watkins added, however, that public schools were not required to
provide the alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The Physicians Committee for Responsible Medicine, an
organization in Washington that promotes vegetarianism, also aims
to play down milk on the food pyramid. The organization has
received letters of support from Dr. Joycelyn Elders, the former
surgeon general; the former boxer Muhammad Ali; the writer Alice
Walker; Rep. Jesse L. Jackson Jr.; the NAACP; the Association of
Asian Pacific Community Health Organizations; the National Black
Nurses Association, and the National Hispanic Medical Association,
among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an ongoing campaign to get every adult to drink three
glasses of milk a day,'' said Willett of Harvard, agreeing with the
groups' efforts to de-emphasize milk. ``That's obviously about
increasing sales and profits.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Agriculture Department advisory committee, who
are university faculty members serving without pay, say this just
is not so. ``The guidelines process is subject to a lot of pressure
from a lot of groups,'' said Dr. Shiriki Kumanyika, a nutrition
professor at the University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine and
an advisory committee member. ``I like to do policy work and I like
to do it without being pressured on either side. And I don't think
the milk issue has been singled out.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, milk industry representatives have denounced the
physicians' group and Willett for engaging in what they call
``scare tactics that try and move people to their vegan agenda,''
said Dr. Greg Miller, vice president for nutrition research at the
National Dairy Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe they're using the racial card in a very
irresponsible way to suggest that dairy products are not
appropriate,'' said Susan Ruland, a spokeswoman for the National
Fluid Milk Processor Promotion Board. ``In fact, there's a calcium
crisis in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ruland, whose group is behind the $160 million ``Got Milk?''
and ``Milk Mustache'' advertising campaigns, called the concerns
irresponsible. (She also called Willett a ``vegetarian,'' a
description he laughingly dismissed as ``dietary slander.'')
</P>
<P>
   The committee working on the guidelines has been meeting since
September and has at least one more meeting scheduled before
writing its consensus report, which will then go to the departments
of Health and Human Services and Agriculture for review. The final
version will be published next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, one committee member, Dr. Richard R. Deckelbaum,
director of the Institute of Human Nutrition at Columbia
University, hinted that milk opponents might be protesting
prematurely. ``The needs of different populations have been one of
the areas of priority for this committee,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
