<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2271 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-NYT &LR;      06-28 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID NEW CONFUSION, THE INDIA-PAKISTAN WAR OF WORDS AND WEAPONS
CONTINUES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Seven weeks into an ever-intensifying war of
words and weapons, India and Pakistan on Monday could not even
agree about whether a Pakistani envoy had come to New Delhi over
the weekend to deliver a diplomatic message.
</P>
<P>
   According to Indian officials, Niaz Naik, a former Pakistani
foreign secretary, arrived in the capital with a communique from
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif. The envoy reportedly met with India's
prime minister, Atal Behari Vajpayee, and his national security
adviser, Brajesh Mishra.
</P>
<P>
   In Islamabad, Zamir Akram, a senior official in the foreign
ministry, denied that any message had been sent at all. ``It's all
wrong,'' he told a Pakistani news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Naik himself said: ``It's all speculation. There was no secret
visit.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes with these bitter adversaries _ the world's two
newest nuclear powers _ their versions of reality during the
current conflict evolving with barely any overlap.
</P>
<P>
   In India, it is widely presumed that the hundreds of invaders
who have crossed the border and taken up positions in the daunting,
windswept mountains of Kashmir are part of a Pakistani operation
that combines specially trained army regulars with a legion of
Islamic militant volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   In Pakistan, news accounts depict the incursion as a valorous
effort by tenacious ``freedom fighters'' who are supported by the
Islamabad government only with good wishes and devout prayers.
</P>
<P>
   In India, each day brings fresh accounts of air strikes with
``excellent results'' and successful, if painstaking, uphill climbs
that end with brave soldiers' overpowering the intruders in
hand-to-hand combat. Precise body counts are given. To date, the
Indians say, 398 Pakistani soldiers have been killed along with 123
Islamic militants _ a remarkable toll compared with far more modest
Indian losses.
</P>
<P>
   In Pakistan, the ``freedom fighters,'' also respectfully known
as the mujahedeen, are said to whipping the better-armed Indians,
surviving the continuing onslaught of air raids by hiding out in
caves and stone fortifications.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any single undeniable truth, it is that this is a
very dangerous situation with the potential to escalate from a
confined scrap along the ridge lines of remote peaks to the fourth
all-out war these two nations have fought.
</P>
<P>
   Statements from the leaders of both countries seem to fluctuate
daily between threatening swagger and professed restraint.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the Indian government has thus far held its troops
back from crossing into the Pakistani-controlled part of Kashmir.
As a result, they cannot use their superior numbers to surround the
enemy and choke off their supply lines. It has forced the military
to fight with ``one arm tied behind our backs,'' as many Indian
officers here complain.
</P>
<P>
   But it is uncertain how much longer those reins will remain in
place as Vajpayee's comments burn with impatience.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, while briefing the political opposition on the
Kashmir conflict, he insisted that ``nothing but the complete and
unconditional withdrawal of the intruders will satisfy our
requirements.'' He said ``no secret deals'' would be made and ``no
proposals or mediation by third parties will be accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   Just four months ago, Vajpayee had personally inaugurated a new
bus route between India and Pakistan. He held amicable talks with
Sharif. The two leaders endorsed the so-called Lahore declaration
that laid a groundwork for pursuing peace.
</P>
<P>
   That declaration now seems a murmur, drowned out by the current
artillery exchanges. Vajpayee said he wanted to continue a peaceful
dialogue with Pakistan, ``but under no condition will we permit any
alteration in the status quo'' concerning Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Many nations, including the United States, have criticized
Pakistan for allowing the peace effort to come untethered. It
remains to be seen, however, if any leverage will be used against
the Indian government. Pakistan, heavily in debt, is known as a
notorious deadbeat among international lenders. A squeeze on
promised credit would further harm an economy that already only
limps along.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif traveled to China on Monday, hoping to muster support
from a nation that has been a dependable ally.
</P>
<P>
   His plans had called for a six-day visit, but late in the day
the Pakistani Foreign Ministry spokesman, Tariq Altaf, said that
the visit would be cut short because ``of the situation back home
in our region.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1746EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
