<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2275 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VALDEZ-THEATER-ART-2T     06-28 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALDEZ-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FESTIVAL IN ALASKA DRAWS GUIDING LIGHTS FOR A 40TH ANNIVERSARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALDEZ, Alaska _ Edward Albee arrived by seaplane. His flight
into Anchorage, 250 miles to the west, had been delayed in Seattle,
so he missed his connection to the commercial puddle-jumper that
would have gotten him here in time. He was late for the production
of his 1961 play, ``The American Dream,'' at the annual theater
conference that (uncomfortably for him, as it happens) bears his
name.
</P>
<P>
   But the hastily chartered seaplane made a pretty landing, and
with the curtain being held at the Valdez Civic Center, he was
hustled to the auditorium by car. As he entered, 500 people waiting
in the audience leapt to their feet and applauded.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' Albee said later, cryptically amused as he often seems
to be, ``was fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the journey of the theater. Ah, wilderness. Albee (now 71
and a three-time Pulitzer Prize winner) first landed on an American
stage with a brief but biting, bordering-on-surreal tragedy, ``The
Zoo Story'' in January 1960 _ in another remote outpost, Greenwich
Village. It was at the start of the experimental theater revolution
that became known as the Off Broadway movement, a breaking away,
both in subject matter and theatrical protocol, from the kitchen
dramas and photographic realism that had become, via Broadway, the
staples of American stagecraft. It initiated a rapid expansion of
the theatrical landscape that flowered soon after in American
regional theaters. Now it has no farther west to go.
</P>
<P>
   Last week those early days were palpably revisited in this town
at the southern end of the Alaska pipeline, at the Edward Albee
Theater Conference, which was devoted to the 40th anniversary of
Off Broadway. Participants included many seminal figures of the
time, among them the actor and director Joseph Chaikin, the
playwrights Jack Gelber and Jean-Claude van Itallie, and Ellen
Stewart, the founder of La Mama Experimental Theater Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like getting the alumni back together,'' Albee said. All,
of course, are still working, but they found themselves both moved
and delighted by the recognition of their early contributions, a
feeling only augmented by the distance they traveled to get here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just like to say thank you to all the people here who
have told me my work is alive,'' said van Itallie, the author of
the long-running political critique ``America Hurrah'' in the
mid-'60s and the leading playwright at the Open Theater, the
ground-breaking enterprise in collaborative play-making founded by
Chaikin. He added, ``It's really important to me, this
validation.''
</P>
<P>
   Gelber, whose fourth-wall-busting play about jazz and drug
addiction, ``The Connection,'' had its premiere in 1959 at the
Living Theater on the second floor of a building at the Avenue of
the Americas and 14th Street, received the annual playwright's
honor, the Edward Albee Last Frontier Award. He was also given the
gift of a world premiere of a play he wrote 10 years ago, ``Magic
Valley,'' a warping-of-the-west tale (a theme that played very well
here) set in a broken-down Nevada saloon. The production was
presented by Eccentric Theater Co., which also staged ``The Zoo
Story,'' a two-handed battle over a bench in Central Park that felt
as discordant here as it did to Greenwich Villagers four decades
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ```The Zoo Story' was not my first play,'' Albee told the
audience in his introduction, before pausing mischievously. ``When
I was 12 1/2 I wrote a three-act sex farce. It had two faults, one
of which was that I knew very little about farce.''
</P>
<P>
   Also honored was Chaikin, who is afflicted with aphasia, the
result of a stroke he had during open heart surgery in 1984. In the
week's most poignant performance, he gave an eerie, affecting
recital of ``The War in Heaven,'' a radio play he wrote with Sam
Shepard early in his recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard, another Off Broadway alumnus, appeared at the
conference on videotape, and looking back on the 1960s in New York,
gave a tempered, perhaps mournful assessment of the Off Broadway
movement that seemed just about right. In the end, he said, ``I
don't know if we revolutionized anything; we made a few wrinkles.''
</P>
<P>
   The weeklong event, which ended on Sunday, was the seventh
annual theater conference sponsored by Prince William Sound
Community College. It is the brainchild of the college president,
Jo Ann McDowell, who has in the past lured writers like Arthur
Miller and August Wilson (Horton Foote has agreed to come next
year) with the promise of an honor in an exotic locale. Now,
however, having grown in both seriousness and renown, the event
appears to have entered adulthood; the Off Broadway celebration was
its first theme-based incarnation. More significantly, its play lab
has become formidable.
</P>
<P>
   Run by Michael Warren Powell, who for 20 years was the artistic
director of the Circle Repertory Company Lab in New York, it
attracted 140 scripts this year and held workshops for 54 aspiring
playwrights from 35 states. The visiting faculty _ who included the
longtime Village Voice critic Michael Feingold and the playwrights
Ed Bullins and William Hoffman _ unanimously agreed that the work
was of high quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bizarre, but this is my favorite conference,'' said
Hoffman, the author of the AIDS drama ``As Is,'' who was working
with the play lab for the fourth time. ``It's the most serious one
I know. All of us are drawn here by Alaska, but I keep coming back
because of the play lab.''
</P>
<P>
   For the participants in the Off Broadway celebration, it was a
disjointed week, melding nostalgia and boat excursions to a nearby
glacier, encouragement of new playwrights and hikes up a waterfall
in the summer solstice midnight sun. It was odd, even surreal,
revisiting lower Manhattan of the early 1960s from a shoreline
strip of land lying like a bib at the base of the verdant Chugach
Mountains, a three-leg plane trip from New York.
</P>
<P>
   In panel after panel, the visiting New Yorkers spoke about the
nurturing atmosphere of those years in the city when, unaware that
they were part of any movement, they simply worked and reveled in a
time of extraordinary artistic ferment.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the Cedar Tavern, the painters there didn't have the name
Abstract Expressionists, and the New York School of poets hadn't
been taken on by Time magazine,'' Albee said. Most important, he
added, commerce had no part in the act of creation; money had not
yet become the driving force behind the arts in general, theater in
particular. In 1960, he said, when ``The Zoo Story'' appeared on a
double bill with Beckett's ``Krapp's Last Tape'' at the
Provincetown Playhouse, ``we put them both on for $2000.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The word innocence was evoked again and again.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started La Mama in 1961, I knew nothing about
theater,'' said Ms. Stewart, whose space has long put out the
welcome mat for otherwise homeless theater artists. ``I started it
because I was interested in the people around me who were
interested in theater. I had a way of sprinkling fairy dust or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course, fairy dust doesn't go as far as it once did, a
point that was being made coincidentally at the same time in San
Francisco, where the Theater Communications Group, the trade
organization for the country's regional theaters, was having its
biannual gathering. There the main business was a discussion of an
elaborate new survey of the field conducted by the organization
this spring that focused precisely on the problems of maintaining
artistic integrity and financial stability.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time the pontoons of Albee's seaplane were
touching down here, the British director Sir Peter Hall, in his
keynote address, was lamenting the dangers of theaters' reliance on
corporate subsidies and warning of its attenuating affect on the
artistic product.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me we're not as audacious as we once were,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For many in Valdez, though, the clock seemed to take a hopeful,
pleasant tick backward. The town is resilient; it was swallowed by
a tidal wave after a mammoth earthquake in 1964, and of course its
name, if not its immediate area, was tainted by a notorious oil
spill a decade ago. (The Exxon Valdez ran aground on Bligh Reef,
some 20 miles southwest of here, and the oil flowed away from
town.)
</P>
<P>
   It is now a growing place with 4,500 residents, supported by oil
money and sprinkled with log-cabinish houses of contemporary
design. The wilderness is a quick walk from City Hall. It is, as
many here irresistibly noted, as far off Broadway as you can get;
but as uncharted theatrical territory, it seemed to many of the New
Yorkers, under the undue influence, perhaps, of stirring
surroundings and an active play lab, as good a place as any for
another revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see the kind of theater in New York that caters to a
large audience, well, people tend to copy each other,'' said
Lawrence Sacharow, a frequent director of Albee's work and the
author of ``The Concept,'' which opened in 1969 at La Mama and,
featuring drug addicts enacting their own stories, was a pioneering
work of performance art. ``You come out here, you're not bound by
what you see around you. That's kind of what we all felt in the
'60s; there was nothing we wanted to imitate.''
</P>
<P>
   Albee, whose new work, ``The Play About the Baby,'' is due in
New York next season, was a bit more sanguine. Characterizing his
role as that of mentor, he said he was pleased with the conference,
though he wants his name taken off it because he can't promise to
be there every year.
</P>
<P>
   He met Ms. McDowell, formerly the president of Independence
Community College in Independence, Mo., at the William Inge Theater
Conference there; when she came here in the early 1990s, he agreed
to help her establish a similar event.
</P>
<P>
   The thing still has a few bugs, he said. For one, the workshop
playwrights are getting only excerpts of their plays read, and that
has to change. And as it continues to grow, the jury selection of
scripts needs to be more rigorous. He also said he wishes they
wouldn't do so many of his plays. He does like having his name on
the awards because he chooses the recipients.
</P>
<P>
   As for the significance of the reunion here, he said the Off
Broadway movement had less to do with conscious experiment than
with a confluence of events in the culture. ``There are times when
cultures do wonderful things, and then they just rest for a
while,'' he said. The dominant ``middle browism'' of the theater
troubles him, the pervading influence of the popular, nonrealistic,
distancing forms of movies and television.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality of the theater is its biggest problem,'' he said.
``You go to a movie and sit with your popcorn and watch people blow
each other's brains out. If you tried to do that in the theater,
people would run out of there vomiting.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, experimental theater _ ``whatever
expands the boundaries of the expression of possibility of what the
theater can be, and which wrenches the mind and the gut'' _ is not
a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   And what about Valdez? Does he see the seeds of revolution here?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe,'' he said. ``Maybe not.'' He looked across the sound at
the snowy mountains disappearing into the clouds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do wish it was a little closer to TriBeCa,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
