<SLUG> BC-SCI-HEART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY CLEARS WAY FOR TRIALS OF HEART DRUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This subs for skedded SCI-HYPERTENSION-BLACKS, now
scratched.)  
 (af)  
 By JOHN O'NEIL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Researchers in a small trial succeeded in turning off a
biological agent that contributes to congestive heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published Monday in Circulation, the journal of the
American Heart Association, cleared the way for mass trials for a
new drug to treat the condition in which the heart fails to pump as
much blood as the body needs. The drug, etanercept, deactivates a
protein called tumor necrosis factor, or TNF, which is produced by
the body in response to cell damage.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies had established TNF as one of three substances
within the body that worsen heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   Medications had already been developed to counteract the other
two, adrenaline and angiotensin. Researchers doing laboratory work
had then determined that a protein with etanercept's structure
could bind with TNF and appeared to render it harmless.
</P>
<P>
   In the new research, led by Dr. Douglas Mann, a professor of
medicine at Baylor and the chief of cardiology at the Houston
Veterans Administration Medical Center, 12 heart failure patients
received a single shot containing varying amounts of etanercept,
while six similar patients received a placebo.
</P>
<P>
   None of the etanercept patients reported any side effects during
the two weeks they were tracked, and their levels of TNF dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Those receiving higher doses of etanercept had significant
improvement on several measures of heart function, including the
percentage of blood leaving the heart and the distance walked
during a six-minute trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will not lead to a cure for heart failure,'' Mann said,
because blocking one biological agent, like TNF, seems to stimulate
others, like aldosterone, to become active.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it will lead to significant improvements in quantity and
quality of life for failure patients,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
