<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2310 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUGHIE-REVIEW-LADN     06-28 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUGHIE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREDIT O'NEILL FOR DIALOGUE, PACINO FOR BRAVADO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 1/2 STARS 
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _The first thing that catches your eye in Al
Pacino's startling new production of Eugene O'Neill's ``Hughie'' is
that the clock hanging above center stage doesn't have any hands.
It's as if the two desperate men standing beneath it were frozen in
time, suspended in some sleazy Times Square purgatory beyond hope
or salvation.
</P>
<P>
   Written by the 52-year-old O'Neill as part of a cycle of one-act
monologues, ``Hughie,'' with a running time of barely an hour,
plays like a Cliff Notes version of ``The Iceman Cometh,'' the
author's four-hour late-career masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Hughie,'' O'Neill distilled his mordant worldview into a
40-proof shot of black humor, bitter epigrams and pitch-perfect
urban slang. Though naturalistic in its plotting, dialogue and Jazz
Age mis-en-scene, ``Hughie'' has a surreal undertow, an
expressionistic tension that permeates the action like ether.
Before you quite know what you're inhaling, you're already under
its spell.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling double duty here as director and star, Pacino, along
with his inspired design team, makes the case that while ``Hughie''
is a miniature work, it's not necessarily a minor one. It's
doubtful this 1941 drama has ever felt more ageless, more vitally
of the moment, than it does right now at the Mark Taper Forum.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the year is 1928, the hour between 3 and 4 a.m.,
the place the lobby of a down-at-the-heels Manhattan hotel. Or, to
put it another way, it is an era of hubristic optimism, at a time
of profound melancholy, in a part of America where the principal
order of business is to sucker or be suckered.
</P>
<P>
   This is where Erie Smith (Pacino), a small-time gambler and
part-time petty hood, has come to unload his last respects to
Hughie, the hotel's recently deceased night clerk and Erie's
personal talisman. Despondent over Hughie's death, Erie is coming
off a five-day drinking binge, ready to pour out his life story to
Hughie's unwitting replacement, a stone-faced fellow named, of all
things, Charlie Hughes (Paul Benedict).
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 55 minutes, Erie will reminisce about his dead
friend with a mixture of fondness and scorn, crack off-color jokes,
and boast about the ponies he bets and the Ziegfeld dolls he
supposedly beds. Hughes will pretend to listen while his own mind
goes sleep-walking through the dark city streets, in search of its
own lurid fictions. For all their differences, Erie, the shabby
hustler, and Hughes the bored family man, will become locked in a
waltz of co-dependent delusion.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially an extended monologue in which Erie slices open a
vein and the night clerk watches him bleed raw emotion, ``Hughie''
contains some of the most elaborate stage notes ever written.
O'Neill supplied the night clerk with line after line of unspoken
ruminations, giving the actor playing him some way of pacing his
character's emotional evolution while Erie spills his guts.
</P>
<P>
   In conceiving this production, Pacino had the bright idea of
letting Benedict speak the clerk's thoughts aloud, using miking
that gives them a sepulchral echo. This effect, alternately creepy
and ironically amusing, combined with David Gallo's set design of
oppressive cutaways of skyscrapers and fire escapes, Donald
Holder's Edward Hopper-esque lighting and Jon Gottlieb's sound
design of rumbling motor cars and far-off snatches of music, casts
a suitably metaphysical pall over the encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully offsetting these abstract elements, Pacino makes Erie
emphatically, almost heroically, of the fleshy here and now. Manic
enthusiasm and scrappy self-importance come easily to this actor,
who falters only when he tries to dredge deep feelings from a man
rarely prone to self-excavation.
</P>
<P>
   Everything about this sentimental mercenary seems fittingly
oversized: his sexual bravado, his rumpled off-white suit, and the
painful isolation that surrounds his life. Pacino inflates Erie's
low-life defeats to near-tragic proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Making the most of what could have been an invisible role,
Benedict conveys wary humor and mild-mannered reserve masking a
raging inner resignation. Though Benedict can't make the night
clerk's last-minute conversion fully plausible, he and Pacino turn
their duet into a dirge of sublime dissonance.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty years after ``Hughie'' was written, Pacino has exhumed
from this rarely produced play O'Neill's masterly and concise
summing-up of existence. It's a creative eulogy for an artist who'd
concluded that romance and fatalism, success and failure, are but
twin sides of a two-headed coin. Whichever way you call it, the
odds don't exactly look great. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
