<HEADER>
A2314 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSTAND29-COX     06-28 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Newsweek looks at anger against newly rich
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The economy is booming and the stock market is soaring. So why,
Newsweek ($3.50) asks, are so many Americans grumpy? The problem
is, many of us think our friends and neighbors are getting rich and
we're not. As stories circulate about young entrepreneurs hitting
the jackpot on the Internet, the traditional road to wealth _ hard
work and perseverance _ seems as outdated as a vacuum tube
computer. ``In this age of Outlandish Expectations,'' Adam Bryant
writes, ``even Horatio Alger might be tempted to trade stocks
online.''
</P>
<P>
   CRUISING: Stanley Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide Shut'' is one of the
most talked-about films since ``The Phantom Menace,'' mainly
because of the shroud of secrecy around the project. In this week's
Time ($3.50), critic Richard Schickel previews the film and dispels
some of the myths surrounding it. Contrary to some reports, Tom
Cruise and Nicole Kidman do not play psychiatrists in the movie.
Cruise is a doctor and Kidman is a former art gallery manager. Yes,
there are nude scenes and an orgy, but, says Kubrick's widow,
Christiane: ``It has nothing to do with sex and everything to do
with fear.'' As for how intimate Cruise and Kidman get on the
screen, Schickel is keeping his mouth wide shut.
</P>
<P>
   SEX SYMBOLS: For a double dose of male pulchritude, take a look
at New York's ($3.99) cover story on Ricky Martin and W magazine's
($3.95) 30-page photo spread of Brad Pitt. In an interview about as
thin as the magazine's pages, pop star Martin talks about the
growing Latin influence in music (``It's a phenomenon''), working
with Madonna (``I learned a lot''), and his sex life (``I leave it
for my room and lock the door''). The grim and gritty Steven Klein
photographs of Pitt in W reflect the actor's new role in ``Fight
Club.'' In the film, Pitt plays the founder of an underground
network of clubs where men pair off to pound each other with their
bare fists until they can't fight anymore.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN AMERICA: Ricky Martin is not the only Latino shaking up
American culture. George ($2.95) examines the Latin influence in
movies, music and politics, and focuses on some of North America's
new players. Among those profiled are novelist Oscar Hijuelos,
White House Deputy Chief of Staff Maria Echaveste, actor John
Leguizamo and actress Salma Hayek. And that's just the beginning.
Out of 800,000 people who immigrated to the U.S. in 1997, the
magazine reports, 400,000 were Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   OUR TOWN: In its most appetizing issue to date, Atlanta's
($3.50) summer dining issue offers a guide to 25 gourmet meals
under $25. Among the choice restaurants: Hong Kong Gourmet, Agnes &AMP;
Muriel's, Watershed and the Crazy Cuban. But when money is no
object, dining critic Christiane Lauterbach recommends Fusebox,
Floatway Cafe, Bone's or Seeger's, among others. . . . Atlanta
Citymag ($3.95), formerly Dossier, has an interesting profile of
Philip Osborne, a Hemingway look-alike and founder of the
Atlanta-based Bush Homes of Africa Safari. Osborne, 67, tells some
hair-raising tales of being rushed by an elephant herd and scaling
Mount Kilimanjaro when he was 65.
</P>
<P>
   THAT'S LIFE: What makes boys and girls different? Besides the
obvious physical things, it's mostly chemistry, says Pulitzer
Prize-winning writer Deborah Blum in the July issue of Life
($2.95). Human males are likely to produce seven to 10 times more
testosterone than females. As a result, boys tend to be more
rough-and-tumble than girls. This is reflected in play patterns as
early as preschool, Blum says. Boys tend to gather in large,
competitive groups and play games that have clear winners and
losers. Girls prefer small groups, playing theatrical games that
don't feature hierarchy or winners. There are exceptions, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   MEN STUFF: The July/August issue of Maxim ($3.50) is obviously
aimed at boosting testosterone levels. A scantily clad Michelle
Williams of TV's ``Dawson Creek'' is used as a cover tease to more
revealing photos and profiles of Hollywood's ``10 Sexiest
Nymphets.'' Those making the list include Reese Witherspoon of
``Cruel Intentions,'' Jennifer Love Hewitt of ``Party of Five'' and
Sarah Michelle Gellar of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.'' Also of note
is a list of the 50 greatest guys of the century, which includes
Hank Aaron, Muhammad Ali, Ray Charles, Chuck Yeager, Clint Eastwood
and Elvis _ in his fat years, white sequined jumpsuit and all.
</P>
<P>
   Eye opener
</P>
<P>
   Time ($3.50) features a revealing interview with Tom Cruise and
Nicole Kidman and a preview of their much-touted film, ``Eyes Wide
Shut.''
</P>
<P>
   Latin beat
</P>
<P>
   Actress Salma Hayek strikes a patriotic pose for George's
($2.95) package on the Latino influence in politics, sports and
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
