<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, June 29, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, wind gusts of 80 mph toppled trees in portions of
eastern Kansas as a complex of potent thunderstorms raced through
the lower Missouri Valley. The storms formed as an inflow of very
humid air intercepted a jet stream disturbance passing overhead. On
Tuesday, a weak cool front will suppress the humid conditions
farther south, setting the stage for additional thunderstorms to
erupt from northwest Texas to Oklahoma, southern Kansas and
Arkansas. Where the storms occur, there will be a moderate risk for
damaging winds and hail.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will also be common along the Eastern
Seaboard as a cold front approaching from the west intercepts and
lifts very sultry air covering the region. Many of these showers
and storms will contain heavy rain, helping to ease the drought
conditions over the region. It is very likely that Boston will have
measurable rain Tuesday for the first time in 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the thunderstorms could be severe across New England
and upstate New York where a jet stream disturbance augments the
ascent of the sultry air. Farther west, drier breezes from the west
will import refreshingly cooler air into the Great Lakes states.
</P>
<P>
   A cluster of showers and thunderstorms will erupt over the
Northern Plains later Tuesday as a cold front sweeps eastward from
the northern Rockies. Elsewhere, sunshine will scorch the
Southwestern deserts and interior California while clouds and
chilly conditions cling to the Northwest Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Returning Rains
</P>
<P>
   After a dry winter and spring, the rains of summer have returned
to Florida. A downpour in Hollywood, Fla., on Saturday brought the
precipitation so far this month to a record 18.68 inches while
nearby Fort Lauderdale's total stands at over 19 inches. Not far to
the north and south of Hollywood conditions have been noticeably
less wet. Thirty miles south, Miami has accumulated 10 inches this
June while 150 miles to the north only 5 inches has fallen in
Melbourne. The variation of rainfall over relatively small
distances is typical in regions that receive tropical showers like
Florida. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
