<SLUG> BC-BRIDGETT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Story of girl's struggle to leave poverty brings huge response
 &HT;    (EDS: CoxNet will resend original story for those who need it.
Call 404-526-5456.)
 &HT;    By Jim Dyer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An article in The Atlanta Journal-Constitution's
Sunday edition that depicted the struggle of a young black girl to
overcome a life of poverty in southwest Georgia prompted torrents
of telephone calls from people across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of readers from Oregon to Florida contacted the
newspaper expressing an interest to send clothes, books or money to
help the family of 15-year-old Bridgett Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgett, like generations of her family, grew up in a
three-room rotting pine shack and struggled against abject poverty.
She became one of her high school's academic standouts in Webster
County, Ga., a rural region 35 miles southeast of Columbus, but the
lanky teenager still faces large hurdles and long odds to realize
her dream of attending college.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's horrible to see people who are subjected to 18th-century
poverty in 1999,'' said one caller, Jane Griffin, 31, of Atlanta.
``Our government and people like (CNN founder) Ted Turner send
millions of dollars of humanitarian aid overseas when we've got
Third World destitution right in our back yards.''
</P>
<P>
   The article rekindled haunting memories for George Nealy, 44,
who fled Webster County's poverty in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can relate to that family's struggle, to working the fields
and picking peas for $2 a day,'' he said. ``Fortunately, I got out.
I hope that girl does, too.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, some people traveled hundreds of miles to Preston,
Bridgett's hometown, to seek out the teen-age girl and offer her
encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been coming or calling all day,'' said Vernette
Goodwin, a retired black school teacher who lives near Bridgett and
has served as her mentor. ``This girl's strength and determination
has touched a lot of lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin has set up a trust fund for Bridgett and is also
accepting donations of clothes, school supplies and books for the
girl and her family. Part of the trust fund will be set aside for
Bridgett for college. Another part will be used to pay Bridgett to
work part-time after school at the town library.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO HELP
</P>
<P>
   For those interested in sending clothes, books or money to
Bridgett and her family, the address is:
</P>
<P>
   Bridgett Stewart
</P>
<P>
   c/o Zeta Phi Beta Sorority Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Attn. Vernette Goodwin
</P>
<P>
   Route 2, Box 6A
</P>
<P>
   Preston, Ga. 31824
</P>
<P>
   Checks may be made out to the ``Bridgett Stewart Fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Dyer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
