<HEADER>
A2345 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-0629-COX     06-28 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-0629-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SERB CHURCH ASKS FOR HELP BUT GETS LITTLE SYMPATHY
 &HT;    575&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRACANICA, Yugoslavia _ On a day that Serbs celebrate a sacred
defeat 610 years ago, leaders of the Serbian Orthodox Church
pleaded Monday for help from NATO in the wake of their latest
national disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The same clergy that two months ago suggested that NATO leaders
were war criminals for their punishing bombing campaign against
Yugoslavia, now threatened to end cooperation with NATO forces
unless their people are protected from ethnic Albanian revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Church leaders coupled their pleas with repeated condemnations
of Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of Yugoslavia and
their sometime-ally, saying he had hurt ``Serbs'' most -- even in
the face of atrocities committed in recent months in Kosovo against
ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has done a lot of evil to all. He has done the most evil to
the Serb people,'' said Serbian Orthodox Bishop Artemije
Radosavljevic, citing Serb refugees from Milosevic's wars in
Bosnia, Croatia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Church leaders said 80 ethnic Serbs have been killed since NATO
peacekeeping forces began moving into war-ravaged Kosovo province
on June 12. That compares to an estimated 10,000 Kosovar Albanians
killed by Serbs in the last three months.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Artemije did acknowledge Serb crimes against ethnic
Albanians, and said the church has opposed violence by either side
in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But, the Serb plea was less over numbers than about emotions,
coming on a day of Serb martyrdom.
</P>
<P>
   In 1389, the Serbs were overtaken in the Battle of Kosovo by the
Ottoman Turks. The battle was a draw, but allowed the Ottomans to
begin their five centuries of rule over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The day is central to Serb history. A Bosnian Serb killed the
Archduke Ferdinand on this date in 1914, setting off World War I.
Milosevic energized his political career with a speech in Kosovo
Polje extolling Serb nationalism and control of Kosovo on this date
in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   A sign of how relations between the two countries have changed,
the United States marked the day in 1918 in gratitude to Serbia's
support in the war.
</P>
<P>
   One casualty of the Battle of Kosovo was the Serbs' Prince
Lazar, who has taken on martyr status. His legacy is spelled out on
a monument to the battle today: ``The Serb who does not fight for
Kosovo, let him be cursed forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Serbs are retreating from Kosovo again. Seventy-eight
days of NATO bombing forced Milosevic to pull his troops from
Kosovo, a province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant republic. While
thousands used to show up for a march every year on this day, there
was no march this year. That's because many Serbs have either fled,
or are afraid to participate.
</P>
<P>
   As half the estimated 860,000 ethnic Albanian refugees have
returned from neighboring Albania and Macedonia, U.N. officials
said Monday, many have sought revenge on the Serb minority. They
have burned houses, committed murders and driven some tens of
thousands out of the province.
</P>
<P>
   But, even Serbs here in Kosovo seem slow to acknowledge what has
happened in this embattled province.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the 1389 Cafe, a local watering hole directly
opposite the Serbian Orthodox Monastery in the village of
Gracanica, Serbs saw themselves almost exclusively as the victims,
rather than the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked for it,'' said Nikola Maximovic, a 40-year-old
mechanic. ``They wanted this situation and this war. The Albanian
people wanted to take Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Serbian Orthodox Church leaders Monday released a letter calling
for NATO to crack down on anti-Serb crime and threatening that the
Serbs of the region will stop cooperating with NATO unless they
feel safe.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Artemije contended the guilty had already fled Kosovo.
``We cannot allow uncontrolled and enraged crowds to exact
justice,'' the bishop told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But, church leaders have in the past supported Milosevic or
served his purposes. Bishop Artemije himself wrote a scathing,
sarcastic, letter to NATO leaders when the bombing started. It
suggested that NATO leaders go before the war crimes tribunal at
The Hague and concluded, ``you are incapable of repentance for the
evil you inflict upon us.''
</P>
<P>
   The church's condemnation of Milosevic actually elicited
laughter from some ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have done more earlier. Not now, but when it could
have helped,'' said Ajet Ismahli, a 53-year-old math teacher.
``They know that NATO is here and they cannot do what they had been
doing before, so they are trying to change their manner.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
