<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWIFT-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SWIFT': BREEZILY READABLE AND WELL INFORMED
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(jw) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Jonathan Swift died in 1745 he was already a legend,
renowned (or infamous) in his day not only for ``Gulliver's
Travels'' and other blackly satirical works but also for his
involvement in Tory politics and the fight for Irish rights. In the
two and a half centuries since his death, the clergyman's
intemperate personality and scathing prose made him a magnet in
literary circles for a host of speculation. Swift, one historian
noted, ``has been the occasion of more nonsense than any other
writer except Shakespeare.''
</P>
<P>
   There were disputes about Swift's paternity, whispers about a
love triangle with two women, and questions about his misanthropy
and supposed madness. Was he actually the illegitimate son of his
patron and mentor, William Temple? Was he secretly married to
Esther (Stella) Johnson, his longtime companion? Did Swift, an
ordained clergyman, actually believe in God? Did he have sex with
Stella's rival, Hester (Vanessa) Vanhomrigh, or did he remain
celibate his entire life? Did his mother's abandonment of him as a
boy plant the seeds of his anger? Or did his rage against the world
stem from his professional disappointments (e.g., his failure to
achieve a senior clerical appointment in England) and messy
romantic entanglements?
</P>
<P>
   In her new book, ``Jonathan Swift: A Portrait,'' novelist and
biographer Victoria Glendinning tackles these questions head-on.
She has chosen not to write a minutely detailed, comprehensive
biography _ that has already been done by Irvin Ehrenpreis, author
of the three-volume ``Swift, the Man, His Works and the Age'' _ but
to provide an extended version of what was known in Swift's time as
a ``character,'' a written portrait.) Her book is tart, opinionated
and subjective _ at once breezily readable and well informed.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Glendinning, who won the 1992 Whitbread Prize for her
biography of Anthony Trollope, devotes considerably less space to
Swift's public career as propagandist and spinmeister to the Tory
Party during the last years of Queen Anne's reign than his last
biographer, David Nokes (``Jonathan Swift, a Hypocrite Reversed''),
did. She instead focuses on Swift's elusive personality, piecing
together clues to his inner life from his own writings and accounts
left by acquaintances and friends. She puts Swift's work in context
with that of such contemporaries as Alexander Pope and Daniel
Defoe, and she enlivens her narrative with chatty asides about such
matters as the coffeehouse culture of the early 1700s, the
sanitation conditions of 18th-century London and Swift's use of
scatological language.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of the book, Swift emerges as a man who, like
Gulliver, was ``always too big or too small for the company he
keeps,'' a man whose ambitions were frequently undercut by his rage
at the hypocrisy and injustice around him. ``He longs for the
world's rewards but cannot respect the world's rules and cannot be
quiet,'' Ms. Glendinning writes. While he champions underdogs out
of his passion for justice, and ``out of his insecurities he is
pleased to consort with top dogs,'' he ``identifies himself wholly
with nothing that he sees.'' This rage and ambivalence, of course,
would fuel Swift's slashing, often shocking humor and animate such
dark, deadpan works as ``A Modest Proposal'' (which satirically
suggested that the poor might alleviate their plight by eating
their children).
</P>
<P>
   This detachment, Ms. Glendinning argues, was even more
pronounced in Swift's private life. In response to his unhappy
childhood, he ``always defended himself against emotional
dependency and preached that gospel to others.'' His strategy for
emotional survival, she writes, was ``flight from all risk of
grief, pain or disappointment _ at the price of fleeing also from
the pleasure and sweetness which make life worth living for most
people.''
</P>
<P>
   With women, he liked to assume the role of teacher,
patronizingly correcting their faults, while holding himself aloof
from emotional commitment. For years he kept both Stella and
Vanessa at arm's length, playing one off against the other and
making both jealous. Stella, whom Ms. Glendinning characterizes as
``the most important person in his life,'' was cast in the role of
nursemaid, caretaker and confidante, while the more amorous Vanessa
was courted as a dangerous but alluring mistress.
</P>
<P>
   Given the lack of credible evidence about Swift's actual
relationship with these women, Ms. Glendinning speculates that he
and Vanessa may have ``consummated their affair once and that the
act established Vanessa's lasting fixation and that Swift regretted
it'' as a moment of human weakness. She argues that ``it is
possible,'' even probable, that he and Stella ``did go through some
ceremony in the summer of 1716'' but adds that the couple quickly
returned to their parallel lives.
</P>
<P>
   Though the reader might well question why Ms. Glendinning
devotes so much space in this volume to unanswerable questions
about her subject's private life, she uses these discussions to
illuminate Swift's prickly, elusive personality and his bitter,
playful work. She also uses them to underscore the difficulties of
retrieving historical facts and the role that subjectivity can play
in shaping a biographical portrait.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no such thing as a definitive biography,'' she
concludes. ``All the versions of Jonathan Swift _ from the gossip
and Chinese whispers of his contemporaries and near-contemporaries,
to the wilder flights of speculative fancy and the sober gleanings
of scholarship and historical research _ contribute something to
our understanding of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the same man is not always the same man. The living,
breathing, joking, suffering Swift remains a lost original.
Biographical writers can do their utmost to avoid saying, to quote
his Houynhnhnms, `the thing which was not.' To say the thing which
was is harder.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   JONATHAN SWIFT
</P>
<P>
   A Portrait
</P>
<P>
   By Victoria Glendinning
</P>
<P>
   324 pages. Henry Holt &AMP; Co. $35.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
