<HEADER>
A2350 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-GUNSUIT-COX     06-28 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-GUNSUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gunmaker cites reasons for Atlanta lawsuit dismissal
 &HT;    By Jay Croft
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta's lawsuit against gunmakers should be thrown
out of court because it is barred by a state law passed five days
after the city brought the action, attorneys for Smith &AMP; Wesson
Corp. argue in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   The company's response, filed in Fulton County State Court, is
the first since the city sued Feb. 4, seeking unspecified damages
estimated in the millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta joined a growing list of cities suing the handgun
industry, after successful government lawsuits against the tobacco
industry for health care costs related to smoking. The suit says
gunmakers do not use enough safety devices to keep ``unauthorized
users,'' including children, from firing them.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 9, the Georgia Assembly passed a law saying cities could
not file such suits _ and extended the ban to any lawsuits pending
at the time, including Atlanta's.
</P>
<P>
   Smith &AMP; Wesson called the city's suit ``a radical departure from
traditional concepts'' of liability and an attempt ``to establish
social policy through the court system.''
</P>
<P>
   The company called the suit vague, argumentative and overly
broad, saying it relied on selective facts, ``unspecified `surveys'
and rumors, much of which is both irrelevant and inflammatory in
tone and content.'' It also said the suit violates Second and
Fourteenth Amendments, guaranteeing gun rights and due process.
</P>
<P>
   And the city cannot try to claim damages for harm allegedly
caused to individuals, Smith &AMP; Wesson says. ``The city has not
alleged any direct harm to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The city wants reimbursement for costs such as police and fire
protection and a loss of tourism, said Atlanta's Assistant City
Attorney Bill McLean, who had not seen Smith &AMP; Wesson's response
Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith &AMP; Wesson says ``the general rule'' is that such costs
cannot be recovered in a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the case hinges on the constitutionality of the state's
law, McLean said, which will be determined by Judge Gino Brogdon
and appealed by the losing party.
</P>
<P>
   McLean said previous cases have shown it is sometimes allowable
for laws to include retroactive bans, as the state's does. ``But
there are also circumstances when it's not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Croft writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
