 For Release TUESDAY AMs, June 29, 1999  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND (Belfast) _ Hopes for breaking the deadlock in North
Ireland focus on a proposal to allow Protestants a token march
through a Catholic neighborhood in return for unionists dropping a
demand that the IRA begin disarming before Sinn Fein takes its seat
in the government. By Kevin Cullen and John O'Farrell. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SURPLUS (Washington) _ President Clinton says the
federal budget surpluses over the next 15 years will be so huge _
about $1 trillion more than the previous estimate _ that the
government can avert a potential Social Security bankruptcy,
include prescription drugs in the Medicare program, cut taxes and
retire the entire national debt by 2015. By Aaron Zitner. 1200
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DRUGS (Undated) _ President Clinton is attempting to
pull off a tricky balancing act in his Medicare prescription drug
proposal. The plan must benefit the great majority of Medicare
beneficiaries. But to meet the greatest need he has to target
low-income elders and heavily subsidize both their premiums and
their out-of-pocket prescription drugs. By Richard A. Knox. 800
words.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HUBBELL (New York) _ Hubbell plea bargain will have an effect
on Hillary Clinton's apparent plans to run for the US Senate from
New York. Fred Kaplan. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-FOOTBALL (Undated) _ In a move with implications for the
entire TV industry, ABC has reached a deal with its affiliate
governing board in which the affiliates would pay a total of $45
million per year to the network to defray the cost of ``Monday
Night Football.'' By Don Aucoin. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FLEET-BANKBOS (Boston) _ Bidding closes in the divestiture of
the merging Fleet-BankBoston branch banks. By Lynnley Browning. 900
words.
</P>
<P>
   FIEDLITY-LEHMAN (Boston) _ Fidelity Investments forms a
strategic alliance with old-line New York investment bank Lehman
Brothers to distribute Lehman research and products, including
IPOs, to Fidelity customers. By Lynnley Browning. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ-ALTAVISTA (Undated) _ Compaq's undervalued asset
AltaVista unveils a new look and new features as rumors continue to
circulate that it is being bought by CMGI. By Hiawatha Bray. 500
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEN-WIMBLEDON (London) _ Her saga is straight out of a bedtime
story, and she could pass for a pixie compared to her elders on the
women's tennis circuit, who include just about everyone. But Jelena
Dokic is for real. By Bob Duffy. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN (London) _ Andre Agassi knew how Wayne
Arthurs felt as a child: tied-up. By Bud Collins.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-WHITESOX-REDSOX (Boston) _ By Larry Whiteside.
</P>
