<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2364 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-28 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL TWINS NO MORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To judge by the clumsiness of his abrupt carping
about President Clinton's moral standards, Vice President Al Gore's
political divorce from his mentor is going to be messy _ personally
and professionally.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president has no choice but to try to reshape his
identity in order to demonstrate he's not just Clinton's sidekick
but presidential timber in his own right. The brother-buddy act of
the past six years is over. It MUST be over, given Gore's uphill
struggle against the popular Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore didn't handle his maiden voyage into new independence
smoothly last week, provoking stories that his mentor resented the
heir-apparent's approach.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton knows perfectly well that Gore must build his own nest.
Nonetheless the president was said to be furious that his
second-in- command seemed excessively enthusiastic in denouncing
the affair with Monica Lewinsky as ``inexcusable'' and repeatedly
endorsing the marvels of so-called conservative family values.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as usual with the White House, wheels may have been spinning
within wheels here. The cagey president could have been reinforcing
Gore's coming-out by creating the impression of a spat _ not all
that farfetched a concept.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton needs Gore to succeed him, not only to protect the
administration's legacy but to have a good shot at a presidential
pardon if the endlessly vindictive Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr indicts him once he's out of office.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Clinton has been supportive of Gore's ambitions in a
multitude of ways. It is difficult to believe Clinton is so
deranged by a temporary irritation that he will actually help Bush
_ son of the man he dislikes, the president he beat in 1992 _
replace him in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there's no way to know for sure, egos in high places being
egos in high gear.
</P>
<P>
   President Lyndon B. Johnson, for instance, actively undercut the
1968 presidential campaign of his vice president, Hubert Humphrey,
despite Humphrey's loyal service. LBJ thought Richard Nixon was
tougher than Humphrey and so would resolve the Vietnam War. He
regretted his mistake later as Nixon won the election by half a
percentage point, let the war limp on and tried to sink the Great
Society programs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton could not have been surprised by Gore's approach but he
might well have been taken aback by its blunt tone. Gore didn't
quite say so, but he left the distinct impression that the
president lied to him _ a communication that might better have been
left confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's new role as presidential candidate requires that he stand
up to, and apart from, his boss. Gore might, however, have adopted
a slightly more ambivalent attitude as he spoke out for the first
time about his own feelings toward the president's misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   This is a delicate path for Gore. Every vice president owes his
influence to the confidence of his superior. Gore has proven over
and over that he can be trusted to deliver for the team. But that
one-dimensional quality is appreciated mostly by its chief
beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
   The polls tell him that. In recent trial heats against Bush, the
vice president trails by roughly 15 points. Voters say they don't
know much about either candidate. But Gore has been around the
White House so long that they prefer the new guy on the block.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a new poll that reports public satisfaction with
the direction the country is going seems to be reversing.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the prosperous economy, a majority used to say that
we are on the right track. But now it seems the school shootings
and a general feeling of moral decay have led 51 percent of voters
to say we're doing something wrong and only 36 percent to say we're
okay.
</P>
<P>
   What this may mean is anybody's guess, but it does suggest that
Clinton is wearing thin. A majority of voters didn't want him
railroaded out of town because of sex, but a majority also wouldn't
want him to have another presidential term.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody claims that Gore is implicated in Clinton's sexcapades or
that Gore's marital conduct has been anything but exemplary. But
he's Clinton's political partner and will remain so even while he
campaigns for president.
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey never figured out how to resolve the dual
responsibility even though Johnson was working against him. HHH was
urged to resign the vice presidency to free himself to speak his
own mind about the Vietnam War, but he refused. He thought it would
be disloyal.
</P>
<P>
   Gore can't take that route either. For one thing, a vice
presidential vacancy would make Republican House Speaker Dennis
Hastert second in line to the throne, an unthinkable prospect. And
a Senate fight over confirming a successor would distract from the
2000 presidential race, elevate partisan tensions, make Gore look
like a cop-out and help Bush.
</P>
<P>
   So what can Gore do? There's always the universal favorite: Keep
your head above water and wait for the rain to stop. Time aplenty
for that before November 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been counted down before and recovered. Even as a
lame-duck president, he demonstrated during his news conference
last Friday that he retains his persuasive powers and is still a
formidable political figure.
</P>
<P>
   Gore we don't know about. But surely he's learned something
about survival from these years at Clinton's side.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means may be reached by e-mail at means(at)hearst
dc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
