<TEXT>
<P>
   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Tuesday, June 29. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton releases his
budget plan, gives briefings on the economy and allocation of a
windfall surplus. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   HUBBELL-STARR (Washington) _ Webster Hubbell reaches a plea
bargain agreement with Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel. By
Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-MURDERS (Littleton, Colo.) _ Two months after the
school shootings here, interviews with scores of people indicate a
fundamental disconnect between the trouble world of Eric Harris and
Dylan Klebold and the lives their parents thought they were
leading. The interviews paint a portrait of the Harrises and the
Klebolds as caring, conscientious parents who structured their
lives around supporting their children and believed they were on
the right track. By Pam Belluck and Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   Special Report: 3,800 words. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED) Eds.: An abridged version is also moving.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-CONSERVATIVES (Manchester, N.H.) _ Conservative
Republicans are distressed at George W. Bush's dominance of the
presidential primaries. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-DRUGS (Undated) _ American charities and drug
companies have donated drugs and medicine to the Kosovo relief
effort _ with mixed results. By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INSURANCE-FRAUD (Undated) _ Details on Martin Frankel's
background and how he gained entry into the world of high finance.
By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIAN-REPORT (Ramallah, West Bank) _ An international task
force issues a critical but sympathetic look at Palestinian
institutions. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ About 75,000 Serbs have
moved from Kosovo to Serbia proper and refugee aid groups say they
are running out of food for them. This comes on top of 500,000 Serb
refugees from Croatia and Bosnia, according to UNHCR estimates. But
the feeding operation is run by the Red Cross and it apparently
stopped shipping food during the war and has not yet resumed
shipments. By Blaine Harden. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STEM-CELLS (Bethesda, Md.) _ The presidential bioethics
advisory commission struggles over the issue of whether federally
financed researchers should be allowed to obtain primordial human
cells from embryos. The cells offer potentially giant advantages in
treating a range of diseases, but opponents of abortion, among
others, say it is immoral to obtain them from embryos. By Nicholas
Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AMISH-GENES (Undated) _ The Amish and Mennonites may forgo
most modern conveniences, but there is one bit of progress that
they are especially eager to embrace: gene therapy. Three children
from these communities are expected to become the first humans ever
to test a new method of gene therapy. If it works, it will spare
them the devastating effects of a rare but deadly inherited disease
known as Crigler-Najjar syndrome. It occurs when a substance called
bilirubin, a waste product from the destruction of worn out red
blood cells, builds up in the body and destroys the liver and grows
toxic to the nervous system. By Denise Grady. 2,800 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
</TEXT>
