<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-PEPSI-BOTTLERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pepsi employees to enjoy extra pay, benefits, under new contract
 &HT;    By Lynn Hulsey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A new four-year contract gives Pepsi-Cola General
Bottlers employees salary increases, pension plan improvements and
extra pay for weekend work.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday workers represented by Teamsters Local 957 voted 173
to 15 to approve the contract with the company, which employs about
250 Teamsters at plants in Dayton and Springfield, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Workers walked out June 17 and did not withdraw picketers until
Friday, when a tentative accord was reached with the Rolling
Meadows, Ill.-based company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased that it was resolved and they're back to work,''
said Andy Kinigson, the company's director of employee relations.
</P>
<P>
   Varney Richmond, Local 957 secretary treasurer, said the strike
was a success and helped gain public support for the workers.
</P>
<P>
   The new contract gives workers no salary increase in the first
year. But in return, the company will pick up the full cost of
insurance, Richmond said. Hourly workers get a 30-cent increase in
the second year and 35-cent increases in years three and four.
Commission workers also get a raise, and the company sweetened
pensions for all unionized workers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the major sticking points had been the company's desire
to change schedules so some employees would no longer get two
consecutive days off each week. The new pact limits to 10 percent
the number of employees who can be assigned to those shifts and
gives them extra pay for weekend work, Richmond said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Hulsey writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
