</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCCOY-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There's no place like the road for the Reds
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ The Big Road Machine did the improbable _ some said
impossible until the Cincinnati Reds did it _ winning seven
straight road games against two first-place teams, three at Arizona
and four at Houston.
</P>
<P>
   And by obliterating the Houston Astros in the Astrodome, the
Reds did the improbable _ even more said impossible until The Big
Road Machine did it _ by coming home in first place in the National
League Central.
</P>
<P>
   Now they have to do it again. Same teams. Same number of games.
Three against Arizona. Four against Houston. Only they have to do
it at home _ and for the Reds home is where the losses are.
</P>
<P>
   While they own major-league baseball's best road record (26-10),
only four last-place teams _ Florida, Milwaukee, Tampa Bay,
Minnesota _ have worse home records than Cincinnati's 15-21.
</P>
<P>
   First place? These Reds? This team with a tissue-paper starting
rotation, this team that was in last place at 14-18 and seven games
out first place on May 14, this team whose clean-up hitter, Greg
Vaughn, is hitting .215 and was 3 for 24 on the trip and stranded
12 while driving in four?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, these Reds.
</P>
<P>
   And captain Barry Larkin insists it is no surprise to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surprised. I don't know if that's the case . . . maybe you
guys didn't expect us to be in first place,'' Larkin said to the
media. ``We expected to play well the entire season and we just
happen to be there right now. It's too bad we got off to a slow
start . . . but we're here now and it is a matter of staying where
we are and continuing this momentum at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jack McKeon preferred talking about the just-completed
odyssey in Adventureland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a tremendous road trip and Larkin was very, very good .
. . but you can't single out Barry without singling out Sean Casey
. . . well, a number of guys,'' McKeon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry especially delivered a lot of key hits on the trip, as
well as Casey, plus Pokey Reese has played inspirational baseball
and Michael Tucker has come on strong,'' McKeon added. ``The
reserves have contributed when we needed it _ Jeffrey Hammonds,
Dmitri Young _ and Aaron Boone started to hit the ball better.
Eddie Taubensee has given us a lot . . . you can go right down the
list and that's the reason you win because everybody does it and
you don't depend on one guy.''
</P>
<P>
   And what does McKeon do?
</P>
<P>
   ``I put the lineup out there and go hide, don't bother 'em, let
'em play,'' McKeon said.
</P>
<P>
   The lineup has four .300 hitters in the first six spots and
Tucker is at .290, with only Vaughn slacking. Leadoff hitter Reese
is at .300, No. 3 hitter Casey is at .387, No. 5 hitter Larkin is
at .312 and No. 6 hitter Taubensee is at .311.
</P>
<P>
   Now, can they reverse the trend at home? For sure, a couple of
angry teams are headed their way, eager to put the Reds back in
their place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same teams again, next seven games and it will be a big, big
test for us,'' Casey said after hitting .487 on the trip with two
homers and six RBIs. ``How do we treat this at home? You treat it
like it doesn't matter where it is, if it's a Little League park,
you play in a Little League park. You have to like to be home, home
with your crowd. It's not like we don't like to be at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we know Arizona and Houston will be angry because you
don't like it when somebody comes into your home and sweeps you
three and four games,'' Casey said. ``We're going to have to be
even more prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is no truth to the rumor the Reds have petitioned
Major League Baseball to either wear their road grays the next
seven games or to play the next seven in Phoenix and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
