u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-ESCAPE-HNS &LR;      06-28 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-ESCAPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS AUTHORITIES SEARCHING FOR KILLER ESCAPEE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ A convicted murderer, who slipped out of his
handcuffs, dodged guards' gunfire and cleared three fences to
escape a high-security prison Sunday, remained on the run Monday
after shedding his inmate clothes and spending the night in a tree
overgrown with poison ivy, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 law enforcement personnel, in boats, on foot and
in the air, continued the search late Monday for Clifford Jones,
33, who was serving a 20-year sentence for murder and for the
attempted murder of a Dallas police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Prison spokesman Larry Fitzgerald said Jones was believed to be
contained in a wooded, swampy area about 3 miles north of the
Estelle prison unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel confident we'll get him back,'' he said. ``It's just a
matter of time.''
</P>
<P>
   A heat-sensing helicopter, on loan from the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, was used Sunday night to try to locate the
escapee, but the sensing equipment was useless as temperatures
climbed toward 100 degrees Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was the first inmate to escape from a Texas prison this
year. Last year, 16 inmates escaped, including death row inmate
Martin Gurule.
</P>
<P>
   Gurule was among seven death row prisoners who attempted to flee
the nearby Ellis I unit last Thanksgiving. Only Gurule cleared the
fences.
</P>
<P>
   After a weeklong manhunt, his body was found floating in Harmon
Creek, about a mile from the prison. He apparently drowned shortly
after escaping.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is considered dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Jones fled the Estelle unit about 12:20 p.m. Sunday as he was
being escorted from his administrative segregation cell into a
fenced-in recreational area at the prison in the East Texas woods
about 12 miles northeast of Huntsville. The inmate slipped off one
handcuff and shoved a guard out of the way. The guard was not
injured.
</P>
<P>
   Jones then climbed a 20-foot fence in the recreation cage and
squeezed through an 8- to 10-inch gap between the top of the fence
and the roof. Once he hit the first perimeter fence, alarms sounded
and cameras began recording the escape. The prisoner then scaled a
camera tower and vaulted off to clear razor wire and the third
fence, prison officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Guards in a van pursued Jones and fired two shots at him, but
didn't hit him, Fitzgerald said. The escapee then ran to a wooded
area about 100 yards from the prison and stripped himself naked,
leaving behind his clothing and shoes to throw off the search dogs,
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Searchers believe Jones continued north toward the Trinity
River, but stopped about 3 miles away from the prison, where he
climbed an oak tree covered with poison ivy vines. ``We believe the
man is experiencing some discomfort at this time,'' Fitzgerald
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that there's ever been a completely fool-proof
prison built anywhere in the world,'' said Gary Johnson,
institutional director of the Texas Department of Criminal Justice.
``... The fatal flaw in this incident was the inmate being able to
get out of that handcuff, and we just need to figure out how that
occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said there was no evidence that Jones had planned the
escape in advance or that he had help from outside the prison. He
had not had any recent visitors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday afternoon, as searchers combed the woods and swamps
north of the prison, crews at Estelle closed in the gap in the
recreation fence, added razor wire to the camera tower and
reinforced other areas.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who was to be released in 2007, was convicted in the 1987
murder of Patrick Haynes, 30, who was shot twice in the head on a
Dallas street.
</P>
<P>
   He also was serving time for the attempted murder of a Dallas
police officer who had tried to pull him over. Jones fired four
rounds from a .12-gauge pump shotgun at the officer, who was
wounded in the hand.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
