<HEADLINE>
BAN ON PROTESTANT MARCHERS CLOUDS PEACE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN O'FARRELL AND KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ The specter of riots this weekend loomed Monday after
Protestant marchers were banned from parading through a Catholic
neighborhood in Portadown Sunday, the traditional flashpoint during
Northern Ireland's summer ``marching season.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the Northern Ireland Parades Commission was
bitterly attacked by Protestant unionists as proof that the peace
process was slanted against them, and brought to a fruitless end
the first of three days of negotiations to revive the stalled peace
process. British Prime Minister Tony Blair and his Irish
counterpart, Bertie Ahern, who returned to Northern Ireland Monday
to oversee the negotiations, will resume their task Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the tension mounting with the approach of both
Wednesday's deadline for an agreement to form a local government
and Sunday's disputed parade from Drumcree Church in Portadown, a
bomb threat was phoned into a Belfast hotel where Northern Ireland
Parades Commission chairman Alistair Graham was reading an 18-page
decision to ban the march.
</P>
<P>
   Graham moved the press conference to the parking lot, and
criticized the Orange Order, the Protestant group that stages the
annual march, for refusing to recognize his commission or find a
compromise with community leaders in the Garvaghy Road area who
consider the parade offensive and do not want it to pass through
their neighborhood. He said the parade organizers had spent the
last year inflaming the situation, rather than seeking a peaceful
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Yet government sources here suggested that in a meeting with
Orange Order leaders Monday night, Blair had promised them they
could hold a limited march on the disputed route later this year if
Sunday passes peacefully and they continue to negotiate with local
residents.
</P>
<P>
   The parade, which is the most contentious of some 3,000 annual
marches held to commemorate 17th century Protestant victories over
Catholic forces, has led to rioting the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   The parades commission had delayed its decision, hoping that a
compromise could be worked out between the Catholic nationalist
residents' group and the Orange Order. That would have boded well
for the negotiations aimed at ending the stalemate over the
formation of a local government, called for under last year's Good
Friday Agreement that was supposed to bring about a peaceful
resolution of 30 years of political violence in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the decision to ban the parade for the second year in a
row has further angered Protestants who say the peace process is
rewarding the Irish Republican Army and its supporters while
ignoring their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Unionists refuse to form a local government with Sinn Fein, the
IRA's political representatives, until the IRA begins disarming.
The IRA has refused to disarm, saying that would amount to a
surrender it did not make. Sinn Fein, meanwhile, claims there is
nothing in the Good Friday Agreement linking the decommissioning of
weapons with its participation in government.
</P>
<P>
   Unionists seized on Monday's disclosure that two men arrested by
police in the Irish Republic last week while transporting materials
used for bombs had asked to be detained in the IRA wing of
Portlaoise prison. John Taylor, the deputy leader of the Ulster
Unionists, said the arrests showed the IRA was still active despite
its two-year-old cease-fire and ``the absolute necessity'' for
disarming the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   But, in an interview with the BBC, President Clinton urged
unionists to take a leap of faith and accept on face value pledges
from Sinn Fein leaders that decomissioning would take place before
May 2000, as called for in the agreement. Clinton said the
unionists could always walk away and collapse the local government
if Sinn Fein did not keep its word.
</P>
<P>
   While Sinn Fein leaders have said they cannot deliver IRA arms,
Clinton suggested the republican movement as a whole could make a
token gesture ``if they decide that the price of failure is far
higher than the price of compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   As he did in the waning hours of last April's negotiations that
brought about the Good Friday Agreement, Clinton is expected to
make a flurry of phone calls, urging party leaders to ``take risks
for peace,'' as he put it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
