<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGASSI BACKHANDS HIS WAY THROUGH ARTHURS TIE-UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Andre Agassi knew how Wayne Arthurs felt as a child:
tied-up.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Agassi is playing a game of tennis that 11,429 people have
dropped by Wimbledon's Court 1 to watch on a damp, blustery
afternoon _ and neither he nor they have any idea whom the other
guy is.
</P>
<P>
   This could be important. It's a fourth-round match, gateway to
the quarterfinals, beneath low, pouty clouds, and Andre is being
roped like a calf at a rodeo. Instead of a lariat, the lefthanded
chap at the other end is twirling a racket, but the effect is the
same. Agassi is bound and squirming. The program says his tormentor
is W. Arthurs, a qualifier from Australia, but gives no indication
that he will truss Agassi in knots for almost two hours.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-century ago, as a tyke in Adelaide, Wayne John
Arthurs, had a net as a baby-sitter. ``My mum would tie me to the
net so she could get on with her own game,'' he remembers. Child
abuse? ``I didn't think so then, but,'' he laughs, ``as I look back
on it . . .''
</P>
<P>
   It was Andre abuse for a long time because of what he classified
as ``a very nasty serve'' after winning, 6-7 (5-7), 7-6 (7-5), 6-1,
6-4.
</P>
<P>
   In tennis if you drop your serve it is broken. Keeping it
unbroken is generally the secret of success, and nobody in town had
avoided that shattering experience longer than Wayne Arthurs.
Breaking Arthurs started to seem as likely as breaking into Ft.
Knox, or breaking Bill Gates's windows.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is nastier, slimier than a lefty serving on a grass
court if he's a spin doctor like Arthurs who uses muscle, too, and
keeps moving the ball as though it's a floating craps game. He was
rolling snake eyes at Agassi for so long that Andre thought the
dice were loaded.
</P>
<P>
   This problem for the reigning French Open champion, the guy with
gleaming pate and shots who won here seven years ago, was hardly
evident when Arthurs showed up at Roehampton two weeks ago with his
rackets and No. 163 ranking to plunge into the maelstrom of the
qualifying tournament. You don't turn your back on anybody at
Roehampton because guys and dolls would kill to make it through the
iron _ that appear pearly _ gates of the Big W.
</P>
<P>
   It was there _ ``in the wilderness,'' he says _ that Arthurs
became as unbreakable as Molly Brown was unsinkable. You needed a
sledgehammer or a hand grenade to pulverize his serve, and nobody
could do it.
</P>
<P>
   Games went by. Hours, sets, matches, days, weeks . . . and
Arthurs, a lanky 28-year-old towhead with his roots in Ireland,
hung onto his serve like a leprechaun clutching a Guinness. He won
three qualifying starts. No breaks. He won three in the main draw.
No breaks. If the other guy served tough, too, Arthurs beat him in
a tie-breaker _ four of four in the quallies; eight of nine in the
bigs until Andre snatched the second set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to be patient,'' Agassi says. ``I thought it would be a
matter of time before I got a bead on the serve _ but not such a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The best returner in the game needed a few choruses of Elvis's
``Return to Sender'' but couldn't find the tune. He was strapped
and gagged by Arthurs's serve-and-volley offense. ``I knew he was
an Aussie, so he could volley. If an Aussie can't volley he loses
his passport,'' said Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get many windows on grass when a guy is serving like
this. Arthurs had such versatility. He was hitting the corners with
that serve. He kicked it wide to my forehand, gave me the big
bender to the backhand, banged it flat, swung it into my hips . .
.''
</P>
<P>
   But Andre does do windows. His returns sharpened in the second
tie-breaker, crippling Arthurs's volleys. He took the breaker and
they were even. Still, he hadn't quite solved the Aussie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next game, start of the third, went to a lot of deuces
(five) and I had some break points (three). I still couldn't break
him, but I was coming closer.'' After 90 minutes Andre had at least
_ at last _ sniffed break points. Arthurs had to crash five of his
25 aces to preserve serve in that game.
</P>
<P>
   Two games later, however, Andre's buzzing backhand return down
the line was the sledgehammer. You could hear the tinkle of a
breaking serve. You were aware of the splintering of a magnificent
jar of tricks that Wayne Arthurs had crafted to keep 6 1/2 foes
mystified through 111 serving games (77 in the tournament proper)
before Andre pulled himself wholly together and broke the chains
that had made him half a player.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody should have sounded a gong at 4:20 p.m. because
Arthurs's serve, invulnerable since June 14, had been dropped and
broken, the shards puncturing his possibilities. It was the fall of
the house of Arthurs, although he would battle to the end as
Aussies do, ``hoping I've made a platform here that I can build
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Andre had cut himself loose from the web spun by an unknown who
got his start in tennis tied to a net.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
