<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-PARK-RATING-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOSENING A STRICT FILM RATING FOR `SOUTH PARK'
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Nearly everyone who has seen the new ``South Park''
has termed it one of the rudest, crudest and most outrageous studio
movies in years. The animated film, opening Wednesday, brings cable
television's most foul-mouthed third graders into movie theaters
after months of intense and private negotiations between the
creators and producers on one side and the ratings board of the
Motion Picture Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   The Motion Picture Association board's objections to the film
have been described in highly specific terms by Paramount Picture
executives in private memos circulating at Paramount, the studio
releasing the film in the United States and Canada. Such memos,
based on what the ratings board told the executives and usually
kept secret, offer an unusual glimpse into the workings of the
normally secretive board, which has been under scrutiny because of
recent accusations by some lawmakers that movies and television
shows share the blame for violence in society.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Park'' has been rated R, which means that anyone under
17 must be accompanied by a parent or adult guardian. For months
the ratings board insisted on the more prohibitive NC-17, which
means no one under 17 may be admitted.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the cartoon film unusual, aside from its raunchy
language, is that it is actually about what its creators call the
``hypocrisy'' of the rating system. In the film, little boys sneak
into a movie rated NC-17 and repeat all the graphic language they
hear from its Canadian stars. Parents wage an anti-Canadian
campaign. Ultimately, the United States declares war on Canada
because of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, an odd mix of celebrities as varied as William
Gates and the Baldwin brothers acting clan are skewered. Saddam
Hussein and the devil are lovers. A child is implanted with a
V-chip that gives him an electroshock every time he says a naughty
word.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ratings board only cared about the dirty words; they're so
confused and arbitrary,'' said Trey Parker, who with his partner,
Matt Stone, created the ``South Park'' series on Comedy Central and
made the new movie, ``South Park: Bigger, Longer and Uncut.''
Parker added, ``They didn't blink twice because of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone said the ratings process became absurd to him when the
trailer for the movie was being considered. The raters objected to
certain words but had no problem with a scene in which cartoon
bullets are killing soldiers. ``They had a problem with words, not
bullets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Internal Paramont memos describing what the ratings board wanted
was obtained by The New York Times from a source involved with the
movie who was critical of the rating board's process. The memos,
sent from a Paramount executive engaged in discussions with the
raters to Scott Rudin, a producer of the film, reported that two
members of the 13-member board discussed in matter-of-fact, almost
clinical ways their objections to various sexual acts discussed in
the film. The memos were were dated March 24, before the shootings
at Columbine High School in April ignited new criticism of movie
content.
</P>
<P>
   The Motion Picture Association declined to comment on the
specifics of the memos, and Jack Valenti, the association's
president, said that the organization had a policy of not
discussing the kind of editing it seeks in giving certain ratings.
</P>
<P>
   One of the raters mentioned in the memos and cited only by his
first name, speaking for the entire board, said simply to a
Paramount executive: ``Some people don't want to get specific, they
said they didn't see any way that this could be anything but an NC.
Others said, `No, it's the more stronger things.' And they
mentioned various things.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the memo, another rater said: ``Here's what happens
when we have these discussions. We collect ballots, and turns out
the ballots said NC-17. Then we, knowing you don't want that, say
what is leading you to vote that way. So at that point there's a
discussion. People said, `Well, look what's in the film.' These
things all contributed to the feeling that it was stronger than an
R.''
</P>
<P>
   One rater listed words describing oral and anal intercourse and
bestiality, which were considered objectionable, as well as
disrespectful references to God.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me ask you, did anybody laugh?'' asked the Paramount
executive, according to the memo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yes, didn't you laugh?'' replied the rater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very funny,'' said the studio executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do too,'' said the rater.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, some editing trims were made that resulted in the R
rating. The rating board is composed of parents whose occupations
range from teachers, homemakers and postal workers. They remain
anywhere from one to four years on the board.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
