<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2392 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTH-PARK-RATING-NYT     06-28 0236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTH-PARK-RATING-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HOLLYWOOD: the board.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert Friedman, vice chairman of the Paramount Motion Picture
Group, said: ``This is a difficult process between filmmakers and
the ratings board. It is also extremely difficult to discuss in the
context of an article of this nature the level of discussion
between all the concerned parties. But suffice it to say we are
satisfied with the rating that we achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   Valenti defended the ratings system and said assertions that the
raters were more concerned about sex than violence were wrong. Last
year, he said, 174 films were given provisional NC-17 ratings for
violence, in contrast to 154 films for sex. The films were edited
to give them R ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to generate publicity for your movie, what do you
do? You trash the ratings system,'' Valenti said. ``The ratings are
not designed to please motion picture studios or producers or
raters. They're designed to give advance cautionary warnings to
parents. And that's the only audience we care about.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker and Stone are both from Colorado, site of the notorious
shootings at Columbine High School in Littleton, and ``South Park''
is set in Colorado. Stone went to Heritage High School, not far
from Columbine High.
</P>
<P>
   Stone said he took off about three days of working on the film
after the school shootings. ``Nothing seemed funny after that,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
