<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2393 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS &LR;      06-28 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOKIC DOES IT AGAIN; PIERCE THE LATEST VICTIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Her saga is straight out of a bedtime story, and she
could pass for a pixie compared to her elders on the women's tennis
circuit, who include just about everyone. But Jelena Dokic is for
real.
</P>
<P>
   That became indisputable Monday when she left a Top 10 opponent
with hideous delusions for the second time in a week. Her latest
victim, No. 9 seed Mary Pierce, squandered two three-game first-set
leads as she got toppled, 6-4, 6-3, by Dokic. The 16-year-old
Serbian refugee, now based in Australia, thus advances to the
Wimbledon quarterfinals, where she'll face the winner of the
Alexandra Stevenson-Lisa Raymond match.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson and Raymond were among many players who never even
made it to the court as intermittent sprinkles caused four
interruptions and finally the postponement of play because All
England Club officials didn't want to turn these into the world
mud-court championships.
</P>
<P>
   Among the contests in progress that were suspended until Tuesday
_ when more rain is forecast _ was the Grudge Match, Tim Henman vs.
Jim Courier on Centre Court. Hoping to strike a blow for the
English against the man who beat him and almost single-handedly led
the United States to a first-round Davis Cup victory at Birmingham
in April, Henman led, 4-6, 7-5, 7-5, 4-3, before play was called
for the final time. Also left hanging were women's No. 2 seed
Steffi Graf, who led Kim Clijsters, 6-2, 4-2; Cedric Pioline, who
held a 6-4, 5-7, 7-6, 1-0 advantage over men's No. 13 Karol Kucera;
and Tamarine Tanasugarn and Mirjana Lucic, who were deadlocked at
5-5.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few fourth-round matches beat the rain, which never would
have been a problem for Joe Mooney's Fenway grounds crew. No. 4
men's seed Andre Agassi became the first foe to break qualifier
Wayne Arthurs's serve here and ultimately served him his eviction
notice, 6-7, 7-6, 6-1, 6-4. No. 11 Gustavo Kuerten put fourth-round
surprise Lorenzo Manta in his place _ back home in Switzerland _
7-5, 6-4, 5-7, 6-3. No. 2 women's seed Lindsay Davenport climbed
out of a two-game first-set hole to beat No. 14 Barbara Schett,
7-6, 6-1. And defending champion Jana Novotna, the No. 5 seed,
swept Nathalie Dechy, 6-3, 7-5, in the day's first match, which
started 45 minutes late because of the weather.
</P>
<P>
   But the major thunderbolt was unleashed by Dokic, who had to
survive a qualifier in Roehampton just to get on the grounds here.
Perhaps it wasn't as earthshaking as her first-round ouster of No.
1 seed Martina Hingis last Tuesday. But it may have been more
important, because it established that the Hingis shocker was no
aberration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think beating Hingis in the first round, there was a little
bit of pressure to win a few more rounds,'' said Dokic. ``And I
think winning the next two rounds and then beating Mary today just
proved it. Beating Hingis was probably still in my head, thinking,
`Well, did that really happen? Am I really able to beat top
players?' Then beating Mary today sort of proved it for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory also proved the resolve of the 5-foot-6-inch,
126-pound Dokic, who at No. 129 is the lowliest women's
quarterfinalist here since No. 154 Molly Van Nordstrand in 1985.
Dokic spotted the 5-10, 150-pound Pierce leads of 3-0 and 4-1
before reeling off the last five games of the first set, and
trailed, 3-2, in the second before running the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a good fighter,'' said Pierce, the onetime Australian
Open winner who became the latest casualty of the coffin known as
Court 2, the cemetery for a host of major champions which this year
alone has claimed Arantxa Sanchez Vicario, Richard Krajicek, and
now Pierce. ``She never gave up. She moves around the court really
well and hit some good shots when she was in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, nothing seems to fluster Dokic. She has answered every
question here in a poised monotone, even prying ones about her
father's ejection from the court and eventually the grounds during
a tournament at Birmingham for boisterous, inebriated behavior; and
the birthmark on her chin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look in the papers,'' she said. ``I just think what's
in the papers is totally out of what's in the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   Reality is Jelena Dokic, Wimbledon quarterfinalist. And she
doesn't need to pinch herself to know it's true.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
