<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-INKSTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND SLAM PUTTING PUTS INKSTER ON HALL OF FAME TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ Juli Inkster was talking on the eve of the
McDonald's LPGA Championship about the glow of winning the US
Women's Open June 6 at Old Waverly GC in sweltering West Point,
Miss. ``It's been a lot of fun,'' she said. ``It's a huge
tournament to win. I'm still kind of walking around with
butterflies in my stomach. It's a great feeling. It's the icing on
the cake as far as my career goes.''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, here is Inkster doing a dance on the 18th
green at DuPont CC, pumping her fists, and adding a few
strawberries to the icing. She entered the history books Sunday
when she put on a remarkable exhibition of putting that even Payne
Stewart must have applauded to complete the Grand Slam and edge one
giant step closer to the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   She busted out of the logjam that had bogged down the
championship for nearly three rounds. Seven putts on the last six
holes, 15 over the last 12. She said she didn't sleep well on the
eve of the US Women's Open final round because winning that
tournament was always her dream when she was growing up in Santa
Cruz, Calif. She held a four-shot lead entering the final round,
and would win by four. ``I slept pretty good (Saturday) night,''
she said. ``I felt, if I win this it's a bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   Inkster, who turned 39 June 24, joins Pat Bradley as the only
players to win the modern Grand Slam: the Dinah Shore, the US
Women's Open, the LPGA Championship, and the du Maurier Classic
(July 29-Aug. 1). The du Maurier may pass into history next year
when the contract expires, since the Canadian government has
instituted a ban on cigarette advertising.
</P>
<P>
   To join Bradley was something special to Inkster. ``I just can't
comprehend it,'' said Inkster. ``Pat Bradley is the ultimate
champion. I always thought this was what I wanted to do. Win the
four majors. I won two really quick, but I didn't think it was
going to be that tough. I just didn't want to get emotional or
overwhelmed out there. I felt I rushed up there too quickly in
Mississippi. I wanted to savor this.''
</P>
<P>
   Inkster, whose husband Brian is a golf professional near the
family home in Los Altos, Calif., had daughters Hayley (9) and Cori
(5) with her and they stayed with a family in nearby West Chester,
where she has stayed for this event the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   She had to work hard to regain the form she showed when she won
the Dinah Shore in 1984 and '89 and the du Maurier in '84. When the
kids came along, family came first.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, she carried Cori in her arms across the 18th green and
Hayley was at her side. They were out there on the course cheering
her on, and she caught a glimpse of them before she made a curling
eagle putt on the 15th that sent her on her way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I don't think I can still play well,'' said
Inkster on the eve of the championship. ``They're in sports and I
just hate to miss the games and stuff like that. It's not like
they're going to be doing it for that long. Hayley is 9 and she's
been traveling with me since she was born. I think it's time more
to put the focus on them now instead of the focus on me. I'm
definitely going to play next year full time because I want to make
the Solheim team (Bradley is US captain) but after that I will cut
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to have them here today. Hopefully they can look
back on this and say, `It was a lot of fun.' Sometimes I think it's
really overwhelming for them. Everyone around. People grabbing at
their mom. I don't think sometimes they know what to expect, which
is something I can understand. That's why when I'm home I try to
get into their lives and get into things they're interested in. I
think it's important for them to have a sense of confidence in
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The revisted criteria for making the Hall of Fame was
implemented Feb. 9. The prior policy required a player to win 30
tournaments (including two majors) or 35 official wins (with one
major) or 40 wins (with no majors). Inkster is on the verge of
qualifying under the new standards. ``I'm sitting here now and I'm
only 1 point away,'' said Inkster. ``If I can do it this year, it
would be a great capper to my year.''
</P>
<P>
   Inkster was paired with Meg Mallon in Sunday's final round, and
this was comforting. They talked walking up 18. ``She said, `You're
making me cry, so go ahead and knock this putt in.' She was great
all day. She gave me some high-fives. She kept me loose out there.
You know, it's a lot more fun to play with a friend out there. I'm
sure she's disappointed with the way she played and wanted a better
run. But she was happy for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
