<HEADLINE>
ABC, AFFILIATES REACH $45M ACCORD ON `MONDAY NIGHT FOOTBALL' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (e, f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a further restructuring of the economic arrangement that has
governed television for 50 years, ABC has reached a deal with its
affiliate governing board under which affiliate stations would pay
a total of $45 million per year for ``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   In return for the payments to the network, the affiliates would
receive a chunk of the revenues from a new cable soap opera channel
ABC has been developing, amid fierce opposition from affiliates
fearful it will steal viewers from them. Affiliates will also
receive eight additional prime-time commercial spots per week.
</P>
<P>
   But what raised eyebrows Monday was the affiliates' capitulation
to ABC's demand that they help defray football costs. If approved
as expected by individual ABC affiliates, the deal would further
tilt the rapidly changing playing field on which networks and
affiliates are now operating.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the networks have paid affiliates to carry their
programming, not the other way around. But financially strapped
networks, facing declining viewership and soaring programming
costs, have lately sought to reorder the relationship by pressuring
their cash-rich affiliates for financial help. It has gotten nasty
at times: Earlier this month, ABC reportedly sent a letter to its
affiliates threatening to yank ad time if they didn't agree to help
with football costs.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, however, the principals strove to present a harmonious
front. ABC Television Network president Patricia Fili-Krushel said
Monday that the deal with the affiliate board is ``mutually
beneficial,'' though she added pointedly that it ``reflects the
urgent need to change our business.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Scott, chairman of ABC Television Affiliates
Association, said he will recommend that affiliates accept it,
maintaining that it it ``underscores the mutuality of our interests
with the network and provides a framework of stability over the
next three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Cheng, director of programming and communications at
WCVB-TV, Channel 5, said the Boston station is ``very relieved that
an agreement has been reached.'' Cheng said station officials do
not yet know how much Channel 5 will have to pay for ``Monday Night
Football'' or how much the station will reap from the soap opera
channel. Channel 5 is the largest ABC affiliate in the country in
terms of market size.
</P>
<P>
   Giving affiliates a piece of the action from the soap opera
channel, slated to launch in January, may partly mollify ABC
affiliates, but is unlikely to fully satisfy them. Affiliates still
fear a loss of viewership during the daytime and prime time alike,
as soap fans realize they can catch their programs at night.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, ABC agreed to financial ``participation'' by
affiliates in the new soap opera channel. However, the network also
asserted broad rights to the ``repurposing'' on other channels of
its entertainment, sports and news programs.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, like other networks, pays its affiliate stations about $200
million per year in compensation fees to carry network programming.
A reversal of fortune began last year, though, when ABC agreed to
pay $550 million per year to retain the rights to ``Monday Night
Football.'' Almost immediately, the network started seeking help
from its 225 affiliates, many of which did not want to pay for
``Monday Night Football,'' especially since football audiences have
dropped in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But the affiliates' hand was weakened when CBS and Fox
affiliates agreed to help their networks with the cost of football
to the tune of roughly $50 million per year. Then in May, a
bombshell hit the TV industry when Fox affiliates agreed to pay the
network up to $60 million a year for advertising time they used to
get at no charge.
</P>
<P>
   When the Fox, ABC and CBS deals are taken together, ``This is a
fundamental realignment,'' said John Rash, director of broadcast
negotiations at Campbell Mithun Esty, a Minneapolis agency that
places millions of dollars worth of network ads each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a challenging era for affiliates,'' added
Rash. ``As the networks are under increasing cost pressures,
they're looking for new streams of revenue _ and their first look
is in their own backyard, with their affiliates.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cella, senior vice president of the McCann-Erickson ad
agency in New York, said the ABC deal with the affiliate board
``shows that network television has become a very difficult
business, more of a bottom-line business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the networks are truly losing money, and the
affiliates are realizing it's got to be more of a partnership, for
the survival of the networks,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
