<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-ALTAVISTA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ REVAMPS ALTAVISTA WEB SEARCH SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compaq Computer Corp. unveiled a major overhaul of its AltaVista
Internet search service, even as Compaq continues negotiations to
sell the AltaVista subsidiary to CMGI Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission is to become the Internet's premier information
and commerce network,'' said AltaVista chief executive Rod Schrock.
</P>
<P>
   But the company has a long way to go. According to Media Metrix
Inc., AltaVista's sites attracted 10.6 million visitors in May,
making it the 10th most popular destination on the World Wide Web.
But Alta Vista is far behind Yahoo, with 31 million visitors, or
America Online, with 46 million.
</P>
<P>
   Schrock said AltaVista won't fight back by copying Yahoo and
appealing to the broad majority of Internet users. Instead,
AltaVista will target more experienced, knowledgeable users.
</P>
<P>
   One way to do this is a new ``freshness guarantee.'' AltaVista
promises to completely refresh its index of Web pages at least
every 28 days, thereby providing the latest listings of what's
available on line. Schrock also vowed to make AltaVista the largest
Web index on earth, capable of listing a billion pages. He said
AltaVista plans to achieve this goal within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, AltaVista has introduced a host of new services to
attract more visitors. One is a ``microportal'' program that runs
on a user's own computer. It's a miniature browser that provides
news updates and instant access to the AltaVista search service.
Schrock said the company hopes to have 2 million microportal users
by early next year and 10 million by early 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced 40 new local portals to provide news
and event information for particular cities. For example, the
company has teamed with the Houston Chronicle to produce a portal
targeted to the Houston area, where Compaq is based. Other cities
set for portals include San Francisco, Seattle, Paris, and
Victoria, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista also showed off its new Ultrastore, an on-line
retailing and auction service based on technology from
Shopping.com, a company acquired by Compaq earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Schrock said the changes announced Monday are just the
beginning. He said AltaVista plans to roll out 25 new search
services by year's end, and that the company will launch a major
advertising campaign to raise its public profile. AltaVista is even
planning an entry into the general-purpose portal market. But
Schrock said it would be quite different from today's offerings
from Yahoo, Lycos, and others, with a greater emphasis on making it
fast and easy to find information.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Parr, Internet portal analyst for International Data Corp.
in Mountain View. Calif., says AltaVista's targeting an upscale
niche is a logical move. ``If you look at the options that were
available to them, this was probably the best one,'' said Parr. But
he noted that AltaVista has fallen far behind the better-known
portal sites and will find it difficult to play catch-up. ``They
are clearly a dark horse in this race,'' Parr said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, AltaVista may be worth billions to CMGI or some other
suitor. Schrock tiptoed around questions about Compaq's
negotiations with CMGI to sell all or part of AltaVista. But he
said negotiations were ``going hot and heavy.'' Schrock also noted
that CMGI's large stable of Internet businesses ``would make a
great set of services and additions, to make the AltaVista network
even more powerful going into the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Compaq closed down 1/16 to 22 5/16 Monday on the New
York Stock Exchange. CMGI, based in Andover, Mass., shares rose 3
7/16 to 97 11/16 on Nasdaq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
