<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-LEHMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY-LEHMAN PACT AIMED AT WEALTHY RETAIL INVESTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments, the nation's largest mutual fund firm, and
Lehman Bros., an icon of New York investment banking, announced a
strategic alliance Monday that will give Fidelity customers access
to products and expertise once reserved for Wall Street's clubby
institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   In a partnership that reflects major shifts in the investment
world, Lehman will offer Lehman-managed stock and bond offerings,
sophisticated derivatives and other investing products, and
professional research on companies and industries to Fidelity
brokerage clients _ ordinary people who buy and sell stocks and
funds.
</P>
<P>
   The juiciest products _ lucrative initial public offerings and
other equity and bond issues _ will be available only to Fidelity's
wealthiest customers.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, for whom the arrangement ends a 149-year-old history of
selling stock and bond offerings exclusively to brokerages, pension
funds, and other institutional investors, will now be able to sell
its products to a much wider audience.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement replaces a similar alliance that Boston-based
Fidelity forged with Salomon Bros. two years ago. That partnership,
pioneering at the time, foundered as the high-powered investment
bank became part of Citigroup Inc. through a series of mergers.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Mazzarella, president of Fidelity Brokerage Services
Inc., and Joseph Gregory, head of Lehman's global equity unit, both
declined to predict how the alliance would boost revenue for each
firm.
</P>
<P>
   The Fidelity-Lehman partnership underscores several aspects of
the democratization of investing.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, it suggests that in a world where investors
increasingly want to do things themselves, especially in a bull
market, investors are becoming more sophisticated and seek access
to tools and products once reserved for professionals.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it shows how money management firms are
sifting through the masses to target the wealthiest _ and most
lucrative _ customers. Fidelity earns more than 80 percent of its
revenue from the wealthiest 20 percent of its clients. Against that
backdrop, the Lehman deal reflects Fidelity's ``strategic decision
to focus on the upper-crust investor,'' said Eric Kobren, publisher
of the Fidelity Insight newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Last but not least, the alliance demonstrates how the Internet
is forcing traditional money management firms to change fast. As
Web-based brokerages attract a flood of new business, their
old-line cousins are racing to develop Internet strategies allowing
cheap on-line trading.
</P>
<P>
   While Fidelity has had a successful Internet strategy for
several years, Lehman is a newcomer to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman's exposure to the ordinary, or retail, investor largely
ended in 1993, when it split from American Express Co.'s Shearson
Lehman retail brokerage unit. While the firm has 200 specialized
brokers who cater to high-net-worth individuals, the investment
bank sells to only institutional investors, and has had none of the
Internet trading capabilities or retail distribution channels
deemed critical to competition.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, privately held Fidelity has more than 2.7 million
on-line accounts at its retail brokerage unit, which caters to
ordinary investors who trade stocks and funds on line. Fidelity,
which oversees total assets of $820 billion, also has 3.8 million
traditional fund shareholder accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of changing times, more than 59,000 of the firm's
93,000 trades last month were executed via the Internet by
customers themselves. Nearly 78 percent of all stocks and mutual
funds Fidelity sells are sold over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   While Fidelity competes with many Web-based brokerages by
offering other companies' research, it may gain an edge by being
able to provide stock and bond offerings. Competitor Charles Schwab
&AMP; Co., the nation's largest discount stock brokerage and a giant
purveyor of other firms' mutual funds, struck similar strategic
alliances with major investment banks in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In its partnership with Lehman, Fidelity sought to avoid pairing
up with a company whose retail distribution network could compete
with Fidelity's. Still, Fidelity is considering offering Lehman
products to its own institutional clients _ a move that takes it
onto Lehman's traditional turf.
</P>
<P>
   With its Fidelity deal, Lehman is hoping to underwrite more
public offerings, especially for technology and Internet companies,
by selling the offerings to a broader audience, according to
Raphael Soifer, an industry analyst at Brown Brothers Harriman. In
a frenzied stock market where IPOs soar manyfold when issued, the
presence of a wider audience of buyers is likely to push prices
even higher.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity, which will begin offering the Lehman products in about
two months, will require that clients have at least $500,000 in
their Fidelity accounts to participate in IPOs or other offerings
lead-managed by Lehman. And customers will be prohibited from
taking quick profits by immediately selling shares of new companies
_ a practice known as flipping. For its part, Fidelity will share
in the fees generated by Lehman offerings, both for private firms
going public and for established companies issuing new stock or
debt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1933EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
