<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2410 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UPS-AIRCARGO-COX     06-28 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS-AIRCARGO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPS to announce acquisition of Challenge Air
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a move to strengthen its Latin American presence
and catch up with rivals, United Parcel Service signed deal to
acquire Miami-based Challenge Air Cargo Inc., the largest cargo
airline serving the region.
</P>
<P>
   James P. Kelly, chairman and chief executive officer of UPS,
said the proposed acquisition would speed the company's ability to
aggressively serve the Latin American market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Challenge Air has a flourishing air cargo business that will
supplement our package delivery system,'' Kelly told members of the
Rotary Club of Atlanta Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This move, in essence, will make us the largest air cargo and
package carrier company in Latin America,'' he said. ``Not to
mention, it will cut years off the process of acquiring operating
rights and landing rights to various Latin American countries.''
</P>
<P>
   The move also shows UPS' attempt to level the competition with
rival FDX Corp., which has an extensive operations in Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms of the UPS-Challenge Air deal were not
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition includes all of Challenge Air's leased
facilities, ground equipment, computer systems, route authorities
and some staff.
</P>
<P>
   The company's fleet of aircraft is not included in the asset
list, said Bill Spohrer, president and founder of Challenge Air
Cargo. Challenge Air operates a fleet of three Boeing 757s and two
DC-10-40 freighters and will be adding a third in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   UPS has leased aircraft to Challenge Air for some time. Last
September, the two companies teamed up to provide expanded package
delivery service for Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Challenge Air has aviation operating rights in 13 countries in
Latin America, making abut 120 flights per week.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said UPS viewed Latin American as an important market to
solidify the company's international expansion efforts.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the company announced plans to acquire the assets
of Union Pak S.A. for an undisclosed price to establish its own
operations under the banner UPS de Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set our sights on the Latin American market after
strengthening our operations and capabilities in Europe and Asia,''
said Ron Wallas, president of UPS International.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said recently that his company has committed $500 million
in investments in Asia, including a logistics center in Singapore
used exclusively to ship goods for IBM.
</P>
<P>
   The company has added seven additional flights per day to Asia
in recent months and plans to soon add a flight from Malaysia to
Singapore and Hong Kong to connect those
</P>
<P>
   major regional trading centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This acquisition (Challenge Air), once completed, makes us the
major player,'' Wallas said.
</P>
<P>
   UPS officials hope to close the Challenge Air deal by the start
of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
