<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S FUND-RAISING TOTAL TO TOP $20 MILLION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``California is a garden of Eden, a paradise to
live in or see'' _ goes a Woody Guthrie song _ ``But believe it or
not, you won't find it so hot, if you ain't got the do re mi.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush will find California hot on his arrival
Tuesday because Golden State Republicans are expected to give his
presidential campaign more than $4 million during a three-day
swing.
</P>
<P>
   That will push Bush's fund-raising through June 30 to more than
$20 million, including $11.9 million from Texas. That total
fund-raising broke Republican Bob Dole's 1995, pre-primary year
record of $13.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bush insiders say that while breaking Dole's fund-raising record
is nice, the more significant factor on Bush's July federal
campaign finance report will be that he has more money in the bank
than Dole did at this point in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Dole at the midyear of 1995 had just $6.6 million left in the
bank. Bush reported he had $6.7 million in the bank after 28 days
of fund-raising in March, and Bush's campaign insiders say there
will be a substantial improvement in the cash-on-hand figure that
will be filed next month with the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign is still playing down his fund-raising total.
Communications Director Karen Hughes said only that the campaign
has raised ``substantially'' more money than its goal of $15.2
million for the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to be in a strong position. The strength and breadth
of the fund-raising is indicative that the governor's message is
resonating across the country,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will be collecting his California campaign gold during
receptions in San Diego, Irvine, Los Angeles, Sacramento, San
Francisco, Palo Alto and Fresno.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also is expected to attend a private meeting with Hollywood
Democratic supporters at the home of Warner Bros. co-chairman Terry
Semel. Semel reportedly is upset with President Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore, the front-runner for the Democratic presidential
nomination, for blaming Hollywood for youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said Bush also will use the trip to introduce himself to
California Hispanics. Bush made major inroads in appealing to
traditionally Democratic Texas Hispanics during his re-election bid
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush on Tuesday will visit the Plaza de Mexico exhibit at a
county fair in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, Governor Bush has succeeded in Texas in attracting a
large number of Hispanic voters,'' Hughes said. ``Part of the
effort in California will be to reach out to Hispanic voters in
California as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the money Bush will rake in, he also received good news
in a June 16 Los Angeles Times poll that found Bush had the support
of 50 percent of California's Republicans, followed by Elizabeth
Dole at 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That same poll found Bush in a statistical dead heat with Gore
in a general election match-up with 49 percent for Bush and 44
percent for Gore. The Times noted that a tie for Bush in the poll
is a major success given that California Gov. Gray Davis, a
Democrat, won election last year by a 20-point margin.
</P>
<P>
   Less surprisingly, Bush's campaign announced that it has
obtained the support of all but one of the Texas House's 72
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   That one, Rep. Charlie Howard of the Houston-area city of Sugar
Land, said he had declined to endorse Bush because he does not like
to make endorsements in Republican primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Howard also said he was a friend of Gary Bauer, another
Republican presidential candidate who sought Howard's endorsement
in January. Howard said he turned Bauer down for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I've got a problem with the governor,'' Howard
said. ``He's been a great governor and he'll make a great
president.''
</P>
<P>
   A statement issued by Bush said he was grateful for the support
of so many home-state Republicans who have helped him push an
agenda that placed public education as a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
