<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South's leaders urge cooperation in tech jobs hunt
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (f) Financial and (a) General news categories.)
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Leaders who are charting the South's future urged
state governments Monday to view one another as allies, not rivals,
in the competition for high-paying technology jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The forces of the global economy are making us aware that we
better collaborate in this competition,'' said Pedro Rossello,
Puerto Rico's governor, who today becomes chairman of the Southern
Growth Policies Board.
</P>
<P>
   Amid a rush by states and cities to bolster recruiting of
technology companies and high-tech employees, the nonprofit board
advised regional cooperation to solve major problems that hamper
the South's overall economic development.
</P>
<P>
   The board, based in North Carolina's Research Triangle Park,
concludes its annual conference today in Charleston, W.Va. Created
in 1971, it devises development strategies for 14 states _
including Georgia _ and Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Board officials spoke to reporters Monday in a telephone
conference call from Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   In its newly adopted report, ``Southern Connections: Connecting
With Each Other, Connecting With the Future,'' the board said
fast-advancing technology threatens to worsen problems caused by a
lack of high-tech training for workers. Leaders who are ignorant
about technology's role in reshaping the global economy rapidly
need to get up to speed, according to the final report from the
board's Commission on the Future of the South.
</P>
<P>
   Especially vulnerable are poor, deteriorating communities with
few if any ties to the technology revolution, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   More so than ever, it's urgent that babies and children receive
adequate health care and day care, or risk entering schools so far
behind they'll wind up burdens on society.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to recognize that work force development begins with a
pregnant mother,'' said former Kentucky Gov. Martha Layne Collins,
who chaired the commission. ``How well we treat our youngest
children will determine how competitive our future economy can
become.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission lauded the South, calling it a $1.9
trillion-a-year ``global economic powerhouse'' ranking as the
world's third-largest economy behind the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Decades of improving the region's business climate and
infrastructure such as roads and airports has paid off, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission noted promising initiatives, including several in
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   It urged other states to mimic the Georgia Policy Council for
Children and Families' benchmarks for measuring the regional
progress of young children and families.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the Georgia Research Alliance's success in helping
academics transfer their technology to the commercial marketplace,
the commission recommended that states double their investment in
such technology transfers.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
