<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2435 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-28 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE SUPREME POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ANTHONY LEWIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Supreme Court term just ended showed us a phenomenon that
this country has not seen for more than 60 years: a band of radical
judicial activists determined to impose on the Constitution their
notion of a proper system of government.
</P>
<P>
   That was the import of three cases decided last week by
identical 5-to-4 majorities. The subject was ``federalism,'' which
sounds abstract. But the consequence of the decisions is far from
abstract. The five justices in the majority changed the structure
of American government. And they did so without a word of support
in the text of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   One case concerned patents, one of the few subjects on which the
Constitution gave absolute power to the federal government. The
purpose was to have a uniform patent system.
</P>
<P>
   The case before the court was a patent infringement suit by a
bank. It claimed that a board set up by the state of Florida was
wrongly using its patented method of enabling families to save for
college tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Congress in 1992 had passed a statute making clear that states,
when they ventured into commercial activities, could be sued for
patent infringement. But the 5-to-4 majority on the Supreme Court
held the statute unconstitutional. Florida could not be sued
without its consent, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   Why? The answer given by the five justices was ``sovereign
immunity.'' That concept was found before the American Revolution
in English law; it was said that the king could not be sued in his
own courts.
</P>
<P>
   The words ``sovereign immunity'' do not appear in the United
States Constitution. Without a basis in the text, the justices
picked out shards of doctrine to justify what was plainly a
preconceived conclusion. They said sovereign immunity assured a
state ``dignity'' and ``esteem.''
</P>
<P>
   The notion that a government is made undignified by being drawn
into court _ is humiliated _ seems grotesquely out of touch with
American ideals and contemporary realities. Americans expect
governments and their agents to defend their practices in court.
</P>
<P>
   Equally odd is the reliance on old English law. Those who wrote
a republican Constitution for America in 1787 did not exactly set
out to make the privileges of the crown part of their new system.
</P>
<P>
   A third curious aspect of the decisions is their notions of
sovereignty. A government might be immune from suits over the laws
it has itself made. But in these cases the laws were federal,
rooted in federal sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Thus federal law has set the rules for overtime pay since 1938.
But the five justices held that the state of Maine had sovereign
immunity from a suit by state employees for overtime pay they were
due under that federal law. The Labor Department could sue on their
behalf, Justice Anthony Kennedy said. But it does not have the
resources to enforce private rights. Justice David Souter,
dissenting, called the suggestion ``whimsy.''
</P>
<P>
   The practical implications of the cases are great. The court has
agreed to decide next term, for example, whether states are immune
from suits charging that they have violated the federal law against
age discrimination. Unless one of the five justices switches, the
answer will almost certainly be that the states can break that law
without fear of being sued.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Warren Court enlarged individual liberty under the
Constitution, conservatives have demanded that judges stick to the
text and the intention of its authors. After last week's judicial
rewriting of the very structure of our government, we should hear
no more conservative talk about original intention, strict
construction or judicial restraint.
</P>
<P>
   In the patent case, Chief Justice William Rehnquist conceded
that Congress had power under the 14th Amendment to provide
remedies for a deprivation of property _ a patent _ without due
process of law. But Congress, he said, had not had a good reason
for bringing states under the patent laws. That amounted to the
court passing on the wisdom of the law: the besetting sin of the
headstrong conservatives on the Supreme Court of the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1936 that court struck down a New Deal law designed to help
desperate farmers in the Depression. Justice Harlan F. Stone,
dissenting, said the majority opinion rang of ``the mind accustomed
to believe that it is the business of courts to sit in judgment on
the wisdom of legislative action.'' He added: ``Language, even of a
Constitution, may mean what it says.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
