<SLUG> BC-HUMAN-RESOURCES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glass ceiling still seen as a barrier
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Women and minorities continue to face barriers in
their advancement in the workplace, according to a survey of human
resources professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly nine out of 10 of the human resources managers who
responded to a Society for Human Resources Management poll said
they believed women face a glass ceiling and more than seven out of
10 said minorities face similar obstacles. Nearly 400 human
resources managers participated in the survey.
</P>
<P>
   The Barriers to Advancement survey was one of three major
studies released at the group's annual gathering this week in
Atlanta. More than 13,000 people are attending the conference,
which runs through Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results of this survey indicate that employers need to
continue to focus on workplace diversity,'' said Sue Meisinger,
senior vice president at SHERM. Getting support from the heads of
corporations as well as concerted efforts to hire and retain women
and minorities were among the top suggestions for eliminating the
glass ceiling, respondents said.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Joyner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
