<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2440 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUAYLE-2000-HNS &LR;      06-28 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE PUSHES FAMILY VALUES IN URGING OVERHAUL OF TAX CODE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican presidential candidate Dan Quayle,
bemoaning the decline of the American family, said Monday he would
push for an overhaul of the tax code so one parent could stay home
with the children.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, returning to the family values theme that became a
``Murphy Brown'' punch line during his vice presidency seven years
ago, assailed ``anti-family'' tax laws for compounding parents'
financial hardship and compelling them to spend more time at work
than at home. As a result, he said, children are learning right and
wrong from television and other nefarious influences.
</P>
<P>
   ``My priority in this presidential campaign is to strengthen the
American family,'' Quayle said in a speech at the American
Enterprise Institute, a conservative think tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can provide the best education in the world, but only if
parents remember they are the most important teachers of all,'' he
added. ``We can control crime, but only if our sons and daughters
understand their responsibilities, and their own worth, as children
of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, whose campaign is stuck well behind those of Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, Elizabeth Dole and Sen. John McCain of Arizona,
took a subtle swipe at Bush's ``compassionate conservative'' theme.
</P>
<P>
   The former vice president, who served in the administration of
Bush's father, expressed outrage at the scorn mothers who choose to
stay at home face from professionals who erroneously regard caring
for children around the clock as less demanding than most career
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every mother is a working mother,'' Quayle said. ``The term
`working mother' is redundant, sort of like `compassionate
conservative.'''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle lags not only in poll numbers, but in fund raising, as
social-conservative contributors are splitting their donations
among several like-minded candidates and Bush rakes in millions
each week.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle practically begged for donations Monday, telling the
crowd and a potential television audience that they could use a
credit card to contribute $21.
</P>
<P>
   ``Join the 21st Century Club. That's only $21!'' he said,
sounding like a zealous ad pitchman on TV. ``Just give us $21 and
get put on a fancy mailing list. You'll be supporting us and then
we'll be well on our way to victory!''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle also criticized Democratic Vice President Al Gore, the
likely Democratic presidential nominee who campaigns on the need
for more federal involvement in day-care and after-school
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``These proposals do help many families,'' Quayle conceded.
``But they do nothing to bring parents and children together, which
is what parents want and need.''
</P>
<P>
   As president, Quayle said he would repeal the tax code's
``marriage penalty,'' which taxes married couples at a higher rate
than single individuals. Quayle also said he would allow
stay-at-home parents to enjoy the same day-care tax break as
employees do at some companies.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he would strive to put hourly workers on equal
footing with salaried professionals, who generally have more
control over their working hours. Workers who punch time clocks
should have the option of receiving ``time and a half off'' rather
than overtime pay, Quayle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is impossible for invisible parents to instill values in
their children,'' he added. ``We need to give working parents more
freedom and choices when it comes to raising their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his 1992 attack on television's ``Murphy Brown'' and its
positive depiction of single motherhood, Quayle said Monday he has
great respect for single mothers, particularly those who must raise
their children alone and who can ill afford it _ unlike the wealthy
Murphy Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Many single mothers must work full time while ``trying to juggle
the responsibilities, the worries and the stresses'' of rearing
children by themselves, Quayle said. ``It's not that way in
Hollywood, but it's the real world for the single mom,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
