<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2442 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HUBBELL-BOS &LR;      06-28 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HUBBELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD NEWS, BAD NEWS FOR RODHAM CLINTON IN HUBBELL DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Webster Hubbell's guilty plea Monday makes life a
little easier for Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It means she won't have to trudge back to Arkansas this summer
and testify at what could have been a raucous trial, reviving
suspicions of her role in financial scandal, just as her campaign
for the US Senate was getting under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bad break for the Republicans,'' Hank Sheinkopf, a
Democratic consultant, said Monday. ``Hillary ought to send Hubbell
a present.''
</P>
<P>
   However, New York politicians have mixed opinions on what would
happen if Mrs. Clinton is indicted or named as an ``unindicted
co-conspirator'' in special prosecutor Kenneth Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   Some think she could be hurt. Others, including some
Republicans, think she might be helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could conceive of a backlash, especially if you had some
right-wing Republicans piling on, saying it proves she shouldn't
hold office,'' said Joseph Mercurio, a local Republican consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have some effect against her, too,'' he added, ``but
I think it would mostly reinforce people who are already against
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollster John Zogby agreed: ``A Republican candidate, I would
think, drops this issue like a hot potato. What you don't want to
do is dredge up something that might backfire. And in New York,
being heavyhanded could backfire. It would make people remember
Newt Gingrich and the Republican Congress, which were never popular
in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   However, a well-placed New York Republican, who asked not to be
identified, said revival of scandal could have consequences. ``This
isn't like Monica Lewinsky and sex,'' the Republican said. ``If she
was involved in a felonious financial transaction, that's quite
different. It's an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheinkopf, who supports Mrs. Clinton but does not work for her
campaign, agreed. ``If she comes up in the indictment, whether
she's indicted or not, the press will restate the charges against
her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for backlash, he said, ``Maybe now it would be backlash, but
15 months from now it will be another fact on TV in a negative
commercial. After she's been a candidate for months, and she's
ripped up her opponent and her opponent's ripped up her, she loses
her immunity from backlash.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, Mercurio, the Republican, doubts this scenario.
``Obviously, it depends what's in the report,'' he said, ``but New
Yorkers have elected indicted people before. Unless you did
something really bad, just being mentioned in an indictment _ I
don't think that would do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zogby agreed: ``The question of whether a Republican candidate
in New York wants to be associated, in any way, with Ken Starr _ I
don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this is to say Clinton faces easy times.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby's latest poll, released Monday, shows her trailing Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, her likely Republican opponent, by 10 percentage
points: 50 to 40.
</P>
<P>
   Other surveys of recent weeks offer a more upbeat picture for
Mrs. Clinton. The Quinnipiac College Polling Institute puts her
ahead of the mayor, 48-42. The Marist College Institute for Public
Polling shows the two running neck and neck, with Mrs. Clinton
ahead by 44-43 percent. All the polls have a margin of error of 4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby said Monday that his poll surveys ``likely voters,'' while
the others look at ``registered voters.'' The question becomes: Did
Zogby guess right about who will vote?
</P>
<P>
   Blacks, Hispanics, and New York City residents, groups that
favor Mrs. Clinton by large margins, tend to vote in smaller
percentages than whites and upstate or suburban residents, who
favor Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   If Mrs. Clinton's hard-core backers turn out in much larger
numbers than usual, the results would be different.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby claimed his new poll includes a somewhat larger share of
urban and minority residents than usual. The question remains: Is
it large enough?
</P>
<P>
   The election, though still 16 months away, shifts into gear next
week, when Mrs. Clinton travels upstate with the retiring
Democratic senator, Daniel Patrick Moynihan, and then tools through
the area for three days, giving speeches and holding informal
conversations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
