<SLUG> BC-HARTSFIELD-TROUBLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Busy Hartsfield suffers day of delays
 &HT;    By Gary Hendricks
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Rain, a balky computer, one airliner with blown tires
and another that needed help getting aligned on the runway combined
to make air travel a miserable experience Monday at Hartsfield
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Flight delays ranging from 30 minutes to three hours snarled
travel plans for thousands of passengers at an airport that sees
2,300 landings and takeoffs on an average day. Airlines expected to
get back to normal schedules by late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad day, because you normally have delays when the
weather is bad,'' said Miguel Southwell, marketing director for
Hartsfield. ``But today it was compounded by other things.
Hopefully, we'll have a better day (today).''
</P>
<P>
   A major problem occurred at 10 a.m. when a hard drive failed on
the computer that supplies information to Federal Aviation
Administration radar screens at the Air Route Traffic Control
Center in Hampton, Ga. The problem was solved at 12:30 p.m., FAA
spokeswoman Tanya Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   Radar contact was never lost because a backup system kicked in,
but the FAA intentionally slowed traffic at Hartsfield as a
precaution. That set off a ripple effect of delays into Monday
night, airport officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In February, technicians working on the same computer system
inadvertently disabled it, resulting in delays.
</P>
<P>
   Problems with aircraft closed two runways Monday. The closings
and rainy weather slowed traffic further.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran Flight 804, with 105 people aboard, blew a nose gear
tire on takeoff for New York at about 8:15 a.m., said airline
spokeswoman Cara Maruskin. The pilot returned but did not declare
an emergency, she added.
</P>
<P>
   A second nose gear tire blew on landing. Passengers were
shuttled on a large tram to the terminal from the stranded plane. A
runway was closed for about 45 minutes, Maruskin said. The
passengers were put on later flights by AirTran and other airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the morning, a second runway was closed for 15 to 20
minutes after Delta Air Lines Flight 55 failed to make a turn and
needed help to get onto the runway properly, Delta spokesman Clay
McConnell said. A crew was sent to adjust the turning gear and got
the 184 passengers and crew on their way to Tokyo about half and
hour late, McConnell said.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Hendricks writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
