A2454 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-POLITICS-NYT     06-28 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLED TIMES FOR CHIRAC'S PARTY
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ President Jacques Chirac has an electoral lease on
Elysee Palace until 2002, but some people are wondering whether the
political party he founded to get himself to the presidency will
last that long.
</P>
<P>
   The latest blow to Chirac's Rally for the Republic was the news
Monday that his successor as mayor of Paris, Jean Tiberi, had been
formally placed under investigation in a criminal case alleging
kickbacks to the party from municipal contractors from 1991 to
1994. The case involves billions of dollars' worth of work in
low-income city housing projects.
</P>
<P>
   Tiberi himself told the daily Le Monde that he had been charged.
But he described the move as incomprehensible, though a special
prosecutor has been investigating municipal corruption here for the
past five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends know very well that I have nothing to do with what
I am being charged with,'' he said. Asked whether the prosecutor's
real target might be Chirac _ who was mayor when the kickbacks
allegedly were made but has immunity from criminal prosecution as
long as he is president _ Tiberi said people were free to draw
their own conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   The charge by Judge Eric Halphen, one step short of formal
indictment, was only the latest in a steady stream of corruption
accusations that have swirled around the Rally for the Republic,
which for 22 years has held power in Paris' city hall. Tiberi has
been unbowed by previous criminal investigations, including one
involving a city contract held by his wife.
</P>
<P>
   But the newest revelation came at a delicate moment, just after
Tiberi let it be known, to the dismay of some members of his party,
that he would run for another term as mayor in 2001. The municipal
elections are already seen as the first round in Chirac's own bid
for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Rally for the Republic has been in chaos since Chirac decided
two years ago to dissolve Parliament in hopes of giving his
longtime favorite and right-hand man, Alain Juppe, then prime
minister, a bigger majority in the legislature. Instead the
elections put Lionel Jospin, a Socialist, in the prime minister's
office.
</P>
<P>
   The political cohabitation of Chirac and his Socialist opponents
has worked smoothly, but left the Rally for the Republic mired in
personal rivalries. Its third leader in two years, Nicolas Sarkozy,
quit this month after the party came in third, behind the
Socialists and even behind a new rightist party led by former
Interior Minister Charles Pasqua, in elections for the European
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Sarkozy's slate got 12.8 percent of the vote, compared with 13
for Pasqua's. The Pasqua slate had been formed to challenge Chirac
for the right to the nationalist legacy left by Charles de Gaulle,
whose political heir Chirac has always claimed to be.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac was off in Rio de Janeiro Monday, making a Gaullist
challenge to American domination of the Western Hemisphere in a
European Union summit with South American leaders.
</P>
<P>
   After the European Parliament election on June 13, he tried to
persuade Juppe, now the mayor of Bordeaux, to come back and lead
the Rally for the Republic again. Juppe turned him down, citing the
poisoned atmosphere. Halphen's investigation of party financing has
also focused on Juppe, who has disputed all charges against him.
</P>
<P>
   Philippe Seguin, who resigned in April after a political spat
with Chirac, said on French television Sunday night that the
president's office had been weakened by cohabitation. France, he
said, might do better with a more American-style system of
government, doing away with the office of prime minister and giving
the president a term of five years instead of seven.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin, the Socialist prime minister, ran against Chirac for the
presidency in 1995 and is widely thought to be preparing to
challenge him again in 2002 _ particularly if a Socialist can oust
Tiberi from Paris city hall a year before that.
</P>
<P>
   A public opinion poll published on Saturday in the weekly
magazine supplement of Le Figaro, a daily that supports Chirac and
his party, showed that Socialist Finance Minister Dominique
Strauss-Kahn, who is widely supposed to be the probable Socialist
candidate, would win 56 percent of the popular vote in municipal
elections, compared with 35 percent for Tiberi.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the agony that Chirac's party is going through, the
extreme right National Front of Jean-Marie Le Pen took an even
worse beating in the European Parliament elections. Actually, two
National Fronts did _ the party bitterly split late last year and
Le Pen's deputy, Bruno Megret, led a separate ticket on June 13
called National Movement.
</P>
<P>
   Le Pen's party got only 5.7 percent of the vote, and Megret's
took less than 3.3 percent. Their combined total, less than 9
percent, was down from the 10.5 percent for the undivided National
Front in the last European elections in 1994. When he ran for
president in 1995, Le Pen won 15 percent of the vote, on a platform
promising to reclaim French sovereignty lost to European
unification, and to reduce unemployment by throwing out millions of
immigrants from Africa.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
