<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: EQUALITY FOR WOMEN IN POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   Members of parliament and senators, fewer than 10 percent of
them women, approved a constitutional amendment stipulating that
men and women should share elective jobs equally. The amendment to
the 1958 Constitution says ``The law favors equal access by men and
women to electoral mandates and elective functions,'' and obligates
political parties to comply. The vote was 745 in favor, 43 against
and 48 abstaining. Women, who make up 53 percent of the population,
first got the vote in France in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: HISTORIC DEFEAT FOR LEFT
</P>
<P>
   Bologna has elected a center-right mayor, the first time in 54
years that the left has lost an election in the traditionally
Communist university town. The new mayor, Giorgio Guazzaloca,
belongs to a coalition led by former Prime Minister Silvio
Belusconi, a media tycoon. ``This is a painful, historic defeat,''
said Alessandro Ramazza, regional head of Democrats of the Left,
the party of Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND: ANTI-ENGLISH BIAS GROWS
</P>
<P>
   The results of a poll by a Scottish newspaper show a growing
bias against England. The Daily Record said 66 percent of the 800
people questioned agreed that many people in Scotland are
anti-English. A newly elected Scottish Parliament, the first since
union with England in 1707, opens in Edinburgh on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: AN EXPATRIATE PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   The leader of a coalition of groups representing Mexicans who
live in the United States accused Mexico's governing party, known
as the PRI, of blocking election law reforms aimed at allowing
Mexican expatriates to vote in the 2000 presidential elections. The
head of the Coalition of Mexicans Living Abroad, Jesus Martinez,
said it would organize anti-PRI protests in the U.S. and collect
financial donations for Mexico's two main opposition parties,
Mexican newspapers reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2458 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DRUGS-BOS &LR;      06-28 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DRUGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PRESCRIPTION DRUG PLAN WOULD COVER MOST ON MEDICARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consensus is building in Washington for adding a prescription
drug benefit to Medicare. Now the question is: for whom?
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, whose proposal is expected Tuesday, is opting
for a plan that would benefit the broadest number _ all 39 million
elderly and disabled Medicare beneficiaries, or at least those who
pay an extra $50 a month or so for help with their ballooning
pharmacy bills.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, sensing the need to have a viable alternative
of their own, are expected to focus narrowly on low-income elders.
</P>
<P>
   If something like the Clinton plan prevails, Medicare will
remain what it started out to be 35 years ago _ a social insurance
plan with a constituency bigger than any government program except
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Republicans work their will, Medicare will become
more like Medicaid, the federal-state program for the poor, in
which benefits depend on beneficiaries' income.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting his party's disdain for a broad-based prescription
drug benefit, House Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer, a Texas
Republican, Monday expressed skepticism about how Clinton
``simultaneously plans to give prescription drugs to every senior
while keeping Medicare from going bankrupt and keeping premiums
from growing out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   But a Medicare program that apportioned benefits according to
beneficiaries' income ``would not be Medicare anymore,'' commented
Judy Waxman, policy director for Families USA, a Washington-based
advocacy group. ``That would be a very different animal with very
different political support.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Clinton's plan is expected to be a significant step
closer to a means-tested Medicare plan. He reportedly will propose
a government subsidy to help pay the new monthly pharmacy benefit
premiums for elders with incomes below 120 to 135 percent of the
federal poverty level ($9,662 to $10,870).
</P>
<P>
   The main difference between the Democratic and Republican
approaches is that Clinton's proposal will include all Medicare
beneficiaries in the benefits _ and Clinton hopes to generate
premium income from all but the poorest to help fund the program.
That's the definition of social insurance, as opposed to a
government handout for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to elders, the gap between ``officially'' poor and
impoverishment by high pharmacy bills is increasingly narrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average Medicare beneficiary has an income of $15,000,''
noted Bruce Vladek, who ran the Medicare program in the early 1990s
and is now director of the Institute for Medicare Practice at Mount
Sinai School of Medicine in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people with that kind of income have a monthly pharmacy
bill of $200, that's a problem,'' Vladek said. ``I have real
trouble thinking you could do something serious and significant
about prescription drug coverage and leave out people with incomes
under something like $20,000.''
</P>
<P>
   While liberals applaud Clinton's inclusive approach, many still
worry about the tradeoffs being made behind closed doors as Clinton
and his aides craft the Medicare drug proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our great concern is that we protect the vulnerable
populations first _ those who really need this coverage as a
medical benefit, as opposed to an economic benefit,'' said Steven
Soumerai of Harvard Pilgrim Health Care, who has studied the effect
of drug coverage on patients' health. ``We have to be careful this
isn't a hugely expensive program that doesn't really help those
with severe needs.''
</P>
<P>
   A key question, Soumerai said, is whether the Clinton plan would
subsidize not only the drug-coverage premiums of low-income
beneficiaries, but also their out-of-pocket costs.
</P>
<P>
   If the White House proposes to subsidize only premiums, that
will sharply undercut the new benefit for many, since the Clinton
plan reportedly will require beneficiaries to pay substantial
copayments _ perhaps up to 50 percent _ for each prescription. The
average Medicare beneficiary fills at least 18.5 prescriptions a
year, each one of which can cost $30 to $200 at retail.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 50 percent copay would be a hefty burden for poor elders,''
Waxman said. ``But it would be some help.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether such a program would really provide a meaningful medical
benefit is a big question. Studies to date show that the poor are
easily deterred from buying prescription drugs if they have to pay
more than a very nominal copayment.
</P>
<P>
   When the province of Quebec raised pharmacy copayments for poor
individuals, elders, and the mentally ill in 1996, from a maximum
of $100 a year to $750, researchers there found a steep increase in
their rates of illness and hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the result of raising people's out-of-pocket costs, people
reduced their drug use and they got into trouble,'' said Robin
Tamblyn of McGill University in Montreal. ``The biggest effect was
among the welfare group, who doubled their number of
hospitalizations and tripled their number of emergency room visits.
For elders using drugs for five or six diseases, we saw similar
effects. The hardest hit were the mentally ill; their
hospitalizations tripled and their emergency room visits increased
five-fold.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
