<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2459 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HAWKS-DRAFT-COX     06-28 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-DRAFT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks try to move up for guard
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Hawks have set moving up in Wednesday's
draft as their top priority so they can take a point guard.
</P>
<P>
   If they are successful, they might open next season in Philips
Arena with a rookie running the show.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Pete Babcock would not confirm his
organization's intention, but he said during a Monday afternoon
briefing that the Hawks probably would have to trade one of their
key players in order to advance into the lottery and dip into the
pool of good point guards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that you're never able to trade two or three
mediocre players for a star player. It doesn't work that way.
That's why you can't trade two or more mediocre picks to get a
really good one,'' Babcock said. ``You have to trade a star
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Since being eliminated in a second-round sweep by the New York
Knicks, the Hawks have said they would trade any player on their
roster, if they can improve. In reality, center Dikembe Mutombo is
the only player exempt from a potential purge because it would be
difficult for the team to improve without a top defensive center.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, veteran point guard Mookie Blaylock has been
targeted, because of the Hawks' stodgy offense and because he
shoots often but not well.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, coach Lenny Wilkens said that Blaylock no
longer owned the position he has occupied as a starter for the past
seven years. Wilkens said it remained to be seen whether Blaylock,
if he remains on the roster, could help the Hawks best by playing
off the bench. With three years remaining on his contract, Blaylock
might be a desirable property for a team that needs a tough
defender. Blaylock gets $4.2 million next season, $4.8 in 2000-01
and $5.4 million in 2001-02.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thinks that he could deal for one of the top five
picks, Babcock said, no. ``That would be very, very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Hawks know they can get a solid young point guard in
trading to the lottery level.
</P>
<P>
   The draft has seven promising points. Some _ Steve Francis of
Maryland, Baron Davis of UCLA and Andre Miller of Utah _ probably
will start next season. They are projected to be among the first
six or seven players taken Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's Jason Terry, Fresno State's Chris Herren, Vonteego
Cummings of Pittsburgh and William Avery of Duke are good enough to
play significant minutes next season. Although Herren is closer to
being a pure point, all four can score, so they fall into a
category of need for the Hawks. Acquiring a combination guard is a
priority, Babcock said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks have picks 17, 20, 21 and 27 in the draft. Curiously,
the keenest interest appeared to be in the last of the picks,
Babcock said, ``because teams have a sense that it's a pick we
would be willing to give up.'' It is likely No. 27 will be dealt
for a first-rounder two or more years from now, easing the
potential glut of young players on a roster that includes eight
returnees, plus free agents Grant Long and Chris Crawford who will
be welcomed back.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to go for a point does not put the need for a
backup center on the back burner. The Hawks still can take a center
with one of their other selections.
</P>
<P>
   Babcock cautioned that any deals reached by Wednesday might not
be completed until August, because the league won't allow contracts
to be signed before Aug. 1, when the new salary cap goes into
effect. The amount of the cap is estimated to be $34 million. If a
team wants to trade a draft pick, it will not sign him, because
rules prohibit moving a newly signed player for three months.
</P>
<P>
   Although all first-rounders must be tendered contracts within 30
days, there are a couple of tip-offs to a deal: A drafted player is
not invited to a news conference Thursday or Friday; a drafted
player does not show up at summer camp; or a contract is tendered
but not signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be difficult keeping anything quiet,'' Babcock
conceded. But the first move is to make a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll know a lot more (today),'' he said. ``There's a lot of
talk, a feeling-out process. But Tuesday, so close to the draft,
that's when you either confirm real interest or move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
