<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-THE-SURPLUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `99 GOLD RUSH _ SPEND THE SURPLUS OR `BUST'  
</HEADLINE>
   News Analysis   
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It has all the earmarks of the California gold rush
of 1849. Jockeying for position. Claims and counterclaims.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the budget-surplus rush of 1999 instead. With the
nation's capital awash in cash, both President Clinton and
congressional Republicans are scampering to spend the federal
government's extra funds _ or give them back in the form of tax
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said Monday that thanks to the hard-charging
economy, the expected surplus for the current fiscal year has
swelled 25 percent beyond what the administration projected in
February. The figure then was $79 billion; now it's $99 billion.
Much of the increase is due to the 4.3 percent growth in the
nation's output of goods and services in the first three months of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The surplus is ``more red meat thrown on the table,'' says
Robert D. Reischauer, former director of the Congressional Budget
Office who is now a fellow with the Brookings Institution, a
middle-of-the-road think tank here.
</P>
<P>
   Reischauer adds: ``This intensifies the debate in Washington and
Congress. It just whets everyone's appetite.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sabato, a political scientist at the University of
Virginia, sees the fevered jockeying between the White House and
Congress as an early skirmish in the 2000 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the 2000 election ends up being about anything that
matters, it will be about what to do with the surplus,'' Sabato
said. ``It is obvious from what we are seeing now that Clinton and
the Republican Congress will not be able to reach agreement on
spending the surplus. There is just too much antagonism between
Clinton and Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Before dashing off to Connecticut and New York on a day-long
campaign fund-raising trip, Clinton said of the added revenues,
``Now we have the chance to do even more _ to use the fruits of our
prosperity today to strengthen our prospects for tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking at a projected $5.9 trillion federal surplus over the
next 15 years, he proposed devoting $3.1 trillion of it to shore up
Social Security. That is roughly $400 billion more than the $2.7
trillion he proposed setting aside in February. The new sum would
prolong the solvency of the federal retirement program until 2053.
If nothing is done, it would not be able to pay full benefits
starting in 2034.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also proposed pouring $794 billion from the surplus into
Medicare, which provides health care coverage for 39 million
elderly and disabled Americans. That's $108 billion more than he
proposed in February. Unless Medicare is bolstered, it is expected
to go broke in 2008. Clinton's plan, which he will detail on
Tuesday, would extend its solvency until 2027 and would have the
federal government pick up a share of elderly Americans'
prescription drug costs for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also offered a new ``children's health and education
trust fund'' that envisions $156 billion in spending through 2014.
</P>
<P>
   And he proposed using all Social Security payroll taxes for
reducing the national debt, making them off-limits for other
spending. After a decade, he said, the government would credit the
interest savings from the debt reduction to Social Security, which
a senior administration official said would further lengthen its
solvency.
</P>
<P>
   ``By 2015, this country can be entirely out of debt ... if we do
not squander the surplus by choosing short-term gain over long-term
national goals,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the federal debt held by the public _ more
than half the $5.7 trillion national debt. The remainder is owed by
the federal government to itself _ including money Uncle Sam
siphoned off from Social Security trust funds that now must be
repaid.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Republicans on Capitol Hill, who have yet to
agree on how much to devote to Social Security and Medicare, are
pushing to devote a big chunk of the budget surplus to heavy tax
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton would provide $327 billion in tax breaks over 10
years, the latest Republican plan, produced by the House Ways and
Means Committee, would give $788 billion over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are working to produce legislation next month to
eliminate the so-called marriage penalty, make substantial cuts in
estate taxes, and further reduce capital gains taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But since they have only a six-vote majority in the House, they
have found it difficult to unite behind a single spending
blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican Conference Chairman J.C. Watts, R-Okla., said,
``Once the solvency of Social Security and Medicare has been
addressed, Congress should use the additional budget surplus to
provide working Americans with tax relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Michele Davis, spokeswoman for House Majority Leader Richard
Armey, R-Texas, hailed the higher surplus estimates, saying: ``This
gives us more opportunity to get real Social Security and Medicare
reform done, and tax cuts, if the president wants to get them
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Finance Chairman William V. Roth Jr., R-Del., sounded a
hopeful note, saying the higher budget surplus projections ``give
us the opportunity to work together in a bipartisan way to save
Social Security, preserve Medicare while allowing for a
prescription drug benefit and significantly reduce taxes for
working Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
