<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2463 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-QUAYLE-BOS &LR;      06-28 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-QUAYLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE PROPOSES TAX CUTS FOR PARENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Once again championing family values, former Vice
President Dan Quayle proposed Monday steps that would allow more
working parents to stay at home with their children.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential hopeful said parents do not spend as
much time with their children as they would like because high taxes
and living costs drive both parents to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we should ask is that parents be allowed to follow their
hearts,'' Quayle said in a speech at the American Enterprise
Institute, a conservative think tank. ``The problem is that
millions of mothers and fathers don't feel like they have a choice
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   To lighten the financial burden on families, Quayle recommended
reducing income taxes by 30 percent and ending ``anti-family'' tax
codes.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle also proposed extending existing tax credits for day care
to parents who take care of their children at home. And he
recommended that workers who buy their own health insurance because
their employers do not provide coverage should be able to deduct
the cost from their taxes as large corporations are able to do.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle called for changes in public education, such as more
charter schools, low-income scholarships and teacher tenure reform,
pushing for ``respect and responsibility'' to be added to the
``three R's of reading, writing, and arithmetic.''
</P>
<P>
   He urged an end to ``bias against stay-at-home moms,'' saying
``dollar power'' should not be attached to the work that women do
as mothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every mother is a working mother. The term `working mother' is
redundant. It's sort of like `compassionate conservative,''' Quayle
said, taking a jab at Texas Governor George W. Bush, the Republican
front-runner who has described himself as a ``compassionate
conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle urged employers to grant parents more flexible work
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst off are single mothers, who have to carry all of the
responsibilities on their own,'' said Quayle, who slammed the
television character ``Murphy Brown'' in 1992 for becoming an
out-of-wedlock parent. ``It's not that way in Hollywood,'' he said,
``but it's the real world for the single mom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
