<HEADER>
A2465 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-GRAVES-ART-NYT     06-28 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GRAVES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BODIES MISSING, BUT FORENSICS TEAM FINDS PLENTY OF OTHER EVIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo and map are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IZBICA, Yugoslavia _ It seemed a strangely peaceful, pastoral
spot, this mass grave, nestled in rolling hills of verdant
farmland, the green brightened by splotches of other colors _ red
poppies, purple thistles, white Queen Anne's lace and a half-dozen
or more shades of yellow _ the only sound the chirping of
songbirds.
</P>
<P>
   When a French forensic team working for the international war
crimes tribunal arrived here at 8 a.m. Monday, they expected to
find the bodies of about 160 Kosovo Albanians who other villagers
said were killed by Serbian forces on March 28.
</P>
<P>
   There were none. The Serbs seemed to have been here first, dug
up the grave and carried the bodies off somewhere, apparently in an
effort to destroy evidence before any war crimes trial could take
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bodies are gone now,'' said Yves Roy, an investigator on
the scene for the tribunal, which is located in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   But he said there was still plenty of evidence. This site was
listed as a count in the war crimes indictment of President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia and three of his top aides.
</P>
<P>
   There was satellite reconnaissance imagery, photographs of which
were displayed by the State Department, and a videotape, shown on
CNN, made by a villager, of the bodies and the burials by Albanian
relatives and neighbors. The satellite photos showed neat rows of
graves, aligned to point to Mecca, in keeping with Islamic
tradition. The ground was featureless, churned earth.
</P>
<P>
   Disappearing bodies, however, are only one problem for the war
crimes investigators, who have six teams here now, an official
said, with six more soon to be in place. In some areas the bodies
are proliferating, with the killing here apparently far greater
than anyone had thought, even given the very specific accounts of
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to prioritize. Every day we discover a new site, all
over Kosovo,'' Roy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult,'' he added. ``We thought it was isolated. But
the more we see sites, 50 or 100 bodies _ the more people come
back, we'll get more and more. You see that in almost every
village. People come back, they see their grandmother, their
grandfather dead in their cellar. We discover more sites every day,
day by day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find all over Kosovo, there are people dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Striding up a hill, he showed where the group of Albanians,
almost entirely men, the oldest 96 and the youngest 14, had been
separated from the other villagers and marched away to be shot. The
shooters, he said, were soldiers of the Yugoslav army and the
special police of the Serbian Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   The village, reachable only through miles of rough dirt roads in
the Drenica region, was the birthplace of the rebel Kosovo
Liberation Army. The population was about 1,500 in normal times. By
the day of the killings, it had swollen to about 5,000, Roy said,
with refugees from smaller villages fleeing shelling _ as was the
pattern in the early days of the Serbian depopulation campaign, and
which accelerated after the NATO bombing began on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   He said that on March 27, the Yugoslav forces entered the
village. They later herded the men into two groups, roughly equal
in size, totaling about 150. He pointed across a hillside toward a
scraggly tree and said about 70 had been shot in the back there,
then finished off with shots to the head. He walked a little
farther up the hill, to a gulch, dry now, but a creek in March's
early spring runoff, cloaked with vegetation. He said the others
had been shot dead there, in three clumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just rounded them up, and they decided at this time to
shoot 150 people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even after French soldiers and the forensic teams had gone over
the meadow Monday, there were still brass cartridge casings from
AK-47 rounds and 7.62 mm Russian machine gun bullets lying in a
rutted track.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were so many bullets,'' Roy said. ``All over the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the hill, under the bright sun, a 10-member French forensic
team, in white coveralls, rubber gloves and sun hats with an extra
brim over the back of the neck slowly combed the freshly turned
earth. The team, headed by Dominique Lecomte of the Institute of
Legal Medicine in Paris, said that the bodies had been dug up with
a backhoe, leaving the distinctive six tooth marks of its shovel.
</P>
<P>
   Having carefully gridded the ground into roughly 25-foot squares
marked by red and yellow plastic tape and labeled A1, B1 and so on,
they said they had found bone fragments and pieces of clothing.
Rubber gloves, apparently used by the Serbs exhuming the bodies,
were also found nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Watching all the activity quietly from across the road, Zeqir
Krasniqi and his wife, Farije, said they had found three relatives
dead in their house when they returned from Albania four days ago,
and wondered who they could tell so that, somehow, it would be part
of the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my father, my uncle and my uncle's son,'' Krasniqi
said. ``They were massacred two weeks ago. It was terrible getting
in, from the smell, and only their bones were left.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Krasniqi added, her eyes tearing, ``The bodies were so
burned you couldn't identify them. But we knew it was them since
they were the only ones left in the house. It is a terrible feeling
to see your family like that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 2001EDT &QL; 
