<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2466 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      06-28 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: BIG SURPLUS DOES NOT GUARANTEE BUDGET COMPROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (With BUDGET-CLINTON, BUDGET-DEBT)  
(sw) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the aftermath of the battle over impeachment
last winter, the friction between President Clinton and the
Republicans who control Congress was so intense that the gears of
government seemed likely to be paralyzed for the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   But an extra half-trillion dollars can buy an awful lot of
lubrication.
</P>
<P>
   No one in either party was willing to predict confidently on
Monday that the budget windfall _ $25 billion next year, $179
billion over the next five years and $517 billion over the next
ten, a 20 percent larger surplus than was forecast in January _
would enable a peaceful resolution of long-standing disputes over
Social Security, Medicare, taxes, education and managed health
care. In their public statements, both sides said they would try.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton concluded his remarks on Monday morning by saying he
hoped ``very much to work with Congress in the weeks ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the House majority leader, declared,
``I hope the president's comments today indicate a summer of
cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, though, members of both parties were
extremely cautious.
</P>
<P>
   An influential Republican senator said he and his colleagues
simply did not trust the president to do more than jockey for
political advantage. Even before the impeachment episode,
Republicans periodically questioned the president's word on budget
matters. Now they reflexively distrust it on nearly everything.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official said he could not imagine anything
more than ``a token tax cut'' that Republicans would vote for and
that the president could swallow.
</P>
<P>
   The newfound money did allow the president, however, to open the
door a little wider to tax reductions, the central element in
Republican dogma. And it permitted Republicans to agree with the
president's point that hefty new spending may be needed to put
Medicare on a sound footing.
</P>
<P>
   That means Clinton can no longer hold, as he did in his 1996
campaign for re-election, that Republicans were determined to cut
Medicare to give tax breaks to the wealthy. And Republicans can
hardly accuse the president, as they did in their successful
campaign in 1994 to win control of Congress, of favoring the
biggest tax increase in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's moving toward us, and we're moving toward him,'' a
political strategist on a Republican staff in the House said.
</P>
<P>
   But as for the outcome, the staff member was uncertain. ``It's
either going to result in a hug, or it's going to result in a train
wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of this presidency, the relationship between
Clinton and Republicans in Congress has been dominated by fights
over the budget.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Clinton's first budget, which raised taxes and also was
the first step toward reducing what appeared at the time to be
indelible red ink, was approved without a single Republican vote in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 and early 1996, the budget dispute resulted in
government shutdowns.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, an eleventh-hour discovery that the annual deficit
would be $50 billion less than anticipated _ a windfall not unlike
the one announced on Monday by the president _ led to passage of
the Balanced Budget Act of 1997, a cooperative arrangement for
which Clinton and Congress took credit.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, for the first time since modern budget procedures
were adopted in the 1970s, Congress was unable to agree on a
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Although these fights involved revenues and expenditures, they
were not primarily over money. They were mainly over competing
views of the role of government in society.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sees the government as a powerful engine for improving
people's lives. Taxes, in his view, are not too high, and the
revenues are needed to support the elderly and improve education.
</P>
<P>
   The dominant Republican view is that the government is an
impediment to social and economic advancement. The government
should be shrunk, Republicans maintain, and taxes should be lowered
so people can decide for themselves how to spend their earnings.
</P>
<P>
   In that vein, the new budget boon does not help resolve some of
the main disagreements between the president and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, they both want to invest some Social Security
money in the stock market. But the president wants the government
to control the investment. Republicans want individuals to have
their own private investment accounts. Neither seems willing to
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   On the matter of taxes, Republicans favor measures like a lower
capital gains tax and a reduction or even abolition of taxes on
inheritances. The beneficiaries would largely be the most affluent
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cuts the president favors would aim at specific social
goals like making child-care more affordable and helping
communities raise money to build and modernize schools.
</P>
<P>
   As a political matter, Clinton's popularity has tended to rise
in periods of confrontation like those of the government shutdowns
and the impeachment hearings. And Republicans have gained when
there has been accommodation, as in the 1997 budget agreement.
</P>
<P>
   So it might seem that Congress would be looking for a deal, and
the president would prefer an issue. But that may not be the case.
</P>
<P>
   The word at the White House on Monday was that the lame-duck
president is thinking more nowadays about legacy than politics. And
in Congress, the bad feelings toward the president among
Republicans and the distaste for cooperating with him can hardly be
underestimated.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Monday afternoon, Sen. Trent Lott of
Mississippi, the Republican leader, began by talking of the
potential for accommodation. But by the end, he could not resist
sticking the needle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says he wants to work with us and then he flies off to
fund-raisers,'' Lott declared. ``I don't know if he's serious or
not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
