<SLUG> BC-WTO-GUESTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOMS WITH A WORLD VIEW: SEATTLE TACKLES BIG PLANS FOR WTO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Got 5,000 guests coming to town? Where are you going
to put them all? And what about pesky guests who think they're
special? You know. Like President Clinton. Or maybe Fidel Castro.
And then there's the minister of this and the minister of that.
</P>
<P>
   The World Trade Organization's hosts face just such a daunting
task when the international group gathers in Seattle Nov. 30.
Official and semi-official guests will fill about 5,000 rooms.
President Clinton will be here, and while Fidel Castro isn't on the
list of those who have already RSVP'd, he could be here.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out where they're going to stay, and who gets which
room, is a world-class juggling act that's already under way.
</P>
<P>
   The WTO's 136 member governments are being offered rooms in 29
hotels, with ordinary rooms starting at $79 at the Quality Inn and
topping out at $315 at the Four Seasons Olympic, plus 15.6 percent
hotel tax. Then come the junior suites, corner suites, specialty
suites and presidential suites.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is expected to be here for the opening
session. During the APEC meeting in 1993, he stayed at the Westin,
which has a presidential suite on the top floor of the north tower.
Presidents Bush and Reagan stayed there, as did Queen Elizabeth.
With the four adjoining bedrooms, it takes up the whole 47th floor
and totals $1,975 plus tax of $308.10. It has a marble bath, a
big-screen audio-video system, wet bar and room to receive 90
guests. It is said to have good security. The Westin is also one of
only three WTO hotels (the others are the Edgewater and the Hilton)
that are union, which traditionally matters to Democratic
administrations.
</P>
<P>
   As one wag reported during the APEC meet a few years ago, the
Westin also has a McDonald's across the street, in case the
Commander-in-Chief has one of his Big Mac cravings.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the U.S. government has not told the Seattle
committee where it plans to stay, a matter of some concern here.
``We need to know what we have left over,'' said Don Lorentz,
director of development for the Port of Seattle and head of the
Seattle Host Organization's accommodations committee.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government is expected to take about 800 rooms, some
for its own delegates and officials, some for the 150 WTO officials
from Geneva and some for a handful of countries too poor to come
here on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dozen countries are coming with no credit cards _ no
government credit cards,'' said Washington Secretary of State Ralph
Munro. ``The U.S will pay all their expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Then come about another 115 countries. Middle-sized countries,
with the economic size of, say, Sweden, are expected to send about
25 delegates each.
</P>
<P>
   Assignment of hotels is being handled by Columbia Resource
Group. Leasa Mayer, president and chief operating officer, said,
``Some countries are very focused on price, some countries on
location. So far, there are no conflicts.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who thought the China-Taiwan issue could be avoided,
because neither so far is a member of WTO, think again: Both will
be here. Taiwan, which will be called Chinese Taipei, has asked for
100 rooms at the Westin for delegates and journalists, says Frank
Liu, director of the Taipei Economic and Cultural Office here.
</P>
<P>
   Most delegations haven't responded yet. Japan will bring 128
delegates, the second-largest group after the United States. The
consulate here says it has asked to stay at the Westin, which has
one of the city's premier Japanese restaurants, Nikko, on the
ground floor.
</P>
<P>
   Canada, which expects a large delegation, has asked for one of
the more moderate-priced hotels, a spokeswoman said. (The mid-price
hotels, $125-$169, include Cavanaugh's, Crowne Plaza, Mayflower,
Roosevelt, Hilton and Warwick.)
</P>
<P>
   The European Union and European Council, with 100 members, will
stay at the Sheraton, said John Richardson, deputy head of
delegation. The Sheraton is the closest to the meetings, which will
be at the Washington State Visitors and Convention Center. It also
has a lot of meeting rooms where delegations can plot strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meeting space is at much more of a premium than hotel rooms,''
Mayer says. Also important is 24-hour room service; delegates
expect to work, and to communicate with their home governments, at
all hours.
</P>
<P>
   The unanswered question is heads of state. The WTO ministerial
is not a meeting of leaders, like APEC was; but the last WTO
ministerial, held in May 1998 in Geneva, attracted Nelson Mandela
and Fidel Castro. Mandela has retired, but it is not impossible to
imagine Castro strolling in green fatigues down Pine Street among
the Christmas shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Waldmann, head of the Host Organization, notes that the
Geneva meeting was a party for the organization's 50th birthday,
and the Seattle meeting will be work. Perhaps that will change how
many leaders show up. One insider says perhaps 15 will come. ``We
have no idea,'' Waldmann said. ``We could handle 15 or so,
especially if they were not all here at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the officials are the NGOs, the non-governmental
organizations, which could include everyone from The Boeing Co. to
the Sierra Club. Some of these groups will be participating in the
meetings; some will be protesting in the streets. Some will get
rooms through the Seattle Host Organization; some won't.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure will be on the local organizers. They are the ones
raising the corporate contributions ($5 million pledged so far, of
a $9.2 million goal), arranging the transportation and assigning
the hotels. The U.S. State Department will review the arrangements,
but Lorentz says, ``We will take the heat if someone is unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't complain about that. The meeting, he says, is a
moderately big deal for Washington, D.C. It is a big, big deal for
Seattle. ``This is something that puts us in the eyes of the
world,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle boosters are hoping the round of talks that begins here
and will last for at least three years will be called the Seattle
Round _ just as an earlier round, begun in Tokyo, was called the
Tokyo Round. It's good advertising, like Safeco getting its name on
the Mariners stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But not all rounds are named after cities. One that began in
Montevideo, Uruguay, was called the Uruguay Round, and one that was
started by President Kennedy and was called the Kennedy Round.
``Perhaps you can call it the Clinton Round,'' a local diplomat
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Leon Brittan, the European Union negotiator, has suggested
it be called the Millennium Round. To that idea, Rep. Jim McDermott
said in a recent speech, ``It suggests that it's going to go on for
a thousand years.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson of the European Union suggested it could be the
Seattle Round. ``Who knows?'' he said. ``Maybe that will partly
depend on how pleased people are at the arrangements in Seattle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
