<SLUG> BC-FLEET-BANKBOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIVISTS DECRY FLEET-BANKBOSTON LOW-INCOME LENDING PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- An activist group Monday criticized a recent proposal
by Fleet Financial Group Inc. and BankBoston Corp. to lend $14.6
billion to low-income borrowers and community projects over five
years, saying the two banks would do less in those arenas after
they merge.
</P>
<P>
   The group, based in New York and known as Inner City
Press/Community on the Move, said it drew its conclusion based on
Fleet-BankBoston's lending proposal and merger-related documents
filed by both banks to the Federal Reserve Board, an industry
regulator that must approve the two companies' combination.
</P>
<P>
   New England's two leading banks rebutted Inner City's finding,
saying the organization had used faulty methodologies and
incomplete or inaccurate statistics. In particular, the banks said,
the group failed to consider that the acquirer of the branches and
deposits that Fleet-BankBoston is selling to meet antitrust
guidelines will assume the community lending requirements for those
assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that is taken into consideration, the amount of community
lending you will get from the combined bank will be equal to or
greater than what you see now,'' said Marjorie Arons-Barron, a
BankBoston spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Community lending has emerged as a major issue for banks that
merge. Quarrels over lending proposals can delay combinations or
lead their participants to make concessions to please regulators,
politicians, and local groups.
</P>
<P>
   Inner City's newest report comes one week before the Boston Fed
will hold public hearings on the Fleet-BankBoston merger, which
will create a $160 billion institution and the dominant bank in New
England. The group, which lobbies on behalf of low-income urban
areas and against bank mergers, released a study earlier this month
suggesting that Fleet has historically reduced lending to
lower-income and minority borrowers after it acquires banks.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Lee, Inner City's executive director, said in the small
business lending arena, Fleet made $1.45 billion in loans last year
compared to BankBoston's $588 million, for a total of $2.1 billion.
Using a formula that takes into account the fact that
Fleet-BankBoston will be 20 percent slimmer after divestiture, Lee
said the combined company would have to spend $8.4 billion on small
business loans over five years, or at least 12 percent more than
the $7.5 billion it has proposed.
</P>
<P>
   For community development lending last year, Fleet made $486
million in loans compared to BankBoston's $245 million. The $2
billion that the combined bank is proposing to lend over five years
is 46 percent less than the $2.9 billion Inner City says is needed
to maintain previous levels.
</P>
<P>
   Inner City did not have individual figures for Fleet's mortgage
lending to lower- and middle-income borrowers last year, and could
not make workable comparisons to the $4 billion that
Fleet-BankBoston proposes spending on this front.
</P>
<P>
   But it called the combined bank's mortgage-lending proposal
``laughable.'' Fleet drew criticism earlier this decade for its
home-loan practices but later took steps to boost lower-income
lending.
</P>
<P>
   Inner City said Fleet originated or purchased $35.5 billion in
mortgage loans to all types of borrowers last year, to BankBoston's
$1.7 billion. Neither bank could immediately provide details for
their recent lower-income lending records.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet-BankBoston ceased accepting bids Monday for the $12
billion in deposits and nearly $2 billion in loans it is selling _
the largest bank divestiture in US history.
</P>
<P>
   A Fleet spokesman, James Mahoney, declined to say how many bids
had been received. But one banking industry executive said the two
banks had extended the bidding deadline by several days for
Citizens Financial Group Inc., the Providence bank that bought UST
Corp. last week. The reason, the executive said, was to give the
new Citizens time to put together a bid _ if it decided to do so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
