<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS ADVANCE IN LIGHT TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices staged a broad advance on Monday, helped
by a rally in the bond market. But with the Federal Reserve
scheduled to begin two days of policy-making meetings on Tuesday,
the pace of trading was subdued.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a great deal of uncertainty about the wisdom of
chasing stocks right now,'' said Ned Collins, head equity trader at
Daiwa Securities America. ``We had a nice, fairly broad-based
market rally today, but people are wondering if this is part of a
quarter-end price markup in front of the Fed meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by financial stocks like J.P. Morgan, American Express and
Citigroup, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 102.59 points, or
nearly 1 percent, to 10,655.15.
</P>
<P>
   Broader market measures did even better.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index gained 16.04, or 1.2
percent, to 1,331.35. Retailers like Wal-Mart and technology stocks
like Microsoft, Lucent Technologies and Worldcom MCI were among the
biggest gainers in the index.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks had a volatile day, but a late surge pushed the
Nasdaq composite index up 49.79, or 1.95 percent, to 2,602.44. And
the Russell 2000 index of small company stocks gained 5.5 points,
or 1.2 percent, to 448.61.
</P>
<P>
   However, with the Fed meeting looming in the immediate future,
trading volume was light.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange 652.9 million shares were traded,
the third-lowest total of the year. On Nasdaq, 761.9 million shares
changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   Given recent statements by Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, and
other central bank officials, there is a broad consensus in
financial markets that the Fed will raise short-term interest rates
by one-quarter of a percentage point when the meeting concludes on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But it is far less clear whether a move by the Fed would be a
one-time event or the first of a series of moves. That uncertainty
is likely to be removed when _ and if _ the Fed announces it has
raised rates. Still, the Fed's message could come as an unwelcome
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the language of the Fed announcement suggests that this is
the first of a series of moves, that would be a problem for the
market,'' said Philip S. Dow, a managing director in equity
research at Dain Rauscher Wessels in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the market is looking for negatives at a time when
second-quarter earnings, which will start coming out next week, are
going to be very good,'' he said. ``For people who look at
investing as a marathon, not a footrace, this is a pretty good time
to be positioned.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which have been jostled by rising interest
rates, soared on Monday's rally in the bond market.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan was the biggest gainer in the Dow, rising 5{, to 134
1/16. American Express gained 2 13/16, to 125\. Citigroup jumped 2
3/16, to 46. And Merrill Lynch rose 2 13/16, to 74 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Retail stores and computer software makers were also strong
performers.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart Stores gained 2[, to 45 9/16. Dayton Hudson rose 2|, to
66~. And Microsoft gained 1 13/16, to 86}.
</P>
<P>
   Oil stocks struggled.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon fell 1, to 75 3/16. Royal Dutch Shell fell {, to 58 7/16.
And Mobil declined 1 1/16, to 95|.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement from Philip Morris that it does not plan to
separate its tobacco and food businesses met with little reaction.
Philip Morris closed at 41, down 3/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
