<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Longtime Braves scouting director leaving organization
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ In a surprise announcement Monday afternoon, Paul
Snyder, the longtime Braves director of scouting and player,
announced he was giving up his duties to spend more time with his
family. Snyder, 63, will remain with the club in a to-be-specified
special assistant's role.
</P>
<P>
   No immediate replacement was named.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have one in place in a week or 10 days,'' said general
manager John Schuerholz. ``But right now, we thought it'd be more
appropriate to make the announcement now to better focus on Paul's
accomplishments and his contribututions to the Braves.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz would not comment on whether Deric Ladnier, the
club's current director of minor league operations, was a candidate
for the post.
</P>
<P>
   Synder signed with the Braves as a catcher prospect in 1957 and
though he never made the majors due in part to a back injury, he
never left the organization. He managed in the minor leagues,
served as the team's first stadium manager when it moved to Atlanta
and then turned to scouting, joining the front office in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've decided it's time to change gears, slow down and spend
more time with my wife and family,'' Synder said. ``These past 42
years have been wonderful. I'm bless to have been a Brave my entire
career and for that, I am grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz said Snyder first brought up his wish to step aside
last winter but guided the club through one more free agent draft
earlier this month before formal announcement was made. He will
help advise his replacement through a transition period before
assuming his new role, which will remain scouting oriented.
</P>
<P>
   Hudek ready to show off
</P>
<P>
   John Hudek showed up for work Monday. The Braves' trick is to
find him some.
</P>
<P>
   Before assuming the demoted Justin Speier's sixth seat in the
bullpen, Hudek had spent on a month-long injury re-hab assignment
with Class AAA Richmond with the idea of finding innings and
working on his slider. His statistics aside _ 6.35 ERA, 14 hits and
17 strikeouts in 11-1/3 innings _ he claimed the month a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going after hitters, develop the breaking ball on a more
consistent basis, get back to the style of pitcher that I was
before,'' Hudek said. ``Also realistically, a lot of it was just
getting innings. I needed to get out there and throw because the
first month and a half, there weren't very many innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Hudek do much to merit them. After coming over the Mark
Wohlers trade, Hudek allowed nine earned runs and 13 hits in 8-2/3
innings before a series of three blisters on the middle finger of
his pitching hand put him on the DL.
</P>
<P>
   He is anxious to test his new slider - a sharper, later break
opposed to a more sweeping curve before.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Walt Weiss again tested his right quadriceps before
the game, running at 80 percent, and though he felt no discomfort,
the Braves remain reluctant to activate him from the DL to play on
the articifical surface at Olympic. . . . Monday marked reliever
Kevin McGlinchy's 22nd birthday. He is the second youngest Brave, a
year older than Odalis Perez but two months younger than Andruw
Jones. . . . .Heavy rains in Montreal only underscored the
strutural problems that have plagued Olympic Stadium during the
Expos' residency. The building was leaking on three different
floors from the rains and a main entrance through the Metro
concourse was under three inches of water.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
