<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINATRA-LIVE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG-FORGOTTEN RECORDING OF 1957 CONCERT NOW A MEMORY-ROUSING
ALBUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The show was a gas, as Frank Sinatra liked to say.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of June 9, 1957, the 41-year-old pop star strolled
up to a microphone at Seattle's old Civic Auditorium and opened
with a buoyant ``You Make Me Feel So Young,'' one of nearly 20
songs he sang that night.
</P>
<P>
   Backing Sinatra for the rare Seattle performance _ his first
since a 1935 appearance with the Major Bowes radio troupe _ was a
26-piece orchestra led by Nelson Riddle, Sinatra's musical director
and favorite vocal arranger of the 1950s. The most expensive
tickets were $5.50.
</P>
<P>
   It was a magical night, full of humor, artistry, excitement.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a night almost lost to time _ until the discovery of
a lost tape in the Sinatra family archives, a tape that has now
resurfaced as a new live album.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a smart-looking suit, Sinatra crooned through a
selection including ``It Happened in Monterey,'' ``At Long Last
Love,'' ``I Get a Kick Out of You'' and Cole Porter's ``Just One of
Those Things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He wrapped the Cole Porter song up neatly, briskly and
delivered it stamped with the Sinatra style, which is as much as
anyone could wish for a Porter tune,'' wrote critic Ann Faber in
the Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   Relaxed and in good spirits after a flight from Portland, where
he had performed a matinee earlier in the day, Sinatra was in the
mood to entertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm about up to here in Crown Royal,'' he boasted halfway
through the show. ``We snared a batch of that stuff last night.
It's going to be awfully drunk in Los Angeles for the next five
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra interjected an impression of Louis Prima (``Lose-a da
charm''), made a joke about his misadventure in Spain a few years
earlier with Ava Gardner and shrugged off a vocal flub during
``Glad to Be Unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   After concluding with the self-affirming ``Oh! Look at Me Now,''
he pretended to head off to the nearest bar while the orchestra
played ``From Here to Eternity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank Sinatra demonstrated that pure professionalism can belt
a nightclub act into the farthest corner of the Civic Auditorium,''
Faber wrote in her review.
</P>
<P>
   The rare Seattle concert, one of the best examples of Sinatra
and Riddle at work on the road, is featured in the new album from
Artanis Entertainment Group, the label founded by Sinatra's family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sinatra '57 in Concert,'' available on 24-karat gold CD and
``virgin vinyl'' audiophile LP, was produced by daughter Tina. It's
the second album from Artanis; the first was ``The Summit,''
featuring a 1962 concert by Sinatra, Dean Martin and Sammy Davis
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sinatra '57'' includes 19 songs, among them ``The Lady Is a
Tramp,'' ``Violets for Your Furs,'' ``One for My Baby,'' ``A Foggy
Day,'' ``The Tender Trap'' and ``They Can't Take That Away From
Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Each numbered copy includes a 16-page booklet with an
introduction by longtime Sinatra fan Kelsey Grammer, star of the
Seattle-based TV sitcom ``Frasier,'' and liner notes by Sinatra
historian Will Friedwald, author of the book ``Sinatra: The Song Is
You.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I love about this concert is that Sinatra isn't in his
best voice, but his spirit is indefatigable,'' Friedwald said by
phone from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Occasionally, he can't hit notes and he's straining, but who
cares? His determination to entertain his fans is just so much more
important than the fact that he's not at his best vocally.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra's 1957 Seattle concert might have been lost to history
had it not been for a man named Wally Heider.
</P>
<P>
   Heider, one of Sinatra's favorite recording engineers, often
traveled up and down the West Coast to record concerts by his
favorite big bands. Using the best equipment he could pack into the
trunk of his car, Heider taped Sinatra's concert at the Civic
Auditorium (now Mercer Arena) and later gave a copy of it to his
Hollywood pal.
</P>
<P>
   Forgotten for decades, Heider's tape of the Seattle show
surfaced after Sinatra's death last year.
</P>
<P>
   Heider, who operated one of Hollywood's top studios, would drive
as far as Portland and Seattle to record shows, Friedwald said. His
recording of Sinatra at the Civic Auditorium, later remodeled for
the 1962 Seattle World's Fair, carries listeners back in time. And
yet it sounds as though it was recorded yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wally's passion was big-band music, particularly location
recordings,'' Friedwald said. ``He was really kind of a genius in
capturing these things.''
</P>
<P>
   Heider often made copies of his tapes for friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wally was very anxious to share things,'' Friedwald said. ``I
know copies eventually found their way into the Sinatra
underground, so to speak, and were circulating that way.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the Seattle concert, Sinatra was filming ``Pal
Joey'' and had completed work on ``The Pride and the Passion''
(directed by Stanley Kramer and co-starring Cary Grant and Sophia
Loren) and ``The Joker Is Wild,'' which spawned the hit single
``All the Way.'' The infamous Rat Pack was in its heyday, and
Sinatra was between girlfriends Lauren Bacall and Juliet Prowse.
</P>
<P>
   Friedwald isn't surprised Sinatra never released Heider's tape
of the Seattle show.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Sinatra was alive there just seemed to be so much Sinatra
product around,'' Friedwald said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say that he heard this concert and rejected
it, but the live album was one of the few things where other people
_ Ella Fitzgerald, Tony Bennett, Judy Garland and others _ beat him
to the punch.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra finally released a live album, ``Live at the Sands,'' in
1966.
</P>
<P>
   In his liner notes, Friedwald describes Sinatra as the man who
invented the pop album as we know it today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Particularly in the big-band years and the era that followed,
singers were really just a part of the machinery,'' Friedwald said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sinatra went to the point of having the approval of all his
material and usually worked on it before the date so he knew the
songs when he came in.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra also studied the orchestration, often outlining exactly
what he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sinatra was one of the first singers to take charge of his own
musical destiny,'' Friedwald said.
</P>
<P>
   The promoters of Sinatra's Seattle show were local theater
impresarios Jack Engerman and Zollie Volchok, later general manager
of the Seattle SuperSonics.
</P>
<P>
   Reached by phone at his Seattle area home, Volchok recalled that
Sinatra's management had asked him to make three reservations for
the singer's after-show meal _ one at a Chinese restaurant, another
at an Italian restaurant and one at a steakhouse. ``They never knew
what mood Sinatra was going to be in after a show,'' Volchok
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Volchok also recalled that Sinatra, who arrived in Seattle on a
charter flight with his entire entourage of musicians, was
surrounded by handlers. ``Any time we wanted to talk to him, we had
to go through his management, until after when he had a few
drinks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Volchok was surprised that a live recording of the show has
surfaced more than 40 years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible that they had permission to tape the show, but
it certainly wasn't to our knowledge,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
