<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2505 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-CLINTON-ART-2T     06-28 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-CLINTON-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OPEN TO COMPROMISE ON SOCIAL PROGRAMS AND TAX CUT AS
SURPLUS GROWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BUDGET-ASSESS, BUDGET-DEBT) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton laid out his proposal Monday to
use the fast-growing federal budget surplus to eliminate the
national debt while shoring up Social Security and Medicare, and
left open the possibility of a deal with the Republican Congress
over its demand for big tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The plan could set the stage for a grand compromise with
Republicans encompassing new spending on the military and social
programs as well as tax cuts and the fate of the two giant
retirement-security programs _ or could lead to a hardening of
positions and a bitter struggle extending into the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, who plan to begin a push in the next few weeks to
pass a $775 billion, 10-year tax cut in the face of a veto threat,
welcomed the news of a growing surplus and said they were heartened
by some aspects of Clinton's proposal. But they remained suspicious
of Clinton, who has repeatedly bested them in budget politics and
like them is torn between a desire for a bipartisan deal and the
need for potent campaign issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're interested in deeds, not words,'' said Sen. Trent Lott
of Mississippi, the Republican leader.
</P>
<P>
   Predictions of budget trends have as often as not proven wildly
inaccurate, and the current rosy estimates rest in part on
assumptions that the economy will avoid any prolonged downturns.
The Congressional Budget Office plans to unveil its own surplus
estimates this week, and they are expected to be even larger than
the White House numbers disclosed by Clinton on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Citing new calculations by the White House's Office of
Management and Budget, Clinton said the surplus will be more than
20 percent higher over the next 10 years than projected just five
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   From 2000 through 2009, the total surplus is anticipated to be a
cumulative $2.93 trillion, up from an estimate of $2.4 trillion in
February, putting more than $500 billion additional on the table.
Over 15 years, the surplus will be more than $1 trillion larger
than previously estimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surplus is the hard-earned product of our fiscal
discipline,'' Clinton said in an appearance Monday morning on the
White House South Lawn before leaving on a fund-raising trip to
Connecticut and New York. ``We should use it to prepare for the
great challenges facing our country _ caring for our parents,
caring for our children, freeing our nation from the shackles of
debt so that we can have long-term sustained economic prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   In the short run, the new administration projections show that
the government will reach a milestone next year when it will not
only run a surplus, but for the first time since 1960 will spend
less than it takes in even without including revenues generated by
Social Security payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The $70 billion surplus the government posted last year and the
estimated $99 billion it is running this year are completely
accounted for by revenues that are technically earmarked for the
retirement system but that in practice go into a pot with all other
tax receipts.
</P>
<P>
   The non-Social Security surplus next year will be tiny in the
context of a $1.9 trillion budget _ about $5 billion _ but it will
grow rapidly, and will total more than $1 trillion over the next 10
years, according to the White House projections. The administration
had previously not foreseen a non-Social Security surplus until
2002.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, the projections foresee a considerably more
far-reaching accomplishment: the elimination by 2015 of the federal
debt held by the public, which stands at $3.6 trillion and has long
hurt the economy by forcing up interest rates and requiring a big
chunk of tax revenues for interest payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have now cut up Washington's credit card,'' Clinton said.
``Now we can pay off the debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's basic approach was to dangle the possibility of
agreeing to a deal on tax cuts and new spending if Congress would
go along with his new ideas for Social Security and Medicare, both
of which face severe financial problems in coming decades as the
baby boom generation retires.
</P>
<P>
   He did not formally propose lifting tight spending caps that
have left Congress struggling to pass appropriations bills this
year even as the pot of excess money grows. But in a nod to his own
party's priorities, he said he wanted to spend $156 billion of the
surplus over the next decade on domestic programs including
education, child care and health, a sum that would require the caps
to be revised or eliminated in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   On tax cuts, administration officials said they would
concentrate on passing Clinton's proposal for tax incentives
intended to stimulate more retirement savings among low and middle
income families. But when asked if he could support additional tax
cuts, Clinton left the door open to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within the framework of achieving these objectives, obviously
I'll be working with the Congress to achieve them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The president is scheduled to release a detailed new plan on
Tuesday for overhauling Medicare. He said Monday that it would
include using nearly $800 billion from the surplus over the next 15
years to keep the system of health insurance for the elderly afloat
at least until 2025, an improvement of a decade over previous
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton effectively backed off of his previous demand that
Social Security's financial health be assured for 75 years, the
traditional actuarial benchmark for long-term solvency. Instead,
administration officials said that while they would still like to
complete an overhaul of Social Security for the long run, Clinton
would be willing to unlock the surplus for tax cuts and new
spending as long as Congress and the administration can make
substantial progress on bolstering Social Security's finances.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve that end, Clinton offered a variant of ideas that
both he and members of Congress from both parties have been
debating for months. He acceded to demands from Republicans that
none of the excess Social Security taxes be available for spending,
a shift from his previous proposal that would have allowed some of
the Social Security money to go for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he proposed that all Social Security tax revenues _
more than $3 trillion over the next 15 years _ go to reducing the
national debt. In addition, Clinton would funnel general tax
revenues into Social Security starting in 2011, in an amount equal
to the interest saved by reducing the debt over the previous decade
_ $107 billion in 2011, rising to $166 billion in 2014.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would insure Social Security's solvency through 2053.
If nothing is done, Social Security will run short of money to pay
benefits starting in 2034.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said the new approach appeared to be an improvement
over Clinton's original Social Security proposal earlier this year,
which relied on what Republicans said was an accounting gimmick.
But the plan set out by Clinton Monday would funnel the new money
into Social Security via a mechanism that Republicans have long
since rejected: by having the Social Security trust fund buy stocks
and corporate bonds.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton's approach would give Social Security tangible
assets with which to finance retirement benefits rather than paper
promises from the Treasury, it runs afoul of Republican opposition
to the idea of government as an investor in private industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a proposal that's doomed to fail from the beginning,''
said Richard E. May, a former Republican staff director for the
House Budget Committee who is now a lobbyist.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   News of the improving fiscal picture called to mind 1997, when a
budget windfall helped break a political logjam and allow both
parties to agree to a balanced budget plan. In that case, both
parties got enough of what they wanted to be able to claim victory.
</P>
<P>
   There is now clearly enough money for the White House and the
Republican leadership to work out a deal.
</P>
<P>
   But that prospect makes rank and file members of both parties
nervous. Conservative Republicans fear that Clinton will again win
a substantial increase in spending, ending their hopes of reducing
the size and influence of the federal government. Liberal Democrats
fear that Clinton will sell out their concerns about the poor and
children in order to chalk up a legacy-enhancing accomplishment
near the end of a presidency marred by the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   The political calculus is complicated by Clinton's desire to
help the campaigns of Vice President Al Gore and Hillary Rodham
Clinton. Eliminating Social Security, Medicare and tax cuts as
issues for the next election could deprive Mrs. Clinton, Gore and
Democrats who are hopeful or regaining control of the House of
time-tested themes in their races.
</P>
<P>
   There are also deep and sincere divisions over policy and
ideology, as illustrated by the failure of efforts to find common
ground on Social Security despite a year and a half of bipartisan
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Having huge new sums of money available ``makes it easier to get
a deal, but it doesn't make it easy,'' said Rudolph G. Penner, a
former director of the Congressional Budget Office who is now a
senior fellow at the Urban Institute. ``There will still be huge
arguments within the parties and between the parties about the
proper way to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
