<SLUG> BC-BEAR-STEARNS-SEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAR STEARNS AGREES TO SETTLE SEC FRAUD CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bear Stearns Cos. has agreed in principle to settle Securities
and Exchange Commission securities fraud charges in connection with
the firm's role as the clearing broker for A.R. Baron, a New York
brokerage firm that failed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In a filing submitted to the SEC Monday, Bear Stearns said that
if the settlement was approved by the commission, it would pay a
fine of $5 million to the SEC and make further payments of $20
million to a fund to settle private lawsuits brought by individual
investors who lost money with A.R. Baron.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal is approved, the $25 million that Bear Stearns has
agreed to pay would be among the top tier of monetary settlements
ever reached by the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the commission nor Bear Stearns would comment on the
settlement or its details Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns has been the subject of an SEC investigation for
two years into the firm's role in the failure of A.R. Baron, a firm
for which Bear Stearns provided capital and processed securities
trades. Regulators have been in talks to settle with Bear Stearns
since April. The discussions were fitful until 12 days ago, when
the SEC signaled that it was preparing to sue the brokerage house.
</P>
<P>
   Until the settlement is approved, there are no details regarding
what violations Bear Stearns may have committed in its conduct in
the A.R. Baron matter, how the $20 million restitution fund will be
administered and what new procedures must be instituted by Bear
Stearns to prevent future violations among its clearing customer
firms.
</P>
<P>
   Neither does the settlement address the future of Richard
Harriton, the president of the clearing subsidiary, Bear Stearns
Securities Corp. Harriton, who is being represented by his own
lawyer, is conducting separate settlement talks with the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Until news of the settlement came out, Bear Stearns had
vigorously denied wrongdoing in the A.R. Baron matter and defended
Harriton. In recent weeks, however, its defense of Harriton has
become less spirited.
</P>
<P>
   Although the terms of Monday's deal remain confidential, the SEC
may charge that Bear Stearns violated securities laws in connection
with A.R. Baron, either through its own actions or by assisting the
actions of others. Also at issue is that although A.R. Baron's net
capital had fallen below regulatory requirements, Bear Stearns'
assistance allowed Baron to keep operating.
</P>
<P>
   In agreeing to settle with the SEC, Bear Stearns would neither
admit nor deny the accusations of securities fraud. It would,
though, sign a ``cease and desist'' order. In its filing, Bear
Stearns said the settlement would have no material effect on the
company's business or its financial condition.
</P>
<P>
   A settlement with the SEC does not mean the end of the
investigations into Bear Stearns' lucrative clearing subsidiary.
The company remains under investigation by Robert Morgenthau, the
Manhattan district attorney, who prosecuted the Baron case and won
13 convictions against executives and brokers of the firm.
Investors lost $75 million when A.R. Baron failed.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns is also under investigation by the U.S. attorney
for the Southern District of New York for the firm's role as
clearing broker for Sterling Foster, a defunct New York brokerage
house. Sterling Foster and several executives were indicted for
securities fraud by a grand jury in the Southern District last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contend that the firm manipulated the stocks of six
small companies underwritten by Sterling Foster in the mid-1990s
and that the firm was secretly controlled by Randolph Pace, a
former principal of Rooney Pace, a brokerage firm expelled by
regulators in 1987. Pace had been barred from operating in the
securities industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
