<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EUROPE-DOLLAR-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STRONG DOLLARS MEANS SAVINGS IN EUROPE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pack up and get going. Europe is cheap. And don't be troubled by
the new single currency, the euro. Think in marks, francs, lire,
pesetas and escudos and you will see what a bargain the continent
is.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with last summer, if the dollar stays where it is now,
travel on the continent should cost 4 percent to 5 percent less,
based on the shift in the exchange rate and assuming local prices
have not risen. In some countries, like Italy, the dollar has not
been able to buy as many lire since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   A double room with spa treatments and meals at La Reserve in
Caramanico, Italy, near Pescara, costs $242 a person a night, down
14 percent from last October, when the dollar was at its recent low
against the lira.
</P>
<P>
   The muscular dollar is a result of two forces: the continued
strength of the American economy and the surprising weakness in
continental Europe, especially in the region's biggest economy,
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   And there are analysts who think the dollar's strength will last
long enough to make traveling this summer even more attractive.
``We expect the dollar to continue to rally,'' said Jeremy P. Fand,
senior foreign-exchange strategist at BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, Portugal and Spain, the dollar has not been as strong
as it is now since the end of 1985, its high point against European
currencies since the early 1970s, when fixed exchange rates were
abandoned. At the end of last month, the dollar fetched 1,866 lire,
beating the 1997 high of 1,839.50 and not all that far from the
1,900 to 2,000 lire to the dollar a tourist could get in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, France, Ireland, Belgium, Austria and the
Netherlands the dollar is on the verge of buying more currency than
it has since 1989, when it began a swoon that would take it to post
World War II lows by 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 1.900 German marks and 6.373 French francs in
early June, the most since the fall of 1989. The dollar has slipped
a little since, but it will take only a small rally to reclaim 1989
highs.
</P>
<P>
   So much attention has been paid to the surprising weakness of
the new euro that the extent of the benefits for the American
traveler has been missed.
</P>
<P>
   The euro, which was introduced in January, has plunged 11
percent to $1.037. And each slip has made the dollar's historical
strength against the old currencies greater.
</P>
<P>
   But this rally should be kept in context. Even in Italy,
Portugal and Spain, where the dollar is at 14-year highs, it is
still only 1.4 percent stronger than it was at its recent high in
1997. So if you were in Europe that year, the savings may not seem
as fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   When you take advantage of the stronger dollar, you will get
most of the breaks in the old currencies. While the euro is the
single currency now of Germany, Belgium, France, the Netherlands,
Italy, Spain, Portugal, Ireland, Austria, Finland and Luxembourg,
the new euro bills and coins do not begin to circulate until the
beginning of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   So when you are getting cash or paying in cash, it will still be
the old currencies. Prices will be listed in the old currencies
and, in some cases, also the new euro.
</P>
<P>
   Your credit card, however, will be charged in euros, but that
should not create any difficulties because the charges will be
translated into dollars when you get your bill, and you will spend
the same number of dollars for something priced in euros or the old
local currency.
</P>
<P>
   But when you are choosing between using cash or your credit
card, you can think like a foreign-exchange trader. If you want to
bet that the dollar rally is going to continue, it is better to use
your credit card. Because it takes time for the charge to go
through, if the dollar is rallying you will get a better exchange
rate. If you use cash, you are locking in the exchange rate right
then.
</P>
<P>
   And when you leave Euroland (the name for the countries joined
by the new euro), the dollar story is different.
</P>
<P>
   While the dollar rally is also making London cheaper this summer
(about 3 percent), the American currency has been in a general down
trend against the British pound since 1994. This summer it costs
almost 3 percent more to stay in a hotel in London, based on the
exchange rate difference, than it did in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In Switzerland, the dollar has just rallied back to the level of
last summer. But the jump in value _ 17 percent _ since the
dollar's low in October 1998 is the strongest of any major European
currency. So for anyone who planned their summer in Switzerland
last winter, it will cost a lot less.
</P>
</TEXT>
