<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE PATIENTS TO GET UP TO $2,500 FOR DRUGS UNDER CLINTON
PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Medicare beneficiary could eventually get up to
$2,500 a year in federal money to help buy prescription drugs under
President Clinton's proposal to expand the health insurance program
for the elderly and disabled, administration officials said on
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton promised Medicare coverage of prescription drugs in his
State of the Union Message on Jan. 19. But administration officials
were still working out the last details on Monday evening, just a
day before Clinton plans to unveil the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Drug benefits are one element of a comprehensive plan that
Clinton has devised to modernize Medicare and strengthen its
financial condition.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing a windfall of new federal revenue, Clinton said on
Monday that he wanted to shore up Medicare with $794 billion of
federal budget surpluses over the next 15 years. Medicare would
thus get 15 percent of the anticipated surpluses, enough to keep it
solvent until at least 2025, a decade longer than expected under
current law.
</P>
<P>
   In the last month, administration officials have analyzed dozens
of options for Medicare coverage of prescription drugs, with
different costs and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   They said on Monday night that they had tentatively settled on
these details: The premium for drug coverage would start at about
$24 a month, then climb gradually in subsequent years to about $44
a month. Under the plan, the government would pay half the cost of
prescription drugs, up to a certain level to be specified by law,
and beneficiaries would pay the remainder.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum federal payment for prescription drugs would
initially be $1,000 a year, rising gradually to $2,500 a year. The
transition would probably occur over six years. But White House
documents show a question mark alongside this number, indicating
that the transition could be different in the final proposal.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the National Academy of Social Insurance said
only 4 percent of beneficiaries had drug expenses exceeding $2,000
a year. (The figures do not include spending for people in
hospitals, nursing homes or health maintenance organizations.)
</P>
<P>
   The president will also propose an increase in the deductible
amount that Medicare beneficiaries must pay for doctors' services,
laboratory tests and outpatient hospital visits, administration
officials said. The amount has been fixed by law at $100 a year
since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Under the president's plan, the deductible would be
automatically increased each year to reflect increases in prices.
Officials said they believed that Clinton would propose linking the
deductible to consumer prices, not to medical prices, which are
expected to rise faster.
</P>
<P>
   A change in the deductible would affect at least 75 percent of
the 39 million Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said Clinton would propose extremely
modest relief for health care providers who have been complaining
about cuts in their Medicare payments. The administration will ask
Congress to establish a special fund for this purpose, with less
than $10 billion over 10 years _ a small fraction of the amount cut
by the Balanced Budget Act of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The administration will work with Congress to decide who should
get the money. Doctors, hospitals, nursing homes and home health
care agencies all want it. Administration officials said Congress
should restore money only if there is firm evidence that the cuts
have harmed the quality of care or impaired patients' access to
care.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said the design of the president's
prescription drug proposal had been heavily influenced by politics.
Clinton, they said, wanted to provide some tangible benefit to a
large number of people, rather than helping a small number with
very high drug expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the president does not propose any limit on how much a
sick person might have to pay for drugs. If Congress approved the
president's plan, the government would pay $2,500, or half of the
cost, for a person who incurred $5,000 of drug expenses in a year.
The government would pay the same $2,500 for a person who ran up,
say, $10,000 of drug expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Under the president's proposal, anyone who voluntarily paid the
extra premium for drug coverage could get some financial benefit
from it as soon as the person walked into a pharmacy and filled a
prescription.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said they tried to keep the premium low so
that large numbers of people would sign up for drug coverage under
Medicare. In particular, they wanted to attract large numbers of
healthy people whose premiums would help pay the costs incurred by
sick people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
