<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Mass., Calif., Fla.)   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spangled Banner Gets Cleaned (in Public) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of American
History has begun the painstaking process of conserving the
Star-Spangled Banner, and it is doing it in full view of the
public, behind a floor-to-ceiling glass wall.
</P>
<P>
   Francis Scott Key saw the flag still waving after Fort McHenry
repulsed an attack on Baltimore by the British during the War of
1812, inspiring him to write the poem that was later set to music
as the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   The flag, which came to the museum in 1907, has undergone two
previous conservation treatments in 1914 and in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   During the three years that it will take to clean the flag,
visitors to the museum will be able to watch as a squad of textile
conservation experts leans from a gantry to snip away the stitches
that bind the 30-by-34-foot flag to a linen backing; they will then
remove decades of dirt from the woolen fabric.
</P>
<P>
   The National Museum of American History, on the Mall in
Washington, is open daily 10 a.m. to 7:30 p.m. during the summer.
Free same-day passes to watch the flag cleaning (a limit of six a
person) are issued at 10 a.m. on a first-come first-served basis.
After 5:30 p.m. passes are not required.
</P>
<P>
   Passes are available in advance from Ticketmaster, (800)
551-7328, for a fee of $2.50 for each pass and a handling fee of $1
for each order.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (202) 357-2700. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway Hometown Celebrates a Centennial &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For decades there was no love lost between Ernest Hemingway and
his hometown of Oak Park, Ill., just west of Chicago. The town,
then stodgy and straitlaced, snubbed the swashbuckling adventurer,
and Hemingway, in turn, lampooned Oak Park as a village of ``broad
lawns and narrow minds.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But in the last 20 years, that has changed, and Oak Park is now
a sophisticated, arts-friendly suburb. And this summer, in honor of
Hemingway's 100th birthday on July 21, the Ernest Hemingway
Foundation of Oak Park is staging a weeklong event with everything
from a literary conference to a ``running of the bulls.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Ernest Hemingway Centennial Birthday Celebration will run
from July 14 through 21, and is designed both for aficionados of
``The Sun Also Rises'' and children more interested in, say, sword
fighting. Some events will include Hemingway's three sons, Patrick,
Jack and Gregory. Patrick edited his father's novel, ``True at
First Light,'' to be published on July 21.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From 5 to 7 p.m. on each day of the festival, a free Humanities
Festival will feature music, dance and art exhibits. There will be
two screenings of a Cuban film, ``Hello Hemingway,'' about a girl's
fruitless search to meet the author. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From July 16 to 18 will be the Fiesta de Hemingway, an outdoor
festival with flamenco dancing, a swing dance competition, Spanish
and Latin food prepared from recipes in ``The Hemingway Cookbook,''
and a Hemingway look-alike contest. On July 17, there will be a
fiesta parade and a running of papier-mache bulls on wheels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oak Park's Hemingway Museum will unveil a new exhibit of
photographs and memorabilia, and nightly performances of ``It Just
Catches,'' a dramatic adaptation of three Hemingway short stories,
written by his daughter-in-law, Carol, will be presented July 18 to
21. Tickets are $18.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An International Literary Conference, featuring renowned
Hemingway scholars, will be July 19 to 21. Cost: $125, $75 for
students. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Contact the Hemingway Foundation, (708) 848-2222, or the Oak
Park Visitors Bureau, (708) 524-7800. The foundation Web site is
www.hemingway.org/hemingway. _Pam Belluck &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Millet Revival In Massachusetts &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Van Gogh, for one, loved the work of Millet, the 19th century
French painter of peasant life and labor. He declared Millet his
``father'' and ``eternal master,'' and used his works to assist his
early drawing efforts. But as the modernist star rose over the last
50 years, Millet fell out of favor in the art world. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now Millet is back. This summer Sterling and Francine Clark Art
Institute in Williamstown, Mass., is presenting ``Jean-Francois
Millet: Drawn Into the Light.'' With 80 works from more than two
dozen private and public collections, it is the largest showing of
Millet in the United States in years (and it follows a popular
exhibition called ``Millet/van Gogh'' in Paris last year). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the paintings on view will be Millet's most famous work,
the harvest scene ``The Gleaners,'' in a rare loan from the Musee
d'Orsay in Paris. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Millet was a great draftsman, as van Gogh knew, and the
exhibition includes many pastels and drawings, too. It is arranged
thematically, with well-known paintings like ``The Sower'' and
``Man with a Hoe'' hung alongside related drawings and pastels to
show how Millet refined his thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   The works also remind viewers that Millet, as a peasant's son
who once worked the land, did not idealize farm life. Nor did he
ignore it, in contrast to artists who considered the peasants'
lives too lowly to be recorded. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Drawn Into the Light'' will remain on view at the Clark until
Sept. 6, and then will travel to the Van Gogh Museum in Amsterdam
(Oct. 26 to Jan. 5, 2000) and to the Frick Art and Historical
Center in Pittsburgh (Feb. 10 to April 23, 2000). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Clark Art Institute, half a mile south of the intersection
of Routes 2 and 7 in Williamstown, is open daily from 10 a.m. to 5
p.m., until 8 p.m. on Tuesday, through August.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $5, except Tuesdays, which are free. Information:
(413) 458-9545. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Judith H. Dobrzynski &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   High-Tech Meets Low-Tech in Two New Coasters &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The retro look has hit the world of roller coasters in a big
way. Two monster-sized coasters, each built of old-fashioned wood
but designed using the latest in computer technology, have recently
opened in California and Florida. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Six Flags Marine World in Vallejo, Calif., 30 miles northeast
of San Francisco, a coaster called Roar is a 10-story-tall,
single-track contraption that features 17 turns, 12 points of
weightlessness, a 60-degree banked turn taken at 50 miles an hour,
and a dozen drops, including a 180-degree spiral. Its 625,000 board
feet are held together by 500,000 nails, washers and nuts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Florida ride, at Busch Gardens Tampa Bay, is a double-track
dueling coaster called Gwazi. Its two trains race each other on two
different tracks that start parallel and then diverge on 15
towering hills, a dozen hard-angle turns (all at speeds of up to 50
miles an hour) and six hair-raising flybys _ points at which the
trains pass each other going opposite directions. Over one million
board feet of lumber were used to build the coaster. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Six Flags Marine World is at 2001 Marine World Parkway, Vallejo,
(707) 643-6722; $30.99; $20.99 children over 48 inches, $15.50
children 48 inches and under. Busch Gardens Tampa Bay is at 3000
East Busch Boulevard, (813) 987-5082; $46.95; $37.35 children.
</P>
<P>
   _Christopher Hall &QL;
</P>
