<SLUG> BC-COMMISSION-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT SAYS GOVERNMENT WAS WRONG TO DENY COMMISSION MEMBER
INFORMATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore and other top officials
invited the widow of a passenger on the Pan Am flight bombed over
Lockerbie, Scotland, to join an advisory commission on aviation
security, then elbowed her aside and denied her information
available to the other members, a federal appeals court has ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The commission was formed after the explosion that destroyed TWA
Flight 800 off Long Island three years ago, and called for security
changes. But the widow, M. Victoria Cummock, was the only one of
the 21 members who complained that many of the recommendations were
vague.
</P>
<P>
   The commission published only part of her dissent in its report,
along with an editor's note that said that the commission had
rejected some of her ideas and had not had time to consider others.
Ms. Cummock sued, and the court, in its decision, said the editor's
note was misleading.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has nearly 1,000 advisory commissions,
with more than 36,000 members. Individuals or groups often sue,
contending that the membership is one-sided, but several lawyers in
Washington said Monday that they could not recall a suit by a
member of a commission.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, by a three-judge panel, says that commission
members have rights beyond those of the general public to view
government information in the commission's subject area.
</P>
<P>
   The court told a lower court to determine what documents Ms.
Cummock had been denied and provide them to her, and give her an
opportunity to update her dissent. The government uses such
commissions to obtain ``political legitimacy'' for its policy
decisions, the court said, and must afford its members an equal
basis to participate.
</P>
<P>
   Michael J. Haungs, Ms. Cummock's lawyer, summarized his client's
case as saying, ``you put me on commission but tried to make me a
potted plant.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cummock said in a telephone interview that she believed the
commission had submitted a classified report to the president, with
her name listed among the endorsers, but that she had never seen
it. The commission was formed, she said, by ``spin doctors who were
trying to calm the waters,'' in the period after the TWA 800 crash,
which was widely believed at first to have been caused by a bomb or
missile.
</P>
<P>
   William Schulz, a spokesman for the Transportation Department,
said that his agency had not decided how to respond to the
decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
