<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOSPEH SIANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I wish to visit the Isles of Scilly, in Britain, in the early
autumn. How do I get there, and what about accommodations and
sightseeing? _ Thomas Chiu, Hartsdale, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. The Isles of Scilly (pronounced silly) may sound as if they
are inhabited by the Monty Python crew, but this archipelago of 45
islands that is 28 miles southwest of Land's End has a history
dating from the Bronze and Iron Ages.
</P>
<P>
   The largest island (about two miles wide) is St. Mary's, where
all but a few hundred of the 2,000 or so Scillonians live. It is
the access point for most transportation from Britain, and for
boats to the other islands.
</P>
<P>
   In summer, St. Mary's is popular for its beaches and its
Friday-evening gig races _ contests among six-oared boats about 30
feet long. In October, bird-watchers alight here to see migratory
species.
</P>
<P>
   The museum in Hugh Town contains a collection of treasures from
shipwrecks, which were a frequent calamity in this area. You can
walk or take a bus to other sights, including Old Town, with a 19th
century church and the remains of a fort from Henry VIII's reign.
Bants Carn is a third century B.C. stone burial chamber and an Iron
Age village.
</P>
<P>
   Tresco, the second largest island, is famous for its 12-acre
Abbey Gardens and Valhalla, a museum with about 50 figureheads and
other carvings from shipwrecks. The other inhabited islands _
Bryher, St. Agnes and St. Martin's _ are notable for dramatic views
of the sea and rocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Scillonian III ferry operates out of Penzance from late
March through October. It leaves at 9:15 a.m. Monday to Saturday
for the two and a half hour trip to St. Mary's, and returns at 4:30
p.m.; in October trips are Monday, Wednesday, Friday and Saturday.
Day-trip fares in the off-season, when you plan to go, are $48
round trip, $24 for children (at $1.60 to the pound); excursion
fares for one to three nights are $67, $34 children; reservations
recommended.
</P>
<P>
   There are flights to St. Mary's from Land's End, Bristol,
Plymouth, Newquay and Exeter on Skybus Airlines. The shortest _ 15
minutes _ is from Land's End, and they leave frequently every day
except Sunday (when there are no boats or flights to the islands).
Off-season fares are $135 round trip, or $89 for excursion fares.
For the ferry and the plane, call (44-1736) 362 009. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   St. Mary's has six hotels. The Star Castle, (44-1720) 422 317,
is in the Garrison, built for Elizabeth I's troops. It has 34 rooms
and is open March through October (as are most Scilly hotels).
Rates are $108 to $157 a person, with breakfast and dinner. There's
also the Bell Rock Hotel, (44-1720) 422 575, 23 rooms, open March
through October, with rates of $43 to $92 a person with breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   The island also has many guesthouses. For a listing, contact
Scilly Isles Tourist Information Center, Old Wesleyan Chapel, St.
Mary's, Isles of Scilly TR21 0JY; telephone (44-1720) 422 536, fax
(44-1720) 422 049. &QL; 
Quebec to Maine &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm planning a driving trip from Quebec City to Portland,
Maine Can you suggest some stops along the way? I plan to allow
three days. _ Ira Briskman, Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A. This drive allows you to combine fairly quick travel with
lots to see. The first 137 miles of your 300-mile route will pass
through a region of Quebec known as the Beauce, with farmland and
maple groves.
</P>
<P>
   You'll follow the Chaudiere River (Route 173 and Route 204)
until you reach its headwaters in Lake Megantic. The sites you will
pass include the Chaudiere Falls, a 130-foot cascade just south of
Quebec City. Farther on is Notre-Dame-des-Pins, with a 507-foot
covered bridge dating from 1929, and St. Georges, with its
three-spired church on the river. Lake Megantic, covering about 10
square miles, is a good spot for scenic cruises. A few miles away,
a drive up Mount Megantic (3,625 feet) offers panoramic views.
</P>
<P>
   You'll have to backtrack several miles to Route 173, which feeds
into U.S. 201 in Maine. It will take you past Skowhegan, along the
Kennebec River, where you might want to see the Margaret Chase
Smith Library, (207) 474-7133, with displays about the woman who
served the state in Congress for almost 33 years.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the quickest way to Portland is I-95, which passes
by the state capital, Augusta, with the Maine State Museum, (207)
287-2301, which has exhibits on the state's natural and economic
history. If you take I-495 toward Portland, you'll go by Sabbathday
Lake, where there is a Shaker museum, (207) 926-4597. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can you tell me about tours to biblical sites in Cyprus? I am
especially interested in Salamis, Larnaca and Paphos, because of
their connections, respectively, to St. Barnabas, St. Lazarus and
St. Paul. _ Edith Sagul, New York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. Two of those places _ Larnaca and Paphos _ are on the part of
Cyprus controlled by the Republic of Cyprus, the internationally
recognized government on the Mediterranean island, and are part of
many tours.
</P>
<P>
   Larnaca is the site of St. Lazarus Church, built in the 9th
century and restored in the 17th. Lazarus, whom Christians believe
was raised from the dead by Jesus, is the city's patron saint.
After his resurrection, he lived there for another 30 years and was
ordained a bishop by St. Barnabas and St. Mark, and his sarcophagus
is in the church. In Paphos, there's the Pillar of St. Paul.
According to legend, the saint was bound to this pillar and given
39 lashes before converting the Roman governor.
</P>
<P>
   Salamis _ the birthplace of St. Barnabas _ will be more
difficult for you to see. It is on the part of the island invaded
by Turkey in 1974, an area that encompasses the northern third of
Cyprus and that is separated from the Republic of Cyprus by a
United Nations buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Republic of Cyprus does not allow visitors to enter or leave
its section of the island from the Turkish side, according to the
State Department, but does allow some strictly controlled day trips
into the north. So you might be able to combine all three sites on
one trip, but don't expect to find package tours with all three.
</P>
<P>
   The crossing point into the north is near the Ledra Palace Hotel
in Nicosia; the United States Embassy in Nicosia, telephone (357-2)
776400, can bring you up to date on whether you can cross. You will
have to arrange getting to Salamis on your own, so be sure your
tour includes a free day in Nicosia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cyprus Tourism Organization, 13 East 40th Street, New York,
N.Y. 10016, (212) 683-5280, can supply a list of numerous tour
operators with packages to the Republic of Cyprus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
