<SLUG> BC-HONDURAN-IMMIG-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUCK FINN REVERSED: HONDURAN BOY HAS 3,200-MILE SOLO ODYSSEY TO
SEEK HIS FATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: 2nd take will move within 30 minutes.) 
(ART ADV: Photo and map are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By SUSAN SACHS and JASON BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alone in the world but for the father he had never
seen, a determined 13-year-old boy equipped with a little money and
enough pluck to charm a string of helpful strangers, set out for
New York City from his hurricane-devastated village in Honduras
last month to find his father.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, Edwin Daniel Sabillon, carrying a paper bag with a
change of clothes, his birth certificate and three cookies, arrived
on a bus from Miami on Sunday. With the aplomb that carried him
through his 3,200-mile journey, he hailed a cab and went looking
for his father.
</P>
<P>
   He did not find him. But the police, who picked the boy up after
being alerted by the concerned taxi driver, said Monday that they
will take up Edwin's search.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary concern is that he is reunited with his father,''
said Capt. Thomas Kelly, of the Bronx Detectives.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin, he added, has nothing to worry about. Although he entered
the country illegally, the boy's story has touched the
highest-ranking heart in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's under the protective custody of the mayor's office,''
Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the youngster is in the hands of the city's
Administration for Childrens Services, which Monday was arranging
for him to spend the night with a Spanish-speaking foster family
while the police continued to hunt for his father.
</P>
<P>
   The father was identified as Grevi Sabillon Vasquez. Detectives
said they do not know what the father does, where in the city he
lives, or whether he is a legal or illegal immigrant. What they do
know about him comes, essentially, from the bits and pieces of
information they gleaned from Edwin.
</P>
<P>
   The boy said he wrote to his father last year, after Hurricane
Mitch roared through Honduras and wrecked his home in Colonia San
Miguel, a suburb of the capital Tegucigalpa. A mudslide, apparently
triggered by the torrential rains of the storm, had killed his
mother, Angela Enamorado, and his 14-year-old brother, Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the father wrote back. As recounted by the police,
who read the letter, he instructed the boy to come to New York
City. He said he would meet him at the entrance to LaGuardia
Airport. He gave three rendezvous dates: June 25, 26 and 27. I will
be wearing a white shirt, black pants, white sneakers and a black
hat, the father wrote, but I will recognize you.
</P>
<P>
   Then the father sent $200 by wire to Honduras and on May 22,
Edwin left the house of friends in San Francisco de Yojoa Cortez,
and set out on a journey that would take him 37 days.
</P>
<P>
   The adventures along the way that he recounted to detectives
sound like the Huckleberry Finn tale in reverse: A stubborn boy
sets out on the road to join his father, steals across the borders
of three countries, gives the slip to lawmen along the way, loses
his possessions and gets rescued by a succession of good
Samaritans.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, it is also an improbable tale of luck and
generosity along a route that most often is paved with hardship and
greed.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin said he hitchhiked up the Honduran coast through Guatemala
and into Mexico. In Matamoros, a town bordering Texas, he said he
won the sympathy of smugglers who agreed to arrange his passage for
free. The normal price for the often hazardous and sometimes deadly
journey is $5,000, according to lawyers who work with Central
American immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   According to the boy's account, he then found a ride to Houston
and then, inexplicably, went to Miami. Somewhere along the way, he
lost his wallet with most of the money his father had sent him and
the slip of paper on which he had written his father's address.
</P>
<P>
   But his luck held. In Miami, he found his way to the Natasha
Cafeteria, where the Cuban-American owner and his patrons took the
boy in blue jeans and a yellow T-shirt into their embrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a five-dollar bill in his hand and he was asking for
change _ four dollars in quarters to take a bus to take him to I-95
North to see how he could get to New York,'' recalled Emilio Jose
Jimenez, who was in the cafeteria last Saturday when Edwin turned
up.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, he said, seemed educated and well-mannered. The
customers took up a collection to buy him an $87 bus ticket so
Edwin would not have to hitchhike, gave him pocket money for food,
took him to the bus station, and bade him goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin arrived in New York City at about 2 p.m. on Sunday. The
police said he got off the bus at 177th Street and Broadway and
then did what most newcomers do: He gaped.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's walking around, he's amazed by the tall buildings, all
the hustle and bustle, where's the countryside,'' said Det. Gilbert
Ramirez, recounting how the boy described his first hours in the
new city.
</P>
<P>
   That evening, Edwin was spotted by Jose Basora, a 35-year-old
taxi driver who emigrated from the Dominican Republic 10 years ago.
At first, Basora said, he thought Edwin was one of the battalion of
young boys who sell flowers in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him looking at me, he was smiling, he was happy,''
Basora recalled. ``Then he came to me and asked me if I can take
him to the airport and how much it would be. I found this strange
because he was a little boy. The light turned green, I told him to
get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwin soon told him of his search for his father. Basora, moved
by the story, drove him around the edges of the airport for 15
minutes, trying various entrances. When he could find no sign of
the father, who had not specified a time for his son to meet him,
the two drove to Basora's home in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 2049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2527 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEORGIA-NUWAUBIANS-10     06-28 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-NUWAUBIANS-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSIONS SIMMER AROUND A BLACK SECT IN GEORGIA
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By TOM LASSETER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EATONTON, Ga. _ When members of a black religious group moved
here from Brooklyn, N.Y., in 1993, their purchase of 438 acres of
pasture about 10 miles outside of town stirred up gossip and some
apprehension, but residents were more curious than frightened.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, with the completion of a 40-foot black
pyramid on the land that belonged to the group, which is known as
the Yamassee Native American Nuwaubians, most neighbors in this
small dairy-farming town east of Atlanta scratched their heads and
figured it would be best to keep their distance.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1997, when the Nuwaubians declared themselves a separate
nation and began issuing passports and organizing armed security
patrols of their property, Sheriff Howard Sills of Putnam County
decided to take a closer look. A copy of a 1993 FBI report he
received, linking the Nuwaubians' New York operations to welfare
fraud and extortion, also concerned him.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Sills learned that the group's spiritual leader, Dwight
York, was a convicted felon. York has admitted he served three
years in prison in the 1960s for resisting arrest, assault and
possession of a dangerous weapon.
</P>
<P>
   He is known among the Nuwaubians as the Master Teacher Dr.
Malachi York, who founded the Nuwaubians sect on a combination of
Islamic, Christian and Hebrew teachings. York says he is an
extraterrestrial being from the galaxy Illyuwn. He and many in his
group say they expect a spacecraft from Illyuwn to visit Earth in
2003. The craft, they say, will take with it 144,000 chosen people,
a number they do not explain.
</P>
<P>
   The front of the compound, which Nuwaubians refer to as the
``Egypt of the West,'' contains eight-foot statues of Egyptian gods
and goddesses placed among columns covered with hieroglyphics, and
a sphinx and several smaller pyramids about 24 feet in height.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the last days and we Nuwaubians have created God's
kingdom right here on Earth,'' said Marshall Chance Jr., president
of the group's Holy Tabernacle Industries.
</P>
<P>
   The similarities between the Nuwaubians and the 39 members of
the Heaven's Gate sect in Rancho Santa Fe, Calif., who committed
mass suicide in March 1997, were too close to ignore, Sills said.
The Heaven's Gate group, like the Nuwaubians, said they believed a
spacecraft would come to save them. There are at least 150 people
living on the Nuwaubian property.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions between Putnam County authorities and the Nuwaubians
have steadily increased in the last two years. In the last few
months, there have been several standoffs between Nuwaubian guards
and the sheriff's department, when deputies were barred from the
property. In April, for example, when Sills attempted to deliver a
court order concerning zoning violations, two Nuwaubian guards,
wearing 9-millimeter pistols on their hips, stood in front of his
car and would not let it pass, Sills said.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontations stem in part from three county lawsuits filed
in the last year against the Nuwaubians, charging the group with
zoning violations and violations of building regulations. The
Nuwaubians were operating a large nightclub on their land, zoned
for agricultural use, and were planning to open, among other
businesses, a health-food store, a bar, a recording studio and a
taxicab company.
</P>
<P>
   York refused to appear in court and was ordered to be tried for
contempt of court on Tuesday for not appearing at previous hearings
on zoning violations.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, thousands of Nuwaubian followers drove by the
dairy farms, fruit stands and bait shops of Eatonton to attend the
annual Savior Day's Festival at the Nuwaubian compound, which
celebrated York's birthday on June 26. Because Sills padlocked some
of the compound's buildings, acting on a court order in the zoning
disputes, the festival was held outdoors, in continual rainstorms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a utopia,'' said Chance, who wears a priestly black shirt
and pants with a white collar. When asked if he was ordained by any
particular denomination, Chance replied that he was ``ordained and
called by God himself.''
</P>
<P>
   But that sort of religious fervor has raised concerns among
state and federal officials. Department of Justice representatives
from the community dispute resolution offices in Atlanta have been
in Eatonton since Wednesday, trying to bring the county and the
Nuwaubians to the same table to quiet tensions.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict in Putnam County, and its potential for disorder,
even violence led Gov. Roy Barnes to call Sills last week to
discuss the situation.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a bench warrant for York's arrest on contempt of
court charges was withdrawn when York's lawyer promised that he
would appear in court on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an atmosphere of tension,'' said Ernie Stallworth, a
mediator for the Justice Department. ``The Nuwaubians feel they
have been unfairly harassed since they've been down there.''
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the Nuwaubians, Leroy Johnson, said he thought
local, white government officials should be more tolerant of the
group's endeavors, but he acknowledged that predominantly white
Putnam County might not be the most suitable place for a black
religious group to build pyramids.
</P>
<P>
   Driving into Putnam, motorists see signs inviting people to join
the local chapter of Sons of Confederate Veterans and the county
has an annual 10-kilometer race, once known to locals as the Tar
Baby Run in celebration of Joel Chandler Harris, a white native of
Eatonton who wrote a series of Br'er Rabbit folktales.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be a realization by the government there that the
situation is a powder keg, where the drop of a hat or a
miscalculated word can incite violence,'' Johnson, a former state
senator, said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   At the festival, people from as far as Trinidad and London came
to honor York. Visitors walked the small labyrinth surrounding the
main pyramid, praying with tracts written by York, who has written
at least 200 of them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many in the crowd were wearing in clerical robes and Egyptian
headdresses, spoke in bits of Nuwabic, a blend of Arabic and
English also invented by York, who appeared briefly on Saturday,
surrounded by five guards and hundreds of admirers.
</P>
<P>
   None of those living on the property, other than a spokeswoman
and Chance, would comment on their organization. Many of the women
had shaved heads, with a single braid on the right side, in honor
of a Mother Nature-like deity.
</P>
<P>
   The Nuwaubians' move from Brooklyn, where the group was known as
both the Holy Tabernacle of the Most High and the Children of
Abraham, Chance said, was driven by rivalries with Islamic
organizations in New York that objected to the group's borrowing of
several Muslim traditions, Chance said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how the group managed to buy its land and finance the
construction, Chance gave a faint smile, and said, ``We attract
people who already have something with them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
