<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2534 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SURPLUS-BOS &LR;      06-28 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SURPLUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOARING TAX SURPLUS SPURS DEBATE OVER WHERE TO SPEND THE MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton Monday said the roaring US
economy would bring $1 trillion more in tax revenues to the
government by 2014 than anticipated only five months ago, and he
proposed devoting the bulk of the windfall to Social Security,
Medicare, and erasing the government's huge public debt.
</P>
<P>
   The unanticipated money is sure to intensify what is already a
heated debate with the Republican-led Congress over what to do with
future budget surpluses _ how much to return to taxpayers, how much
to use to pay off government debt and how much to spend on federal
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The debate could produce major changes in the nation's two
largest domestic programs, Social Security and Medicare. Both
parties say they want to shore up the shaky finances of the
programs, but Clinton also wants to use much of the surplus to help
finance new benefits.
</P>
<P>
   He has already proposed new tax incentives for low- and
middle-income workers to save for retirement in private stock and
bond accounts, which would supplement their Social Security income.
And Tuesday, he will unveil a sweeping Medicare overhaul that
claims to keep the program solvent for an additional 10 years while
giving seniors a signficant new benefit: partial coverage for the
cost of prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the growing surpluse projections, Clinton so far has
offered no help to one ailing sector of the economy _ money-losing
hospitals. In fact, hospitals are wary of the president's new
Medicare plan because it is expected to steer surgeries to a fewer
number of hospitals, which would be asked to cut their prices and
offer volume discounts to the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to see the administration add money to the system,
not squeeze the system further,'' said Andrew Dreyfus, executive
vice president of the Massachusetts Hospital Association. Under a
1997 law, he said, Medicare is on track to pay less than cost for
many surgeries, and contracting certain hospitals to perform even
more unprofitable operations would cause more financial damage.
``We're still hopeful the administration will restore some of the
cuts made in 1997,'' Dreyfus said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have proposed spending far more than the president
on tax cuts and on defense. Still, early reaction to Clinton's
plans for the larger surplus was warm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us more opportunity to get real Social Security and
Medicare reform done, and tax cuts, if the president wants to get
them done,'' said Michele Davis, spokeswoman for House Majority
Leader Richard Armey, a Texas Republican.
</P>
<P>
   In his announcement Monday, Clinton also made a claim that would
have been unthinkable only three years ago. He said this plan would
boost spending on government programs while buying back all federal
debt held by the public within 15 years _all Treasury bonds, bills
and notes.
</P>
<P>
   Few people think the government would actually eliminate all its
public debt, which is more than half the $5.7 trillion total. The
rest is debt the government owes itself, such as money it has
already spent from Social Security trust funds that must be repaid
to the retirement program.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that a president claims to have a plan to wipe out
public debt shows how profoundly the robust economy has changed
government finance.
</P>
<P>
   Only three years ago, someone who made such a claim ``would be
told to go lie down and sleep it off,'' said Henry Aaron, who
studies economic policy at the Brookings Institution. ``The fact
that it's within shouting distance is amazing,'' said Robert Bixby,
policy director at the Concord Coaltion, the group devoted to a
balanced federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced the new budget projections before traveling to
several fund-raisers in New York City. His announcement comes only
days before the Congressional Budget Office is expected to lay out
an even rosier vision of future surpluses. With that, Republican
lawmakers will also release their plan for how to spend the money.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his economic team said the budget surplus next year
will be $142 billion, $25 billion more than was forecast in
February.
</P>
<P>
   Economists generally said the White House predictions, based on
a 2.3 percent annual economic growth rate over the next five years,
appeared to be realistic. The economy is now growing at about 4
percent a year. The projected surplus is bigger because the
government expected the economy to slow down this year but it
hasn't so tax revenues are up.
</P>
<P>
   The surplus is expected to include $5 billion produced by taxes
other than the Social Security payroll tax, the first surplus of
this type in 40 years and a significant political milestone. Both
parties have said that every dollar raised by Social Security taxes
should be devoted to the retirement program. Now, is is clear that
Clinton and lawmakers will have money available from non-Social
Security sources to spend on possible tax cuts or federal programs.
</P>
<P>
   The cumulative surplus over the next 15 years will be $5.9
trillion, the White House said, about $1.1 trillion more than
anticipated in February.
</P>
<P>
   In proposing how to spend the money, Clinton laid out a 15-year
plan, even though his term ends in 18 months and Congress is now
discussing a budget that lasts only through late 2000. Clinton
proposed spending:
</P>
<P>
   -- $794 billion over 15 years to strengthen Medicare. That is
$108 billion more than he proposed in February, when he released
his fiscal 2000 budget.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said most of that money would be used to
extend the life of the program, which is now expected to become
insolvent in 2015. In announcing his Medicare overhaul, Clinton
will also propose a new competitive bidding system to win discounts
on goods, like wheelchairs, and services, like surgeries. Those
savings would help extend the financial life of Medicare by 10
years, to 2025, and cover the prescription drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   -- $522 billion for discretionary programs, up $41 billion from
his February plan. The money includes $183 billion in additional
defense spending and $183 billion for crime prevention, health
research and several other social programs.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Clinton proposed that $156 billion over 15 years be
devoted to a ``children and education trust fund,'' which consists
of Head Start, after-school programs, Pell grants for low-income
college students and other existing programs.
</P>
<P>
   -- At least $540 billion on tax cuts over 15 years. House
Republicans want a larger tax cut _ as much as $778 billion over 10
years _ and they generally favor broad reductions in the income,
estate and capital gains taxes. Clinton generally favors
``targeted'' cuts to help specific groups, such as people caring
for elderly relatives, parents with child-care costs and low-income
people saving for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also revised his earlier plan for how to improve the
finances of Social Security. The plan would extend the solvency of
Social Security to 2053, White House aides said. That is two years
earlier than under a similar plan in February, but aides said the
new idea would be more politically palatable. Without any changes,
Social Security will be unable to meet its commitments in 2034.
</P>
<P>
   Under Clinton's plan, all surpluses generated by the Social
Security program over the next 15 years _ some $3 trillion of the
$5.9 trillion total surplus _ would be used to buy back government
debt held by the public. This would reduce the government's debt
service costs, and that savings _ an estimated $543 billion _ would
be transferred to the Social Security program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
