<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2535 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INSURANCE-FRAUD-2TAKE     06-28 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-FRAUD-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELL-CONNECTED CONSULTANT LINKED SUSPECTED CON MAN TO THE
POWERFUL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Ohio)  (rm) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN and KURT EICHENWALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the mysteries about Martin Frankel, the man authorities
suspect of orchestrating a spectacular insurance fraud, is how a
financier who almost never left his well-guarded Greenwich, Conn.,
mansion befriended corporate and religious elites on two
continents.
</P>
<P>
   The answer appears to be that Frankel turned to Thomas Corbally,
a business consultant whose ties to powerful people made him an
insider at Kroll Associates, one of America's best-known private
investigative agencies.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from London on Monday, Corbally
acknowledged that he helped Frankel put a veneer of credibility on
an operation that federal investigators believe siphoned more than
$300 million from a string of insurance companies. He introduced
Frankel to Robert Strauss, the Democratic party heavyweight and
Washington lawyer, Thomas Bolan, the law partner of the late Roy
Cohn, and a monsignor with ties to the Vatican, among others.
</P>
<P>
   He also arranged one of the more bizarre episodes to come to
light in the unfolding saga, a meeting last August at a monastery
in Florence in which a woman friend of Frankel, clad in hot pants
and a bikini top, tried to persuade a prominent priest to accept a
$50 million donation to his charity in exchange for helping Frankel
buy insurance companies. The offer was rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   Corbally said Monday that he was ``in free fall'' after helping
Frankel. He described himself as a dupe who had no inkling of
Frankel's alleged criminal plans. ``This is the shock of my life,''
Corbally said. ``It is destroying relationships that I built up
over 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has notified Corbally, who is vacationing in London,
that it wants to question him about his role in vouching for
Frankel and hooking him up with lawyers, businessmen and Catholic
leaders in the year before Frankel's insurance empire collapsed.
Corbally said he has nothing to hide and that he intended to
cooperate fully with the FBI. Federal authorities have issued a
warrant for Frankel's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure puts Kroll Associates in an awkward position. The
agency, which recently went public, is one of the companies
corporate America enlists to scrutinize potential business partners
and adversaries. In fact, it was retained last year to look into
Frankel and quickly found potential problems with his operation.
That inquiry apparently did not uncover the role of Corbally, who
had worked directly with Jules Kroll for almost 20 years and had an
office at the firm's Manhattan headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, Corbally's records were removed from Kroll
offices under subpoena and delivered to the FBI, according to
people close to the Kroll firm. In an interview Monday, Kroll said
that Corbally misled him about his relationship to Frankel and said
the long-time associate no longer worked with him. He also stressed
that that his company never had any dealings with Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   The ties to Kroll Associates have already had one effect on the
inquiry. Stephen C. Robinson, the United States Attorney in
Connecticut, and a former employee of Kroll and acquaintance of
Corbally, has recused himself from the case.
</P>
<P>
   As a gadfly American businessman in London more than 30 years
ago, Corbally, 78, played a role in exposing the Profumo political
sex and spy scandal that rocked the British government.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of the U.S. ambassador to Britain at the time, he
used his contacts to help uncover details about a high-priced call
girl who had relationships with the British minister of war and a
top Russian spy, according to ``Affair of State,'' a book on the
case. Since then, he said, he has worked as a business consultant
to law firms, corporations and governments.
</P>
<P>
   Corbally splits his time between New York and London and lives
mostly in hotels _ the Delmonico in New York, the Claridge in
London. He speaks in a deep baritone voice made gravelly by a
life-long addiction to cigarettes. A flashy dresser partial to
jewelry, Corbally is often chauffeured around in a Mercedes sedan,
people who know him said.
</P>
<P>
   He remains vague on how he first hooked up with Frankel, whom he
knew by the alias David Rosse. He said he learned of Frankel
through ``osmosis'' and struck up a dialogue by phone, followed by
a series of meetings at Frankel's Greenwich estate in the spring of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard about this reclusive multi-billionaire who made $100
million a day trading stock,'' Corbally recalled. Though Frankel
grew up in a Jewish household, he appeared to know a great deal
about Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``I was an altar boy but he knew much more than I did. He was
compulsive talker and pontificated about great wealth, prolonging
life, curing sick children and feeding the hungry. He was devoted
to St. Francis of Assisi. I was mesmerized.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Corbally said he was never on Frankel's payroll. But he said he
was attracted by the business possibilities in helping the
financier expand his insurance companies. He said Frankel had a
plan to expand insurance assets he managed more than tenfold, to
$100 billion, in a short time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a business prospect for me, and I wasn't
indifferent,'' Corbally said.
</P>
<P>
   In the months that followed, Corbally opened his Rolodex to
Frankel, a native of Toledo, Ohio, who had few known friends or
supporters when he moved his operation to Greenwich in the early
1990s. One of the most important introductions was to Strauss, the
former ambassador to the Soviet Union who now recruits clients for
the Washington law firm of Akin, Gump, Strauss, Hauer &AMP; Feld.
</P>
<P>
   After Corbally vouched for Frankel, Strauss accepted the
financier as a client for the firm, several people directly
involved in the matter said. Akin, Gump subsequently represented
Frankel's organization in business deals that were not successfully
concluded, earning several hundred thousand dollars in fees.
</P>
<P>
   Corbally also tried to persuade Lee Iacocca, the former Chrysler
chairman, to serve of the board of advisers of a Catholic charity
Frankel was starting.
</P>
<P>
   Iacocca did not agree.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But Corbally subsequently arranged for Iacocca to fly on a
leased Gulfstream IV jet from Los Angeles to Milan, Italy, as a
gift from Frankel designed to get the former auto executive to
reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Frankel, who turned to the insurance business after the
Securities and Exchange Commission demanded he stop trading stocks,
aggressively pursued links to Catholic charities in the summer of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Corbally said he was persuaded that Frankel genuinely hoped to
donate huge sums to charity and he introduced him to people he knew
with connections in the Catholic world.
</P>
<P>
   One of these was Bolan, who would come to serve as Frankel's
attorney in negotiating with Catholic priests. According to court
documents, Bolan was paid at least $75,000 for legal advice he
provided to Frankel. Bolan's lawyer said the actual payment was
smaller.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And it was through one of Corbally's contacts in Italy that
Frankel made his first big pitch to a Catholic charity, known as
the Genesis Center. The center is based in Florence and run by
Father Christopher Zielinski, prior of the San Miniato al Monte
monastery.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Corbally set up a meeting, Frankel sent Kaethe
Schuchter, a young Russian woman who was living in one of his
several homes in Greenwich, to Italy, according to Michele Spike, a
lawyer for the Genesis Center.
</P>
<P>
   Zielinski awaited their arrival in the courtyard of the
monastery. Ms. Schuchter, dressed in scanty summer wear, arrived in
a stretch Mercedes limousine along with a young male friend, an
Italian law student. They boasted of having flown to Europe on the
supersonic Concorde, Ms. Spike said.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch did not go well. Ms. Schuchter offered the $50 million
gift if the Genesis Center would agree to purchase insurance
companies on behalf of Frankel. Funds would come from ``off
shore.'' The Genesis center was not to know their source, Ms. Spike
recalled. (Ms. Schuchter could not be reached for comment.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Spike said in a recent interview that she was distraught
about the offer. On Aug. 10, a few days after the meeting, she
wrote a letter to Kroll, saying that the executive's name had been
mentioned as a supporter of Frankel during the presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Spike warned Kroll in the letter that a man she identified
as David Ross and Corbally might be ``trading off your good name.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Monday, Kroll confirmed that he had received the
letter. At the time, he said, he did not have any idea who Frankel
was. But he said he and a senior member of his staff confronted
Corbally twice to ask whether he was involved with the man the
letter referred to as Ross. According to Kroll, Corbally denied any
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was confronted, he was asked specifically about it, and he
denied it,'' Kroll said. ``He denied knowing anything about it to
us.'' Corbally offered a different account of the meeting, saying
he told Kroll that he believed that Frankel was sincere.
</P>
<P>
   Kroll said he had no reason to question Corbally's denial at the
time. He said the inquiries were unrelated to a separate
investigation into Frankel that Kroll Associates did on behalf on
an investment banking client last fall. That inquiry, which Kroll
described as cursory, did not turn up information about Corbally's
role.
</P>
<P>
   Though rebuffed by the Genesis Center, Corbally and Bolan, the
lawyer he recruited to the Frankel team, had success at the
Vatican. Certain that Frankel intended to share his wealth with
Vatican-sponsored charities, the two helped persuade priests there
to work with Frankel. After negotiations, an organization whose
leaders had ties to the Vatican founded a charity called the St.
Francis of Assisi Foundation. It failed in several attempts to buy
insurance companies in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   When state regulators who oversee insurance companies began to
raise questions about the way Frankel dealt with the insurance
companies' investment money, Corbally defended Frankel. During one
bout with regulators in Mississippi, Corbally and Frankel together
called Strauss, the Akin, Gump, lawyer, asking him to get involved
on their behalf, people briefed about the conversation said.
Strauss declined, these people said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Corbally said he did not learn of Frankel's
suspected corrupt dealings until after Frankel disappeared. ``I had
no idea Frankel was a crook,'' he said flatly.
</P>
<P>
   But Corbally's relationship with Frankel raises the question of
whether he's the ``Tom'' Frankel cryptically referred to in a note
he left behind before fleeing. According to court documents filed
by federal prosecutors, Frankel wrote out a series of questions and
then consulted astrological charts for answers. Among the questions
was one that read: ``Will Tom turn me in?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 2058EDT &QL; 
