<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2541 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-BUDGET-HNS &LR;      06-28 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON UNVEILS PLAN TO AID SOCIAL SECURITY, MEDICARE AMID NEW
BUDGET FIGURES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton unveiled new budget figures
Monday that project an extra $1 trillion in surpluses over the next
15 year, and he proposed the money be used to shore up Social
Security and Medicare and pay off the national debt by 2015.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have now cut up Washington's credit card,'' Clinton said in
a South Lawn ceremony to unveil mid-year White House budget
revisions.
</P>
<P>
   The new projections revise figures compiled in February that
projected a $700 million surplus within five years, $2.4 trillion
in 10 years and $4.47 trillion in 15 years. The new projections
raise the accumulated surplus after 15 years to $5.47 trillion. The
event upstaged a planned Republican news conference Tuesday to
unveil Congressional Budget Office figures that project even
greater surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and Congress are staking out positions now for a
crucial showdown later this legislative session over the surplus.
Republicans favor a broad-based tax cut while also setting aside
money to save Social Security from bankruptcy. Clinton favors
extending Social Security and Medicare while offering targeted tax
cuts and increases in spending for programs such as education.
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton suggested to reporters he would be willing to
negotiate on the tax cut issue. ``Within the framework of achieving
these objectives, obviously I'll be working with the Congress to
achieve them,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The new figures announced by Clinton also allowed him to amend
the budget plan he outlined in February. The revised forecasts
project a $98.9 billion surplus for this fiscal year which ends
September 31, almost $20 billion more than predicted in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``Improvements in the outlook since February have added $179
billion to the projected budget surplus over five years, half a
trillion over 10 years and a trillion over 15 years,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   The extra money, Clinton said, means all Social Security payroll
taxes can be devoted strictly to the Social Security trust fund and
the fund, now facing bankruptcy, could be extended to 2053. The
additional surplus means Medicare can be extended and expanded, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Money also can be set aside for the national debt, targeted tax
relief and more money for education and children, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the unexpected cash is just proof to some that taxes are far
too high. Rep. Bill Archer, chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, said Americans have a right to pay less.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can shore up Social Security and Medicare and still provide
tax relief to American families and individuals who are working
harder than ever but can't seem to get ahead,'' Archer, R-Texas,
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., blasted Clinton for
announcing the new figures, outlining his new proposals and then
leaving for New York and Connecticut to raise money for the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``He runs into town, throws out supposedly an agenda; does
nothing to really make it happen; and off he goes again,'' Lott
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I don't know whether he's serious or not, but if he is,
we're going to have to see more than words. We need to see some
deeds,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the extra cash, Clinton called for all Social
Security payroll taxes to be earmarked for Social Security only.
Clinton initially called for 62 percent of the projected surplus to
be saved for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   The United States technically marked its first budget surplus in
30 years last fiscal year. But even then, critics noted, the use of
Social Security trust funds, which are invested in government
notes, mask the true size of the annual federal deficit. However,
Clinton said new projections forecast a $5 billion surplus next
year even excluding Social Security funds.
</P>
<P>
   It's the repayment of those invested Social Security funds and
the use of the non-Social Security surplus for other programs that
would lower the $5.7 trillion national debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we can pay off that debt; by 2015, this country can be
entirely out of debt. This is a remarkable milestone, but it is
clearly within reach, if we do not squander the surplus by choosing
short-term gain over long-term national goals,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan would extend the life of Social Security to 2053.
Currently, Social Security will go bankrupt when the large baby
boom generation retires.
</P>
<P>
   The president also said he will announce Tuesday revisions in
Medicare that not only will extend the life of that health
insurance program to 2025 but also provide coverage for
prescription medicine for senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced the creation of a new $156 billion children's
and education trust fund. The proposal would provide money for Head
Start, hire 100,000 new teachers and pay for improvements in
children's health.
</P>
<P>
   The president noted that the additional surplus would allow the
financing of his own tax relief ideas, including the creation of
USA Accounts that would use tax credits to encourage workers to set
up their own retirement accounts. His other tax relief proposals
include the use of tax credits for: stay-at-home mothers, long-term
care, modernizing 6,000 schools, child care and encouraging
business investment in poor communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surplus is the hard-earned product of our fiscal
discipline. We should use it to prepare for the great challenges
facing our country _ caring for our parents, caring for our
children, freeing our nation from the shackles of debt so that we
can have long-term, sustained economic prosperity,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
