<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2544 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-UNION-SOUTH-ART-     06-28 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-UNION-SOUTH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UAW FACES UNCOMMON ODDS IN BID TO ORGANIZE ALABAMA PLANT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Germany)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCE, Ala. _ Steven Merrill was one of the first autoworkers
Mercedes-Benz hired as it geared up to build sport utility vehicles
here in 1994. He has received steady raises and a two-month
training trip to Germany. He even met his wife on the assembly
line.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the United Automobile Workers union is trying to organize
the Mercedes factory, and Merrill does not want any part of it. ``I
really don't believe we need the UAW,'' said Merrill, 37, who
earned more than $80,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   He is delighted with his pay and benefits and with the collegial
atmosphere on the factory floor, and many of his co-workers agree
with him, more than a dozen interviews suggest. They say they
signed on for nonunion jobs at what was a 100 percent German-owned
factory, but after Daimler-Benz bought Chrysler Corp. last year,
they found themselves caught up in a high-profile union organizing
drive.
</P>
<P>
   UAW officials say they will prevail at Vance _ if Daimler plays
fair. The union has repeatedly contended that Mercedes managers
made their anti-union views clear when the plant opened and at
frequent intervals subsequently. The company, which now employs
69,000 union members from the former Chrysler Corp., has promised
to stay neutral during the organizing drive. ``I feel very
confident that those workers, given a free choice, will choose to
be UAW,'' said Bob King, a union vice president.
</P>
<P>
   But the UAW is in new territory in Alabama, the heart of a
region that has not only been inhospitable to unions but that
increasingly beckons to foreign automakers. DaimlerChrysler, BMW
and Honda Motor have recently announced plans to expand or add
factories in the South. As the auto industry disperses from its
traditional base in the more union-friendly Midwest, the UAW may
face more fights like the one shaping up in this unlikely hotbed of
union activity.
</P>
<P>
   Down the street from the one-room Vance Town Hall, the UAW has
set up a recruiting office sandwiched between an insurance agency
and a Texaco station that doubles as Vance's grocery store. Modest
houses and trailer homes offer views of the highway and the
railroad tracks that bisect the town. A few rolling hills away,
well back from the highway, the pale white and gray outlines of the
Mercedes factory glint through tall stands of pines.
</P>
<P>
   The organizing campaign here is a big topic in Detroit, where
the UAW and DaimlerChrysler began negotiating earlier this month on
the labor contract that will cover the company's UAW workers when
the current contract expires this fall. Eager to avoid a strike
that could shutter DaimlerChrysler's highly profitable American
operations, executives have taken the unusual step of promising not
to fight the union in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the UAW, Stephen Yokich, and the vice
president, Jack Laskowski, have pressed the point with the
DaimlerChrysler co-chairmen, Juergen Schrempp and Robert Eaton,
along with other top executives. ``It is a large company, and Steve
and Jack remind us whenever something seems not neutral,'' Thomas
Stallkamp, president of DaimlerChrysler's North American
operations, said as labor talks opened earlier this month. ``We're
making every effort we have to to make sure that the large number
of people involved in management know that that's the management
position on this.''
</P>
<P>
   He has not heard the last from the UAW. ``We'll continue to meet
until we can get this done right,'' Yokich promised.
</P>
<P>
   The union must win support from a majority of the factory's
1,300 workers here to represent them, and that is proving an uphill
battle. In Alabama, as in the rest of the South, unions are far
less common than elsewhere in the country. Just 9.7 percent of
Alabama's workers belonged to a union last year, compared with 21.6
percent in Michigan, traditional home of the American auto
industry, and 13.9 percent nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, workers at the Fieldcrest Cannon plant in
Kannapolis, N.C., apparently voted to join the Union of
Needletrades, Industrial and Textile Employees, but only after 93
years of campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   Even when unions are established in the region, they find it
more difficult to operate. Like North Carolina, Alabama is a
so-called right to work state, which means that even if a union
wins the right to represent employees, the workers are not
compelled to join and pay full dues and union fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a right-to-work state, you have to have a lot of courage to
be a union supporter,'' said Dennis Devaney, a former member of the
National Labor Relations Board and a labor law professor at Wayne
State University in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Brown, a management lawyer at Duvin, Cahn &AMP; Hutton in
Cleveland, said, ``You've got a generally nonunion and
union-unfriendly environment'' in the South.
</P>
<P>
   While Daimler-Benz set out to make its first American Mercedes
factory nonunion, it has long had close working relationships with
unions in Germany. Mercedes-Benz workers there are represented by
the powerful IG Metall union, whose members have sat on the
company's board for years. Daimler's German workers are well paid
and, like other European workers, have generous benefits that
include six weeks of vacations.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercedes workers in Alabama earned far less than their
German counterparts when the factory opened in October 1994 _ just
$12.80 an hour _ but the company gave them frequent steady raises.
With current exchange rates, the Alabama Mercedes workers now earn
roughly the same as their German counterparts, while their benefits
remain lower.
</P>
<P>
   Even some workers at the Vance factory who oppose the union
acknowledge that they would be unlikely to be paid so much if it
were not for the UAW's efforts in the North. But because Mercedes
already pays well, the UAW cannot woo supporters with promises of a
jump in wages. Workers here for more than two years earn between
$20.50 and $24.25 an hour, depending on their jobs, compared with
an average $21 an hour at DaimlerChrysler's unionized plants.
Benefits are comparable. At Vance, however, perks include discounts
of roughly 25 percent on leases of Mercedes sport utility vehicles,
bringing the fee for factory workers to about $400 a month.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In random interviews conducted as employees drove out of the
factory gates, many volunteered that they were grateful to be
working here, contrasting this job to others in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   The factory has adopted the kind of feel-good practices favored
by both modern management gurus and anti-union labor lawyers, and
that has helped keep workers content. The company doles out free
Mercedes clothing, emphasizes teamwork and responsibility and even
gave away movie tickets when the Mercedes sport utility vehicle
starred in ``The Lost World,'' the dinosaur sequel to ``Jurassic
Park.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the biggest complaint of pro-union workers here seems to
be that there is too much overtime. ``I appreciate my job, and I
make good money,'' said J. Chris Johnson, 27, who said he
nonetheless favors union representation. ``It is about having time
with your family.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he did not get to see much of his 20-month-old
daughter because she goes to bed at 8 p.m. and he does not get home
until 6:30, more than 12 hours after starting his shift.
</P>
<P>
   With fatherhood came fond memories of his father's history as a
union man. ``As long as I ever remembered, he worked eight hours a
day with a paid lunch,'' Johnson said. ``That's the way he fed me
and clothed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson estimated that the UAW has the support of about half the
workers here. Other workers interviewed _ both those for and
against the union _ put the level of support lower, closer to 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Few workers openly support the union, but many who oppose it are
not shy about letting their views be known. Some workers wear
anti-union stickers in the factory and many have found anti-union
leaflets on tables in break areas. While both the union and the
company are allowed to distribute information, little pro-union
material is found in the plant.
</P>
<P>
   The union says it has not asked workers to distribute its
material in the plant for two reasons: It wants to protect them
from possible retaliation, and it wants to take the high road in
the organizing campaign, while pressing DaimlerChrysler to do the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to divide the shop floor,'' said King, the UAW
organizer. ``We think the power of the relationship should really
create an open environment where people can decide whether they
want to be in the union.''
</P>
<P>
   The company insists that the anti-union fliers and stickers have
not come from managers. Merrill said they came from the anti-union
group he formed, the Team Members Information Committee, which
began distributing the leaflets and stickers about a month ago. So
far it has spent about $800 on printing, he said. The money came
from workers and from small businesses in nearby Tuscaloosa, he
said, declining to identify them except to say they include real
estate agents, contractors and restaurant owners but ``no one
that's a supplier or no one that we supply to.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill added, ``The company is doing nothing to support this.''
</P>
<P>
   In phone calls and meetings at the union hall and a nearby
hotel, the UAW has been asking workers to sign cards indicating
their interest in joining. Typically, when a union collects
signature cards of at least 30 percent of the work force, it may
petition the National Labor Relations Board to hold a secret-ballot
election, and, if at least 51 percent vote in favor, the workers
can then organize, according to NLRB spokesman Dave Parker.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, companies recognize a union without an election
if the union has collected cards from at least 51 percent of the
workers, he said. While the UAW has pressed DaimlerChrysler to
agree to a card check, and the company has not refused outright, it
has said it wants to be sure workers' voices are heard.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many workers here seem to shun the union because times
are so good. More than 45,000 people applied for jobs here, and
turnover is rock-bottom: about 1 percent a year at this cavernous,
clean factory, where workers wear company-provided slacks and polo
shirts stitched with their first names. They build about 375 cars a
day, various models of the ML-320, which starts at $35,450, and the
ML-430, which costs $45,000, fully equipped.
</P>
<P>
   Tonya Hallmark, 33, was among the 3 percent of applicants chosen
by Daimler. In the last three years, she has been transformed from
an $8-an-hour T-shirt factory seamstress to a $50,000-a-year
autoworker who drives a Mercedes-Benz. Her teen-age son begs her to
get him a job like hers someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company gives us very good benefits, and they pay us
well,'' said Mrs. Hallmark, a welder, who said she saw no need for
a union. ``If they come in we're going to lose what we've got.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 2105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2548 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-NEW-ORLEANS-2T     06-28 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NEW-ORLEANS-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ORLEANS, A CITY OF SERIOUS EATERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To assert that New Orleans is serious about its restaurants is
like saying that mountains are high and water is wet: It's a
natural fact.
</P>
<P>
   Offer even a tentative opinion about a particular restaurant to
a resident of this food-crazed city and chances are the response
will include not only a detailed history of that establishment and
its food, but a list of a half-dozen other places that are better,
and subtle suggestions about why partisans of the restaurant in
question are so misinformed.
</P>
<P>
   The level of debate is so high that finding restaurants about
which New Orleans residents actually agree is a rare thing. Yet
consensus is possible. I visited the city late in March, when warm
southern breezes were easing the region into its pleasant
pre-humidity interlude, and with friends found a handful of
restaurants that enjoy deserved local popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Another restaurant, Delmonico, is an old landmark under new
ownership, and the returns from the parishes are not yet in.
</P>
<P>
   Though regional food today is no longer confined to its home,
these restaurants could probably exist no place other than in New
Orleans, and not just because of the particular blend of Cajun and
Creole cuisines that gives the area its culinary identity.
</P>
<P>
   They are defined as much by their casual, easy pride in a
tradition that so values eating. Pretension is a rare thing, even
in the more formal, historic New Orleans establishments that cling
to old-fashioned rituals with tenacious crab claws.
</P>
<P>
   As eager as I was to join in the local debate, I found myself
following a paradoxical but sage bit of advice: ``Just close your
mouth and eat.'' Even in New Orleans, you sometimes can't argue
with what's on the plate. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Upperline
</P>
<P>
   This welcoming, intimate restaurant near the Garden District is
as idiosyncratic as a secondhand bookstore, reflecting the tastes
and interests of the owner, JoAnn Clevenger. Almost every inch of
the three small dining rooms is covered with folk art, and the
front room contains shelves of urns and pitchers, like some old
collector's attic.
</P>
<P>
   Not content with this display, Ms. Clevenger includes with her
menu a list of her favorite things, including radio stations,
antique shops, clothing stores and smells. ``Remember to be a
little silly, a little jaunty,'' she advises.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing silly about the food, though. While Richard
Benz's menu is not nearly as quirky as the dining room, it is
distinguished by the outstanding cooking and lively turn it gives
familiar Cajun and Creole dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Fried green tomatoes, a signature dish, are terrific. They are
served underneath an exceptional shrimp remoulade that achieves the
perfect ratio of sauce to shellfish. Greedy for a variety of
flavors, I ordered as an appetizer the trio of soups, which
included demitasse servings of creamy oyster stew, rich duck gumbo
and thick turtle soup, all notable for their deep, complex flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Duck is ubiquitous on New Orleans menus, but by far the best I
had was at Upperline, where it is called Tom Cowman's Famous Roast
Duck, named for a former chef who clearly had solved the problem of
cooking duck without drying it out.
</P>
<P>
   The enormous portion, a half duck, is moist and delicious,
accompanied by a superfluous sweet garlic-port sauce, sensibly
served on the side. Veal grillades, or sauteed veal scallops, are
also unusually flavorful, served in a sauce with green peppers and
mushrooms and excellent Cheddar grits.
</P>
<P>
   The wine list is not thrilling but includes some decent,
moderately priced bottles like a California pinot noir from Kent
Rasmussen ($40) that hit just the right peppery notes.
</P>
<P>
   When appetizers and main courses achieve such a high level,
desserts can often be anticlimactic, but Upperline's were as good
as everything else. Bread pudding is a classic New Orleans dessert,
and Upperline's version is delicate and deep, served with cinnamon,
nuts and caramel sauce. Creme brulee came with pralines crumbled
across the top, a sweet, satisfying combination.
</P>
<P>
   Service at Upperline is relaxed yet precise, one of many
indications that Upperline, more than halfway through its second
decade in business, is not about to coast. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peristyle
</P>
<P>
   With its casual, comfortable dining room, checkerboard terrazzo
floor and mural of City Park on one wall, Peristyle has the
deceptively unpretentious air of a neighborhood bar and grill,
belying an almost obsessive pursuit of fresh ingredients and clear,
strong flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Kearney, the chef and owner, combines the discipline of a
French kitchen with a casual New Orleans manner, making this
romantic little restaurant on the fringe of the French Quarter a
favorite of people obsessed with food and couples obsessed with
each other.
</P>
<P>
   Appetizers are wondrous, like Louisiana crab salad, a tangy
blend of crab meat and horseradish set over paper-thin slices of
chilled beets and pickled red onions. Taken as a whole, the dish
has the spicy, syncopated harmony of a jazz quintet.
</P>
<P>
   Another appetizer, a generous serving of oysters poached in a
sauce of roasted peppers, leeks and tomatoes, sounds similar hot
notes, accented with the pure flavors of fresh basil and bacon.
</P>
<P>
   The main courses don't have quite the jaunty style of the
appetizers, offering subtle luxury instead. Thick squares of
beautifully charred lamb loin are served in a sweet reduction of
red wine and garlic surrounding a layered mound of tomatoes and
zucchini, while rich, meaty squab has a lively gaminess cushioned
by a velvety sauce of red wine and foie gras.
</P>
<P>
   The well-chosen, reasonable wine list includes more than a few
choices that can match the elegance of these dishes, like one of my
favorites, a Chinon Clos du Chene Vert from Charles Joguet ($45).
</P>
<P>
   Sumptuous desserts include a beautifully textured semolina fig
cake, topped with a plump, sweet fig and served with hazelnut ice
cream, and a fine tart of pears poached in red wine set in almond
cream.
</P>
<P>
   Service at Peristyle is flawless, right up to the valet who
refused a tip for the privilege of parking my friend's restored
1963 Buick Riviera. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Brigtsen's
</P>
<P>
   In its little cottage in the Riverbend section, Brigtsen's is so
homey that you feel as if you've been welcomed to spend the night
with a great-aunt. The dining area is spread out among three small
rooms, with maybe three or four tables each, and the bright
lighting, chintz and patterned wallpaper suggest an old Midwestern
parlor, an effect enhanced by the friendly, efficient service.
</P>
<P>
   The food, though, is pure New Orleans, freshened by an
experimental approach that often works, but sometimes doesn't. An
appetizer of sauteed sweetbreads, for example, is tender and
delicious in a rich, dark mustard-flavored demi-glace, served with
roasted new potatoes, capers and shiitake mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   But a soup, called ``Backyard Crawfish Boil,'' is monochromatic,
full of crawfish and potatoes but with little flavor outside of the
thyme-scented broth. ``It's the first night we've served it,'' the
waitress explained, suggesting that it was a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't want to take a chance with the new, Frank Brigtsen,
who does almost all the cooking himself in a kitchen not much
bigger than a phone booth, keeps old reliables on the menu, like a
big, gutsy appetizer of rabbit tenderloin in a peppery mustard
sauce, served with a cylinder of Parmesan grits threaded with bits
of spicy tasso, a Cajun cured pork specialty.
</P>
<P>
   Proximity to the Gulf of Mexico gives New Orleans chefs access
to all sorts of unusual seafood that is typically labeled on menus
as ``Gulf fish,'' and that changes according to the catch.
</P>
<P>
   One night Brigtsen's was serving broiled sheep's-head fish,
mildly flavored, moist and loosely textured, crusted with crab meat
and Parmesan. The delicate white fish would have been quite good,
but it was covered in a creamy lemon mousseline, burying the
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Grilled pompano is another busy dish, served with oysters and
artichoke hearts in a bordelaise sauce. Yet this time the
beautifully cooked fish was enhanced rather than overwhelmed by the
accompaniments.
</P>
<P>
   Roast duck is crisp-skinned and tender, served with cornbread
dressing and a sweet gravy made with honey and pecans, while
Brigtsen takes a decidedly un-New Orleans turn with tasty braised
lamb shank, served in a phyllo pouch with pine nuts, rice, spinach
and feta.
</P>
<P>
   The short wine list at Brigtsen's includes some excellent,
moderately priced bottles, like a soft but spicy California syrah
from Fess Parker ($28).
</P>
<P>
   I loved the desserts, from fresh, ripe strawberries served with
zabaglione, creme fraiche and a thin slice of pound cake to an
exceptionally delicate banana bread pudding in a banana-flavored
rum sauce. But my absolute favorite was the intensely
coffee-flavored cafe-au-lait creme brulee, served warm and
crisp-topped. It's worth lying sleepless at night if only to think
about it. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Delmonico
</P>
<P>
   On the edge of the Garden District, this landmark restaurant had
closed in 1997 after a century in business, and was renovated and
reopened by Emeril Lagasse, the TV chef. Unlike Lagasse's earlier
New Orleans restaurants, Emeril's and Nola, which display his
contemporary Louisiana cuisine, Delmonico looks back, offering
formal Creole cooking almost as if it were a dying tradition in
need of protection.
</P>
<P>
   More than a few historic New Orleans restaurants continue to
serve this sort of food, though, and you can't help but wonder why
Lagasse feels the need for such self-conscious preservation.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Delmonico's hushed dining room, with solid, heavy
chairs of soft tan leather, thick linens and hefty silverware, has
a serious air about it, complete with tableside cooking and
carving. Our roguish waiter managed to lighten the atmosphere with
some welcome wisecracks, but the food showed little evidence of his
humor or flair.
</P>
<P>
   Turtle soup with sherry, typically a robust, peppery dish,
packed little punch, while fried green tomatoes with crab meat
tasted mostly of heavy breading, and had precious little crab. The
best appetizer by far was crab meat Remnick, a wonderfully savory,
peppery rice dish that blended soft textures and classically
assertive flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Main courses included some beautifully old-fashioned cooking,
like redfish sauteed in butter until it was crisp outside but still
deliciously moist within. Yet there were also mushy baked shrimp,
overwhelmed by their crab stuffing and smothered in shoestring
potatoes that seemed out of place on the plate. Country-style duck
was powerfully flavored, almost gamy, served both as sliced breast
and as confit, duck leg that has been preserved in its fat.
</P>
<P>
   I preferred the confit to the tender breast, but the best part
of the dish was the garnish of greens with ham hocks, a great
old-time combination.
</P>
<P>
   The wine list, extensive and expensive, does include some fine
mid-range bottles like a tart, dry Savennieres from Yves Tijou
($45) and a forward, easy to enjoy California pinot noir from
Sanford ($44).
</P>
<P>
   Dessert included a marvelous bread pudding and a fair bananas
Foster, the old-time New Orleans dish, which was prepared with
great panache tableside, complete with a flambe moment. But in the
end, it's just sauteed bananas over ice cream. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Commander's Palace
</P>
<P>
   When I expressed disappointment to a friend over my meal at
Delmonico, he insisted that we go to Commander's Palace in the
Garden District, where Lagasse was executive chef in the 1980s. The
old-fashioned Creole cooking that Delmonico celebrates so
ponderously is offered at Commander's with consummate grace and
ease. It's all the more noteworthy because Commander's is such a
huge operation, serving an astonishing volume of food seamlessly
and beautifully.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, the confusing complex of dining rooms that surround the
central kitchen seems slightly threadbare, and the rooms are not
shown to their best advantage in the dull lighting. But the turtle
soup here, with lots of pepper and bits of turtle, has spirit and
depth, made with a stock that doesn't just deliver flavor but soars
high before easing into a long finish.
</P>
<P>
   Duck gumbo is rich, complex and peppery. One appetizer, though,
a stew of wild mushrooms and truffles, is a bore, with little to
offer beyond the one-dimensional mushroom flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Our main courses were uniformly wonderful. Crawfish maque choux
is a robust stew served over fluffy rice with plenty of tender
crawfish, corn, okra, peppers and onions, and a dark and dense
crawfish sauce flavored with thyme. Roasted boned quail are spicy
and full of flavor, stuffed with crawfish sausage and served with a
relish of sauteed corn and jalapeno.
</P>
<P>
   The book-length wine list includes many worthy selections,
though the wine I chose, an Alsatian pinot gris from Trimbach
($37), wasn't quite hefty enough for the food.
</P>
<P>
   Commander's is famous for its bread pudding souffle, but we
sidestepped that dessert for strawberry shortcake, made with sweet
local strawberries, whipped cream and a buttermilk biscuit, the
perfect end to a rich meal. If you're after something more solid,
though, you couldn't do better than the cheesecake, made with
Creole cream cheese, a tart Louisiana product that paradoxically
manages to impart both lightness and richness. It's the kind of New
Orleans mystery that is best left unresolved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
