<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NETS HOPING TO DO WHAT KNICKS DID 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The word ``interim'' had been extracted
from Don Casey's title as if it were a bad tooth.
</P>
<P>
   He now was the Nets' coach with a three-year contract, although
only the first season's $1.1 million was guaranteed. As he talked,
Keith Van Horn and Kendall Gill sat nearby, and now Stephon
Marbury, in a sport shirt, shorts and sneakers, strolled across the
court at the Nets' complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll cost you $500,'' the coach said, alluding to the Nets'
fine for tardiness. ``And you forgot your tie.''
</P>
<P>
   Marbury laughed along with everybody else, hugged Casey, then
sat down with Van Horn and Gill, their presence showing their
support for the retention of the 62-year-old Casey, a basketball
lifer who never had a big break before.
</P>
<P>
   ``With everybody back healthy,'' Casey was saying now, ``it'll
be fun, it'll be exciting and we'll win.''
</P>
<P>
   More than ever, the Nets must win, if only to challenge the
``team across the river,'' as the Knicks are known here. After a
shortened season that began with the Nets the team to watch before
injuries depleted their roster and Coach John Calipari was fired,
the Knicks were the team that was watched throughout seven weeks of
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   And in conversations during Casey's coronation Monday, the
Knicks' success in getting to the National Basketball Association
finals intruded every so often.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Rowe, the Nets' president, even called the Knicks ``my
second-favorite team,'' and Willis Reed, a Nets senior vice
president, joked about his former favorite team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I wasn't working for the Nets, I would've gotten one of my
old Knick uniforms and limped out on the Garden court before a game
last week,'' Reed said, thinking of when he did just that as the
Knicks' captain before they routed the Lakers in the seventh game
of the 1970 finals. ``But I don't think my Nets bosses would have
appreciated that.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Knicks' seven weeks of playoffs, the Nets were
watching and learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned that anything is possible,'' Gill said. ``What the
Knicks did with Patrick hurt was amazing. And if Patrick could've
played in the final, I think they would've won it.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing would presumably agree that the Knicks would have
won the title with him at center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to play, that's it,'' Ewing said Sunday, looking to
next season. ``My role is not going to change. I have a lot of
great players on my team; we just have to believe in each other and
play.''
</P>
<P>
   What has to change, of course, is Ewing's health: a damaged and
eventually partly torn Achilles' tendon this season, a shattered
wrist the year before. And at age 37 next season, what will go
next?
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we have just as much talent as the Knicks,'' Gill
added. ``We just have to keep everybody healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with Jayson Williams, the rebounder whose slow
recovery from a broken right leg might prevent him from starting
the season at full speed and full strength. But Van Horn's broken
left thumb has healed; a free agent after next season, he's hoping
to hit the NBA salary ceiling of $72 million over six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do what the Knicks did,'' Van Horn said. ``We have the
talent. We just have to put it together.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn, a 6-foot-10-inch forward who averaged 21.8 points and
8.5 rebounds last season, acknowledged that the champion Spurs are
unique in having two 7-footers as dominating and determined as Tim
Duncan and David Robinson, but there's no other obvious challenger.
Not even the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel we missed out on something,'' Van Horn said. ``Watching
the Knicks built a fire under me, and I hope it did for my
teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Nets were a sad 16-34 last season, including an
improved 13-17 after Casey took command, Marbury remembered that
the Spurs struggled to a 6-8 start before streaking through the
rest of the schedule and the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't chase the ring,'' Marbury said. ``You have to really
work for it. It takes hard work. It takes effort. It takes luck. We
have a great situation now. We're young. We're talented and we're
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets are happy because Don Casey is their coach, but in the
NBA, happiness isn't everything. The team across the river proved
that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
