<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKUD DECIDES NOT TO JOIN A COALITION LED BY BARAK
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The rightist Likud Party withdrew Monday from
coalition talks with Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak, announcing
that it would not join his government and was headed for the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The move defined the contours of Barak's emerging coalition as
he negotiated into the night with Shas, an ultra-Orthodox party of
Sephardic Jews that is the third-largest faction in Parliament and
a likely key partner in the new government.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who won a resounding victory over Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu as the Labor Party candidate in the election on May 17,
has already reached coalition agreements with three parties. An
accord with Shas, along with expected agreements with three more
parties, would give Barak a 77-seat majority in the 120-member
Parliament. He has until July 8 to form a government.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of talks with Likud came amid reports that Barak
had decided instead on a deal with Shas, whose relatively dovish
positions on peace talks and territorial compromise with the
Palestinians contrast with Likud's harder line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry to say that the partnership offered us was not a
true partnership,'' Ariel Sharon, the acting head of Likud, said
after a five-minute meeting Monday with Barak. ``We don't see a
possibility of entering the government. We will fight this
government from the opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon cited disagreements over a withdrawal from the Golan
Heights as part of a peace deal with Syria, and over construction
of housing for Jews in Arab areas of East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Barak's One Israel bloc reportedly objected to the
inclusion of Likud in the government on the grounds that its
hawkish positions would hamper peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition agreements already signed by Barak have signaled a
change in domestic priorities, removing two key ministries from the
control of religious parties.
</P>
<P>
   The Education Ministry, controlled for years by the National
Religious Party, was assigned to Yossi Sarid, head of the leftist
and secular Meretz Party. The ministry has the second largest
budget after the Defense Ministry, and Barak has promised to make
education one of the highest priorities of his administration.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Ministry, controlled by Shas for the last 15 years,
was assigned to a Natan Sharansky, the leader of the Russian
immigrant party, Yisrael Ba'Aliya. The party had demanded control
of the ministry, which registers immigrants as Jews and awards them
Israeli citizenship. Under the stewardship of Shas, the ministry
has questioned the Judaism of many of the new arrivals, refusing to
register them as Jews and even deporting some of them.
</P>
<P>
   Although Shas has been stripped of the Interior Ministry, it is
expected to be awarded four ministries in Barak's coalition. Meretz
originally opposed the inclusion of Shas after the party's leader,
Aryeh Deri, was convicted and sentenced to jail for bribery. But
Deri has since stepped down, and leaders of Meretz indicated Monday
that they no longer ruled out serving in a coalition with Shas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
