u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CHAOS-FOR-A-DAY-AR     06-28 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHAOS-FOR-A-DAY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TIMES SQUARE GRIDLOCK, IT'S NOT THE HEAT, IT'S THE CELEBRITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: 2nd take should move within 30 minutes.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some 113 years ago, when the Statue of Liberty began
advertising New York's affection for huddled masses, probably no
one envisioned just how much of a multitude might show up one muggy
day in midtown, or that so many of them would come carrying cameras
by car or stretch limo.
</P>
<P>
   But that is what happened Monday as a confluence of cultural,
political and gustatory events in Times Square made it truly seem
like the crossroads of the world, or at least its most
celebrity-studded corner.
</P>
<P>
   There was starlock at the premiere of Spike Lee's new movie,
``Summer of Sam,'' with craning fans packed in six deep on West
44th Street.
</P>
<P>
   There was squealing inside the Official All-Star Cafe, at
Broadway and 45th Street, as Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter and
several of his teammates held a benefit for children.
</P>
<P>
   As for 46th Street, it was entirely closed for a two-block
stretch between Ninth Avenue and Broadway as some 12,000 people
came to sample the fare of three dozen restaurants at the annual
Taste of Times Square street festival.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh yes, one block away, President Clinton and some
corporate heavy hitters attended a special matinee performance of
the ``The Iceman Cometh'' at the Brooks Atkinson Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just another day in Times Square,'' sighed Brendan Sexton,
head of the Times Square Business Improvement District, one of
several officials who pretended to be unfazed by the idea that a
single section of the city, over four hours, had hosted enough
special events to entertain another municipality for a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing like this,'' said Edward Hanrahan, of
Chesapeake, Va., who stood with his wife and seven children on a
storefront window ledge, trying to catch a glimpse of stars like
Jennifer Lopez as they headed into Lee's movie, which premiered at
7 p.m. ``We have Octoberfest. We have Harborfest. We have stars
coming in once in awhile. But not like this. This is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   The menu of events would have been even longer, but the
incendiary Ricky Martin, a singer whose performance outside
Rockefeller Center drew thousands of frenzied fans earlier this
month, canceled an appearance on the Late Show with David
Letterman.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the panoply of events and moments of pandemonium were
such that hardly anyone noticed a crew filming an episode of the
television show ``Law and Order'' on Ninth Avenue. And the 130
people who packed Broadway outside the 45th Street studios of MTV
to scream at their favorite personalities seemed like a small
sideshow.
</P>
<P>
   As exciting as it was for some, it was not a day to drive a car
or to be caught in the crush on a Times Square sidewalk, where the
sweltering temperatures and honking horns turned a trip for a
sandwich into an urban endurance test.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really inconvenient and really unsafe,'' offered Bill
Kavanah, an operations manager for the city's Off-Track Betting
Corp. as he tried to navigate West 44th Street. ``I remember when
we had the muggers and the pimps. It was dangerous, but it wasn't
like having some tourist push you in front of a bus.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who arrived at 3 p.m., carried most of the blame for
the traffic mess. His visit forced the closing of 42nd Street and
Eighth Avenue for a portion of the afternoon and a stretch of 47th
Street for the entire day.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
