<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL PARKS MAY BE ROOMIER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those eager to see national-park attractions they have been
reluctant to tackle, from Old Faithful at Yellowstone to the
Grinnell Glacier at Glacier Park, from the Sequoias in California
to Acadia in Maine, this is a particularly fortunate year. Getting
in may be less of a problem than in past years.
</P>
<P>
   The national park system, after years of increases in numbers of
visitors, expects a leveling-off this year, to a mere 286.6
million, virtually the same as in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The head of Amfac Parks and Resorts of Colorado, which operates
the lodges at the Grand Canyon as well as in Everglades and other
popular national parks, says this flat rate _ and an already
apparent drop in visits to parks in the Southwest _ is due to a
decline in tourists from Asia, to a perception that the parks are
overcrowded, and possibly to confusion about future changes in
automobile access at the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 percent of park visitors are from other countries, and
these travelers are a function of the American economy, said David
Barna, a spokesman for the National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not a cheap visit anymore,'' he said, and that is what
tourists are seeking at a time of recession in Asia and economic
problems in northern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign visitors have always focused on the best-known national
parks. As Barna said, when tour organizers try to tell foreigners
that the less-crowded parks might be interesting or fun, they
usually respond: ``When you come to Paris, you do not want to go
see other towers. you want to see the Eiffel Tower.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus the drop in international visitors is most affecting the
iconic parks: Grand Canyon, Yellowstone, Yosemite. Grand Canyon
recorded 5 million visitors in 1997; that figure dropped 11 percent
in 1998 and is expected to fall another 6 percent this year, to
under 4.2 million. Yellowstone is expected to drop 3.5 percent this
year, and Yosemite 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Not every park will be gasping for business, because in many
places the pressure is still climbing. But a burst of repairs and
additions to hotels, coupled with slowed demand, meant that late in
June, reservations at the major park hotels were still showing an
average of 10 percent availability for July and August.
</P>
<P>
   That softness does not apply to campsite reservations. The
company that handles phone and Internet camping and
recreational-vehicle reservations at the busiest parks said that
reservations were holding steady against last year. One sales
representative said that campgrounds wouldn't be hit by a fall in
foreign tourists because they are usually booked into park hotels
rather than campgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a roundup of changes in national parks this year,
including a report on the impact of fires at Joshua Tree National
Park in California. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yellowstone's New Rooms
</P>
<P>
   The Old Faithful Snow Lodge, within walking distance of Old
Faithful geyser, is an important addition to visitor housing at
Yellowstone, the first national park. Half of the 100 rooms opened
a year ago, and the other half this May, when the hotel was
dedicated.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing a building originally intended as employee housing, it
was built by Amfac, the concessionaire, and the Park Service, using
recycled timbers and low-energy fixtures. The architecture is in
the style used for the early lodges in the parks. Like Mammoth Hot
Springs Hotel in Yellowstone, the Snow Lodge is also open for a
midwinter season. Rooms range from $101 to $141 a night.
</P>
<P>
   Dunraven Lodge, near the Yellowstone Grand Canyon, is even
newer, having opened June 14. The 44 rooms, all with private bath,
replace cabins built in the 1960s. Rates are $105 a night, double
or single.
</P>
<P>
   A restaurant at the registration area serves the Dunraven and
the Cascade Lodge and nearby cabins. Reservations at Yellowstone
may be made at (307) 344-7311 or on the Web at
www.travelyellowstone.com.
</P>
<P>
   At Sequoia National Park in the Sierra Nevada of California, the
concessionaire, Delaware North Parks Services, has opened the new
Wuksachi Lodge. This year-round hotel, with 102 rooms with private
baths, opened on Memorial Day weekend. Some rooms have sitting-room
areas with sliding doors and convertible sofas, attractive to
families.
</P>
<P>
   The rates are $110 to $155 in the peak season. The Wuksachi has
a restaurant on the premises that is available to day visitors as
well as guests. Reservations: (888) 252-5757.
</P>
<P>
   The Wuksachi and the smaller John Muir Lodge in adjoining Kings
Canyon National Park provide lodging to replace 200 old cabins,
lodges and shops that are being removed from the Giant
Forest-Lodgepole area under a 1980 park development plan. The John
Muir has 30 rooms, 6 of them suites, all with baths, with rates
starting at $125 a night for the standard rooms.
</P>
<P>
   There is no restaurant in this small lodge; guests can take
meals in the restaurant that serves all lodges in the Grant Grove
area. Reservations: Kings Canyon Park Services, (559) 335-5500. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grand Canyon Plans
</P>
<P>
   Completion of a new transportation system for Grand Canyon
National Park is still some time off, although ground was broken
this spring for the new Canyon View information plaza. The goal, as
with many other long-term national park plans, is to reduce the
number of private cars by offering other choices that are less
damaging to the environment and the air quality.
</P>
<P>
   By 2002, according to Sandra Perl in the park office, a six-mile
light-rail transit system will link a parking lot at Tusayan,
outside the south park entrance, to the new information plaza near
Mather Point.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   From there, visitors will be able to board shuttles running on
an alternative fuel, ride a bicycle (they will be available for
rent) or a wheelchair, push a stroller or walk to the Greenway
along the north and south rims.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Hillary Rodham Clinton visited the Grand Canyon park to
inaugurate work on the Greenway, which covers 73 miles. The
information plaza is scheduled to be finished in September 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But when this is all done, park officials and Amfac point out,
people with reservations in the lodges will still be able to take
their cars into the park, either directly to lodges that are away
from the rim, or to parking lots where shuttles will pick up guests
for the lodges at the rim. At the moment, autombile access
continues as before.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Canyon lodge reservations are available at (303) 297-2757,
or at www.amfac.com. Some specials for the Grand Canyon were posted
on the site in mid-June. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aftermath of Wildfires
</P>
<P>
   Four wildfires at Joshua Tree, set by lightning, consumed 13,000
acres in 96 hours in late May, according to Ernest Quintana, the
superintendent. ``Parts of the park may look a bit scruffy for a
while,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the areas closed while the fire was fought were reopened
by Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Zarki, the chief of interpretation, said that most visitors
to Joshua Tree in late June were from overseas and that his staff
was making every effort to explain about the fire and the Park
Service's new policy on handling wildfires, which emphasizes
techniques that are ``light on the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Things are moving along in East Coast parks, too. North
Carolina's Cape Hatteras Lighthouse began a 2,900-foot journey back
from the ocean in mid-June. It will take at least six weeks to get
the lighthouse, 4,800 tons of it, onto steel tracks and over to a
new, safer spot, where it will be lowered onto a new foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The lighthouse will be closed to visitors, but the process will
be visible through frequently replenished pictures at
www.nsp.gov/caha/lrp.htm. The Park Service hopes to have the
lighthouse open again by next Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   At Acadia National Park in Maine, a propane-powered bus system
began its first summer of free runs two weeks ago, making circuits
of the park with calls at the Bar Harbor airport, motels and ferry
landings.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have visited the main section of Acadia, on Mount
Desert Island, know that automobile traffic is a bane. The
procession through the park dissipates pleasure in the
surroundings. If you can find a parking spot in Bar Harbor, the
main town, it is difficult to avoid a parking ticket because the
limit is two hours.
</P>
<P>
   The bus system, called the Island Explorer, will operate eight
vehicles on six routes every day until Sept. 6. Each bus can carry
28 passengers and 5 bicycles. For bike riders, being able to get
into the park with their bikes means that they need not pedal the
whole 20-mile loop at once, but can get in and pick the route they
want.
</P>
<P>
   Hikers, too, can pick up another bus to leave the park. Campers
using Blackwoods Campground will get from Bar Harbor Airport to the
campground in an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen agencies, including the state and federal Departments of
Transportation, and several towns in the area contributed to the
Island Explorer project. The buses are operated by Downeast
Transportation, a local nonprofit bus company.
</P>
<P>
   A Free Acadia Shuttles flier will be available at hotels, shops,
the airport, ferry terminals and elsewhere. Information: (207)
667-5796. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reserving Campsites &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reservations for camping in the most popular national park areas
are handled separately from lodge reservations, by a company under
contract to the government, Biospherics in Beltsville, Md. Here are
the phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   For Yosemite in California, reservations open on the 15th of
each month for camping up to five months later; call (800)
436-7275.
</P>
<P>
   For the following parks, reservations open the 5th of each month
for camping up to five months later; call (800) 365-2267: Acadia in
Maine, Assateague in Maryland and Virginia, Cape Hatteras in North
Carolina, Channel Islands in California, Chickasaw in Oklahoma,
Death Valley in California, Everglades in Florida, Glacier in
Montana, Grand Canyon in Arizona, Great Smoky Mountains in
Tennessee and North Carolina, Greenbelt in Maryland, Gulf Islands
in Florida and Mississippi, Joshua Tree in California, Katmai in
Alaska, Mount Rainier in Washington, Rocky Mountain in Colorado,
Sequoia-Kings Canyon in California, Sleeping Bear Dunes in
Michigan, Shenandoah in Virginia, Whiskeytown in California and
Zion in Utah.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
