<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MASSACRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL ILLUMINATES '68 MASSACRE IN MEXICO
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ For three decades, one of Mexico's most explosive
secrets has been the identity of the snipers who carried out the
country's worst massacre since the 1910 Revolution, firing machine
guns from rooftops into a crowd of peaceful protesters on the eve
of the 1968 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Now newly published documents, signed by the general who was
Mexico's defense minister at the time, appear to have cleared up
the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The snipers were plainclothes members of the Presidential
General Staff, an elite army unit that protects Mexican presidents,
according to the documents, written and signed by Gen. Marcelino
Garcia Barragan. The documents suggest that the orders for the
snipers to shoot on the crowd were issued by President Gustavo Diaz
Ordaz.
</P>
<P>
   One mystery that remains is how many snipers there were. The
documents refer to at least 10 and previous documents said scores
of suspected snipers had been arrested. No one was ever charged.
</P>
<P>
   Successive Mexican governments have always blamed the
demonstrators for the violence. The government originally said that
29 people died in the bloodshed at the Plaza of Three Cultures, a
broad courtyard surrounded by high-rise buildings in the Tlatelolco
housing complex in downtown Mexico City, but others put the count
far higher. An American diplomat at the time estimated that nearly
200 died.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, a consensus formed among historians that the
government had orchestrated the violence to justify a broader
crackdown on protesters, who were considered an embarrassment
before the 1968 Olympics. But never before have documents,
originating within the government elite, detailed so explicitly who
issued the orders and who carried them out.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia Barragan died in 1979. He wrote the documents as a kind
of memoir in the years after the 1968 massacre. One, which he
penned in his own hand as a letter to his son, was titled ``The
Truth for History.''
</P>
<P>
   The documents are published in a forthcoming book, ``Parte de
Guerra. Tlatelolco 1968'' or ``war report,'' written by Julio
Scherer Garcia and Carlos Monsivais, both prominent intellectuals.
Garcia Barragan's family shared the documents with Scherer.
</P>
<P>
   ``These documents are of extraordinary importance, because they
fill one of the largest gaps in our knowledge of the 1968
violence,'' Sergio Aguayo, a historian who wrote a 1998 book on the
massacre, said Monday ``This is the first time that the identity of
the snipers has been confirmed with documents from within the
military.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the documents refer to conversations that Garcia
Barragan had the night of the violence, Oct. 2, 1968, with Gen.
Crisoforo Mazon Pineda, the commander of a Mexico City army brigade
whose troops had been sent to the protest rally at Tlatelolco and
came under fire from rooftop snipers, some of whom were arrested
and identified themselves as soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Another conversation was with Gen. Luis Gutierrez Oropeza,
commander of the Presidential General Staff, who worked directly
for Diaz Ordaz.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 7 or 8 p.m., Gen. Crisoforo Mazon Pineda asked me for
authorization to search the apartments from which the snipers were
still firing on the troops,'' Garcia Barragan wrote in one of the
documents. ``The authorization was given. Only 15 minutes had gone
by when I received a call from Gen. Oropeza, commander of the
Presidential General Staff, who said to me, `My general, I put
officers armed with machine guns to shoot on the students. All of
them succeeded in getting out of there, only two were unable to get
away. They're in civilian clothes, I'm afraid for their lives.
Don't you want to order that their lives be respected?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why didn't you inform me about the officers you're referring
to?'' Garcia Barragan said he asked Oropeza.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because those were my orders, my general,'' Oropeza replied,
according to the documents.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview published Monday in the newspaper Reforma,
Oropeza, who is 80, denied any responsibility for the 1968
massacre. ``I worked directly for President Diaz Ordaz,'' he said.
``I had nothing to do with that Oct. 2 mess.''
</P>
<P>
   In another document, Garcia Barragan refers to ``terrorists''
who had fired their weapons earlier in 1968, during street
demonstrations protesting the army's takeover of the National
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those terrorists were officers of the Presidential General
Staff who received training for that type of operation,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   A week before the massacre, officers of the Presidential General
Staff rented apartments in the buildings surrounding the Plaza of
Three Cultures to use as machine gun nests, Garcia Barragan wrote.
</P>
<P>
   A smiling Diaz Ordaz once told Oropeza that Garcia Barragan
appeared, naively, to believe that Oropeza had issued unilateral
orders for the snipers to shoot on the crowd, without the
president's knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never tell,'' Oropeza said he told the president in a
later recounting of the incident to a military colleague, who in
turn told Garcia Barragan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
