<HEADER>
A2561 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DAYTON-VIOLATIONS     06-28 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DAYTON-VIOLATIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dayton awaits NCAA recommendation on violations
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ University of Dayton athletics director Ted
Kissell said Monday it will probably be mid-July before the school
learns whether the NCAA recommends that violations involving its
men's basketball program are major or minor.
</P>
<P>
   UD officials had hoped to hear from the NCAA enforcement staff
this month on whether it believes improper loans by UD trustee and
booster Clayton L. Mathile to the father of a top recruit are
considered a major infraction. But Kissell said delays have
resulted, in part, because NCAA officials are in the midst of a
move from Kansas to their new offices in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The delay) is not anything that reflects that the process has
become more complex,'' Kissell said.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said a recent report in the Dayton Daily News about
a truck lease to Brooks Hall from UD booster Frank Z Chevrolet
``raised issues'' that the NCAA asked the university to look into.
Kissell said that inquiry took additional time but, ``There is no
reason to believe that there is any impropriety with the lease. And
we have reported that to NCAA enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   The university first announced in April that it had
self-reported two violations, which it considered ``secondary'' or
minor, to the NCAA in December: the two loans from Mathile to Chuck
Hall, father of UD recruit Brooks Hall of Troy; and ``impermissible
contact'' between Chuck Hall and Mathile. The NCAA then launched
its own investigation, which has included visits to Dayton to
conduct interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Kissell said a report in the Dayton Daily News about how Hall
repaid the loan _ through an unusual second mortgage worth $32,000
from KeyBank, where UD trustee Mervyn L. Alphonso is the Dayton
district president _ has not slowed the NCAA's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That repayment had already been part of the self-report,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kissell said to his knowledge the NCAA ``has not alleged any
further violations'' other than the two the university originally
reported. But he said the university won't know all of the details
until the enforcement staff completes the process.
</P>
<P>
   Kissell said Brooks Hall remains eligible to play for UD next
season and unless the NCAA ``finds something new,'' that shouldn't
change.
</P>
<P>
   If the enforcement staff decided that a major infraction has
occurred, UD could be notified informally or through an Official
Letter of Inquiry, according to NCAA enforcement director Chuck
Smrt. The official letter would outline the NCAA's allegations and
the university would be invited to respond. If school officials
disagreed with the allegations, they could appear before the
Committee on Infractions, which rules on the enforcement staff's
recommendation and metes out punishment.
</P>
<P>
   If UD officials agreed with the NCAA enforcement staff's
conclusions, they could avoid the Infractions Committee hearing and
go straight to the sanctions phase.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Vinella writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2563 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CHAOS-FOR-A-DAY-AR     06-28 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHAOS-FOR-A-DAY-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: entire day.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``This is a pain in the neck,'' said Walter Angulo, 29, of On
Time Delivery Services, who was having a hard time keeping his
company's promise as he waited 20 minutes in his van on West 44th
Street for the president's motorcade to pass. ``I can't even cross
Eighth Avenue to drop off my work.''
</P>
<P>
   Angulo was among the hundreds who converted the side streets
into a sea of cell phones, as they related their delays to
superiors. City officials say crosstown traffic speeds are
improving, but Monday afternoon the traffic flow could still be
measured in snail time.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was difficult to accurately calculate the traffic
volumes, Joan Eisman, a painter from Brooklyn, had fashioned her
own sort of measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep trying to see things that I was seeing the other day
and you can't see them,'' she said, peering north from an island in
the middle of Broadway to adjust her painting of the square. ``The
traffic lights used to give you a clear view every seven and a half
minutes. Not today.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Littler, general manager of the Millennium Broadway
Hotel on West 44th Street, noted the one silver lining to a Times
Square traffic jam.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least the people stuck in the cars have something to
watch,'' he said, ``like the signs and all the people, ranging from
sober-suited business people like me to people with purple hair and
most parts of their body pierced with something.''
</P>
<P>
   Littler's business is among those affected when the streets
become parking lots. But Monday he displayed that classic New York
what-me-worry attitude, realizing perhaps as a hotelier that many
of the hassles were signs of a city in renewal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disruption in the area is part of the pattern of what
Times Square is all about,'' he said. ``There is nothing
predictable about the area except that it is unpredictable and
busy.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officials also took the day's travails in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no nightmare,'' said Chief Allan H. Hoehl, the
commander of police in southern Manhattan who directs everything
from ticker tape parades to the ball-drop on New Year's Eve. ``It's
all part of the informal entertainment of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For the police, the primary focus was the president, who was in
town to raise money for Democratic congressional campaigns. After
the benefit performance at the theater, Clinton moved down the
street by foot to the Supper Club where a second fund-raiser was
held. Outside, in the middle of 47th Street, one officer
entertained the crowd on a megaphone, trying to convince them to
clear the street as he ticked off the many parades and events that
had been staged in midtown in just the past three days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to New York City,'' he concluded. ``This is just a
typical day here.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercifully, it was a dark day for Broadway theaters, or the
crowds would have been more fearsome. Indeed, the sponsors of the
food festival on West 46th Street had picked the date a year ago
knowing there was no chance their guests would be trampled by
people with Playbills. Then, 10 days ago, word began to drift in
about other events. The Times Square Business Improvement District
planners put together a memo listing the lineup of the events
(their longest ever), and sent it to all the building managers and
hotels in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to plan and then plan for the unplanned,'' said
Sexton. ``The president usually does not call us up to check before
he drops by.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   If they all seemed a bit blase at the improvement district,
Sexton said it was because it is hard to speak in superlatives when
it comes to a place of true history like Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will anything ever equal VJ day?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
