<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2567 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-MUSIC-NYT &LR;      06-28 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACT REACHED ON DOWNLOADING OF DIGITAL MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS and MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After months of struggle over the future of music distribution,
the music and electronics industries announced an agreement Monday
that will enable electronics makers to begin mass production of
portable digital music players while technology to protect against
piracy is still being developed.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement gives the record industry what it wanted in the
long run: a standard that will ultimately prevent the playing of
illegally duplicated music on digital devices. But in the short
run, it has agreed to the manufacture of devices capable of playing
pirated music.
</P>
<P>
   The recording industry was under heavy pressure from the
electronics industry to come up with a standard by June 30, in time
to get portable devices into stores by Christmas. And record
companies themselves, responding to a grass-roots boom in the
digital distribution of music over the Internet, had announced a
flurry of deals in recent months intended to grab a share of the
digital market.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's announcement came from a consortium called the Secure
Digital Music Initiative, representing more than 100 companies from
the recording, home electronics and technology industries
worldwide. It said the agreement would be submitted for
ratification at a meeting in Los Angeles next week.
</P>
<P>
   Record industry officials said they had grudgingly acceded to
the standard. Cary Sherman, general counsel for the Recording
Industry Association of America, the trade group representing the
industry, called it ``a substantial compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's also premised on a reality,'' he said. ``The reality
is that a collaborative approach working with the tech industry to
appeal to consumers is the greatest business opportunity for
everyone.'' Several electronics manufacturers intend to begin
production of portable devices based on the standard, which could
become as ubiquitous as cassette-based portable players.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman said the recording industry had to concede that the
market is demanding such devices _ specifically players capable of
recording and playing popular MP3 files, which are not copyright
protected. He said the recording industry calculated that it would
pay to cooperate with electronics manufacturers in exchange for
more secure distribution in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The standard, devised by a working group that has met several
times a month, is to be carried out in two phases. In the first
phase, devices complying with the standard will be permitted to
play any type of file, whether or not it is illegally copied.
</P>
<P>
   But the devices must include technology that will permit them to
be modified once anti-piracy technology is ready, probably in the
form of a digital watermark embedded in legitimate digital
recordings, whether distributed on CD or over the Internet. Once
that second phase takes effect _ probably not for 18 months _ users
will be asked to ``upgrade'' the players to enable them to play
legitimately copied music that has been recorded under the new
system.
</P>
<P>
   There is one catch. The recording industry conceded that even
once the anti-piracy technology is in place, devices using the
approved standard will not be able to block out illegal copies of
songs already recorded.
</P>
<P>
   This means that millions of CDs already in existence can be
loaded onto computers, uploaded onto the Internet and traded, and
downloaded onto portable players _ even if the recipient has not
paid for a licensed copy.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Sherman said, record companies will forgo hefty
potential revenues. ``For some companies we're talking about giving
away a musical heritage,'' said Sherman. ``Think about Elvis, think
about the Beatles _ we're talking about giving away the catalog.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the first meetings of the consortium in January, there has
been heavy debate between technology companies, which want to
develop products that will be easy for consumers to use; record
companies, which originally wanted to make products that would not
be compatible with existing digital music formats like MP3, which
has no safeguards against piracy; and digital music users, who have
built a music playground on MP3. For Monday's agreement to work,
participants in the meetings say, these three parties need to be
willing to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Samit, the senior vice president of EMI (with a catalog that
includes the Beatles, the Beach Boys and the Rolling Stones), said
that the label planned to have ``as much music as is humanly
possible'' available in approved digital form by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers of portable electronics were more cautious. ``We
are preparing our future products to be compliant, but it would be
premature to say that they definitely will be because we need to
see the final specifications and ratify them first,'' said Chris
Smith, the program manager at Creative Labs, which already has a
digital music player on the market, the Nomad.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the recording industry association sued to stop sales
of another portable digital music player, the Rio, asserting that
it did not comply with the Digital Home Recording Act. A federal
court dismissed the lawsuit two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Rio's manufacturer, Diamond Multimedia, which has sold more
than 100,000 of the devices, said it intended to comply with
Monday's agreement and that the standard should ultimately be good
for business.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a customer and had to choose between compliant and
noncompliant devices, I'd definitely choose the compliant one,''
said Lorraine Comstock, a company spokeswoman. She said the company
planned a new portable player that will record and play both
existing MP3 music and files complying with the new standard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
