<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- June 28, 1999 -- IMMIG-EMERGENCY-CARE, 6-28
-- Dr. Lewis Goldfrank, chief of emergency services at Bellvue
Hospital, in his emergency room on Monday. City hospitals in New
York, Chicago and Miami are encountering an increasing number of
what is known as medical immigrants, foreigners who arrive from
usually Third World countries seeking treatment at the emergency
rooms of city hospitals. In commenting about treating a patient
suspected of being a medical immigrant, Goldfrank says that his
main responsibility as a doctor is to treat a patient, not ask
about his background. (Nancy Siesel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) IZBICE, Yugoslavia -- June 28, 1999 -- KOSOVO-GRAVES-2,
6-28 -- Ethnic Albanians Zeqir Krasniqi and his wife Farije, who
fear that relatives and friends who lived in the village have been
killed by Serbs, watch as members of a French forensic team look
for evidence in a field suspected of having been used as a mass
grave on Monday. The team, working for the International War Crimes
Tribunal, said Serb forces had buried in the area 160 victims of a
massacre in March but found that the bodies had been dug up. The
team leader said that plenty of evidence remained despite the
bodies having been removed. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) GRACANICA, Yugoslavia -- June 28, 1999 --
KOSOVO-ANNIVERSARY-FLOATER, 6-28 -- A Serbian Orthodox nun at the
Gracanica Monastary lights candles on Monday to mark the 610th
anniversary of the Serb's epic battle in 1389 against Ottoman Turks
near Pristina. The Serb defeat, followed by 500 years of Turkish
domination, has taken on mythological symbolism over the centuries
as the foundation of Serb nationalism. (Alan Chin/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) IZBICE, Yugoslavia -- June 28, 1999 -- KOSOVO-GRAVES,
6-28 -- Members of a French forensic team working for the
International War Crimes Tribunal carry bags containing what they
believe is evidence that a mass grave existed here on Monday. The
team said Serb forces had buried in the area some 160 victims of a
massacre in March but found that the bodies had been dug up. The
team leader said that plenty of evidence remained however despite
the bodies being removed. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
LITE
