<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2569 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QWEST-FRONTIER-NYT     06-28 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QWEST-FRONTIER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE MOUNTS AS FRONTIER WEIGHS QWEST BID
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Frontier Corp., one of the nation's largest
long-distance telephone companies, said Monday that it was
continuing to evaluate the unsolicited offer made two weeks ago by
Qwest Communications International.
</P>
<P>
   Frontier did not say when it would make a decision about the
offer. But there was speculation last week that Frontier's
directors would decide at Monday's regularly scheduled meeting
whether Qwest's recently revised offer was attractive enough for
the company to discuss a merger with Qwest.
</P>
<P>
   On June 13, Qwest said that it was making unsolicited offers
then valued at $55 billion for both Frontier and U S West, the
smallest of the regional Bell companies. Both companies have
already agreed to be acquired by Global Crossing Ltd., the
Bermuda-based telecommunications upstart, which agreed to buy
Frontier in March and U S West in May.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of their agreements, the boards of Frontier and
U S West have to decide whether Qwest's offer is superior to
Global's before they can share financial information with Qwest. U
S West's board is expected to meet this week.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the two companies have reaffirmed their
commitment to the Global Crossing deal, saying they would take no
action on Qwest's offers. As a result, Qwest revised its bid on
Wednesday, raising the price and adding a price protection in the
event Qwest's stock price drops. That was necessary, people close
to the talks said, when Qwest's stock plummeted 24 percent the day
after it was announced and investors panned the combination.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing is offering Frontier shareholders $63 a share in
Global stock and U S West stockholders about $60 a share in stock.
Qwest is offering Frontier shareholders $68 in stock and cash and U
S West shareholders $69 in stock or cash. But there are several
issues both boards will have to consider besides price, including
regulatory risks, the deal's structure and the strategic rationale
of the combinations.
</P>
<P>
   Frontier also announced Monday that its second quarter and 1999
revenue and earnings results would fall short of analysts'
expectations because of lower prices for long-distance phone
service. Frontier said it expected to earn 20 to 22 cents a share
in the second quarter and about $1 for the full year. Frontier was
previously expected to earn 28 cents a share for the quarter and
$1.19 for the year, the average estimates of analysts polled by the
First Call Corp., which tracks company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, a report on CNBC indicated that Frontier
could be blaming Qwest, in part, for the current earnings
shortfall. Qwest is helping build Frontier's network and there were
delays last year. But Rolla Huff, Frontier's president and chief
operating officer, dispelled that notion, saying, ``The thing that
has affected earnings is the long-distance market over all.'' The
earnings shortfall is not expected to affect the merger agreement
with Global Crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest said it would not revise its offer based on Monday's news,
asking Frontier for a ``prompt affirmation so we can proceed
together. Time, of course, is of the essence to us and the Frontier
shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Since announcing its hostile offer, it seems Qwest has had to
deal with such market rumors or comments almost every day. On
Thursday, for instance, a report by Bloomberg News quoted Reed
Hundt, former chairman of the Federal Communications Commission,
saying that a combination between Qwest and U S West ``would take
an exceedingly long time to travel the regulatory minefield and it
may well blow up trying.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Joseph Nacchio, Qwest's chief executive, sent a
letter to Solomon Trujillo, U S West chief executive, saying, there
were ``no minefields'' and indicating that any regulatory concerns
could be addressed in a timely fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Nacchio spent Monday in New York, attending meetings with
investors to gain further support for his bids.
</P>
<P>
   But he has already sent a letter to investors that he would
consider a hostile battle or other alternatives in his quest for
Frontier and U S West.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
