<SLUG> BC-SOC-WCUP-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McMILLAN'S MISSILE OF A SHOT DEFIES GRAVITY  
(jt) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. _ The ball rocketed off Shannon MacMillan's right
foot from 19 yards out as it always does, sharply and with biting
movement, diving nastily and finally short-hopping into the North
Korean goal on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   There was only the smallest available room between Kye Yong Sun
and the left post, but goalkeepers, unlike catchers, have no such
thing as bigger mitts to handle a knuckleball. Kye did what she
could, but she grabbed only a fistful of air with a flailing dive.
At the other end of the field, Briana Scurry felt elation for her
team and sympathy for a fellow goalie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate it,'' she said of MacMillan's shot. ``The ball moves
around. It knuckles and dips. She hits it harder than anyone on the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans won, 3-0, as MacMillan also assisted on a pair of
acrobatic headers by Tisha Venturini. But this start was only to
give another teammate a breather. When the Americans play in the
quarterfinals of the Women's World Cup on Thursday against Germany,
MacMillan and her knuckleball will return to the bullpen, available
as a closer or in middle relief. Meanwhile Coach Tony DiCicco is
struggling to explain why she isn't always in the starting
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   This is what passes for controversy on a team that has scored 13
goals in three matches, while surrendering only 1. DiCicco sees no
need to fix something that does not appear to be broken. He prefers
to start Cindy Parlow, who, at 5 feet 11 inches, is the tallest
player on the team and who provides an inviting target for holding
the ball and dishing it to the slashing forwards, Mia Hamm and
Tiffeny Milbrett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel Shannon is starter material,'' DiCicco said. ``I'm
looking for the combination that fits the best.''
</P>
<P>
   As the tournament enters the knockout phase, there is little
margin for error. MacMillan is faster than Parlow and plays a more
vibrant, cheeky game. She led the Americans with three goals in the
1996 Summer Olympics, including the most urgent goal in the history
of the women's national team, a shot in overtime that defeated
Norway by 1-0 in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the Olympic tournament, she knocked in the game
winner against Sweden. In the championship game against China,
MacMillan scored again. But the American formation has changed from
four midfielders to three, and so now MacMillan must sit and wait
her turn, preparing to heat up quickly when DiCicco signals for her
microwave offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``My role has changed,'' the 24-year-old MacMillan said. ``My
job is to be ready and take whatever time I get. I think I've shown
Tony that I'm ready to go. Ten minutes, 40, 90, I'll do anything he
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   There is not a more improbable member on the World Cup roster
than MacMillan, who traveled soccer backroads instead of the
traditional upper-middle-class route from suburbia to the national
team. A native of Syosset, N.Y., MacMillan grew up in Escondido,
Calif., unable to afford the fees required to play in the Olympic
Development Program, a soccer fast lane for superior players.
Instead, she played high school and club soccer, which provided a
ticket out of her neighborhood the way basketball provides a ticket
out of some other neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the only way I was going to get into college,''
MacMillan said. ``If I wanted to go to a good school, I needed a
full ride.''
</P>
<P>
   She played soccer constantly, at recess, during physical
education class, in the yard, at nearby fields. When there was no
goal, a pair of shoes would suffice as markers. ``My big tough-guy
brother would get upset when his friends would come over and ask
for me to play,'' MacMillan said with a laugh. ``When I was on the
soccer field, nothing else mattered. That was my time.''
</P>
<P>
   She received a scholarship from the University of Portland,
where MacMillan and Milbrett were known as the M &AMP; M line.
MacMillan became a four-time all-American and led the country in
scoring as a sophomore in 1993. As a senior, MacMillan led Portland
to the national championship game and was named national player of
the year. She attended a tryout camp for the 1996 Olympic team
after the season, but DiCicco left her name off the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was completely devastated,'' MacMillan said. Her college
eligibility had expired. There was no professional league to join.
``The national team was all that was left,'' she said. ``I wondered
if my career was over.''
</P>
<P>
   She returned to the University of Portland, where Coach Clive
Charles convinced her to keep training. Maybe she would get another
chance. The chance came later in 1995, when members of the national
team went on strike over a salary dispute. MacMillan was called
into camp and not only did she make the Olympic team, she became a
starter. ``I made a mistake with Shannon,'' DiCicco freely admits.
</P>
<P>
   The American formation changed after the Olympics and, with it,
so did MacMillan's role. Now she is the first forward off the
bench, relieving Hamm, spelling Milbrett, always threatening out of
the bullpen with her sledgehammer knuckleball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so good at bending the ball,'' MacMillan said. ``I'd
rather rip it and have them try to save it.'` &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
