</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-LIBRARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE CLINTON LIBRARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 29: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every modern president, beginning with Herbert Hoover, has
established a separate library in his home state to house his
papers. These facilities are built with private money, and Bill
Clinton, who wants to see a $125 million library, museum and public
policy center in Little Rock, is already working on his. While
Clinton is not directly soliciting contributions, he seems to be
engaged in what might be called the softening-up process. During a
visit to New York City, he scheduled a private dinner Monday with
about 40 potential donors. News accounts suggested that Clinton
would share his plans for the library, and that the guests will
receive a follow-up call from the fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan, the only other recent chief executive to win
re-election, started this process even earlier in his second term.
But the danger of conflict of interest is obvious, and the library
foundations, as private nonprofit groups, can accept any amount of
money from anyone, including a foreign government.
</P>
<P>
   Constructing a presidential library is not an ordinary
charitable enterprise, as long as the president who is to be
honored is still in office. Congress should examine ways to limit
the size of donations, require full disclosure of contributors'
identities and bar money from foreign governments. A still better
approach might be to appropriate a set amount of money for each
president's outgoing library and leave it at that. Critics of the
current system even argue that presidential papers should be
gathered at a single site in Washington. They note that libraries
with such close ties to the families of their subjects can become
too protective, as many charged the Kennedy Library was during its
early years of operation.
</P>
<P>
   But some scholars defend the current system, arguing that a
large government institution devoted to all American presidents
would be unlikely to be as aggressive in collecting every possible
scrap of information about any given administration. ``If you want
a device to clean the bone as much as possible, the presidential
library does it pretty well,'' says Michael Beschloss, the
presidential historian.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton presidency may have picked its own bones clean
already. Subpoena-shy aides learned early on that anything written
down or tape recorded was potential evidence in some future legal
proceedings. But whatever documents do exist may therefore be
particularly critical, and a library that seeks them out would be a
valuable asset. However Clinton needs to be careful that he does
not wind up adding to the administration's already too-long list of
fund-raising scandals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 2153EDT &QL; 
