<SLUG> BC-ELIZABETH-DOLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIZABETH DOLE CALLS FOR INTERNET DISCIPLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLEVUE, Wash. _ Elizabeth Dole, whose run for the White House
is a disciplined, focused antithesis of her husband Bob's 1996
campaign, used a Bellevue visit Monday to call for discipline on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Dole asked Congress to pass legislation that would deny federal
money to any school or library that does not shut off access to
pornography among users of the Internet _ while also arguing that
the technology industry should be allowed to grow with ``as little
government intervention as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Libraries should not use federal money to put pornography on
their shelves, or their desktops or laptops,'' Dole said during an
appearance at the Bellevue Regional Library.
</P>
<P>
   Dole had a similar message when asked what measures she would
support to curb violence in schools. ``I think what we need is to
give teachers control of the classroom to restore discipline,'' she
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, and at a fund-raising breakfast in Seattle,
Dole declared herself a strong supporter of free trade and endorsed
China's bid for membership in the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would make the entire Western Hemisphere a free trade
zone,'' Dole said. She said that President Clinton should press
Congress for fast-track authority to negotiate new trade
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Of China, Dole added, ``Twenty percent of the world's population
lives there. Exports are essential to the continued growth of our
own economy.''
</P>
<P>
   She was twice a cabinet secretary, and later president of the
American Red Cross, but Elizabeth Dole has long been known as the
skilled, always-upbeat supporting player behind Bob Dole's three
losing campaigns for the White House and his 1976 bid for the vice
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband was perhaps the moodiest, least manageable
presidential candidate in modern American history. He dropped
one-liners, lampooned his consultants and pollsters, joked about
``my program _ whatever it is,'' and at times turned a mean face to
adversity, in 1988 telling George Bush: ``Stop lying about my
record.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole has watched Texas Gov. George W. Bush, son of the
former president, dominate early fund-raising in the 2000 GOP race
and take a commanding lead in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stay focused. I'm not distracted,'' Elizabeth Dole said with
a smile yesterday, when asked to comment on the bad news.
</P>
<P>
   Media commentators writing her off are ``the same pundits who
said (Bush's) father couldn't possibly lose the presidency'' after
the 1991 Gulf War victory,'' Dole added, still smiling. They were
the same pundits who, after the Monica Lewinsky scandal broke,
``said that President Clinton would have to resign.''
</P>
<P>
   Styling herself a ``courageous conservative,'' and saying she
intends to ``explain who I am,'' Dole has taken a series of blunt
stands in her campaign, and is the lone Republican presidential
contender to make an issue of gun safety. She initially raised the
issue at a dinner of conservative, pro-firearms New Hampshire
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe there is any reason for a family to have an
AK-47 to defend themselves,'' Dole said Monday, referring to the
Soviet-made assault rifle.
</P>
<P>
   She also called for a ban on so-called cop killer bullets, and
child safety locks on all guns. ``I call it crime control, not gun
control,'' Dole said in the interview.
</P>
<P>
   The audience at Bellevue Regional Library cheered Dole's call
for gun safety. She raised $50,000 at a Seattle breakfast, at which
her calls for free trade and China ties won an equally warm
reception.
</P>
<P>
   During a Seattle visit last week, Iowa's newly elected
Democratic Gov. Tom Vilsack was asked about potential surprises in
his state's first-in-the-nation caucuses next February. ``Watch
Elizabeth Dole. She is getting big crowds everywhere,'' Vilsack
replied.
</P>
<P>
   But a Des Moines Register poll, released Monday, showed Bush
with a commanding lead of 40 percent to 13 percent over Dole among
the state's Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Dole said that she is drawing people ``never active in politics
before,'' as well as young people, into the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Before her library appearance, she made what is becoming a
mandatory pilgrimage for presidential candidates visiting
Washington. She traveled to the Microsoft campus in Redmond for a
meeting with company chairman Bill Gates and a talk with Microsoft
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Dole said she told Gates it was ``great'' that Microsoft had
developed software filters to keep pornography off childrens'
computer screens. She said she touted a proposal to make permanent
research and development tax credits, and her support for
legislation that would provide limited immunity for Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   A number of veteran GOP operatives watched Dole approvingly _
not as a potential threat to Bush, but as the Texas governor's
strongest possible running mate. In 1996, women voters preferred
Clinton over Bob Dole 54 percent to 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Al Gore could pack up and go home,'' said Republican
consultant Brett Bader.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush will show his wares to the Northwest early next
month, with a Portland appearance on July 7 and stops in Spokane
and Seattle on July 8.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how her ``courageous conservatism'' differs from the
``compassionate conservatism'' touted by Bush, Dole laughed and
replied: ``I will let W. define his phrase.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
