<HEADER>
A2591 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHARMACEUTICALS-MARKE     06-28 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHARMACEUTICALS-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: ESCAPE FROM AGRICULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Home Products Corp., the current ne'er-do-well of the
pharmaceutical industry, is having a hard time selling its troubled
agricultural division, analysts said Monday, because two of the
most likely buyers _ Novartis AG and Astra Zeneca Group _ are also
trying to sell theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a lot of houses suddenly becoming available in a
poor market,'' said David Saks, a managing director at Gruntal &AMP;
Co. ``I'm sure American Home will find a buyer. They just won't get
a peak price.''
</P>
<P>
   The flight out of agricultural products is an abrupt change for
the pharmaceutical industry. Not more than a year ago, many
pharmaceutical companies were trying to strengthen their
agricultural holdings during a downturn in pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, an agriculture division has become more hindrance
than help. Plagued by market troubles in Europe and Southeast Asia,
sales worldwide of agricultural products are projected to drop 3
percent or so this year, analysts said. The slip has prodded many
chief executives to jettison their divisions before the carnage
gets worse.
</P>
<P>
   Several directors at Novartis, Astra Zeneca and American Home
had also become concerned that the companies' continued presence in
agriculture might hurt their competitiveness in pharmaceuticals.
Analysts said that several board members had balked at allocating
additional research money to agricultural projects when the cash
could be used to develop new drugs, which would deliver much higher
profit margins than seeds and herbicides.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Monday how the sales of the agricultural
divisions _ three of the world's largest _ would take place.
Novartis, which is based in Switzerland, and Astra Zeneca of London
declined to comment on what each company called ``market
speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for American Home, which is based in Madison, N.J.,
reiterated that the company was ``reviewing strategic
alternatives'' for its agricultural division. American Home had
first made such a statement earlier this month when the company
announced that the poor performance of its agricultural holdings
would reduce its earnings forecast for the second quarter by 17
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceutical industry's experience in agriculture may one
day become fodder for business textbooks. While agricultural
divisions did provide several advantages, like research synergies
with some pharmaceutical projects, the worldwide market for seeds
and herbicides was more turbulent than most pharmaceutical
executives had believed possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pharmaceutical companies learned an important lesson
here,'' said Alex Evans, a pharmaceutical analyst at Deutsche Bank
Securities in London. ``When things get messy in the agricultural
industry, they really get messy. The beautiful thing about
pharmaceuticals is that they are noncyclicals.''
</P>
<P>
   Many pharmaceutical executives who had an agricultural presence
had projected that sales of seeds and herbicides worldwide would
grow by 9 percent annually. These projections proved to be
shortsighted, when pharmaceutical executives did not see what
effects their products would have on the market.
</P>
<P>
   As more pharmaceutical companies raced to develop genetically
improved crops, many European consumers were becoming increasingly
concerned about crops with altered DNA. As a result, many European
governments are trying to limit their use, dampening what
executives had hoped would one day be a booming market.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts noted, too, that pharmaceutical companies may have not
seen the cutthroat nature of the market. Monsanto developed a corn
seed that required less herbicide than any that had been developed.
When that seed became a popular seller, analysts said that its use
hurt the herbicide sales of Novartis and American Home.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the market for agricultural divisions has suddenly
become flooded, analysts noted that the properties on the block are
far from equal. Novartis replaced Wolfgang Samo as head of its
agricultural division last month with Heinz Imhof, his deputy.
</P>
<P>
   Imhof wasted no time in shaking up the division. He announced
last week that Novartis would cut 1,100 jobs from its worldwide
agricultural division _ some 6 percent of its 18,000 workers. Sales
in the Novartis agricultural division were off 8 percent in the
first quarter, but analysts have projected the unit to post a 5
percent gain for the year.
</P>
<P>
   During the last several weeks, there has been speculation in
European markets that Astra Zeneca and Novartis would spin their
agricultural businesses into one, which would easily be the world's
largest. Astra Zeneca's agricultural sales are expected to remain
flat this year at $2.9 billion, a respectable performance given the
industry decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, both companies have denied that it will happen,'' said
Paul Diggle, a pharmaceuticals analyst with SG Securities in
London. ``There could be buyers from the chemical companies. And
then they could spin them off. But I can tell you they will be
volatile stocks if that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have begun to ponder if American Home will find a
buyer. The company's agricultural products are not as sophisticated
as those of many of its competitors. If the company spins off its
agricultural division, analysts said Monday that it might fetch as
little as $2 billion. It had been valued at $5 billion just two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, whatever happens with the agricultural divisions of
Novartis, American Home and Astra Zeneca, many of their competitors
have reasons to gloat. Analysts noted Monday that agricultural
products may soon become just another one of the pharmaceutical
industry's sidelines _ like pharmacy benefit managers and medical
device companies _ that were bought with high hopes and then sold
because of low margins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
