u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-BUDGET-SURPLUS-N     06-28 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BUDGET-SURPLUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A WINDFALL'S PROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 29: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new era of government surpluses forecast last January has
suddenly grown bigger and brighter. Over the next 15 years,
President Clinton announced Monday, the federal government will
produce surpluses of $5.5 trillion, a cool $1 trillion higher than
January's number. The president also offered some ideas about how
to spend this windfall. In terms of broad intent, his proposals are
not much different from those he unveiled five months ago. But in
important details they are much improved. Clinton has also left the
door ajar for discussion of broader tax cuts down the road. That is
a political necessity, given Republican control of Congress, and
positions the president to argue for tax relief for low- and
middle-income families. But Clinton has no intention of cutting a
deal on taxes until Congress addresses his main priorities.
</P>
<P>
   His top priority, one that he hopes will become an important
part of his legacy, is to reduce the national debt and shore up
Social Security and Medicare. Fully 80 percent of the surplus would
be devoted to these purposes, with the rest divided equally between
discretionary-spending initiatives and a program to encourage
individual retirement accounts. The emphasis on Social Security and
Medicare is sensible and farsighted. If nothing is done, Social
Security will be threatened with insolvency as the baby boomers
retire. Medicare also requires substantial investments.
</P>
<P>
   One addition to the president's plans is a program to provide
improved prescription drug benefits for the elderly. The potential
of this program for cost escalation has to be studied closely. But
the most important change involves Social Security. In his earlier
proposal, Clinton wanted the flexibility, in the early years, to
spend Social Security surpluses on other programs _ much as those
funds are spent now. Responding to criticism from both Republicans
and Democrats, Clinton has now adopted the idea of a ``lock box''
to insure that excess revenues are used only to reduce the debt and
to insure Social Security's long-term health. In addition, the
interest saved by reducing the debt in future years would be
earmarked exclusively for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   In sum, Clinton's fire wall around the country's two biggest
entitlement programs is even stronger than before, which should
please his Republican critics. Of course nothing will fully satisfy
these Republicans unless he also gives some ground on their
proposals for high-end tax cuts. On this score, Clinton reiterated
his preference for targeted tax cuts for low- and moderate-income
families, while not ruling out discussions about something bigger.
</P>
<P>
   But he was tactically smart to insist on first things first.
Strengthen the entitlement programs, he said, then we can talk
about taxes and spending. That is the correct order. These rosy
predictions, after all, are only predictions. No one can be sure
what the economy will look like three years from now, let alone
fifteen. The reasonable approach is to capitalize on today's boom
to fix tomorrow's problems in Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
