A2594 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-BUDGET-COX     06-28 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-BUDGET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio senate sends budget to Taft for passage
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Members of the Ohio legislature finished up
their budget-making chores Monday, giving overwhelming approval to
a two-year, $22.6 billion general operating budget and sending it
to Gov. Bob Taft.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted 32-1 for the report of the conference committee
that worked out differences in separate budgets passed by the House
and Senate. The House vote was 83-12.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's action followed House and Senate approval last week of
a separate $17 billion education budget, which Taft is scheduled to
sign today.
</P>
<P>
   The governor is expected to sign the operating budget _ after
reviewing it for possible line-item vetoes _ by Wednesday night,
said Scott Milburn, Taft's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Both budgets must be signed by Thursday, the start of the
state's new fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   The operating budget included more than $20 million in high
technology assistance for the Miami Valley, including $4 million
for the National Composite Center in Kettering. The $4 million was
inserted by the conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel J. Curtis, vice president of the Miami Valley Economic
Development Coalition, praised the area's legislators, particularly
Sen. Charles Horn, R-Centerville, for pushing to get the money for
the composite center and other high-tech projects.
</P>
<P>
   The money will be used to start building 100 bridges throughout
Ohio using composite materials to give bridges longer life than
concrete and steel, said Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also included $7 million for the Ohio Research
Collaboration, to promote cooperation in graduate studies between
the Air Force Institute of Technology at Wright-Patterson Air Force
Base and four Ohio universities, including Wright State University
and the University of Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   Additional money in the budget will pay for high-tech training
for Miami Valley toolmakers and machinists.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 percent of the operating budget went to human
services, including expanding Medicaid health insurance to the
working poor and providing support to grandparents and other family
members other than mothers and fathers raising children.
</P>
<P>
   Although the budget is supposed to focus on spending, it
included a controversial provision to exempt the records of the
law-writing Legislative Service Commission from Ohio's public
records law. This provision was opposed by the Ohio Newspaper
Association but lawmakers said they want to keep the early stages
of bill writing confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Hartley, D-Springfield, said this provision alone
caused him to oppose the budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to do a whole lot of mischief with this
provision,'' said Hartley.
</P>
<P>
   The levels of spending in the education and general operating
budget will leave enough money to provide a 3 percent personal
income tax cut next year, compared to a cut of about 9 percent this
year.
</P>
<P>
   A family of four with an income of $40,000 that received a tax
cut of about $120 this year would get a $40 tax cut next year, said
Rep. J. Donald Mottley, R-West Carrollton, who voted for the
operating budget.
</P>
<P>
   William Hershey writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
