<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-LAYOFFS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech company laying off workers
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Computer Sciences Corp.'s Austin-based Financial
Services Group laid off 122 workers nationwide Monday, as the
company cut back because of a short-term slump caused by year
2000-related concerns.
</P>
<P>
   CSC's financial industry customers, many of them large insurance
companies, have cutback spending on computer software, said CSC
spokesman Howard Falkenberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Y2K problem,'' Falkenberg said. ``Customers are slowing
down their investment in new systems or in modification of their
existing systems. As a consequence, the Financial Services Group is
a little overstaffed. They are having to make an adjustment.''
</P>
<P>
   The downturn doesn't affect the rest of El Segundo, Calif,-based
CSC, which has major business operations that serve European
corporations and the U.S. government. And the Financial Services
Group doesn't expect to make any further Y2K workforce reductions.
</P>
<P>
   The much-publicized year 2000 computer problem may create
problems for companies that sell complex software systems to
corporate clients, one analyst said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many companies that are buying software are playing it very
safe,'' said analyst John Dunkle with Workgroup Strategic Services
of Portsmouth, N.H. ``They are not canceling orders. They are
deferring purchases. They already have their Y2K fix in place, but
they don't know how badly the patient is going to be bleeding until
the calendar changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are Y2K problems that occur, some companies will be
spending millions of dollars (on software fixes) in a matter of
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Other business operations plan to interview laid-off workers
this week for possible rehire elsewhere within the company. Workers
will receive outplacement assistance and severance payments
according to their seniority.
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs, which take effect July 9, affect a broad range of
jobs, including computer programmers. Many of those laid off were
recently hired.
</P>
<P>
   The short-term Y2K-related slump won't affect the company's
expansion plans in downtown Austin, Falkenberg said. CSC expects to
build three buildings totaling 700,000 square feet downtown. It
expects to start work on the first two buildings early next year.
Those buildings should be occupied by mid-2001. The company is
expanding downtown because it expects its Austin work force will
grow from 1,300 workers to 3,500 workers during the next several
years.
</P>
<P>
   CSC is one of the largest software companies in the world, with
50,000 workers and more than $7.6 billion in revenue for the fiscal
year completed in March. The company's Financial Services Group
employs 3,000 people worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Ladendorf writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
