<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SERBIA-REBUILD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RESTRAINT ON REBUILDING SERBIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 29: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As NATO peacekeepers struggle to quell ethnic violence in
Kosovo, the West is considering the larger job of reconstruction in
the Balkans. The initial impulse to limit aid to Serbia while
Slobodan Milosevic remains in power is right. Some humanitarian
assistance is justified, but no money should go to Milosevic or his
government.
</P>
<P>
   The West has agreed to raise money for the rebuilding of Kosovo
and Montenegro and economic development aid for Macedonia, Albania
and other neighboring countries that suffered because of the war.
The idea is to help them recover and tie the region more closely to
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   While few Serbians showed interest in the atrocities their
countrymen were committing in Serbia, they do not deserve to freeze
this winter because of it. Democracy will be furthered in Serbia if
people get over their fury with the West and realize that it is
their leader, not ordinary Serbs, who is the target of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever possible, humanitarian aid should go to Serbia through
independent groups, such as nongovernment organizations, opposition
political leaders who run cities like Nis and Cacak and the
Orthodox Church, which recently called for Milosevic to step down.
Serbia has a temporary shortage of commodities that can most easily
bypass the government _ food and medicine. But the long-term threat
is a winter of rolling electricity blackouts, which will cut heat
and water for many. The country's electric power system should be
rebuilt, but through the work of foreign companies or those owned
by the opposition in Serbia. The West should support democracy in
Serbia by helping groups like the independent media and opposition
mayors, perhaps even helping them rebuild factories or
infrastructure in their cities.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most difficult reconstruction issues is what to do
about roads and bridges needed by Serbia's neighbors. Bulgaria, for
example, depends on Serbia's portion of the Danube river _
currently blocked by bombed-out bridges _ for shipping. The river
should be cleared of debris so commerce can resume, but the West
ought not to rebuild the bridges.
</P>
<P>
   If the reconstruction of Bosnia is prologue, then money will
surely fall short of what Kosovo, Montenegro, their Balkan
neighbors and democratic groups in Serbia need. Serbia's most basic
need is not economic help, but democracy, which is best furthered
if Milosevic is denied Western aid. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 2202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
