A2601 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-STEEL-NYT &LR;      06-28 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-STEEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLED MEXICAN STEELMAKER TALKS OF MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICK WILLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexico's largest steel manufacturer, which
defaulted on $1.9 billion of debt two months ago, announced Monday
that it was discussing a proposed merger with one of the country's
largest industrial conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   Altos Hornos de Mexico and executives from the prospective
buyer, Industrias Monterrey SA, filed a letter of intent with the
Mexican stock exchange Monday. Under the plan, Altos Hornos will
negotiate with no other companies for 90 days. Industrias Monterrey
said it would own a controlling stake in Altos Hornos if the talks
led to a deal.
</P>
<P>
   But Santiago Clariond, the president of Industrias Monterrey's
steel division, said in an interview Monday that his company would
not invest in Altos Hornos unless the steelmaker's debt was
reorganized. Neither company explained how this would be
accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be impossible for us to merge with Altos Hornos with
the debt they now have,'' Clariond said.
</P>
<P>
   Altos Hornos has been dragged down by onerous debts that now
total about $2.4 billion. Trading of shares for the company, which
had temporary court protection against creditors, was suspended in
New York and Mexico City on May 26.
</P>
<P>
   To many industry analysts, the announcement Monday said little
about how Altos Hornos could be rescued financially.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know nothing more today about how they will manage their
debt than we did on the day they defaulted,'' said Rodrigo Marin, a
steel industry analyst at the Inverlat brokerage in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Still pending is the seizure of 17.5 percent of Altos Hornos
shares by Banco Nacional de Mexico just before the steel company
announced default in late May.
</P>
<P>
   The company's other large creditors include Chase Manhattan Bank
and Bank of America.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said they expected Industrias Monterrey would
agree to take on the bulk of Altos Hornos' debt in exchange for
majority control of the company.
</P>
<P>
   A government-run company that was privatized in 1991, Altos
Hornos was hit hard by last year's sharp drop in steel prices as
cheap Russian and Asian steel flooded world markets. But some
analysts blame Altos Hornos management for the company's decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management of the company was extravagant and created a potent
cocktail of too much debt and voluble steel prices,'' said Damian
Fraser, head of Mexico research at Warburg Dillon Read.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
