<HEADLINE>
SELLING SAINT LAURENT TO DAUGHTERS WHO LUNCH
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I'm usually in New York for five hours,'' Alber
Elbaz was saying last week in the middle of a whirlwind of public
appearances and private dinners to promote him as the designer of
Yves Saint Laurent ready-to-wear. ``I get here, and I'm right back
on a plane. And I get jet lag going from New York to New Jersey!''
</P>
<P>
   He was relaxing at Il Cantinori with a small group of store and
magazine people when, sometime between the antipasto and the pasta,
he remarked on how personally he took everything written about his
collections and how he had been hurt by some criticism of his first
Saint Laurent show last March. Joan Kaner, the fashion director of
Neiman Marcus, tried to console him by saying he had been in a
no-win situation because whatever he did, somebody would find
fault. If he had made drastic changes, she told him, some people
would be unhappy, and if he didn't, others would be unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're damned if you do and damned if you don't,'' she said,
``so don't worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   She was right, of course, but a designer's career is put on the
line with every collection. And it's a heavy burden for a young
designer to be given the responsibility of carrying on the
tradition of a venerable house. Of course, Saint Laurent was only
21 when he took over at Christian Dior after the master's death,
and Elbaz is now 37 and has years of experience. But this is a
highly competitive era, and Saint Laurent is still alive and
involved in designing the couture.
</P>
<P>
   Elbaz may have won praise for his previous work at Guy Laroche,
but his successor, Ronald Van der Kemp, lost his job after showing
just one collection. So Elbaz is walking a tightrope without a net,
attempting to breathe new life into a 40-year-old house that has
just been bought by Pinault-Printemps-Redoute, which plans to sell
it to Gucci, which it also controls. That has to worry the new
designer on the block, especially a thin-skinned one like Elbaz,
who, in a low-key way, always seems anxious to please.
</P>
<P>
   And that is why he was in this country for a week to show a
sampling of the fall clothes to potential customers, to introduce
the cruise 2000 collection to the industry and, not so
incidentally, to make nice with retailers and members of the press.
</P>
<P>
   The balancing act for Elbaz is to make Yves Saint Laurent
relevant to younger women who associate the label with their
mothers _ and at the same time not turn off those older,
tried-and-true customers. He is trying to do that by showing
classic Saint Laurent styles like pinstriped pants suits,
bubble-shaped tops and trench coats, changing them enough so that a
potential customer will look at them in a new way. He has taken the
bubble tops, for example, that Saint Laurent makes in evening
fabrics like taffeta and transformed them into day wear by whipping
them up in raincoat fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Elbaz's whirlwind tour began when he boarded the Concorde in
Paris on June 17, arriving in Washington for a three-day stay that
included a black-tie dinner that night for 120 high-profile guests
like Vernon Jordan and Deeda Blair. It was held at the Potomac,
Md., home of Ernest and Sally Marx, the owners of the Saks Jandel
stores in the Washington area, with two Saint Laurent boutiques.
The next day there was a presentation of the fall collection for 50
top customers.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was on to New York for model fittings and working with
Saks Fifth Avenue's visual staff on displays for the store windows,
before a Monday dinner given by Roberta Myers, the editor in chief
of Mirabella, and Michelle Morgan, the magazine's fashion director.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's agenda included a 9 a.m. meeting with Saks employees
to familiarize them with the clothes, a fashion show and cocktail
party that evening at Saks, and a dinner that went on until well
past midnight at the trendy Bond Street restaurant, where the hosts
were Princess Yasmin Aga Khan and Philip Miller, the chairman of
Saks.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday began at 7 a.m. with more model fittings and another
showing of fall clothes at the Saint Laurent Rive Gauche boutique
on Madison Avenue, capped by a lunch in the store for members of
New York's young social set.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Saltzman, fashion director of Vanity Fair, had invited
friends like Marina Rust, Liz Cohen and Samantha Phipps and the
actresses Patricia Arquette and Chloe Sevigny to meet Elbaz and see
the Saint Laurent clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Alber,'' Ms. Saltzman said, ``and I grew up loving
Saint Laurent and wanting to wear Saint Laurent. Alber is giving me
that chance. I'm crazy about him. So I put together 50 young women
who wouldn't think of coming here to shop. They're the next
generation of people thinking about designer clothes, and I'm
hoping this becomes more like clothes we can wear.''
</P>
<P>
   She had advised Donna Faircloth, the Rive Gauche
public-relations director, to keep the lunch menu simple and have
plates on the table when the guests sat down so people could get
out fast. Ms. Faircloth took her at her word. Lunch turned out to
be a timbale of fresh vegetables and fruit, served with thin slices
of French bread, followed by melon-ball-size scoops of sorbet and
petits fours iced with the orange and pink Rive Gauche logo. Elbaz,
for one, was still hungry; he said he hoped he would have time for
a hamburger before going on to fit the cruise wear.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   His sentiment was echoed by Ms. Sevigny, who was seated next to
him, but it didn't dampen her admiration for the collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved the clothes, especially the day clothes,'' she said.
``I did a shoot for Harper's Bazaar a month ago in all Yves Saint
Laurent clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Venerable fashion houses, like cosmetic companies, automakers
and television networks, are all working feverishly to attract a
new generation. The trick, though, is to do that without losing
their loyal customers. Hence, the presence of longtime customers of
the couture house like Princess Yasmin and Nan Kempner, who sat
next to Elbaz at the Bond Street dinner (``He's adorable,'' she
said) and who popped into the Rive Gauche boutique Thursday while
Nancy Reagan was there with her Secret Service escort.
</P>
<P>
   Another longtime fan, Sandy Hill, was at Wednesday's lunch.
``Saint Laurent was the first designer I was aware of and wanted to
buy when I was new to New York,'' she recalled. ``I found a tuxedo
dress on sale and said to myself, `I'll wear this forever.'''
</P>
<P>
   She went on to say she liked what Elbaz had done in his first
collection for the house. ``He resisted making a radical break,''
she said. ``He honored someone who is arguably the greatest
designer of his time. He made it modern yet unmistakably Saint
Laurent.''
</P>
<P>
   Elbaz said repeatedly during his round of appearances here that
he had tried to represent Saint Laurent and not himself in the
first collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about me _ it's about him,'' he told the guests in
the Madison Avenue boutique, seated on a low platform before the
show started, as he answered questions posed by Ms. Saltzman. ``For
every designer, Saint Laurent is not just the name of a designer or
of a house. It's a dream. A lot of people were expecting me to
change, but it was more about going back to the archives. Then I
did it my way with a different cut and different proportions. I cut
off the evening dresses and made them shirts and showed them with
pants, always with pants.''
</P>
<P>
   But he kept the pagoda shoulders on the tailored suits.
``Without them, it's not a Saint Laurent suit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Fischelis, fashion director of Saks, checked out the
stock that arrived at her store last week and said that while the
cut was streamlined, it would still please longtime customers.
</P>
<P>
   Elbaz's last appearance was on Thursday at the press showing of
40 pieces out of 400 that make up the cruise collection. The
tailored pants suits, shirtdresses and raincoats still bore the
Saint Laurent stamp very strongly. Elbaz has said that he believes
in evolution, not revolution, which has been the house's credo for
the last 20 years or so. That has also been the main criticism of
those who believe fashion should always be moving ahead and is no
doubt one of the reasons Pierre Berge, Saint Laurent's longtime
business partner, brought in a new designer. And why that designer
was acting last week much like a movie star promoting his latest
film. But it will be a while before the box-office results are in
on this one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
