u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUBBELL-STARR-1STLD-W     06-28 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUBBELL-STARR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTEDLY REACH DEAL, MOVING 5-YEAR INVESTIGATION TOWARD END 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs 1st and 3d grafs to clarify sourcing) HUBBELL AND STARR(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater prosecutor, has
reached a tentative plea agreement with Webster Hubbell, lawyers
familiar with the case said Monday, in which Hubbell will plead
guilty to a felony charge of lying about the role he and Hillary
Rodham Clinton played in a questionable Arkansas land deal.
</P>
<P>
   The plea agreement should avert a trial scheduled for August
that was likely to have explored Mrs. Clinton's conduct as a lawyer
in the land deal, which federal regulators characterized as a sham
and which led to the collapse of a savings and loan institution.
Mrs. Clinton might even have been called as a witness in the trial,
which would have taken place at the same time she is expected to
begin her campaign for the U.S. Senate from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Although he will plead guilty to the felony charge as well as to
a misdemeanor charge in a separate tax evasion case, Hubbell is not
expected to cooperate with Starr in providing additional
information about either President Clinton or Mrs. Clinton, the
lawyers said. Nonetheless, the lawyers said that Starr will not
seek any additional jail time for Hubbell, who was released from
prison two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Hubbell is sentenced to jail depends on the judge in the
fraud and tax cases, U.S. District Court Judge James Robertson, who
will also decide whether to accept the plea agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The two Hubbell cases were the last to be brought by Starr. The
last two cases prosecuted by his office, against Susan McDougal and
Julie Hiatt Steele, ended in hung juries. The Hubbell plea
agreement means that the independent counsel is effectively close
to the end of his five-year investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In reaching the agreement, it appears Starr has finally relented
in his efforts to press Hubbell to produce information damaging to
the Clintons. One associate of Starr, not in the prosecutor's
office, said he believed the decision to dispose of the Hubbell
cases reflected Starr's eagerness to be done with the long and
difficult investigation of the Clintons and to close down the
office.
</P>
<P>
   Although his office is still investigating a few matters
involving the Clintons, the major task remaining is for Starr to
issue a report about his activities. Some of Starr's associates
have said that he is tentatively planning to issue a report that
could be highly critical of the Clintons' behavior, especially that
of Mrs. Clinton. Under the independent counsel law, Starr is
required to issue a report on his activities to the three-judge
panel that appointed him. But it is unclear under a 1994 amendment
as to how much he is allowed to criticize people who have not been
indicted, like the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's years-long pursuit of Hubbell, whom he had indicted
three times, had become for critics of Starr and the independent
counsel statute a prime example of prosecutorial over-reach.
Starr's supporters have said Hubbell was pursued so vigorously
because his case was an example of stonewalling by the Clintons'
associates.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel law, enacted in the aftermath of
Watergate, expires at midnight Wednesday. Although Congress held
many hearings, there was in the end no interest in extending the
statute. Starr is not obliged to close down his office because of
the law's demise.
</P>
<P>
   But he has testified before Congress that he believes the law,
which was supposed to insulate high-profile prosecutions from
politics, has not worked because independent prosecutors invariably
are accused of being political by associates of the subjects of the
investigations. As a result, he too believed the law should lapse,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell, a former chief justice of the state of Arkansas and
once the No. 3 official in the Clinton justice department, spent
nearly two years in prison after pleading guilty to charges brought
by the independent counsel that he bilked his partners in the Rose
law firm of Little Rock, where he had once worked with Mrs.
Clinton. He is currently a research analyst at the National Center
on Institutions and Alternatives, a non-profit study group in
Alexandria, Va. He has been working on criminal justice issues,
according to a statement from the organization and in his recent
book, he said he was paid about $12,000 a year. As a convicted
felon, he can no longer practice law.
</P>
<P>
   The felony charge to which he is expected to plead guilty does
not involve the Whitewater land development but a lesser-known but
more complicated land deal in Arkansas known as Castle Grande.
Castle Grande was funded by Madison Guaranty Savings and Loan,
which was owned at the time by James B. and Susan McDougal, the
Clintons' partners in Whitewater. Federal regulators attributed
Madison Guaranty's eventual failure in part to its involvement in
the Castle Grande development.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment of Hubbell did not mention Mrs. Clinton by name
but refers more than 30 times to the ``1985-86 billing partner'' on
the Madison Guaranty account, a description of Mrs. Clinton's role
in the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, Hubbell's concealment of the role
he and Mrs. Clinton played in the Castle Grande development
defrauded the federal government in two ways. Had the Rose law firm
disclosed its activities to federal regulators, the law firm would
probably have been prohibited from lucrative legal contracts with
the same federal agencies. Under the employment contract, the firm
was obliged to disclose what appeared to be a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Starr had charged, the concealment interfered with
the ability of the regulators to understand just how troubled an
institution Madison Guaranty was, delaying its shutdown, and
increasing the eventual cost to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton had for a time denied any involvement. But when
long-missing billing records from the law firm were discovered in
the White House book room in January 1996, two years after they
were subpoenaed by Starr, Mrs. Clinton said she remembered having
done legal work on the development but knew it by a different name.
</P>
<P>
   The tax fraud indictment had accused Hubbell, his wife, Suzanna,
his accountant and lawyer of scheming in the last four years to
avoid paying taxes and penalties of more than $850,000. Under the
proposed plea agreement, all charges will be dropped against Mrs.
Hubbell and the two family advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had contended that much of the owed taxes stemmed
from money Hubbell had embezzled and from hundreds of thousands of
dollars in income from jobs referred to him by friends and
supporters of the president. The indictment said Hubbell did little
work for those jobs and suggested that they might have been
arranged to discourage him from cooperating with investigators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
