<SLUG> BC-LEHMAN-FIDELITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY AND LEHMAN IN DEAL ON BROAD RANGE OF SERVICES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   (nk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments, the giant retail-oriented investment
group, and Lehman Brothers, the old-line Wall Street house that
caters to institutions, announced a broad alliance Monday involving
an array of products, distribution channels and research.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, which will be phased in over six to eight
weeks, the 6.5 million customers of Fidelity's brokerage unit _ 2.7
million of them online _ will get access to a wide range of Lehman
research and underwritings of stocks and bonds. The biggest and
most active of these customers will be eligible for allotments of
initial public offerings, which have been particularly coveted
recently because many issues have jumped spectacularly in price.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman will get a big retail outlet for its stock and bond
underwritings and research and greater marketing capability,
particularly in Fidelity's Internet clients. That is expected to
help it win new underwriting business, a traditional strength.
</P>
<P>
   Terms were not disclosed, but officials said no money would
change hands between the publicly held Lehman, the fourth-biggest
brokerage house, and Fidelity, whose $819.8 billion of assets make
it the world's biggest money manager. Fidelity, based in Boston, is
a unit of the FMR Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Holders of Fidelity's 280 mutual funds will be largely
unaffected unless they also have Fidelity brokerage accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expressed approval of the strategies reflected in the
deal, which may have contributed to a gain in the shares of Lehman,
which rose $3.6875, to $57.125.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lehman needs to find ways to more extensively broaden the
distribution base for their products,'' said Judah Kraushaar, a
financial services analyst at Merrill Lynch. ``Fidelity
increasingly has to find ways to broaden their product reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraushaar said the joint effort, rather than a merger, would
allow the companies to continue to focus on what they know best.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Eberling, senior analyst at Putnam, Lovell de Guardiola &AMP;
Thornton, agreed, calling the alliance ``a very smart strategic
move,'' one that recognizes the growing importance of the Internet
as a distribution channel and helps keep rivals for stock and bond
underwritings at bay. ``The ability to defuse the pitch against
them is critical,'' Eberling said.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's link with Lehman replaces a narrower one formed two
years ago with Salomon Brothers, which ended with Salomon Smith
Barney's absorption into Citigroup. That effort put much of its
focus on initial offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new relationship, participation in initial and other
stock offerings will be confined to brokerage customers with at
least $500,000 in assets with the fund manager, members of Fidelity
Premium Services or customers qualifying for Active Trader or Gold
Circle reduced-commission status. A spokeswoman declined to give
the number of such clients. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
