<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GAY-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: STONEWALL, THEN AND NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 29: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gay politics today are dominated by men and women in business
clothes, representing buttoned-down organizations like the Human
Rights Campaign, Log Cabin Republicans and the Lambda Legal Defense
and Education Fund. But the movement that looks so mainstream in
1999 was born at a bar in Greenwich Village 30 years ago this
summer. When police harassed gay patrons of the Stonewall Inn in
June of 1969, the patrons stood their ground and touched off three
nights of fierce civil disobedience _ prominently featuring men in
drag. Within a year, the name ``Stonewall'' had become synonymous
with the struggle for gay civil rights and full protection under
the law.
</P>
<P>
   The building that once housed the Stonewall Inn on Christopher
Street has earned a listing in the National Register of Historic
Places, becoming the first site in the country to recognize the
contributions that gay and lesbian Americans have made to the
national culture. This also marks the gay rights movement's
evolution from a fringe activity to a well-organized effort with
establishment affiliations and substantial political clout.
</P>
<P>
   The Gay and Lesbian Pride March held over the weekend captured
the transformation. At the end of the 1960s, few political and
civic leaders participated in the event. But over the weekend, the
marchers included Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Fire Commissioner
Thomas Von Essen, as well as firefighters and police officers.
Things have come a long way since those stormy summer nights in
1969.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
