<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-FINANCIER-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER N.J. FINANCIER TO SETTLE STATE CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Brennan, the former New Jersey financier whose prominent
philanthropy and love of horse racing turned out to have been
financed by stock fraud, has agreed to a $100 million settlement of
state charges, prosecutors said Monday. The settlement would also
bar Brennan from any involvement with the securities business in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was first announced in state Superior Court in
Newark, N.J., on Friday, but the terms were not disclosed until
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement may mostly be a paper victory for New Jersey and
the investors it represented. The main benefit may be to save the
state and Brennan the expense of a trial, which was about to begin
in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan, 55 and retired in Juno Beach, Fla., filed for
bankruptcy in 1995. Soon before, a federal judge in New York issued
a $71.5 million judgment against Brennan and First Jersey
Securities, a brokerage firm he founded, for violating federal
securities laws. The Securities and Exchange Commission also banned
Brennan from the securities business.
</P>
<P>
   Bankruptcy officials have been seeking to recover cash Brennan
was suspected of moving offshore as his empire crumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, $55 million would come from a
settlement that Brennan's bankruptcy trustee negotiated with
investors last year as part of the liquidation of estate assets
still in this country. Brennan is liable for the other $45 million.
</P>
<P>
   Even if all of the money could be collected, it would be a
fraction of the $1.2 billion in compensation and fines the state
sought when it filed the suit four years ago. The state charged
that after Brennan cut back First Jersey's activities under
pressure from the authorities, he swindled investors out of $300
million from 1988 to 1995 using high-pressure sales tactics and
price manipulation of penny stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that Brennan and six others used two brokerage
firms that Brennan secretly controlled, Hibbard Brown and L.C.
Wegard &AMP; Co., to carry out their maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan has an unlisted phone number, and a message left with
his lawyer, Gerald Gline, was not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan became nationally known in the 1980s for television
commercials in which he stepped from a helicopter and urged
investors to ``come grow with us.'' By then, the SEC had already
begun its investigation into stock manipulation. One SEC official
called him the ``Johnny Appleseed of penny stock fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Brennan, who lived in Monmouth County, N.J.,
strongly maintained his innocence and was a major figure in the
thoroughbred horse racing industry in New Jersey. He gave millions
of dollars to Seton Hall University, his alma mater, and other
charities. He also financed an advertising campaign for gun
control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
