<HEADER>
A2612 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CLINTONS-630&AMP;ADD-N     06-28 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTONS-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FOR MONEY AND A HOME, THE CLINTONS PAY A VISIT
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.Y., Ill., Conn., Ark.)   (jw) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ President Clinton came here Monday to raise more than
$1 million for Democratic candidates running for Congress next
year. But one of the better-known of those potential Democratic
candidates _ Hillary Rodham Clinton _ skipped the event, spending
the day looking for houses in New York City and Westchester.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies and gentlemen, the president of the United States,''
the announcer said as Clinton took his eighth-row aisle seat,
unexpectedly alone, at a special afternoon performance of ``The
Iceman Cometh.'' For the next five hours, the president joined a
not-quite-full house of donors who had paid $1,000 a head to watch
the harrowing production of the Eugene O'Neill play about a group
of down-and-outers at Harry's Bar on New York's West Side.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton took in the drama, Mrs. Clinton and their daughter,
Chelsea, for the first time began viewing houses where the they
might move in anticipation of Mrs. Clinton's likely run for the
U.S. Senate. Her spokeswoman, Marsha Berry, said that the process
took longer than was expected; hence, she missed the play and
showed up on Monday night at a fund-raising dinner after the play.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Berry said that Mrs. Clinton and Chelsea had spent the day
looking at houses and apartments in ``New York City and its
environs.'' She declined to offer any details, though another
associate of Mrs. Clinton said that the main focus of her attention
continued to be Westchester County and that she had viewed
videotapes of a house in North Salem that had caught her eye.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the play, Clinton joined the audience in giving
the cast, including Kevin Spacey, who plays the lead, a standing
ovation. Clinton then took the stage, shaking hands with the entire
ensemble and repeatedly embracing Spacey, who suggested the
fund-raiser for the Democratic Senate and Congressional Campaign
committees.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his remarks, made no mention of his wife's absence
or her political ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, as Spacey stood to his side, the president took note of
the human struggles and frailties presented in the O'Neill play,
and linked them both to his own politics and to the 30th
anniversary of the modern gay rights movement, that was marked in
New York City over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons that I became and stayed a Democrat is that
I always felt that our party was more interested in people in their
individual struggles, and we always thought everyone should have a
chance,'' Clinton said. By way of example, Clinton discussed the
uprising at the former Stonewall Inn, a gay bar in Greenwich
Village.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 30 years ago today not very far from here that the
Stonewall riots occurred, which sparked the gay and lesbian civil
rights movement,'' Clinton said. ``I'm proud of the fact that the
Democratic Party has been clearly and unambiguously for the
elimination of all forms of discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrived in New York on the same day that the New Yorker
magazine reported that friends in Arkansas were encouraging him to
run for Senate from Arkansas in 2002. A White House spokesman, Joe
Lockhart, quoted the president as disputing the story. ``I think
his quote to me was, `That story is crazy and I don't know where
they got it from,' '' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   As Mrs. Clinton spent the day in New York _ preparing for a
three-day swing across New York next week to announce that she is
creating an exploratory committee for a Senate run _ Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, a Republican who is seeking to challenge her, prepared to
fly to Mrs. Clinton's home town, Chicago, for a fund-raiser Tuesday
night. As part of the trip, Giuliani plans to attend a Chicago Cubs
baseball game, presumably in an attempt to lampoon Mrs. Clinton's
attempt to portray herself as a New York Yankees fan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Before coming to New York, Clinton spoke to about 60 Democratic
donors in Westport, Conn., at a luncheon that was expected to raise
$400,000. The president repeated earlier remarks in Washington
about a larger-than-expected federal budget surplus and called on
Republicans to work with him on measures to ensure the long-term
solvency of Medicare and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was introduced in Westport as a president taking a
well-deserved victory lap _ a characterization with which Clinton
took issue, suggesting that he still considered himself relevant in
national political debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel I'm on a victory lap or a final lap,'' Clinton
said with a laugh. ``They're beginning to talk to me as if I'm _
there is a sort of ring of eulogy about all of this. As far as I
can tell, I'm reasonably healthy, I still show up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
