<SLUG> BC-NJ-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN QUIETLY SIGNS BILL LIMITING TEEN-AGE ABORTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Avoiding the kind of public fanfare that she
often uses when she signs major legislation, Gov. Christie Whitman
signed into law Monday the first significant restriction on
abortion rights in New Jersey in more than 20 years, prohibiting a
girl younger than 18 from obtaining an abortion unless her parents
are notified.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman, who has built a national reputation as a moderate
Republican by supporting abortion rights, signed the measure in the
privacy of her office, just hours after conducting a highly
publicized bill-signing ceremony to enact the state's $19.5 billion
budget for fiscal year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey conservatives stunned many lawmakers in Trenton early
this month by quickly ushering the bill through the Legislature
during the last two weeks before summer recess. Whitman, who had
long opposed parental notification, acknowledged Monday that she
began negotiating with legislators after they presented her with a
bill that had been approved by a veto-proof majority.
</P>
<P>
   And she said she agreed to sign the bill only after persuading
its sponsors to include exceptions for pregnant teen-agers who can
prove to a judge that they are mature enough to make the decision
on their own and for cases in which there is evidence of physical,
sexual or emotional abuse by a parent or guardian.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation strikes a common-sense balance that
recognizes the rights of parents to know when a medical procedure
will be performed on their minor child, while preserving a young
woman's legal right to choose whether or not to have an abortion,''
the governor said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day she rejected suggestions that she was trying
to play down the abortion bill-signing, saying that she signed a
dozen measures Monday without public ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The new law, which will take effect in 90 days, will make New
Jersey the 39th state to require either parental notification or
parental consent for minors seeking abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion-rights supporters have pledged to challenge the
constitutionality of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Lenora Lapidus, legal coordinator for the American Civil
Liberties Union, said early this month that she believed the law
violated the state Constitution's guarantee of equal protection
because it would deny minors access to the same health care options
available to women over 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Jersey's state Supreme Court, in its past decisions, has
ruled that the state Constitution gives broader protection to
reproductive rights than the U.S. Constitution,'' said Ms. Lapidus,
noting that courts in four states have struck down parental
involvement laws. ``And we're confident that they will rule that
way in this case as well.''
</P>
<P>
   But abortion opponents say that similar bills have been upheld
in many other states, and that New Jersey's law was carefully
crafted to withstand a court challenge.
</P>
<P>
   John Tomicki, the conservative lobbyist who helped negotiate the
bill, said he suspected that any court challenge of the parental
notification law would be financed largely by abortion providers,
like Planned Parenthood, whose employees' livelihoods are at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that these people are putting profits in
front of parents' rights,'' said Tomicki, director of the League of
American Families.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
