<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEHRIG-AUCTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE GEHRIG FANTASY FOR REALLY BIG DOLLARS
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In historic terms, it is a sacred relic worn by a
36-year-old man two years from death. The size 46 pinstriped suit
is slightly faded, the fabric soft to the touch, but heavy for
summer wear. Yet even on a steamy morning, you're tempted to hop
the No. 4 train to 161st Street, sneak into the local ball park and
try it on.
</P>
<P>
   Still, you wouldn't dare because it is the uniform worn by Lou
Gehrig at Yankee Stadium on July 4, 1939, when, between games of a
doubleheader, he declared himself ``the luckiest man on the face of
the earth'' despite a diagnosis of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   And consider that the Leland's auction house in Manhattan hopes
to sell the simple flannel jersey and pants for at least $295,000
when telephone, fax and online bidding, which began last week,
concludes on July 9.
</P>
<P>
   So you would no more don the Gehrig uniform than you would
Abraham Lincoln's suit when he delivered the Gettysburg Address,
unless you are David Wells, who paid $35,000 for a 1934 Babe Ruth
cap and wore it when he pitched the first inning of a game in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fantasy piece, one of the top five you'd hope to
have,'' said Michael Heffner, the president of Leland's, as he
gazed at the uniform, freed from the protective plastic covering.
He was in a back room of the auction house, where items are packed
and unpacked and game-used autographed bats stand at attention.
</P>
<P>
   The Gehrig uniform is the most tantalizing item in an auction
that includes the home run ball Carlton Fisk hit in Game 6 of the
1975 World Series (retrieved and being sold by George Foster, the
Reds' left fielder), the ball Mickey Mantle hit off the Yankee
Stadium facade in 1956 and a saxophone given to Ruth by band leader
Paul Whiteman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a privilege to handle the thing _ you can't touch the
stuff at the Hall of Fame,'' Heffner said. ``It's a sacred piece,
but in reality, it's just flannel, which happened to be worn by
someone who was admired by a lot of people.'' Bidders should be
reminded: the uniform requires no dry cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   Up close, the pinstripes are bluer than you'd imagine.
``LGehrig'' is embroidered in orange thread in the neck of the
jersey and the waistband of the pants. A ``39'' is stitched into
the bottom of the jersey.
</P>
<P>
   By matching the pattern of pinstripes _ where they meet a button
or the ``N'' of the ``NY'' on the front of the jersey _ to
photographs of Gehrig delivering his speech, authenticators
declared the suit the true thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pinstripes match to a T,'' Heffner said.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Gehrig kept the uniform from 1941, when her husband
died, until the collector Barry Halper accompanied her to her
Manhattan apartment after the 1971 Yankee Old-Timers Day. ``She
asked me up, and walked ahead of me,'' he said. ``The doorman said,
`You must be special; she doesn't let anybody upstairs.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Halper recalled Mrs. Gehrig's East Side apartment, with doilies
on the sofa arm _ ``a typical elderly woman's apartment'' _ and
little memorabilia of her husband's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me she was thirsty, and I said, `Do you have any
soda?' '' Halper said. ``She said no, but she said she wanted some
hooch, a term I'd only heard in black-and-white movies. `That's
what I could use, some hooch.' I assumed it was liquor. She said,
`When you come back, I have something special for you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Halper went to a nearby liquor store, wondered how much to buy,
and settled on six bottles of J&AMP;B scotch. The ``something special''
was the uniform, which was hanging in a clothes closet. On a
photograph of her late husband, Mrs. Gehrig wrote to Halper: ``I
know Lou would want you have this.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago Monday, Halper sold it at auction to four buyers
from Ohio for $306,000. Recently, the Ohio buyers consigned the
uniform to Leland's to sell. If bids do not reach $295,000, it will
be taken off the block.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price is what the consignors wanted,'' Heffner said. ``I
would have preferred to start lower, but I didn't want to argue.''
</P>
<P>
   Halper figures the uniform has retained its value because it is
in such good shape _ ``he probably played no more than two weeks in
it'' _ and because Gehrig's speech remains such a powerful oration.
</P>
<P>
   If the sellers are lucky, they may match the buyer's frenzy that
led to the Guernsey's auction house's selling Mark McGwire's 62nd
home run ball for $3 million, the costliest item in sports
memorabilia. The next most expensive is a rare Honus Wagner tobacco
card, which sold for $640,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before our auction, Leland's sold a Babe Ruth ball for
$126,500,'' said Arlan Ettinger, the owner of Guernsey's. The ball,
which Ruth slugged for the first home run at Yankee Stadium, sold
for the most ever at auction. Ettinger projected a minimum price of
$1 million for the McGwire sphere, but the Canadian buyer tripled
that. ``That's about 23 times the world record for a ball. So we
were surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Leland's wants the highest possible price for Gehrig's uniform
but exerts no control over a buyer who would treat it with
disrespect. Last year, for example, the Upper Deck card company
paid $23,000 for a game-used Ruth bat, then chopped it into 200
pieces for random insertion into thousands of baseball card packs.
A spokesman said Monday the uniform's one-of-a-kind status and the
steep price would keep the company from bidding. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 2243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
