<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0421 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2622 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-DEBT-1STLD-WRI     06-28 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-DEBT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIT OF NATIONAL DEBT MAY BE BETTER THAN NO DEBT ALL, EXPERTS
SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS lede to change `will' to `would'; SUBS 13th graf, If the
government ... to clarify what could happen if the government stops
long-term borrowing; SUBS last graf to tighten and trim.) 
(With BUDGET-CLINTON, BUDGET-ASSESS) 
 (nk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton raised the mind-bending
possibility Monday that the giant national debt clock in midtown
Manhattan would soon start running in reverse _ and that by the
year 2015, the government would owe no money to investors around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   There is little question that Clinton described the general
direction of the clock correctly. Barring a stock market disaster
or a Japan-like recession, the federal government's $5.6 trillion
in debt, the figure on the clock, will begin diminishing in the
next few months. That number includes debt that the government owes
to itself.
</P>
<P>
   The more important figure _ debt that the government owes
individual investors, companies and governments around the world _
has actually been in decline for the last two years. How much it
can be reduced in 15 years is a far more problematic calculation,
dependent on a huge range of economic assumptions _ chiefly the
growth rate of the national economy _ that, given the inexact
nature of such things, are most likely subject to major revision.
</P>
<P>
   But even if this country could pay off all its debts in the next
15 years, many economists and some government officials say it
might not be as great an idea as it sounds. While huge debts in the
1980s and early 1990s were a tremendous drag on the economy, just a
bit of national debt may be a very good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost hard to imagine what this country would be like
debt-free,'' said Alan Sinai, the chief economist of Primark
Decision Systems, an economic consulting group. ``But while no
politician would want to admit it, the optimal debt for the United
States is probably not zero. What that optimal level should be,
though _ now that's a subject for a real national debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Without question, reducing the debt creates a host of advantages
for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   As the U.S. Treasury tames its appetite for borrowed money, it
no longer competes with homeowners looking for mortgages, for
example, or companies seeking to raise money. As a result, interest
rates have more room to fall.
</P>
<P>
   And as the debt declines _ Clinton's projections show that it
will fall below $3 trillion in 2005, and below $2 trillion in 2009
_ the amount of interest the government is forced to pay out each
year goes down substantially. That frees up even more cash, while
raising the national savings rate. And that, in turn, helps to
compensate for the free-spending ways of American consumers, who in
these boom times are barely saving.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may be the biggest single advantage,'' one of Clinton's
senior economic advisers said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But a debt-free United States, however, might create a more
complex, and some say a riskier, financial landscape around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   For investors around the world, there is no safer place to put
money than in U.S. Treasury bonds. When the Asian economic crisis
hit in 1997, and accelerated last year after the collapse of the
Russian economy, investors around the world put their assets into
Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   These investments help make the dollar the world's most popular
``reserve currency,'' the money other governments hold for economic
security in their central banks. And they give the United States a
subtle but significant economic clout around the world.
</P>
<P>
   If the government stops long-term borrowing, the money that
becomes available may stay in the United States, invested, say, in
mortgages or corporate debt. But if investors do not have the
security of investing in U.S. Treasuries, they may be less
interested in holding their cash in dollars, and that could affect
the dollar's value on world markets.
</P>
<P>
   Investors could put their money in another country's treasury
bonds _ say those issued by the new European Central Bank or the
Bank of Japan. But that requires taking a bet on the future of
European and Japanese currencies, adding a significant risk to the
investment.
</P>
<P>
   But is any of this likely to happen?
</P>
<P>
   That depends on a series of assumptions. The chief one is about
the future of the American economy. Clinton's projections, released
Monday, assume that the American economy will grow between 2.1
percent and 2.6 percent a year for the next 15 years. It made
similar bets for the past seven years, it was wrong every time. But
the surprise was pleasant: The economy expanded far faster, and for
far longer, than even the most optimistic government projections.
</P>
<P>
   The risk, of course, is that the next errors could be in the
opposite direction. That is exactly what happened to Japan, which
blithely assumed that the successes of the 1980s would extend into
the 1990s. It was the blunder of the decade, and the country now is
mounting up a huge debt as it tries to spend its way out of a
seven-year-long recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are difficult projections to make for even the next year
or two,'' Sinai said Monday, ``and even more difficult for beyond
that.''
</P>
<P>
   And that risk is accentuated by the fact that most of the
paydown of the debt is scheduled to occur between 2010 and 2015,
allowing plenty of time for economic and political miscalculation
or happenstance.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the government is closer to paying off the
debts that really matter than even Clinton indicated Monday. While
the debt clock reads $5.6 trillion, the figure that kicks around
the U.S. Treasury is less than half that: $2.77 trillion, when the
amount of debt held by the federal and state governments and the
Federal Reserve is subtracted. And under the president's
projections, the debt will be paid off around 2011.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
