<SLUG> BC-ABC-AFFILIATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC AND AFFILIATE STATIONS REACH FINANCIAL AGREEMENT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After months of often rancorous negotiations, ABC and
the board representing its affiliated stations struck a deal Monday
that will bring the network some much-needed cash to pay for the
heavy costs of professional football, while the affiliates will
receive more commercials to sell in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ABC also agreed to some limitations on how it will re-use
programs in the future, a point of intense disagreement with the
affiliates, especially after ABC announced in April that it was
starting up a soap opera cable channel consisting of same-day
repeats of shows carried by ABC stations.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, in the new three-year deal, ABC will receive $45
million a year from the affiliates, which it will apply to the $550
million in annual costs for ``Monday Night Football.'' The network
will also receive 10 commercials in the Saturday morning block of
cartoons that had previously been controlled by the stations.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the affiliates will receive eight commercials a
week in prime time from the network. ABC is not giving up its own
commercials, however, but is carving out eight more commercials
from promotion and other nonprogram time, though Patricia
Fili-Krushel, the president of ABC, said the network might simply
add some commercials to prime time each week. She estimated the
value of the overall deal to ABC at $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   The affiliates also extracted some promises from ABC not to
change the number of commercials they have the opportunity to sell,
as the Fox network did when it reclaimed 20 commercials from the
affiliates. The affiliates have also been given a financial stake
in the Soap Opera Channel.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will limit ABC, a unit of the Walt Disney Co., to
re-use other entertainment programming on cable channels only after
180 days have passed since the time the program ran on the network.
</P>
<P>
   But ABC gained other less restrictive ``repurposing rights'' on
cable as the re-use of programming is being called, including
unlimited use of any ``breaking news'' programming after a delay of
four hours on such programs as ``Nightline'' and ``The View,'' 60
days on news magazines, 48 hours on sports programs and awards
shows and 60 days on mini-series.
</P>
<P>
   Networks increasingly are looking to re-use programs on cable
channels and, in the future, digital channels, to establish new
profit centers.
</P>
<P>
   David Barrett, the executive vice president of Hearst-Argyle
Television and a member of the affiliate negotiating committee,
said he hoped the deal could ``serve as a template for future deals
between affiliates and networks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
