A2624 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-EXPOS29-CO     06-28 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-EXPOS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A. Jones' HRs bury Expos 13-5
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Given the remote possibility that baseball won't die
of its own natural causes in this town, they tried poisoning it
here Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Millwood was not sharp, the Braves infield was a little
duller and it didn't matter. Montreal bailed out the Braves with a
dismal pitching performance in a 13-5 runaway that taxed the
fortitude of the 7,078 who paid to see it.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta tested the game's scoring limits, scoring four times off
a pair of Andruw Jones home runs, twice off sacrifice flies and
once off a wild pitch. Ryan Klesko drove in four runs, Brian Jordan
scored three times and the Braves won for 10th time in 14 games,
stretching their NL East lead to 4 1/2 games over idle New York.
</P>
<P>
   As an added bonus, there was a bench-empyting incident in the
seventh after Jones' second homer when Anthony Telford plunked
Randall Simon on the right elbow. But while the Braves scrambled
all over the infield to keep Simon away from Telford, the Expos
remarkably remained in their dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood (9-4) earned the victory but last just five innings
after throwing 92 pitches. He was charged with five runs, though
two were unearned because of errors by Chipper Jones and Bret
Boone.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal closed to 8-3 in the fourth, thanks to some defensive
malpractice by Atlanta. Orlando Cabrera reached first when Boone
dropped his pop-up, and Manny Martinez's infield single moved him
to third.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood appeared to be out of the inning when Fernando
Seguignol hit a pop foul behind third base, but neither Chipper
Jones nor Ozzie Guillen could find the ball, and given another
swing, Seguignol brought in an unearned run with a single.
</P>
<P>
   After struggling through a 32-pitch first inning, when he walked
two batters, hit a third and gave up an RBI single to Vladimir
Guerrero, Millwood never really found his rhythm. Montreal scored a
second run in the third inning on a single, a double and a Guerrero
ground-out.
</P>
<P>
   Expos starter Miguel Batista didn't make it out of the second,
giving up seven hits to the 10 batters that manager Felipe Alou
allowed him to face.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta brutalized Batista immediately, scoring five runs in the
first five at-bats. Jordan delivered a bases-loaded sacrifice fly,
and Klesko made it 2-0 with an RBI single. Still with no outs,
Andruw Jones next launched a 1-1 fastball into the left field
stands for the Braves' second three-run homer in three games and a
5-0 lead.Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
