<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2626 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT     06-28 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y., N.J.) 
GOLDEN OPPORTUNITIES 
SHAPE OF THINGS TO COME 
HOSPITAL STYLE
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To every thing there is a season, the Bible says. For
jewelry the biggest season is the year-end holiday time, and this
year the extra added attraction of the millennium has jewelry
makers and retailers rubbing their hands in anticipation of another
year of record sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last five years have seen consecutive growth in jewelry
sales,'' said Lynn Ramsey, president of the Jewelry Information
Center, a trade group. ``Sales are healthier than for many luxury
items, and we expect them to continue, especially with the
millennium. It presents a great marketing opportunity. We believe
that pieces stamped 1999-2000 will become family heirlooms.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jewelers of America's annual business survey of independent
retail jewelers showed an average sales growth of 9.3 percent for
1998. For total retail sales of all jewelry, ``our guesstimate is
$40 billion in the United States,'' Ms. Ramsey said. That would
include $13.7 billion in gold jewelry (up 8 percent) and $22
billion for diamond jewelry alone, representing a 4 percent
increase in the number of pieces sold.
</P>
<P>
   That may be why QVC is getting on the diamond bandwagon with the
Promise Diamond collection to be offered for sale from 8 to 10
Tuesday night. The line of 40 styles of women's and men's rings,
pendants and earrings in 14-karat gold costs from $185 to $5,800.
Invited guests will get a preview of the jewelry at a lunch here
Tuesday at Le Cirque 2000, so sales hopes must be high.
</P>
<P>
   QVC reports that jewelry, including silver, gold and gemstones,
accounts for nearly one-third of its year-round on-the-air
marketing. Although the company won't give figures on jewelry
sales, it does say that total sales for last year were more than
$2.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   SHAPES OF THINGS TO COME
</P>
<P>
   Some jewelers of note showed their new designs for the
millennium to the press at informal presentations last week. These
included additions to Baccarat's line of crystal jewelry, this one
called Tentation and based on the shape of the olive (for those,
perhaps, who will toast the new century with a martini), and Fred
Joaillier's curvaceous Mouvementee rings, earrings, bracelets and
pendants in sleek gold or set with precious stones.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany's offerings ranged from Elsa Peretti's new lacquer
pendants in bean or round shapes to Jean Schlumberger's corsage
bracelet with six raised flowers, each different, of diamonds and
pearls.
</P>
<P>
   Cartier is going for a younger, more casual look, which Simon
Critchell, the chief executive, describes as ``nice purchases, not
crazy at all.'' They include unadorned gold rings with flat square
tops, gold chains that look like pop-apart key chains and that can
be worn in multiples of different lengths, and tank rings of heavy
gold set with one big stone.
</P>
<P>
   HOSPITAL STYLE
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Rowley is likely to be a popular designer with some
hospital patients. She has come up with hospital gowns and pajamas
that preserve modesty and dignity by providing coverage for backs,
which standard-issue gowns expose.
</P>
<P>
   There are two women's gowns, one mid-calf style with snaps down
the back, a mock turtleneck and three-quarter-length sleeves; the
other, ankle-length, pulls over the head, with a drawstring scooped
neck, which allows a new mother to breast-feed. For men there are
drawstring pajama pants with a snap-front shirt and a matching
robe. Children get calf-length snap-back gowns with optional
drawstring panties.
</P>
<P>
   But these styles will be seen only at Hackensack University
Medical Center in New Jersey, which commissioned them and will get
them in the fall. But maybe Ms. Rowley can interest other hospitals
in providing more coverup for patients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
