<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2628 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPUBS-CONSERVATIVES-     06-28 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-CONSERVATIVES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LACONIA, N.H.: my enemy.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a Republican barbecue on Sunday at the Belknap County 4-H
Fairgrounds near here, Elizabeth Dole, who runs a distant second to
Bush in most polls, said in an interview that the party needed to
be more pragmatic.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to her view that the party need not press for a
constitutional amendment on abortion, she said: ``This is a
dead-end discussion because it's not going to happen. Let's don't
fight each other in the party over something that doesn't have a
chance of happening. We're just churning and spending energy within
the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Such talk infuriates Smith. In weighing a third-party bid, he
said he was worried that in the eagerness to broaden its appeal the
Republican Party was forfeiting its principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we have one political party in America: It's run by
moderate Democrats and moderate Republicans, and conservatives are
stuck,'' Smith said in an interview. ``If you talk to conservative
activists there's a lot of frustration. I have no desire to see the
demise of the party. But I'm not going to see our views
compromised.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Bush's impressive support, many conservatives are even
more unsettled because there are so many conservatives vying for
the nomination that their field is fractured and no one has emerged
to take on the leading candidate. Smith, Quayle, Buchanan and
Bauer, the former head of the Family Research Council, are
competing on the right with Steve Forbes, the wealthy publisher,
and Keyes, a former State Department official.
</P>
<P>
   One candidate on the right who seemed to be gaining steam among
conservatives last year was Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri. But he
decided not to make the race, in part because he faces a tough
re-election challenge in 2000. Compounding the difficulties is the
fact that religious conservative groups seem to be losing
influence, particularly the Christian Coalition, which has been in
turmoil in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The activists can't get together on one candidate,'' Smith
said. ``If all of us were one candidate instead of split up, we'd
have 15 to 20 percent in the polls right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans have little sympathy for such talk. They say
conservatives should be grateful that Bush is playing smart
politics as Bill Clinton did in 1992 when he moderated his
positions and called for welfare reform, a balanced budget and a
middle-class tax cut. As Clinton did, Bush is following more of a
general election strategy _ appeal to the broadest base of support
_ in the primaries. For now at least, polls show that it seems to
be working.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers say they are confident that the governor is
popular enough to withstand attacks from conservatives without
moving to the right. Still, the hope among Democrats is that Bush
will be forced to appeal more to conservatives, which would make
him more vulnerable in a general election, when he would want to
win votes from independents and even Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among conservatives there is an enormous frustration because
the party isn't what it was four years ago,'' said Roger Stone, a
Republican strategist who is a moderate. ``The Christian Coalition
is in hard times. There's a tremendous thirst in the party to win.
Therefore, it seems to me that Bush is getting the pass that Dole
didn't get. I don't see any of these other guys getting any
traction.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dave Philbrick, a conservative from Dover, is among those
who said he would not succumb to the allure of Bush as a candidate
who might win the general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather,'' Philbrick said, ``go to bed with a clear
conscience after losing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
