</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDURAN-IMMIG-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU--NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUCK FINN REVERSED: HONDURAN BOY HAS 3,200-MILE SOLO ODYSSEY TO
SEEK HIS FATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: ADDS 15th graf, Honduran consular officials ..., to add
authorities checking into boy's account; combines takes.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo and map are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By SUSAN SACHS and JASON BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alone in the world but for the father he had never
seen, a determined 13-year-old boy equipped with a little money and
enough pluck to charm a string of helpful strangers, set out for
New York City from his hurricane-devastated village in Honduras
last month to find his father.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, Edwin Daniel Sabillon, carrying a paper bag with a
change of clothes, his birth certificate and three cookies, arrived
on a bus from Miami on Sunday. With the aplomb that carried him
through his 3,200-mile journey, he hailed a cab and went looking
for his father.
</P>
<P>
   He did not find him. But the police, who picked the boy up after
being alerted by the concerned taxi driver, said Monday that they
will take up Edwin's search.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary concern is that he is reunited with his father,''
said Capt. Thomas Kelly, of the Bronx Detectives.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin, he added, has nothing to worry about. Although he entered
the country illegally, the boy's story has touched the
highest-ranking heart in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's under the protective custody of the mayor's office,''
Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the youngster is in the hands of the city's
Administration for Childrens Services, which Monday was arranging
for him to spend the night with a Spanish-speaking foster family
while the police continued to hunt for his father.
</P>
<P>
   The father was identified as Grevi Sabillon Vasquez. Detectives
said they do not know what the father does, where in the city he
lives, or whether he is a legal or illegal immigrant. What they do
know about him comes, essentially, from the bits and pieces of
information they gleaned from Edwin.
</P>
<P>
   The boy said he wrote to his father last year, after Hurricane
Mitch roared through Honduras and wrecked his home in Colonia San
Miguel, a suburb of the capital Tegucigalpa. A mudslide, apparently
triggered by the torrential rains of the storm, had killed his
mother, Angela Enamorado, and his 14-year-old brother, Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the father wrote back. As recounted by the police,
who read the letter, he instructed the boy to come to New York
City. He said he would meet him at the entrance to LaGuardia
Airport. He gave three rendezvous dates: June 25, 26 and 27. I will
be wearing a white shirt, black pants, white sneakers and a black
hat, the father wrote, but I will recognize you.
</P>
<P>
   Then the father sent $200 by wire to Honduras and on May 22,
Edwin left the house of friends in San Francisco de Yojoa Cortez,
and set out on a journey that would take him 37 days.
</P>
<P>
   The adventures along the way that he recounted to detectives
sound like the Huckleberry Finn tale in reverse: A stubborn boy
sets out on the road to join his father, steals across the borders
of three countries, gives the slip to lawmen along the way, loses
his possessions and gets rescued by a succession of good
Samaritans.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, it is also an improbable tale of luck and
generosity along a route that most often is paved with hardship and
greed.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin said he hitchhiked up the Honduran coast through Guatemala
and into Mexico. In Matamoros, a town bordering Texas, he said he
won the sympathy of smugglers who agreed to arrange his passage for
free. The normal price for the often hazardous and sometimes deadly
journey is $5,000, according to lawyers who work with Central
American immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Honduran consular officials in New York and the police were
checking details of the boy's account and his background.
</P>
<P>
   According to the boy's account, he then found a ride to Houston
and then, inexplicably, went to Miami. Somewhere along the way, he
lost his wallet with most of the money his father had sent him and
the slip of paper on which he had written his father's address.
</P>
<P>
   But his luck held. In Miami, he found his way to the Natasha
Cafeteria, where the Cuban-American owner and his patrons took the
boy in blue jeans and a yellow T-shirt into their embrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a five-dollar bill in his hand and he was asking for
change _ four dollars in quarters to take a bus to take him to I-95
North to see how he could get to New York,'' recalled Emilio Jose
Jimenez, who was in the cafeteria last Saturday when Edwin turned
up.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, he said, seemed educated and well-mannered. The
customers took up a collection to buy him an $87 bus ticket so
Edwin would not have to hitchhike, gave him pocket money for food,
took him to the bus station, and bade him goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin arrived in New York City at about 2 p.m. on Sunday. The
police said he got off the bus at 177th Street and Broadway and
then did what most newcomers do: He gaped.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's walking around, he's amazed by the tall buildings, all
the hustle and bustle, where's the countryside,'' said Det. Gilbert
Ramirez, recounting how the boy described his first hours in the
new city.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday evening, at 8:30, Edwin was spotted by Jose Basora, a
35-year-old taxi driver who emigrated from the Dominican Republic
10 years ago. At first, Basora said, he thought Edwin was one of
the battalion of young boys who sell flowers in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him looking at me, he was smiling, he was happy,''
Basora recalled. ``Then he came to me and asked me if I can take
him to the airport and how much it would be. I found this strange
because he was a little boy. The light turned green, I told him to
get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwin soon told him of his search for his father. Basora, moved
by the story, drove him around the edges of the airport for 15
minutes, trying various entrances. When he could find no sign of
the father, who had not specified a time for his son to meet him,
the two drove to Basora's home in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, after making sure Edwin showered and buying him
some in-line skates, Basora went with the boy to the 43rd Precinct
nearby. Edwin slept there Sunday night and Monday he gorged on
hamburgers and ice cream and slept some more.
</P>
<P>
   Eyleen Schmidt, a spokeswoman for the Immigration and
Naturalization Service in Washington, said that Edwin may have
several options for remaining in the United States, depending on
his father's status.
</P>
<P>
   If the father is in the country legally, he may petition to have
his son join him. If he is not here legally, he may apply up until
July 5 for a temporary work permit through a six-month-old federal
program intended for Honduran immigrants in the aftermath of
Hurricane Mitch. Ms. Schmidt said that the immigration agency would
then recommend that Edwin be allowed to stay with his father for as
long as the work permit is valid.
</P>
<P>
   The police said they are monitoring an overpass near LaGuardia
Airport because they believe Vasquez, the boy's father, may have
meant that location for the meeting with his son.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said the police, the children's services
agency and his office would do what they could to find Vasquez.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do the best that we can to try to help him,'' the mayor
said. ``I think that's the only fair and decent thing to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
