<SLUG> BC-REMOVAL-HEALTHYLUNG-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Suit: Doctor cut out parts of healthy lung
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Van Sickler
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   FORT PIERCE, Fla. _ Lawnwood Regional Medical Center has been
named in a lawsuit claiming that the hospital tried to cover up a
misdiagnosis of cancer that led to the removal of portions of a
healthy lung from a 61-year-old Navy veteran.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart, Fla. attorney Willie Gary filed the suit on behalf of
John Hawley, claiming that Lawnwood not only failed to properly
examine, evaluate and treat Hawley, but also conspired to conceal
lab evidence that Hawley's lung was healthy before and after parts
of it were removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case about a cover-up,'' Gary said at a news
conference Monday. ``The worst kind imaginable.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the complaint, Hawley, now 63, went to the Lawnwood
emergency room in December 1997 complaining of shortness of breath,
fever and chills.
</P>
<P>
   Hawley told the doctor that he was a former smoker, and that he
quit in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint said that Hawley was admitted to the hospital for
pneumonia, and during the stay, a biopsy of Hawley's right middle
lobe was reviewed by the hospital's pathology lab.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor concluded, incorrectly according to the lawsuit, that
the lung was cancerous.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, portions of Hawley's right lung were removed.
</P>
<P>
   Those portions were sent to the pathology lab and studied, but
this time, the portions showed no sign of cancer, according to the
suit.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of telling Hawley about these results, his doctors told
him they had removed all of the cancer, the lawsuit states.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when he reviewed his medical history, Hawley found out
that he never had cancer. That's when he contacted the law firm of
Gary, Williams, Parenti, Finney, Lewis, McManus, Watson, &AMP;
Sperando.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little mad,'' Hawley said Monday. ``Somebody cut my
lungs half off and for no reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Lawnwood Regional Medical Center have not seen the
lawsuit and could not comment, said spokeswoman Janie Hellstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Van Sickler writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
