A2766 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT &LR;      06-28 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORGANIZERS OF TOUR DE FRANCE HOPING TO MAKE A CHAMPION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ That hum coming from the headquarters of the Tour de
France is an ancient mantra: It's not champions who make the Tour;
it's the Tour that makes champions.
</P>
<P>
   The chant is sounded whenever, like this year, the world's
greatest bicycle race is bereft of some of its biggest names. So
bereft is the 86th edition that, for the first time in memory,
there will probably not be a single previous Tour winner at the
starting line in western France on July 3.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Indurain, the Spaniard who won from 1991 to 1995, is long
retired. Bjarne Riis, the Dane who triumphed in 1996, is out with a
broken right arm after a fall in the Tour of Switzerland this
month. Jan Ullrich, his German successor in 1997, is at home with
pain in his right knee after a crash in the Tour of Germany a few
weeks ago. And Marco Pantani, last year's hero, is in Italy both
sulking and under a cloud after he failed a blood test in the Giro
d'Italia early this month.
</P>
<P>
   Many other stars are on the sidelines, too, including Laurent
Jalabert (also sulking), Michele Bartoli (injured), and Richard
Virenque and Francesco Casagrande (spurned by the organizers).
Their absence, however, does not necessarily mean that the race
will be wide open.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who can win this year,'' said Bobby
Julich, the 27-year-old American rider for the Cofidis team who
finished third in the last Tour. When pressed, he could not come up
with an especially long list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Myself,'' he started, ``Lance, of course,'' referring to Lance
Armstrong, the American leader of the U.S. Postal Service team.
``Olano, Zulle, Boogerd. Perhaps Vinokourov can pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously not the usual suspects. I think it's going to be
young, up-and-coming talent, hopefully myself included.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet most of those names are familiar in Tour final standings.
Abraham Olano, 29, a Spaniard with ONCE who looks and sounds like
Indurain and sometimes even rides like him, having finished fourth
in the Tour two years ago, has been an outside favorite before. So
has Alex Zulle, 31, a Swiss now with Banesto, who finished second
in the race four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Boogerd, 27, a Dutchman with Rabobank and the winner of
the Paris-Nice stage race this year, finished fifth in the 1998
Tour. ``He's a class act,'' Julich said, and observers agree,
making him the early favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Vinokourov, 25, a Kazakh with Casino, seems ready in
his Tour debut to move up in quality from the lesser races he has
been winning for two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   As for Armstrong, 27, he has ridden strongly the last month in
time trials and in the mountains _ the keys to winning the Tour _
but has finished the three-week race only once.
</P>
<P>
   The list may be shortened or altered when the 20 invited teams
of nine riders each gather in Le Puy du Fou, the starting point for
the 3,680-kilometer (2,286-mile) trek clockwise around France, with
a foray into Italy. Olano's ONCE team has threatened to defy the
organizers and attempt to bring along two officials who have been
banned in the ongoing drug scandals. If they are refused
credentials, the team has said, it may withdraw, as it did last
year to protest the police investigation of doping.
</P>
<P>
   Whether any of the three other Spanish teams would follow ONCE,
as they did last year, is doubtful but unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   Another unknown factor is Pantani's state of mind. He began
complaining immediately after the Tour unveiled its schedule last
fall _ a prologue, two long time trials and 18 other daily stages.
</P>
<P>
   By Pantani's lights, the mountains were not challenging enough
and the time trials were too long. Before he was ejected from the
Giro, he often said that he would not ride in the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   He is still saying that, despite heavy pressure from his
sponsors and friends to take his revenge in France for the
humiliation in Italy. His Mercatone Uno team is invited to the Tour
and, at the moment, is due to be led by Stefano Garzelli, 26,
another fine Italian climber, if not one in Pantani's class.
</P>
<P>
   What happens if Pantani changes his mind and decides to ride the
Tour? He has served his two-week suspension and is, at least
theoretically, eligible to participate.
</P>
<P>
   But the organizers withdrew an invitation to the Vini Caldirola
team from Italy on June 18 after one of its best riders, Sergei
Honchar, failed the same blood test in the Tour of Switzerland that
Pantani did. Honchar would have completed his suspension the day
before the Tour de France started and thus also would have been
theoretically eligible.
</P>
<P>
   If Pantani does not turn up, it will be the first time in three
decades that a Tour winner who was still competing and not injured
failed to defend his championship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
