<HEADLINE>
THE BAILING OUT OF SPORTS AGENTS: IS IT BUSINESS OR FEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The easy cheap shot _ and who am I to
resist? _ is that it's the classic case of rats abandoning the
sinking ship.
</P>
<P>
   If it were true, this cataclysmic upheaval in the world of
sports would make the Titanic look like the Minnow, washing up on
``Gilligan's Island''.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, that's not Ginger and the Professor tiptoeing
through the sand. These people leave Godzilla-sized footprints in
their wake.
</P>
<P>
   The would-be ``rats'' are sports agents and the ``sinking ship''
is baseball, but don't believe everything you hear until the cash
register stops ringing.
</P>
<P>
   There's big business doings afoot in the land of sports and
games, yet it almost slipped by somewhere in the fine print, filed
innocently under that oh-so-benign heading, ``Transactions.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks Brother sports agency: Sold.
</P>
<P>
   David Falk sports agency: Sold.
</P>
<P>
   ProServ: Sold.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the biggest sports agencies in the business, selling
out just like that, and rumors flying that superagents Leigh
Steinberg and Jeff Moorad will be right behind, divesting
themselves of the baseball-side of their operation for a whopping
$50 million, if you believe one published report.
</P>
<P>
   These are definitely not nickel-and-dime operations we're
talking about here and while agents in general have rightfully
earned something of a slimy reputation, these are the granddaddy
bullfrogs in the pond, folks who are well-respected _ and sometimes
even genuflected to _ throughout their industry.
</P>
<P>
   Falk is an NBA heavyweight, even charged by some insiders as the
man behind the NBA labor dispute that almost cost the league its
1999 season. Alan and Randy Hendricks, whose client list includes
Roger Clemens, announced their sale last week. Both were bought out
by SFX Entertainment of Houston, and then re-signed to employee
service contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, speculation is rampant in baseball that these
heavyweights in the agent industry are getting out while the
getting is good, before the next catastrophic labor showdown when
the current Basic Agreement is up in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Fascinating gossip, says Moorad, but just not true. And that
includes the $50 million he and Steinberg are supposedly about to
bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be nice,'' an amused Moorad said yesterday. ``I
just wish somebody had told me about it. Please know that we're not
getting out of the baseball business. That's the furthest thing
from the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Might we do something at some point, partner with a larger
group? Yes. We've talked to SFX and we've been talking to a
financial services group that would obviously be interested in
having access to our clients. But we haven't done anything yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The key word in that sentence is obviously ``yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Moorad, who will have lunch with his latest star client today in
Anaheim _ one Ruben Mateo, Texas Ranger _ points out that he and
Steinberg have been through labor strife before. It doesn't scare
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between you and me, I'm not running from it,'' he said.
``That's preposterous. Labor problems are part of the landscape of
sports and not just something that's exclusive to baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   This _ a large company gobbling up smaller ones to form an even
larger entity _ is simply another evolution in the big business of
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a couple of big players in the market, looking
to acquire these businesses, and there are a couple of agencies in
the latter stages of their maturity whose principles are in their
late 50s and they are ready to cash out,'' is the way Barry
Meister, who represents Rangers' infielder Luis Alicea, sees it.
``For the companies which are doing the buying, this provides a
ready source of athletes for the other things they do. SFX may see
an opportunity to work both ends of the ledger.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, I have several old W2 forms on file with ``SFX''
stamped them. At one time, SFX owned KRLD radio, among other
stations nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Bob Sillerman, whose reputation as a cutthroat business
man is widespread in the broadcast industry, was a partner of Steve
Hicks, Tom Hicks' brother, before they sold their radio operations
to Capstar. It was later acquired by Tom Hicks' company,
Hicks-Muse.
</P>
<P>
   Now Sillerman is obviously trying to put together an
entertainment conglomerate that links the entertainment industry
with high profile professional athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agent business is so oriented to giving the client special
service, it'll be interesting to see if it'll work this way,''
former Rangers president Tom Schieffer said. ``There are a lot of
egos involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine \Rthe agents\S are saying, `Hey, I can't believe
these guys will pay this much for it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sort of like the former Rangers ownership group when Tom Hicks
came along with that $250 million check, huh Tom?
</P>
<P>
   ``No comment,'' I think he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to tell the way he was giggling.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
