<SLUG> BC-BBA-MATEO-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE INJURY SETBACK, FUTURE APPEARS BRIGHT FOR MATEO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ A week ago, the Rangers' future came up
limping with a strained groin.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Mateo, who had been called up to replace an injured Tom
Goodwin in center field, was placed on the disabled list himself
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But never fear Rangers fans: Expect to see your future center
fielder back again in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to pay to come to the ballpark just to watch
him one day,'' says Rangers reserve infielder Luis Alicea, a
veteran of nine major-league seasons. ``That's how good he is. He's
unbelievable, and he's got that much talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite struggling through his first taste of top-of-the-line
major-league pitching, Mateo showed flashes of the player he can be
in the bigs. Facing pitchers such as Roger Clemens, David Cone and
Pedro Martinez, Mateo hit one home run, had four doubles and three
runs batted in for 33 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo's first 10 games in the major leagues did not produce
eye-popping statistics. But the Rangers and most of major-league
baseball are high enough on him that nearly every team attempting
to do business with the Rangers mentions his name as a potential
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Manny Batista, the Rangers' Latin America scouting coordinator,
predicted as early as four years ago that Mateo would be a hit once
he made it to the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw Ruben in 1995, he reminded me of Raul Mondesi and
Sammy Sosa,'' Batista said. ``The first time I saw him, I thought:
`Something is there. This guy can be an All-Star in the future.'''
</P>
<P>
   That would explain why Toronto general manager Gord Ash sought
Mateo in February during the Rangers' attempts to acquire
right-hander Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of parting with Mateo made some in the
organization uncomfortable, and the Rangers' proposal put a ``knot
in my stomach,'' general manager Doug Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough deal for us to do,'' Melvin said. ``We were not
all in agreement on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays eventually traded Clemens to New York for
left-handed pitchers David Wells and Graeme Lloyd and infielder
Homer Bush, but the Rangers' inclusion of Mateo in their proposal
drove up the price the Yankees paid.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo recognizes the expectations on him, but says they do not
intimidate him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can be better than what people say,'' Mateo said
quietly while sitting in front of his locker in the Rangers'
clubhouse at The Ballpark in Arlington last week. ``I just have to
work hard, but I enjoy what I'm doing. I love to play baseball.
It's my life, and I want to be the best at what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can do better, but I've faced'' the Yankees'
Clemens, Cone, Orlando Hernandez and Hideki Irabu and Boston's
Pedro Martinez, Mateo said. ``Those are the best pitchers in the
league.''
</P>
<P>
   But according to one major-league scout, Mateo did not appear to
be overmatched.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates also noticed his potential. ``He has so much
ability,'' Rangers right fielder Juan Gonzalez said. ``He has all
the tools to become a superstar. He can run. He can throw. He can
hit. He he can hit for power, and he's a good outfielder, too.
We're going to see him for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, the Rangers' two-time American League most valuable
player, could offer a glimpse of what Mateo might become.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez spent only one season at then-Triple-A Oklahoma City
and played there at the age of 20. Gonzalez hit .258 with a
league-best 29 home runs and 101 RBI during 128 games.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo, 21, ranked fourth among Pacific Coast League hitters in
batting average (.340) and home runs (17) and second in RBI (58)
during 59 games with the RedHawks before his promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``A kid with that much talent and to have had as much success as
him will tend to be arrogant and cocky and let it go to his head,''
Alicea said. ``He's not that way. Now, he's very confident in
himself and what he does, but he's not cocky. He's very humble and
very professional. That's a good sign.''
</P>
<P>
   It serves as another reason why the sky could be the limit for
Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   Batista sees Mateo, Gonzalez and Sosa as the best three
prospects he's seen to come from Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan Gonzalez is Juan Gonzalez,'' Batista said. ``Sammy Sosa
is Sammy Sosa, but I think Ruben could be in their class in the
future.'' d nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
