<SLUG> BC-BKN-JOHNSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE A HANGER-ON, NOW A HERO, JOHNSON IS AN INSPIRATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DONALD EMMONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ With nearly a hundred basketball campers
watching yesterday, San Antonio Spurs guard Avery Johnson fired up
a mid-range, baseline jump shot that clanged off the side of the
rim at the Elzie Odom Recreation Center.
</P>
<P>
   He re-set, tried again and made the shot reminiscent of the one
he hit in the closing seconds of Game 5 of the NBA Finals on Friday
night at New York's Madison Square Garden that delivered the Spurs'
first championship.
</P>
<P>
   The message yesterday from Johnson to this group of 7- to
14-year-olds attending the weeklong camp was clear: Keep trying.
It's a message he has preached regularly at summer camps during his
11-year NBA career. Even though he was less than 72 hours removed
from sinking the biggest shot of his life, Johnson still seemed to
be the same person who kept trying long before he became an NBA
hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank God for the opportunity to be here,'' said Johnson,
who was known in the past more for his high-pitched voice than for
his outside shooting. ``I'm very blessed to be in this situation,
and it's not just because we won the championship or I hit the shot
that won the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really blessed to be here because I've had a lot of ups
and downs in my career. But it's through perseverance that I'm
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colony High School basketball coach Tommy Thomas, director
of the Premier All-Star Basketball Camp, says he wasn't concerned
that Johnson might bail out on his commitment because of a busy
weekend of celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always been good about coming,'' Thomas said. ``He came
to the camp when the Spurs were 20-62 \Rin 1996-97\S and said a lot
of the same things. The only difference was the \Rcampers\S didn't
listen to him as much because he hadn't hit the last shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``His heart is still the same, and he still cares about kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson spoke for approximately an hour, talking about his
journey to and through the NBA, and his game-winning shot. His
17-foot jumper gave the Spurs a 78-77 victory against the New York
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still hasn't sunk in yet,'' Johnson said in response to a
question about being an NBA champion.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson attends basketball camps remembering how important they
were to his development as a player and a person. He also recalls
meeting NBA legends such as ``Pistol'' Pete Maravich and George
Gervin at camps while growing up in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Camp coordinator Mike Welch said Johnson _ a 5-foot-11 playmaker
who went undrafted and was let go by the Spurs in 1992 and '93
before rejoining them in '94 _ is an ideal camp speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our purpose is to get a \Rprofessional\S in here and to give
these kids a little insight on what it took for them to make it to
the big time,'' Welch said. ``Somebody like Avery, who was
handicapped size-wise, worked his way up through the \RU.S.
Basketball League\S, up to being a marginal NBA player to the
ultimate: winning an NBA championship.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
