<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENTURA POWERS METS OVER MARLINS, 10-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ When Robin Ventura has homered with more than one man on
base this season, the Mets have yet to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Monday evening, at a mostly deserted Pro Player Stadium, Ventura
hit a pair of three-run home runs to power the Mets and Al Leiter
to a 10-4 rout of the hapless Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the 16th in the last 21 games for the Mets
(43-33), who remained four games behind the Atlanta Braves in the
National League East. The Braves beat Montreal, 13-5.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter (7-5), who fell behind 2-0 early, won for the fifth
straight time. He allowed three runs and seven hits in 6 1/3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura's first home run, off righty Brian Meadows (5-9) with
one out in the fourth, gave the Mets a 3-2 lead. Ventura's second
home run, off left-hander Vic Darensbourg, capped a six-run fifth
and made it a 9-2 game.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, in the stadium where the Mets' season had
started nearly three months ago, Mets manager Bobby Valentine was
asked what he has learned about his team.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine talked about the emergence of both Benny Agbayani and
Roger Cedeno, about how well Edgardo Alfonzo and Rey Ordonez have
worked together, about Rickey Henderson not being over the hill.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine also mentioned how well his bullpen has fit together
and how resilient this team has been.
</P>
<P>
   There was a pause. And then Valentine said: ``I think Robin's
blended in well. I think he adds a lot to the group.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 20, Ventura hit a pair of grand slams, one in each game
of a doubleheader sweep of the Milwaukee Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Ventura had his first multiple home-run game with
the Mets, with whom he signed a 4-year, $32 million deal during the
off-season. There were those who wondered if the Mets had overpaid
for an infielder who will turn 32 on July 14 and who had just
endured two subpar offensive seasons while plagued by injuries. But
Ventura might have been a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   The only down note for Ventura was his seventh-inning throwing
error, while trying for a double play after he had snagged a line
drive. That snapped a club-record streak of 12 consecutive
errorless games. The error was the fourth of the season for
Ventura, a five-time Gold Glove winner.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura is putting together an all-star season at the plate.
Through the Mets' first 76 games, Ventura has 15 home runs, second
on the team to Mike Piazza's 16, and a team-high 59 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, who also has eight solo homers and three two-run homers
this year, is on pace for 32 home runs and 126 runs batted in. He
has led the Mets in runs batted in for most of this season and is
now in the top 10 in the National League after Monday night's
outburst.
</P>
<P>
   And 14 of those runs batted in have come on two memorable days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-28-99 2323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
