<DOCNO> NYT19990628.0435 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-28 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2773 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRISONBREAK-MANHUNT-C     06-28 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISONBREAK-MANHUNT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Killer sought after prison break
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ More than 250 armed searchers intensified a
dragnet in river swamps near Huntsville on Monday for a convicted
Dallas killer who escaped from Texas' highest-security prison in an
episode described by authorities as worthy of a Superman caper.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shed all of his clothes _ everything _ after he got out
and, at this point, we believe he is naked in an area that is
heavily infested with poison ivy,'' said Glen Castlebury, a
spokesman for the Texas Department of Criminal Justice. ``Even so,
we consider him to be extremely dangerous. He has a long history of
combative and assaultive comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Clifford Dwayne Jones' escape from the Estelle High-Security
Unit on Sunday afternoon was the first from a Texas prison this
year and the first from the ``super max'' lockup, as the unit is
called. It came seven months to the day after seven death row
convicts pulled a headline-grabbing escape from death row on
Thanksgiving Day 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Other states with similar ``super max'' units said Monday they
have had no such escapes.
</P>
<P>
   Prison investigators said Jones, 33, fled about 12:30 p.m.
Sunday while he was being escorted by a guard from his cell to a
fenced-in recreation yard at the northeast corner of the 660-man
prison 12 miles northeast of Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   Jones jerked one hand from his handcuffs and threatened to use
the cuffs to kill the female guard, officials said. As the guard
retreated for help, Jones ran across the exercise yard and scaled
the 20-foot-high, chain-link fence that surrounds it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an eight-inch space at the top and he somehow managed
to pull himself through there, dropped down 10 feet onto the top of
a (guards') catwalk, then down onto the ground,'' said Larry
Fitzgerald, another prison spokesman. ``It appears he used his
hands to tear through the fencing . . . This guy must have been
like Superman.''
</P>
<P>
   The convict quickly scaled a sensor-equipped perimeter fence,
setting off alarms and alerting another guard who fired at Jones
with a tear-gas shell. Officials said Jones then used a
triangle-shaped camera tower as a ladder to get over a second
fence.
</P>
<P>
   The tower has metal plating eight feet high on its sides to
prevent anyone from climbing it. Guards reported watching Jones
jump high enough to get a handhold above the plating.
</P>
<P>
   ``He climbed to the top of the tower and leapt flatfooted from
the tower, across the razor wire of the outside fence _ from all
indications, a distance of more than eight feet,'' Castlebury said.
``That tower is about four feet inside that fence, and his
footprint we found deeply imbedded in the dirt was about four or
five feet outside that fence.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones then ran across a water-filled ditch and into a wooded
area about 100 yards north of the prison, where he abandoned his
shoes and prison-issued clothing _ a move prison officials believe
was an attempt to foil tracking dogs. Shots fired
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald said a perimeter guard fired once at Jones with a
.357 Magnum pistol as he ran into the woods_ and missed. A deputy
warden at the nearby Ellis Unit fired another .357 shot _ but also
missed _ at Jones about an hour later as the naked convict ran
across a clearing about a mile from the escape site.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald said initial search attempts Sunday _ by guards,
state troopers and sheriff's deputies assisted by dogs and a U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service helicopter equipped with a
heat-sensing device _ failed to turn up any trace of Jones.
Investigators said temperatures well into the 90s interfered with
the device that focuses on body heat.
</P>
<P>
   Early Monday, searchers found a tree covered with poison ivy
where they believe Jones spent the night. ``The ivy was disturbed
and pulled out, and it was obvious someone had recently been
there,'' Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   By late Monday afternoon, the small army of searchers ringed an
area roughly 10 square miles from northeast of the prison to the
Trinity River, an area law enforcement officials described as
``heavily infested with mosquito- and snake-infested swampland.''
</P>
<P>
   Small boats from the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department were
brought in to assist the search along the riverbanks. Recent rains
made it almost impossible to access much of the search area in
vehicles or on horseback, and officials said much of the search was
under way on foot.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday evening, prison officials had installed razor wire
around the base of the camera tower and welded chain-link over the
gap in the exercise yard fence.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Johnson, director of the prison system, said the ongoing
investigation focused on how Jones slipped out of his handcuff.
Handcuffs are required whenever a convict leaves his cell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fatal flaw in this incident was the inmate being able to
get out of that handcuff, and we just need to figure out how that
occurred,'' Johnson said. Searchers optimistic
</P>
<P>
   Despite no new trace Monday of Jones, searchers remained
optimistic. By late afternoon, Department of Public Safety troopers
had set up roadblocks leading to the prison, and prison guards were
stationed every 100 yards along FM 980, the main road to both the
Estelle and Ellis prisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel confident at this point he is within this area, and we
think it's just a matter of time until we find him,'' Castlebury
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's escape marked the first from the Estelle High-Security
Unit, billed as Texas' most secure prison where the most violent
and troublesome convicts are housed. Castlebury, Fitzgerald and
other prison officials Monday declined comment on what went wrong
to allow Jones to escape such a place.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will be under investigation,'' Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   The Estelle High-Security Unit is a self-contained prison
located just north of the Estelle Unit, which houses 2,200
convicts. Both prisons share a large wooded compound with the Ellis
Unit, located about three miles away, where seven condemned killers
broke out of death row last Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Only one, Corpus Christi killer Martin Gurule, managed to escape
from the prison. He scaled two fences much like those at the
Estelle Unit where Sunday's escape occurred and was later found
drowned in a creek.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald characterized Jones as ``much more dangerous'' than
the seven death row inmates.
</P>
<P>
   A Dallas native who has been imprisoned three times, Jones was
serving 26 years for murder, attempted murder and assault of a
prison guard. Officials said he was convicted in the March 1987
shooting death of Patrick Anthony Haynes, 30, and for seriously
injuring Dallas police officer William Prettyman in a shotgun
attack early the following day as Prettyman tried to stop a car in
which Jones was riding.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials said he has a lengthy arrest record _ four
stints in the Dallas County juvenile detention lockup, two terms in
Texas Youth Commission schools in Brownwood and Gainesville and a
29-day stint in a Dallas jail for robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Jones' escape from what was touted as Texas' ``super
max'' prison _ the most secure of all 112 units and the prototype
for four more high-security prisons now under construction _
Castlebury said Texas still has one of the lowest escape rates of
any state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're one of the lowest in the nation for escapes and have one
of the highest recapture rates,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ward writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
