u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-EUROPE-1STLD-WRI     06-28 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-EUROPE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
...)  
 COKE SCARE IN BELGIUM WAS PRECEDED BY A MAY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert new 6th graf, beginning: Another Coke spokesman(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Almost four weeks before Coca Cola Co.
publicly acknowledged the contamination in Belgium that led to the
biggest recall in its 113-year history, four people had become sick
at a bar near Antwerp and blamed their illness on drinking Coke, a
senior Belgian health ministry official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The first the public in general knew of the scare, which
eventually led to a total, 10-day ban on Coca-Cola products in
Belgium and spread alarms across Europe, was on June 8 after more
than 30 teen-age schoolchildren in the town of Bornem were taken to
the hospital complaining of stomachaches, dizziness and nausea.
</P>
<P>
   But, the health ministry official said, that incident had been
preceded on May 12 when the owner of a bar at Noorderwijk, a tiny
village 20 miles east of Antwerp, called both the Ministry of
Public Health and Coca-Cola Co.'s staff in Belgium to say four
adults had displayed similar symptoms after drinking Coke. As in
other cases, the four people complained that the Coke they drank
smelled strange. Neither the company nor the Belgian authorities
had alluded to the earlier incident in their accounts of the
recall. The official spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Coca-Cola at the company's Atlanta headquarters
said the company had checked out the May 12 incident and had found
no reason to be concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing was found in the plant, so it was thought to be an
anomaly,'' said the spokesman, Randy Donaldson. As for why the
company had not mentioned it as more recent reports of problems
with Coca-Cola products emerged, he said it was not clear that the
incidents were connected, even though the same plant in Antwerp was
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Another Coke spokesman in Atlanta, Rob Baskin, said he had not
heard about the May incident until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Noorderwijk case provides a fuller picture of the sequence
of events surrounding Coca-Cola Co.'s handling of an affair that,
by the company's own admission, has hurt its reputation and has
drawn public apologies from the company's chief executive, M.
Douglas Ivester. Coinciding with a food scandal in Belgium over the
contamination of meat and poultry with cancer-causing dioxin, it
illustrated anew why many Belgians have become nervous about the
safety of the food they buy in stores.
</P>
<P>
   In early May, the Belgian official said, the incident at
Noorderwijk seemed like an isolated incident. The Coke drunk by the
adults had been packaged in small bottles by a Coke plant in
Antwerp _ like those sold to schoolchildren in Bornem _ and,
afterwards, the four people complained of stomachaches, dizziness
and a burning sensation in the throat.
</P>
<P>
   Three of them were examined in a hospital, ``but the doctor
could not find anything,'' the official said. Samples of Coke from
the same batch were sent for analysis to a government-licensed
laboratory, and Coca-Cola was also believed to have ordered tests
on the same batch, the official said. But ``because it was one
case, because nothing was found in the laboratory, no action was
taken,'' this official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could not find any poison. There was no proof that it was
linked to Coca-Cola,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   With hindsight, however, the official's account seemed to
suggest that the scare may have been building slowly in Belgium for
weeks before it blew up into a major embarrassment and marketing
disaster for the company. But, at a time when government officials
were preoccupied with the dioxin scandal _ and only weeks before
elections June 13 that brought down the government _ it appears
that the incident at Noorderwijk was simply filed away.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference last week, Ivester said laboratory tests
had found traces of sulfur in the carbon dioxide used to make
bubbles in sodas and had discovered that cans of Coke imported from
Dunkirk, France, had been contaminated by a chemical used on
transportation pallets. He blamed these factors for the 249 cases
of Coke-related sickness reported to the Belgian authorities. But
the Belgian minister in charge of the case, Luc Van den Bossche,
said the government did not accept this explanation, arguing that
the concentrations of the chemicals identified by Ivester were too
low to cause illness.
</P>
<P>
   The sicknesses among teen-age students in Bornem, also near
Antwerp, were the first reported of a series in other parts of
Belgium, including Bruges, Harelbeke and Lochristi. On June 14, the
government issued a highly unusual ministerial decree banning a
range of Coca-Cola products from sodas to mineral water. The ban
was eased June 17 and totally lifted June 23.
</P>
<P>
   The Belgian health official said that, once Coca-Cola had begun
to recall its products in Belgium, several people contacted an
emergency call center to say that, for ``one or two months,'' they
had detected strange smells from some new vending machines
installed by Coke. Thousands of Coke vending machines in Belgium
remained off limits when the overall ban was lifted last Thursday
and there has been no word on when they will reopen. The smell has
been described by some of those who became sick as being like
gasoline or sulfur.
</P>
<P>
   The Belgian official said that two Coca-Cola plants closed
during the ban _ at Ghent and Antwerp _ were near reopening or
already had reopened after inspections by government officials.
</P>
<P>
   Belgian officials said the bulk of the illnesses appeared to
have been linked most to sodas produced in early June. But, despite
the easing of the restrictions, the health ministry official
insisted that the cause of the sicknesses remained unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been given proof of contamination, but we haven't been
given proof of the link between contamination and the symptoms,''
the official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
