u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-THANKYOUS-COX     06-28 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-THANKYOUS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush says thank you to Texan backers
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ On the eve of his first campaign swing through
electorally crucial California, Gov. George W. Bush paused Monday
night to thank the Texas supporters who have helped him fill his
campaign coffers.
</P>
<P>
   He has a lot to be thankful for.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the front-runner for the Republican presidential
nomination, announced that Texans contributed $11 million to his
campaign during the first six months of this year. As a reward for
their efforts, the roughly 600 contributors and organizers who
showed up Monday evening at the Four Seasons Hotel were treated to
an open bar, pretzels, peanuts and the stump speech that Bush has
been delivering across the nation in the last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an indication that my base of support, the great state of
Texas, is strong, is vibrant, and it sends a large message to the
rest of the nation,'' Bush said of his Texas contributions.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Bush is expected to announce that he has collected
more than $20 million nationwide. He may have garnered as much
campaign cash as all his GOP rivals combined, and his total far
exceeds the roughly $13.7 million Bob Dole raised during the first
six months of 1995. In recent presidential races, the candidate who
has raised the most money in the first half of the year preceding
the election has won the party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Texans contributed 54 percent of the money that Bush collected
during the first three months of this year. But the governor began
to make out-of-state fund-raising forays in June, so Texas money
probably represents a smaller chunk of his six-month total.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's goal is to collect $45 million or more, a figure that
would enable him to forgo federal matching money and the spending
limits that come with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty million dollars at this point in the election cycle is
phenomenal,'' said Shelia Krumholz of the Center for Responsive
Politics, a Washington-based research group that studies the role
of money in the political process.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Bush is inspiring people to open their wallets in a way
that Dole did not.
</P>
<P>
   Amarillo lawyer Roger Cox describes himself as a ``fairly
active'' Republican, but he didn't contribute to Dole because he
wasn't ``all that energized'' by the senator. Although he makes a
modest salary, Cox gave $1,000 to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sacrificed at my house for a couple of months to make up
for that contribution,'' he said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But Brian Kennedy, a spokesman for Republican candidate Lamar
Alexander, cautioned against equating early fund-raising prowess
with certain victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing a Texan raise a lot of money in the year prior to a
presidential race reminds us of Presidents Gramm and Connally,''
Kennedy said, referring to previous Texas candidates who collected
millions of dollars that didn't translate into votes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush collected $7.6 million during the first three months of
1999, far more than his Republican rivals. Bush's take was
especially impressive because he didn't begin collecting money
until the end of February, and didn't appear at a single
fund-raising event during that period.
</P>
<P>
   Bush first hit the fund-raising circuit on June 11, when he
raised about $800,000 in St. Louis and Chicago. Since then, he's
appeared at events in Massachusetts, Connecticut, Washington, D.C.,
South Carolina, Pennsylvania, Michigan and Florida, collecting a
total of more than $8 million from donors in those states. In
California he'll tap into the state's wealthy high-tech community
with a Thursday fund-raising breakfast in Palo Alto. Austin
high-tech mogul Michael Dell was at Monday's event.
</P>
<P>
   Bush leaves for California buoyed by poll numbers that indicate
that he has an increasingly large lead over the rest of the GOP
field. A CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll of Republican voters released
Monday puts Bush at 59 percent, with all ten of his rivals
languishing in the single-digits. A month ago Bush led his nearest
challenger, Elizabeth Dole, 46 percent to 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, the Bush campaign announced that all but one of
the 72 Republicans in the Texas House signed a letter endorsing the
governor for president. The lawmaker who didn't sign, Rep. Charlie
Howard of Sugar Land, said he thinks Bush ``would make a great
president'' but that he never endorses candidates before the
general election.
</P>
<P>
   Scott S. Greenberger writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
